<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWAT TEAM: SPURS' TWIN TOWES MAUL THE KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The San ntonio Spurs flaunted their good health,
depth and size until the patchwork Knicks frayed at the edges and
came undone Wednesday night at the Alamodome, 89-77, in Game 1 of
the National Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Knicks have lost a Game 1 through four
series of their improbable playoff run, but this was also their
first glance at the Spurs' David Robinson and Tim Duncan, a mighty
pair of 7-footers. Duncan finished with 33 points and 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who pulled to within 6 points of the Spurs with 8
minutes left before folding under foul trouble, were led by Allan
Houston and Latrell Sprewell, both with 19 points. But Sprewell had
six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have to shake off their miseries and play the Spurs
in Game 2 Friday night at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were in dire need of manpower before the game began
and received a lift when Johnson determined that he could at least
provide a presence. It was a limited version of Johnson due to the
sprained right knee he has been nursing for five days, but he
started and was able to absorb some fouls for a Knicks team that
was vulnerable to the attrition factor with an injured Patrick
Ewing on the bench in a suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same as when Patrick was playing hurt, and he was
doing what he could to help us win,'' said Van Gundy, referring to
how Ewing played with a sore Achilles' tendon until it tore two
weeks ago. ``Even if Larry can't look as good as he would like,
that unselfishness goes a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Unselfishness was the mantra of a Knicks team that stepped on
the court undaunted by the looming Twin Towers and the ominous odds
it was facing. Even in pre-game warm-ups, there was a sense that
their us-against-the-world mentality was in the air _ literally _
as Sprewell was exploding for vicious dunks and landing with a
snarl on his face.
</P>
<P>
   He was ready, but so was the low-key Houston and the unlikely
menace in the paint, Chris Dudley. But the adrenaline rush that
kept the Knicks with the Spurs in the first half began to get
undermined by foul trouble as the break neared. The deep Spurs were
just getting warmed up. Leaning on Duncan and Robinson, they went
on a 14-2 run to take a 45-37 lead at the half. The Knicks were
going to have to gamble with their foul trouble. At the break,
Johnson, Houston and Camby had three fouls each.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs knew who was who. They drove right at Houston _ who
had 14 first-half points _ to start the third quarter. Mario Elie
slipped by him for a layup to put the Spurs up by 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio held that edge as Duncan took the game over. If he
wasn't fading away for jumpers over Johnson, he was the receiver of
a lob pass from Robinson and popping up between two defenders for a
layup. The latter left Van Gundy calling a timeout with 4:43 left
in the third, and the Knicks down, 60-50.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs went up by 12 points, but then Camby made an impact.
He darted in for a tip-in and then stripped Robinson on a play that
led to a fast-break basket by Sprewell. On the next possession,
Sprewell, beating Sean Elliott down the floor, hit an off-kilter
jumper and pulled the Knicks within 7, at 67-60. A 3-point play by
Jaren Jackson gave the Spurs some separation and helped them take a
71-63 lead into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were staying within range. Their strategy all along
was to keep themselves in the game just long enough to give
themselves a chance for a clutch finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks began with the right mentality. All or nothing. After
the Spurs pounded the ball inside to Robinson to grab a 5-point
lead in the opening minutes, Dudley emerged and turned the tempo of
the game around. He blocked shots, forced turnovers and came up
with rebounds to feed the fast-break hungry Knicks. Sprewell and
Houston took it from there and tied the game with four minutes left
in the first.
</P>
<P>
   As the aggressors, the Knicks drove into the paint for layups
when Robinson was resting. When Robinson's wingspan was in play,
the Knicks drove and kicked the ball out to the perimeter. By the
end of the first quarter, the Knicks were eating away at the
league's best defense by shooting 52 percent, ignoring the size
differential with nine more rebounds, and took a 27-21 lead on the
heels of a 16-6 run.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a joint packed with people _ some sitting on an angle
behind the curtain that divided the dome _ could see the favored
Spurs were up against a team that wasn't about to back down.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks watched as the Spurs went on a 10-3 lead to regain
the lead while Camby picked up his third foul and went to the bench
five minutes into the second quarter. Once again, Dudley _ playing
smart and foul free for most of the half _ came up with the
rebounds to start the Knicks back on the fast break. Sprewell
pulled up for a jumper over a soft defender, Elliott. Then Houston
slipped past an overeager Mario Elie and knocked down a jumper
after the Knicks got the ball back when the diminutive Childs stood
in front of Robinson and drew a charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks held a 35-31 lead and threatened to pull ahead at the
break. But the Spurs went back to Robinson and Duncan, both of whom
bludgeoned the Knicks inside to give the Spurs a 39-35 lead. The
Knicks were floating into choppy waters now. Foul trouble was
gaining on them, leaving Van Gundy to insert the 41-year-old Herb
Williams into the game for a clumsy last 1:30 of the half.
</P>
<P>
   In that span, the assertive Spurs _ who were creating their own
fast-break attempts off blocked shots and Knicks misses _ finished
the half with a 6-0 run and took a 45-37 lead at halftime. The
Knicks scored just one field goal in the last 4:12 of the first
half. At this point, Duncan had a quiet 19 points around the
defense of Kurt Thomas and Johnson, while Robinson added 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, whose gaudy field-goal percentage plummeted in the
second quarter, finished the half shooing 38.6 percent with Houston
leading the team with 14 points, while Sprewell added 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   This was part of what the Knicks feared. They were playing all
out, and still the Spurs were able to go to their big men inside
and make up for any runs the Knicks could pull out of their hat.
This is what the Knicks had to do, create something from nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were the underdogs in this series for a reason. The
Spurs had all the size, health and depth. And they had almost
40,000 fans on their side. The Knicks had a lot of work to do if
they were going to take their fourth Game 1 of the playoffs on the
road and put the pressure on the Spurs. The Spurs had a 10-day
layoff, but after stumbling around a bit in the face of a
determined opponent, they were showing why so many wondered if
destiny was still on the side of the Knicks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
