<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OLD DIFFERENCES ON KNICKS RESURFACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Beneath the feel-good atmosphere created by the
New York Knicks' opportunity to play for the NBA championship,
there is lingering uncertainty over coach Jeff Van Gundy's future
and the impact his strained relationships with Latrell Sprewell and
Marcus Camby may have on it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Knicks' 89-77 Game 1 loss to San Antonio Wednesday,
they were greeted with questions about a report in the current
issue of Sports Illustrated. Sprewell, the magazine reported, has
told teammates that he does not want to play for Van Gundy next
year and that if Van Gundy returns, he wants to be traded to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where that came from but it's not true,''
Sprewell said before the Knicks' shoot-around this morning. ``I
never said it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was asked if at any point during the season _ perhaps
when his frustration with his sixth-man role was at its peak _ he
indicated a desire to be traded should Van Gundy return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I've ever said was that I prefer starting,''
Sprewell said. ``That wasn't really a problem with Jeff, it was
something I preferred. It took me a while to adjust. That was the
only thing that was ever there between him and I.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, that issue is dead. As a result of Patrick Ewing's
injury diagnosis after Game 2 of the Eastern Conference finals
against Indiana, Van Gundy placed Sprewell in the starting lineup.
Sprewell has continued to play well and appears happy, basking in
the glow of a comeback from his tarnished image in the nation's
largest market. Add to that his flair for the dramatic dunk, and
companies are knocking down his door to be their pitchman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of offers,'' his agent, Robert Gist, said
Wednesday. ``And some of them ask, `Is he going to be with the
Knicks next year?' He wants to be back. He loves the fans there.
There are a lot of reasons for him to stay. I'm optimistic that
everything will work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, next year has entered our minds. But we'll take a step
back and watch and see how things evolve. Everything will be taken
into consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes Sprewell's role when Ewing comes back from his
injury. Will Ewing's return mean that Sprewell will go back to
sixth man in his contract year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we don't go back and repeat history,'' Gist said. ``How
could anyone want to change what has taken place and go back to the
old way of doing things? As a result of what's happened this year,
all Latrell has done is increase his value. There could be 16 to 18
teams in line for him. I don't think the Knicks want to lose him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a way to get Latrell and the Knicks on the
same page. When this team is on the same page, they're an awesome
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point after the season, Sprewell and Camby are expected
to express their views on Van Gundy to Dave Checketts, the
president of Madison Square Garden. Although Camby has publicly
kept his feelings about Van Gundy quiet, he has privately expressed
dismay over what one friend described as Van Gundy's early personal
bias against him after he came to the Knicks in the emotional trade
of Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be helpful if Jeff tried to establish some
relationship with Marcus, like he has built with Larry Johnson and
Patrick Ewing over the years,'' the friend said, speaking on the
condition of anonymity. ``Right now, there's no relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it would seem that Van Gundy, who has already earned an
automatic $3.5 million extension beyond the $2 million he has left
on his contract next year, has all the leverage to return as coach
of the Knicks if that is what he wants after dealing with the
cloak-and-dagger operations of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Typically focused on the task at hand, Van Gundy shrugged off
the Sports Illustrated article.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only thinking about this year,'' Van Gundy said. ``I'm
sure Latrell is only thinking about this year. Next year will work
itself out. It always does. And sometimes it does so in unexpected
ways. But I'll say this, I have no problem with Latrell at all,
never have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Latrell has had a problem not starting. I understand
that. Any great player would have a problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsolicited, Van Gundy then dropped Camby's name into his
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Marcus and I, or Latrell and I having a problem?
No,'' he said. ``I think they have been unhappy at times. With
Latrell, it has been more about how he's been used, as far as not
starting. And Marcus, it's with not playing as much as he would
like. But it's never been a problem at practice where they've been
uncoachable or been less than anything about the team. They've been
all about the team. They've been great.''
</P>
<P>
   All is well for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
