<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COMBATANTS A MYSTERY UNTIL NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It took too long, but Game 1 arrived at last,
along with the news that Tim Duncan is as good as advertised. No
surprise, really. Or that Larry Johnson's sprained knee ligament
had miraculously healed. If we'd waited much longer for the finals
to begin, Phil Jackson would've found a cure for Shaquille O'Neal's
free-throw shooting disease, or the common cold.
</P>
<P>
   Sit around long enough, you start to believe anything. The Spurs
were even suspicious that Patrick Ewing was taking limping lessons
in case he is needed to make the first two jump shots of Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys around here, we joke that Patrick's going to
do the Willis Reed thing,'' said the Spurs' Jaren Jackson, who made
his own opening impression with fourth-quarter shooting as San
Antonio defeated the Knicks, 89-77, kicking off the finals that
should have begun last Sunday night when most Eastern time zone
children weren't asleep. One would think that the league would want
the first post-Jordan finals to get maximum exposure, especially to
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Tell it to the Commissioner, Dick Ebersol.
</P>
<P>
   David Stern, the NBC honcho's partner-in-patronage, once said
that no finals game should ever end after anyone's late-night news.
That strategy has apparently gone the way of the 100-point offense,
with the games beginning after most East Coast kids and even a few
working parents have gone to bed. Had the series commenced last
Sunday and not skipped next Sunday, three of the possible seven
games could have begun at 7:30 in the East and finished at 7:30 in
the West. Something for the fans, to conclude a season that began
three months late. Does anyone even remember the lockout?
</P>
<P>
   Stern has always wanted his championship series to develop the
cachet of the World Series and, by golly, it has. His first
showcase flirted dangerously with spilling into the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. This series actually has a quaint, old World Series
feel to it. The Knicks and Spurs did not meet during the 50-game
regular-season contrivance. It felt as if the teams were from rival
leagues, the establishment Knicks against the first descendants of
the old American Basketball Association to advance this far.
</P>
<P>
   Before baseball panicked into interleague play, the Series was
always guaranteed to contain a freshness other sports lacked in
their championship events. It was a novelty to see the Yankees
confront the Braves in 1996. It was a pleasure to have Tony Gwynn
walk into Yankee Stadium and get caught up in its history, like
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks fans were waiting Wednesday night with their
sophisticate's curiosity and provincial dread to find out about
Duncan. It took one night, as Duncan quietly torched the
stressed-out Knicks front line for 33 points and 16 rebounds,
leading a 14-2 run that gave the Spurs a 45-37 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen the Knicks, but the good thing is that they
haven't seen us either,'' Duncan said. ``By the time the teams are
used to each other, the series will be coming to a close.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't saying it was going to be short or sweet, because
there was just no way to know anything until these teams finally
hit the Alamodome court. Only then could the Knicks know that
Duncan is poised beyond his years. On the other hand, they quickly
and happily discovered that the Spurs are awfully thin beyond
Duncan and David Robinson. When one was on the bench, Allan Houston
and Latrell Sprewell were every bit as dangerous as they were in
the three series' past.
</P>
<P>
   Don Chaney, the Knicks' assistant coach, once traded Dennis
Rodman for Sean Elliott when he was coaching in Detroit. He
received an injured player who did not appear to be tough enough to
play in the more physical East. Was it Elliott's bad back, or was
he also too soft? Elliott's scoreless first half on one shot was a
good Knick omen.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to know if Marcus Camby could soar over the
Spurs' front line as he did Indiana's, but Camby's no-rebound first
half and gamelong foul trouble suggested a quick adjustment was in
order. Larry Johnson actually looked pretty limber, but was
overmatched guarding Robinson in the first half and Duncan in the
second. A very bad Knick omen, and, for Jeff Van Gundy, the
anticipated matchups nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was decided Wednesday night, but the first impression
was that the eighth-seeded Cinderella may be coming to the end of
the ball. A few strokes, unfortunately, before midnight back home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
