</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON MAKES GOOD IMPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ If Phil Jackson's first day on the job
with the Los Angeles Lakers is any indication of what will unfold
in upcoming seasons, then this troubled team might be destined to
once again become the dominant NBA presence it was during the
Showtime era.
</P>
<P>
   In his Laker coming out press party staged Wednesday in the
International Ballroom at the Beverly Hilton, Jackson worked the
large gathering of sportswriters, sportscasters, agents, attorneys,
photographers, hangers-on, Howard Stern props, sports talk radio
buffoons and the usual gate-crashers with a practiced smoothness
that his Laker coaching predecessors, Del Harris and Kurt Rambis,
never were able to display.
</P>
<P>
   ``After listening to Phil talk, I now know why he's a great
coach and why the Bull players loved him and why the Bulls won six
world titles,'' said an admiring spectator, Mr. Magic Johnson,
after Jackson had concluded his session with the media. ``In the
past, the Lakers could lay the blame on their coach for their
failures. No more. Now it's up to the Lakers to shut up and play
because I think they have one of the greatest coaches in NBA
history coaching them now.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm still uncertain about that, but the Lakers indisputably now
have a man leading them with almost a Churchillian facility with
the English language, a true Zen master at rhetorical acrobatics in
which he leaves you shaking your noggin in admiration of his
eclectic mixture of sly locutions, deft euphemisms, wry humor and
florid asides.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Michael Jordan loved this guy!
</P>
<P>
   After listening to his eloquent blarney for more than 30
minutes---had I closed my eyes, I could have sworn it was William
Jefferson Clinton without the Arkansas drawl---I loved the guy,
too!
</P>
<P>
   And here's wagering that Shaquille O'Neal also will love him and
actually do what Jackson will want him to do---play sounder
defense, practice harder on his free throws, cease with the cloying
excuses for his teams' annual failures, lose all those unflattering
pounds and get in legitimate shape.
</P>
<P>
   I also have an overwhelming feeling that Kobe Bryant will do
something he's never done before, either---actually listen to his
coach and actually subordinate his vast skills for the overall good
of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling that Jackson will make a huge impact on the
Lakers,'' said Magic Johnson. ``How's any player going to argue
with this guy with six rings on his fingers? There's a commanding
presence about him. I'm excited for the team. This is just what it
has needed. A guy who's been there, and knows the game
thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about Jackson's X's and O's expertise---Michael
Jordan's heroics seem to supply him with all the X's and O's
knowledge he ever needed---but I now know first hand about his
oratory skills that border on grandiloquence.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, he said all the right things during the interview
ritual without offending anyone in the process---yes, the Lakers
were the right team for him because they had a potential MVP in
Shaquille O'Neal and a Michael Jordan-like player in Kobe Bryant,
yes, it would be just great to work with Jerry West and Mitch
Kupchack, yes, it was nice to be in sunny Southern California and
by the beaches, yes, he expects the Lakers to become a serious NBA
title threat immediately, no, he wouldn't compare West and Jerry
Krause (Bulls' GM), etc.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe McDonnell asked Jackson if it were ethical of him to be
interviewed by the New York Knicks' boss, Dave Checketts while Jeff
Van Gundy still was coaching the team, he rambled on for a minute
and a half without answering the question. But he sounded terrific
doing it, and you weren't aware of his evasive tactics until you
checked your notes.
</P>
<P>
   He took a similar filibustering tack when someone asked him who
he thought would win the NBA finals between the Knicks and San
Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about what a wonderful storybook story the Knicks were
and how powerful the Spurs were, but slyly failed to offer a
prediction.
</P>
<P>
   When the Howard Stern stooge, Melrose Larry Green, asked him if
he were going to rise at 3 a.m. to catch Stern's show live, he
replied coolly, ``I don't deign to listen to Howard Stern, although
I catch (Don) Imus once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about bringing a couple of his former Bull players
like Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman, to the Lakers, he said,
``Probably not. Scottie's got his own thing going, and Dennis is I
think in another ozone.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that this Phil Jackson is a slick one, a
immensely intelligent fellow who reportedly could have made twice
as much money---he signed a five-year contract with the Lakers for
a reported $30 million---had he accepted an offer with the New
Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson is quite aware that the New Jersey Nets have no one
who faintly resembles Shaquille O'Neal, or even Kobe Bryant---and
that the Nets aren't anywhere near being a formidable team and that
his legacy of coaching greatness would be seriously tarnished at
such a place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers are much like the Bulls were when he took over in
Chicago in 1989---just on the verge of being champions,'' said
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson knows the Lakers are only a sound point guard, a
reliable power forward and a change in outlook by Shaquille O'Neal
and Kobe Bryant away from being serious NBA title threats.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson knows that coaches in the NBA don't win championships
without talented personnel, and he knows the Lakers have a solid
enough foundation in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have to make a few roster adjustments,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson was flawless in his Laker debut.
</P>
<P>
   The Laker owner, Jerry Buss, finally has snapped out of his
strange administrative slump with this surprising hiring of
Jackson, surprising in that Buss was willing to spend so much money
to secure Jackson's services.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Jerry Buss who did everything it took to make the
Lakers a championship team throughout the 1980s, not the Jerry Buss
who dragged out contract negotiations needlessly with Jerry West
and nixed West's trade for Mitch Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excuses are now over for the Lakers,'' observed Magic
Johnson. ``If Phil Jackson can't win with the team, no one will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
