<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-COLUMN-NYT     06-17 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL AND HOUSTON SENDING OUT AN SOS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ When they were finding seams in the defense in the
first half of Game 1 Wednesday night and knocking down jump shots,
Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston were exploiting the one clear
mismatch the Knicks have over the Spurs in the National Basketball
Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   They can't do anything about Tim Duncan; he is simply too good.
And David Robinson is going to eventually get to the free throw
line, so the Knicks can forget about completely neutralizing him,
too. So much for the frontcourt matchup. That the Knicks would
concede.
</P>
<P>
   But on the perimeter, it was different. They had scorers and
creators, players who could get to the basket and draw a foul. It
was thought to be their one great chance at upsetting the
multifaceted Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as the Chicago Bulls learned over the last decade,
two potent scorers on the perimeter can compensate for any quality
dropoff at point guard or center. And for the Knicks to not only
compete, but to pull off a monumental upset, they need Sprewell and
Houston to play extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   They had combined for 33 points through three quarters on
Wednesday night, with Sprewell going on a third-quarter binge and
Houston often making a gambling Mario Elie pay. That kind of
productivity should have been a harbinger of great things to come
for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But when your other offensive options have trouble producing,
it's tough to keep pace with a good team like San Antonio. Charlie
Ward, Chris Dudley, a gimpy Larry Johnson and Kurt Thomas did not
give the Knicks enough offensively to seize Game 1 at the
Alamodome, and an 89-77 loss left the Knicks wondering what they
could do to stop the Spurs over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have caught too many bounces and good breaks this
post-season to fold easily in the finals. Even in the fourth
quarter Wednesday night, they were within striking distance of at
least making it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   But after Sprewell and Houston essentially had to monopolize the
basketball because no one else could score, you half-expect the two
natural shooting guards to send out an SOS to their Knick brethren.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Houston each scored 19 points, combining for nearly
half of the Knicks' total points. They kept New York in the game in
the first half and were relied upon exclusively in the final
quarter to help bring the Knicks out of a deep rut.
</P>
<P>
   But they need help. That much is clear.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three rounds of the playoffs, the Knicks found ways
to win on the road in Game 1. They did it by moving the ball around
and finding the open man. No matter who that player was, he would
usually knock down an open shot with the game in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs get a lot of credit for their defense, which was
menacing and impenetrable at the ends of the second and fourth
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was Elie bodying up Houston or Sean Elliott flailing
his arms to disrupt Sprewell, they put serious kinks in the Knicks'
game. Chris Childs and Ward never really made themselves serious
threats, either.
</P>
<P>
   This was more about the Knicks' inability to generate points at
crucial moments of the game than any tremendous defensive stop by
Duncan or Robinson. Thomas began to show signs of life near the
end, scoring on his patented arching jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson, who surprised everyone by rehabilitating his knee
injury in five days and starting on Wednesday night, gets a pass.
He did all he could given the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing he is not completely healthy and that his performance
might suffer, Johnson could have easily have taken this week to
rest the aching knee and play in Game 3 in New York on Monday. But
Johnson, realizing perhaps that playing in the league championship
series only comes around once for many star-crossed souls, saw the
chance to play and seized it. He made the most of a fleeting
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their contributions and those of Sprewell and Houston,
though, the rest of the Knicks have 48 hours to fix their broken
offensive games. Going home to Madison Square Garden in an 0-2 hole
would be rough.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks should not take their own opportunity for granted.
</P>
<P>
   In the grand scheme, they might not be a contending team for the
millennium. Instead, they may be a combustible bunch of veterans
and role players who have ridden an unpredictable tsunami of
momentum into the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, two months before New York was joyfully celebrating
this team, it was uniformly denigrating it. Somewhere between San
Antonio, Here We Come, and Back Up the Truck, there is a middle
ground.
</P>
<P>
   If this wacky lockout season proves anything, it's that you
can't be too sure of your franchise's future today because tomorrow
it may headed toward destruction through free agency, turmoil or
both. Treasure the good times, because lean days may not be far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   As the Knicks take the court Friday night for Game 2 of their
implausible run, they should be mindful of that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
