<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNCAN TOO MUCH, AS KNICKS DISCOVER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ By halftime, he had already recorded an entire
game's worth of statistics, already established himself as the man
who would control this NBA championship series, already shown why
this San Antonio Spurs team might not lose another game this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan, the quiet and unassuming 7-footer, was simply too
much for the Knicks to handle, especially with Patrick Ewing
cheering from the sidelines in a suit. Scoring on jump shots from 9
to 20 feet out, layups off offensive rebounds, and one wicked
finger roll, Duncan finished with 33 points and 16 rebounds in the
Spurs' 89-77 victory over the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The calm and efficient showing was a glimpse into the future of
the N BA, the league Duncan, 23, will likely dominate for years to
come. Wednesday night, he was the youngest starter on the court yet
at the same time, the most collected.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, when his teammates were struggling and the
undermanned Knicks were playing beyond themselves, he almost
single-handedly kept the Spurs from falling into a hole as
cavernous as the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   After the Knicks jumped to a surprising 27-21 lead after one
quarter, Duncan put his club on his back, outscoring the Knicks by
himself in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   His 11 points was one more than the Knicks managed in the entire
quarter. He scored nine of them in the final four minutes to lift
the Spurs to a 45-37 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   His solo run started when he lofted a driving finger roll over a
falling Chris Dudley with 3 minutes 54 seconds left. Moments later,
he drew a foul, then sank the ensuing free throws. Next, he
finished a pass from David Robinson with a soft layup. After
baskets by Robinson and Antonio Daniels, he sank a jumper from the
top of the key, then hit one of two fouls shots.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not just Duncan's scoring that turned the tide of
this game and enabled the Spurs to build their cushion. With Kurt
Thomas grabbing seven rebounds, the Knicks dominated the backboards
in the first quarter, outrebounding the Spurs by 15-7, including
5-1 on the offensive glass.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, however, put an end to the Knicks' fun by equaling their
rebounding total in the second quarter with seven. His board work
allowed the Spurs to outrebound the Knicks by 14-7. Duncan's
splendid quarter gave him 19 points and 10 rebounds by halftime.
More impressively, he did it on just 10 field goal attempts,
hitting seven of them.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliance of Duncan was that he did his damage in the flow
of the Spurs offense. In fact, early on San Antonio looked like it
wanted to feature Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly trying to get Larry Johnson in foul trouble, Robinson
relentlessly drove the ball at the basket to draw two fouls on
Johnson within the game's first three minutes. The Spurs' never
seemed to force the ball to Duncan, but with the Knicks' covering
him one-on-one with Dudley, Thomas and Camby, the ball found its
way to him.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a good thing for the Spurs because besides Robinson,
who scored 11 of his 13 points in the first half, no one else in a
white and black uniform was doing anything. That changed in the
second half, though, when the Knicks were forced to pay more
attention to Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Sending another defender at Duncan once he got the ball, the
Knicks left the perimeter open and Spurs like Jaren Jackson and
Sean Elliott began finding the range. Duncan, who is not a great
passer out of double teams _ yet, proved more than adequate in the
second half, kicking out assists to both Elliott and Jackson for
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the reserve guard, was also outstanding, hitting 5 of
10 3-pointers, including four in the second half, to finish with 17
points. With any one of the Spurs' wing players shooting like that,
and Duncan playing his typically remarkably game, San Antonio will
be incredibly tough to beat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
