<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CANDIDATES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SCHOOL BOARD TO INTERVIEW FOUR CANDIDATES FOR SUPERINTENDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR 
and TANIKA WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four finalists for Kansas City school superintendent will
interview privately with the Board of Education on Friday, but
members say a selection probably will not be made for several
weeks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members received the resumes of four candidates in a
closed meeting late Tuesday. A candidate screening committee said
it may submit additional names to the school board next week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members declined to release the names of the finalists,
citing instructions from U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple to keep
the candidates confidential. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   School board President John Rios confirmed that Pascal Forgione
Jr., currently a U.S. education commissioner, is among the four. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members and others familiar with the candidates said two
have nontraditional backgrounds for an urban superintendent. One is
a former high-ranking officer in the military. Another has a law
degree and does not work in public education. The fourth is a
longtime educator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several large urban districts, including Seattle, San Diego,
Chicago and Washington, D.C., have turned to nontraditional
superintendents in recent years with mixed success. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to look at all of them,'' board member Sandy Mayer
said Wednesday. ``I'm pleased with what I've seen. I think we have
a good selection to choose from. And there may be some more.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The interviews will be held at offices of Blackwell Sanders
Peper Martin, one of the district's legal counsels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several school board members said it could be the end of the
month before all interviews are completed. At that point, district
lawyers will conduct a background check on the finalist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some board members and Whipple said they wanted to avoid a
repeat of the haste that led to the hiring of Henry Williams in
August 1996. Williams clashed almost immediately with some board
members and eventually took a buyout with a year remaining on a
three-year contract. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the school board voted to give the district's
current instructional leader, Phyllis Chase, a 90-day extension on
her contract, which expires June 30. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayer and Helen Ragsdale voted against the extension. Board
member Fifi Wiedeman abstained. The board did not discuss a similar
extension for Bonnie McKelvy, who oversees the district's business
and finances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Desegregation Monitoring Committee still must approve
Chase's contract extension, which calls for her to continue at her
$125,000 salary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, several board members said they discussed removing
Rios as president. Member Lance Loewenstein said he asked Rios to
step down during a break in the school board meeting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loewenstein and other board members said they were angered and
embarrassed by comments Rios made during a court hearing Tuesday
with Whipple. Some members said Rios' comments were only the latest
evidence of his inability to lead the board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Rios criticized the DMC. Whipple, who
appointed the three-member panel, said Rios lacked evidence to back
up the allegation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rios said Wednesday that he had no intention of stepping down. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way,'' Rios said. ``I'm board president and expect
to be board president until my term ends.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forgione also can expect some pointed inquiries about his
leadership. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several board members have expressed concern about his failure
to file his tax returns in a timely way for eight consecutive
years. Officials in the Clinton administration have cited the tax
issue as the reason Forgione was not reappointed as the
commissioner overseeing the National Center for Education
Statistics, which collects, analyzes and disseminates education
data. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forgione has acknowledged he missed the filing deadline but said
he was always due a refund and violated no federal tax laws. Other
educators contend Forgione was not reappointed as punishment for
criticizing Vice President Al Gore over the release of test score
data. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forgione could not be reached Wednesday for comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other board members also were angered that Arthur A. Benson II
had met with Forgione before some board members even knew he was a
candidate. Benson is the attorney for the plaintiff schoolchildren
in the federal desegregation case, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forgione interviewed last Friday with the Austin Board of
Education in Texas but was not chosen as a finalist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the monitoring committee considered but rejected
sending only Forgione's name to the school board for consideration.
That led Rios to question whether Forgione is the favored
candidate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to review (the other candidates) and see exactly if
they're qualified candidates or just individuals thrown out there
for us to sort through to get the other guy,'' Rios said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
