<HEADER>
A8666 &Cx1f; kan-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENE-RECORD-KAN &LR;      06-17 0291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENE-RECORD-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Maurice Greene tramples world 100-meter record  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM PEDLEY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maurice Greene carried the title of ``World's Fastest Human''
into Wednesday's running of the 100 meters in Athens, Greece. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greene carried the title of ``History's Fastest Human'' out of
the meet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old sprinter from Kansas City, Kan., covered the
distance in 9.79 seconds. That trashed the 3-year-old record of
9.84 set by Canadian Donovan Bailey in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greene said in a telephone interview late Wednesday night that
as he crossed the finish line, he was not thinking about the
record. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, Ato (Boldon, his teammate, training partner and friend)
came over and said, `It's legal, it's legal,' '' Greene said.
``That's when I looked up at the scoreboard.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And smiled. ``Very excited,'' he said. ``I was very excited.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then, he celebrated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who attended Schlagle High in Kansas City, Kan., looked
for an American flag to wave, but couldn't find one. So, he grabbed
the banner of his track club _ Handling Speed Intelligently _ and
basked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of his coaches, Darrell Smith, said that when the scoreboard
flashed the news, ``the place exploded.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There were upward of 40,000 people there,'' Smith said. ``When
he crossed the finish line and everybody looked at the clock, it
became a madhouse. There were television people and photographers
running all over the place.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kansas City, Kan., Greene's first call to his mother
went unanswered. Nobody home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A second call a while later got through. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he said, Jackie Greene was ``very excited'' too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
