<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON IN, EXCUSES OUT FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ A fawning crowd gathered in the hotel
ballroom to fete its candidate. When he arrived, flanked by
security men wearing earpieces and scowls, the applause that
welcomed him left no doubt he was the people's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson received a reception fit for a presidential
candidate Wednesday when he was introduced as the L.A. Lakers' 15th
coach. About the only thing missing was a high school band
serenading him with ``Hail to the Chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's buddy, Bill Bradley, whose quest to become the 43rd
president of the U.S. facilitated the ex-Bulls coach's date with
destiny, would be buoyed beyond belief to feel such love when he
addresses local supporters tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity that Jackson created with his acceptance speech
left one admirer, ex-Lakers great Magic Johnson, gushing, ``I was
sitting there with chills, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind all the goose pimples and applause, beyond the obnoxious,
obsequious blathering of a New York radio-show bozo and the camp
characters trying to pass themselves off as journalists and the
clicking of the cameras, one issue sat unaddressed.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests Jackson has only a slightly better chance of
going all the way with the Lakers than a former NBA player does of
ascending to the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Many fine coaches have drawn X's and O's for more than one NBA
team; Pat Riley, Chuck Daly, Lenny Wilkens, Jack Ramsey and Bill
Fitch, to name just a few. But only one coach has guided two
franchises to the NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. product Alex Hannum coaxed St. Louis to the championship in
1957-58 and cajoled Philadelphia to the crown nine seasons later.
Reached at his home in San Diego Wednesday, Hannum, a product of
Hamilton High and USC, said it's an awfully tall order for anyone,
puncturing the ``superstar aura'' that covers the L.A. basin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole aura of L.A., with its spotlight on superstars, it
hasn't been the right formula,'' Hannum said. ``Personnel-wise, I
think the Lakers have had the players to win (an NBA title) the
last two years. If any coach can get them (over the hump), Phil
Jackson can. He can communicate with the modern athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the Zen master with the Midas touch, can tilt a room
toward him as easily as Shaquille O'Neal or Kobe Bryant. His star
appeal gives him a foot in the door of the Lakers dressing room,
which never opened even a crack for diligent but dull Del Harris or
sassy but suspicious Kurt Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has an edge on his two immediate predecessors in that he
has been the subject of more books than Bryant and he speaks with
as much authority as O'Neal's stepfather, ``Sarge.'' So words
aren't likely to get in the way when he addresses the Lakers' two
young and stubborn stars.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant braved traffic to get here in time to greet Jackson on
Wednesday. He enjoyed a private audience with his new coach before
Jackson met with the press. It was an eloquent gesture by the
20-year-old who is maturing by the minute.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson would later say he is ``intrigued'' by Bryant, who
reminds him ``a lot of Michael Jordan.'' Jackson suggested Bryant
has the same work ethic and competitive spirit as the former Bulls
icon. All he's lacking is experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe is a player still uneducated in basketball and in life,''
Jackson said of the guard who jumped directly from high school to
the NBA in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal didn't make it, but what else is knew?. The Lakers' team
captain also was a no-show for the final team meeting of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably just as well that O'Neal found better things to do
Wednesday. Had he been at the Beverly Hilton, he would have heard
the echoes of Bill Russell in Jackson's observation that the
7-foot-1 center ``can be better, I feel, than he has shown the past
couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   And he would have heard Harris and Rambis being parroted in
Jackson's pronouncement that how well Tex Winter's pass-predicated
triangle offense works for the Lakers will depend on ``how willing
Shaq will be to make his offense not primary but secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannum employed a similar offense in Philadelphia in 1966-67. It
worked like a dream because his big man, Wilt Chamberlain, was
comfortable passing the ball in critical situations. Chamberlain
also switched on defense when he was supposed to, stepping out into
the high post if need be. Indeed, he was a thorn in San Francisco
shooter Nate Thurmond's side throughout the 1967 NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain won two of his four league MVP titles before
Philadelphia's championship season. In one of the 76ers' four
victories in their six-game championship series against San
Francisco, Chamberlain took only six shots. Rick Barry heaved 41 in
the losing effort, leading Chamberlain to note wryly, ``Sometimes
it is actually easier to play against a team that has one man do
most of the shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is _ and this should give Lakers fans a glimmer of
hope _ Chamberlain didn't arrive at that conclusion without a
fight. He and Hannum nearly came to blows in the early 1960s while
arguing the merits of Chamberlain's occasionally serving as a
decoy, the better to involve all of his San Francisco teammates in
the offense.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the two men went at each other and had to be
separated by the other players. By the time they were reunited in
Philadelphia a few years later, Chamberlain was wiser and also
wearier, having been denied time and again the NBA's ultimate
prize.
</P>
<P>
   In his desperation he recognized the point that Jackson raised
Wednesday when he said, ``Basketball is not putting your own self
ahead of the team.'' Wherever O'Neal was, Johnson hopes he got the
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq says he wants to win a championship. Kobe has been saying
the same thing,'' Johnson said. ``OK. We're going to find out if
that's all true. It's all on them now. There are no more
excuses.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
