r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SOCNOTE-LADN-(SLA     06-17 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY'S PANICO AVOIDS LEGEND'S SHADOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CULVER CITY, Calif. _ Throw a United States uniform on her, take
a quick glance and you might mistake Italy's Patrizia Panico for
one of her famous American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   But Panico has more in common with Mia Hamm than merely a slight
facial resemblance. She also has developed into the Italians' best
goal scorer and is labeled as the country's next great player
following the retirement of Carolina Morace two years ago. Panico
makes it clear she is her own player without the pressure of living
in another's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy when they compare me to Carolina,'' Panico said
through an interpreter at the team's hotel Wednesday, ``but I am
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Panico will lead Italy into Sunday's 4 p.m. Women's World Cup
game against Germany at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Panico knows Morace well, having played with the Italian legend
for a year on the national team and later being coached by her on a
Rome-based club team. Morace is one of the world's all-time leading
scorers with 105 international goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being coached by someone who has played in your position,''
Panico said, ``she teaches you all the tricks of the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   But Panico uses quickness and a sly nature in the penalty area
to get the job done, in contrast to Morace, who was more of an
opportunist around the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for her,'' Panico said, ``and what she
did (in her career) is really unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Panico seems poised, however, to pick up where Morace left off.
</P>
<P>
   __ Team to watch: When it comes to Nigeria, much of the
attention has been placed on striker ``Marvelous'' Mercy Akide, who
scored 10 of the team's 28 goals during qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   But as evidenced by the Super Falcons' 4-3 friendly win against
China on Saturday followed by Tuesday's 9-0 rout of a
Torrance-based club team, there is plenty more to consider.
</P>
<P>
   One clear advantage for Nigeria is its speed down the wings and
an ability to run onto through balls with a precision unlike many
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest weapons on every team is speed,'' said
Nigeria coach Ismaila Mabo. ``That is one thing we have been
working on and it is paying dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   An emerging talent is Patience Avre, who scored three goals
against China and created numerous scoring chances Tuesday from the
right wing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mysterious: North Korea, Nigeria's first opponent Sunday, has
earned the reputation of not being cooperative with the media. It
doesn't seem to be any easier for its foes to find out about the
team's tactics, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know much about them and we haven't watched
any film yet,'' Mabo said. ``But we hope to.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Local outing: Italy's only scheduled scrimmage will take
place this afternoon at Loyola Marymount against a collection of
local players, according to press officer Laura Folchi.
</P>
<P>
   __ Going fast: The World Cup opener between the United States
and Denmark on Saturday at East Rutherford, N.J., is approaching a
sellout.
</P>
<P>
   More than 74,000 tickets have been sold for the doubleheader,
which also features Brazil against Mexico. The stadium seats about
77,000 for soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, more than 460,000 tickets have been sold for the
32-game event that concludes in the Rose Bowl on July 10. If the
U.S. team gets that far, the tournament is likely to break a
half-million in attendance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
