A8669 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBER-FAULTS-KAN &LR;      06-17 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBER-FAULTS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Report cites four lingering faults with B-2 bombers  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fresh from its widely praised missions to
Yugoslavia, the Missouri-based B-2 bomber is still taking hits from
government reports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office says testing indicates the B-2
meets most of its operational requirements but still has four
``significant deficiencies that will limit or under some
circumstances slow its pace in flight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone ought to tell those people sitting behind the desk
that the B-2 won the air war,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton, a Democrat
from Lexington, Mo., whose district encompasses Whiteman Air Force
Base, where the stealth bomber is based. ``It did the job. You
can't top what it did.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office's study is its sixth in five years on the
expensive and complex B-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The findings are not new or major, Skelton said Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skelton, ranking Democrat on the House National Security
Committee, joined President Clinton and others at Whiteman last
week to commend the B-2 and its crews for successful bombing
missions over Yugoslavia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report was completed before the air campaign ended. The
B-2 flew only about 1 percent of the missions flown over Yugoslavia
but accounted for 11 percent of the weapons dropped, military
records show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The four deficiencies cited in the report: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Incomplete development of the ground mission planning system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Limited ability of the crew to be aware of enemy threats to
the plane. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Questionable durability of materials intended to keep the
aircraft undetectable to radar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Difficulty operating the plane anywhere but out of Whiteman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A March 1999 Air Force assessment of progress on correcting
the deficiencies confirmed that three of the four had not been
remedied but that one _ development of the ground mission planning
system _ was nearly corrected,'' the report said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the GAO, a Defense Department official concedes
that more work lies ahead in meeting the performance levels desired
for the B-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``However, the department believes that more progress has been
made in some areas than indicated in the GAO report,'' wrote George
R. Schneiter, director of strategic and tactical systems. Schneiter
also disputed the estimated cost of up to $155 million to make
necessary improvements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schneiter said mission plans can be developed within an
eight-hour goal using new hardware and software, but the GAO said
that had not been accomplished as of April 20 this year. Further
progress was later reported but not tested, the GAO said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schneiter acknowledged problems in technology that tells air
crews about threats, but he said it results in limited or reduced
capability, not ``insufficient'' capability as the GAO said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Insufficient implies an inability to perform the mission,
whereas the B-2s are currently participating in combat
operations,'' Schneiter wrote on April 28. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schneiter said improvements to the durability of the
radar-deflecting skin of the plane are being pursued. The need for
repairs diminishes the available flying time, the GAO report said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth problem mentioned in the report, efforts are being
made to acquire maintenance shelters so the planes can stop at
places away from Whiteman if necessary, Schneiter said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said ``the Air force cannot sustain operations at
the level required for eight aircraft over a 14-day period without
shelters'' for indoor maintenance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten B-2s are at Whiteman, and 11 more are in production. Under
the 1994 National Defense Authorization Act, the GAO is required to
make periodic reports on the B-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A defense consultant said the latest report on the B-2
deficiencies should not be a surprise, ]given the aircraft's
complexity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like there is anything there that is
unsolvable,'' said Bill Dane, senior aerospace analyst for Forecast
International in Connecticut. ``It sounds to me like normal
teething. There are always things that turn up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
