<HEADER>
A8673 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-AZR &LR;      06-17 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE ATTACKS BUSH `TRIANGULATION' STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 and CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ GOP presidential hopeful Dan Quayle ripped what
he views as the ``mushy'' message of GOP front-runner George W.
Bush, saying Wednesday that it could lead, at best, to a hollow
victory for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   An intense Quayle compared the Texas governor's unwillingness to
take a stand on many issues to President Clinton's
``triangulation'' strategy designed to seek the middle ground
between the extreme factions of his party. It was developed by
Clinton's former adviser Dick Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans don't win elections trying to be like Bill Clinton
and being Dick Morris Republicans,'' Quayle said in an interview.
``If you are going to run an ambiguous, mushy, equivocating,
triangulation, Dick Morris type of campaign, what good is it to be
elected? You're not really going to change the country. And I want
to change the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who is basing his campaign in Arizona, is trailing Bush
badly in New Hampshire, according to a poll taken last week by the
``Boston Herald.'' It shows that 45 percent of Republican voters in
the state favor Bush, and only 4 percent would vote for Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began campaigning only a few days ago, swinging through
Iowa, Connecticut and New Hampshire, and taking less-than-hardline
stands on abortion and taxes. On Tuesday night in Greenwich, Conn.,
he laid out his ``compassionate conservative'' platform. He
promised to cut taxes, but help people learn to save; to confront
teenage pregnancy, but offer practical help to women in crisis; and
to raise standards in school, but enact programs to ensure no
children are left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say Republicans are backing him so strongly
because they believe his moderate stance will help them regain the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign did not return phone calls Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   In his tour of New Hampshire on Wednesday, Quayle took a ``been
there, done that'' approach to Bush's message of conservative
compassion. Quayle spoke out repeatedly in favor of cutting taxes
and against abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning visit in Manchester to the New Life Home for
Women and Children, a Christian residential program in which women
struggle to overcome such problems as addiction to alcohol and
drugs, Quayle used it as an example of how private operations often
outdo government in such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I call real compassion,'' Quayle said later at a
press conference in Concord. ``These are conservatives out there
working every day, saving lives. Getting people off of drugs and
getting them back on the right road. This goes to prove a point
that I have made over and over again. That conservatives are
compassionate. We care deeply about our friends, our neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   During his public appearances, Quayle was measured in his
criticism of Bush's gospel of moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle left it to former New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, the
national co-chairman of Quayle's campaign, to accuse Bush of trying
to bend with the political winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is trying to be like Clinton,'' Sununu said. ``Bush is
running with the rhetoric of the Clinton campaign that was
successful for Clinton in '92 and '96.''
</P>
<P>
   Sununu, a former chief of staff under Bush's father, President
George Bush, warned that selecting Bush as the GOP's supposed
savior will drive the party into a train wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Still popular in his home state, Sununu is also a notorious
arm-twister, and is believed to be cranking a few limbs behind the
scene in order to swell the ranks of grass-roots activists who
support Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Sununu denied he is working his troops over, but suggested he
would begin calling in chits for Quayle in September or October,
when the campaign season is in full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's trip to New Hampshire was designed to cajole a wide
range of possible supporters: grass-roots activists, legislators
and voters.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the hopeful's efforts have netted him only three
endorsements from state lawmakers. But campaign observers at least
perceive Quayle to have a significant foundation of local workers
in place for the upcoming primary.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle seemed compassionate enough, and impressive as a
candidate, said several people who clasped hands with him
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him to be a very gentle spirit, and he cares about
people,'' said Carole Cadieux, 35, who kicked a cocaine habit to
rebuild her life and become a staff member of the New Life Home.
</P>
<P>
   But even some people who liked Quayle's message and his looks
said they were going to do just what he doesn't want them to do:
vote for Bush because he looks like a winner.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pleasant View Retirement Home in Concord, Sara Edsall,
93, shook Quayle's hand and told him, ``You're as handsome as your
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   But she later told a reporter she wasn't going to vote for him,
because she thought Quayle couldn't be elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to live long enough to get the Republicans back in
office,'' Edsall said. ``I hope we're all going to get in back of
Bush and elect him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
