<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-ALABAMA-RICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUSTED RICE OWLS ENJOY GAME, NOT RESULT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ At the end of a dream yesterday, the Rice Owls
opted for reflection instead of tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great baseball game, and I enjoyed being in it,''
said coach Wayne Graham, after the Owls (59-15) lost a 6-5 College
World Series elimination game to Alabama (53-15). ``The score just
didn't turn out right, that's all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bloop hit won it, but that's how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The bloop _ a sinking fly ball that landed a few feet in front
of charging right fielder Will Ford _ came off the bat of Alabama's
Sam Bozanich, and scored G.W. Keller with the winning run with two
out in the bottom of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The hit came off Mario Ramos (13-3), who had entered the game in
the ninth as the fourth Rice pitcher of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was rested, and he's been our best all year,'' Graham said.
``You wouldn't want to lose a game with him sitting on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, playing in its second CWS in three years, indeed went down
with its best _ including shortstop Damon Thames, who slugged the
Owls back into it with two home runs off Alabama starter Justin
Smith, who allowed only four hits and struck out 12 in eight
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama got a big boost in the third when Rice starter Marc Gwyn
walked the bases full and Keller hit a deep drive into left center.
Left fielder Charles Williams got his glove on the ball, but
couldn't make the catch, and three runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Thames hit a solo shot over the left-field fence in the seventh
to cut the Crimson Tide lead to 4-2, then came up in the eighth
with two runners aboard via walks.
</P>
<P>
   He fouled off four pitches on an 0-2 count, and then the tiring
Smith, who had beaten Oklahoma State on Friday, threw his 125th
pitch of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Thames hit it into the left-field seats, giving the Owls a 5-4
lead and launching Graham into a hopping, leaping celebratory dance
in the third base coaching box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love baseball,'' the 63-year-old coach said. ``I get
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   So did everyone else wearing blue _ but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a moment, we were on top of the world,'' Thames said.
``But we came down fast.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom half, Bozanich walked, was sacrificed to second,
stole third _ one of six successful thefts by the Tide _ and scored
on a wild pitch. Brent Boyd then singled, stole second, and tried
to score the potential winning run on another hit, but was cut down
at the plate on a perfect throw from Ford.
</P>
<P>
   But Andy Phillips, rolling on a 36-game hitting streak, opened
the ninth with his third double, and Keller drew an intentional
walk. The Owls nearly got out of it when Ramos threw Phillips out
at third on a bunt and got a ground ball to short from former
Mansfield High School standout Kelley Gulledge.
</P>
<P>
   But the runners were going with the pitch, averting the double
play and forcing Thames to throw to first. The stage was set for
Bozanich's bloop, which scored Keller from third.
</P>
<P>
   Thames, a coaches National Player of the Year in '98 and one of
three Rice draftees who chose to return for their senior years,
walked away with no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we came back for,'' said Thames, a ninth-round
pick this year by St. Louis. ``We knew we were going to have a
great team and we thought we could get back here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great program, obviously a great education, and it was
a fantastic experience that you'd be crazy to miss. For me, it's
the end of a chapter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
