r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICKS-TEX     06-17 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS' TOWERS STIFLING, BUT JACKSON KEYS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ When the pope visited in 1987, this city put him
in a Stetson.
</P>
<P>
   In case it wants to get a head start with Tim Duncan, he wears
an 8 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by their typically stifling defense and a predictably
dominating edge in the paint, the San Antonio Spurs rode Duncan's
33 points and 16 rebounds for an easy 89-77 victory over the New
York Knicks in Game 1 of the NBA Finals before a raucous crowd of
39,514 last night at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't as easy at it looked, not at all,'' Duncan said. ``I
had to work to get position, but I worked hard. Once I got the
ball, I had a good rhythm going and my shots were falling. Once I
got rolling, my teammates kept coming back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a bigger brother holding his flailing sibling at bay by
simply palming his forehead, the Spurs stymied several Knicks' runs
led by Latrell Sprewell's transition energy by simply pounding the
ball into their Twin Towers and getting five clutch 3-pointers by
Jaren Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   While Duncan and David Robinson combined for 46 points and 25
rebounds, it was Jackson's off-balance 3-pointer which pushed the
Spurs' lead to 74-65 and at least momentarily stopped New York's
huge heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duncan was awesome, but we know he's going to get his
points,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``The one that killed
us with Jackson. We've got to take him away or it's going to be a
short series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goody Two Sneaker Spurs held the Knicks to 38 percent
shooting, a near Finals-record low 10 points in the second quarter
and 14 in the fourth in tying the NBA record with its 11th
consecutive playoff victory.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing without leader Patrick Ewing and with forwards
Larry Johnson and Marcus Camby hobbling with knee injuries, the
Knicks stayed close behind the creativity of Allan Houston and
Sprewell. But when New York closed to within five in the third
quarter, the 7-foot-1 Duncan scored three consecutive times over
the 6-foot-8 Johnson to produce some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks got as close as six again, but Jackson hit his
falling 3-pointer and sealed the victory with another triple in the
final two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jaren's making that shot, we can really click,'' Spurs
coach Gregg Popovich said. ``They chose to leave him open and he
hit some big ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' game plan worked perfectly for 18 minutes, as they
spread the floor for Houston jumpers and allowed Sprewell to attack
the Spurs in transition, sometimes even one-on-four. New York led
27-21 after the first quarter and 35-31 before San Antonio's size
took over.
</P>
<P>
   With Sprewell resting on the bench and his big men piling up
fouls, the Knicks' pace slowed to a walk and, predictably, an
offensive meltdown. In one of the worst quarters in Finals history,
the Knicks went without a point for five minutes, without a field
goal for seven minutes and produced a paltry 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, as they have throughout their playoff stampede, took
advantage of their defensive lockdown. Robinson sparked a 14-2 run
with a block on Chris Dudley, a lob assist on a Duncan layup and
foul-line jumper that propelled the Spurs into a 45-37 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   With San Antonio's interior size turning the Knicks into
jump-shooters, the Spurs held the Knicks to the second-lowest
scoring quarter (10 points, more than only Utah's nine-point fourth
quarter in last year's Game 3) in Finals history in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan dominated in the third quarter and early in the fourth,
almost effortlessly scoring on a variety of spin moves, layups,
offensive rebounds and fadeaway bank-shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still very young, but if he keeps that up, he'll be a
legend here pretty quick,'' Popovich said. ``I hope I have to keep
digging deep to come up with words to describe him. Tonight he was
pretty special.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
