<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' HELLING PUTS UP STOP SIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There will be no debate should a must-win scenario
present itself this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Helling would make that start,'' said Rangers manager
Johnny Oates, who gave no latitude for ambiguity. ``That's the
reason he was our Opening Day pitcher, and he has not done anything
to change my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night could not be considered one of those must-win
situations, but the Rangers breathed a collective sigh of relief
after their 3-0 victory against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers snapped their season-high four-game losing streak
and beat the defending World Series champions for the first time in
eight attempts at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Helling (6-6) pitched seven scoreless innings despite only one
natural 1-2-3 inning, but he retired all six batters he faced with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers needed a hero, and Helling stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   Others emerged, too.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Lee Stevens hit a two-run, second-inning home run
off right-hander Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez (7-6).
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer robbed the Yankees of at least three
hits with his range.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman worked out of a two-on, none-out jam
by retiring three consecutive batters.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland pitched a 1-2-3 ninth inning for his major
league-best 22nd save.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ruben Mateo halted the Rangers' slump with
runners in scoring position at 0-for-26 with his run-scoring,
seventh-inning double. The Rangers are 1-for-32 with runners in
scoring position in five games at Yankee Stadium this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, center stage belonged to Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all starts with starting pitching,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Helling gave no greater demonstration than after surrendering a
third-inning double to third baseman Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   ``A situation like that can get out of hand really quick,'' said
Helling, who improved to 6-3 with a 3.05 earned-run average in his
past 11 starts. ``I did everything in my power to make good pitches
there. I think that was as sharp as I was all night. I don't think
I missed a spot. I think I threw every pitch where I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' No. 2, 3 and 4 hitters _ shortstop Derek Jeter,
right fielder Paul O'Neill and center fielder Bernie Williams _ can
verify that. Helling retired all three on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Helling credit,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``He pitches around the strike zone, and he'll throw enough
pitches up and then throw a couple of knee-high pitches. He got
O'Neill that one inning and Jeter both on knee-high fastballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who surrendered only four hits and two walks, departed
after 123 pitches. The performance again demonstrated why the
Rangers signed Helling to a three-year, $10.5 million contract in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Helling has pitched well for us,'' Oates said. ``I think
he's been the one guy who has went out there and kept us in
ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling also squelched those irritating,
Rangers-can't-beat-the-Yankees post mortems for at least an
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we'll get more,'' Oates said of victories against the
Yankees. ``It's not the first. It won't be the last.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
