<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALK DEFENDANT: `THERE'S NO WAY I COULD DO THAT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Scott Falater, fighting a charge that he murdered his
wife in a coldblooded act of mayhem, cried Wednesday and told the
jury a love story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people talk about their spouse as their right arm,'' said
the man who claims he was sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife 44
times. ``She was like both my arms, and my legs, half my head and
all of my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater repeatedly choked back tears as he took the stand before
a packed courtroom and a grim-faced jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to do without her,'' Falater said. Then he
covered his mouth with his hand, his chest heaving in muffled sobs.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Michale Kimerer's first question went to the
core of the trial: Did Falater have any reason to murder Yarmila?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Falater responded firmly. ``There's no way I could do
that. Not intentionally. I loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater's hope for acquittal hinges on whether the jury is
convinced that he was asleep and not acting deliberately when he
killed his wife of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   As his tears flowed in Maricopa County Superior Court, Falater
reached for a handkerchief to dry his eyes and wipe his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really my only confidant and she was by far my best
friend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do without her. She was
probably virtually all of my emotional life.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Motorola engineer will return to the stand today to
continue his testimony under the gentle direction of Kimerer, a
big, bearded man who asked his questions in a tone of pained
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   Then he will face cross-examination from prosecutor Juan
Martinez, who has repeatedly attacked the professional credibility
and personal integrity of defense witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's tender story of his love affair with Yarmila provided
a stark and strange counterpoint to the trial's repeated discussion
of the night in 1997 that ended with her body floating in the
crimson waters of the family's backyard pool.
</P>
<P>
   Falater talked of his high school infatuation with the spunky
girl who spoke her mind and helped him manage the trauma of an
Illinois home life wrecked by his father's violent alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   ``She helped me a lot to deal with those feelings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marriage seemed inevitable, he said, smiling as he recalled
Yarmila's plucky reaction when he dropped to a knee to propose
while they were still in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Of course. What were you waiting for?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The young couple lived first in Chicago, then moved to Florida
and on to Minnesota as Scott pursued his career in engineering and
Yarmila dedicated herself to rearing their two children.
</P>
<P>
   Falater said the repeated moves were difficult for his wife, who
struggled to adjust and made friends slowly. But the family found
comfort in the Mormon Church, he said, ridiculing the prosecution's
claim that Yarmila resented the church's demands upon her time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say she didn't like her involvement in the church is utter
hogwash,'' Falater said.
</P>
<P>
   What about Martinez's suggestion that the couple had argued over
Scott's desire to have more children, Kimerer asked.
</P>
<P>
   Falater responded that he created a standing family joke about
wanting more kids because he and Yarmila had done so well with
Megan and Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted more children than she did, but I also realized that
she ended up with 90 percent of the job there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of pushing Yarmila, Falater said, he defused the
issue with humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started urging my kids to have their kids so we could be
grandparents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what about about Martinez's idea that Scott's interest in
Yarmila had cooled because she gained a lot of weight, Kimerer
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like large women,'' Falater shrugged. ``It only
impacted me because she was upset at how large she was. . . . She
might have been large, but she was always beautiful to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater admitted that Yarmila had been unhappy when the family
moved to Phoenix in 1987. With prodding from a bishop, he committed
himself to building a stable home life and told Yarmila he would
become a taxi driver rather than subject her to another move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Make all the friends you want; they're going to be
yours as long as they're around.' ''
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Falater said, ``Our marriage got better and
better and was better than ever at the time of her death.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he dreams constantly about Yarmila in his cell at
the Maricopa County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I open my eyes and see the jail walls and realize what's
happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's testimony came after the jury submitted to the last
defense expert more than dozen written questions that suggested
skepticism about the defense case.
</P>
<P>
   Could Falater have planned the killing to make it appear to have
occurred while he was sleepwalking?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some pieces of the evidence are not fakeable,'' responded Dr.
Rosalind Cartwright, a psychologist and director of a sleep
disorder center in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   How could Cartwright know that Falater was actually sleepwalking
that night of Yarmila's death? That conclusion is ``a deduction . .
. from all the pieces we put together,'' Cartwright said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
