<SLUG> BC-RAINIER-STRESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES AT MOUNT RAINIER PARK MAKING SOME CLIMBERS, HIKERS GO
ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Washington's high hiking places have long been seen as
a spot to escape crowds, controls and congestion.
</P>
<P>
   But the 235,612 acres of Mount Rainier National Park have become
the state's most closely regulated and most jammed alpine
environment _ from the packed parking lot at Paradise to climbers
squeezed in at the Thumb Rock bivouac site, 10,775 feet up on
Liberty Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulation of Mount Rainier is pretty extreme and the
issue driving it is the number of people wanting to partake of a
fabulous place,'' said Tim McNulty, co-author of ``Washington's
Mount Rainier National Park: A Centennial Celebration'' (The
Mountaineers, 144 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   So regulated is Mount Rainier that many hikers and backcountry
campers are taking their feet elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   And even more strict regulations are on the horizon, including a
possible limit on personal vehicles allowed inside the park.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy use is the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2.2 million people will visit the park this year,
as it celebrates its centennial.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 visitors will venture out onto a trail for at
least a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Up on the mountain, the National Park Service recorded 11,118
climbers last year.
</P>
<P>
   The park is drawing up a 20-year management plan to establish
``visitor carrying capacities,'' designed to prevent both damage to
alpine environments and frayed human nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be managed a lot more than it is, particularly
during times of peak use,'' said John Wilcox, wilderness district
ranger in charge of climbing and back-country maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would anticipate during those peak periods, the traffic will
be heavily managed, and there may be limits to how many personal
vehicles are allowed in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   National parks are an idea that America gave the world.
Americans insist on seeing their nation's scenic crown jewels,
arriving in ever-increasing numbers at parks long starved for
money.
</P>
<P>
   Several parks have already resorted to shuttle buses at peak
points and periods of use. Private cars are banned over most of the
80-mile road in Alaska's Denali National Park. A shuttle system on
the south rim of Grand Canyon National Park ``assured that visitors
experience something other than gridlock and carbon monoxide,''
said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service is drawing up a plan on how to handle
the 4 and a half million yearly visitors to California's narrow
Yosemite Valley. The park currently limits entry of private cars at
peak use periods.
</P>
<P>
   At Mount Rainier, backcountry camping has been stringently
regulated since 1973. The Park Service long ago imposed camping
limits on the mountain's two most popular climbing routes.
Recently, it has limited overnight use at Camp Hazard on the Kautz
Glacier route, and put a cap of 12 people a night at Thumb Rock.
</P>
<P>
   The rules have critics, particularly among backpackers. Camping
along trails is allowed only at designated sites.
</P>
<P>
   Campsites were put in what Wilcox calls ``durable areas,''
largely in forest and well below the famous meadows, high lakes and
moraines of the mountain. For many hikers, ``durable'' translates
to dull.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put camps so far from the scenery,'' said Ira Spring,
renowned Northwest photographer and coauthor of ``50 Hikes in Mount
Rainier National Park'' (The Mountaineers, 144 pages, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``The sunsets, with their brilliant colors, are one of the
mountain's premier attractions _ but campsites are so far away
(from good viewing spots) that you stumble back in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   The heavy-handed regulatory environment is chasing people away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very controlled hiking experience, and perhaps has to
be for the number of people,'' said Rick McGuire, a Seattle hiker
and conservationist. ``I would rather hike where I can go where I
want and camp where I want.''
</P>
<P>
   John Zilavy, a Seattle attorney, drove up to Mount Rainier with
friends in 1997. They planned to hike a fabled chunk of the
round-the-mountain Wonderland Trail through the meadows of
Summerland, up over Fryingpan Gap and down to Indian Bar.
</P>
<P>
   All campsites on the route were full, however, and Zilavy's
party found itself sent off to Palisades Lakes, a remote area with
no views of the mountain, near the northeast corner of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all backcountry, it's all wilderness and I didn't mind
getting shunted off to an area I found fascinating,'' Zilavy said.
``Still, it really screwed up our plan, and it would have been a
lot tougher on people who had come here from elsewhere in the
country with the dream of going to a particular place on the
mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   A new system has gone into effect this year. Mount Rainier
National Park is taking advance reservations for backcountry
campsites. Up to 60 percent of sites are reservable up to two
months in advance of a backpacking trip or a climb of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 40 percent will be filled on a first-come,
first-served basis on the day of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   A reservation costs $20 per party per trip. (The park can be
contacted by by e-mail at morawilderness &LR; nps.gov for backcountry
sites; or by phone at 360-569-4453 for backcountry sites and
climbing, 800-365-2267 for front-country car camping sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new system sounds saner,'' said author Bruce Barcott, who
had to gamble on dates as he hiked the Wonderland Trail while
writing his book ``The Measure of a Mountain: Beauty and Terror on
Mount Rainier'' (Sasquatch, 278 pages, $23.95).
</P>
<P>
   Barcott was irritated at some rangers he encountered on
backcountry trails. He developed a lot more admiration for the
approach of the park's climbing rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure most hikers have had the experience of walking down a
trail, and having a ranger grill you more than necessary about
where you are going and what your plans are,'' Barcott said. ``The
answer you feel like giving is, `It's none of your business and I
don't know.' ... It's their job, but part of you bristles at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The climbing rangers, he found, were far less intrusive,
generally content just to check in and give briefings on route
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were the least parental rangers in the park,''
Barcott said. ``They are the people who have to risk their lives if
you get in trouble, but they make an effort not to act like big
brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Mount Rainier was the first national park in the country to
allow cars, about 60 of which arrived by muddy road in 1907. The
car craze proved to be what author Ruth Kirk called ``an
unstoppable flood.'' President William Howard Taft was driven to
Paradise in 1911, although mules had to pull his car part of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Finding one of the 758 parking spots at today's Paradise can be
a midsummer afternoon's nightmare. The lots at Paradise, and
sometimes Sunrise, fill up by noon on summer and holiday weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Spaces are generally plentiful on weekdays. At peak use periods,
however, ``We just can't get 'em all up there in the way they want
to get up there,'' said the park's chief planner, Eric Walkinshaw.
</P>
<P>
   The park seems loathe to bar the automobile if planners can
avoid it. A shuttle bus system is economically questionable.
Instead, park planners are looking at ways to warn Rainier-bound
visitors that parking lots are full, and suggest other places to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to it is getting people information long before they
get to the park,'' said Walkinshaw.
</P>
<P>
   Other road problems at Mount Rainier National Park are working
to shunt visitors onto the heavily used routes up to Paradise and
Sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, there are two problems at Mount Rainier National
Park over which its managers have no control: The park is small,
and the 14,411-foot mountain is a magnet.
</P>
<P>
   The national park was created largely with straight-line
boundaries, long before recreation and conservation planners began
to look at drawing boundaries with an eye to protecting entire
valleys and safeguarding both winter and summer habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the park ``protects'' is rocks and ice, land that
the Northern Pacific Railroad happily traded a century ago for
productive lowland forests in southwest Oregon. The lush,
low-elevation forests west and north of Mount Rainier have been
transformed into a sea of clearcuts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, however, Congress did protect the remaining unlogged
and unroaded valleys by designating five wilderness areas bordering
on or near Mount Rainier National Park.
</P>
<P>
   If visitors are willing to step back from the densely visited
park areas and head into the national forest wilderness, Mount
Rainier can be enjoyed without the crowds, the congestion and the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Spring identifies several short hikes outside the national
park that provide perspective and breathtaking panoramas on the
Northwest's greatest volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Bearhead Mountain, in the Clearwater Wilderness, delivers an
eye-popping view of the mile-high Willis Wall. The Glacier View
Lookout is a premier spot to watch sunset colors. High Rock, south
of Rainier, has bottom-to-top vistas and an unmatched experience of
mountain light at both the beginning and end of day.
</P>
<P>
   But people just keep coming, coming and coming. Mount Rainier
National Park may even figure in next year's race for the White
House. Vice President Al Gore wants to climb the mountain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
