<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     06-17 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JACKSON FIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Only in the mystical, magical world of
Phil Jackson, all Native American symbolism and perfect Zen
moments, could a career move happen this way.
</P>
<P>
   There he was, fishing in Alaska, thousands of miles from his
dream job in Los Angeles and completely unaware of the negotiations
between his agent and the Lakers. Then the news came, from the
mouths of babes. Or, rather, a young Eskimo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a little Eskimo village, coming off the river after
fishing, and some kid came out and said, `I hear you're the coach
of the Lakers,' '' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, Jackson ended his one-year basketball
sabbatical and resumed his storied coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   By late Sunday night, back home in Montana, Jackson's agent
confirmed the kid's story _ that, indeed, he was just a few clauses
and pen strokes away from coaching the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, an agreement in principle was reached. By Wednesday
morning _ at 10:57 Pacific Daylight Time, to be exact _ he had
signed for five years and $30 million to take over the only team he
wanted to coach after leaving the Chicago Bulls last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a very lucky man today,'' Jackson said at his noon
coronation ceremony at the posh Beverly Hilton. ``I think this was
a marriage that was in the making, and of all the jobs that were
out there this year, this is the one that piqued my interest.''
</P>
<P>
   More so than a return to the New York Knicks, where he won two
championships as a player. More so than a partnership with the New
Jersey Nets, who were prepared to make him the richest coach in the
land.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lakers, Jackson saw the best of opportunities _ to
recapture a moment in time, or more precisely an era. In the
Lakers, he sees the same promise he saw 10 years ago when he
embarked on a nine-year run with the Bulls that netted six
championships and an aura of success that could put him in the Hall
of Fame without ever coaching again.
</P>
<P>
   But here he is, looking to start another three-peat with a
supremely gifted, if underachieving and underdeveloped team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that is talented, it's young, it's on the
verge. It's been on the verge, but it hasn't been able to get over
the top,'' Jackson said. ``That's a similar situation to what
happened 10 years ago in Chicago, and we hope to have the same type
of success here.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen, of course. But with
able stand-ins in Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, whom Jackson
said ``reminds me a lot of Michael Jordan, and there's not too many
players who have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant greeted Jackson at the hotel Wednesday, then quietly
slipped away. But both Bryant and O'Neal have enthused about
Jackson's arrival. And by all accounts, Jackson is exactly what the
Lakers _ who were swept out of the playoffs two years straight _
need.
</P>
<P>
   Del Harris lost the players' interest. His replacement, Kurt
Rambis, lost their confidence. In Jackson, the millionaire
20-somethings have a leader who commands instant respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' agreed general manager Mitch Kupchak. ``I mean,
the X's and O's of the game, the triangle offense, those are all
key, important things. But there are literally dozens of NBA
coaches who are great X's and O's coaches. . . . We needed more
than that. We needed a certain presence and somebody to respect
when he spoke in the locker room. That was the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will install the passing-reliant, movement-oriented
triangle offense made famous by the Bulls. And he said O'Neal,
Bryant and Glen Rice, a potential free agent, will all fit
perfectly in that system.
</P>
<P>
   He also was decidedly blunt in his assessment of his new
proteges. That O'Neal is not yet a leader, and that he must learn
to pass more and score less. That Bryant, while already a force at
age 20, is ``uneducated in basketball and in life.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jackson's challenges are clearly laid out. And on a team with
three guys who demand the ball, his selfless triangle system could
be stretched to its limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who likes to play basketball in a team-oriented system
will find this very easy to play in and very enjoyable,'' Jackson
said. ``It's a player-run offense, it's not a coach telling a team
what he wants out there on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson beamed under the spotlights, the Lakers family stood
in the wings beaming at his confidence and his words. Part-owner
Magic Johnson was there, along with two of owner Jerry Buss'
children, Forum president Jeanie Buss and assistant GM Jim Buss.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss could not attend the ceremony, but Jerry West,
standing proud, offered thanks to the owner for making the
financial investment that could finally restore the franchise's
past glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a very exciting day for us,'' said West,
calling Jackson ``a preeminent coach in America.''
</P>
<P>
   His arrival happened more easily than anyone could have
anticipated. Jackson wanted to be here, but Buss had to commit the
dollars for a premier coach, something he's never done. Once Buss
decided to make that commitment, he had West contact Jackson-agent
Todd Musburger about two weeks ago. The rest happened quickly, in
what Musburger called ``an ideal negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lakers have restored, at the very least, a sense of
stability. Each of the last three seasons ended with speculation
over the coaching situation _ first with Harris, who eventually was
fired, then with Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have to worry, at the end of the season,
about coaches anymore. I think for all of us, that certainly is a
help,'' West said. Of the once-nagging questions about the coaching
position, he added, ``That will never be asked again as long as
he's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stability seems guaranteed. Wins and championships, those are of
course expected to follow. But Jackson, as others have before him,
preached patience to a city starved for a victory parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an educational process,'' he said. ``So to set goals of
60 wins or whatever this next season would not be appropriate,
because it could take this young team two months to learn how to
play together in a system of offense. But the end results are going
to be fine. I'm very confident of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
