<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNCAN LEADS SPURS TO 89-77 VICTORY OVER KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Spurs' cerebral Tim Duncan tilted his chin
down and saw the ragged beard and bulky knee brace on a tattered
and hardly agile Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The math was easy. Duncan spent a stretch of the fourth quarter
picking on the hampered Johnson for awhile before he moved on to
the next Knick who dared to cover him. They came and went and each
plunged into foul trouble as Duncan overwhelmed the revolving door
of Knicks on his way to scoring 33 points and grabbing 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan was part of a Spurs team that flaunted their good health,
solid depth and looming size until the patchwork Knicks frayed at
the edges and came undone, 89-77, at the Alamodome during Game 1 of
the National Basketball Association finals on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Knicks had an unfamiliar look of exasperation as
they departed the court as the loser of a Game 1 on the road for
the first time in their improbable playoff run. They became
flustered by their foul trouble, and grew uncharacteristically
frantic at the finish.
</P>
<P>
   `'I thought we were frenetic offensively,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy
said. `'We were trying to create shots so hard, I thought we were
playing at such a pace that we lacked poise.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston went from asserting himself against Mario Elie to
losing that edge with just 2 of his 19 points in the fourth
quarter. Latrell Sprewell went from creating turnovers and
transition opportunities through three quarters to making mistakes
and pulling up for way too many jumpers at the end, finishing with
3 of his 19 points in the fourth quarter. That helped turn a
6-point lead by the Spurs with 8 minutes 33 seconds left in the
game into a 15-point bulge with 2:22 left in the game. And there
was nothing the Knicks could do to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   `'I started off good because offensively, we were in better
flow,'' said Houston, who scored 14 points in the first half. `'The
second half, we were frantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was an example of this. He had a full head of steam as
long as the Knicks were getting out on the fast break, and the
layups were coming easy. But once the Spurs' shot-blocking picked
up and the Knicks' defense wore down, Sprewell seemed to rattle
just a bit, particularly on defense.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when he lost Jaren Jackson in transition, and
wound up watching him launch a 3-pointer to cut off whatever
momentum the Knicks had mustered. There were times when he lost
control of the ball by trying to make too much happen and ended the
night with six turnovers. .
</P>
<P>
   `'Jaren Jackson was big,'' said Sprewell, who shot 1 for 8 in
the fourth quarter as a part of a 22 percent effort by the team
down the stretch. `'Mario Elie made some shots. Those guys were
huge. We have to regroup. We expect their big guys to get some
points, but we have to pay more attention to the others.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to stay aggressive with foul trouble. The Knicks
had fouls hanging on them like a tree decked with ornaments. By the
end of the game, Johnson and Marcus Camby had five fouls, while
Kurt Thomas and Chris Childs were on edge with four fouls. And
Houston played most of the second half with three.
</P>
<P>
   Fouls brought hesitation, and any timid stance was at the mercy
of Duncan and David Robinson, who added 13 points, 9 rebounds, 3
blocks and delivered 7 assists, finding the man cutting to the
basket all night.
</P>
<P>
   `'That's what he does,'' Duncan siad. `'He doesn't have to score
big amounts for us. On any given night he can do that. When he goes
out and gives us defensive intensity and changes people's shots, it
changes the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The game turned when the Spurs went on a 13-4 run that began in
the middle of the fourth quarter. It was Robinson and Duncan, and
then a big 3-pointer by Jackson to put the Spurs ahead, 87-72, with
2:22 left.
</P>
<P>
   `'They have great size and strength and quickness,'' Van Gundy
said. `'We're going to have to have some better answers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to come up with those answers when attrition through
foul trouble began to creep up on an already thin Knicks lineup in
need of the man in the gray suit on the bench, Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   `'It's tough for them because they are hurt,'' Duncan said.
`'But they are physical, and they can do the job on us on any given
night.''
</P>
<P>
   It's wasn't Camby's night to pull off that trick. Camby couldn't
fill the void on his own, not like he had in the Knicks' previous
series with the Indiana Pacers. He was a live body, who brought
energy and soared inside for dunks off missed layups, and even came
up with a blocked shot in 23 foul-plagued moments. He could help
keep the Knicks close for only so long.
</P>
<P>
   `'I got in foul trouble early,'' Camby said. `'It's not
something I'm used to. David and Tim, they're definitely
exceptional. We had a very hard time stopping them.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter who tried. At the frustrating end, Johnson limped off
after scoring 5 points and grabbing 1 rebound and went straight to
the trainer's room after the game. He was a haggard symbol of a
ragged night by the Knicks, not accustomed to coming up empty in
Game 1s.
</P>
<P>
   `'At this point, it make us more hungry,'' Houston said. `'We
can't expect to win every Game 1 because we've done it in the past.
We have to come out and keep trying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
