<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK RESTED, READY TO BE TESTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park traveled to Oakland, spent the
pregame shagging balls or taking grounders or throwing in the
bullpen. He was with the Dodgers, but he certainly didn't feel that
way.
</P>
<P>
   It was worse since the Dodgers were losing. Park didn't pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last seven games I was really bored,'' Park said. ``I feel
really ashamed of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Park admitted the last seven games have been some of the
toughest of his professional career, and he didn't even throw a
pitch. The right-hander was serving a seven-game suspension for his
part in a fight with Anaheim's Tim Belcher. The suspension ended
with Wednesday's game against the Pirates, which Park watched from
the stands, and his new hope is the imposed rest invigorates his
season. Park starts the series finale against the Pirates tonight
at Dodger Stadium with the hope of putting the first two months of
the season behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The cerebral Park, who is 4-3 with a 4.84 ERA, said he made sure
the time off helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``For myself, it was a good time,'' Park said. ``I feel a little
stronger than before. It was a very good experience for myself and
it made me feel stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Park missed one start and was fined $3,000 by the National
League after punching and then hitting Belcher with a flying kick
during his June 5 start against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rookies ready: If the Dodgers are going to surge soon,
rookies Jamie Arnold and Angel Pena need to play an important role.
Arnold took over Darren Dreifort's spot in the rotation and will
pitch Saturday against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love starting,'' said Arnold, a former No. 1 pick by
Atlanta. ``When I was with the Braves, I came up through the
organization as a starter. I said I didn't care what got me to the
major leagues. I didn't care. If the chance to start came up, that
would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Angel Pena is the new No. 1 catcher, taking over for
Todd Hundley on Tuesday. Pena said he's got much more confidence
than he had during his six-game stint last September in which he
hit .231.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Scioscia (the manager at Triple-A Albuquerque) worked me
hard every day down there,'' said Pena, who's hitting .214 since
joining the Dodgers on May 18. ``I had to do something every day,
like blocking balls, even when I wasn't catching. I'm ready now.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Arizona talks heat up: Representatives of the Fort McDowell
Indian Community presented a new proposal to the Dodgers regarding
a spring-training facility near Phoenix, Ariz. The new proposal is
for baseball facilities only, but there is room for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the ideas were very conceptual,'' Dodgers president and
CEO Bob Graziano said. ``(Wednesday) was to get more specific of
what the proposal contained.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the Dodgers said they wanted on-site housing,
particularly for their minor-leaguers. However, Graziano said that
can change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to listen to that,'' Graziano said. ``No other
major-league team has on-site housing. It's convenient for
minor-league players. . . . Maybe they can accommodate that with a
hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian community is talking about building a hotel and golf
courses on the barren land. But Graziano said there's no hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we think there's a better deal to be made in six months,
we'll wait,'' Graziano said. ``We don't have a lease that expires
in Vero Beach, so we don't have to rush.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Meeting of minds: Dodgers manager Davey Johnson and general
manager Kevin Malone spent much of the pregame in a closed-door
meeting. Malone and Johnson said the discussion was on the general
mood of the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make sure we have things squared away and we
know how each other is doing,'' Malone said. ``I wanted to see what
his thinking is, what he's feeling. He's been great, positive,
still believes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
