<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLING OUTDUELS HERNANDEZ AS RANGERS DOWN YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez had another effective outing for
the New York Yankees and continued to prove that he can still be
that same ornery and baffling pitcher who blazed through the
American League as if it were the American Legion last year.
</P>
<P>
   His manager, Joe Torre, saw how much crisper the Yankees can
look when their starter is reliable. Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   There was one important element that ruined Hernandez's night.
Rick Helling was a lot better. No matter how competent Hernandez
was, it did not really matter because the right-hander for Texas
dominated the Yankees for seven innings and made sure their offense
was anything but crisp in guiding the Rangers to an impressive 3-0
victory at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Rangers, like the Yankees, are leading their
division, they have developed an inferiority complex against the
defending champions after having lost 6 of 7 games against New York
this season and 14 of the last 18 regular-season meetings. Add the
three-game sweep by New York in the 1998 division series and the
Yankees had grabbed 17 of the last 21 meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're obviously a good club,'' Torre said. ``We've been
fortunate against them.''
</P>
<P>
   For one night, though, the Rangers ruled. Lee Stevens socked a
monstrous two-run homer off El Duque into the right-field bleachers
in the second inning and Helling thwarted the Yankees with a strong
fastball, a sweet curveball and precise control.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had numerous scoring opportunities, but the magical
Helling performed like David Copperfield in making them disappear;
he allowed no hits in six at-bats with runners in scoring position
and just four hits overall.
</P>
<P>
   After Helling departed, the Yankees used a walk and an infield
error in the eighth to bring the potential tying run up against
Jeff Zimmerman with none out. But Zimmerman, a rookie who might be
the finest setup man in the league, was just as fierce as Helling
as he got Paul O'Neill to line to left, struck out Bernie Williams
and retired Tino Martinez on a groundout. The Yankees finished an
abysmal 0 for 9 with men in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not getting good swings against him,'' Torre said of
Helling. ``That's what it's all about. He changes speeds well on
his fastball. He has a curveball and a changeup. It looked like he
had everything tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who is 4-2 with a 1.99 ERA in his last six starts,
had one forgettable sequence in the second. After jumping ahead of
Juan Gonzalez with two strikes, Hernandez picked at the strike zone
and walked the Rangers' cleanup hitter.
</P>
<P>
   With Hernandez pitching from the stretch for the first time, he
tossed a weak changeup, and Stevens hammered it 419 feet. ``The
location was a little bit high,'' Hernandez explained. ``It was a
good pitch to hit. I made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The fan who whipped the ball back onto the field did not know it
then, but the hit basically decided the game. Ruben Mateo had a
run-scoring double in the seventh off Hernandez, who yielded three
runs and five hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Derek Jeter dived for Todd Zeile's low liner and
landed awkwardly on his left elbow and collarbone. Jeter remained
sprawled on the dirt for a few seconds before slowly standing up,
causing second baseman Luis Sojo to wave into the dugout for
assistance. But, after Jeter grimaced a few times and flexed his
arm a few times, he stayed in the game. Everyone affiliated with
the Yankees exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter seemed fine, but the Yankees were not. Helling, who had
allowed three earned runs in his last 18 2/3 innings, somehow had
one loss and two no-decisions during that span. But he ended that
drought and won for the first time since May 26 against a team he
beat once while going 20-7 last season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees want to remember how and why they lost this game,
they could start the review in the first inning. After Jeter
singled and O'Neill walked, the Yankees were in position to damage
Helling. But Helling retired Williams and Martinez on fly balls to
left.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees trailing, 2-0, in the third, Scott Brosius, the
leadoff man for one night, opened by tucking a ball into the
right-field corner for a double. Once again, Helling was in a
sticky situation. But he struck out Jeter, O'Neill and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees left Jeter at second in the fifth, and Martinez was
inexplicably picked off first base to finish the sixth. By then, it
was obvious that it was Helling's night, not Hernandez's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always confident,'' the Yankees' Cuban right-hander
said. ``The day I'm not confident, I'm going home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
