<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
 
McCLURE PREPARED TO TAKE THE TWO-CAR WINSTON CUP PLUNGE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry McClure has begun the countdown he hopes will keep his
racing team off NASCAR's endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   A single-car owner in a sport where survival now is measured in
two-, three- and five-car budgets, McClure is in the midst of a
sponsor and driver search suitable for the launch of a second
Winston Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   McClure's target date is ``sometime in July,'' the official
start of the schedule's second half and unofficial beginning of the
silly season for rampant rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Mark this down as fact: You can hardly win in Winston Cup racing
without a teammate any more. That point dramatically was hammered
home during 1998. Led by Jeff Gordon's single-season, record-tying
13 victories, multiple-car teams won 29 of 33 events. Bobby Labonte
was crowned single-car team ``champion'' with two rousing victories
last year. Team owner Joe Gibbs was so giddy at that success ratio
that he added rookie Tony Stewart and millions of Home Depot's
dollars to prop up his Pontiac program.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte (sixth) and Hamilton (10th) were the only single-car
drivers to wind up among the top 10 in points at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton and Ricky Rudd _ one of the dwindling members of the
once-trendy owner/driver ranks _ were the other single-car entities
to score Cup victories last year. Neither Hamilton nor Rudd has
come close to sniffing the rarefied fumes of Victory Lane during
the season's first 14 races. In fact, heading into the Pocono 500
at Pocono (Pa.) Raceway this weekend, no single-car team has won a
Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   Only one single-car operation, Bill Davis Racing with persistent
Ward Burton, is listed among the drivers' top 10. And Davis has
begun grooming Dave Blaney, former World of Outlaws Sprint Car
champion and his current Busch Grand National driver, for a
full-time Cup ride in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As we have seen with the disparate results racked up by team
owner Jack Roush's five-car fleet of Ford Tauruses in 1998-99, more
is not automatically better for all hands. At a time when NASCAR is
strictly controlling test dates, the primary sponsor pool is
beginning to dry up by some accounts and computers are spewing out
reams of information, more is just more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The multi-car team is here to stay,'' said McClure, whose No.
4 Kodak Film Chevrolet Monte Carlo has become a series fixture. As
recently as 1995, however, McClure won three races with driver
Sterling Marlin. After going 0-for-1997 with Marlin, McClure hired
Hamilton away from Richard Petty's No. 43 STP team, which then was
a single-car deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is 15th in points and dutifully waiting on a teammate
whom McClure might summon from the Winston Cup, Busch Grand
National, Craftsman Truck or Indy Racing League ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because expectations in Winston Cup are at an all-time
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your sponsor's expectations are high. My expectations are
high. Bobby Hamilton's expectations are high,'' McClure said of his
team based in Abingdon, Va. ``I don't need to do it personally. But
for this team to survive, we need that two-car team.''
SPOTLIGHT ON...Kay Keselowski
Woman owner earns respect in truck series
With an assist from her famous husband, Teresa Earnhardt paved the
way for successful women team owners in NASCAR's Craftsman Truck
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Earnhardt owned the No. 16 NAPA Chevrolet pickup that Ron
Hornaday Jr. steered to series championships in 1996 and 1998. That
husband Dale Earnhardt is a seven-time Cup champion unquestionably
accelerated that team's development.
</P>
<P>
   But Kay Keselowski and her not-as-famous racing husband, Bob,
are beginning to make headlines. That was the case Friday night,
when Dennis Setzer won the Pronto Auto Parts 400K at Texas Motor
Speedway in the No. 1 Mopar Performance Dodge owned by Kay
Keselowski.
</P>
<P>
   Setzer stands fifth in series points after 10 events, and has
finished in the top five in four of the past five races. Setzer
also has led laps in five of the past six events, assisted by
spotter Kay Keselowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of drivers would have a problem with a woman spotter,
but we have a great relationship,'' Kay Keselowski said. ``It helps
me feel like I'm part of that race, and I have something to do with
winning and losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Keselowski's team is only the second non-NASCAR Winston Cup
Series affiliated outfit to win races in three consecutive seasons
(1997-99).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty excited to be where we're at,'' said Kay
Keselowski, whose husband is a former Automobile Racing Club of
America stock car champion and Truck series regular. ``We can't
match resources with the Hendrick's and Childress' and Earnhardt's
_ there's no way for us to do that. So we have to draw on our
knowledge and the fact that Bob and \Rteam manager\S Ron Keselowski
have been hands-on their whole lives. It's difficult. But we try
real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Keselowski said she had never been to a racetrack before she
met and eventually married Bob 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw this zinger at me, called racing,'' she said. ``Why
in the world would you ... I didn't understand it at all. I didn't
know who Richard Petty was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Kay Keselowski now deals with King Richard as a
fellow Dodge truck owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely in the minority; there's only a couple of us
women \Rowners\S out there,'' she said. ``But I haven't thought
about being `accepted.' I do what I need to do to make this a
successful team.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
Miller gets BGN ride
Team owner Darwin Oordt hired his third driver of the NASCAR Busch
Grand National Series yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR veteran Butch Miller will be in and Stanton Barrett out
as driver of the No. 40 Channellock Chevrolet Monte Carlo when the
series visits Watkins Glen, N.Y., for the Lysol 200 on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who replaced Kerry Earnhardt after the season's seventh
race, was upset that Oordt had hired Miller to drive on the Glen's
2.45-mile road-course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though that's just one race, I felt like it would be
devastating to what we've been trying to build,'' Barrett said.
``You don't change drivers in midstream when things are going well,
no more than you change crew chiefs or engine-builders.''
</P>
<P>
   Oordt said he made the move in a bid to run up front and
generate more TV exposure for his sponsor.
Setzer goes to school
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge Boys never have won a NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series
road-race, going 0-for-11 in that category since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to snap that streak, five Dodge drivers attended
Skip Barber's three-day road course academy in Sebring, Fla., at
the end of April. The group traded their 3,400-pound trucks for
1,100-pound Formula Dodge open-cockpit cars for lessons from chief
instructor Terry Earwood and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this driver is more ready than he's ever been,'' said
Dennis Setzer, winner of the Pronto Auto Parts 400K at Texas Motor
Speedway on Friday night. ``We also went to a small track in
Georgia \RJune 1-2\S and tested our road-race truck, which I've
never done. That's a big ace in the hole for us. Because any
right-hand corner is a major thought for left-hand racers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Truck series will run the first of back-to-back road-course
events at Portland (Ore.) International Raceway tomorrow.
CART also hits `road'
</P>
<P>
   The road-course season also begins for the Championship Auto
Racing Teams FedEx Series this weekend with the Budweiser/G.I.
Joe's 200 at Portland International Raceway. Ten of the next 12
CART events are to be run on either road or temporary street
courses. Fried begins therapy Crew chief Steve Fried has begun a
physical therapy program after his release from Methodist Hospital
in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Fried, crew chief for Energizer Motorsports rookie Robby McGehee
in the Pep Boys Indy Racing League, suffered head and chest injures
in a pit road accident during the Indy 500 on May 30. The immediate
focus will be for Fried to regain his strength and balance.
Last words
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is best described as three straightaways of sheer
boredom, and three turns of sheer fear.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ken Schrader, commenting on the triangular, 2.5-mile Pocono
(Pa.) Raceway
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
