<HEADER>
A8700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-HNS     06-17 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux may be able to tell their sad stories
of struggle to the rest of the National League. They may even be
able to get a little sympathy in a few of those locales.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the rivers they cry won't flow through Houston, where the
Astros' bats have suddenly come up dry. Coincidence? Likely not.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Glavine had done a day earlier, Maddux dumped a season's
worth of frustration on the Astros, helping the Atlanta Braves to a
3-1 victory Wednesday night at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what all the talk is about those guys
struggling,'' Astros interim manager Matt Galante said. ``I don't
see it. Maddux had great stuff. I didn't see a struggling pitcher;
I saw the same old Maddux.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux and Glavine brought mediocre records and high ERAs to
town, but none of that seemed to matter against the Astros, who
managed nine hits over the past two days _ just three in
Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   But a testament to the way the Astros battled was the fact they
still managed to have the tying run at the plate in the eighth
inning despite being outhit 14-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how a three-hit game could have been that
exciting,'' Galante said. ``We battled our butts off; we just came
up a little short.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros dropped their second game in a row but remain
percentage points ahead of the Braves for the best record in the
National League. That figures to be a dogfight for the rest of the
summer, and it has the potential to get as heated as things became
in the bottom of the seventh inning Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux (6-4) stomped around the mound and screamed obscenities a
couple of times after calls he didn't particularly like. Braves
manager Bobby Cox eventually had words with home-plate umpire Bruce
Froemming and was ejected after a spirited debate on the subject of
balls and strikes. Cox got his money's worth, serving up a
lip-reader's buffet before finally leaving the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with a little emotion in baseball,''
Maddux said. ``It's not basketball or football, but every once in a
while emotion slips in. We do care.''
</P>
<P>
   Once that squabble ended, a stink broke out involving Astros
center fielder Carl Everett, who had stolen third base one batter
earlier. Everett apparently was responding to something said by a
Braves player _ perhaps someone on the bench _ but he declined to
get into specifics about the matter after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Those fireworks were far more explosive than anything the
Astros' offense produced.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux held them to three hits and a run in 6 innings, and
relievers Mike Remlinger, Rudy Seanez and John Rocker combined for
2 innings of hitless, scoreless relief. Rocker collected his second
save in as many days and his 15th of the season. For the game,
Braves pitchers struck out 13 _ the most times Astros hitters have
fanned this season.
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Sean Bergman didn't appear to have his best
stuff, but he kept the game close nonetheless. Four of the first
five batters reached base, including right fielder Brian Jordan,
who singled home Bret Boone in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves put at least one runner on base against Bergman (4-3)
in every inning except the fourth. Shortstop Ozzie Guillen hit a
one-out double in the fifth and scored on Chipper Jones'
two-bagger. Bergman allowed three doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bergy's location wasn't good,'' Galante said. ``His pitches
were up a lot. He made too many mistakes up in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves added salt to Bergman's wounds in the sixth inning
when first baseman Brian Hunter started a two-out rally with a base
hit and scored on the second of Maddux's two singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you give up a base hit to the pitcher in that situation,
you just can't do that,'' said Bergman, who allowed three runs and
11 hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros hit only two balls out of the infield through the
first six innings, but they finally broke through for a run in the
seventh. Bill Spiers, a career .467 hitter against Maddux, led off
with a double, moved to third on Derek Bell's chopper to the mound
and scored on Everett's clutch two-out single.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who is 14-for-26 when a runner is at third base,
managed to punch the ball into left field despite breaking his bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been trying to pound me inside,'' Everett said of
Maddux. ``He had success the first two times, and the third time I
got him. I went up there with a heavier bat.''
</P>
<P>
   That was about the only time the Astros got the best of Maddux,
who had five 1-2-3 innings and retired 17 in a row at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the stuff he had, you would think he has 10 or 11 wins,''
Astros shortstop Ricky Gutierrez said. ``He was putting the ball
wherever he wanted to put it. He pretty much breezed through us.
That was his type of game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
