<SLUG> BC-MURDER-ARREST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE MAKE ARREST IN 23-YEAR-OLD MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYNNWOOD, Wash. _ Twenty-three years ago, police thought they
knew who killed 18-year-old Kimberly Marie Kuntz. Now they think
they can finally prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly's brother-in-law, James L. Stephens Jr., was charged
with first-degree murder Wednesday in her 1976 stabbing death.
Police used DNA evidence to make the case to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers say Stephens' then 3-year-old daughter was
somewhere in the apartment when Kimberly died and was able to
confirm that her father had been there that night.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens was charged in 1976 with Kimberly's rape and murder,
but prosecutors dropped the charges after deciding there wasn't
enough evidence for a solid case.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly's family never forgot her. Neither did police.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by new advances in DNA technology, Lynnwood
investigators reopened the case in 1997, poring over dusty boxes of
reports and evidence, reinterviewing witnesses, looking for
anything they could have missed before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to guess how many times we read the reports, just to
make sure we had everything,'' Detective Jim Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   They hit gold this week when a private laboratory solidly
matched a blood sample taken from Stephens six weeks ago to a semen
stain on the shirt Kimberly Kuntz wore when she died, police and
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the oldest murders charged in Snohomish County
history, Prosecutor Jim Krider said in a statement, calling the
arrest a result of ``excellent and persistent'' police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those cases _ that's why we get into the business,
for justice,'' said Lynnwood Detective Sgt. Steve Bredeson, who
worked on the Kuntz murder as a young detective between 1978 and
1981, and directed Nelson and Detective Steve Rider to reopen it in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Kuntz's life was cut short just as it was beginning,
her family said in a statement Wednesday. She had graduated the
year before from Mountlake Terrace High School, where she had been
a cheerleader, and she worked as a file clerk for Allstate
Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so vibrant and fun. Her life was just beginning. She
had plans for college and a bright future,'' her mother and sister
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a daughter, she was such a joy, so loving and
considerate,'' wrote her mother, Gwen Kuntz. ``She and her dad were
quite close. I loved her dearly and miss her always.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Wednesday's charging papers, Kimberly was killed
while she was baby-sitting her 3-year-old niece _ the daughter of
Stephens and his estranged wife, Donna Stephens, who was Kimberly's
sister _ on the night of May 8, 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens had moved out of the apartment and Kimberly had told
friends she was hesitant to baby-sit in case she ran into him
because he had recently raped his estranged wife, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
   When Donna Stephens (who has since remarried and changed her
name) came home around 2:15 a.m., there was no answer when she
knocked at the door, papers said. She then saw a man standing 15
feet away wearing only a stocking mask. The man ran, and she called
police.
</P>
<P>
   Police found Kimberly Kuntz dead on the floor of the master
bedroom. Her niece was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did daddy come over tonight?'' Donna Stephens asked the little
girl, the papers said. The child nodded yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did daddy come see you?'' Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did daddy yell at Auntie Kimmi?'' Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did daddy say goodbye?'' No.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens admitted stopping by the apartment, but denied arguing
with Kimberly, the papers said. He skipped a follow-up appointment
with police, and later was arrested in a Bellingham, Wash., motel
where he had checked in under an assumed name.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Lancaster, who used to work with Kimberly, remembered her
friend in a telephone interview Wednesdsay night. Lancaster
recalled talking with Kimberly the night she died, asking her if
she wanted to come over. Kimberly said she couldn't, that she had
to baby-sit. The next thing she heard, her friend was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, justice has been served after all these years,''
Lancaster said, stunned by the news. Kimberly was ``a beautiful
girl,'' she said, outgoing and friendly and fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never forgotten about her.''
</P>
<P>
   After his 1976 arrest, Stephens pleaded not guilty to charges of
raping and murdering Kimberly Kuntz. Crime laboratory reports at
the time could neither exclude nor definitively identify him as the
killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology wasn't there,'' said Bredeson, who was a patrol
officer at the time. But each time the case was reopened it
progressed a bit, finding a few new witnesses or eliminating
potential other suspects.
</P>
<P>
   When he took his supervisory position in 1997, the department
was reorganized and priority was given to solving the old cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years is a long time, but it's not impossible by any
stretch of the imagination,'' said George Riley, scientific
director of GeneLex, the Seattle-based laboratory that did the key
DNA tests in the case.
</P>
<P>
   New techniques allow the lab to test samples that would have
been considered too small for adequate results even a few years
ago, and they also are ``so specific that it gets very good results
even when the evidence is in bad shape,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say the DNA profile from the semen stain that had
been kept for 23 years as evidence in the Kuntz case would be found
only in one in every 377 million Caucasians. The semen stain was a
perfect match for Stephens' DNA, Snohomish County Deputy Prosecutor
Paul Stern wrote in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens, who lives in West Seattle and works for a shipping
company, has remarried and has a child, police said. He had been
under intermittent surveillance for some time, and under a steady
watch since police got a search warrant and took a blood sample six
weeks ago, Rider said.
</P>
<P>
   The case has consumed the detectives for two years now.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens was arrested without incident Wednesday afternoon at a
McDonald's restaurant near his home, police said. He's scheduled to
be arraigned Thursday. Police said they don't believe he's been in
trouble with the law in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Kuntz's family noted the department's tenacity in their
statement Wednesday and thanked police for bringing some kind of
closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might seem like a long time ago that she was murdered, but
we never forgot,'' they wrote. ``Not a day passes that we don't
think of her. We have lived with this loss since then and it never
goes away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
