<HEADLINE>
FOR WIN-PARCHED UNSER, PORTLAND HAS BEEN WELLSPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND _ Father's Day in the Unser family historically has
been fast-paced. It usually includes winning a CART FedEx Series
race at Portland International Raceway, or coming darn close. It's
an occasion celebrated with victory champagne, not another gaudy
necktie.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a ritual Al Unser Jr. hopes to revive Sunday in the
Budweiser/G.I. Joe's 200 at the 1.967-mile Portland road course
where he scored the first of his storied 31 career wins on Father's
Day 1984.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon made for a particularly poignant holiday scene.
Unser's father, in the prime of his own legendary racing career,
was by all accounts the happiest last-place finisher in series
history _ his car unable to turn a lap because of mechanical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very gratifying day, let me tell you,'' said Al Unser
Sr., who still gets excited recounting it. ``To have your son
follow in your footsteps and then get to the point where he wins a
race and to do it for the first time on Father's Day ... It was
just great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest also is home to Al Jr.'s most recent win _ 1995 in
Vancouver, B.C. It's been a l-o-n-g 44 months since the two-time
CART series champion has sprayed champagne in victory circle.
</P>
<P>
   The same driver who won a dominating eight of the 16 races en
route to the 1994 PPG Cup has only seven podium finishes during
this nearly four-year winless streak, prompting the media and some
fans to suddenly question Unser's unquestionable abilities. And for
one of the most talented racers in history, this second-quessing
stings the ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating for him not being able to win, but he's a
great driver, and there are so many things that are out his
control,'' said Team KOOL Green driver Paul Tracy, a former Unser
teammate at Team Penske.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through these same sort of things, and you have to
put your head down and know it will eventually come around. He's an
icon in terms of Indy-car racing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's understandably tougher to endure the disappointments when
you've become accustomed to great success. Only Michael Andretti
has more wins (38) than Unser (31) among active drivers. In 17 CART
seasons, Unser has ranked among the top-five in points 11 times,
but hasn't finished among the top-10 since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   What he's done in the Northwest, is reason for optimism. He's
never finished lower than fifth place in nine starts at Vancouver
and has a record four victories there, including three straight
from 1993-95.
</P>
<P>
   Unser has finished among the top five in 12 of his 15 starts in
Portland, including back-to-back wins in 1994-95. He finished fifth
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But while struggling in races elsewhere, he has faced trying
times off the track, as well.
</P>
<P>
   His 12-year-old daughter Cody was stricken in February with a
rare neurological condition that has left her partially paralyzed
and unable to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after vowing to win the Miami season-opener for Cody a
month after her diagnosis, Unser broke his ankle on the first lap
of the race. His Marlboro Team Penske Mercedes-Benz was a mangled
and innocent victim of a rookie driver's first-race mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The injury sidelined Unser for the next two races and he comes
to Portland with only two points toward the championship standings
_ his lowest total ever through eight races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought last year was a tough year and the year before that
was tough, but, boy, was I wrong,'' Unser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my daughter getting hurt, then breaking my leg at Miami
after I thought we had a good shot in the race. ... I've just been
going, `Oh, O.K.' I believe in the good Lord, and there must be a
reason why things are happening like this. I have to believe He'll
get me through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Unsers are not quitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser hopes that kind of determination will make a difference
for his daughter, the second of his four children. Doctors have
been cautiously optimistic about Cody's recovery, reticent to give
a time frame. The virus that has caused the condition could go away
as quickly as it struck. And Cody, a youth basketball player and
avid outdoors person, could be walking again soon.
</P>
<P>
   There are no certainties, however, and Unser's voice cracks with
emotion when he talks about her. Some days, he'd prefer not to.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was a brief time when Unser thought about stepping
away from racing _ first when Cody fell ill, then again when he
broke his ankle so severely. It seemed like he was being hit by one
misfortune after another and he wanted to be at his daugher's
bedside.
</P>
<P>
   Then he decided the best therapy for Cody would be setting an
example, by meeting the frustrations and mounting challenges
head-on and not giving in when that's the easier route.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing Cody needed right now was for me to stop
racing,'' Unser said. ``She needs the inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the inspiration goes both ways. A long-awaited
victory Sunday would make it Unser's kind of Father's Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
