<HEADLINE>
DANISH A GOOD FIRST BITE FOR U.S. WORLD CUP TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is billed as the 1999 FIFA Women's World Cup, but
let's be honest. Up until now, World Cup fever has been mostly
about Mia Hamm and the dominance of the home team.
</P>
<P>
   That Stars and Stripes mood and marketing motif was certainly
clear Wednesday, when Women's World Cup officials opened a press
conference at the Essex Hotel on Central Park West with a video
montage that featured, well, a lot of footage of the mighty
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   We expect a lot more of this kind of thing the next three weeks,
provided the Americans do what is predicted of them, which is to
score goals, whoop it up with big wins and entertain the masses.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, this decidedly American mode of hyping the
World Cup has been a predictable approach here in the United
States, where the 16-team, 32-game soccer tournament begins
Saturday and ends July 10 with the championship in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm we know from those Pert commercials and because People
magazine told us she was one of the 50 prettiest people.
</P>
<P>
   And we know the general greatness of the skilled, veteran and
determined U.S. women's team because ever since 1991, when a
fledgling bunch won the first-ever Women's World Cup in China, the
U.S. has won Olympic gold and Goodwill Games and made the rounds
during exhibitions to the delight of soccer moms, dads and kids
across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the World Cup, not the America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams are here. The U.S. has to beat other countries,
starting with Denmark, who is the opponent in Saturday's
anticipated U.S. opener at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday, just to set the record straight, the coach of
Denmark's World Cup team clarified a few facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all,'' Jorgen Hvidemose said in his best
Scandanavian-inflected English, ``let me just say that Denmark is
not the capital of Holland, as one person in Detroit once told
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall, hunched over the microphone, speaking slowly and
deliberately to make sure no one missed his droll point, the Danish
coach played his underdog role without a flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark, along with 14 other World Cup participants, certainly
has the right to feel as if this entire World Cup on U.S. soil was
created to make the visitors feel like they are playing Vivian
Vance to the American team's Lucille Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Denmark and the rest can show up for this breakthrough
event for women's soccer (460,000 tickets have been sold and all 32
games are on TV), but it is best to understand that the marketing
of the event and the sport is all about the home girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I know that this is the way it will be,'' Hvidemose
said. ``It is promotion of the World Cup and women's soccer so the
Americans are the ones featured. I think it's OK. The Americans are
the Olympic champions and they probably have the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, in Denmark, there is no equivalent of Mia Hamm, no way
for the Danes, or Mexicans or Brazilians or Norwegians, to fight
fire with star power.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could not happen there,'' Danish defender Lene Terp said.
``You cannot get that big. It's too small a country. If you start
to get that big, they bring you down. The sky is not so high in
Denmark. We are a little more ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when the best players from all 16 World Cup teams met
in San Francisco for a World Cup media event in February, Terp
said, she raised her eyebrow in disbelief when World Cup officials
handed her a Mia Hamm Barbie Doll.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so American,'' Terp said, smiling a knowing smile
about the largesse of this big country.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes know exactly what they are up against in this 1999
Women's World Cup. And they don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, they say it does not bother them.
</P>
<P>
   They view the U.S. as the one true professional team in the
World Cup, although they are certain there are ways to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not afraid,'' Hvidemose said. ``All teams have
weaknesses. You only have to find them. We know how to beat them,
but we're not sure we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   It does not faze the Danes that this World Cup is being played
in eight of America's biggest sports venues and corresponding
crowds, from Giants Stadium and a crowd of nearly 76,000 for the
opener to Foxboro, Soldier Field and the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have 300 Danes at Giants Stadium,'' Hvidemose said.
``I have heard from the Danish American Club in New York and they
promised they would be there, sitting behind the Danish flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred vs. 75,700. You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, yes, in Denmark, maybe we have 100 people at our games.
Mostly family. They come and eat a picnic,'' Terp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a great chance for us. We know our real chances
are against Mexico and Brazil (the other two teams in this
bracket), but this opening game, everyone will be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get too high, maybe we can use this opening game
to our advantage. But if we lose, we should go out of that game
with our heads held high. We're prepared. We'll make it a good
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heavy dose of America boosterism, that is exactly
what soccer fans want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   So welcome to the Danes. Their sense of humor, proportion and
irony are much appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
