<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER BAFFLES TIGERS FOR EIGHT, WINS 7TH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Humility was the first thing Jamie Moyer learned as a
major leaguer. He won his debut in 1986, beating his hometown team,
the Philadelphia Phillies, and his childhood idol, Steve Carlton. A
few days later, also against the Phillies, he failed to survive the
third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is a game of failure, Moyer said Wednesday night, after
succeeding again. He beat the Detroit Tigers 7-1 with a performance
typical of his recent stretch. Moyer worked eight innings, allowing
seven hits and walking none. It was his seventh win in a row and
improved his record to 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to win games,'' the 36-year-old left-hander said.
``I know it's not going to go on forever, and I'm not going to get
caught up in it. You could just as easily lose two or three in a
row and be pitching well, or pitching poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going well for me right now. I'm not going to gloat
about it, I'm not going to brag about it. That's not me, because I
know _ I've been humbled so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   He was humbled earlier this season by the Tigers, who beat Moyer
7-0 at the Kingdome on April 26. That night, said Tigers manager
Larry Parrish, Detroit was able to take Moyer's changeup to right
field. Not so at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't read Moyer's changeup at all tonight,'' Parrish
said, ``and he had a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a good slider, as Brian Hunter observed from center
field. The Mariners outfielder was with Detroit in April, and this
was his first time playing behind Moyer as a center fielder. That
vantage point gave Hunter new insight into Moyer's stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some pitches today playing center field, and it's a
whole different angle on the game,'' Hunter said. ``He even had a
little backdoor slider working along with his curveball. He was
throwing four pitches for strikes, and when a pitcher's doing that,
you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter was one of four Mariners with multi-hit games, including
Ken Griffey Jr., who had two doubles as the designated hitter, and
David Segui, who had three singles and two walks. Alex Rodriguez
and Butch Huskey drove in runs, Dan Wilson hit a solo homer and
John Mabry was 2-for-4. But all Moyer needed was David Bell's RBI
double and Wilson's run-scoring groundout in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer lasted until the ninth, when rookie Aaron Scheffer came on
before some 40-45 family members and friends. Scheffer fanned the
first two he faced at his hometown park, then gave up two singles
before getting a fly out to end it. He kept the game ball, which
was no doubt a popular item at the Scheffer home in nearby
Westland, where Aaron stayed over Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dream come true,'' Scheffer said. ``It was awesome,
especially with my family and friends out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a Detroit reporter if he pitched Scheffer because of
his local ties, Mariners manager Lou Piniella smiled. Tiger Stadium
had no impact on his decision, but he was happy with how it worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   He was happiest, though, about Moyer, whose innings have been
invaluable to Piniella's inconsistent staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most important thing,'' Piniella said. ``You need
innings from your starters. We got eight good ones from Jamie
tonight _ eight excellent ones, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer struck out a season-high nine Tigers, and his eight
innings gives him 1051/3 for the year, tops in the American League.
He has a 2.56 earned run average during the eight starts in his win
streak and has worked eight innings in five of those outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job,'' Moyer said, ``is to go as deep into the game as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer spread around the credit, pointing to his defense and even
the new Tiger Stadium groundskeeper. Before, Moyer said, there
would be a 6-inch hole beneath the rubber on the mound by the
second inning, and the landing spot was essentially dust. Wednesday
night, the conditions were ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it is, it's my office,'' Moyer said. ``I
want my office to be just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the office or the employee in it, this much is
known about Moyer: the last five weeks, productivity is at a high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
