<HEADLINE>
U.S. DIPLOMAT FAILS TO CONVINCE BEIJING THAT EMBASSY BOMBING WAS
ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CORRECTS headline; SUBS first 11 grafs with Chinese response,
details)  (rk)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Under Secretary of State Thomas Pickering spent
Wednesday trying to convince determinedly skeptical Chinese
officials that the bombing of China's embassy in Belgrade on the
night of May 7 was a mistake. But after listening attentively, the
Chinese made clear that they were not persuaded, American diplomats
said today.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, supported by officials from the Defense Department
and intelligence agencies, gave a detailed account of ``a long
series of errors over time'' that led to the bombing, members of
the delegation said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese side, represented by Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan
and Deputy Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi, ``listened with respect
and appreciation of the seriousness with which we spoke,'' an
American diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're digesting what we said,'' the diplomat said. ``They
have to think it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering arrived with a letter of introduction from President
Clinton that included an offer to pay compensation to the families
of the victims. Three Chinese died in the embassy attack, which
Chinese officials condemned as a deliberate act of aggression and
which created severe strains in Chinese-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   The officials refused Wednesday to give details of the oral and
written explanations given to the Chinese, saying that the same
information will soon be released to the American public.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the previously offered theory involving a faulty
map was far too simple to explain how NATO planners identified the
Chinese Embassy as a military site and pummeled it with multiple
bombs. ``It was a more complicated series of mistakes than that,''
a diplomat said. ``It wasn't just one faulty map.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering spent more than four hours meeting with Yang and with
other officials from the Foreign Ministry and the Chinese military.
In the afternoon, he met with Tang for about one hour. Wednesday
evening, during a two-hour dinner with Yang and others, the two
sides turned to discussion of bilateral and strategic issues,
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   China has demanded not only a full and public explanation of the
bombing but also the punishment of those responsible, a condition
the Americans may have difficulty meeting. .
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the Americans promised that at the end of the
investigation into the bombing ``the issue of accountability will
be addressed,'' the diplomat said, and the Chinese did not press
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the visit's sensitivity, even the fact that the
U.S. delegation had arrived in Beijing was not reported in
newspapers Wednesday morning or on Wednesday's night's television
news.
</P>
<P>
   In the angry aftermath of the embassy attack, which killed three
Chinese journalists and created indelible images here of a
smoldering building and weeping relatives, China suspended talks
with the United States on its proposed entry into the World Trade
Organization as well as on human rights and arms control, and put
off planned military meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The two governments are now feeling their way toward a new,
perhaps more realistic, relationship than in the past, when both
spoke of building a ``constructive strategic partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   The night of the embassy bombing, China's leaders were already
angry over the NATO military campaign in Yugoslavia, which they
called an illegal intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here described the embassy bombing as a criminal act
of aggression, and encouraged the state-controlled press to run
wild with accusations that it was the intentional act of an evil
empire, out to keep China down.
</P>
<P>
   In place of last year's friendly talk of partnership, top
officials including President Jiang Zemin, began warning about U.S.
plans for global domination, although they always maintained that
business ties should continue.
</P>
<P>
   When news of the bombing broke, latent public resentment of U.S.
power erupted into days of rock-throwing demonstrations at the U.S.
Embassy, mainly by students. Their fury was genuine, but they also
received logistical support from the government, which seemed to
view the outpouring of nationalism as a useful way to unify the
population and divert attention from economic and political issues
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Few Chinese openly accept the proposal that the United States,
with its technological wizardry, could have hit their embassy by
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   And if Chinese do accept the U.S. excuse of an outdated map,
they have to confront another painful truth: that the United States
and NATO simply were not paying much attention to China, which
expects to be treated as a great power.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, the vitriolic attacks on the United
States have moderated. Communist Party leaders have tried to
channel the nationalistic energy into hard work and support for the
Party in its drive to build a stronger China that can better stand
up to any attempts at foreign domination in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have stressed the need to resume business and
political ties with the United States _ after receiving an adequate
accounting of the Belgrade strike.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's newspapers reported the foreign trade minister's
statement that the right atmosphere for negotiations over China's
entry into the World Trade Organization will not be restored until
``U.S.-led NATO'' gives a satisfactory explanation for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The negotiations will be continued only if the good and
friendly atmosphere reappears,'' said the minister, Shi Guangsheng.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the trade body has been a longtime goal of China,
and President Clinton has said he wants to see China's entry this
year. But negotiations will be difficult in any case, because the
United States insists that China make hard concessions to open up
its markets.
</P>
<P>
   As they decide how to portray Pickering's visit, the Chinese
leaders face another delicate task: how to escape from a month of
aggressive anti-American rhetoric and credibly declare the
resumption of, in Shi's words, a ``good and friendly atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang and Prime Minister Zhu Rongji are pragmatists who in the
past have stressed that Western trade and investment are important
to China's economic modernization. But they cannot afford to look
weak in the face of what they personally have called U.S.
aggression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
