<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSERO NOT KEEN ABOUT MOVE TO BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Jeff Fassero was not excited when he learned he was
moving to the bullpen, but he held out hope he could close games,
as he did in Montreal at times between 1991 and 1993. That won't
happen in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted me to be a set-up man,'' Fassero said of his
conversation with manager Lou Piniella. ``I said, if that's the
case, I want to close, too. I'm not going down there just to get
left-handers out. I want to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella: ``I've got a closer. I didn't put him in the
bullpen to close. If I use (Jose) Mesa two or three days in a row,
it's a different story. I'm going to use (Fassero) like I use
(Jose) Paniagua.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero has made 170 starts since his last relief outing, on
Sept. 11, 1993. The Mariners had raised the issue of moving him to
the bullpen when he struggled in April, so Piniella's move wasn't a
total shock. But Fassero was unsure Wednesday how he'll adjust to
his new role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be (difficult), because in my heart I still want to
be a starter,'' Fassero said. ``I don't know how that will affect
me down there.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old left-hander does not think he'll have trouble
re-learning the mentality of a reliever, because he has made 162
relief appearances in his career. But he's not sure how his arm
will hold up after so many years as a starter, and pitching coach
Stan Williams admitted, ``We're going to have to learn him all over
again, from a bullpen standpoint, what he's able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella insisted Wednesday that the bullpen is best for
Fassero, and he has numbers on his side. Left-handers are batting
just .203 with two homers off Fassero, compared to .357 with 23
homers by right-handers. Only Boston's Pedro Martinez had thrown
more pitches than Fassero before Wednesday night's games, and
Fassero's effectiveness has dwindled after the early innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I told him (Tuesday), if he can piece together two or
three good innings, that's a way to get him back on track,''
Piniella said. ``It sounds like a demotion from the rotation, but
he can really help us. He'll get work on a more steady basis as
opposed to every five days, and it could get him sharper. He wasn't
happy when I told him about it, and I didn't expect him to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero is a free agent at the end of the season, and figured to
be one of the more attractive starters on the market. Now, he'll
have to pitch his way back into the M's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a job to do, and I have to go out there and do
it,'' Fassero said. ``It's my free-agent year, and I'd like to put
up good numbers, and so far I haven't. I don't know _ we'll see
what happens the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Melvin Bunch still is scheduled to start in
Fassero's spot on Saturday. However, veteran Paul Abbott pitched
well in his first start for Class AAA Tacoma on Tuesday, working
seven innings, allowing four runs and averaging 91 mph with his
fastball. He may need one more start, but if he doesn't, Abbott
will start Sunday and Frankie Rodriguez will move up to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   AVOIDING THE `KILL ZONE': Williams has begun a routine with
Mariners relief pitchers to help them pitch to the corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been hurting us are balls in the `kill zone' and
walks,'' Williams said. ``What we're trying to do is eliminate the
middle eight-tenths of the plate and make up a plate on either side
of that, and have them throw side to side.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, when the program began, pitchers spent much of
the pre-game playing catch. Now, Williams is supervising each
pitcher throwing off a mound in hopes that the individual
attention, combined with the emphasis on avoiding the middle of the
plate, will help them develop consistent release points for inside
and outside pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the young pitchers to know that they can throw in and
out, and gain confidence in their mind that they can do that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Williams isn't slicing up home plates for his
makeshift model. He's using towels.
</P>
<P>
   CALLING ON MAC: Right-hander Mac Suzuki, designated for
assignment Tuesday, has attracted some interest from other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a few inquiries, a few calls from some clubs,
and we've made a few calls,'' said vice president for baseball
administration Lee Pelekoudas. ``We'll see how that plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are gauging interest in Suzuki partly to see if any
team would claim him if they tried to outright him to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL REPORT: Piniella expects to have right fielder Jay
Buhner (strained hamstring) back within a week. ... With Edgar
Martinez likely out until Friday with a sore left elbow, Ken
Griffey Jr. started at designated hitter again Wednesday as he
nurses a minor muscle pull in his upper thigh. ... Reliever Eric
Weaver, out since May 15 with bone spurs in his right elbow, threw
before Wednesday's game without pain. He is hoping to return in two
to three weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
