u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     06-17 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  
 SPORTS COLUMN: COMBATANTS A MYSTERY UNTIL NOW  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It took too long, but Game 1 arrived at last,
along with the news that Tim Duncan is as good as advertised. No
surprise, really, or that Larry Johnson's sprained knee ligament
miraculously healed. If we'd waited much longer for the finals to
begin, Phil Jackson would've found a cure for Shaquille O'Neal's
free-throw-shooting disease, or the common cold.
</P>
<P>
   Sit around long enough, you start to believe anything, even that
Patrick Ewing has been taking limping lessons in case he is needed
to make the first two jump shots of Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys around here, we joke that Patrick's going to
do the Willis Reed thing,'' said the Spurs' Jaren Jackson, who made
his own finals impression on Wednesday night with torrid
fourth-quarter shooting as the Spurs defeated the Knicks, 89-77,
kicking off a series that should have begun last Sunday night when
most Eastern time zone children weren't asleep.
</P>
<P>
   David Stern, the National Basketball Association commissioner,
once said that no finals game should ever end after anyone's
late-night news. That strategy has apparently gone the way of the
100-point offense, with the games beginning after most East Coast
kids and even a few working parents have gone to bed. Had the
series commenced last Sunday and not avoided next Sunday, three of
the possible seven games could have begun at 7:30 in the East.
Something for the fans, to conclude a season that began three
months late. Does anyone even remember the lockout?
</P>
<P>
   Stern has always wanted his championship series to develop the
cachet of the World Series and, by golly, it has. Game 1 flirted
dangerously with spilling into the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. This series actually has a quaint, old World Series
feel to it, with the Knicks and Spurs having not met during the
50-game regular season. It actually felt as if that they were from
rival leagues, the establishment Knicks against the first
descendants of the old American Basketball Association to advance
this far.
</P>
<P>
   Before baseball panicked into interleague play, the World Series
was always guaranteed to contain a freshness other sports lacked in
their championship events. It was a novelty to see the Yankees
confront the Braves in 1996. It was a pleasure to have Tony Gwynn
walk into Yankee Stadium and get caught up in its history, like
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   So Knicks fans waited Wednesday night, with their sophisticate's
curiosity and provincial dread to find out about Duncan, seen only
once, as a rookie, last season in New York. Let Marcus Camby
explain what the Knicks are up against.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside, outside, he does it all,'' Camby said after Duncan
torched the Knicks with 33 points and 16 rebounds, after the Spurs
won their 11th straight playoff game and put these Knicks behind in
a playoff series for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said he should have been the mvp and based on tonight,
you'd have to agree,'' Latrell Sprewell said. ``You see him on TV
but not until you get out there and have to bang with him, do you
have a different respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Only then could the Knicks know that Duncan is poised beyond his
23 years, that, as his coach, Greg Popovich said, ``Nothing fazes
the guy.'' Duncan hurt the Knicks from the high post and killed
them from the low post. And just when the Knicks were starting a
fourth-quarter push, Jackson hit three ``daggers,'' in Jeff Van
Gundy's opinion, mainly because Duncan was commanding so much
attention down low.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Duncan and David Robinson, this is not a fearsome Spurs
cast, but on Wednesday night it contributed in a way that was
reminiscent of those championship Bulls not named Jordan and
Pippen. Jackson brought his microwave offense off the bench. Avery
Johnson ran a competent point. Jackson and New York-raised Mario
Elie did an excellent job steering Sprewell and Allan Houston into
the 14 feet worth of interior Spurs defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spurs basketball,'' Robinson said. ``Close down the rim.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Camby, his no-rebound first half and gamelong foul
trouble indicated how much the Knicks have moved up in class from
Rik Smits. For a man so wounded, Larry Johnson looked mighty
limber, but grossly overmatched guarding Robinson in the first half
and Duncan in the second. This was a bad Knick omen, and, for Van
Gundy, the predicted matchups nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was decided last night. The Knicks only need one victory
to make this a successful trip. First impressions did mean
something in their three previous series, though. Based on last
night's, eighth-seeded Cinderella may be coming to the end of the
ball. A few strokes, unfortunately, before midnight back home. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-COLUMN-1ST     06-17 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL AND HOUSTON SENDING OUT AN SOS TO TEAMMATES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs for rewriting throughout)  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ When they were finding seams in the defense in the
first half and knocking down jump shots Wednesday night, Latrell
Sprewell and Allan Houston were exploiting the one clear mismatch
the Knicks have over the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   They can't do anything about Tim Duncan; he is simply too good.
And David Robinson is going to get to the free-throw line
eventually, so the Knicks can forget about completely neutralizing
him, too. So much for the frontcourt matchup.
</P>
<P>
   But on the perimeter, it was different. The Knicks have scorers
and creators, players who can get to the basket and draw a foul. It
was thought to be their one great chance at upsetting the
multifaceted Spurs in the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could just give Allan and Spree a little help, there's
no telling what we could do,'' Kurt Thomas said after San Antonio
won Game 1, 89-77. ``We definitely need to get more of a rhythm
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for some atrocious moments in the second and fourth
quarters, the Knicks didn't completely fall apart. Given that the
Spurs had come off 10 days of rest and the Knicks were hobbling, a
blowout would not have been strange.
</P>
<P>
   And when you break down the numbers, the dynamic duo of Duncan
and Robinson (46 points, 25 rebounds, nine assists, five blocked
shots) was simply more productive than Sprewell and Houston (38
points, eight turnovers and 23 missed shots).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those factors, the Knicks never moved the ball like the
team that picked apart Indiana in the conference finals. Too often,
their offensive sets boiled down to Sprewell and Houston
monopolizing the ball on the perimeter and waiting for the shot
clock to wind down before moving.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had six turnovers, but he kept the Knicks in the game
with his scoring binges. Houston scored 10 points in the first
quarter, but went from assertive to awestruck over the next three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more aggressive at getting the ball where I wanted to
get it,'' Houston said of his first-quarter onslaught. ``I have to
be more intent on getting to my spot. I didn't do that later in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``When we're in a good flow, everyone looks better.''
</P>
<P>
   The main problem was, neither Sprewell nor Houston received much
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys are double-teamed, we definitely have to hit outside
shots,'' said Chris Childs (1 for 8). ``There's going to be nights
when shots don't fall. And when they don't fall, you have to do
other things. I've got to knock down more shots. As for those guys,
we need to get them more points in transition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls learned over the last decade that two potent
scorers on the perimeter can compensate for a drop-off at point
guard or center. And for the Knicks not only to compete, but to
pull off a monumental upset in the NBA finals, they need Sprewell
and Houston to play extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   But when your other offensive options have trouble producing,
it's tough to keep pace with a team like San Antonio. Charlie Ward,
Chris Dudley and a gimpy Larry Johnson did not give the Knicks
enough offensively. They finished a combined 5 for 20 from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have caught too many bounces and good breaks this
post-season to fold easily in the finals. Even in the fourth
quarter Wednesday night, they were within striking distance of at
least making it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three rounds of the playoffs, the Knicks found ways
to win on the road in Game 1. They did it by moving the ball around
and finding the open man. No matter who that player was, he would
usually knock down an open shot with the game in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs get a lot of credit for their defense, which was
menacing and impenetrable at the end of the second and fourth
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was Mario Elie bodying up Houston or Sean Elliott
flailing his arms to disrupt Sprewell, they put serious kinks in
the Knicks' game.
</P>
<P>
   But this was more about the Knicks' inability to generate points
at crucial moments of the game than any tremendous stop by Duncan
or Robinson. Thomas began to show signs of life near the end,
scoring on his patented arching jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson, who surprised everyone by rehabilitating his knee
injury in five days and starting Wednesday night, gets a pass. He
did all he could, given the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their contributions and those of Sprewell and Houston,
though, the rest of the Knicks have 48 hours to fix their broken
offensive games. Going home to Madison Square Garden in an 0-2 hole
would be rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurried shots,'' Childs said when asked to describe the
Knicks' offensive breakdown that led to 38.3 percent shooting and
50 missed shots. ``We weren't looking at the third and fourth
option. We were looking at the first option, staying on the strong
side instead of reversing the ball and pick-and-rolling more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in too much of a rush, shooting too many early jump
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much Sprewell and Houston and not enough of anyone else is
not going to cut it against this team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
