<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8728 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-HNS &LR;      06-17 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Maybe it was that Tim Duncan did so much so well.
Maybe the New York Knicks' injury and foul problems inside finally
caught up with them. But Duncan began Wednesday to take another
step toward the top level of superstardom.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His team began to look like him. The San Antonio Spurs made it
look easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs didn't break any records, though they did extend their
playoff winning streak to 11, matching the longest ever in the
postseason. They were far from their best, only occasionally
matching the play in their sweeps of the Los Angeles Lakers and
Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   But that made the Spurs' 89-77 victory Wednesday night so
remarkable. The Spurs didn't rout the Knicks to begin the NBA
Finals before 39,514 in the Alamodome. They just never seemed
terribly concerned with them, as if they could pick the score and
humbly chose to stop where they did.
</P>
<P>
   After taking over in the second quarter, the Spurs seemed to
need only to lean on Duncan enough to roll past the surprising
Eastern Conference champions. Though Knicks forward Larry Johnson
started despite a sprained right knee, Duncan all but toyed with
him and whatever else New York threw at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy at all,'' Duncan said. ``Those guys were
playing hard out there. They're a very physical team. I worked very
hard to get in position before they got down there. I worked hard
tonight. I really did.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan needed to make that point and insist so emphatically
because once he finished shaking off the rust from the nine-day
layoff since completing the sweep of the Trail Blazers, he had so
little trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't always take away greatness,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy said. ``We can't live with Duncan getting 33.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who ended the game by pointing to an upper-deck group of
supporters from the Virgin Islands, dominated as if he was still
taking on the best of St. Croix.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 33 points, 16 rebounds and a pair of blocked
shots. He teamed with David Robinson, who had 13 points, nine
rebounds, seven assists and three blocked shots, to choke off most
of the Knicks' offense, reducing them to one-on-one jump shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably a little young to be a legend yet,'' Spurs coach
Gregg Popovich said of Duncan. ``I'm willing to call him that if
he's going to do this every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, however, only began the Spurs' flight to a 1-0 lead.
Once he began to roll, the outside shooters, particularly Jaren
Jackson, were left open. Jackson made five of 10 3-pointers to add
17 points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Knicks, who will try to bounce back in Game 2 on
Friday, made just 31 of 81 shots (38.3 percent) despite hitting 52
percent of their first-quarter shots and taking a six-point lead.
And though the Knicks remained within six points with eight minutes
left, they made just five of 22 shots in the final 12 minutes with
Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston making only one of 12.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Robinson combined to block five shots. But they
changed countless others until they changed the Knicks' offense
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing they do is clog the lane,'' Van Gundy said.
``Any time you penetrate the ball, they have two great
shot-blockers. We played three great shot-blockers in the first
three series, but never two on the court at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Spurs forward Malik Rose, ``Our defense in the fourth
quarter, led by David, man, they just covered the rim up.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan had begun to take over late in the first half, scoring
nine points in the final four minutes of the half and blocking the
last Knicks shot at the buzzer as the Spurs turned a 27-21
first-quarter deficit into a 45-37 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan continued to dominate the third quarter, and for most of
the period the Knicks did little but watch as either Sprewell or
Houston went one-on-one. Duncan scored the first three times he
touched the ball, and when Sean Elliott took a pass from Avery
Johnson for an open 17-footer, the Spurs had a 62-50 lead, their
largest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   While the Spurs were just beginning to finally get their entire
offense going, the Knicks were bogging down, limited to whatever
Sprewell and Houston could create for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the first nine minutes of the game, the Knicks had worked
their offense well enough to have five assists. In the next 24
minutes, they had just three.
</P>
<P>
   But as they always seem to, the Knicks stayed just close enough.
With the Spurs temporarily going away from virtually everything
they did to gain command, the Knicks knocked six points off a
12-point Spurs lead with eight minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson nailed a trey, his fourth of the game, to give the Spurs
a 77-68 lead. But they did not finish off the Knicks until Duncan
took over one last time.
</P>
<P>
   After a Robinson free throw pushed the lead to 10, Duncan scored
six of the Spurs' next seven points, all on layups. His tip of a
missed reverse gave the Spurs an 84-70 lead with 3:07 left.
</P>
<P>
   While the Spurs were becoming increasingly efficient, the
Knicks' offense went from sporadic to dreadful.
</P>
<P>
   Relying almost entirely on one-on-one moves, the Knicks made
just two of 14 shots in the quarter, until a Kurt Thomas jumper
with 2:46 left. Indefatigable in the Pacers series, the Knicks
appeared worn to a collapse. And the Spurs cruised to a no-doubt
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for them, just because they are hurt,'' Duncan
said. ``We're going to keep playing hard through it. They're a very
physical team. Even when they beat us up, we're going to find ways
to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he left little doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
