r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     06-17 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE'S HIT GIVES DODGERS VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With two months of frustration built up from poor
start after poor start, Los Angeles Dodgers lefty Carlos Perez used
a bat to take some of that pent-up energy out.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it was on the water cooler in the dugout after
Perez was hooked after giving up four runs in 31/3 innings in
another abbreviated start against the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the slumping Dodgers beat the Pirates 6-5 in a slow-paced
game Wednesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre gave the Dodgers the slight edge
with a single to right with two outs in the seventh off reliever
Brad Clontz. The floater down the line scored Raul Mondesi and came
after Devon White was intentionally walked.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers entered the night having lost a season-high four
straight, seven of eight and 10 of 13.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers used the home run and hustle to climb back
into the game, it doesn't solve the mystery of what to do with
Perez. Manager Davey Johnson has talked repeatedly about how Perez
throws too many pitches and doesn't challenge hitters. Johnson
contemplated pulling Perez out of the rotation but said he needed
to work out his problems as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Pirates, Perez threw 82 pitches, allowed five hits,
walked three batters and hit another with a pitch. It's the fourth
time this season Perez has lasted fewer than four innings. Perez's
last start ended after a season-low 21/3 innings in which Oakland
scored eight times. In his last three starts, Perez, who saw his
National League-worst 7.18 ERA rise to 7.38, has allowed 19 earned
runs in 121/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the previous night, when Kevin Brown trailed 2-0 after
two pitches, it took the Pirates a little longer to get to Perez.
Pittsburgh didn't score until the third batter, Brian Giles,
singled to center. The Pirates took a 2-0 lead when Giles, who was
eventually balked to third, scored on a popup in short right field.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh took a 3-0 lead in the second when Abraham Nunez
scored on Mike Benjamin's single to right.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tied it with one swing in the bottom of the third on
Gary Sheffield's three-run homer off Pittsburgh starter Francisco
Cordova. It was Sheffield's 14th homer.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez, who is 2-8 with the no-decision, walked three
straight to begin the fifth before Johnson pulled him in favor of
Jamie Arnold, who is slated to start Saturday. Johnson said Arnold
would be available through Wednesday's game without it affecting
his pending start.
</P>
<P>
   Perez walked to the dugout, picked up a bat and started swinging
wildly at the water cooler, taking repeated hacks at it before
throwing the bat down and disappearing down the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold hit Ed Sprague with his first pitch to force in a run and
give the Pirates a 4-3 lead. It was the second straight outing
Arnold entered the game with the bases loaded only to hit the first
batter he faced. But the rookie righty escaped further damage when
he got Giles to ground to Young for an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tied the score 4-4 with White's solo homer to lead
off the bottom of the fourth. They took the lead later in the
inning when Beltre popped a ball just out of the reach of second
baseman Nunez and stretched it into a double. Beltre went to third
when right fielder Jose Guillen's throw bounced off him and scored
on Angel Pena's double to right-center field to give the Dodgers a
5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh tied it in the top of the sixth off Arnold with the
aid of an Eric Young error. The second baseman misplayed Warren
Morris' grounder to lead off the inning. Morris scored on a two-out
single to right by Giles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
