<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-17 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ Tim Duncan gave the New Yorkers a dose of their own
brand of hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   It was as easy as mugging tourists from Iowa on the subway.
</P>
<P>
   As an opening-night performance in the NBA Finals, it was good
enough to receive a curtain call on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   He was inside. He was outside. He hit jump shots. He rolled to
the hoop for simple layups and difficult reverses.
</P>
<P>
   He was up above the rim grabbing rebounds. He was down
scrambling all over the floor for loose balls.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a second-year pro in his first game in the championship
round, and he rolled to 33 points and 16 rebounds, telling the
Knicks right from the start that it was going to be a long night.
And maybe a very short series after an 89-77 decision by the Spurs
in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just really happy and really relieved to finally get
back out there on the floor and play a game after a 10-day
layoff,'' Duncan said. ``Those 10 days seemed like an eternity, and
in the first quarter tonight a couple of us got winded.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all we wanted to do was sort of weather the storm at the
start, get our legs back and get back into our rhythm, and we
thought it would be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   For Duncan, the former swimmer from St. Croix in the Virgin
Islands, this one looked like a lazy day in the pool. Doing the
backstroke.
</P>
<P>
   With the Knicks missing the injured Patrick Ewing and playing
with the hobbled Larry Johnson, they were virtually helpless
against the Spurs' Twin Towers combination of Duncan and David
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   This was a night that began with San Antonio legend George
Gervin whipping the crowd of 39,514 into a frenzy with a ceremonial
jump ball using the red, white and blue ball of the old ABA, where
the pace was often breakneck and scoring was at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan and Robinson quickly showed the Knicks that times
have most certainly changed around these parts as they stopped up
the middle on defense and choked off virtually any chance that New
York had of taking the ball to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game where the Knicks shot a miserable 38 percent from
the field, where Latrell Sprewell missed 15 of 24 shots, where
Allan Houston couldn't fully recapture his magic from the previous
round and shot just 7-for-17.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when the Spurs took awhile to blow all the rust
out of their pipes.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, it was a night when there was absolutely no answer
for Duncan and everything that he did.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk before the series about the last meeting between
Duncan and the Knicks' Marcus Camby back when they were in college.
Camby got the best of that matchup. But it wasn't even close this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan started off the night by banking in an 18-foot jumper,
and by the end he was tiptoeing along the baseline and dropping in
nifty reverse layups. He may be only in his second NBA season, but
he performed like a veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim didn't like the way he started off in the last series
against the Trail Blazers,'' said Spurs point guard Avery Johnson.
``So he worked hard during the break before this one. He worked
extra hard. I could see that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see in his eyes before the game that he was ready, and
I told him, `Big fella, I'm coming to you the whole game.'''
</P>
<P>
   And they did. And there was nothing the Knicks could do to stop
him.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the hoop on Chris Dudley, and he shot the ball over
Johnson. He zoomed past Camby, and he devoured Herb Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Just the fact that the 41-year-old Williams _ the oldest player
in the NBA _ was in the game near the end of the first half spoke
volumes about how desperate the Knicks are and will continue to be
in this series, trying to find any way to just slow Duncan down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is a strange bird,'' said Spurs coach Gregg Popovich. ``He
is so mature for his age. He has a natural disposition that I call
island time. It seems like absolutely nothing fazes him. Whether he
makes a fantastic play or he makes a big turnover, nothing bothers
him. He just goes on, and he plays his game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about Tim that I noticed right from the
start,'' said Robinson. ``He came into the league in his first
season, and it wasn't like he was excited or in awe of anything. He
knows how to play the game, and he goes about doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is the rarity these days as a rookie who remained in
college for his entire four years, and that is one of the primary
reasons that his game is so solid, so fundamentally sound. He
sounds like a veteran, and he plays wise beyond his years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just started calling plays and I hit a few baskets, and
so they kept coming to me,'' Duncan said. ``I had to work hard out
there tonight, because the Knicks play hard and they're a physical
team. I had to work hard to get my shots. It wasn't easy out there
at all for me.''
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine how the Knicks felt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
