</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROMP IN THE PARK FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TWINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Throw in a few palm trees, and this could easily have
been March and another spring training game between those Fort
Myers cohabitants, the Red Sox and Twins.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the 30,085 in attendance at Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's
5-1 Sox win at Fenway Park was to remain engaged in a game so
devoid of excitement, one spectator, Pedro Martinez, amused himself
by standing on top of the dugout steps and giving the choke sign in
the direction of the press box.
</P>
<P>
   There was more at stake, of course, for rookie Brian Rose, who
ran his record to 4-0 by scattering seven hits in six-plus innings,
the only Minnesota run coming on Torii Hunter's leadoff home run in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think the more I'm throwing the more confidence I have
that I can throw pretty much all my pitches,'' said Rose, who in
spring was one of the team's first cuts but in six starts since his
promotion from Pawtucket has been a part of five Red Sox wins.
</P>
<P>
   The win keeps intact the most astonishing stat of the Sox season
so far: the Pawtucket callups of Rose (4-0), Juan Pena (2-0), and
John Wasdin (6-0) remain unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty low-key type of guy,'' said Rose, of the South
Dartmouth Roses. ``I think I'm a little more mature than I was in
'97. I'm just going out there every five days, trying to do my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who had no-decisions in his previous two starts, including
his last outing in New York when he allowed just three hits in
seven scoreless innings, was given a 2-0 lead in the second on RBI
doubles by newly revived Mike Stanley and Damon Buford.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox widened that lead to 4-1 when Stanley hit his second
double of the night, scoring Brian Daubach, who had led off with a
double and taken third on Nomar Garciaparra's drive to deep center.
Troy O'Leary, who walked, took third on Stanley's hit and scored on
a sacrifice fly by Jason Varitek, newly ordained in Baseball
America as the best-ever catcher in college baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who on Tuesday night broke an 0-for-27 slump and wound
up collecting his 1,000th hit, played the numbers game again
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night when he recorded the 200th double of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longevity,'' Stanley said. ``I'm just thankful that I've been
able to stay healthy and stay around this game. I mean, they're not
Hall of Fame milestones by any stretch of the imagination but
they're Hall of Fame in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The first four Sox runs were scored against another
Twins-pitcher-in-training, rookie Dan Perkins, who won 13 games in
each of the last two seasons, but had never pitched higher than
Double A New Britain. It's been a tough week for Rock Cats alumni,
who are heavily represented on this 13-rookie roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perkins obviously had a hard time throwing strikes,'' said
manager Tom Kelly, host of the Twins' nightly community auditions,
who lifted Perkins after three innings in which only half his
pitches (32 of 64) were strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Those brave souls who stayed for the duration were rewarded for
their patience with Garciaparra's 11th home run and first of the
month. It was a first-pitch blast into the left-center-field screen
in the eighth inning off lefthander Benj Sampson that ended a
14-game homerless streak for the Sox shortstop, Yawkey Way's
favorite son for the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a home run hitter,'' said the only man in the Sox
lineup whose baseball card suggests otherwise, ``so I don't worry
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The night's one whiff of controversy _ or comedy, depending on
your interpretation of Martinez's gestures _ was inspired by the
Twins seventh, which began with a single by Chad Allen. The next
batter, A.J. Pierzynski, skidded a ground ball up the middle that
was cut off nicely by Offerman as he glided to his right. The Sox
second baseman, with his momentum carrying him toward left field,
attempted to flip the ball with his glove to Garciaparra at the
bag, but his throw flew past the Sox shortstop and both runners
were safe. Official scorer Bruce Guindon charged Offerman with an
error on the play.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, manager Jimy Williams lifted Rose for Derek Lowe,
who extricated the Sox from further trouble when he retired pinch
hitter Brent Gates on a flyball and induced Jacque Jones to bounce
into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   But it was in the eighth inning, when Williams used three
relievers _ Rheal Cormier, Kirk Bullinger, and Mark Guthrie _ that
Martinez appeared to register his displeasure with the Offerman
error call.
</P>
<P>
   He stood on the steps for several moments while looking at the
press box, pointed at the scoreboard, held up four fingers (the
number used to designate the second baseman), formed an ``L'' _ his
gesture for loser _ then grabbed his throat with his hand
repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said it was a mistake to think he was motioning toward
the scorer. ``I was giving the `L' Johnson to Kevin Shea,'' he
said, referring to the Sox publicist. ``Don't assume what I was
doing until you ask me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea laughed when told of Martinez's remark. ``He gives me the
`L' all the time,'' Shea said. ``I thought he was waving to his
father in the grandstand.''
</P>
<P>
   Guindon, who has been the regular scorer at Triple A Pawtucket
since 1992 and estimates he has scored about 25 games here in a
backup role, defended his call after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't hesitant then, and I'm not hesitant now,'' Guindon
said. ``If he wanted to concede second base, I think he still gets
the batter. If he makes a good throw to second base, I think he has
a chance at a double play, though I can't assume that.''
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about nothing? Given the chance to tell the truth, the
whole truth, and nothing but the truth, Martinez is almost always
above reproach.
</P>
<P>
   Then again . . . he still insists that was Jim Corsi in the Yoda
mask last summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
