<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNCAN DOES IN KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ This one came right from the script. You want to
beat the Spurs, something's gotta give. They gave away little
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. Tim Duncan killed the Knicks inside, Jaren
Jackson tortured them from afar, and once the Spurs got rolling,
things pretty much fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio shook off its predictable rust from a nine-day
layoff and then, riding Duncan like the thoroughbred he is, took
over the game. The result was a convincing 89-77 triumph in Game 1
of the NBA Finals, the Spurs' 11th straight playoff victory. Game 2
is Friday night at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan put on a clinic at the expense of any Knick who had the
temerity to try to defend him. He finished with 33 points, 16
rebounds, 2 blocked shots, and a host of hosannas from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside, outside, he did it all,'' saluted Marcus Camby, who
was limited to 23 minutes by foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Added Duncan, ``I'll stick with rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, whose raison d'etre is the long ball, knocked down five
treys, including a couple of improbable daggers. He finished with
17 points. David Robinson did not shoot well (3 for 10) but did
everything else, collecting 9 rebounds, 7 assists, 3 blocks, and
getting a handful of Knicks into early foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But the story was Duncan. He outscored the entire Knicks team in
the second quarter, 11-10, which also coincided with the Spurs'
takeover of the game. San Antonio turned a 6-point deficit after
one into an 8-point lead at the half with Duncan already in
double-double land (19 and 10.).
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks never seriously threatened, but, true to their style
and purpose, stayed within reasonable striking distance. But they
never got closer than 6, and the Spurs limited them to 14 points in
the fourth, pulling away with a Duncan-led 8-0 run to make it 82-68
with 4:51 to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did get something from Larry Johnson, but not much.
He had as many fouls (5) as points. Latrell Sprewell and Allan
Houston each had 19, but Sprewell patterned his night after Antoine
Walker (24 shots) and Houston missed nine of his last 11 shots
after starting out strong in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, collectively as a team, we were a little
frantic and lost our poise on the offensive end,'' Houston said.
``We lost a little of our rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the foul trouble, the big game from Duncan and
the ongoing injury woes (Camby hurt his knee, but dismissed it
afterward), the Knicks were hanging around, within 6 with 8:28
left. The Spurs called time and decided to put an end to formal
competition for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the break came (a) Camby's fifth foul and (b) Jackson's
fourth trey on an inside-out pass from Duncan. Then came five
botched possessions and a Robinson free throw. Duncan then went
over Chris Dudley for a short jumper and, after another Robinson
rejection, hit a short pop to complete a game-breaking 8-0 run. The
lead was 14 with 4:51 left and the Knicks, who shot 27 percent in
the quarter and 38 percent in the game, were cooked.
</P>
<P>
   The two unknowns going into the game were the status of Johnson,
who sprained his right knee last Friday, and the effect of the
nine-day layoff on the Spurs. Johnson told coach Jeff Van Gundy he
could go and started the game. But he was gone in less than three
minutes due to two quick fouls, a pattern the Knicks battled,
unsuccessfully, all game.
</P>
<P>
   The one Knick who survived the battle inside was Kurt Thomas,
who had 13 points and 16 rebounds. The Knicks outrebounded the
Spurs, 43-37, and had a huge edge in second chance points, 20-2.
That prompted San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich to say the team
needed to shore up those two areas, along with poor free throw
shooting (19 of 31).
</P>
<P>
   Popovich might not have anticipated those shortcomings, but he
had to expect it would take awhile for his team to get rolling. The
Spurs actually trailed by 6 at the end of a very shaky first
quarter which was easily predictable. Then the Knicks got
Duncanized in a hurry. He had 9 of his 11 points in the final 4:16
as San Antonio closed the half with a 14-2 run, holding the Knicks
without a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped giving them the easy shots they had in the first
quarter,'' Duncan said. ``We started contesting everything. It
really took us about a quarter to get everything going and a half
to get back to where we were.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a place the Spurs know quite well these days. That's in
the script as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
