<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS FACE TALL ORDER AGAINST SPURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For the first time in the semi-august history of
the NBA Finals, the 1999 version features an eighth-seeded team,
the New York Knicks. Also unprecedented is an appearance by one of
the survivors of the old American Basketball Association, the San
Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   This series also may be the first time in Finals history that
the free throw is celebrated as the coin of the NBA realm.
</P>
<P>
   In other words _ bring back the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's a tad harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Bring back Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Besides lacking a certain Air and a certain pedigree, this Green
Acres matchup of Eddie Albert country vs. Eva Gabor urbanity lacks
a flow, if Wednesday night's first game is representative of the
next week's best-of-seven grind.
</P>
<P>
   While 50 combined free throw attempts is not a Finals record,
they did serve as a pleasant diversion to the 29 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   And since the Spurs had 31 foul shots, that was as good a
symptom as any in explaining the Spurs' 89-77 opening win over
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But in searching for a cause for the symptom, and its result,
extensive research is not required.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are taller. Remember where you read it.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly Tim Duncan, who by the time Game 2 rolls around
Friday, figures to be 11 feet, 6 inches in the imagination of the
Knicks. His 33 points and 16 rebounds dwarfed the Gothams in the
fashion of Manhattan skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   In the likely event that Jordan does not come back today, Duncan
has made a credible effort to give America a fresh hoops hero. He
needs to work up a good gambling jones, as well as snappy patter
with phone-service-shilling cartoon characters. But a guy has to
start somewhere, and splattering a Big Apple team is a great way to
some big pub.
</P>
<P>
   Along with fellow 7-footer David Robinson (13 points, nine
boards, seven assists), they were exactly as advertised: Way too
much for the Knicks, as they have been for the Western Conference.
Eleven consecutive postseason triumphs not only ties an NBA record,
it leaves the Knicks with a formidable task in just pulling out a
win, much less the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great size, strength and quickness in the post,''
said a slightly baffled Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks coach. ``We
studied them a lot, but you don't know a team until you play
them.''
</P>
<P>
   What Van Gundy knows now is what seemed obvious to many less
scholarly basketball mavens: Missing injured center Patrick Ewing
and struggling with hobbled power forward Larry Johnson (21
minutes, five points), the Knicks may as well be catching buffaloes
with box traps.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's ease with which he grabbed entry passes and slithered
past the Knicks' aggressive double-teams was remarkable. On
defense, he and Robinson combined for five blocks and shocked the
Knicks with threats to so many other shots that they missed 17 of
their 22 fourth-quarter casts.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed as if the heavily draperied Alamodome had fallen in on
the New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've faced three good shot-blockers in the playoffs,'' Van
Gundy said of Miami's Alonzo Mourning, Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo
and Indiana's Rik Smits. ``But never two at the same time. That's a
big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   While no one is quite set to reward the Spurs with the
championship trophy, Wednesday night did establish that the talent
mismatch between the Knicks and Spurs is formidable. And given the
patchwork nature of the Knicks' lineup owing to injuries, the Spurs
seem to have an edge in the ever-elusive matter of chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you just have those years where everything clicks,''
said Robinson, who couldn't be more delighted that he has evolved
into a high-post passer from a low-post scorer. ``And when you have
the team that comes together, there's a bond on the floor that's
real positive. This is just one of those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, sluggish from the nine-day layoff, began to hum in
the second quarter as the Knick fouls piled up, leaving poor Chris
Dudley as the helpless, hopeless big man to work on the Spur
tandem. Dudley, perhaps the worst shooter this side of Olden
Polynice, was readily abandoned by the double-teaming Spurs'
defense, and thus wound up with three of the Knicks' final five
shots of the first half. Two had to be removed surgically at
halftime from his soul, so harshly were they rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan claimed his night was much harder than it looked, and
presumed that the Knicks would again dump heavy ordnance in the way
of fouls for the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are physical,'' he said, ``and can do a job on us on a
given night.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that the given night could occur in the next three
games. But already gone is the chance to catch the Spurs at the end
of a nine-day nap. Just as is the chance get taller.
</P>
<P>
   There's always the chance that the Spurs, having never been to
the Finals before, could outthink themselves. But Spurs coach Gregg
Popovich seemed hip to the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get real dumb in nine days,'' he said, ``trying to
think of something clever.''
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious Wednesday night that Popovich and the Spurs were
concentrating only on the obvious:
</P>
<P>
   Tall guys good. Short guys short.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
