<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS STRIKE FIRST AS DUNCAN DOMINATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ He is usually so reserved and mild-mannered. San
Antonio Spurs center Tim Duncan rarely gets accused of anything
bad.
</P>
<P>
   So it would be hard to believe that Duncan got into his share of
trouble as a child. But he did _ doing ``stupid things'' _ though
Duncan insists he was not one to cut school.
</P>
<P>
   He liked homework.
</P>
<P>
   And you can bet the New York Knicks were studious before Duncan
and the Spurs tagged an 89-77 loss on them in Game 1 of the NBA
Finals Wednesday night at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   What the Knicks found out while falling behind in this
best-of-seven series is that Duncan isn't a quick study. He's also
neither as soft or as aloof as he is often made out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan still can be ornery, which is how he amassed a game-high
33 points and 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bad for the Knicks, who dropped Game 1 for the first time in
four playoff series. Good for the Spurs, who won their 11th
straight playoff game behind Duncan's muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy at all,'' said Duncan, who made his 13-for-21
shooting seem effortless. ``Those guys were playing hard. They are
a very physical team. I had to work to get into positions where I
could get easy shots before they could get down there on me. I
worked hard. I really did.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard the Knicks pushed, pulled and crowded Duncan,
he appeared immovable. He was one of the few Spurs who seemed to
benefit from their 10 days off before Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job of posting deep, avoiding the double team
and just getting up and shooting over guys,'' teammate Mario Elie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Duncan's teammates looked rusty with the exception of
Jaren Jackson. He chipped in 17 points off the bench, including
five 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can live with Duncan scoring 33,'' New York coach Jeff Van
Gundy said, ``but we've got to take away Jaren Jackson's threes.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy may change his tune if San Antonio begins to get its
usual firepower from several different sources. For the moment, the
Knicks' primary concern might be how to score against the Spurs'
tall front line.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell did what they could and
scored mostly in transition. Both New York guards scored 19 points.
But Larry Johnson, Chris Dudley, Kurt Thomas and Marcus Camby
combined for just 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Knicks won the rebounding battle 43-37, they
were held to 38-percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kind of lost our poise a little bit on the offensive
end,'' Houston said, ``instead of passing the ball to each other
and being a little bit unselfish and taking shots that we need to
take. That's really the key for our team at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks trailed by 11 points in the third quarter, but cut
the Spurs' lead to six early in the fourth. But Jackson buried a
3-pointer and Duncan made three straight field goals.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:05 left in the fourth quarter, Duncan tipped in his own
miss. That put the Spurs ahead 84-70 and finished off the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for them because they're all hurt,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson started despite a sprained right knee that made his
availability a game-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   Though Johnson, the Knicks' most effective post player in the
playoffs, did not seem bothered by the knee, foul trouble left him
ineffective. Only 2:11 had elapsed in the first quarter before he
picked up his second foul while trying to defend San Antonio's
David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   New York sent double teams at Duncan and Robinson early. But
Duncan and Robinson attacked the double teams with strong moves to
the basket. The Spurs' aggression put the undersized Knicks in foul
trouble for most of the first half. Johnson and Camby each had
three fouls midway through second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim and I talked about it before the game,'' Robinson said.
``We were going to have to take it to the hole and be real
aggressive to get things going. We knew we had to get them low and
get some opportunities down low. The aggression early was
important.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Knicks had was their backcourt. If Houston wasn't able
to push the ball up court and sink a pull-up jumper, Sprewell did.
New York parlayed the fast-paced assault into a 35-31 lead with
4:16 left in the second.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a matter of time, though, before San Antonio flexed
its muscle.
</P>
<P>
   And Duncan took advantage of the Knicks inside shuffle the most.
</P>
<P>
   He scored eight of his 19 first-half point during a 14-2 run
that put the Spurs ahead 45-37 just before halftime. From there,
the Spurs never let up.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people see that laid-back demeanor and they don't
think he's that kind of competitor,'' Robinson said. ``We went at
it from Day One. ... I know he's going to bring it every night.
When he's got a great matchup, he's going to go to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
