<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8877 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOD-FATHER-NYTSF &LR;      06-17 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOD-FATHER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOD THE ULTIMATE FATHER -- AND MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey, conservative Protestant pastors picked
``Father'' and ``Master'' as images for God over those of
``Mother'' and ``Spouse'' by a wide margin. Indeed, of the
ministers responding not one chose ``Mother'' as appropriate to
understand God.
</P>
<P>
   Although such views might be expected among conservatives, the
preference is also strong with more liberal Christians. Given a
choice in a different poll, Episcopalians said they would rather
have a homosexual minister than address God as Mother.
</P>
<P>
   Why do American Christians hold onto ``Father'' as their image
of choice for God so tenaciously? Why is fatherhood equated to
Godhood?
</P>
<P>
   Since my daughter Emma's birth, I have enjoyed watching my
husband father his little girl. He reads stories, changes diapers,
packs lunches, washes clothes, cleans up messes, feeds, hugs,
bathes, and plays. Since we both work, we share her care equally.
He does a remarkable job. And among our friends, he is not alone in
shared parenting. Most, if not all, have similar arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of these tasks reflect God's tender care and
provision. But none of them is particularly masculine -- or
feminine for that matter. Emma's daily needs are provided by both
parents regardless of gender. When it comes to discipline, which
some may define as ``male,'' we share that as well. For us, and for
many of our friends, the gendered categories of parenthood have all
but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   In the Victorian culture that persisted until the 1960s,
fatherhood was viewed as a distant and forbidding role. Father
provided; mother nurtured. Father went to work; mother stayed at
home. Father disciplined; mother comforted. Children trembled when
mother warned, ``Just wait until your father gets home.''
</P>
<P>
   Victorian fatherhood, however outdated, continues to shape
American images for God. God the Father is a rather distant
character: Master, Judge, and King of the universe. He is feared,
revered, and loved out of respect for his power.
</P>
<P>
   To continue to cling to ``Father'' as the dominant image of God
perpetuates these inappropriate stereotypes. Most Christians call
God ``Father'' only out of tradition and do not stop to think about
the implications of this practice.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christians insist that ``Father'' is the biblical name for
God. It is not. In the Hebrew Bible, God's name is YHWH
(transliterated Jehovah). Jewish scripture rarely uses ``Father''
to describe God.
</P>
<P>
   Those who equate God with Father usually point out that Jesus
called God Father -- and who should know better than Jesus what God
is like? In spite of misleading English translations, Jesus did not
refer to God as Father as often as Christians believe. In the
Gospel of Mark, God is called Father only four times. In Luke, 15
times. In Matthew, 49 times. In the Gospel of John, Father occurs
109 times.
</P>
<P>
   This wordcount reveals an interesting fact. The earliest gospel,
Mark, written closest to Jesus's ministry, refers to God as Father
much less frequently than the latest one, John. Calling God
``Father'' was a late first century theological development and not
the regular practice of early Christians. Scholars argue that this
reflects a growing influence of Roman secular ideas of hierarchy
and fatherhood on the church as it moved away from its Jewish
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting on ``Father'' as the sole image for God seems bad on
two counts: first, it perpetuates harmful gender stereotypes of
masculinity and fatherhood; and second, it is not (as many think)
biblical.
</P>
<P>
   What is clearer from the biblical text is that when Jesus
referred to God as Father he was alluding to the relationship
between himself and God -- not a stereotype or a role. The word
Jesus used for father, ``abba,'' connotes intimacy and relation. As
biblical scholar Elizabeth Johnson points out, ``Jesus' Abba is not
a patriarchal figure ... but a God of community and celebration.
Everyone related to the one Abba stands in a relation of mutuality
with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, it is appropriate to think of God as Father.
However, given contemporary cultural ideals, it is equally
appropriate to depict this God as Mother. The emphasis is on
community and relatedness -- not lines of authority and kingship.
</P>
<P>
   On this Father's Day, I'll be thinking of God the Father -- the
One who is always willing to be there, to lend a helping hand, to
roll around on the floor and play. The Father who feeds, clothes,
comforts, disciplines, and brings home half of the bacon, too. God
the Father; God the Mother; God the Parents; God the Baby; and God
in intimate community.
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1008EDT &QL; 
