<HEADLINE>
RACHEL GRIFFITHS: OUT FROM DOWN UNDER AND HEADED FOR THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Rachel
Griffiths in ``My Son the Fanatic.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The secret to success for today's Australian actors seems fairly
obvious: Pack a bag, leave home and expect to be away for years.
 &HT;    Cate Blanchette, who starred in ``Elizabeth'' (1998), and
Russell Crowe and Guy Pearce, both of ``L.A. Confidential'' (l997),
took that approach. After the shine wore off of ``Shine'' (l996),
Geoffrey Rush headed for England and ``Shakespeare in Love''
(l998), and he's just finished a horror movie in Hollywood.
 &HT;    And then there's Rachel Griffiths.
 &HT;    ``I haven't been home for I forget how long,'' the Australian
actress admits.
 &HT;    If you can't quite place Griffiths, who was everyone's favorite
``what was she in again?'' nominee at the 1999 Oscars, she first
came to our attention as Toni Collette's feisty best friend in
``Muriel's Wedding'' (l995). She followed that with a small role in
``Jude'' (1996) and then a supporting part in ``My Best Friend's
Wedding'' (1997).
 &HT;    Earlier this year she found herself in the rarefied ranks of
Best Supporting Actress contenders for her role as Hilary du Pre,
older sister of the late British cellist Jacqueline du Pre (Emily
Watson), in ``Hilary and Jackie'' (l998).
 &HT;    For the past few years Griffiths has worked steadily in England,
appearing in films such as the offbeat romantic comedy ``Among
Giants'' (l999), which opened and closed pretty quickly in March.
Her newest film, ``My Son the Fanatic,'' is due to open in America
on June 25.
 &HT;    Even more than ``Hilary and Jackie,'' ``Fanatic'' showcases
Griffiths' ability to completely lose herself in a role. It's her
strength as an actress, even if it's also a weakness when it comes
to winning name recognition and Hollywood stardom.
 &HT;    In ``Fanatic'' she plays a refreshing variation on the classic
hooker-with-a-heart-of-gold. The movie _ original, charming and
funny _ is set in northern England in working-class Bradford, the
kind of drab, industrial town that rarely turns up in movies, even
British ones.
 &HT;    Sporting a very credible north-of-England accent, Griffiths
plays Bettina, a local hooker who befriends and then falls in love
with an older man, am Indian taxi driver named Parvez (the
celebrated Indian actor Om Puri). As if their age and background
differences weren't enough, suddenly Parvez's son becomes a
fanatical, fundamentalist Muslim and institutes a violent campaign
to wipe out vice in Bradford.
 &HT;    ``Bettina is a woman with a lot of pain, but still she has such
positivity and warmth,'' Griffiths says. ``She's similar to many of
the 15 girls I met while doing research for the role. All of them
had a truckload of pain in their faces and in their eyes.
 &HT;    ``At first I saw them as victims who could not have had any
self-esteem to do what they did,'' the actress says. ``But while
many had a history of sexual abuse, surprisingly they did have a
good feeling of self-worth.
 &HT;    ``These were not glamorous call girls getting $1,500 a night
working for Heidi Fleiss in jobs that came with a nice condo, a car
and a college fund,'' she adds. ``These women serviced blue-collar
workers in a region of high unemployment, facing hatred in their
community from men and women.
 &HT;    ``They plied their trade in dangerous areas, never knowing for
sure whether their clients were going to beat them up, rape them or
even kill them. Yet many of them insisted they did have
self-esteem.''
 &HT;    The script, which was based on a short story that appeared in
The New Yorker, caught Griffiths' attention at once.
 &HT;    ``I was touched by it and the way in which it juxtaposes love
and compassion against hatred and intolerance,'' she says. ``It
also shows that the most unlikely people can fall in love and
affect each other's lives in powerful ways.''
 &HT;    Although she has a home in Sydney, Griffiths is heading back to
Britain to polish her Welsh accent for the new comedy ``Pavarotti
in Dad's Room,'' which co-stars Jonathan Pryce.
 &HT;    ``It's a much lighter role,'' she says, ``which I need to help
me lighten up after doing Bettina.''
 &HT;    Griffiths recently returned home to Sydney to star in the play
``Sylvia.'' It was a reunion of sorts, since she had started out on
stage in Sydney and Melbourne before winning international acclaim
for ``Muriel's Wedding.''
 &HT;    ```Muriel' put me on the map,'' she recalls, ``and even though
Americans were saying I looked like Juliette Lewis or Debra Winger,
or I was the next Jamie Lee Curtis, I didn't think I was like any
of them. I thought of myself as the next Anthony Hopkins or Daniel
Day-Lewis.''
 &HT;    She makes no apologies for her penchant for globetrotting, which
she doesn't see as neglecting Australia.
 &HT;    ``It's good to work overseas,'' she says. ``Our industry is very
small, and it makes sense to do only one picture a year in
Australia. Otherwise you get overexposed.''
 &HT;    That's not a problem for her so far in the United States, but
she notes that, after her Oscar nomination, things are changing
fast.
 &HT;    ``Today I'm in a wonderful position,'' she says. ``I no longer
get scripts sent to me with other actresses' fingerprints on them.
 &HT;    ``I don't think I'll ever be a personality movie star, because
I'm not really a personality actor,'' she says. ``I love supporting
roles that have a very strong function, and to me `Hilary and
Jackie' and `My Son the Fanatic' fit that bill. In `Hilary and
Jackie' Emily did all the fireworks and created all the sound, and
I could do the feeling.
 &HT;    ``I did my role like somebody who feels the audience will make
an emotional connection with her,'' she says, ``even though she's
not the blinding light.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
