 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2550-- June 17, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2550 -- June 17, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. VERDUN IN THE DESERT: THE HORROR OF AFRICA'S
</P>
<P>
   FORGOTTEN WAR Along a stretch of worthless no-man's-land in the
Horn of Africa, a half-million troops from poverty-stricken
Ethiopia and Eritrea have been facing off in a little-noticed war
that may be the most pointless of Africa's many pointless wars.
They are locked in trench warfare, armed with high-tech weapons but
applying tactics more worthy of World War I. The toll has been
horrific - 40,000 lives lost, a third of them in a single three-day
battle - and the war has drained both countries' already barren
treasuries. Yet neither side will back down. Only the United States
and the United Nations appear capable of imposing a solution, and
their attention is focused elsewhere. By Alexander Smoltczyk. From
Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
THE BALKANS' IMPERIAL TRADITION - NOT ONE OF HATE Jason Goodwin,
author of ``Lords of the Horizon: A History of the Ottoman
Empire,'' writes that the Balkans have not always been a theatre of
war and Slobodan Milosevic's vision of the Balkans riven by ethnic
hatreds actually masks a far older and wiser imperial tradition.
New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3. IN
THE AFTERMATH OF KOSOVO : ENVIRONMENTAL CATASTROPHE? ``The fact
that military conflicts in our time can cause both a human and an
environmental catastrophe makes the task of preventing them even
more urgent and important ... Specifically, I believe that strikes
against certain industries and infrastructure, such as nuclear
power stations and some chemical and petrochemical plants, must be
prohibited ... The time has come to convene a second conference on
the environmental consequences of war in order to discuss
thoroughly issues of this kind.'' By Mikhail Gorbachev. 1,200
words. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
-------------4. DIVIDE AND SURVIVE Partition and population
exchange may be solutions of last resort in ethnic conflicts, but
they are better than the alternatives : war or the permanent
presence of an outside military force. By Anatol Lieven. From
Prospect magazine. 3,000 words. (N/A U.K.)
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. SMALLPOX : THE ONCE AND FUTURE SCOURGE? Until modern medicine
banished it, smallpox was once the world's most remorseless killer.
Now, as health and military officials fear the ancient scourge
could return, researchers have renewed interest in research and
questions regarding the virus and the aging vaccine stocks. What
makes the virus so deadly? How well do old vaccinations work? What
about new drugs and vaccines? How likely is a smallpox attack? By
Lawrence K. Altman, William J. Broad and Judith Miller. New York
Times Science Times. 3,600 words + graphic. (Abridged version
available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
CHINA SPYING IS A BLOWN-UP THREAT ``There has been a toxic cloud of
speculation, exaggeration and some sheer falsehoods released by the
report of Chinese spying on American nuclear secrets. Sorting out
information from feverish dramatization, nuclear strategy from
political agitation is complex and necessary. `` By Flora Lewis.
800 words.
