<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A WWII victory in Kosovo
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tidying up:
</P>
<P>
   Germany contributed some 500 military personnel and 14 aircraft
to the Kosovo campaign. Its pilots flew 394 missions to suppress
Serb anti-aircraft. They also flew 44 reconnaissance missions, and
remote-controlled German planes flew another 192. Now German armor
has rolled into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The German military had participated in recent years in various
multilateral peacekeeping missions, but this was the first time
German arms were engaged in Europe since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Germany returned to action as a well-established democratic
nation _ its 50th anniversary was May 23 _ in the company of other
democratic nations fighting to end a policy of murderous ethnic
abuse. Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you win one. Really win one.
</P>
<P>
   _ George W. Bush, on his maiden presidential campaign swing,
dubbed ``Great Expectations,'' is apparently confident the American
electorate doesn't know its Dickens. Otherwise he would fret that
voters might remember that the great expectations of the novel were
secretly funded by a crook. Poll-challenged Al Gore, for his part,
has lauched his ``What? Me worry?'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Great Practical Joker, the gremlin of Washington, D.C.,
has pulled off another nifty prank.
</P>
<P>
   The always holier-than-thou Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., was in
such a righteous huff over President Clinton's executive
appointment of a gay man as ambassador to Luxembourg that Inhofe
asserted senatorial privilege to block all other Clinton
appointees, and never mind the damage to U.S. interests. This is an
especially foolish time, for instance, to leave the U.N.
ambassadorship vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, technicians trying to puzzle out why the computer
system in Inhofe's office was being balky discovered it was
engorged with pornography three of the senator's staff had
downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Larry Flynt no doubt smiles, like the Happy Buddha.
</P>
<P>
   _ While Inhofe was being embarrassed, telepreacher Pat Robertson
was being exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson has always insisted with a straight face _ well, with
that perpetual Howdy Doody grin that on him passes for one _ that
his Christian Coalition is a nonpartisan organization busy about
the Lord's social work here on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Robertson has fooled the Lord is anybody's guess, though
it would seem an obvious mismatch, but he couldn't fool the
Internal Revenue Service. It has denied the tax-exempt status the
Christian Coalition had long sought. Groups that engage in
``substantial'' political activities aren't qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson is regrouping and has resumed direct command of the
coalition. The taxes it will now have to pay probably will be
small, but exposure of the organization as substantially political
lifts its mask of piety and may make some churches reluctant to let
themselves continue being used as religious cover for the partisan
energies of the Republican right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the IRS in your prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
