<HEADLINE>
PINEHURST NO. 2: SECOND TO NONE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ True golfers need not take the awkward route
of dying to savor golfers' heaven. They need only travel to the
Sandhills Country of Pinehurst, N.C., where 35 gems of golf courses
jewel this area, making it the true golfers' paradise of the world.
</P>
<P>
   And, of all the courses, Pinehurst No. 2 is the jewel of jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Ross's old homestead is on the third hole of Pinehurst
No. 2 and Ross's pilgrims trek to the site. Some of the more
fanatical bow and others linger to swap tales of America's foremost
golf course architect and, when they finally turn their backs on
Ross's home, they can stare out at his creation. A masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Little of American architecture _ of any kind _ moves the soul.
But here in Pinehurst, with sand so strangely afoot 100 miles from
the Atlantic Ocean on ``the course that Ross tinkered with for most
of his (later) life,'' as golf architect Rees Jones put it, the
soul is most definitely moved.
</P>
<P>
   Ross took great pride in this creation, which is on the byroads
of east-central North Carolina. Elizabeth Shapiro, Ross's
Boston-born granddaughter, Wednesday read a letter that Ross had
written in 1935 to Lillian Pippitt, Ross's daughter and Shapiro's
mother, after Ross had replaced the sand greens at Pinehurst with
grass and had made other improvements on No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new course is just grand,'' read Shapiro, from the letter.
``It is, I think, the best job I have ever done, and it will always
be a monument to (Donald Ross).''
</P>
<P>
   It was said to be impossible but even the hard souls of the men
of the US Golf Association also have been moved. For decade after
decade, the signature of virtually all courses the USGA revamped
for the Open has been frightfully narrow fairways as the first name
and ankle-high rough as the final name of the signature.
</P>
<P>
   Out of deference to Ross, though, there is neither at Pinehurst.
Fairways are wide and open and the rough at Pinehurst No. 2 might
cover a worm, but little more. These Open golfers will be tested as
Ross wanted all golfers to be tested, by their approach shots to
canny, subtle, and inscrutable greens. Miss by a foot or 2, and
those approach shots will bounce or roll to purgatory in front of
the greens or hell behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman's words were gushing, and not atypical as the
golfers took their final practice swings Wednesday for the US Open.
``Overall, as I think of all the US Opens I've played in,'' said
Norman, ``this is by far the best. By tenfold. They've maintained
the integrity of Donald Ross. This is the best US Open I've seen
and that's pretty much the word on the driving range and on the
putting green.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross designed hundreds of courses in the United States, and
Massachusetts golfers can debate until the last word rims out of
the 19th hole whether Essex, Salem, Worcester, Oyster Harbors or
Winchester country clubs are among his best creations, as Rhode
Island golfers can debate the merits of Rhode Island Country Club
versus Wannamoisett. But Pinehurst No. 2 was Ross's pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pleasure to play this golf course,'' said Norman.
``This is going to be very, very high up on my list of favorite
golf courses to play. I played very few courses on the PGA Tour
that challenge you in every aspect of your game, from the putting
all the way down to your driver. And Donald Ross has done it
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(It) is a second-shot golf course,'' said Norman, ``just as
Donald Ross wanted it. There's not a lot of trouble off the tees.
Not a lot of fairway bunkers. But Ross designed it as a second-shot
course. It's a very, very precise second-shot course and that's how
Ross did it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Rees Jones was called in four years ago to refine Pinehurst
No. 2, the fifth time he has refined an Open course for the USGA,
he went out of his way to be true to what Donald Ross cherished in
golf architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said Jones, ``was Ross's ultimate design. He tinkered
with it until the day he died.'' And, most of all, Jones wished to
be true to Ross's concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree it's like what I did at Brookline (Mass., for
the 1988 US Open at The Country Club),'' said Jones. ``Because,
like there, I had old photos to work from and when I rebuilt the
three greens at Brookline, I had a model. Here, the model was out
there for me to find.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jones searched Ross's archives at Pinehurst and located old
photos and plans for the 1962 US Amateur played at Pinehurst No. 2.
``(Ross) lived at the third hole and saw the course every day
(during the winter) and this was his ultimate challenge,'' said
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Golf legend has it _ although golf historians debate the facts _
that the reason Ross was so determined to make Pinehust No. 2 the
ultimate in course design was because he was miffed that Bobby
Jones chose Alistair MacKenzie _ and not Ross _ to design Jones's
ultimate course, Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say,'' said Rees Jones, ``that he was trying to outdo
Augusta National, when really Augusta National was trying to outdo
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ross) actually built No. 2 twice and then he redid it,'' said
Rees Jones, ``to make it the ultimate challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   To an average golfer, Pinehurst may not seem difficult because
the fairways are wide, the greens are large, there is only one
water hazard, and pine straw not hackable rough lines the edges of
the fairways. In that sense, this course is similar to Augusta
National.
</P>
<P>
   But, for a professional golfer, the subtleties are devilish. The
greens may be large, Jones explained, but there actually is only a
small area of the green to which a golfer may hit and expect his
ball to stay on the green. And, if the ball bounds off, trouble
abounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
