<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8922 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-COURSE-2ND &LR;  &UR;      06-17 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-COURSE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PINEHURST, N.C.: ... trouble abounds.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any golfer who has played Ross courses in New England knows the
absolute truism, said Jones: ``You never want to miss a Donald Ross
green over the green; you want to miss it short.''
</P>
<P>
   Revamping The Country Club for the Open ``will always be my
favorite job because it was my first Open (reconstruction),'' said
Jones, ``and because The Country Club was just a natural piece of
ground where they had left it alone a lot. But here, Ross created
this. Nature created The Cuntry Club.''
</P>
<P>
   But both jobs, said Jones, ``are like working on sacred ground.
So I came back here lots of times to make sure that everything was
done with what I thought Ross would have done. I think Ross would
be very happy. It's as close to way he left it in 1948, when he
died.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gods of golfing are warring with the gods of weather.
Wednesday, the weather gods won for the second day in a row,
dropping gentle rain on Pinehurst No. 2, slowing the greens, the
soft ground saving wayward shots from wandering afar.
</P>
<P>
   If there is controversy to what Jones did to refine Ross's
course, it is that the greens were expected to be very fast and the
grass surrounding the greens very trim. An errant shot was expected
to roll off the greens, confounding the golfers with which club to
use to get back onto the green. ``In Ross's day,'' said Jones,
``golfers were using mid-irons to get to the greens. Now, they're
using short irons'' and Ross's whole concept of the all-important
second shot was being thwarted by better equipment and more talent.
</P>
<P>
   Getting up and down from off the green was expected to be
improbable under Jones's re-design; Wednesday, balls were not even
leaving the green. ``This may be the only course in the world where
every green is crowned,'' said Jones. And every green is raised.
Havoc was supposed to loom.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinehurst played kindler and gentler Wednesday because of
the rain and the unthinkeable for the USGA _ a winning score of
12-under par _ possibly loomed as wet weather is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real hazard here is not the bunkers _ many are not even
close to the green _ but the chipping area,'' said Jones.
``Historically, we knew that's what Ross envisioned (a
lightning-quick and confounding chipping area) and the USGA wanted
to do what Ross envisioned. It'll be interesting to see how the
USGA reacts after the tournament.'' They might not come back if the
scores are too low.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1975 and the Atlanta Athletic Club has the Open been
held in the South and the prospect of unbearable weather has been
one of the reasons. But the cool, damp weather of this week has
furrowed more than a few brows. Rees Jones and the USGA may be
imploring the spirit of Donald Ross to convince the gods of golf
that Pinehurst No. 2, of all courses, should not be reduced to the
status of just another course because the weather gods wanted to
rain on yet another parade.
</P>
<P>
   Especially now that the US Open is paying its first visit to
Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eons and eons ago, long before scares of global warming or
global cooling, this part of North Carolina was under water. But
the earth cooled, the Atlantic Ocean retreated and tons of sand
were left behind here in these gentle hills.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1895, Bostonian James Walker Tufts, flush with money from
soda fountains, visited this ``Sahara of North Carolina,'' replete
with barren and forbidding dunes, and promptly bought 5,000 acres
at $1 an acre. The climate was temperate here and Tufts believed in
the therapuetic values of the longleaf pine tree.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts promptly built a New England-style village, naming it
Pinehurst Village, and North Carolinians thought this Yankee baron
to be a grand fool as he assembled architects, engineers, planners,
and workers to build a resort and grand hotel. Tufts also planted
220,000 pine seedlings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, an unhappy dairy farmer complained to Tufts that guests
at the resort were trampling through his fields, chasing a little
white ball with strange-looking clubs. His cows were being
disturbed
</P>
<P>
   Tufts found a New Yorker to lay out a nine-hole course at
Pinehurst, placating the farmers and, in time, brought in a young
Scotsman who had come to Boston a few years earlier to finish the
job and lay out a grand golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Ross would spend the winters of the next 48 years in
Pinehurst, directing his mules and men with spade and shovel to
move dirt, but not move it too far. To build a course, but a course
that was natural in the truest sense of the word, in tune with
nature.
</P>
<P>
   And now, nearly a century later, Tiger Woods came to Pinehurst
and said, ``To me, (Pinehurst No. 2) is the ultimate. I don't know
why. I think it's because it's not artificial.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lee Westwood said this course is unique, not seen in his
Europe nor here in the US. ``We have nothing like this in Europe,''
said Westwood. ``I don't know why people have the provision this is
going to suit the European player. Very rarely do we have to play
shots that we have to play around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus has seen virtually all the best courses in the
world and he came to Pinehurst and said, ``This golf course right
here is my favorite golf course from a design standpoint. I enjoy
this as much as any golf course I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rees Jones again repeated that all the greens on No. 2 are
crowned ``and you won't see that aywhere else in the United States,
or maybe in the world.'' The golf architect paused, ``You know,
Ross helped build (Pinehurst) No. 1 and he built course No. 3 and
No. 4. So he had other courses to play . . . for mere mortals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
