<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8923 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-17 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS THE REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Here are some of the clubs Payne Stewart has
experimented with around the greens at Pinehurst Number 2: 2-iron,
3-iron, 4-iron, 5-iron, pitching wedge, sand wedge, lob wedge,
putter, 7-iron, and 8-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great out there,'' he promises. ``It's going
to be special.''
</P>
<P>
   I certainly hope so. The United States Open is usually a very
aggravating affair. It doesn't matter whether it's Oakmont or
Oakland Hills or Congressional or Olympic, it's always the same old
baloney. They take a nice golf course, narrow the fairways to the
width of a hotel corridor, grow the rough higher than Muggsy
Bogues's head and dare the greatest golfers in the world to shoot
par.
</P>
<P>
   I hate it. Stray 2 feet off the fairway and you might as well be
in Canada. That's not golf. That's sado-masochism.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard, sure, but it's phony. The game, in theory, should be
challenging and rigorous. I think we all would agree to that. But
the standard US Open course of late is artificial. Phony. Bogus.
Stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic Donald Ross golf course. There is no need for
trickeration, unless you count making a couple of par 5s par 4s, a
move that simply means that additional decision-making will be
necessary. Other than that, this is the basic golf course laid out
by the great man 92 years ago. It is what it is.
</P>
<P>
   When people talk about this course, they use words such as
``creativity'' and ``imagination.'' OK, most of that imagination
will take place around the greens, but isn't that where we all know
big tournaments are customarily won, anyway? One of the things that
makes golf so fascinating is its complexity. Strength and distance
count. Soft touch counts, too. Thinking is another factor, and on
this course a man is forced to do a lot of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Big drivers are going to whale away on this course. ``It's
actually going to bring in the driver more than most (Open
courses),'' observes Colin Montgomerie. ``Because the fairways are
4 or 5 yards wider than normal, people are going to use drivers,
and because of that fact, miss the fairways as much as if they used
2-irons or 3-woods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the normal US Open,'' points out Greg Norman, ``you had to
be very conservative. The driver wasn't in your bag; the driver is
in your bag this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The big hitters will be hitting their 290s and 310s and if that
gets them off, fine. That's when the fun will start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course from tee to green is pretty simple,'' says Tiger
Woods. ``It's around the green where it gets complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   The standard Open green is surrounded by thick rough. There is
no mystery. You dig your feet in and you hack away. Either you get
lucky or you don't.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 2 there is no rough around the greens. They don't need
any. The greens are elevated and sloped. Things are not what they
seem. What works for one competitor may not work for another. You
will see lob wedges. You will see mid-irons. You will see many a
player putt uphill from long distances. And that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger is working on his 3-wood as a means to get close to the
pin, and he is not alone. Others think he's a bit daft. ``A 3-wood
or a 5-wood for a shot of 10 yards doesn't really make a lot of
sense to me,'' says Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   It happens to make sense to Greg Norman. ``I grew up using that
3-wood putt shot since I was in my teens and early 20s,'' he says.
``So I know that shot and I've played it before. I'll use it here
if I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   As will Mr. Woods. ``Because my 3-wood has more loft, it enables
me to put the ball on top of the grass faster and running,
especially when I've got grain to deal with,'' he explains. ``And
here you do.''
</P>
<P>
   So there.
</P>
<P>
   There is never going to be one answer for everybody. There will
be an improvisational theater air to the play around the greens.
There will be first-guessing, second-guessing and 10th-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   There was early speculation that because it is not a stereotyped
US Open course it might open the door for someone to become the
first European winner since Tony Jacklin in 1970. ``The runoffs
around the green are similar to Augusta in many ways,'' suggests
Montgomerie, ``and we've won 11 of the last 20 of them, so it might
favor the European player here for the first time in many years.''
</P>
<P>
   That's his opinion, anyway. It sure isn't Englishman Lee
Westwood's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing like this in Europe,'' he maintains. ``I don't
know why someone has the impression it's going to suit the European
player. That's just a proviso in case one of us wins.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter who wins, the star of the 1999 US Open will be a man
who died in 1948. For this course sprang from the fertile brain of
Donald Ross, the Scot who had a hand in fashioning an almost
unfathomable 400 golf courses. ``I grew up on a Donald Ross golf
course,'' says David Duval. ``I think what you see with these golf
courses, they're like ageless. They will always seem to be good
chip-and-putt challenges for any type player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun for the players to hit different shots,''
concludes Curtis Strange, the last man to win back-to-back Opens
(The Country Club in '88 and Oak Hill in Rochester, N.Y., the
following year). ``It's going to be fun for you to watch, the
viewers to watch on television, because there's going to be a lot
of different shots hit and a lot of imagination used.''
</P>
<P>
   We live in an age of hype and BS and nonsense. We ache for
something authentic. Most of America has become one big theme park.
And now we give you Pinehurst Number 2. This is a real golf course
for a real golfer. May the best thinker win.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
