<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN20-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bad news does not always travel fast
 &HT;    (Eds: Fixes misleadingly dropped word in 4th graf.)
 &HT;    (For release June 20, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday, my doctor wrote me a prescription for Rezulin, a
drug used to treat type-2 diabetes. I am among an estimated 15
million Americans with the disease. On Wednesday, the Food and Drug
Administration issued a report saying that there is ``further
evidence of serious and sometimes fatal liver injury in patients
treated with Rezulin.''
</P>
<P>
   It recommended that Rezulin no longer be used as a first therapy
for type-2 diabetes, that users need more frequent liver testing
and that the labels for the drugs be redone to reflect these
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The medication has had a troubled existence, so much so that my
doctor, before writing the prescription on Tuesday, chatted about
it with me, acknowledging the possibility of liver problems but
citing statistics that made it seem quite infrequent, considering
the number of people using the drug. (On March 19, the
manufacturers of the drug admitted it has been linked to about 28
deaths and seven liver transplants since its 1977 arrival on the
market.)
</P>
<P>
   Quite professionally, my doctor wanted me to know the dangers
and asked my approval before writing the prescription. I trust my
doctor and gave him the go-ahead. That was a day before the FDA
pronouncement, which included news that doctors were going to be
mailed letters from the FDA explaining the increased concern about
the drug and the new labeling.
</P>
<P>
   But here's what's got me really upset about the FDA
announcement. My hometown paper _ the Miami Herald _ did not carry
a word about it. Since type-2 diabetes has more impact on older
persons, and the South Florida area is awash in them, it seemed a
pretty important announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Had I not been keeping up on news via America Online, I never
would have known about the Wednesday announcement, would have
filled my prescription and, likely, would have gulped down a pill
by now.
</P>
<P>
   The next newspaper up the road, the Sun-Sentinel of Fort
Lauderdale, carried the news from the FDA as three paragraphs at
the very bottom of a story about a new diabetes monitor _ the
headline being on the monitor, not the warning.
</P>
<P>
   The National Edition of the New York Times carried not a word
about it and USA Today carried one paragraph inside the Lifeline
column_ just below the paragraph that said beheaded snakes still
can bite.
</P>
<P>
   A long-gone friend once noted that there is just enough news in
the world every day to fill up a newspaper. Not so. There is far
more, and we are having to seek alternative sources to keep track
of those many things that govern our quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   And even when you find the material, you are not certain of what
you are reading or seeing. The Associated Press story on Rezulin
carried by America Online made mention that the drug ``can cause
sudden and lethal liver failure, the government decided today.''
Yet the FDA's public announcement, put out on its Web page, made no
reference to ``sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   That caused me to call the FDA. Dr. John Jenkins, the agency's
director of the Office of Drug Evaluation II, said the word
``sudden'' is an interpretation. What the FDA has found, he said,
is that people who test normal one day can start showing symptoms
of liver failure within a week or two. That would be ``sudden.'' He
said it was not typical and that most cases of liver failure as a
result of the drug are gradual.
</P>
<P>
   So, what we have here is an example of when the information
highway is there but not used by many, despite the public's right
to know, and how some of that information eventually comes to us
not only late but a bit skewed.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
