<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8972 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEADLY-KNEE-BENDS-NYT     06-17 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADLY-KNEE-BENDS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY KNEE BENDS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By TONY DAJER  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Dec. 29, 1940. The Luftwaffe had roared over London. The dome of
Saint Paul's Cathedral rose ghostly above the smoke and flames.
Below, buried in rubble, hundreds of people were dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any alive in there?!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here. I'm Alice. Please find me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescue crews reached Alice only after nine hours of desperate
digging. To their relief, she seemed intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all right, my girl. You're all right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My leg. Please. I can't feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City, 1998. A quiet day in the emergency room. William,
my resident, ambled over and said, ``Twenty-five-year-old male with
gross hematuria. He's been peeing red since he woke up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' I asked. Many hidden pathologies can turn a healthy
young man's urine a shocking red. ``How many red cells in the
urinalysis?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Five to 10 per field.''
</P>
<P>
   Too few for frank bleeding caused by a kidney stone or a
ruptured kidney cyst. Something besides blood was making our
patient's urine red.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's he do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, not much. He's a prisoner. The cops brought him in
not long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   William and I approached the patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Kelly, how are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts. Damn. Pardon the language, but it hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing original there. Prisoners often feel the urge for a
change of scenery, and a trip to the ER can fit the bill. But then
Kelly gripped his thighs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're killing me, Doctor!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anybody hit you? Did you have a bad fall?'' I asked, more
attentive now.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. God help me. I need something for the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to picture an inmate's schedule of daily activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you worked out recently?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a contest _ deep knee bends. Not much else to do in
jail, Doctor. And I won _ 1,134.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-oh. When?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Night before last. Winner got extra dessert.''
</P>
<P>
   Now I understood. I owed that understanding to E.G.L. Bywaters,
the brilliant English doctor who treated Alice after her rescue
from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   At first Alice had seemed fine. Nothing but her left calf had
suffered. But by evening the next day, the leg had turned cold and
blue below the knee. Bywaters called the surgeons in to amputate.
That should have been the end of the case.
</P>
<P>
   But soon afterward Alice's urine turned an ominous brown. Under
the microscope it teemed with casts _ crescents of debris that
congeal when the kidneys' collecting apparatus is dammed or
poisoned. Her kidneys seemed to have shut down.
</P>
<P>
   On the seventh day, wrote Bywaters, Alice ``collapsed and died
in three minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I didn't feel any pain at all,'' continued the
prisoner. ``We did 'em night before last.''
</P>
<P>
   The resident's face lit up. ``Now I know. Rhabdomyolysis,'' he
announced. The word means ``destruction of skeletal muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly had trashed his thigh muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple,'' I agreed.
</P>
<P>
   It was far from simple in 1941. In March, Bywaters and his
colleague D. Beall noted in the British Medical Journal the deaths
of three more young people with injuries similar to Alice's. Their
autopsies recorded the kidneys as ``the point of major interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidneys are the first stop in the body's waste elimination
system. Blood carrying waste flows into the kidneys via coils of
porous capillaries.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapped around the capillaries are cells that act as
gatekeepers. They keep big items like blood cells and large
proteins inside the blood vessels and permit water, smaller
proteins and waste to pass into the kidney tubules, where, with
more distilling, urine forms.
</P>
<P>
   Bywaters noted that the victims' tubules were clogged with
``dense, brownish material ... that seemed to be all of the same
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked exactly like what he had seen in Alice's urine before
she died. Alice's kidneys, and those of her fellow victims, had
been choked and poisoned. But by what?
</P>
<P>
   The problem begins with wrecked cells. As every budding
Schwarzenegger knows, muscles require constant remodeling. So each
cell is loaded with a potent package of protein-chewing enzymes.
And the cells must also store oxygen and fuel to be ready at a
moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   When muscle cells are crushed or cut off from their blood supply
(as in Alice's case) or violently stressed (as in Kelly's case),
they leak myoglobin, the oxygen-storing protein of the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   What Bywaters did was trace the steps between muscle injury and
kidney failure. He figured out that the brown substance was
myoglobin. At one-fourth the size of hemoglobin, it was the perfect
size to sneak through the meshwork in the kidney capillaries and
clog the urine-forming draining tubules.
</P>
<P>
   Bywaters also figured out why myoglobin was muddy in color.
Myoglobin with a neutral pH stays red and is nontoxic to tubule
cells in the kidneys. But at an acid pH, myoglobin separates into
two daughter molecules, one of which is muddy brown in color and
poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   Patients with muscle injury are often dehydrated, which turns
their blood acidic. Meanwhile, myoglobin, released from dying
muscle cells, clogs kidney tubules. The piled-up myoglobin is then
exposed to increasing amounts of acid, which turns it into its
noxious form.
</P>
<P>
   If this poisoning goes on, the kidneys stop working. They no
longer excrete potassium. And potassium buildup can trigger cardiac
arrest, as it did in Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Kelly's condition wasn't that advanced, but he
could get there. His thighs, at least on a cellular level, were
mincemeat. His urine was saturated with myoglobin. Kidney function
was borderline, and it could go south without warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Kelly's pipes need flushing, William,'' I said. ``Let's go
with a quick liter of saline.''
</P>
<P>
   Bywaters had recommended a minimum of three liters a day to
flush the kidneys. We now know that up to 20 liters is needed. We
also added a hefty dose of baking soda to Kelly's fluids to
neutralize the acid buildup in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Rhabdomyolysis goes hand in hand with humanity's penchant for
mayhem. Today doctors can treat the condition, but only if we catch
it early. Kelly's brush with killer knee bends was proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tony Dajer lives in Paris with his wife, an attorney, and
their three children. Dajer is at work on a book about medical
mistakes and the science of diagnosis.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; `
</P>
</TEXT>
