<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8982 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-ANTS18-COX     06-17 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-ANTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phorid fly and fire ants
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _Watch out, imported fire ants: Your historic
antagonists from the old country are settling in in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gnat-sized flies, imported from Brazil, bred in Austin, and
released in February near Laredo, seem to be thriving. Despite heat
and drought, they are reproducing on their own and attacking
imported fire ants every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are definitely optimistic and on course,'' said Larry
Gilbert, chairman of the Zoology Department of the University of
Texas, who is part of a state-supported effort to find biological
controls for the stinging red ants to replace expensive chemicals
that kill even beneficial insects.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert recently found the flies active at 30 percent of ant
mounds around release sites on a private ranch near Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   The ants are known for disrupting many a family picnic and
causing billions of dollars in damages from North Carolina to Texas
since arriving from Brazil on ships early in this century. But the
flies keep them on their best behavior in Brazil, where they are
not pests.
</P>
<P>
   The flies throw fear into an entire mound by attacking only a
few workers, laying eggs in gaps between the ant's armor. When the
eggs hatch, the larvae kill the ant by eating their way out of its
body. Maturing into flies, they start the process all over again.
</P>
<P>
   The flies shouldn't become a problem themselves, since they only
prey on the imported ants in an ancient parasitic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's work ``seems to be progressing very well,'' said
Harlan Thorbilson, a Texas Tech entomologist studying a species of
fungi that can infect a whole mound.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists say it could be a decade before batches of
flies, or other controls, are available for your own back 40.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
