<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-PLUNGE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mayor flush, as he plunges into big `toilet' issue
 &HT;    By Scott McCabe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ It nearly killed him last year, but Mayor Tom
Ramiccio vows he'll again make the annual July 4 trek across what
he calls Palm Beach County's biggest toilet: the Intracoastal
Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, he'll take the seventh annual one-mile
``Plunge Against the Grunge'' in a donated plastic bubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not crazy,'' said Ramiccio, who was hospitalized twice
with a mysterious virus after last year's dip. He lost 30 pounds
and suffered earaches, headaches and 103-degree fevers. ``People
need to know the lagoon is dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles of canals and about 1,500 storm drains dump fertilizers,
grease, cigarette butts, rubber, pesticides and animal excrement
into the lagoon. Anything can be found there: cyanide, gold,
silver, even the polio virus, health officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiccio's ready to return, despite vowing to ban recreational
activities in the lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   He's taking BOB, a scooterlike submarine that'll keep his head
dry in a plastic fish-bowl helmet. Whether the mayor submerges
completely or just bobs along, he'll remain dry, said inventor
Andrew Sneath of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiccio said he won't dip his head. Not after last year. Not
after the battery of tests, CAT scans, an MRI and a spinal tap.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, in the ``Dead Zone,'' where the swim takes place,
``It's so polluted you can't see your hand in front of your face,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gargiulo, county director of environmental health and
engineering, said the swim _ initiated by former Mayor Rodney
Romano in 1993 to dramatize the need for a cleanup _ sends the
wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect, it's a horrible idea,'' Gargiulo said.
``It's like eating bad food to discourage others from eating bad
food.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
