<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8985 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANCHOR-RAISED18-COX     06-17 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANCHOR-RAISED18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spanish anchor, cannons pulled from sea
 &HT;    By Joe Brogan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Two barnacle-encrusted cannons and an anchor
from the wrecked Spanish ship San Miguel de Archangel were raised
recently from the sandy bottom of Jupiter Inlet, where they had
lain awaiting restoration.
</P>
<P>
   When the 340-year-old artifacts broke the surface of the inlet's
azure waters with a salty spray and were hoisted onto a barge in
the shadow of Jupiter Lighthouse, it marked the first step in a
two-year process that will refurbish them.
</P>
<P>
   They were donated to the town, which will pay the state Bureau
of Archeological Research, Conservation and Collection in
Tallahassee $5,000 to undo centuries of corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real good example of the town partnering with the state
so the public can see these artifacts in a setting that is very
close to where they came from,'' said Russ Ruskay, town parks and
recreation director.
</P>
<P>
   Once restored, the 1,000-pound items will be displayed outdoors
in the recently-redesigned Lighthouse Park on the inlet's north
side. They will be visible from U.S. 1, Ruskay said. But that could
take two years, state archaeologist Jim Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   An electrolysis process will slowly remove salt and other
contaminants from the metal. Then it will be sandblasted and
painted with a primer coat and an industrial-quality finish coat.
</P>
<P>
   The archaeological bureau has restored more than 100 artifacts
since it was formed in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Leo, a Palm Beach County lifeguard and president of
Jupiter Wreck Inc., donated the artifacts to the town. He found the
remains of the ship while swimming in the ocean off Jupiter Inlet
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The San Miguel de Archangel began its fateful journey in 1659
when the viceroy of Lima, Peru, ordered it to sail to Spain to
impress King Philip IV with the quality of gold and silver coins
minted in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   It sank in a storm off Jupiter Inlet in either December 1659 or
January 1660 and rested in 10 feet of water until Leo's discovery.
</P>
<P>
   He has salvaged more than 10,000 gold and silver coins, gold
bars and various artifacts from the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
