</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's joy in watching a thunderstorm
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The storm swept through late Wednesday
afternoon, coming from the south, a blue-black wall of clouds
accompanied by thunder slowly arriving, sounding like a parade
rounding the corner. We were trying to finish our round of golf,
but a few flashes of lightning convinced us to head to the
clubhouse and to stop wielding lightning rods made by Big Bertha or
Ping. We barely made it before the skies opened. The round was
over, time for a few beers, chips and salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's dusk and a gentle rain still comes down. My roses and
tomato plants look pleased.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a wet spring, for which we're grateful here behind
the Pine Curtain. Much of Texas is still experiencing the drought
that started early last year and made last summer the most
miserable in recent memory. I made a vow last year, while lugging
around hoses and desperately trying to keep the lawn alive, that I
would never complain about rain again. So far, I've kept my
promise.
</P>
<P>
   I do love a thunderstorm. I'll sit on the back porch at night,
reading a book under the ceiling fan, watching the heat lightning
build in the southeastern sky down by Lake Sam Rayburn, making
silent bets about whether it will turn into wind and rain. And a
good trash-hauler in the early morning is perfect for lounging in
the recliner under a comforter, sipping coffee and listening to the
radio.
</P>
<P>
   Storms out of the south seem to pack more rain and less wind
than storms that start out in the Staked Plains of West Texas and
sweep across into the Piney Woods. I pay attention to those storms
coming from the west. They often bring big winds and occasional
tornadoes. Storms that come up from Houston or Beaumont are laden
with moisture from the Gulf, but not much wind or hail. We've had
our share of both lately.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my two best lightning stories:
</P>
<P>
   _ As a child, growing up in New Hampshire, our tiny house had a
cellar that was too small and nasty to call a basement, with a dirt
floor and a musty smell that conjured up images of boogeymen in my
young mind. It also tended to flood when it rained hard, so we had
a sump pump to get the water out. One afternoon a thunderboomer
hit, and the cellar began taking on water. My mother enlisted me to
help her run the pump. I held the hose out the window while
lightning bolts lit up the sky. Suddenly there was a crackling in
the air, and a white-blue arc of light came through the window,
went around us both and back out the window. In my mind, more than
30 years later, I can still smell the air after the lightning came
through, as if someone had set fire to a milk jug and then snuffed
it out. My mother and I stood there in shock for a moment, finally
realizing neither of us had been struck. That ended our attempt to
pump out the cellar, and I did my level best to never go down there
again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many years later, I was playing golf by myself on a now-closed
course in San Augustine. A storm came up when I was as far away
from the clubhouse as you could get, maybe a half-mile. I didn't
have much warning before I realized I was in trouble. As I drove
the cart pell-mell toward safety, lightning hit on the course at
least a dozen times, sometimes less than 50 yards away. The wind
was blowing at least 60 mph. I was trying to remember the words to
the Act of Contrition from my Catholic upbringing as I weaved
through trees bent over from the wind. I felt like I was in a
Stephen King novel, the trees looking like monsters as the
lightning illuminated them, gnarled branches reaching malevolently
for me. (I have always suffered from an overactive imagination.)
</P>
<P>
   Later, safely back at the pro shop, I found out lightning had
struck a house near the course, causing a fire.
</P>
<P>
   The finest summer weather I've ever experienced was in
Flagstaff, Ariz., a town about the size of ours, just south of the
Grand Canyon. I spent a week there a decade ago. Each day it would
start clouding up promptly at 3 p.m., and a thunderstorm would pass
through, lasting roughly an hour. You could set your watch by the
storm's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Sauna Land, an afternoon thunderstorm's aftermath is
nearly unbearable, steam rising from the asphalt and the air heavy
enough to bottle. But in Flagstaff, up high and surrounded by the
San Francisco mountains, it feels like the world has been reborn
after a summer storm. There's a cool dry air, a magical light that
makes the world look like an Ansel Adams photograph, and a
freshness that makes you optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   One of these days I'm going to go back to Flagstaff in summer
just so I can revel in an afternoon storm from the safety of a
porch, and then sit under a birch tree when it's done and read a
good book. I can think of few finer ways to spend a day.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
