<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LCRA water deal blew in on the winds of fate
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The $100 million water accord struck between
Austin and the Lower Colorado River Authority was the product of a
lot of hard work and a twist of fate.
</P>
<P>
   In an illustration of how long a shadow one decision can cast,
Mark Rose, general manager of the LCRA, might not have been in the
position to make either the Garwood or the Austin deal if his dream
of becoming mayor of Austin had come true.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was elected to the Austin City Council in 1983. He was
re-elected in 1985, the year Frank Cooksey was elected mayor.
Cooksey soon discovered that his relationship withRose had more
than a few thorns. Their running disagreement over the direction of
the city resulted in Rose mounting a challenge to Cooksey in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Five months after announcing his mayoral candidacy, Rose
withdrew in an announcement that stunned his supporters. He quit to
take a top administrative job with the LCRA. He said at the time
that it was an offer he couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   If Rose ever looked back, he never said so publicly and last
week he probably left a bigger imprint on Austin than he ever would
have had as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Rose and Austin Mayor Kirk Watson signed an agreement that will
guarantee Austin's water supply for the next 50 years at a price
tag of $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, the city locks up water rights _ bought and sold in
Texas like any other commodity on a first-come, first-served basis
_ that could easily have gone elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Given current and projected growth, the deal was a wise one, but
one that will be shot at by those unfamiliar with the Byzantine way
Texas water rights are allocated or by those who see water as a
tool with which to manipulate growth.
</P>
<P>
   Ensuring a water supply to meet the future demand is
fundamental, but it took commitment and vision. Rose had the
foresight to acquire the water rights owned by the Garwood
Irrigation District. Rose bought 133,000 acre feet _ enough water
to cover 133,000 acres under one foot _ for $75 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   It was the largest such deal in the history of the state. In so
doing, Rose ensured a water supply for the Austin area for the next
50 years. That didn't automatically ensure that Austin would get a
share of it, though.
</P>
<P>
   The LCRA's district stretches from the Hill Country to the coast
and there are plenty of potential customers for that water. Just
because the water flows through Austin doesn't give the city
automatic rights to it.
</P>
<P>
   The city staff had to move _ and fast _ toward acquiring those
rights. With any hesitation, Rose and the LCRA would have been
required to sell to whoever came to them with a deal ``We had a
chance to do something without a crisis,'' Rose said last week.
``Austin feels good; we feel good. This is the way things are
supposed to work.''
</P>
<P>
   For Watson, the deal is also a source of great pride. A
longtime, behind-the-scenes political player, Watson stepped into
the spotlight to run for mayor. The chief opponent in the race was
Ronney Reynolds, a former City Council member whose cherished dream
was to be mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Watson led Reynolds going into a run-off, and Reynolds suddenly
withdrew. Reynolds' supporters were as stunned as Rose's were 10
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   However able a council member Reynolds was, he was always cast
as a villain by environmentalists. Had Reynolds tried to put
together the deal, the muted grumbling you hear about it now would
have been long and loud.
</P>
<P>
   Both Watson and Rose say _ with justification _ the deal is
their proudest moment. To think _ that moment hinged as much on a
twist of their fates as it did all the hard work that went into
putting it together.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at agarcia(at)statesman.com
or (512) 445-3667.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
