<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plenty of candidates are aiming for Archer's seat
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Texas congressional districts don't turn over very
much. And Houston's 7th District, where Republican Bill Archer
won't be standing for re-election next year, will be turning over
for the first time since Archer inherited it from George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That's former President Bush _ not his son George, the Texas
governor who wants to be president. The elder Bush, who still lives
in the district, quit the 7th in 1970 to make a run for the U.S.
Senate against liberal Democrat Ralph Yarborough. But he lost to
Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, who upset Yarborough in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Archer is 71 and chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
He's quitting partly because he's been around for a long time. But
undoubtedly adding to his decision is that Republicans limited
their committee chairmen to three two-year terms when they took
over Congress in the 1994 elections _ and next year is Archer's
last as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of candidates to replace him. So far, a
state representative, an investor, a journalist-turned-preacher,
the daughter of a former mayor and a lawyer have announced. All are
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That's no surprise, since the 7th District is among the most
Republican in the country. In 1996, GOP presidential nominee Bob
Dole got 67 percent here. The last time a Democrat had the gall to
challenge Archer, in 1988, she got just 21 percent. Archer's idea
to abolish the income tax system and replace it with a national
sales tax is wildly popular here.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. John Culberson (R-Houston) officially announced his
candidacy four days after the legislative session ended. But he's
been waiting for years for the time when Archer might retire and
has been running for months.
</P>
<P>
   Culberson's well-rehearsed platform is built around removing
U.S. District Judge William Wayne Justice in particular and the
federal government in general from any control over state school,
prison and other systems.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year veteran of the Texas House says he would continue
the work of the Republican Congress in cutting taxes and government
spending to strengthen job growth and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Culberson notes that he has filed lawsuits and worked with
``Chairman Archer'' to pass laws aimed at vastly reducing federal
control over local affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Culberson, who plans to rely on grass-roots campaigning, says
his chief competitor is Peter Wareing, 47, an investor. He's also
been running for months, and there are lots of bumper stickers on
Suburbans to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Wareing is the son-in-law of Jack Blanton, a popular and
well-known donor to politicians of both political parties. Blanton
was appointed to the University of Texas Board of Regents in 1985
by Democratic Gov. Mark White.
</P>
<P>
   Wareing says he's voted in both parties' primaries and
contributed to conservative Democrats as well as Republicans. He
has already raised more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to raise whatever it takes to run an effective
campaign,'' Wareing says matter-of-factly _ and is ready to dip
into his own pocket if necessary. Message: He'll have TV ads in
Houston's hugely expensive market; Culberson might not.
</P>
<P>
   Wareing's campaign sounds similar to Culberson's: shrink the
federal government. ``The message of most of the candidates is
going to be pretty similar, since we're all Republicans,'' Wareing
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates likely to get support from hard-core
religious conservatives are Republican National Committeewoman
Cathy McConn, whose father Jim was mayor decades ago, and Wallace
Henley, who quit as the preacher of the Encourager Church to run.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney and GOP political activist Mark Brewer also is running.
</P>
<P>
   That Gov. Bush will be on the Republican primary ballot, and
that there will be churning among candidates seeking Culberson's
state House seat and perhaps another seat, should help make the
turnout larger and mainstream _ blunting the impact of the
religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Look for a long, hard race. Dave McNeely writes about politics
for the Austin American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com or (512) 445-3644.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
