A8993 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEM-RESIGNATIONS18-CO     06-17 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-RESIGNATIONS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Democrats' rebuilding effort takes another direct hit
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _The Texas Democratic Party, looking for a return
to its glory days, is also looking for replacements for three top
officials who had been working on that mission.
</P>
<P>
   The party's executive director, finance director and
communications director all quit in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Cook, the former executive director, said he left because
he and Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm operated on different
frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chair and I had some differences in approach to the job,''
he said. ``We sat down and talked about it. I decided it was a good
time to leave.'' Neither he nor Malcolm wanted to talk about those
differences but Cook said Malcolm, a former Republican who was
elected state Democratic chairman last June, was a more
``hands-on'' leader than others had been.
</P>
<P>
   The other resignations were turned in by Finance Director
Shannon Finley and Communications Director Liz Chadderdon. Finley
will move to Reno to serve as finance director for Nevada Attorney
General Frankie Sue Del Papa's 2000 race for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Finley said her departure is for career and family reasons.
Chadderdon, who took a job with a Washington direct-mail firm,
could not be reached for comment on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm called the staff turnover ``just the normal of what goes
on.'' Cook has a long record of party leadership. In addition to
serving as executive director since December, he had been the
director of the party's effort to help coordinate all of its
candidates' campaigns in 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The turnover comes amid rumblings of dissatisfaction with
Malcolm's performance as head of the party. Democratic sources say
several people are considering challenging Malcolm when her term
ends next June. She said Wednesday she plans to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said she is aware of the undercurrent of
dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter who is doing anything there are always going to be
detractors. Yes, it is different,'' she said of her leadership
style. ``That's the very reason I was elected.'' Malcolm has
stressed improving communications among Democratic activists and
re-energizing the grassroots.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of elections under Malcolm's leadership did not
go well for the Democratic Party, which for generations was the
dominant party in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of last November's election, Republicans hold every
statewide office. Next year, in addition to the uphill challenge of
trying to carry Texas for a Democratic presidential candidate who
could be running against Gov. George W. Bush, the Democrats face a
monumental challenge in trying to unseat Republican U.S. Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said the party's top goal for 2000 is maintaining its
slim edge in the Texas House of Representatives and trying to
regain a Senate majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making a lot of progress and part of what we see as you
move on down the road is that you do make changes as you go toward
a goal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
