<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0619 TARZAN RETURNS _ Tarzan of the Apes,
Lord of the Jungle. What makes the ape-man so compelling? Is it his
ability to communicate with animals? Is it his can-do attitude? Or
is it his luxuriant mane of hair, rippling pecs and tiny loincloth?
(Boas, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes 4-column color photo
from new Disney film, 18-pica color photo from the film ``George of
the Jungle,'' 1-column B&AMP;W photo of Johnny Weissmuller, who
portrayed Tarzan in ``Tarzan Escapes.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TARZAN LIST _ Ten reasons why we love Tarzan (Boas, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TARZAN ACTORS _ A list of actors who have played the role of
Tarzan. (Boas, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   STAR FILE: Pop star Seal answers questions and reveals his
thoughts on his fears and his heroes. (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column color photo of Seal.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ ``Enemy of the State'' shows George Orwell's Big
Brother has nothing on the U.S. National Security Agency. Also,
``In Dreams'' and ``My Name is Joe,'' ``The Faculty,'' ``Little
Voice,'' and ``Dancing at Lughnasa.'' (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column color photo from
``Enemy of the State.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ Randy Newman is back to his satirical self in ``Bad
Love.'' Also, Smash Mouth and the score of ``Fosse.'' (Staff,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0615 -- Hide the Chianti and fava beans. Hannibal
Lecter, the cannibalistic psychiatrist from Thomas Harris' best
seller ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' is back. And he's as hungry as
ever. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
1-column color photo from film ``Silence of the Lambs'' and 6-pica
color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: OUT FOR GOOD -- ``Out for Good: The Struggle to
Build a Gay Rights Movement in the United States'' is an invaluable
document, impressively researched, remarkably well-written and
groundbreaking in its scope. (Harrison, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) art includes 3 column color photo of gay
rally at 1996 Democratic National Convention and 6-pica color photo
of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THREE REVIEWS -- Reviews of three recent releases: ``Betty
Friedan: Her life'' ``Dreaming of Columbus,'' and ``Cleaving, A
Storyof Marriage.'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Includes
3 color 6-pica color photos of book jackets.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- Periodically there come in one's life
Rubicons that must be crossed. Punctuation is one of these. Anyone
who begins a sentence and ends it with a little black dot knows the
uncertainty of getting from here to there. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column color photo of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-INNERGOLF _ Here on the suburban golf driving range, deep
thinking is going on: Which club should I use? Should I try
changing my grip? Who am I really ? It's the newest trend in one of
the oldest games around, and it's hitting the publishing industry
with the force of a Big Bertha: Getting in touch with yourself
through golf. We talk to publishing experts, authors, a sports
psychologist and golfers for a fun read with an eye towards Fathers
Day timing. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-NOTES _ Thomas Harris remains as much a mystery as
Hannibal Lecter; report on sales of ``Hannibal'' and reaction; In
``Cleaving,'' a Birmingham writing couple reveal an unsparing
portrait of their marriage; Looking for yesteryear's best sellers?
The Antiquarian Book Fair this weekend in Gwinnett County offers
first editions of Frankenstein, Zora Neale Hurston's ``Jonah's
Gourd Vine,'' and an others at prices ranging from $5 to $250,000.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 21.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HICKMAN _ Homer Hickman Jr. captivated the country with
his memoir ``Rocket Boys,'' which was made into the movie ``October
Sky.'' Now the Huntsvilla, Ala., ex-NASA engineer has written his
first novel, ``Back to the Moon,'' about a hijacked Space Shuttle.
In town on Friday, Hickham talks about his new career as a writer
and why our space program is heading in the wrong direction.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 18.
</P>
