</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-INNERGOLF _ Here on the suburban golf driving range, deep
thinking is going on: Which club should I use? Should I try
changing my grip? Who am I really ? It's the newest trend in one of
the oldest games around, and it's hitting the publishing industry
with the force of a Big Bertha: Getting in touch with yourself
through golf. We talk to publishing experts, authors, a sports
psychologist and golfers for a fun read with an eye towards Fathers
Day timing. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-NOTES _ Thomas Harris remains as much a mystery as
Hannibal Lecter; report on sales of ``Hannibal'' and reaction; In
``Cleaving,'' a Birmingham writing couple reveal an unsparing
portrait of their marriage; Looking for yesteryear's best sellers?
The Antiquarian Book Fair this weekend in Gwinnett County offers
first editions of Frankenstein, Zora Neale Hurston's ``Jonah's
Gourd Vine,'' and an others at prices ranging from $5 to $250,000.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 21.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HICKMAN _ Homer Hickman Jr. captivated the country with
his memoir ``Rocket Boys,'' which was made into the movie ``October
Sky.'' Now the Huntsvilla, Ala., ex-NASA engineer has written his
first novel, ``Back to the Moon,'' about a hijacked Space Shuttle.
In town on Friday, Hickham talks about his new career as a writer
and why our space program is heading in the wrong direction.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 18.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
