<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9050 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BALKANS-$ADV20     06-17 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BALKANS-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR FEEBLE RUSSIA, THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING IMPORTANT
 &HT;    EDs: An analysis sig can be used with this story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Winning isn't everything. For Russia these days, with
its economy a shambles and its president ailing and oblivious to
affairs of state, winning isn't even possible.
</P>
<P>
   But being in the game is.
</P>
<P>
   Possessing a prominent role in world affairs has become
all-important for the withered superpower still struggling to
define its role in the post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing troops to take the Pristina airport last weekend ahead
of NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo was the latest and most audacious
example of an approach, which, by design or default, has given
Russia a conspicuous role in determining the future of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the United States seldom agree on policy in some of
the most contentious and dangerous parts of the world, from Iraq to
Yugoslavia, from economic reforms in Russia itself to NATO
expansion in Europe. At the United Nations and elsewhere, Moscow's
diplomatic vexing of America and its Western allies seldom
prevails, but it cannot be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The bold move by Russian generals, with an apparent nod from
President Boris Yeltsin, to speed troops into war-torn Kosovo was
viewed as an important achievement in Russia, where nationalists
are suspicious of both NATO's eastward expansion and America's
intentions in a region once under the sway of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   . ``What did Moscow accomplish with this frantic gesture? A
great deal. Western politicians, recently grown accustomed to
presenting Russia with a fait accompli, were reminded that two can
play this game,'' said Maxim Yusin, a political commentator for the
Russian daily Izvestia.
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, Russians have lived with a fact of life seldom
discussed here but widely comprehended: They lost the Cold War. As
a result, Russians are loath to tolerate what they perceive as the
West dictating the terms of a New World Order.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States and Britain bombed Iraq last December
after U.N. weapons inspectors there were thwarted, Russia reacted
with hard rhetoric. Frustrated by the Kremlin's inability to affect
policy, some Russians took to the streets to protest the action
against a traditional Russian ally.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia, launched in March,
took the simmering collective resentment a step further, giving
Russians a reason to vent their anger. The U.S. Embassy in downtown
Moscow remains marred by paint stains and broken windows after it
was pelted by angry mobs at the start of the NATO air war nearly
three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Thursday, Russia's Communist-dominated lower house of
parliament, the Duma, passed a resolution calling on NATO Secretary
General Javier Solana to be tried as an international war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has historic, cultural and Orthodox Christian ties to
Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic. Since the end of World War
II, Yugoslavia has been an important customer of Russian arms
suppliers and oil and gas exporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian self-esteem plays a larger part in motivating
Moscow's policy than Slavic brotherhood or regional trade.
</P>
<P>
   For the majority of people in the former Soviet Union, life was
austere, but nonetheless filled with self-satisfaction with the
communist empire's military, scientific, cultural and sports
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall of the Soviet Union in 1991, the new Russia
promised greater prosperity and peace, but ultimately failed to
deliver. Most Russians are poorer than they were 10 years ago; the
country's army is falling apart as is the social net of health and
welfare services.
</P>
<P>
   Since Russia's economic collapse last August, polls have
consistently shown a sizeable majority of Russians blame America
for Russia's failures, despite ample evidence of Russia's own bad
management, corruption and failure to enact meaningful economic
reforms. Many believe the United States -- despite its economic aid
and advice, or perhaps because of it -- has a policy designed to
humiliate and weaken Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia retains its powerful seat as a permanent member of the
United Nations Security Council. It also has stepped up to the
table as the eighth member of the G-8 - the world's seven largest
industrialized democracies, plus Russia, added last year as a
signal of Moscow's importance.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomacy is slow and, for Russia of late, unsatisfying. Its
military glory was long ago tarnished by humiliating failures in
Afghanistan and Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is why the dispatch of 200 troops to Pristina's
airport touched a patriotic chord here. The Russian public
applauded Russia's bold move of troops into Kosovo. The general in
charge of the operation received a promotion and a medal. Russian
newspapers were filled with headlines celebrating Russia's
``lightening strike'' that got the better of the United States and
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The event underscored Russia's desire to be a player on the
world stage, to flex its muscle as in the days of the Soviet Union.
With Yeltsin's clout slipping steadily and no one with the
authority to fill his role, a foreign policy has emerged to defy
the West first, and ask questions later.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic-reform advocates in Russia regarded the Kosovo troop
deployment -- if indeed it was planned by the Kremlin, or merely
the act of unrestrained generals forcing Yeltsin's hand -- as a
policy of denial. They saw it as yet another example of Russia's
continuing inability to shift its world thinking from Cold War
politics to 90's-style global economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irreparable damage has been inflicted to Russia's image,''
said Konstantin Borovoi, a reform-minded member of the Duma.
``Russia's self-isolation is already a fact of life. There will be
a cooling of long-term relations with Russia. That will not be a
cold war but a cooling of relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilly or not, the West cannot afford to neglect Russia, which
has the world's second largest nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, ruled by the ostensibly westward-leaning Yeltsin, is
still awkwardly searching for its identity. Like a bad habit from
bygone days, it embraces brutal dictators like Iraq's Saddam
Hussein and Yugoslavia's Slobodan Milosevic, clinging to them as
tools to be used in the Russian foreign policy to leverage more
influence for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's policy may be irksome, but it is not ideological. If
there is one bright spot, it is Russia's willingness to bend.
</P>
<P>
   The divisiveness over the Kosovo war, and the disorderly peace,
has not significantly influenced other areas of U.S.-Russian
cooperation. On Wednesday, Russian and U.S. officials in Washington
extended for another seven years the program begun in 1991 to
reduce the threat of nuclear, biological, chemical and other
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, in the Balkans, Russia defied its combative posture in
favor of pragmatism. Russia ardently opposed the NATO air campaign
against Yugoslavia. In the beginning, there was even speculation
that Moscow would try to re-supply the Serbs with arms. But in the
end, Russia helped broker Milosevic's capitulation. Russia eagerly
wanted to be included in the international peacekeeping mission to
oversee the post-war Kosovo province, then rushed in setting up a
potentially dangerous stand-off between Russian and NATO troops at
the airport in Pristina. In the end, Moscow agreed to quietly
negotiate the terms of its peacekeeping role.
</P>
<P>
   Even Moscow commentators who praised that daring move in Kosovo
see a need to sober up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Moscow has to remain cool and try not to overdo it. It has
to keep this success from going to its head. We should not demand
too much. We should bear in mind our actual capacities, financial
and otherwise,'' said Yusin, the political commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's self-consciousness about its world image was apparent
in a recent domestic debate over a tax bill rejected by the Duma.
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin warned that Russia could become a
``world pariah'' if the parliament failed to pass the tax-revenue
package designed to pave the way for badly needed financial
assistance from the International Monetary Fund -- which itself,
has become a target of Russian animosity.
</P>
<P>
   In short-term diplomacy, Russia is making the best of a weak
hand. But in the long run in world affairs, Russia still must
decide what it wants to be -- participant or pariah?
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentally, little will change until Yeltsin moves on, and
the government and the parliament end their feuding. His term is
scheduled to conclude next summer when new presidential elections
are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the support and aid in the world will not make a
difference if Russia and her leaders do not get serious about
reform and overcoming the Soviet, communist legacy,'' said David
Kramer of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
