<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9053 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV20     06-17 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN'S THEATER GROUP WAGES OWN WAR IN MEXICO'S CHIAPAS STATE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico _ In a tidy house in this
quiet Mexican city, children scamper in a courtyard while women sew
and bake -- and rehearse the hard-boiled plays they've written
about lives scarred by rape, poverty and child labor.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from Broadway, but the Mayan Women's Strength
theater group is an experiment in drama all its own. The group also
provides childcare and community services for Mayan Indian women
here, and has toured the American Northeast, Texas, California,
Australia and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   FOMMA -- the Spanish acronym for the troupe -- remains a very
modest organization despite some measure of acclaim and its tours
abroad. Its primary goals remain providing bread-and-butter
services to abused and impoverished women and performing its plays
in the Mayan villages that encircle the city of San Cristobal de
las Casas in Mexico's Chiapas state.
</P>
<P>
   The women don't have to look far for inspiration for their
stories.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same area on the Guatemalan border where Zapatista
Indian rebels rose up in 1994, initiating a still unresolved
rebellion against centuries of injustice that Indians here have
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   The women of FOMMA, who choose to remain neutral in the
conflict, have their own war to wage, particularly against machismo
and inequality. With their plays, they often hold up a mirror to
their communities to reflect flaws from within.
</P>
<P>
   Founding members Petrona de la Cruz, 32, and Isabel Juarez
Espinosa, 40, were both put to work as children because their
families were so poor. Juarez was nine when her mother left her
with a non-Indian family in San Cristobal, where she was put in
charge of caring for the family's baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family wanted me to study, but they didn't even have
anything to buy a notebook,'' Juarez said. ``I also worked in
another family's home where all I got was leftovers to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Juarez married but her husband was killed in a dispute
over land, a precious commodity here that often leads to bloody
clashes.
</P>
<P>
   De la Cruz left her Mayan village at 12 to become a domestic
servant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to wash diapers at dawn and my hands would freeze,''
she remembers bitterly, sitting in FOMMA's small library for
children.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to her village, but had to work so hard at
gathering firewood, fetching water and cooking that she rarely had
time to get to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing for women was to learn to run the house,''
De la Cruz said. ``And if I didn't do my chores, I wouldn't get any
food.''
</P>
<P>
   At 17, De la Cruz was raped, an experience that led to her to
write her first play, ``A Desperate Woman,'' about a man who tries
to rape his stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   After the rape, she quit her community because her assailant was
never brought to justice and she found living there intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   Both women said they were finally able to fulfill dreams of
learning to read and write when they worked for sympathetic foreign
families in San Cristobal de las Casas who gave them time off to
study.
</P>
<P>
   Through the city's small-knit community of anthropologists and
social workers, the women gradually found their way into writing
and drama classes. Patient coaching brought their stories to the
stage and they learned to make props, costumes and shed their fear
of acting.
</P>
<P>
   They joined a drama troupe dominated by men, but split because
the men refused to perform ``A Desperate Women'' and told Juarez
she couldn't act because she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of conflict being in the group with men,
especially when it came to expressing opinions,'' Juarez said.
</P>
<P>
   FOMMA was born in 1993 and De la Cruz and Juarez sought funding
from the state of Chiapas and from abroad, including from the
Global Fund for Women in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A group called Cultural Survival in Boston, Mass., helped fund
FOMMA's maiden journey to the United States several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy initially balked at giving the women visas
because of fears the Mayan women would violate their visas and look
for work in America, according to Pia Maybury-Lewis of Cultural
Survival.
</P>
<P>
   An anthropologist at the Smithsonian Institution in Washington
D.C. had to intervene to vouch for de la Cruz, Juarez and others,
Maybury-Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   At FOMMA's headquarters in San Cristobal, De la Cruz and Juarez
host a revolving group of Mayan women who have left villages
because they were abused or expelled due to religious or political
differences.
</P>
<P>
   The women take literacy classes in their Mayan dialects and
Spanish, and learn to sew, bake and to develop other job skills. De
la Cruz and Juarez said they learned from their own experiences
that childcare is a critical service as well, otherwise the women
wouldn't be able to study and work.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone, children too, help write plays and learn to act.
</P>
<P>
   A work called ``The Juanas' Life'' is a warning to women who
become domestic servants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the kind of treatment you might expect, how to look
for jobs,'' De la Cruz said, ``and how to not just keep quiet when
you don't like something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Victims of Deceit'' explores family crises that develop when
Indian men leave villages to find work in the city, leaving their
wives behind.
</P>
<P>
   Other works combine Mayan mythology with feminist messages. When
they perform before audiences in the traditional Indian villages,
the group is often met with mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprises people when they see we can dress up and act like
men,'' said De la Cruz. ``There's still a lot that needs to be
changed for men to realize that women are equal.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
