another family's home where all I got was leftovers to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Juarez married but her husband was killed in a dispute
over land, a precious commodity here that often leads to bloody
clashes.
</P>
<P>
   De la Cruz left her Mayan village at 12 to become a domestic
servant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to wash diapers at dawn and my hands would freeze,''
she remembers bitterly, sitting in FOMMA's small library for
children.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to her village, but had to work so hard at
gathering firewood, fetching water and cooking that she rarely had
time to get to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing for women was to learn to run the house,''
De la Cruz said. ``And if I didn't do my chores, I wouldn't get any
food.''
</P>
<P>
   At 17, De la Cruz was raped, an experience that led to her to
