<HEADER>
A9067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TARZAN-TRADITION-HNS &LR;      06-17 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARZAN-TRADITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ELEMENTAL MALE IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call him Monkey Boy. Call him Vine Man. Call him Lord of the
Jungle, Lord of the Apes or Lord of the Loincloth. But whatever you
call him, he's back _ Tarzan, poster boy for the 20th century's
deep aboriginal urge.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's new animated version marks the 51st time the movies
have visited Edgar Rice Burroughs' classic adventure series.
Featuring the voices of Tony Goldwyn as Tarzan, Minnie Driver as
Jane and Glenn Close as Tarzan's gorilla mom, Kala, the new film
boasts a few sumptuous visuals as well as the studio's usual canned
cheer. And it retains a scrap or two of the original Tarzan, that
Ape-reared English nobleman who grows into a paradigm for
humanity's lost innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, when you get right down to it, why we still care about
him. Teetering at the edge of the second millennium, tipping
hesitantly into the third, we see in Tarzan a throwback to less
complicated times: The bugs in Tarzan's jungle have nothing to do
with Y2K. Tarzan is the elemental male, a creature of strapping
build and simple communicative skills who can shrug off a bullet
wound as a minor scratch.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a fetching ad for environmental purism, representing a
no-frills, back-to-nature lifestyle that's unsullied by food
additives or fossil fuels. If he were only vegetarian, he'd be
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs published his first Tarzan story in 1912 and two years
later released a novel, ``Tarzan of the Apes.'' Twenty-four sequels
later _ swept along by a stream of films, comic strips, radio shows
and boob-tube incarnations _ the monosyllabic heartthrob was a
multimedia global hero.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of a hero was he? Unlike other popular figures of the
early 20th century, Tarzan was a stripped-down figure, a paragon of
maleness without the usual sidearms. Like Zorro or D'Artagnan or
the Black Pirate (all of them played by Douglas Fairbanks), Tarzan
was a swashbuckler _ but he bore no weapons, swung from vines
instead of ropes and was always way too naked to come across as a
man of mystery.
</P>
<P>
   No swords, no masks, no blousy shirts, no clutter. His was
minimalist masculinity: the Visible Man, a Bauhaus Braveheart with
rippling pecs.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Tarzan that's survived a zillion popular imaginings:
an oversize Y chromosome with a quavering yodel. In 1932, when
Johnny Weissmuller first oogh-ooghed and found his Jane in
``Tarzan, The Ape Man,'' he solidified for all ages the image of
Tarzan as a fantasy He-Man _ a wordless jungle stud who swung from
trees and killed charging lions with a single blade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the most horrible man I ever met,'' Maureen O'Sullivan
told him, giggling and twirling his hair, and he stared back,
bemused. He was the swinger to end all swingers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tarzan was always more than a big male bimbo. He was Adam to
Jane's Eve. He was mythic. He loomed. He was a classless refutation
of England's caste system; born Lord Greystoke and orphaned in
Africa as a baby, he later returned to civilization, only to
abandon its suffocating confinements in favor of Africa's wild
tangles. And he represented, ultimately, both communion with and
dominion over nature _ a dominion earned not by gunpowder but by
muscles and smarts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a power that still lures. Despite all the talk of the
ozone, despite all of our obsessing over extinct species and
free-range chickens and chlorofluorocarbons, we're still rather
fond of the idea that human beings rule Earth. And while Tarzan may
be softened up and Disneyfied into a gamboling tree-hugger, it's
important to remember that the Lord of the Jungle has always been
one for a good, raw steak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
