<HEADER>
A9068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TARZAN-CHRONOLOGY-HNS     06-17 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARZAN-CHRONOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MANY FACES OF TARZAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1912: Edgar Rice Burroughs publishes his first Tarzan story.
</P>
<P>
   1914: Burroughs publishes his first Tarzan novel, ``Tarzan of
the Apes.'' Twenty-four more follow.
</P>
<P>
   1918: Elmo Lincoln stars as the first cinematic Tarzan in a
silent film, ``Tarzan of the Apes''; the boy Tarzan is played by
Gordon Griffith. Three more Lincoln Tarzans follow.
</P>
<P>
   1920: Gene Pollar, ``The Revenge of Tarzan.'' In the same year,
P. Demsey Tabler stars in ``The Son of Tarzan.'' 1927: James
Pierce, ``Tarzan and the Golden Lion.''
</P>
<P>
   1928: Frank Merrill, ``Tarzan the Mighty.'' The following year,
Merrill reprises the role in ``Tarzan the Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   1932: Johnny Weissmuller, the five-gold-medal Olympic swimmer,
debuts as Jane's squeeze in ``Tarzan, The Ape Man.'' Maureen
O'Sullivan plays his amour. Eleven more Weissmuller Tarzans follow
in the next 16 years _ including ``Tarzan's New York Adventure''
(1942), ``Tarzan and the Leopard Woman'' (1946) and his last
appearance in loincloth, ``Tarzan and the Mermaids'' (1948).
</P>
<P>
   1933: Buster Crabbe, who later hits it big as Flash Gordon and
Buck Rogers, does the vine thing in ``Tarzan the Fearless'' _
culled from serial shorts. In the same year, he also appears in
``King of the Jungle,'' a non-Tarzan Tarzan movie.
</P>
<P>
   1935: Herman Brix, ``The New Adventures of Tarzan,'' a serial.
Brix returns to Africa in ``Tarzan and the Green Goddess,'' 1938.
</P>
<P>
   1939: Johnny Sheffield debuts as Boy to Weissmuller's Tarzan in
``Tarzan Finds a Son!''
</P>
<P>
   1949: Lex Barker takes over from Weissmuller in ``Tarzan's Magic
Fountain.'' Four more Barker Tarzans follow.
</P>
<P>
   1955: Gordon Scott, ``Tarzan's Hidden Jungle.'' Five more Scott
Tarzans follow.
</P>
<P>
   1959: Denny Miller, ``Tarzan, The Ape Man.'' Denny goes nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   1962: Jock Mahoney, ``Tarzan Goes to India,'' followed in 1963
by ``Tarzan's Three Challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   1965: Ron Ely, ``Tarzan's Jungle Rebellion.'' Three more Ely
Tarzans follow.
</P>
<P>
   1966: Mike Henry, ``Tarzan and the Valley of Gold.'' Two more
Henry Tarzans follow.
</P>
<P>
   1981: Miles O'Keefe goes primitive opposite Bo Derek's Jane in
``Tarzan, the Ape Man.''
</P>
<P>
   1984: Christopher Lambert, doing a cool, broody Tarzan, appears
in ``Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes.'' Best in
years.
</P>
<P>
   1998: Casper Van Dien, the bug-zapper from ``Starship
Troopers,'' does ``Tarzan and the Lost City.''
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``Tarzan of the Internet''
(http://www.ac.wwu.edu/stephan/Tarzan/index.html), which includes
information from Gabe Essoe's ``Tarzan of the Movies'' and David
Fury's ``Kings of the Jungle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-TARZAN-HN     06-17 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TARZAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TARZAN' FAILS TO GET OFF THE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 87-year-career of Tarzan, the Lord of the Apes, he has
been attacked by leopards, shot at by hunters, seduced by ladies,
belittled by fops and chased along the Brooklyn Bridge. And now,
he's been Disneyed.
</P>
<P>
   This might have been a good thing. It might have meant an
imaginative animated reworking of a hoary legend, similar to the
studio's spins on ``The Little Mermaid,'' ``Beauty and the Beast''
or ``Hamlet'' (better known as ``The Lion King''). But either the
folks at Disney are tired of the grind or old Lord Greystoke is
losing his fizz, because ``Tarzan'' isn't quite the children's
classic it's cracked up to be.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the animation is exquisite, but mere artwork doesn't
make a movie. No, something's missing _ something crucial, and not
just the standard show-tune score, deep-sixed to make room for a
conventional soundtrack scattered with percussive Phil Collins
jungle ditties.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Tarzan crooning a few major-key showstoppers on
growing up hairless in a hairy world, we get Collins' wispy,
agreeable tenor, commenting in song while our vine-swinging
mesomorph surfs through the trees. (A true child of the '90s, he
skids along branches like a skateboard.) But it's not just the
rousing choruses we're missing, here. Two other elements are
absent: Characters and plot.
</P>
<P>
   If you look closely, you'll find the remains of Edgar Rice
Burroughs' original in the directors' (Kevin Lima and Chris Buck)
compressed tale; this ``Tarzan'' is still the tale of an English
infant adopted by apes in the African jungle. Kala (voiced by Glenn
Close) is still his ape mom, Kerchak (Lance Henriksen) is still the
fearsome king ape, Tantor (Wayne Knight) is still the elephant,
Jane (Minnie Driver) is still the bosomy squeeze, Clayton (Brian
Blessed) is still the blowhard rival and Professor Porter (Nigel
Hawthorne) is still Jane's fogeyish, well-meaning pop. All such
tidbits of Tarzanicana remain.
</P>
<P>
   And Tarzan himself (Tony Goldwyn) still belts out the occasional
yodel, though it lacks Johnny Weissmuller's coloratura warble.
</P>
<P>
   The film's cast throws kitchen-sink energy into their roles, but
none of the dialogue takes them anywhere new. ``Tell me I'm not
looking at the hairless wonder!'' is about as original as it gets.
Even the comic relief feels factory made.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell puts honking Nooh Yawk attitude into the role of
Terk (a gorilla with a Foghorn Leghorn crest of hair), but you
almost wish she hadn't tried so hard _ it all sounds vaguely
desperate, like a stand-up comic trying to goose laughs out of
lousy material. And when a rhythm-happy band of gorillas starts
whacking out a jazzy tune on campsite knickknacks, the result is
unexpectedly, bizarrely racist.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing is really a matter of gravity. The original
``Tarzan'' (and indeed, the better film versions, particularly
``Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes'') combined
raw-flesh adventures with some serious philosophizing on humanity
and the uncivil nature of civilization. A touch of that is found
here: Clayton, animated with the bulging arms of a malevolent
Popeye, is a gun-toting maniac who'll shoot anything that moves.
But this ``Tarzan'' so condenses the plot that the
nobleman-turned-wildman never gets a taste of the outside world. He
never learns to use a fork. And judging from his sleek, sharp jaw,
he never makes it out of peach-fuzz adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Artistically, the filmmakers seem so obsessed with animating
their jungle milieu _ and with Tarzan's bunchy musculature _ that
the more mundane aspects of storytelling get short shrift. A
newfangled ``deep canvas'' technique mimics 3-D and provides a
cavernous, richly detailed backdrop for the ape-man's rambles, many
of which are dashing fun. Yet the secondary characters are
workmanlike and flat, rendered with little depth and none of the
out-there stylistic flare that marks Disney's best films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' is a serviceable film for kids: bright, eager to
please, full of spry action sequences and a fair bit of slapstick.
Some of the violence (person-on-person, animal-on-person,
animal-on-animal) may be too intense for small children, but it's
generally safe territory for families. What it lacks is grandeur.
For all its whooshing athleticism, breezy humor and soaring palette
of greens and blues, the legend of the ``white ape'' stays
strangely earthbound.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
