<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9079 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-TEXAS-ARLINGTONATHLET     06-17 2258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-ARLINGTON SAVORS SWEET SUCCESS AS NONREVENUE PROGRAMS THRIVE
</HEADLINE>
AM-TEXAS-ARLINGTON ATHLETICS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Bill Reeves often jokes about his coaching
achievements at Texas-Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Although his position as associate athletic director involves no
sideline duty, Reeves will laugh and take credit for Southland
Conference tennis titles, outstanding track performances and great
golf shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marsha came by and got some advice,'' Reeves said about
Texas-Arlington shot putter Marsha French, the SLC record-holder in
the event. ``We worked on some technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's basketball is also one of Reeves' specialties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave Lawanna Allen some pointers on making last-second
shots,'' Reeves said of the UT-Arlington women's basketball player.
``It's working.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, a lot has worked for Texas-Arlington in the past
school year, especially in its nonrevenue programs. Texas-Arlington
won seven SLC titles in the 14 programs it sponsors. The revenue
sports _ men's basketball and baseball _ could have used some of
that valuable Reeves advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need to get those sports going,'' Texas-Arlington
athletic director Pete Carlon said. ``That's the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   As Texas-Arlington heads into the next academic year, it can
brag about making the most of a limited $3.2 million budget and
rising graduating rates. But there is no football team for Reeves
to offer tips. Men's basketball attendance is poor, and the team
has gone through seven consecutive losing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The gymnasium is a converted theater. The baseball program is
working on six consecutive losing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Carlon said the department's journey from here might be directly
tied to enrollment. He says that because the department's budget
definitely is.
</P>
<P>
   More students at Texas-Arlington means more money for the
Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   More money means a larger recruiting budget, fully funded
programs and the ability to market the revenue sports. A dramatic
rise in enrollment even means the return of football can't be ruled
out, Carlon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few things have to happen in our favor, but we could really
take off,'' Carlon said. ``You could see this department explode in
the next few years.''  &LR; subheds:SLC victories come in bunches
Texas-Arlington has emerged as the all-around sports king of the
SLC, an 11-team league of six Texas schools and five Louisiana
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks accomplished the feat by dominating in nonrevenue
sports, which the rabid college sports fans often call ``minor.''
But in Texas-Arlington's case, sports such as women's tennis and
men's golf are considered on equal ground with men's basketball,
women's basketball and baseball. That philosophy has earned the
Mavericks plenty of overall success in the past school year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the seven SLC titles in 1998-99 are a school record.
Texas-Arlington's teams won five titles in 1992. In women's
athletics, Texas-Arlington won conference championships in
volleyball, indoor track and field, outdoor track and field and
tennis. The softball team was third.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has joked that his work with pitcher Cassie Brand could
have helped the Mavericks softball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked on her fastball,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks men were SLC champions in golf, tennis and indoor
track and field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to give each coaching staff enough funds to compete for
a conference championship in that sport,'' Carlon said. ``A lot of
schools only care about football or men's basketball. If we were
like that, I would have a hard time looking our other
student-athletes in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   So the SLC titles mount and accolades come from the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington won the women's all-sports trophy this season
for the third consecutive year. The award is based on a points
system in which each university is given points based on its
conference finish.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington's men captured the all-sports trophy for the
second time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, men's basketball failed to draw more than 1,000 fans
to a single home game at Texas Hall _ for the second consecutive
season. In fact, NCAA statistics showed that Texas-Arlington's
1997-98 attendance of 689 per game was fifth-worst among 301
Division I universities.
</P>
<P>
   The saving grace of the revenue sports was women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach Mike Dean guided his team to an 18-11 season, a
second-place tie in conference play and a Women's National
Invitation Tournament berth. It was the first national postseason
appearance in the program's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the obstacles that our basketball coaches face
with the facility we have, our budget, and that our academic
standards are the highest in the conference,'' Carlon said. ``I
would hope that students would come to UTA for the academics and
everything the university can offer, rather than a basketball
gym.''  &LR; subheds:Texas-Arlington basketball, coming to a theater
near you Last summer, Texas-Arlington closed in on a deal that
would have broken ground on a 10,000-seat, on-campus arena.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington would lease the land to a developer in exchange
for dates to use for home events. There was space for coaching
offices, luxury boxes, and the primary tenant was supposed to be a
minor-league hockey franchise.
</P>
<P>
   A drawing of the arena even made it on booster club membership
pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
   The deal fell through, just days before the bid was to be
awarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a done deal, and so did everybody else,''
Texas-Arlington men's basketball coach Eddie McCarter said.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems Texas-Arlington will be playing in Texas Hall _ and
dealing with its deficiencies _ for quite some time. The 4,200-seat
facility is a theater that converts to a basketball arena with the
floor placed on the stage. Fans sitting in the lower level have to
look up to see the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Williams, UT-Arlington's senior vice president of finance
and administration, said last month that an arena is on the
university's master plan. But the construction of it would be at
least 20 years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, McCarter would be 65 years old.
</P>
<P>
   When it looked like an arena might be built, Texas-Arlington
coaches used it as a recruiting tool. The men's program landed
Bossier Parish Community College guard Keith Greene, the team's
leading scorer last year, who said the arena was part of the reason
he chose Texas-Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Longhorns transfer Anthony Goode said a new arena also
swayed his decision to attend Texas-Arlington. The situation made
it appear that McCarter wasn't being honest with potential
recruits, when he was simply relaying what administrators were
telling him.
</P>
<P>
   McCarter said he will never talk about an arena again until a
shovel is in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to mention anything about it to anybody,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The university has, however, decided to improve Texas Hall for
the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Carlon said the athletic department has drafted a proposal for a
new basketball floor, replacing one that received some damage while
being removed at the end of last season. Carlon said he would like
to improve the locker rooms and create office space for coaches, in
addition to their offices in the Gilstrap Center.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas-Arlington, even something that might seem small to a
Division I university _ such as office space at the arena _ is a
big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those offices will help Eddie and me when we bring kids in
here,'' Dean said. ``I'd be very excited if we could get that done.
We won't be going back and forth to Texas Hall all day during the
season. At every other school in the country I know of, the
basketball coaches have offices at the arena.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Texas Hall improvements, the football stadium is
getting new artificial turf in a project scheduled to begin June
28.  &LR; subheds:Finding the money, or a niche for football Whether a
Texas-Arlington football team will ever use the turf remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington football was killed in 1985 because of poor
attendance and the cost of operating it at the Division I-AA level.
</P>
<P>
   Carlon said there isn't anybody who would like to see
Texas-Arlington football return more than him, but the department
doesn't have the estimated $1 million a year it would take to
operate it at the Division I-AA level.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington rents out Maverick Stadium for high school
events such as football and soccer games.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington's budget barely pays for travel costs, coaching
salaries and scholarships for the sports Texas-Arlington already
sponsors. In fact, women's basketball offered 13 of the NCAA limit
of 15 scholarships last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a return received a boost when students at the
university passed a referendum last summer that asked for $7.75 per
credit hour to be given to the athletic department. It was an
increase of $4 on what students were already spending.
</P>
<P>
   Although other universities across the nation have such a fee,
Texas-Arlington was the first in Texas to try a separate athletics
fee. The student-fee bill has unanimously passed the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the fee, Texas-Arlington's athletic department can
keep its $3.2 million budget. If enrollment goes up, so does the
amount of money Texas-Arlington can spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to bring football back if it meant cutting
into our other sports, and there are still a lot of things that
have to happen,'' Carlon said. ``Students didn't pass the
referendum with an idea that it meant we would get football. But
they understood that, if it didn't pass, there would be no way.''
</P>
<P>
   For Texas-Arlington students to see football, Carlon said, the
department would have to raise enough money for start-up costs.
That includes purchasing equipment and building a field house
underneath the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   To get the field house erected at an estimated cost of $1.5
million, the athletic department would rely on a money-raising
campaign targeted at alumni and sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have to come from external sources,'' Carlon said.
``The referendum ensures that we have internal funds to keep
programs alive, but anything more we do would have to come from the
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington's booster organization, The Maverick Club,
already has started to tap an alumni base of almost 100,000 people
in the Fort Worth-Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Davis, the organization's president and a longtime booster,
is trying to revive the Maverick Club to its glory days of the
1980s with the help of Texas-Arlington coaches and current club
members.
</P>
<P>
   The Maverick Club has embarked on a membership drive similar to
those it used to have in Texas-Arlington's football playing days.
Davis has elected 35 people to captain teams with plans to canvass
the city of Arlington for support.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent booster club luncheon, Davis said, ``Everybody wants
to go a men's basketball game at Texas-Arlington and see people in
the stands. You wonder which comes first, the chicken or the egg.
If you support them, they win. If they win, people go there to
watch. The booster club is going to do everything it can to get
people out there. We haven't had a campaign like this one in a very
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlon said there also is a chance the NCAA will create a
Division I-AAA in the next few years. That division would allow
Texas-Arlington to start nonscholarship football without dropping
from the Division I level in other sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Student Congress recently passed a resolution, 25-1, to
conduct a football feasibility study.  &LR; subheds:Graduating to better
times In the booster club and in the department, there is still
plenty of room for growth and improvement, Carlon said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said it's hard to ignore how far the athletic department
has come in the past three years. After the 1995-96 school year,
Texas-Arlington had a $2 million deficit created by the previous
administration, and there were rumors of the university dropping to
nonscholarship status.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, coaches said those rumors made it almost impossible
to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   The student-athlete graduation rate was 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morale was about as low as it could possibly get, and I think
that trickles down to the athletes,'' Texas-Arlington sports
information director Steve Weller said. ``On top of that, nobody
was winning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, that certainly has changed.
Texas-Arlington teams have won 15 conference titles.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves can take credit for only 15 of those.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit has been erased, and Texas-Arlington's athletic
department is operating in the black. The graduation rate has more
than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable what Pete, his staff and coaches have done in
a very short period of time,'' University President Robert Witt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the department's image has been significantly
improved after being torn apart by debt at the end of 1996. In
fact, Carlon's first responsibility was to open communication lines
and regain respect from the rest of the university's faculty, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That accomplished, Texas-Arlington has focused on improving its
standing in the SLC.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly did that this season.
</P>
<P>
   Carlon said the next steps are to improve the higher-profile
sports, try to keep a staff of talented, young coaches and watch
the enrollment numbers.
</P>
<P>
   If those numbers rise dramatically, Texas-Arlington sports could
rise, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves will be there to offer some tips. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
