<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9094 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-VEEP-HNS &LR;      06-17 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-VEEP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BUSH BONANZA, DOLE KEEPS HER EYES ON NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Tired of suggestions that she would make a
good running mate for Republican front-runner George W. Bush,
Elizabeth Dole says she isn't interested in the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not undertake this sort of rigorous process in order
to be vice president,'' Dole told the Rotary Club of San Jose
Wednesday. ``You do it to win. I'm in it to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential hopeful spoke to about 300 Rotarians
who went out to the Italian Gardens Meeting Center less for the
ham-and-spaghetti buffet than to hear the woman who, some believe,
could be the first woman president.
</P>
<P>
   Or the first woman vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's honest ... and there's no question she's
capable,'' said Bill Cassidy, a Republican and retired real estate
broker from San Jose. But Cassidy said he wouldn't bet on Dole
winning the nomination, especially in the face of the groundswell
of support for Bush, the Texas governor and son of former President
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, 62, a Cabinet member in the Reagan and Bush
administrations, gave up her job as president of the American Red
Cross in January to form an exploratory campaign committee. She
said Wednesday she would likely make a formal announcement by this
fall, but by all appearances she is in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dole has run second behind Bush in some national polls,
the gap between the front-runner and his competitors has been
widening. A Los Angeles Times poll of California voters Wednesday
showed Dole lagging behind Bush by 50 percent to 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dole urged voters not to be distracted by polls nearly 18 months
before the election. ``It is early. Only 5 percent of people are
even thinking about the year 2000 right now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, Dole called for tax cuts and increased military
spending. She said she would push for more local control over
federal education dollars and for ``sensible'' gun control,
including mandatory child locks on all guns and a ban on bullets
that pierce body armor.
</P>
<P>
   She also did the ``Dole Stroll,'' the tag put on her penchant
for walking Oprah-like through an audience that first drew
attention when she appeared at the 1996 Republican presidential
convention on behalf of her husband, former Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas. Only a noisy, static-filled microphone forced her back to
the podium at the Rotary Club.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in the cradle of Silicon Valley, Dole discussed her
views on technology issues and her belief that the government
should, for the most part, take a hands-off role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep the government out of the way as much as
possible,'' she said. ``We want to leave the industry free to grow
and not be swamped with regulations and with government
intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, she said there should be no tax on Internet
access. She argued for making the research and development tax
credit permanent, as leaders of the technology industry have
sought. She praised the Senate for passing legislation Tuesday to
protect companies from lawsuits stemming from the millennium
computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said she would also increase the number of visas to allow
technology companies hire workers from abroad to help ease the
industry's chronic shortage of skilled help.
</P>
<P>
   ``More workers should be permitted to come in as a remedy,'' she
said. ``But I think the long-term solution to that problem is
education. We've got to educate our young people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leslee Coleman, executive director of the powerful industry
group the American Electronics Association, said Dole's views
mirror the association's positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things she said were music to our ears,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole also attended a fund-raising event Wednesday evening at the
Atherton home of Republican activist Carolyn Bechtel. The event was
expected to raise at least $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who has visited nine states in the last nine days,
including two trips to California, said she raised $500,000 last
week alone. ``Clearly we will have enough for a very viable
campaign,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
