<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9111 &Cx1f; tad-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN20-COX     06-17 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHEELCHAIR RAMPS TO CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    Moving in ``k'' (commentary) and ``f'' (financial) categories.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 20
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Several years ago, as personal computing became more
widely popular, I told a friend named Sandy Greenberg about a voice
recognition program that I'd been testing. He leaped at the chance
to use it too.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, a former White House aide and a successful business
executive, is blind. So being able to deal with his computer via
voice has dramatically changed his life. Since then, Greenberg has
operated on the cutting edge of an on-going revolution in
accessibility to high-tech services for handicapped people.
</P>
<P>
   At some stage, however, society must weigh how changes aimed at
helping the disabled should evolve. Should they be voluntary and be
driven by market forces or should they be mandatory and be driven
by federal regulations?
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Applied Special Technology, a non-profit group
that expands horizons for individuals with disabilities through
innovative uses of technology, opts for the voluntary approach.
Webmasters are invited to download Bobby, the logo of a jolly
policeman, as a seal of approval, indicating they've met the
group's user accessibility guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   To become Bobby-certified, a Web site must offer alternative
text equivalents for all its non-text elements, such as images,
animations, audio, and video. It must also provide summaries of
charts and ensure that data conveyed by the use of color is
available as well in monochrome.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has similar ideas in mind for the
federal government and anyone who does business with the feds. But
in working to enforce the 1998 Workforce Investment Act, Reno has
invested in a billy club.
</P>
<P>
   By June 15, all federal agencies were required to report to Reno
on how they will ``ensure that the electronic and information
technologies used in their programs are accessible'' to the
disabled. (Only national security systems were exempted.)
</P>
<P>
   Standards written by the Access Board, a little-known 25-member
federal panel, apply to all devices and software ``used for
communication, duplication, computing, storage, presentation,
control, transport and production.'' Under rules to go into effect
in 2000, these functions ``must be accessible and usable by as wide
a range of people with disabilities as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes people who are blind or lack color perception, who
are deaf or hard of hearing, people with ``limited strength, reach
or manipulation, tremor or lack of sensation,'' people with speech
disabilities, people with ``reading, thinking, remembering, or
sequencing disabilities'' and people who are ``short of stature.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal net covering the Internet is being widely cast: the
Department of Education, for example, requires states that get
school funds to comply as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a world that is becoming increasingly cognizant of
the needs and rights of persons with disabilities,'' Reno wrote.
``We also live in a world that is becoming increasingly dependent
upon computers and other electronic and information technologies
for providing the information that we need in our daily lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The feds appear committed to weaving those ideas into an
integrated reality.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
