<HEADER>
A9117 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ENVIRONMENT-DI     06-17 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ENVIRONMENT-DISASTER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN THE AFTERMATH of KOSOVO: an ENVIRONMENTAL CATASTROPHE?  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world affairs. To publish it as a ``separate
buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _
from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Now that the air strikes against Yugoslavia have been stopped,
the world community will have to assess the damage and draw lessons
from the events of these past months. We should not allow the
misguided and unwarranted bombing operation to be followed by
hollow proclamations of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the plight of the Kosovars, the destruction of much
of the essential infrastructure in the rest of Yugoslavia and the
tremendous damage to international relations, any triumphalist
statements are jarring. Claims of victory are being made by those,
on either side, who must be troubled by the thought of being held
accountable for what has happened to Yugoslavia. Make no mistake
about it: The outcome is a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   As president of Green Cross International, a non-government
environmental organization that was among the first to sound the
alarm about environmental consequences of NATO's military action, I
feel duty bound to continue the discussion of this vitally
important subject. Some might now be tempted to ask: Was the threat
perhaps exaggerated? Could nature be much more resilient to the
impact of war than we thought? But this is a dangerous complacency
that could serve all of us badly.
</P>
<P>
   Let us recall the effects of the hostilities that followed
Saddam Hussein's aggression against Kuwait. The data cited at an
International Conference on the Environmental Consequences of War
held in Washington in June 1998 indicate that these consequences
are of a long-term nature. Scientists and environmental experts
estimate that 40 percent of Kuwait's strategic water resources have
been irreversibly polluted with oil. Quite alarming are the reports
of health problems among U.S. and British soldiers who fought in
that war problems that now also affect their children.
</P>
<P>
   I might add that the environmental and medical consequences of
the war in Iraq itself are, for reasons that are well known, not
widely covered by the media or studied by scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Military action against Yugoslavia included extensive use of
weapons containing depleted uranium. Such weapons burn at high
temperatures, producing poisonous clouds of uranium oxide that
dissolve in the pulmonary and bronchial fluids. Anyone within the
radius of 300 meters from the epicenter of the explosion inhales
large amounts of such particles.
</P>
<P>
   Although radiation levels produced by the external source are
quite low, the internal radiation source damages various types of
cells in the human body, destroys chromosomes and affects the
reproductive system.
</P>
<P>
   We are told by officials that depleted uranium components are
harmless and that DU weapons are therefore a legitimate means of
warfare. Let us recall, however, that many military and political
leaders initially believed and some seem to believe even now that
nuclear weapons too are quite ``conventional,'' albeit a more
powerful kind of weaponry. Do we need another, ``slow Hiroshima''
to understand this new mistake?
</P>
<P>
   We must now call for a comprehensive expert analysis of the
environmental situation in Yugoslavia and other countries in the
region and in the Danube basin. This should be a priority task. But
we must do more than just that.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that military conflicts in our time can cause both a
human and an environmental catastrophe makes the task of preventing
them even more urgent and important. Prevention must be foremost in
our thinking and our actions. But, if hostilities break out despite
all our efforts, they must be constrained by certain legal limits.
Such constraints have been laid down by the Geneva conventions and
their protocols. It is now clear that they should be supplemented
by provisions to limit the environmental damage caused by warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, I believe that strikes against certain industries
and infrastructure, such as nuclear power stations and some
chemical and petrochemical plants, must be prohibited. Similarly,
we should prohibit weapons whose use may have particularly
dangerous, long-term and massive environmental and medical
consequences. In my view, weapons containing depleted uranium
should be among the first considered for such a ban.
</P>
<P>
   The time has come to convene a second conference on the
environmental consequences of war in order to discuss thoroughly
and in depth issues of this kind. It could adopt some urgently
needed amendments to international law and create a mechanism to
continue this work. It should also address the need for an
emergency fund to finance measures to deal with the aftermath of
environmental catastrophes. Recent events only underscore the
urgency of this initiative, which I put forward at the Washington
conference in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, political leaders and public opinion should
now demonstrate that we can learn the right lessons from the
tragedies of the 20th century. The human drama and the drama of
nature should be of equal concern to us. They should sound a call
to responsible action.
</P>
<P>
   (Translated from the Russian by Pavel Palazchenko.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
