<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-LOLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUN LOLA RUN' BURSTING WITH ENERGY 
OUR RATING: 3 STARS
</HEADLINE>
 By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just about every kind of film form you can think
of finds its way into the kinetic German urban fantasia ``Run Lola
Run.'' There's pixilation, video, cel animation, special effects,
all manner of camera speeds in every conceivable moving pattern; in
other words, it's the kind of showoffy showpiece that should
rightfully be a cacophonous mess.
</P>
<P>
   Except that all of these diverse style elements and more are
orchestrated with astonishing rigor by writer-director Tom Tykwer.
The film bursts with percussive, creative energy even when it
teeters under the strain of aesthetic overreaching.
</P>
<P>
   The end result? Definitely too clever by half, but a gas
nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Though only 81 minutes long, ``Lola'' moves so rapidly that it
can tell the same story three different times in three different
ways with varying outcomes. The basic plot concerns Manni (Moritz
Bleibtreu), a young underworld courier who has carelessly lost
100,000 marks he needs to deliver to his unforgiving boss in 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The panicked Manni calls his girlfriend Lola (Franka Potente),
who is partially responsible for the dire situation. She assures
him she'll get the money to him in the alloted time, even though
she hasn't got a pfennig and will have to run halfway across Berlin
to meet him. If she's late, he's going to rob a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The desperate, athletic Lola cuts quite a memorable figure
trotting along cobblestones and broken concrete, her persimmon hair
flopping atop her head like a worrying flame. Avoiding angry dogs,
flocks of nuns and aggressive hustlers of all stripes, she
variously relies on pleading, violence and gambling to get her job
done.
</P>
<P>
   Assaulted by emotional betrayal and relentless sight gags (a
favorite Tykwer ploy is to insert snapshots of the future fates
that await people Lola passes), our plucky distance gal displays an
imaginative resilience that is as impressive as her physical
stamina. Tykwer does pretty much the same thing, always coming up
with a robust bit of staging that brings urgency to even
thrice-repeated scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The director has a fine instinct for pacing, too. The movie's
driving forward motion is punctuated by still, character-revealing
moments, and there's even a contrapuntal shot of a turtle trudging
along. As might be expected from a filmmaker so fixated on visual
rhythms, Tykwer was also involved with composing the film's score,
a barrage of appropriately Teutonic techno-beats.
</P>
<P>
   And the triple attack on the same plot line gives Tykwer, well,
endless opportunity to play with cinematic time and narrative
caprice. Split-second decisions and encounters lead Lola in
amusingly varied directions, turning the whole filmgoing experience
into a kind of labyrinthine game.
</P>
<P>
   Fun as it all is, though, by the third go-'round tedium perhaps
inevitably sets in. Tykwer's final set of formal and story ideas
just can't sustain the level of inventive momentum we've come to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   That noted, there's still more real filmmaking in the short span
of ``Run Lola Run'' than you'll see in hundreds of hours' worth of
conventional Hollywood movies. Catch it if you can. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
