<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBECUE-SAUCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BETTER MARINADE FROM SCRATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Making your own barbecue sauce doesn't have to be
a two-hour, labor-intensive ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, you can have all kinds of fun making a tangy sauce
from scratch for marinating and basting chicken and other meats.
And odds are it will be better than almost anything available in
the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   But the secret to a big-time shortcut is to start with one of
the commercial sauces found in the condiment section of the
supermarket, and start adding to it.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the bottle into a large bowl, and start to improvise. The
goal is to tinker with the commercial sauce and give it a zing it
probably is lacking. Creating a new sauce that is distinctly
different from the base and far more pleasing is as simple as
striking a match to soaked briquettes.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author William Rice identifies five distinct flavor
areas in the ``Steak Lover's Cookbook'' (Workman Publishing, 1997),
and suggests ingredients to add to a commercial sauce that will
take your barbecue sauce into the area you desire.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sour or tart: Add lemon juice, lime juice, tamarind, plain and
flavored vinegars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sweet: Brown sugar, honey, hoisin sauce, corn syrup.
</P>
<P>
   _ Salty: Coarse salt, celery salt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tomatoey: Ketchup, tomato paste, tomato juice, chili sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spicy: More or less in descending order of popularity:
coarsely ground black pepper, cayenne pepper, paprika, chili
powder, garlic powder, cumin (ground and seeds), anise or fennel
seeds, onion powder, ground ginger, white pepper, coriander seeds,
ground cinnamon, ground clove, ground allspice, grated nutmeg,
dried basil, dried oregano.
</P>
<P>
   Rice offers other helpful hints for preparing a homemade sauce,
using a commercial barbecue sauce as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Combining flavors from two or more of the flavor categories is
perfectly permissible. The idea is to experiment and improvise as
you prepare a sauce that caters to your particular tastes.
</P>
<P>
   If the sauce becomes too thick, add water to thin it. And if
you've been a little heavy handed adding hot ingredients, such as
cayenne pepper, counteract that by adding some sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Until you have found the combinations that work best for you and
the folks you are preparing food for, it is best to work with small
quantities. Start with only a third of the bottle and experiment.
This way, if the sauce takes off in a direction that makes your
eyes water, you've limited the expense of failure as well as the
number of ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   For those willing to start from scratch, here is a quick and
easy recipe for homemade barbecue sauce from ``The Ultimate
Barbecue Sauce Cookbook'' by Susan Puckett and Jim Auchmutey's
(Longstreet, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWESTERN LOW-ACID MARINADE AND MOP
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 1 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup bourbon or sherry
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, combine all ingredients over low heat and
simmer 15 minutes. Use as a marinade and baste on beef and poultry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
