<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-INNS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seaside inns: Sun, sand, surf and the sweet life
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's early afternoon, and the guests are rocking on the front
porch of a quiet inn that looks more like a house on Cape Cod than
a hostelry on a Florida beach. Instead of listening to the birds
chirp or breathing mountain air, they're rocking in sync with the
waves as the ocean breeze blows over the sand and sea oats.
</P>
<P>
   Bed-and-breakfasts are often referred to as country inns because
so many are quaint little getaways in the mountains or countryside,
far from the hustle and bustle of big cities or popular vacation
resorts. But some are springing up in beach towns, providing guests
that charming feel of being in the countryside with all the
sun-drenched opportunities that go along with being at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Two fine examples are in celebrated Southeastern vacation spots:
Elizabeth Pointe Lodge on historic Amelia Island in northeast
Florida and Henderson Park Inn in ever-developing Destin, Fla., in
the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Come along as staff writer Susan Laccetti Meyers tours both.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
