<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two Florida inns near ocean offer scenery and serenity
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By Susan Laccetti Meyers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ELIZABETH POINTE LODGE
</P>
<P>
   AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. _ Resembling an 1890s New England captain's
house, Elizabeth Pointe Lodge is one of the most attractive
structures on Florida's Amelia Island, a barrier island just south
of Georgia's Cumberland Island. The 25-room inn is covered with
gray Nantucket shingles and inside there is a maritime feel with
photos of old ships and nautical decor, including a captain's bed
in some rooms. Windows in some parts of the inn are in the style of
ship portholes.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Pointe stands out because the island is developed
primarily with older beach homes, condo resorts, such as the Amelia
Island Plantation, and the Ritz-Carlton hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Inn owners David and Susan Caples are also the proprietors of
Lodging Resources Workshops, a company that offers seminars
throughout the country (and at Elizabeth Pointe) on the nuts and
bolts of purchasing, owning and operating bed-and-breakfast inns.
They obviously know their business. From the moment you check in,
the hospitality is exemplary: warm but not overbearing. The owners
and front desk personnel readily offer suggestions for things to do
while on Amelia such as horseback riding or visiting the island's
seaport town of Fernandina to see a scattering of restored
Victorian homes. Fort Clinch State Park is also close by, home to a
fortress that was active from the Civil War through World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The inn's layout is cozy. On the ground floor there is a sitting
area around a stone fireplace. A favorite spot is the beachfront
porch with white slat rocking chairs. The dining area features a
wall of windows overlooking the ocean. A daily complimentary buffet
breakfast is served with items such as eggs Benedict, Spanish-style
eggs, grits and pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to pass the day sitting in one of the inn's Adirondack
chairs on the beach and watch the sea gulls fly by or read a book.
There is no pool, but it's never really missed.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Pointe has a limited lunch menu, and Fernandina is a
short bicycle ride away if you want to dine out. Days wind down at
the inn with lemonade served in the afternoons and a wine and
cheese happy hour at 6 p.m. The chocolate chip cookies, left in the
room after turndown service in the early evening, are divine.
They're also available in a jar by the front desk if you have a
craving earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HENDERSON PARK INN
</P>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ Driving up to the Henderson Park Inn, you have to
pause for a second to consider if you really are in Destin. Just a
mile back on U.S. 98 are strip malls and towering condos that house
the thousands that flock to this gulf hot spot. But here on U.S. 98
East, the road dead-ends. And in the cul-de-sac is a green-roofed
inn that looks like a two-story, Victorian house out of the late
1960s television show ``The Ghost and Mrs. Muir.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson Park is not only eye-catching but is one of the most
distinctive places to stay in Destin. The rates aren't cheap. In
summer high season, the price can soar to $264 a night for a corner
room with a coastal view. (During the spring, smaller rooms run
about $160.) Despite the high tariff, the inn is often booked
months in advance because it is unique for the Panhandle. Guests
often include honeymooners or those celebrating an anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The inn is also a business destination, hosting meetings in a
small conference hall in a second building that has 15 guest rooms
in addition to the 20 rooms in the main house. The inn's restaurant
(serving breakfast, lunch and gourmet dinners, including seafood)
draws raves from locals and is the site of wine club dinners, baby
showers and birthday parties. The complimentary buffet breakfast
for guests includes Spanish frittatas and luscious eclairs and
helps visitors put on some vacation pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson Park bills itself as a ``beachside
bed-and-breakfast.'' But it's got all the trimmings of a luxury
beach resort: towel, beach chair and umbrella service, a pool,
poolside bar and complimentary happy hour on most nights (also
poolside). There's even bellboy service when you check in. But
instead of taking an elevator, guests assigned a room on the third
story must climb three flights of stairs. It's worth the work,
however, if yours is a room with a coastline view _ looking down
the beach over pristine dunes and surf instead of directly facing
the ocean. One drawback is that the less pricey rooms are small.
But there is no skimping on bathrooms, as most have a Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   What really separates the Henderson Park Inn from some of
Destin's overindulgent development is its prime location adjacent
to Henderson Beach State Recreation area, which suffered minimal
damage after 1995's Hurricane Opal. The park provides a natural
barrier, and its convenient 1 1/4-mile beach is one of the few
undisturbed oceanfront sites in this busy area of the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Pointe Lodge, 98 South Fletcher Ave., Amelia Island.
From Atlanta take I-75 south to Macon then I-16 east toward
Savannah. At Exit 32, take I-95 south to Exit 130, which is U.S.
17. Go south on U.S. 17 to Eulee, Fla., and turn left at A1A onto
Amelia Island. Summer rates: $140 to $235. Rates include buffet
breakfast, afternoon lemonade, wine and cheese happy hour and
nightly turndown service. Reservations: 904-277-4851. On the Web:
www
</P>
<P>
   .elizabethpointelodge.com.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson Park Inn, a beachside bed-and-breakfast, 2700 Highway
98 East in Destin. From Atlanta take I-85 south to Montgomery. Get
off at Exit 164, which is U.S. 331, and follow this road to the
Florida line. Then pick up Fla. 85 at the state line and follow
until it dead ends into Fla. 293 (the bridge into Destin). Summer
rates range from $180 to $264 per night or $1,183 to $1,729 per
week. Tariff includes buffet breakfast, happy hour and nightly
turndown service. Reservations: 1-800-336-4853 or 850-837-4853.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www .HendersonParkInn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Laccetti Meyers writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
