<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Braselton, Ga. _ Chateau Elan's Swinging on the Grapevine
Summer Concert Series continues Saturday with ``Swing Night,''
featuring Zoot and the Swingin' Suits (free swing lessons before
the concert). $25 per person. 770-932-0900 or 1-800-233-9463.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blairsville, Ga. _ Vogel State Park hosts a square dance
beginning at 4 p.m. Saturday as caller Joe Dinatale and his dancers
teach all comers the steps. 706-745-2628.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Simons Island, Ga. _ The Southeastern Writers Conference
presents its 24th annual conference at Epworth by the Sea Sunday
through June 26. Open to amateur and professional writers. Call Pat
Laye at 912-679-5445 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Highlands, N.C. _ The Highlands Playhouse presents the musical
``Grease'' Saturday through July 4. Upcoming: the farce ``Cash on
Delivery'' July 7-18, the musical ``Crazy for You'' July 21-Aug. 8
and the comedy ``Take This Man'' Aug. 11-22. 828-526-2695.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Waynesville, N.C. _ The fourth annual Studio and Gallery Tour
on Saturday gives visitors the opportunity to meet about two dozen
local artists who display their work in downtown studios and
galleries. In addition to artist demonstrations, there will be
refreshments, strolling musicians and poetry performances.
828-456-3517.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cherokee, N.C. _ The annual outdoor drama ``Unto These Hills''
tells the story of the Cherokee people from 1540 through the 1800s.
Through Aug. 21. 828-497-2111 or www.dnet.net/(tilde)cheratt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cosby, Tenn. _ The 23rd annual Dulcimer and Harp Festival is
Friday and Saturday at the Folklife Center of the Smokies. The
event includes homemade food, crafts and nightly concerts.
423-625-9675 or www.cockecounty.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ Riverbend Festival through Saturday features
more than 100 musical artists on five stages, sport events, family
activities, fine arts, food and fireworks. 423-265-4112 or
www.chattanooga.net/cvb.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sevierville, Tenn. _ The second annual American Eagle Weekend,
Friday through Sunday, features a golf tournament, the World of
Wildlife Fine Art and Photography Show, Concert for America's
Eagles, Taste of the Smokies and Wings of Eagles Christian Music
Concert. Headquarters is the Governor's Crossing complex.
423-429-0157.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nashville _ The International Country Music Fan Fair,
continuing through Saturday, gives country music fans the
opportunity to mix and mingle with their favorite stars. Also, 35
hours of live shows, exhibits, autograph sessions, concerts,
celebrity games, photo sessions and the Grand Masters Fiddling
Championship. 615-889-7503.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birmingham _ City Stages, an outdoor music festival Friday
through June 20, features concerts, dance, food and arts and crafts
in Linn Park and surrounding streets downtown. Among the acts:
Isaac Hayes, Bonnie Raitt, Chaka Khan, Martina McBride, Robert Cray
Band, David Wilcox, Radney Foster and Bill Lloyd, Nanci Griffith
and Iggy Pop. 205-251-1272 or www.bhamnow.com/citystages
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tuscumbia, Ala. _ Playwright William Gibson's ``The Miracle
Worker'' is performed on the grounds of Ivy Green, Helen Keller's
birthplace, Friday through July 4. 256-383-4066 or
www.bham.net/keller/home.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamsburg, Va. _ ``Brothers in Arms: The African-American
Military Experience'' will be presented at Carter's Grove
Plantation in Colonial Williamsburg on Saturday and Sunday. Black
re-enactors representing the Revolutionary War, the Civil War,
Buffalo Soldiers and World War I will demonstrate military
techniques and discuss life in military camps. WWII veterans will
present informal lectures about their experiences before
desegregation. 757-220-7645.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. _ The 24th annual Spanish Night Watch
Weekend, Friday through Sunday, will include a torchlight march
through historic downtown, 18th-century military and civilian
demonstrations, re-enactments and period entertainment.
904-797-7217.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
