A9137 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-FACIALHAIR20-CO     06-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-FACIALHAIR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    R A Z O R S H A R P
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the hair on his head started thinning three years
ago, Atlanta graphic artist George Tierney grew a goatee to improve
his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   He got a good reaction from his girlfriend. ``So, from now on,
I'm going to have facial hair in some form or another,'' Tierney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Jimmie Warner holds his facial hair _ a mustache and
goatee _ in equally high esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand women love facial hair,'' he said. ``It's that
animal magnetism type of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   They are just two of the men who're fueling the ever-expanding
array of male grooming products in stores. Whether they're bearded,
cleanshaven or somewhere in between, men are paying more attention
to their whiskers than ever, and shaving product manufacturers have
taken note. The Gillette Co. wouldn't have spent an estimated $750
million on research, development and marketing of its new,
triple-bladed Mach 3 razor if it hadn't seemed like a good
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Browse the grooming section of any major drugstore and it will
appear as if there are as many different beard-softening gels and
foams as there are hairs sprouting from the average man's chin.
Many now contain such ingredients as aloe vera and oatmeal extracts
to ease skin irritation. And for the ultimate in shaving comfort,
men can opt to lather up with a shaving brush and soap. Brushes
start around $60 and can cost as much as $500 for a silver-tipped,
badger-hair model.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a fogless shower mirror on the market that's
designed to help prevent nicks because it won't cloud up. The $35
acrylic mirror, made by Z'Fogless, has five times the magnification
of standard mirrors and comes with compartments for shaving cream
and a razor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to men shaving in the shower, it's huge,''
Michael Parker, assistant manager of Brookstone in Lenox Square
(shopping mall), said of the mirrors. ``We usually end up running
out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Razors have evolved from standard safety blades and plastic
disposables to ones like Gillette's Mach 3 ($7) and Norelco's
Advantage, which dispenses Nivea lotion, for $95.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest razors on the market is Panasonic's Linear
Float Shaver, which costs $299 and came out in January. The
electric, wet-dry razor works with foams or gels and can perform
13,000 strokes per minute as compared to the standard 8,000 to
12,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Mercedes-Benz of shavers,'' declared Henry
Woodard, manager of the Sharper Image store at Lenox Square. ``Of
all the ones we have on the shelf, it sells above all others.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the gadgets men can buy to shave at home, more
and more are treating themselves to a relaxing shave at a
barbershop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men take their shaving seriously,'' said Lauren Cross, owner
of the Shaving Gallery in Cartersville. ``The art of shaving is
starting to be rediscovered, because men have got more time and
disposable income to spend on themselves. They're coming here from
miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross says she's booked solid every day with men willing to pay
$25 for a 40-minute shave. Some even pay her extra to redesign the
shape of their beards or mustaches.
</P>
<P>
   Lifestyle and personal preference determine a man's shaving
regimen more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Bevil of Dacula says he wears a full beard just to please
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look terrible without one,'' he said. ``I have a little
skinny chin. When I shave it, it scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   SHAVING TIPS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use a hard shaving soap, put it into a bowl and soak with
water
</P>
<P>
   to soften.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  With a badger brush (a top-of-the-line, silver-tipped one
costs about $500), rub in a circular motion to lift the beard
bristles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shave with the grain of the beard. (Going against the grain
causes razor burn and ingrown hairs.) Use small, downward strokes.
At the bottom of the neck, however, shave upward.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  After shaving, rinse the face with warm water, then cold.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Seal pores with a block of alum, a natural astringent. Never
use alcohol or mineral-based products, because they can irritate
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use an after-shave balm to moisturize the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
