<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book on cutting edge of shaving info
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wallace G. Pinfold's new book reached stores just in the nick of
time for all you last-minute Father's Day shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Closer Shave: Man's Daily Search for Perfection'' (Artisan,
$16.95) is a laudable alternative to whatever lame gift you might
have rushed out and bought today. As Pinfold says, more than nine
out of every 10 men shave, trim or clip their facial hair daily. In
other words, they can identify.
</P>
<P>
   But, while this CD-case-sized tome is packed with
well-researched information, anecdotes and prose in homage to
shaving, it won't be an easy sell. Shaving, after all, isn't
something most men devote much thought to. They just do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, I wondered, `What do people think about when
they're not thinking about anything?' '' Pinfold said last week
duri
</P>
</TEXT>
