<SLUG> BC-ICED-TEA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ANY OLD ICED TEA WON'T DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Receiving instant or bottled tea when I order
iced tea is like getting a TV dinner when I've asked for filet
mignon. And don't think for a minute that just because it's poured
into a plastic tumbler, I can't tell the difference. Iced tea does
not taste like powdered raspberries, nor does it leave sludge in
the bottom of the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Iced tea, like hot tea, is brewed, with water and tea leaves,
into a transparent, reddish-brown beverage. It's clear, it's crisp,
it's refreshing. It's not Snapple. And unless you add sweetener,
it's calorie free.
</P>
<P>
   Making iced tea is as easy as boiling water. In fact, it is
boiling water. But there are a few fine details for achieving the
best flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Use good water. Tap water is usually good enough but here's a
clue: If it comes out of the faucet opaque instead of clear, mosey
on down to the market for a gallon of noncarbonated water instead.
</P>
<P>
   Bring 1 quart water to a boil in a saucepan. Turn off heat, add
4 or 5 tea bags and cover. Let steep 5, 10 or 20 minutes. Whenever
you get back to it will do. Then pour into a pitcher with another
quart of water. Refrigerate to cool quickly so you can drink it
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   You can sweeten it, or flavor it with citrus wedges or mint. But
in the name of Gen. Robert E. Lee, serve it in a real glass. Tea
served in plastic tastes like plastic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
