A9152 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYDRANGEAS1STTAKE17-C     06-17 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYDRANGEAS1STTAKE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia gardener opens gates to share passion for hydrangeas
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Penny McHenry saunters up her garden path, it's
as if the cherubic faces of her ``girls,'' as she calls them, lift
ever so gently to beam for Momma.
</P>
<P>
   The 74-year-old matriarch, dubbed Atlanta's ``Hydrangea Lady''
because of her 400-plus family of showy plants, pauses. She clasps
her hands adoringly around one of the fat blue mopheads and
shrieks, ``Look at that! Mmmmmwha!'' giving one a big smack on the
forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kiss 'em, I talk to them, but,'' she says, lowering her
raspy voice to share a secret, ``I never, never tell one, `You're
so pretty,' because the one beside her might hear me. I'm convinced
that plants are like children _ they know when they're loved.''
</P>
<P>
   For 24 years, McHenry _ her little baby-blue wagon in tow _ has
wandered her garden not just in search of the most perfect bloom
but of answers in the tragic loss of a daughter. ``I feel very
strongly that Deede lives here,'' she says of the 23-year-old,
killed in a shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
   Deede's death in 1975 inspired her mother's garden and
quarter-century passion for the hydrangea. It was then that friends
brought McHenry two potted hydrangeas, which she planted in the
back yard. Her care for the plants led her to propagate them, or
``make babies,'' she says. Over the years, she began to experiment
with many of the hundreds of cultivars, producing a garden often
billed one of the country's finest hydrangea collections.
</P>
<P>
   And Momma couldn't be more proud of her girls. So much so she
prefers that visitors _ such as those taking part in this weekend's
American Hydrangea Society Tour _ tour her garden only in the
morning and evenings. In the afternoon heat, hydrangeas bow their
heads, and ``You don't want your girls looking all droopy if
company's coming by,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The ``company'' grows each year as the hydrangea hooks fans
drawn to a striking, yet low-maintenance plant that delivers
long-lasting summer color while kindling memories with its
nostalgic charm. ``It's a plant that evokes a lot of emotion,''
says Elizabeth Dean, whose nursery, Wilkerson Mill Gardens in
Palmetto, grows about 100 hydrangea cultivars. ``I do lots of slide
shows, and when I talk about hydrangeas, the audience goes orgasmic
with more oohs and ahhs than for any other plant. The blooms are
just so showy, when you stand in front of a loaded bush you just
want to dive right into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny takes the dive: McHenry's a lot like the bold, gaudy
plant. Sporting big blonde hair, big dark sunglasses and a
self-described big mouth, the one-time actress is a public
relations megaphone for the hydrangea. Garden designer Ryan Gainey
calls her ``Mrs. Mophead.''
</P>
<P>
   When McHenry first met the plant she was like most people, who
admire the billowy mopheads but are unfamiliar with its many
cousins. Her first two were simply tagged hydrangea macrophylla,
the common big-leaf varieties, which include hortensias and lace
caps. Hortensias have globe-shaped, or dense ``mophead'' blossoms;
lace caps have disc-like clusters of smaller flowers encircled by
larger ones. Others species include the panicle hydrangea (H.
paniculata) with cone-shaped flowers, the smooth-headed hydrangea
(H. arborescens), the climbers (H. anomala) with lace cap blossoms,
the small-flowering types (H. serrata) and the oakleaf (H.
quercifolia), a native to Georgia with elongated cluster blooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to have only one,'' McHenry says, glancing around to
see if any of her girls are listening, ``it would be the oakleaf.
It's pretty all year round,'' with white flowers that turn pink,
then mauve, and leaves that become crimson in fall.
</P>
<P>
   All hydrangeas are deciduous, which means McHenry's hundreds of
girls get ``naked,'' she says, in winter. Four years ago, landscape
designer Sandra Jonas convinced her to add evergreen shrubs and
perennials to brighten the drab landscape until spring and enhance
the sea of all blue, pink and white in summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that was here was acuba and 'ugly Agnes,' '' she says,
referring to the shrub elaeagnus.
</P>
<P>
   In spring and summer, squatty hostas, rocket-like foxgloves and
meandering clematis complement the fat mopheads with contrasting
form and texture.
</P>
<P>
   McHenry developed most of her collection of some 100 cultivars,
including one named in her honor, the 'Penny Mac,' the
old-fashioned way _ ``layering.'' By lowering a branch to the
ground, covering it with soil and anchoring it with a brick until
it takes root, she was able to extend her back yard's blue blanket
of shrubs to the front, where a sign welcomes visitors to
``Hydrangea Heaven.'' Others she acquired through hydrangea fans,
including the 400-member American Hydrangea Society, which she
founded five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, McHenry, whose big white station wagon sports
a license plate reading ``Hydrangea Lady,'' ran out of room in her
Flair Knoll Drive yard and got permission to plant hydrangeas on
church property behind her. ``Here are my Presbyterians!'' she
says, opening a rear gate to reveal dozens more mopheads.
</P>
<P>
   Penny's blue heaven. The key to growing beautiful hydrangeas,
she says, is pruning and sunlight. In addition to eliminating old
growth in early spring, McHenry cuts her flowers throughout the
summer, producing a second blooming in fall. And despite their
reputation as shade plants, most hydrangeas prefer several hours of
morning sun. Still, they are low maintenance plants with no enemies
to speak of, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Their only mystique is bloom color, which McHenry has
experimented with over the years by adding aluminum sulphate to the
soil to get blue, lime for pink. In general, acidic soil, produces
blue blossoms, while alkaline soil yields pink and red ones. Yet
sunlight also affects color. For that reason, both McHenry and Dean
believe gardeners place too much emphasis on changing hues. ``As
(Southern Living garden writer) Steve Bender once told me, 'Let
them be what they want to be,' '' she says. ``They're like your
children.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what had kept gardening a pleasure, not a chore, for
McHenry all these years. ``I don't have a gardener or a maid,''
says McHenry, whose only help is the moral support she gets from
husband Dave. ``I do not think gardening should be stressful. I
know when I come out here every day I'm not going to get everything
I want to do done. I garden because I'd rather be here than playing
bridge or at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as a grandmother of four, I strongly believe that if I can
teach them the wonders of nature (She's already taught three to
layer hydrangeas), I've achieved something.''
</P>
<P>
   Her thoughts suddenly get interrupted: ``Look at this lace
cap!'' she shouts, darting to inspect a discovery. ``How can
someone not like these girls?''
</P>
<P>
   Love is something Momma's girls know all about.
</P>
<P>
   Deede, no doubt, would vouch for that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
