<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9153 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYDRANGEAS2NDTAKE17-C     06-17 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYDRANGEAS2NDTAKE17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: would vouch for that.
</P>
<P>
   P E N N Y ' S S E C R E T S
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta gardener Penny McHenry's best advice for growing
hydrangeas includes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start with the soil. Make it rich and friable by providing
lots of amendments. She adds Nature's Helper Soil Conditioner and
manure. She also feeds her plants manure tea, which she makes by
placing barrels of manure at the corners of her house to collect
rain water, and a slow-release 10-10-10 fertilizer in spring and
fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Give them plenty to drink. McHenry prefers soaker hoses to an
irrigation system so that the ground, not the plant, gets wet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't be shy with shears. McHenry believes the secret to her
second bloom in fall is a heavy pruning in spring and cuttings
throughout summer. In late March, she prunes several of the largest
canes to the ground and the remaining ones to just above the point
at which new growth has emerged. (Oakleafs don't require pruning.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recycle those blooms. McHenry wastes nothing; all cuttings are
composted and returned to the soil as a layer of mulch, which helps
retain moisture and prevents weeds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Be patient with color. Mophead bloom color can range from deep
blue to bright red. The soil's acidity, or pH, determines bloom
color, but sunlight and other conditions also play a role. To make
blooms blue, apply 1/4-ounce aluminum sulphate in one gallon of
water, once each in spring and fall; conversely, to make them pink,
add lime around the base of the shrub in spring and fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make ``babies'': To propagate hydrangeas the old-fashioned
way, McHenry lowers the branch of a shrub to the (ground, covers it
with soil and anchors it with a brick. With frequent waterings and
feedings, roots emerge in six to eight weeks. Clip the branch from
the shrub and plant.
</P>
<P>
   I F Y O U G O
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangea Festival and Tour of Hydrangea Gardens
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hydrangea Festival
</P>
<P>
   Habersham Gardens is sponsoring a series of free seminars on
hydrangeas each weekend in June. Topics include pruning, drying,
arranging, bloom color, propagating, varieties, and new
introductions.
</P>
<P>
   When: 10 a.m. Saturdays, 1 p.m. Sundays. This weekend: Allen
Sistrunk, pruning (Saturday); Becky Baxter, drying and arranging
(Sunday). Next weekend: Jimmy Stewart, choices for Atlanta
(Saturday); Sara Henderson, propagation (Sunday)
</P>
<P>
   Where: 2067 Manchester St., Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-873-2484
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tour of Hydrangea Gardens
</P>
<P>
   The American Hydrangea Society is sponsoring its annual garden
tour, which at some sites includes demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   When: Saturday and Sunday (Hours vary for locations.)
</P>
<P>
   Where: Six gardens in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $15, which includes a one-year membership in the American
Hydrangea Society. Tickets and brochures: Habersham Gardens, 2067
Manchester St., Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-873-2484
</P>
