<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-ZINNIEAS17-COX     06-17 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-ZINNIEAS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zinnias sow seeds of disappointment
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The seed packet pictured a rainbow of perfect blooms, zinnias in
all their glory: red, yellow, orange _ hot colors for the hot times
when they explode in the garden and shower it with butterfly-loving
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   With memories of Big Momma dancing in my head _ Big Momma who
planted zinnias and collards in the front yard before it was cool _
I carefully scratched shallow little trenches into the ground. I
then scattered the seed in them, just as my grandmother had done
each spring back in Cuba, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I waited. Sure enough, in a few days the seeds sprouted,
and tiny green leaves on needle-sized stems pushed from the ground.
Wonderful. Now, just water and watch these babies grow into tall,
tough stems before producing blossoms of perfection like those on
the packet.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, disappointment, thy name is Zinnia.
</P>
<P>
   The stems reached a height of 2 inches and just stood there,
forlorn, weak, vulnerable. A large ant could accidentally trample
the poor darlings.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, I went to the garden to monitor the progress of
my would-be zinnia patch. Day after day, I marveled that any plant
could reach such a sad plateau and remain poised there, not growing
taller, yet not giving up and falling down, either.
</P>
<P>
   Yet again I had failed in the seed department. If my success
rate in growing plants from seed were translated into a baseball
player's batting average, I'm afraid I'd be booted off the team.
</P>
<P>
   For years, pride, manifesting itself as sour grapes, made me
disparage seed growing; I'd dismiss my failure by claiming I didn't
have time to grow plants from seed. I need more immediate
gratification, I'd say, cavalierly, knowing I was only trying to
fool myself.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain my repeated quests? Most springs find me
trying again. And there's never any shortage of potential failures;
my seed drawer is filled to the brim. Loose seeds, packets of
seeds, seeds nestled in paper towels, seeds stored and sealed
efficiently in little plastic bags. I even know what year some of
them were collected. However, what plants some of them came from
has grown a bit hazy.
</P>
<P>
   But the zinnia seeds were no mystery. And they were labled for
planting this year. They couldn't fail.
</P>
<P>
   Just as those okra seeds several years back were sure-fire.
Shared by a great grower in Rockdale County, the seeds produced
awesome okra _ in his garden. In mine, they grew plants that were
awesomely puny.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the hollyhock seeds for which I had such high
hopes when a friend sent them through the mail. Black hollyhock
blossoms _ I could just see them. Seems I never will. I didn't even
see shoots from the seeds so carefully planted. Same goes for the
poppy seeds I planted for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing about the poppies. When I first planted the gift
seeds a couple of years ago, the plants came up in the spring and
bloomed bright red, producing seeds of their own. Those seeds,
however, refused to germinate this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, my experience with seeds resembles my efforts to
grow certain houseplants that ``you just can't kill.'' I've had no
problem dispatching the unkillable snake plant, the invincible jade
and deathless cactus. Arguably, when I've had them keel over it's
because I watered too much, but there may be more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, overwatering might have been the way I lost my first ones
many years ago. After that, however, they may have fallen victim to
unconscious dread, self-fulfilling prophecy; I believed they'd drop
dead, and they did.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, my speculation could be way off base; failure has
a way of breeding uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   What I do know for sure is that I'm hurting for zinnias. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I love pain, but I'll continue planting seeds; there's
always another spring, another summer. Meanwhile, I'm looking for a
few good (ready-made) plants.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May suspends his zinnia hunt to visit two Georgia gardeners
for upcoming broadcasts of the PBS program ``The Victory Garden.''
The shows run on Atlanta's WPBA on June 19 and 26 at 5 p.m. Each
program will be rebroadcast statewide on GPTV one week later at
7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
