 Thursday, June 17, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the
following for Friday. If you have questions, please call Susie
McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in
all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MILOSEVIC (Paris) _ President Clinton says the U.S.-led
western alliance will not stage a raid in Yugoslavia to arrest its
president, Slobodan Milosevic, on war crimes charges. By STEWART M.
POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Paris) _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
touts the benefits of technology in a speech here, telling how
refugees from Kosovo, currently living in the French city of Lyon,
will soon be able to track down missing relatives on the Internet.
By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (New York) _ Vice President Al Gore touts tax cuts
for small businesses, an effort that his aides say shows that Gore
is able to deal in specifics, in contrast to the general themes
being offered by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leading contender
for the Republican presidential nomination. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HILLARYCLINTON (New York) _ Tony Coehlo, chairman of Vice
President Al Gore's campaign, insists that Gore's efforts to raise
funds and attract media attention aren't hindered by Hillary Rodham
Clinton's burgeoning candidacy of the U.S. Senate seat in New York.
By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-PASSENGERS (Washington) _ The nation's major airlines
announce a plan to improve customer service by giving passengers
more information about fares and delayed flights. The action is an
attempt to keep Congress from imposing new rules on the industry.
By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   BREZINSKI-KOSOVO (Washington) _ Zbigniew Brezinski, President
Jimmy Carter's former national security adviser, warns that this
weekend could provide a critical test in the Kosovo crisis. That's
when Serbian forces are scheduled to withdraw from their last zone
in northern Kosovo. If they refuse, it could mean that Moscow and
Belgrade are in collusion to gain power, he says. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL/BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-BOOKS (New York) _ The Hearst Corporation announces that
it has agreed to sell the Hearst Book Group consisting of William
Morrow &AMP; Co. and Avon Books to the News Corporation Limited, owner
of HarperCollins Publishers. The transaction is expected to be
completed in July. By The Hearst Newspapers. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-INVESTORS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
federal judges cannot stop insolvent companies from spending or
giving away their assets while they are being sued by investors
trying to recoup their money. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   FLEX-TIME (Washington) _ Another fight looms over a proposal by
Republican Sens. John Ashcroft of Missouri and Kay Bailey Hutchison
of Texas to allow employers of hourly workers to grant them time
off instead of overtime pay. A similar proposal was filibustered
last year because Democrats argued that it would undermine federal
labor laws and allow employers to take advantage of employees. BY
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's a classic case. Republican Rep.
George Nethercutt of Washington state, hailed as a hero for
defeating House Speaker Tom Foley in 1994 largely by championing
term limits, now says he will break his word. He wants to cling to
his job rather than keep his promise not to overstay his welcome.
Will the voters stand for such hypocrisy? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
