   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of Kosovo coverage:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Helsinki, Finland) _ Secretaries Albright and
Cohen continue talks with their Russian counterparts trying to
agree on a Russian peackeeping role in Kosovo. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Cologne, Germany) _ Developments on the
president's European trip: Clinton says NATO will not try to arrest
Yugoslav President Milosevic, who has been indicted for war crimes.
In Paris, French President Chirac agrees that there will be no
economic aid to Yugoslavia while Milosevic remains in power. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Dateline to kum) _ A tour of remote villages in
Kosovo reveals many mass graves. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ China calls ``unconvincing'' the
explanation of the NATO bombing of its emabssy in Belgrade offered
during a visit here by Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of
state. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina) _ A roundup of developments from the
Kosovar capital. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PATROL (Dateline to kum) _ On patrol with U.S. troops
helicoptering into the villages of Kosovo; plus a look at how NATO
tries to establish its presence. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Podujevo) _ Story on Serbian civilians fleeing
Kosovo in big numbers. There are still many Serbian soldiers
around, cheek by jowl with British peacekeepers. By David Rhode.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SHORT (Paris) _ In a telephone interview, Lt. Gen.
Michael Short, who ran the air war, says the West should not expect
another operation like this with no casualties. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
