<SLUG> BC-HOME-REPRODUCTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLPAPERS AND CARPETS WITH A PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKLAND, Mass. _ It's a big old yellow house that sits on the
main street in this town south of Boston. It's a very stately place
next to its more modest neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   At the side of the house is a very small sign: J. R. Burrows &AMP;
Company, Historical Design Merchants. John Burrows, 42 and the
owner, has found a market for what he loves best: re-creating
19th-century hand-printed wallpapers, lace, and carpets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came to the Boston area, people were just
beginning to get interested in Victorian homes,'' says Burrows, a
soft-spoken man with a burly beard. ``There was new interest
because people couldn't afford the Colonial homes of their parents'
generation. You could find some real bargains 15 years ago. Of
course, that's not true anymore, with skyrocketing real estate
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally from Wisconsin, then South Dakota and California,
Burrows says he was looking for a change in 1985. He'd always loved
New England, so he decided to move east and open his own small
shop. He chose Rockland (not one of the most beautiful of New
England settings) because it reminded him of towns in the Midwest
that were settled in the 1880s, his area of expertise.
</P>
<P>
   And with an interest in things Victorian growing in these parts,
Burrows thought he'd fill a needed niche by providing products for
people looking to furnish these large, creaky homes authentically.
Owners of historic houses, he says, are do-it-yourself people. They
tackle the plumbing and stripping themselves over years, and then,
finally, comes the fun part _ the decorating part. And they want to
do things affordably, but also authentically.
</P>
<P>
   His business began with people bringing him small pieces of old
wallpaper they'd found in their homes and wanted copied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created the artwork here and found the proper people to do
the printing,'' Burrows says. ``Initially, we did the painting for
the silkscreens in-house, but now a studio does the work. We
silkscreen instead of using woodblocks,'' which were used for the
19th-century originals, ``to make the papers less expensive to
produce.''
</P>
<P>
   The company now makes 15 patterns, which go by such terribly
British names as Sandringham, Priory Garden, and Kensington.
Perhaps the most gorgeous, and expensive, is The Stag. A single
roll, which covers 30 square feet, is $75.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lace from Scotland
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burrows also sells 10 patterns of Victorian lace _ the only
local company to do so. Others sell lace from France; Victorian
lace has larger patterns and a larger scale of weaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lace is made in Scotland,'' says Burrows, ``in the small
town of Kitmarize, near Glasgow. Many of the patterns are
representative of the Arts and Crafts movement _ a style that
suited Bostonians very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrows does a great deal of research. The pattern for his
Victorian Albertine lace panels, for example, was found while he
was doing research in an English textile museum archive. These
panels, he says, were used as the sole window covering or paired
with fancy valances.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps what Burrows &AMP; Co. is most known for is its
re-creation of 19th-century carpets. These are woven by Wood
Grosvenor &AMP; Co. Ltd., established in 1735 in Kidderminster, near
Birmingham, ``in the heart of England, but I usually only go there
in the dead of winter,'' says Burrows with a smile. ``They have
large archives, with 15,000 original designs dating back to the
1790s.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that Americans who could afford it during the Victorian
years bought their carpets from England because the weaving
techniques there were more advanced. He now markets his carpets not
only in the States but in England and Austria as well.
</P>
<P>
   The colors and patterns are spectacular, each painstakingly
matching the originals. His carpets are also not for the
financially fainthearted _ they run about $250 a square yard.
</P>
<P>
   Although Burrows works with the public, much of his business is
with house museums and interior designers. He was a consultant on
the carpet for the White House's Blue Room, and he is working on
carpeting for the Virginia governor's mansion, carpeting for the
Iowa state Capitol, and wallpaper for the Fred Holland Day house in
Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   Burrows says his interest in things historic began as a young
boy when his father, an English professor at the University of
Wisconsin in Whitewater, would take the family on summer treks to
museums and national parks, and then ``we did the grand European
tour'' when he was 10. The family often visited New England because
his father's family is from Reading. He said his passion for
England was solidified when he worked in a puppet factory in a
little town called Marlborough when he was 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Architectural history
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He studied architectural history at Grinnell College in Iowa and
received a master's degree, also in architectural history, from the
University of Virginia, where he graduated in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first job after school was as state architectural historian
for South Dakota, because there weren't any job openings in the
preservation field,'' says Burrows. ``Then I worked for a wallpaper
firm in California (Bradbury &AMP; Bradbury), where I learned a great
deal. I got increasingly interested in interiors.''
</P>
<P>
   As did the rest of the country, he points out. When he graduated
from college, there were very few books out there and only the Old
House Journal, which was a newsletter. But color Victorian
magazines began to appear in the early 1980s, and now they cover
large sections of newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Burrows said he bought his 1829 clapboard house in part because
it included a doctor's office _ a warren of small rooms that
Burrows uses as office space and a small showroom. He is slowly
restoring the rest of the house with his partner, Nelson Villafane,
and they are quickly filling it up with Victorian antiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wonderful about my job is making things available again
so people can live with them and not just see them in museums,''
says Burrows, who also lectures around the country. ``Being able to
re-create from history and use it _ to bring things into your own
environment _ it's an active way of using history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
