<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES.COM WILL HAVE TO IMPROVE TO OUTDISTANCE RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once companies worried about being taken over. Today they worry
about being ``Amazoned,'' which means waking up one day and finding
that an Internet upstart has stolen a big chunk of their business.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble got Amazoned by Amazon.com. Merrill Lynch got
Amazoned by E-Trade and a host of others.
</P>
<P>
   Staples Inc. isn't about to let that happen. ``If you don't
think about this offensively and defensively, someone could eat
your lunch,'' says Jeff Levitan, head of Staples.com, the on-line
arm of the Framingham office supply retailer.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Staples is in little danger of being Amazoned. The
office supply business on line already looks an awful lot like the
office supply business in the real world. The three big players on
the retail side _ Staples, Office Depot, and OfficeMax _ are the
three big players on line. And like their stores, their Web sites
are somewhat hard to tell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of similarity among them,'' agrees Fiona
Swerdlow, an analyst with Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The Staples experience holds an interesting lesson for
investors, who have assumed that traditional bricks and mortar
companies will be vanquished by pure Internet firms. In many
industries, the established players may do just fine. As in
politics, the incumbents turn out to have some formidable
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Take Staples. It has a well-known brand name. Because it is a $7
billion operation, Staples can buy goods at discounts a small
upstart could not match. The company also has an existing
distribution system that would be very expensive to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   Staples already does $2 billion a year in sales outside its
retail stores. Much of that business is done by customers who leaf
through a catalog, order products over the phone, and take delivery
by truck at their offices. The leap from there to an on-line
ordering system is not a huge one. ``What we have today is pretty
much an electronic catalog,'' says Levitan. ``We haven't reinvented
the shopping experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Christner says Staples will eventually have to do
better. ``The winners on line will be those who do the best job of
figuring out how the new medium can solve problems,'' says
Christner, a consultant with Mercer Management. ``Just transferring
a catalog on line isn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Staples is trying. The company has created a number of features
in its Web business that do not exist elsewhere. On-line customers,
for instance, can easily get a history of their past purchases.
They can get e-mail reminders to reorder.
</P>
<P>
   Using a feature called Group Account Manager, individuals within
an office can order their own supplies, subject to approval from
the office manager. Levitan thinks the new feature will free up the
office manager, but still let him stop Jones in accounting from
ordering too many Cross pens.
</P>
<P>
   Staples is also trying to practice cross pollination. Customers
who are unhappy with products ordered on line can return those
products to any of Staples' 1,000 stores. There is advertising for
the on-line business in the stores and advertising for the stores
on line.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan thinks customers will find the channel that works best
for them. The same customer might come into a store to buy a chair,
a product that requires touching and feeling, but use the Internet
to buy paper clips. ``We don't think we have channel conflicts,''
says Levitan. ``The more points of contact we have with the
customer, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitan insists Staples can grow its Web business, estimated at
$200 million this year, even as its adds more bricks and mortar.
The company plans to erect 170 stores this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Temkin, an analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge,
suspects that at some point, Staples will have to make some hard
choices. ``They've got a finite amount of investment dollars,'' he
says. ``Eventually they may have to make some tradeoffs between
bricks and mortar and on line.''
</P>
<P>
   Temkin also suspects that Staples' stores may have to morph into
something more like showrooms as the buying action shifts on line.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan doesn't deny that moving to the Web requires some major
adjustments. He has struggled to find talented people, learned to
deal with new advertising media, and strained to work at a faster
pace. Staples.com was launched last November and the Web site has
already been redesigned twice. ``Our motto is fast and flexible,''
says Levitan.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan also constantly scans the competitive landscape, looking
for potential upstarts that might try to gain a foothold in the
on-line office supply business. So far he hasn't seen anybody who
poses a major threat.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan's second motto might be: Staples isn't about to be
``Amazoned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
