<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOT ENOUGH FOR YA?' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot enough for ya? If I hear that once more I'll commit
something or other, although anything specific is not politically,
or legally, correct.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, someone could coin a phrase, and ask the handyman,
Hottonuff for ya? Ooh!
</P>
<P>
   A smart remark like one of the above is likely to get you even
hotter in these dog days of June. Not all the days of June are that
hot, but we can be confident that if a few days are cool, there
will be plenty of scorchers through September.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, let's see what we can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Easy and expensive &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Air conditioning is the easiest way, and the most expensive of
all the cooler-offers, but remember, central air is like your
heating system, burning fuel to create cool rather than heat, and
the season is much shorter, therefore, more affordable. And, you
don't have to run it all the time because the heat is not
consistent. While an air conditioner is expensive to run, because
it is electric, it is not that pricey to install.
</P>
<P>
   While central air is great, room units are good, too, allowing
you to cool individual rooms instead of the whole house. If you're
thinking of putting in only a few room units, pick and choose where
to put them: kitchen, bedrooms, and family room are good choices.
</P>
<P>
   Room units have become little dynamos in recent years, small
packages with a big cooling capacity. They are small but powerful,
and light in weight so they can easily be installed in a window and
removed for winter storage.
</P>
<P>
   Or, a unit can be installed permanently in a wall opening, with
better sealing against air loss than can be done in a window. A
hole-in-the-wall unit also frees up the window for ventilation and
the view.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Portable units, too &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relatively new on the market is a portable room air conditioner,
one that's on wheels so you can move it where it is needed. While
these units are portable, they are not free-standing, and still
must be exhausted through a window to the outdoors. They are sold
at appliance stores, and are more expensive than standard room
units.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you must be careful about room units is their size,
capacity and amperage. A large unit, rated, say, at 13 amps, is
likely to blow a fuse, trip a circuit breaker, or burn wires when
plugged into a 15-amp service. If you put such a unit on such a
service, you cannot plug anything else into the circuit, because
adding just a few lamps would bring it over 15 amps, resulting in a
short or overload.
</P>
<P>
   An important part of air conditioning is dehumidification. All
air conditioners are dehumidifiers, an important fact in keeping
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Short of air conditioning, is there anything else to do? Yes,
thank goodness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
All kinds of fans
</P>
<P>
   Fans, for a start. After an initial heat wave, you may not find
fans in a store, but if you buy early, you will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   First, install window fans, which exhaust hot air out of the
house. Put a big one on the first floor and second floor. They work
best when the temperature outdoors is lower than that in the house,
when set on exhaust, not intake. Open several windows elsewhere in
the house, where cooler air will be drawn in as hot air is
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Window fans like these can cool the house overnight, even if
it's 90 in the house and 65 in outdoors late in the evening. By
wakeup time, it will be 65 in the house.
</P>
<P>
   A whole house fan works the same way as window fans, except that
it exhausts more air faster. Usually located in the attic floor, it
exhausts air from the house into the attic where it is vented
through vents. The vents are essential, and there should be enough
of them to handle the high volume of the fan.
</P>
<P>
   Another type of fan can bring relief. These are floor fans and
oscillating fans, ones that simply blow air, hot or cool, on you.
The blowing air is cooling on a hot, sweaty body; the evaporation
process does the cooling. You may feel clammy, but at least a
little cooler.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Some personal tricks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the personal tricks, all of which are temporary.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, avoid coffee and alcohol. These stimulants may
cool you off but soon you will be even hotter.
</P>
<P>
   Wear loose clothing. Cotton is your best choice. Avoid socks and
panty hose whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ice water and ice cubes are great coolers. One quick
cooler-offer is to run cold water over your wrists. This is
supposed to cool the blood, and it does help a little.
</P>
<P>
   Soak your feet in cool, cool water. Take tepid showers. Hot and
cold showers will make you hotter. Pat, don't rub dry; rubbing
creates friction, and you know what friction causes.
</P>
<P>
   Drink water, fruit juices and other non-alcholic goodies, and
avoid sugar as well. One of the best coolers is a tall glass of ice
cubes filled with orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is this trick, which is like hitting yourself
with a 2 x 4, because it feels so good when you stop.
</P>
<P>
   Find the dirtiest, hottest chore that you can do around the
house. Putting insulation in the attic floor comes to mind the
dirtiest, hottest of them all, except maybe laying an asphalt
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Finish the chore, take a tepid shower and sit down with a tall
glass of ice cubes and orange juice. No sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that does feel good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
