A9182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-TOUR-BOS &LR;      06-17 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOWING A GARDEN WITH PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's showtime in Dover, Mass. The palms and bananas and
oleanders are stage right. The cannas, brugmansias, and hibiscus
are stage left. And directing it all is Kevin Doyle, a garden
impresario cum designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The garden comes to life whenever it's full of people,'' Doyle
told me on a recent meander around his three-acre property. ``It's
an art form; it's a performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle discovered the joys of taking others on tours of his
garden, which he has named Cairn Croft, eight years ago, when he
shared his remarkable works with his garden club. Now he regularly
escorts visiting horticulture groups, such as the American
Horticultural Society this month, and outings from the Tower Hill
Botanic Garden in Worcester and classes from the Boston Learning
Society.
</P>
<P>
   He subscribes to a definition of a garden as ``a place where you
enter and quickly forget from where you've come,'' and while it can
offer peace and sanctuary, ``I like to think that a fair amount of
my garden is kind of jazzy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's putting it mildly. Doyle's garden, on which he has been
working for 22 years now, is wild and different, lush and colorful.
It's been called a tropical garden, and at first glance, it is. But
that's not what Doyle had in mind. He set out to have a garden with
four-season interest, and that means a design based on foliage, and
that requires some big, bold items. Those either are tropical or
look that way.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle also relies heavily on variegated plants, including
several superb mock oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are follies, topped by a semicircle of eight-foot
columns, which help form a garden room and also keep the eye from
wandering off to spy a nearby house. There is a bench that on
closer inspection is a brownstone cornice from the original Jordan
Marsh store. A 60-by-40-foot pond has a number of Asian glass
fishing floats in it. They look like bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's garden is a brilliant, diverse composition. ``This is my
garden, and I'm crazy,'' he told me, as Ryan, the golden retriever,
dug up plants and performed other unspeakable acts to gain
attention. Just another actor on Doyle's stage.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle learned to love gardening as a young boy at his
grandfather's place in Kingston. ``I thought it was borderline
magic what was going on there,'' he said, before looking around his
own garden and adding, ``I think this is magic.''
</P>
<P>
   His other grandfather was a South Boston caterer, and so was
Doyle, for 14 years. Eventually, he inherited the business, but by
then he was taking gardening courses, developing Cairn Croft, and
traveling to great gardens in this country and abroad. He sold the
catering business.
</P>
<P>
   He began as a garden professional working for a landscape
architect, installing new plantings at an estate. Doyle still
maintains estate gardens, but ``now I basically live on designing
gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes pride in designing gardens that are all different, that
reflect their owners, not him. ``Gardens are all about people's
dreams and their aspirations and their ambitions.'' As a designer,
he applies psychology and good listening skills to solve the
problem of just what it is a client really wants.
</P>
<P>
   At his Dover home, he lets loose, he is impulsive: ``The most
magic occurs quite by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Gloria helped clear his then overly wooded site, which
amounts to a drumlin with a house on it. His garden rooms are on
various levels. Past the columns, a bare path turns grassy and
winds up to the left, a spot providing a view of the sloped back
gardens. To the right at the back of the house are a greenhouse and
terrace, with plants seasonally shuttling between. A level grassy
swarth separates the house and a perennial border that Doyle,
inspired by the borders at Great Dixter in England, is turning into
a mixed border, the shrubs providing backbone and extending
seasonal interest.
</P>
<P>
   A grass path leads down the hillside, between other beds, and
down to the pond, which Doyle likens to a field: ``It sets
everything off.'' Functioning similarly along the opposite bank of
the pond is a great patch of petasites, moisture-loving plants with
enormous leaves. They help pop the smaller actors into view. They
are invasive but also hardy, a good substitute for gunnera.
</P>
<P>
   A bridge leads across the pond to woodland trails, and they lead
to Doyle's latest efforts, stands of hardy bamboos, some huge, some
ground covers. There are sculptural elements scattered around,
pseudo-stone balls, echoing the fishing balls in the pool, and old
tools. Here there is peace and sanctuary.
</P>
</TEXT>
