<HEADLINE>
SURF'S UP! BUT BE CAREFUL SWIMMING  
 AIDS AT TOP OF LIST IN RESEARCH FUNDING  
 IN WAKE OF FIRING FLAP, JOURNAL ADDS OVERSIGHT PANEL  
 EXERCISE IS FOUND TO HELP PSYCHOLOGICAL DISORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Surf's up! But be careful swimming
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Monica Bay, people who swam closest to a storm drain
had twice the risk of developing an ear discharge, while many of
those exposed to high levels of coliform bacteria got bloody
diarrhea and skin rashes, according to a study involving more than
13,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that, 25 to 40 cases of swimming-related illnesses for
every 1,000 swimmers can be expected, according to an editorial
accompanying the study in the journal Epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
   A second study, in the current Journal of the American Medical
Association, explored another hazard of water sports _ drowning.
While drownings have actually declined in the United States, from
5,700 in 1986 to fewer than 4,000 in 1996, researchers have been
mystified about the reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The study and an accompanying editorial conclude that the
decline may come from a drop in alcohol use, an increase in
sedentary lifestyles among young people and, even, fear of water
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AIDS at top of list in research funding
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   US funding for research has often come under fire, with some
people saying too much is going to AIDS and not enough to cancer,
for instance, while others argue the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the current New England Journal of Medicine tries to
look at funding based on each disease's burden on society.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1996, AIDS ranked No. 1 in overall National Institutes
of Health research funding, with 28.7 percent, or $1.4 billion,
while it was ranked 10th in mortality and 20th in new cases being
diagnosed every year.
</P>
<P>
   Heart disease ranked fifth in terms of funding, with 5.5
percent, or $269.1 million, while it was the No. 1 killer and No. 7
in new cases being diagnosed every year.
</P>
<P>
   But the study and an accompanying editorial by NIH director
Harold Varmus say mortality and newly diagnosed cases are not
necessarily the best measures of the burden posed by a disease.
Instead, they point to something called disability-adjusted
life-years, or the number of years of healthy life lost to a
disease.
</P>
<P>
   That measure was ``strongly predictive of NIH funding,''
according to the study's authors, who are from Johns Hopkins
University School of Medicine. Nonetheless, they found that AIDS,
breast cancer, diabetes, and dementia received ``relatively
generous funding,'' while chronic obstructive pulmonary disease,
birth-related conditions, and peptic ulcer were relatively
underfunded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In wake of firing flap, journal adds oversight panel
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In response to controversy over the firing of its editor, the
Journal of the American Medical Association Wednesday laid out a
new plan to ensure editorial independence ``while also preserving
the AMA's responsibilities as publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   But JAMA has not named a permanent replacement for Dr. George D.
Lundberg, who was fired in January after the journal published a
survey of college students that backed President Clinton's
contention that oral sex is not ``having sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ``editorial governance plan'' calls for the creation of
a seven-member journal oversight committee to serve as a ``buffer''
between the editor and AMA management. The editor will continue to
report to management ``only for business and financial
operations,'' not editorial content, the plan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Editorial independence of the editor-in-chief will be
absolutely protected and respected by AMA management,'' according
to the journal, a widely cited source of medical news that was
roundly criticized for firing Lundberg. The editor can still be
dismissed if the oversight committee makes that recommendation, and
two-thirds of the AMA board agree, however.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Exercise is found to help psychological disorders
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exercise is good for the psychological health of people
diagnosed with depression, anxiety disorders, developmental
disabilities, and it may help those with schizophrenia, according
to a new in-depth review of the scientific literature.
</P>
<P>
   With the growing evidence of exercise's importance and its
relative affordability, ``It is somewhat surprising that it has not
become a more popular treatment alternative,'' write the authors in
the current issue of Professional Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest evidence of benefit comes from studies of patients
with depression. Major improvements were seen as soon as five weeks
after people begin exercising three times a week, for 20 to 60
minutes at a time, finds the report, which assessed nearly 20
years' worth of studies of exercise as therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The authors called for more research into the benefits of
exercise for people with schizophrenia, alcohol dependence, and
other psychiatric disorders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
