<HEADER>
A9186 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALCOHOL-FREE-BEER-(NE     06-17 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-FREE-BEER-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THAT AWFUL FLAVOR IN ALCOHOL-FREE BEER?  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JUNE 14, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By DEBORA MACKENZIE  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alcohol-free beer may seem a contradiction in terms. And if the
lack of bite doesn't get to you, the nasty taste will _ as any
pregnant woman or designated driver will attest.
</P>
<P>
   Now Belgian scientists have identified the chemical to blame,
and they'd be halfway to solving the problem, but for public
mistrust of genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Real beer contains between 3 and 12 percent ethanol, while any
brew with less than 1 percent can be classified as
''alcohol-free.''
</P>
<P>
   All beers start out as wort, a mixture of ground, malted grain
and water, which is then fermented with yeast. This creates both
the alcohol and the mixture of esters, sugars and complex alcohols
that give a beer its unique taste and aroma.
</P>
<P>
   Most low-alcohol beers are fermented at 1 degree C, to keep the
yeast from making much alcohol. But this also stops the flavorful
chemicals from developing, says Philippe Perpte of the Brewing and
Food Industries Laboratory of the Catholic University of Louvain,
Belgium. ''The worty, 'off' flavor of alcohol-free beer comes from
chemicals that would ordinarily have been transformed by the
yeast,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His team analyzed the chemical make-up of alcohol-free beer,
ordinary lager and wort by passing them through a gas
chromatograph. This separates the compounds, letting researchers
smell each one as it travels past a ''sniffing port.''
</P>
<P>
   Four samplers took 20-minute turns to describe the scents that
wafted by. ''One person can't do the whole thing,'' says Perpte.
''You can't smell anything after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Using mass spectrometry to identify the chemicals behind the
smells, they discovered a particularly unpleasant one was
3-methylthiopropionaldehyde, or methional. Its scent persisted at
low dilutions, and was especially strong in both wort and
alcohol-free beer, the authors report in the Journal of
Agricultural and Food Chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Further experiments showed that the methional in wort is largely
broken down by subsequent fermentation. What little is left in
normal beer is masked by other flavors, says Perpte. Even the few
alcohol-free beers that are made by evaporating alcohol from normal
beer suffer from the ''off'' taste, he says, because the chemicals
that usually mask it are removed with the alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the American Society of Brewing Chemists in
Phoenix, Ariz., later this month, Perpte's team will announce their
bid to solve the problem: an artificial yeast in which the gene for
one enzyme, an alcohol dehydrogenase, has been snipped out. The
yeast needs the enzyme to make ethanol, but it also produces
methional.
</P>
<P>
   Perpte suspects the modified yeast would be perfect for
alcohol-free beer, but the food industry in Europe is nervous about
genetic engineering. ''No brewer is ready to use it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
