<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IDEA WHOSE TIME IS DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first question to ask about any new gimmick or gadget is
always the same: Who's this thing really for? Is this invention
meant to make life better and easier for lowly users like me? Or is
it mainly an opportunity to put another Porsche in the garage of
some bright young thing?
</P>
<P>
   Asking this question a couple of years ago would have
forestalled much of the hype surrounding ``push technology.'' You
remember _ the software that went onto the Internet on its own to
bring you news headlines and the like. After an early blaze of
enthusiasm, people finally came to see push as a solution to a
nonexistent problem. And so after an initial blaze of enthusiasm,
most of the old pushers are long since reduced to ash.
</P>
<P>
   This winnowing of clever but useless innovations will never end.
Indeed, another tech victim was flung onto the pyre just Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City Stores Inc. of Richmond, Va., last year rolled out
Divx, a variant of the popular DVD video format. The difference
with Divx was that you could rent one of these video disks without
having to return it.
</P>
<P>
   The disks worked only in special players connected to your
telephone line. Registered Divx users could play a disk for 48
hours. After that, the disk would become unplayable. The ``renter''
would then either trash the useless disk or use the modem in the
Divx player to reactivate the disk, and charge an additional
viewing fee to a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Divx was no engineer's dream. A Hollywood entertainment-law firm
came up with the concept _ there's a warning sign for you. But they
persuaded Circuit City to go along. Together they developed the
necessary software and special video players. Then they waited for
customers to come trooping in.
</P>
<P>
   Only they didn't. And so Circuit City Wednesday gave up on the
whole hopeless idea and wrote it off as a $114 million loss.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? The usual. Divx brought more benefits to
Circuit City and its allies than it brought to consumers. The Divx
disks played only in Divx players, which were more expensive than
standard DVD devices. And the disks wouldn't even play in a
friend's Divx machine _ only yours. Granted, the system cut back on
return trips to the video store. But that's also the big selling
point of pay-per-view cable movies, which have never caught on.
</P>
<P>
   So, scratch one stillborn technology. There's plenty more to
come. I'm expecting not-so-great things from the recorded music
industry, still scrambling to minimize the impact of computers and
the Internet on record sales.
</P>
<P>
   The popular MP3 music format lets people make both legal and
illegal copies of popular music and pass them around over the World
Wide Web. Alarmed by the threat to their members' sales, the
Recording Industry Association of America has campaigned hard
against unrestricted MP3 use. The RIAA lost a big one on Tuesday,
as a federal judge upheld Diamond Multimedia Systems Inc.'s right
to sell its Rio portable MP3 player. The ruling means that other
electronics companies will soon peddle MP3 devices of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Record companies are being forced to find voluntary means to
limit the spread of MP3. They've tried alternative Internet music
formats like Liquid Audio and A2B, which have features that prevent
unlimited copying of records. But neither format is making much
headway. After all, they bring almost no benefit to listeners; they
exist solely to protect the record companies. For most people
that's just not reason enough to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Now the RIAA is working on yet another solution. It's a set of
software standards that'll be compatible with MP3, but will also
allow companies to slap copying restrictions on the music. For
instance, you'll be able to make a personal MP3 copy of the next
Rolling Stones CD, but you won't be able to send the copy to
somebody else over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   I can't blame the RIAA for trying. Nobody has a right to steal a
musician's work. And yet, software companies have tried ``copy
protection'' systems like this for years. They've yet to find one
that can't be beaten. Even Liquid Audio and A2B have been hacked. I
expect the RIAA system to meet the same fate _ another clever idea
smashing head-on into the public's irrepressible desire to have it
their way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send e-mail to Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
