<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-THREE-BOS &LR;      06-17 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-THREE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FASCINATING VOYAGE INTO OCEANIC DEPTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THREE MILES DOWN 
A Hunt for Sunken Treasure 
By James Hamilton-Paterson 
The Lyons Press, 304 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Hamilton-Paterson's books, fiction and nonfiction alike,
assemble experiences and observations that no one else would think
to put in the same place.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Hamilton-Paterson's previous books centered on the sea,
like this one, which begins with a phone call from a friend the
writer had met during the research for ``The Great Deep: The Sea
and Its Thresholds'' (1992). ``How do you fancy coming on a hunt
for sunken treasure?'' the friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton-Paterson fancied the idea a lot, and signed on for an
expedition to look for a Japanese submarine and a British troop
ship buried 3 miles deep in the Atlantic, off the coast of Africa.
Both boats carried cargoes of gold, tons of it. Hamilton-Paterson's
role was to chronicle the voyage of the Akademik Mstislav Keldysh,
the ship that found the Titanic, and the efforts of the British
team, code-named ``Orca,'' to bring back the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably Hamilton-Paterson's friend realized the writer would
not turn in a routine journalistic account of the trip, a work of
direct reportage; some of the others aboard, British and Russians
alike, probably didn't realize how they would figure in an offbeat
masterpiece by a writer who as unpredictable as his subjects, which
are nature and human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Miles Down'' is a work of history, of science, of
observation, of reflection; it is a narrative of adventure and an
explosion of thought and feeling _ exciting, unsettling, amusing,
and profound, often all at once. Before it is over, we journey with
the writer to a place few men have been before; it is an underwater
landscape, but it also carries us to some kind of center, as in
meditation.
</P>
<P>
   The history comes from the research carried out by the Orca team
on the final fatal voyages of the submarine and the troop ship;
these have all the excitement of an old-time war movie, but without
the romance _ there's nothing romantic about how men die in a
torpedoed submarine.
</P>
<P>
   The science comes through Hamilton-Paterson's fascination with
the ocean, its facts, its mysteries. Everything that occurs on the
sea is a kind of miracle; landlubbers, he writes, ``don't know in
their bones that the sea has no plans, that we don't belong here,
that every additional day successully spent afloat is a blessing.''
Science is most vividly represented in the work of the Russian
oceanographers aboard the Akademik Keldysh, including the great
Anatoly Sagalevitch, who invented the submersibles that can
withstand the pressure of water 3 miles deep on top of them.
Sagalevitch, an ironist worthy of a place in Turgenev, finds
himself in the position of hiring his invention out for commercial
purposes, fitting his own scientific interests and pursuits around
the edges of the journey. ``The quest for gold ingots has a certain
narrative suspense, but it is of no real interest compared to
biology or meteorology,'' the scientists believe.
</P>
<P>
   The adventure is the search for the gold _ will the Orca team
find it? will they be able to bring it up? An air of romance still
surrounds this quest, because deep salvage is an expensive and
risky operation _ Hamilton-Paterson points out that ``the business
of recovery is as specialized in its way as that of space
exploration, much more dangerous, and very nearly as expensive.''
Not all the dangers are underwater; the legal complications are
extraordinary. At all costs, for example, the Orca team wants to
avoid having the troop ship declared a war grave by the British
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in a modern salvage operation like this,''
Hamilton-Paterson observes, ``the central factor is not the gold at
all but the personalities involved. It is easy to center one's
attention on the technology: the dazzling science, precision tools,
electronic wizardry. But underneath are critical chains of command,
leadership issues, differences of opinion, alliances and
animosities which outweigh everything else. High stakes produce
high tension.'' So the drama of ``Three Miles Down'' becomes a
drama of character, a comedy of mixed and conflicting motives, of
language barriers, of functioning and dysfunctional technology, as
well a tragedy of irreconcilable goals. The American edition omits
several pages of color photographs that appeared in the original
British publication, photos that make these people visible;
Hamilton-Paterson's writing makes them real, and understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton-Paterson not only sees, records, and understands
everything before him; he feels it. ``Suddenly everything about
this enterprise, this chain of events which had its roots so long
ago, afloat on this ocean, seems trivial. The boundless waste of
human intelligence in war, the waste of lives and loves and time;
the futility of power; the sense that gold itself is no more than
compressed emptiness, a locus of dreams. All this contributes to a
melancholy which is never far away on this voyage, hanging like
dark smoke just over the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the book is Hamilton-Paterson's own journey to
the ocean floor, his account of an experience few have had, of a
place few have seen. The writing here is as prosaic as a bathroom,
but at the same time, the matter-of-fact achieves the sublime.
Hamilton-Paterson is close to something primordial, to the engines
of creation; in writing about it, he comes as close to reverence as
any modern writer is going to get. By the end, the narrative of the
search for gold still interests us, but we don't really care how it
comes out because Hamilton-Paterson has engaged us on another level
of consciousness, and reawakened and renewed our sense of wonder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
