<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUSADER'S MESSAGE OBSCURED BY HIS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVANSTON, Ill. _ He was not exactly a household word, at least
not until February when the media picked up the story of Anthony
Porter, a man who was sprung after 17 years on death row. One of
his first acts of freedom was to embrace the Northwestern
University journalism professor who _ along with his students _
unearthed the evidence that Porter was slated to die for murders he
didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, David Protess has been inundated with roughly 2,000
emails, letters, and phone calls from prisoners, advocacy groups,
and clergy seeking his help in righting similar wrongs. The media
have descended upon him, Hollywood is abuzz with story ideas, and
maintaining his privacy has become a problem. From his newfound
bully pulpit, Protess criticizes ``corporate journalism'' for not
pursuing the kind of truth-seeking that has made him famous.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year old Brooklyn native has been working to reverse
``wrongful conviction'' cases since he was at Chicago Lawyer
magazine in the 1980s. (By his count, Porter represents his eighth
successful effort. Another one of his class projects, death row
prisoner Aaron Patterson, is currently awaiting a state Supreme
Court hearing and Protess is ``positive Aaron Patterson is going to
get relief.'')
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, Protess has turned his once traditional
investigative journalism class into a real-life detective drama. As
the syllabus for his C73 Investigative Journalism Class states,
``we will use advanced reporting methods . . . to investigate
evidence of real world miscarriages of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I believe we ought to be doing in journalism
is teaching how inspirational this profession is,'' says Ken Bode,
Dean of Northwestern's Medill Journalism School, when asked about
Protess.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Protess is unveiling The Center for Wrongful
Convictions, which will be connected to both Medill and the law
school. Once his journalism students unearth evidence of a
miscarriage of justice, the case will go to the law school ``to
bring it to the attention of the courts,'' he says. There will also
be a parallel effort to get these stories on the media radar
screen, since as Protess puts it, ``the truth not only has to be
found, it has to be told.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Protess takes a somewhat disapproving view of much of
modern journalism. (He tells reporters seeking an interview with
him that their time is better spent looking to unearth an
injustice.) He sees an industry beleaguered by ``corporate
journalism'' which he defines as ``decisions about allocations of
resources . . . based on the bottom line instead of on the need to
find the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he cringes at the idea that he is more activist than
journalist. When asked whether he is anti-death penalty, Protess
says his personal views are ``irrelevant. . . . For me, the issue
is `are we putting innocent people on death row?' which is an
empirical question. That is an issue that trancends ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one piece of popular Protess mythology that he says
originated in a 1996 People magazine profile. The story goes that
the foundation for his future career was laid when he read about
the executions of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg _ for spying for the
Soviets _ as a 7-year old in 1953. Protess says he felt sympathy
for the Rosenbergs' two young children, but denies the episode
``was a defining moment in my life. . . . I'm not even sure it was
a wrongful conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Protess actually gravitated toward investigative reporting
during the Watergate era when he was a political science professor
at Loyola University. ``It seemed like journalists were shaping
public consciousness about the issues of the day,'' he says. ``Here
I was standing in front of the class.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late '70s and early '80s, he worked at a Chicago civic
watchdog group, the Better Government Association, which aided two
infamous and controversial Chicago Sun-Times' undercover
investigations _ the infiltration of unscrupulous abortion clinics
and the Mirage bar, which the paper bought and operated to ensnare
local officials engaging in routine corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a rush when you hold a political official
accountable,'' says Protess. But he began to tire of the pursuit of
official misconduct, noting it simply reinforced the idea that
``the system isn't working'' and felt like ``just slinging mud.''
Once he channeled his energy into wrongful conviction cases, he
says, ``I had this tremendous sense of satisfaction'' _ of ``saving
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Protess now sees himself as a victim of his success,
saying the ``fun ended'' the day Porter marched out of jail. His
class was disrupted, demands on his time grew, the media hordes
invaded, and he became stressed out. Protess wants and needs the
spotlight to turn his investigations into ``a public education
experience.'' But the double-edged sword of media attention is
frustrating him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not uncomfortable with the amount of publicity,'' he says.
``I'm uncomfortable with the focus. . . . We're not the story.''
Both his admirers and detractors might debate that point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a coup for Newsweek, Anna Quindlen _ who gained fame as the
voice of baby boomer feminism on The New York Times' op-ed pages in
the early '90s 90's before becoming a successful novelist _ will
succeed the late Meg Greenfield as the magazine's back page
columnist in October. Her journalistic comeback will likely to
provide readers with a distinctly different worldview than her
fellow back page commentator, George Will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can chalk Medill Dean Ken Bode off the list of potential
hopefuls to succeed Marvin Kalb as director of the Kennedy School
of Government's Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and
Public Policy. ``In a phrase, it's the right job, wrong time,''
says Bode, who is preparing to break ground on a major public
affairs facility at Medill and who couldn't wait for a Harvard
decision in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
