<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERVEDLY IN THE DOGHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I came home to find a notice from the dog officer on my door. It
read: ``CRUELTY INVESTIGATION. 10:45 _ 5/29/99 _ Dog left in car _
No water _ Windows up. VIOLATION OF THE LEASH LAW. Numerous
complaints from neighbors. Dog is loose constantly in
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   I knew what the cruelty to animals charge was about. I'd driven
to exercise class that morning. The sky had been overcast; rain was
predicted. It was cool enough so that I was wearing a light jacket,
but when I came out of the building after my one-hour class, I
noticed that the sun had come out and hurried to the car to check
on the dog. The woman who'd called the dog officer had the courage
to tell me she'd reported me, and to point out that the dog had
pooped in my car. Pandy did look pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't surprised. After eating a cake intended to feed 30
people, the dog had done nothing but poop and vomit for three long
days and nights, with such a demoralizing effect that Pandy could
have been cited for cruelty to humans. I'd brought her with me for
humanitarian reasons _ she was so miserable, I didn't want to leave
her home alone.
</P>
<P>
   And now here I was, being cited as a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   It was also true that I'd been running late and even though the
temperature was below 70 degrees, I'd been negligent in not opening
a car window. As for the water, if there had been any, Pandy would
have spilled it. When she's been in the car a while, I bring her
water and let her drink it outside on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   This is an example of how my mind was working: I have been bad.
I'm not so bad. Yes, I am. Well, maybe a little bad. Waves of
annoyance and resentment alternated with waves of shame and guilt.
I felt awful.
</P>
<P>
   Our anonymous neighbor's complaints came as a surprise, though
they shouldn't have. All spring Jack and I have been working in our
unfenced yard, only minimally aware of whether Pandy was in or out.
When I put the dog outside alone, I always attach her to a run in
our yard, but there had been several occasions this spring when I'd
said, ``Jack, where's the dog?'' only to discover she was still
outside without our having noticed her absence. I also knew Pandy
was stealing toys from a neighbor's dog, and early this spring,
after a conversation with the dog's mom, I'd filled a grocery bag
with dog toys and delivered them as a peace offering. I know now
that a state of peace between us and the neighbors was a figment of
my imagination.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question: We were entirely at fault for not obeying
the law and keeping Pandy on a leash at all times, though for the
life of me I still can't figure out how to keep Pandy from slipping
out when people walk in and out of our house. We're bad. Maybe not
so bad. Just a little bad. Here I go again. Perhaps, I thought,
people as disorganized and inattentive as I am shouldn't have dogs
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   What would life be like without the dog? No more hair on every
surface in our house, no more fleas, no more waking with the weight
of a 60-pound dog on my feet, no more veterinary fees, no more dog
sitters, no more 24-hour-a-day responsibility for another life.
Then I thought of lonely car rides, hikes in Vermont with only
human company, the loss of Pandy's warmth in our bed, an end to
early morning remember-me-I'm-ready-for-breakfast kisses. You make
a lifelong commitment when you adopt a dog, even if that dog can
feel like a mixed blessing if your name shows up in your local
newspaper's police log.
</P>
<P>
   I'm actually grateful that some woman cared enough about my dog
to report me. I like busybodies. I should. I am one, dropping
warnings about pesticides into people's mailboxes, slipping
reminders of the anti-idling law under violators' windshield
wipers. I believe we are each other's keepers, though I admit I
would have preferred a note on my windshield to a citation from the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is one merit of living in a small town. If I'm any
example, human nature is so seriously flawed that we occasionally
need other folks looking over our shoulder who will remind us of
our responsibilities. Although it may be disconcerting to be nudged
in the right direction when your attention wanders, it is also true
that chastisement is one of the ways a community shows that it
cares.
</P>
<P>
   To fiddle with the title of a sermon on Christians at our
Baptist church: Citizens aren't wrinkle-free. We all need pressing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
