<HEADLINE>
CONFEREES GET A BARGAIN ON PERSONAL ORGANIZER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN BERGER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sun Microsystems' JavaOne conference features
rooms full of computers with enough processing power to compile,
sort, collate and analyze every available piece of data on your
life, and use it to compute your life expectancy to the nanosecond.
</P>
<P>
   But the real hit of the show that opened Wednesday in San
Francisco was 3Com's Palm V, on sale to conference attendees for
$200, less than half the suggested retail price of $450.
</P>
<P>
   Called a ``connected organizer,'' it has a date book, supports
e-mail, holds to-do lists, memos and addresses, plays games and
resembles a ``Star Trek'' communicator (the original '60s version).
</P>
<P>
   And for a limited time only, it was half-price for everyone
attending JavaOne.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 Palm Vs have sold since the conference began
Tuesday, according to Curtis Sasaki, a director of product
marketing for Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The conference for Java developers kicked off with the
announcement that 3Com had licensed Java, a programming language
that runs on many different kinds of computer systems, for use in
its Palm Computing line of hand-held organizers. The Java II Micro
edition is aimed at the consumer electronics market, for products
like the Palm personal organizers and other small electronic
devices, including smart mobile phones to pocket-sized computers.
</P>
<P>
   The fire sale on the Palm V had a not-so-hidden agenda promoting
3Com's corporate purposes. By offering Java developers an
apparently irresistible discount on the Palm V, it hoped to get
more of them excited about developing software that runs on the new
Java II Micro edition platform.
</P>
<P>
   Like a personal computer or a home video game console, the Palm
V lives and dies on the strength of the software that developers
create for it. The theory is that putting the device into
consumers' hands _ and giving them their first peek at the Java II
Micro edition _ will get them to embrace 3Com's vision of the
device's potential.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, judging from both the buzz on the show floor and the
pace of sales, the strategy is working beyond expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not everyone was agog over the Palm V. David Smith of Rhode
Island-based American Power Conversion said that it seemed nice,
but he'd never really used a pocket organizer before.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a bargain at half the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't like it, I'll sell it to someone,'' he said, with a
shrug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
