<HEADLINE>
`SOCIAL CLUB' CATCHES THE VITALITY OF AFRO-CUBAN MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Buena Vista Social Club'' communicates the rapture of Ry
Cooder over the bubbling fusion of Afro-Cuban music in a single
scene. The camera tracks across a field to where Cooder sits on a
concrete abutment, which seems to be deteriorating before our eyes.
His head is down, down, he's puffing on one of Havana's finest
smokes, his eyes are closed and his head nods to a lovely, rhythmic
throb. As the camera closes in and enters the area, we see a
bassist and percussionist at work, slapping out a beguiling and
elegant beat. That's just one instance in which ``Buena Vista
Social Club'' shows that it's steeped in a sense of pleasure that
is rare in documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many documentary films about music have the earnest and
lifeless feel of the CD ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' for which
producer Cooder assembled the group of Cuban musical all-stars a
couple of years ago. The CD has the well-meaning drabness of an
archaeologist rebuilding a lost civilization _ an inability to get
across what attracted him to this stuff in the first place. But the
movie, directed by Wim Wenders, lets these robust, vital men, who
proudly bear in their faces the experience of having survived Cuba,
tell their own stories. As they explain how they work _ watching
the stylish old smoothie, vocalist Ibrahim Ferrer, chat is like
seeing a king restored to his natural place in the world _ and
their pleasure in jamming with each other is in evidence, we can
see why Cooder was drawn to them. That his affection for their
talents isn't the slightly patronizing notion of an archivist out
to commit their performances to tape for posterity. These cats are
the joint!
</P>
<P>
   Cooder, a superb musician in his own right, has a large,
camera-ready head that looks like it's struck for the side of a
coin. He's scored several films on his own, and unfortunately some
of the best of his music _ like his work on Walter Hill's
``Southern Comfort'' and the incidental score for ``Hearts of
Fire'' _ has never been released. He and Wenders have worked
together in the past, too. (Seek out the wonderful ``Paris, Texas''
soundtrack.) Unlike much of director Wenders' previous work,
``Social Club'' has the full-bodied zest of a director in love with
his subject.
</P>
<P>
   Wenders also displays an ease and authority, getting a warmth
and intimacy from the digital video cameras he used to shoot the
film that exploits what might be limits of the technology in the
hands of others. The mobility of the equipment makes the film light
on its feet, almost athletic. Nowhere is this kinetic aplomb more
apparent than in a sequence featuring a jam in a rotting hotel
ballroom as young dancers bounce around. The scene is simply
mesmerizing. The film ends with a triumphant session filmed in New
York, and ``Buena Vista Social Club'' is such a powerful and
involving film that it will make you rethink the musty good will of
the CD.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Buena Vista Social Club''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 5 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Wim Wenders
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ry Cooder, Ibrahim Ferrer, Compay Segundo
</P>
<P>
   Length: 101 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: G _ suitable for everyone's enjoyment; some of the film
is subtitled
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
