<HEADLINE>
DIVORCED PARENTS CAN HELP KIDS ENJOY VACATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (First of two parts.)
</P>
<P>
   For children whose divorced or separated parent doesn't live
nearby, summer can loom large. Whether they are two or 12, and even
if they are excited about seeing a far-away parent, they feel the
stress of change. For them, the most successful vacation visit
focuses on what they are capable of handling rather than on a
parent's need or a legal agreement.
</P>
<P>
   For the parents, this is no small order.
</P>
<P>
   It means that the distant parent who's dying to spend time with
his kids may have to settle for a shorter vacation than he wants or
one that isn't even on his turf, keeping the big picture in mind
rather than seeking short-term gratification. For the primary
parent, it means encouraging collaboration all year long and
tolerating flexibility around the vacation itself, including having
your ex-spouse on your territory.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sheehy of Hingham, Mass. and her ex-husband, Steve, who
lives in Seattle, could be the poster parents of how it can work.
</P>
<P>
   Susan moved from the West to the East Coast when their son,
John, was 4 1/2, two years after the divorce. In that first year of
transcontinental parenting, Steve would come east three or four
times a year to stay with friends or in a hotel and see John during
the day. In the second year, John went to Seattle, but only after
his father came here first, refreshing their collective memory of
what it was like to be together and then flying with him in both
directions. It was costly financially, says Steve, but worth it
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this was intuitive, believe me,'' he says. ``It just
seemed to make good sense for John. That's really all you can think
about. Neither Sue nor I wanted to do anything that would be too
disruptive for him.''
</P>
<P>
   With children 5 and under, that's key. Young children miss home
and routine sooner and with more intensity than we realize, says
psychotherapist Isolini Ricci, who heads the office of family court
services for the Family Court System of California.
</P>
<P>
   It's because they don't have the cognitive ability to hold two
different thoughts at once. ``They're immediate, concrete thinkers:
`If I can't see it, it's not there.' A 3-year-old knows there's a
mom, but if Mom isn't there, she's lost her anchor,'' she says.
That, along with changes in routines and unfamiliarity with the
physical place, can be so stressful for the 2- to 5-year-old that
Ricci does not even recommend an overnight visit with a parent a
child sees only infrequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a very sturdy child who is not only confident
in himself but can express feelings clearly _ and kids like this
are rare _ my recommendation is for the parent to come to the
child's town and spend a few days with him there. Even an overnight
at the hotel should be at his initiation, not yours: `Daddy, I want
to sleep with you!' '' she says. Ricci is author of an excellent
book for divorced parents, ``Mom's House, Dad's House (Revised
Edition)'' (Fireside Books).
</P>
<P>
   While this arrangement can be hard on a distant parent and even
harder on grandparents and relatives, don't take it personally,
says psychologist Carol Philpot of Florida Institute of Technology,
a specialist in issues of divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a reflection on you or on whether a child loves
you,'' she says. Even if you see your children three or four times
a year, she tells parents to expect to start each visit from
scratch. ``Children can be slow to warm up,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   If a child winces at your kiss or withers at your hug, it can be
incredibly hurtful, of course. But Philpot says if you push a child
of any age to accept your affection, she'll shut down. On the other
hand, if you offer no sign of affection, she may think you don't
love her. The solution is to tell her how you feel _ ``I'm so happy
to see you, I'd love to give you a hug and kiss!'' _ and ask
permission: ``Do you think that's OK, or would you rather I wait a
while?'' If she wants to wait, ask later in a playful kind of way:
``Any chance for that hug now?''
</P>
<P>
   It's through behavior that young children will likely show that
they're ready, perhaps snuggling closer as you read a book. ``If
you put your arm around her and she doesn't shrug it off, you're
golden,'' says Philpot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The older child
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The older child poses different challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime between 5 and 7, evolving cognition makes him better
able to connect his two worlds and tolerate being uprooted from his
primary home. Nonetheless, Ricci would wait for his initiation _
``I want to stay at your house!'' _ and keep visits short. John
Sheehy, for instance, at first spent only a week in Seattle,
gradually stretching it as he got older, until he was there six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Between 8 and 12, expect a child to want more to say about the
vacation, not just what you do but how long it is. Three years ago,
when John was 11, he no longer wanted to go for six weeks
altogether. He missed his friends. So he split his visit between
June and August. He'll do that again this year and take a friend
for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Steve can cope. ``It's not that I don't get jealous (of time not
spent with me),'' he says. ``But I'm glad he's comfortable enough
to bring friends. It's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal'' is an important operative word.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Anthony E. Wolf urges parents not to get caught up
in entertaining a visiting child. ``It sets up false expectations
and gets in the way of having a relationship that is nurturing and
close,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The more normal the activities, the better, especially at the
onset of the visit, including things like grocery shopping. Ricci
recommends walking the neighborhood together, not just to reorient
your child, but also to renegotiate boundaries, which may need to
change in response to increased maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal'' also refers to behavior. ``When children are with you
for a day or two, they can be on their best behavior; it's more
like they are a guest. When they are with you for an extended
period, however, you get the real thing, from sibling squabbling to
noncompliance and defiance,'' says Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   When there's behavior you've never seen, it can throw a parent.
``Don't make it your mission to shape these kids up,'' he says.
``Set appropriate limits, accept that this is what's normal, and be
grateful they are comfortable enough to be themselves. That
conflict increases between you and your kids or between siblings is
not necessarily a bad thing at all.'' Wolf is author of ``Why did
you have to get a divorce? And when can I get a hamster?'' (Farrar,
Straus and Giroux).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Homesickness
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As normal as things may seem to you, homesickness may strike.
While this is more likely with a 5- to 7-year-old at the start of
the first long visit, it can also happen to an older child because
he's discombobulated from the strain of travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had kids tell me that when they first get to the
parent's, their `insides feel jumbled,' '' says Ricci. ``I tell
them it's what happens when you make a big change.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of empathetic response is good for a parent, too.
Equally important is the ability to tolerate calls to the other
parent: ``Not, `You want to call your mother again? but: `I bet it
feels good to talk to your mom,' '' says Philpot. Wolf, however,
suggests the call be made during the day rather than at bedtime
when a child is typically most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Not only should you facilitate your child calling his other
parent, but you should be calling, too, says Philpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the times when collaboration in the child's
interest is so important,'' she says. Whether your child is
homesick or acting out, brainstorming with the other parent can
make a big difference: Is this behavior typical? What will make him
feel more comforable?
</P>
<P>
   John Sheehy's parents talk throughout the year as well as when
he is in Seattle, but Sue remembers one call in particular when
John was 6 or 7. ``Steve called to tell me he thought John was
worried about me, about how I was doing and whether I was lonely,''
she says. That made her able to bring the subject up with John and
to reassure him. Without Steve's call, the topic might or might not
have gotten addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, when he was 8, John called and wanted to come
home. ``I asked if he had talked to his dad about it; I said he
needed to do that,'' says Sue. ``Once he did, he was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing it's OK to call the other parent is what will keep calls
to a minimum, says family therapist Suzanne Midori Hanna of the
University of Louisville, a specialist in custodial issues. But
it's not just phone calls or e-mail to the other parent that help;
Ricci says kids need to stay in touch with friends, too. John
Sheehy echoes the thought: ``I would tell another kid: Pick some
friends you want to stay in touch with so that when you get back
you aren't saying, `Whoa, when did that happen?!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's a veteran of summer stays with his dad, and
even though he's always glad to get back to his mom and his school
routine, John says he also always needs a little time to make the
transition back to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad to know I won't see my dad for a long time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Next week: Getting your child ready to go.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended for toddlers, ``I Spy Little Book,''
rhymes by Jean Marzollo, photographs by Walter Wick.
(Scholastic/Cartwheel Books, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Even without a change in time zone, travel puts a strain on
children of all ages. Expect some fussiness as a result.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't assume children have the same likes and dislikes as the
last time you saw them. Ask: ``Do you still love pasta?''
</P>
<P>
   --Early in the vacation, go through photos from last year's
vacation together. It can speed the bonding.
</P>
<P>
   --If you've remarried, don't force the step-relationship, rather
allow it to develop at its own pace.
</P>
<P>
   --Help your children establish a network of friends in your
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). She
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
