<HEADLINE>
THE IMMERSION METHOD OF CLEANING SILVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I'm looking for the formula for cleaning silver by the
immersion method. I think it has something to do with an aluminum
pan. Do you have it?
</P>
<P>
   E. J., Jamaica Plain, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure do. And the aluminum pan, please. Place the silver in
the pan. Each piece must touch the pan. Bring to a boil a solution
of one tablespoon baking soda in a quart of water. Pour this
near-boiling solution over the silver. After several minutes,
remove the silver, rinse, and wipe dry.
</P>
<P>
   Do not use this method on glued silverware; the solution will
melt the glue. And, if some of your silver is black in deep
crevices of the pattern, do not use this method. That black
oxidation is there for a purpose: to highlight the relief. If this
oxidation is removed, the silver will appear washed out and the
pattern hardly visible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You suggested putting plastic sheeting on the dirt floor of a
crawl space to prevent water vapor from coming through the ground
and into the crawl space. I understand the need to do this, but
what kind of plastic? Can it be walked on?
</P>
<P>
   DONALD LAMBERT, Concord, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. Use polyethylene plastic, 6 mil thick. The 6-mil plastic is
hard to find, so you can use 4-mil instead. You can walk on it,
carefully, but not if it is over crushed stone or any sharpish
objects. If it is torn, it defeats its purpose of blocking water
vapor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The saga of those big gaps between floorboards continues.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing, too, because D. Martin of Dedham, Mass. told
us how to fix those gaps, or at least disguise them.
</P>
<P>
   He writes: ``Another solution for gaps in hardwood floors which
worked beautifully on our dark floor was to use Dark 'n Rich liquid
paste wax. It is liquid enough to seep into the gaps, especially if
used in the winter when the gaps are most obvious. A thin coat
applied, rubbed in with a rag, then buffed has concealed the gaps
in our dark floor . . . This elminates relaying the floor or any
sanding!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it sure would, and why didn't the handyman think of that?
But the key to success here is the darkness of the floors. The wax
darkened the wood in the gaps, disguising them. And if you do have
a dark floor, the paste wax is not necessary; you can apply an
ordinary penetrating stain to the sides and bottoms of the gaps,
with a similar result.
</P>
<P>
   Such a trick may not work for a light-colored floor, but if the
gaps are lighter than the floor because they are bare wood, then
varnishing them may darken them enough to disguise them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, D. Martin. Your idea goes right into the handyman's
super electronic file for future reference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've been having a discussion with friends, and have this to
ask: What are the stones on a tar-and-gravel roof for?
</P>
<P>
   WOODCHIPPER, Revere, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That's an easy one. The stones, called ballast, do two
things, which are closely related. It's a matter of protection. The
stones protect the tar underneath from the weather, and they
reflect heat, thus protecting the tar even further from getting too
hot and softening. The grit on asphalt shingles and roll roofing
does the same thing, in addition to providing the desired color.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am insulating my basement ceiling. Where does the vapor
barrier go? I'm also having a new burner installed. Can it be
vented through the side of the house, without a chimney?
</P>
<P>
   TED BRODERICK, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The vapor barrier, usually kraft paper backing on fiberglass
insulation, goes paper-side up, toward the rooms above. And that
makes it difficult to hang. To do so, insert insulation hangers,
sharp-pointed wires between joists, spaced about 24 inches apart.
Some people have put the insulation in backward, paper-side down,
because it is easier to do. While this is ``wrong,'' it may not
cause any condensation damage.
</P>
<P>
   As for the side-venting burner, you can do it if the burner has
a power vent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a man apply a semitransparent stain on my
pressure-treated deck. Places where he sprayed the stain look light
and washed out. Where he had to brush on the stain, the color is
darker and better. Can I have more stain applied to even out that
color?
</P>
<P>
   LAURIE DIODATI, Hull, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The difference in color and intensity is a good example of
the inadequacy of spraying. Brushing is better, unless the spray is
a high-pressure one, which yours obviously was not.
</P>
<P>
   You could try having the stain brushed onto the light areas.
That might not work because even a thin layer of stain cannot be
recoated. If the new stain beads up on the old, you cannot do it.
If the new stain soaks in, then go ahead and brush it on.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the new stain does bead up, while you cannot restain
immediately, you can wait a year or so for the sprayed stain to
wear off; then you can restain. With a brush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
