<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
June 18. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   SLAVE: While researching their genealogy in Missouri, two women
made a startling discovery. The ancestor of one had owned an
ancestor of the other, who was a slave. Now the two women _ from
Chicago and Seattle _ are using their ties to promote frank
discussion about race relations. They will travel the state this
summer presenting a talk called ``Entangled Lives: Facing Our
Slaveholding Past.'' A story about history and how it stays with
us. Their first presentation was in Jefferson City on June 11.
Oscar Avila. 30. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   REPARE (with SLAVE): Something called the Reparation Team of
Missouri is making plans for a national convention in St. Louis
this summer made up of groups and families seeking compensation for
slavery. Where does the reparation movement stand? And what drives
people who are pushing it? There is a bill in Congress that is
being debated on the subject. Convention starts Friday. Oscar
Avila. 18.
</P>
<P>
   DENTIST: Dentist Frank Meyer will be sentenced today for
Medicaid fraud. He overcharged and billed for procedures never
performed. Prosecutors say he gave children morphine and other
drugs without parental permission. Angry parents are expected to
testify at the hearing. The dentist may get from 10 months to 16
months. Ruth Igoe. 15.
</P>
<P>
   BENT: As part of his job as the plaintiff schoolchildren's
attorney in the Kansas City schools desegregation case, Arthur
Benson sends observers into the district to do a report. This
year's report, however, is less negative than earlier ones,
indicating some progress in improving curriculum. Phillip O'Connor
and Tanika White. 20.
</P>
<P>
   FATHER (will be late): National Center for Fathering awards
first-ever Dan Quisenberry Award Thursday night. City Fathers of
the year are Jim Caccamo and Buck O'Neil. Staff TBA. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-SHAKESPEARE: So, just how good was William Shakespeare,
anyway? Sure, he's the most-produced playwright in the
English-speaking world. He's also one of the hottest screenwriters
in Hollywood this year. His fictionalized love life was the subject
of last year's Oscar-winning film ``Shakespeare in Love.'' And,
yes, his plays have been translated into scores of languages. The
ubiquity of Shakespeare's work makes it clear: He must have been
doing something right. 54 inches. Derek Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   ORCHESTRA-MILLENIUM: Maybe every century has troubles with its
own music _ or at least some of it. Bach was criticized for
excessive complexity, Mozart for harmonic weirdness, Beethoven for
unruliness. But nothing in history has prepared us for the deep and
enduring hostility of concertgoing audiences toward large chunks of
20th-century music. 33 inches. Scott Cantrell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
