<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9245 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     06-17 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A '90S GUY? HERO GETS MAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you didn't spend your innocent youth mowing through Claire
Bee's books about America's most clean-cut sports hero, here's a
quick description:
</P>
<P>
   Chip Hilton was the greatest sports hero ever. A student at
Valley Falls High School (and in later, lesser books, at State
College), he was the embodiment of squeaky-clean achievement. He
excelled at every sport. He was an excellent student. He had an
after-school job. He didn't get into trouble. He loved his mother,
who raised him by herself after his father (another sports hero)
died. No plot was too hokey, and Chip always did the right thing in
the end.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't he make you want to puke?
</P>
<P>
   Not when you're a kid, he doesn't. Problem is, Bee wrote these
books in the &UR; 1940s and '50s. They didn't age well. Chip's friend
Speed, for instance, drove a jalopy. Not exactly contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   A small publishing company is doing something about that. It's
republishing the books and modernizing them. Speed, for instance,
is now Black and drives a Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough. If we're really going to pull Chip into
the late '90s, we'll need to replace titles like ``Hoop Crazy'' and
``Clutch Hitter!'' with these:
</P>
<P>
   Papa's Got a Brand New Bag: Chip turns counselor when he
discovers Soapy has run into some paternity problems. ``I can't
make the game next week because I can't get a baby-sitter for my
son,'' he tells Chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you're our point guard, Soapy,'' Chip says, ``and . . .
wait, I thought you had a daughter. With Nancy, the head
cheerleader. You remember the scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ``do'' have a daughter with Nancy,'' Soapy replies. ``I also
have a son with Beth. I may be having another one with Ellen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Soapy, you're taking your adoration of Shawn Kemp too far,''
Chip says, before asking his mother to baby-sit for Soapy's son and
scheduling him for family-planning classes at the local clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing With Myself: Chip and his buddies on the baseball team
go in together on a hotel room for the after-prom party. Chip
repeats to his mom the story Biggie and Lefty tell their parents _
the girls will have a room where they sip sodas and gossip, while
we guys will have a place to play cards and talk about sports.
</P>
<P>
   Things turn sour for Chip when he realizes this isn't really
what the other kids have in mind. ``You mean I ``lied'' to my
mom?'' he shrieks in a crucial confrontation with Biggie. Upset by
the deception and disgusted with the intended purpose for which the
kids plan to use the room, Chip rats on his pals to the baseball
coach, who tells the other kids' parents. Chip, meanwhile, goes
stag to the prom, where he is beaten up by Biggie and Lefty while
the rest of the students (and some of the chaperones) cheer. All is
forgiven in time for Monday's big game.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Agent Man: After a stellar sophomore season with the
State College basketball team, Chip faces the toughest decision of
his life _ whether to turn pro early. At first the prospect of a
million-dollar contract pales in comparison to his promise to his
mother that he would complete his education. But when an
underhanded agent begins illegally wooing Chip with the promise of
unlimited cars, mansions and women, he rethinks his commitment.
``Don't worry,'' he promises his distraught mother, ``one of my
tattoos will be a picture of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Sides Now: Chip learns a valuable lesson in diversity when
Speed, alone with Chip in the shower after practice, declares his
love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you too, Speed,'' Chip replies. ``You're like a brother
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not ``that'' kind of love,'' Speed says. ``The other kind.''
</P>
<P>
   After several more explanations, it finally dawns on a horrified
Chip what Speed is saying. ``I'm sorry, Speed,'' he says, ``but I'm
afraid I could never have that kind of relationship with you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm a guy?'' Speed pleads. ``Because I'm . . .
different?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Chip says. ``Because I've never, in any of these books,
had even a hint of that kind of relationship with anyone, male or
female.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good point,'' a relieved Speed says and heads for his locker. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
