<HEADER>
A9252 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TARZAN-TEX     06-17 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TARZAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VINE KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the first few beats of tribal drums beneath Walt Disney
Pictures' familiar Cinderella castle logo, you know you're in for
something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' immediately immerses you in its world, where we're
introduced to two different families _ an enterprising couple and
their baby trying to survive in the jungle after a violent
shipwreck, as well as a group of gorillas led by the imposing
Silverback, Kerchak. Both clans are devastated by a bloodthirsty
leopard when the beast makes a quick meal of a runaway baby gorilla
_ leaving its mother, Kala, childless. It then turns on the human
couple _ leaving an infant Tarzan motherless.
</P>
<P>
   The stage is beautifully set, and much as in 1994's ``The Lion
King,'' all within the refrains of the opening song _ ``Two
Worlds,'' one of five new tunes crafted for the film by
vocalist/percussionist Phil Collins.
</P>
<P>
   But three deaths in the first 10 minutes of the movie? It may
seem like tough stuff for the folks who brought you fluffy fun like
``The Aristocats'' and ``A Goofy Movie.'' Although the studio used
to settle for kinder and gentler cartoons, Disney animation is in
the midst of a sophisticated growth spurt.
</P>
<P>
   Films like ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame'' and last year's
``Mulan'' have tapped into something more substantial than singing
candlesticks and dancing sea creatures _ not that ``Tarzan''
doesn't have its share of warm fuzziness. But the picture feels
like the beginning of a new breed of animated pictures, the kind of
movies adults will seek out, rather than attending as the reluctant
chaperons to their overeager children.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows Tarzan's growth after he is rescued from the
leopard by Kala (voiced sweetly by Glenn Close) and raised in the
gorilla family, much to the consternation of Kerchak (brought to
life perfectly with Lance Henriksen's booming, gravelly voice).
</P>
<P>
   As a young man (voiced sparingly, but effectively, by Tony
Goldwyn), Tarzan has become as agile as a monkey and almost as
strong as his surrogate gorilla father. But his world is about to
change when he comes across a new breed of jungle creature: humans.
</P>
<P>
   Enter gorilla expert Professor Porter (Nigel Hawthorne), his
headstrong daughter Jane (Minnie Driver, in a hilarious turn) and
their trigger-happy jungle guide, Clayton (Brian Blessed). Tarzan
quickly finds himself torn between these two worlds, cautious about
protecting his family from the intruders, yet anxious to introduce
his eager new friends to his other life _ a move that will surely
bring trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Along for comic relief are Tarzan's animal buddies, Terk, a
wiseacre female gorilla voiced by Rosie O'Donnell, and Tantor, an
accident-prone elephant voiced by former ``Seinfeld'' star Wayne
Knight.
</P>
<P>
   While fans of Tarzan creator Edgar Rice Burroughs might take
exception to Disney's liberties with the story, they can't help but
be pleased with the ape man's stunningly agile performance, pulled
off with the help of the amazing new ``Deep Canvas'' technique,
which allows the two-dimensional Tarzan to swing through a
hand-painted, three-dimensional background that meshes together
seemlessly.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of Disney's best-looking cartoon features to date.
Thanks to the film's heightened pace, unobtrusive musical numbers
and engaging vocal performances, ``Tarzan'' promises to be a strong
contender for king of the box office jungle.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Tarzan''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Tony Goldwyn, Minnie Driver, Rosie O'Donnell
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Kevin Lima and Chris Buck
</P>
<P>
   Length: 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: G _ suitable for all audiences, though there are some
moments that might frighten younger children
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
