<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF SIZZLE AT ITALIAN CAR DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say the names out loud:
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   Maserati.
</P>
<P>
   Lamborghini.
</P>
<P>
   Alfa Romeo.
</P>
<P>
   There is something evocative just in their sound.
</P>
<P>
   Now picture a couple hundred of them arrayed on a sprawling lawn
on a hot Sunday in June with a few thousand auto enthusiasts
milling about. You could call it an auto show. I prefer to call it
an art exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The event was the Tutto Italiano, the fourth annual Italian Car
Day Lawn Show at the Museum of Transportation in Brookline, Mass.,
and, owing to the presence of so many Ferraris, the dominant color
was red.
</P>
<P>
   So much red on all that green lawn. So many cool curves of
fender, curls of chrome, sharp edges, gentle rises. And that's only
on the outside. Inside, all that leather arrayed like fine
furniture, instrumentation like fancy watches, handles and knobs
and switches gleaming like expensive kitchen gadgets. So much art.
</P>
<P>
   And none of this by accident, because this is, after all, what
the designers of Italian autos do. Producing formidable power and
handling is left to the engineers; the designers are mandated to
produce works of art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aesthetics mean a lot to them,'' says Neal Heffron, a
Brookline collector who, with wife Susan, owns two Ferraris and an
Alpha Romeo.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, when you look at a Ferrari or Maserati that you
just know will sizzle out on the pavement, you also get the sense
you are looking at something more. It might be the feeling you get
when looking at sculpted leather chairs from Design Centro Italia,
or cutlery from Firenze.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour of Ford design headquarters last month, Jac Nasser,
the Ford's chief executive, was heard by a Wall Street Journal
reporter telling his designers that he wanted them to know what the
furniture in Americans' homes looks like; what their kitchen
appliances look like.
</P>
<P>
   And that is precisely the point that Italian designers latched
onto years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Nuccio Bertone designed his first Alfa Romeo, he was
referred to not as a designer, but as a coachbuilder.
</P>
<P>
   Battista Farina, born in 1893 in Turin, Italy, designed his
first car at 17 _ the Fiat Zero. At 27 years old, the childhood
nickname ``Pinin'' having stuck, he turned down Henry Ford's offer
to go to work in Detroit and instead teamed up in Italy with
Vincenzo Lancia.
</P>
<P>
   Today, under the tag Pininfarina, you see the results of this
late artist's works everywhere _ most notably, of course, on
Ferraris. But the name Pininfarina, Heffron points out, is also now
associated with even pens and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   When you think style and think Italian, you can relate the
thought to furniture, clothes, shoes, neckties _ and superbly
designed sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Walking the lawn at Brookline last week, it was hard not to be
struck by how many elements of all that Italian craftsmanship have
shown up down the years on other autos.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the 1964 Alpha Romeo Zagato Milano. With its sloping
hood and slightly clipped rear, it reminds you of the Nissan Z. And
then you notice, on the front quarterpanel just behind the wheel
well, the big Z. Curious.
</P>
<P>
   Noses and tails and grilles and fender lines and so many of them
make you wonder: Where else have I seen this?
</P>
<P>
   Picture a 1999 Corvette convertible, the lowest and sleekest
model yet. Now picture it beside a 1999 Ferrari F355 Spider.
</P>
<P>
   (If you want to play this game, pick up the June 1999 issue of
duPont Registry in the auto section at your nearest magazine rack).
</P>
<P>
   Compare any of the latest models of the Accura NXS with the 1999
Ferrari F355 TB.
</P>
<P>
   The 1985 Maserati Quattroporte? Picture the formerly sharp-edge,
chunky Audis before their rounding off.
</P>
<P>
   Go back in time even more and think of early 1960s Lincolns and
Buicks. Then stroll across the lawn to see the 1961 325 Dual-Ghia.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fun game to play: Haven't I seen you somewhere before?
</P>
<P>
   And it has its surprises.
</P>
<P>
   In what evidence suggests may have been a reverse derivation
there is the 1963 Maserti 3500, looking remarkably like the 1957
Ford Thunderbird.
</P>
<P>
   Did those bulbous fenders on the 1968 Alpha Romeo T33 Stradale
(the latter term meaning ``street'' as in this is a race car made
street legal) influence, say, designers of the new Audi TT or the
Dodge Viper GTS?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Battista ``Pinin'' Farina must be chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's email address is ford(at)Globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
