<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARRISH-EXHIBIT-2TAKE     06-17 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARRISH-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAXFIELD PARRISH: LUSH IDYLLS IN NEVER-NEVER LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa. N.H., N.Y.)   (editors: exhibit notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In 1925 a New York printing company called the
House of Art estimated that one of its best-selling products, a
lithograph of Maxfield Parrish's painting ``Daybreak,'' could be
found in one of every four American homes. Even allowing for a
titanic dose of hype, the statistic rings true. Like apple pie, the
flag and indoor plumbing, ``Daybreak'' was, indeed, an American
fixture.
</P>
<P>
   So was Parrish himself. He was an art machine. He turned out
countless paintings, many of them intended for print reproduction.
His images appeared in books and advertisements, on posters,
magazine covers, calendars, jigsaw puzzles and candy boxes.
Together they made him one of the country's first brand-name
artists, and they helped define the mood and style of an era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maxfield Parrish, 1870-1966,'' which opens Saturday at the
Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts in Philadelphia, is a
first-time look at the full range of a career that, almost
preposterously, stretched from the Victorian Gilded Age of the
1880s to the Pop world of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   An example of almost every kind of thing the Philadelphia-born
artist did is here, from a hand-decorated ukulele to a nude
photographic self-portrait, to the original oil-on-board version of
``Daybreak,'' a classical fantasy bathed in pastel light, which
fetched a cool $4.2 million when it was sold at Sotheby's a few
years ago. Despite formal variety, however, Parrish's work boils
down to just a few general themes.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is the fairy-tale narrative, comical or romantic,
set in Old World Europe, Colonial America or some exotic Middle
Easternish never-never land. Parrish often used such images for
private commissions. (His mural of Old King Cole, now installed in
the bar of the St. Regis hotel in Manhattan, is an example.) But
much of it appeared in book illustrations that show him working at
his inventive best.
</P>
<P>
   Another motif, one for which Parrish was celebrated in his day,
is the pastoral tableau. It often includes a gardenlike setting
populated by pre-pubescent girls and young women. The atmosphere is
idealizing (lots of classical pillars and pots) but also
genteel-erotic (sheer Grecian gowns galore). And the palette is
outlandish: an acid-bath mix of sulfuric-yellow, copper-orange and
what came to be dubbed Maxfield Parrish blue.
</P>
<P>
   The most extravagant example of this theme is a 50-foot-long
glass-chip mosaic titled ``Dream Garden,'' designed by Parrish,
executed by the Louis Comfort Tiffany studios in New York and
installed in the lobby of the Curtis Publishing building,
birthplace of Ladies Home Journal, in Philadelphia in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of those staggeringly elaborate visual trifles, at
once delicate and gross, of which Parrish and Tiffany were masters.
No one traveling to Philadelphia should miss it, particularly as
the mosaic recently came very close to being sold and removed from
its site. (Casino mogul Steven Wynn of Bellagio fame was the
purchaser who backed off after local preservationists protested the
sale.) Its future is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Everything Parrish did was an exercise in conspicuous
virtuosity. He developed his expertise at the Pennsylvania Academy
itself, where he was enrolled from 1892 to 1894, and even as a
student he was fixated on the challenges of craft.
</P>
<P>
   Early on he created entire drawings from stippled ink dots, a
kind of hand-done Benday effect, and he invented a time-consuming
painting method based on repeated glazing. He built his own frames
and packing crates and lettered his shipping labels in pretty
calligraphy. He contructed minute objects _ elf-size chairs,
tabletop houses and castles _ as models. He took photographs of
people and places for his photo-dependent work.
</P>
<P>
   He lacked, or suppressed, any natural feel for paint as an
expressive substance, or for organic composition. He was a
pictorial organizer, with a watchmaker's hand and the mind of a
computer programmer who, through adding, revising and patching,
gets every link and command in just the right place to produce a
preordained result.
</P>
<P>
   Given his high-precision bent, it's no wonder he was fascinated
with the technology of mechanical reproduction. Aubrey Beardsley
and other artists in England had elevated the printed poster to a
respectable art form by the 1890s. Book and magazine illustrations
earned a similar cachet as the American Arts and Crafts movement
gained momentum, in part as a reaction to continental modernist
trends like Impressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish's reputation was secured by a cover he designed for
Century Magazine. And he genuinely relished his role as popular
artist, never viewing himself as a genius painter condescending to
do graphic work. (``I'm hopelessly commonplace,'' he once said.) He
actually conceived many of his paintings with an eye to how they
would look as prints.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia show, which has been organized by Sylvia Yount,
chief curator at the academy, pays particular attention to
painting, probably in part because it is still the medium of which
heavyweight shows are made, but also because Parrish's work, much
of it now in fragile condition, is seldom seen.
</P>
<P>
   He first explored the chromatic possibilities of pigment when he
visited Arizona; the light-drenched mountains of the Southwest
became part of his stock image pool. But most of his high-color
work came after his permanent move to the artists' colony in
Cornish, N.H., in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   In New England he found the idyllic, all-purpose settings that
served for the ubiquitous ``Daybreak'' and for the annual
promotional calendars he designed for Edison Mazda Lamps. He did
dozens of these, all with a sylphlike woman in a landscape: in the
1930 version, titled ``Ecstasy,'' she stands poised on a cliff,
wind blown and exultant, a New Woman perched like a supermodel on
an Aegean headland.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   By this point, Parrish's paintings and prints were physically
hard to tell apart, even up close. ``Mary, Mary, Quite Contrary,''
the oil-on-board painting for the Ferry's Seeds package, for
example, is so smoothly brushed as to be textureless, and the
lettering below the image, though painted by hand, looks print
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Such trompe l'oeil realism played a part in his popularity.
Americans have always had a thing for illusionist painters, from
William M. Harnett to Andrew Wyeth to Superrealism in the 1970s.
But Parrish's work also seems to have struck some strong
psychological chords.
</P>
<P>
   His larky women and his serious, sybilline girls (his daughter,
Jean, was often the model and posed for ``Mary, Quite Contrary'')
looked reassuringly benign in an early 20th century made jumpy by
Freudian revelations of the power of sex. His freeze-dried Arcadias
were a balm to many in the rapidly industrializing, urbanizing
America of the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s Parrish's harping on dreams, myths, make-believe
and the bliss of childhood bathed grim social realities in an
escapist haze. And one can easily imagine that his 1940s depictions
of farmhouses, sitting serene under a full moon, lights shining in
their windows, were like an I'll-be-home-for-Christmas lullaby to a
country at war.
</P>
<P>
   In the postwar years Parrish's reputation plummeted. His
association with commerce was suddenly suspect. His images began to
look like the calculated, anti-modern pastiches they were. His last
painting, appropriately titled ``Getting Away From It All'' and
done in 1961 when he was 91, is truly, deeply weird, a kind of
surreal version of 19th-century Luminism.
</P>
<P>
   Here the farmhouse has turned into a teensy frontier cabin,
dripping icicles and glowing like a blast furnace. The setting is a
surreal mountain landscape, part Rockies, part Mars. The snowy
surfaces have the look of sugar sprinkled on molten steel, and a
leafy New Hampshire tree pops up smack in the center as if spliced
in by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But it was just such trippy images that brought Parrish back
into vogue in the acid-dropping, poster-loving, Pop Art '60s. (Andy
Warhol was a big fan.) And his exoticisms have gained a New Age
following: the singer Enya adapted one of his images for an album
cover, and his paintings are hot collector's items in Hollywood
(George Lucas owns one), where special-effects wizardry of all
kinds is much admired.
</P>
<P>
   Even the art world has come around from the days when a Clement
Greenberg could peer down on the likes of Parrish from a great
height and dismissively thunder, ``Kitsch!'' A recent exhibition of
Victorian fairy painting at the Frick Collection in New York, a
traveling Norman Rockwell survey scheduled to open at the High
Museum in Atlanta in November and arrive at the Guggenheim in 2001,
and the scholarly catalog that accompanies the Pennsylvania Academy
show are all evidence that popular art is being seriously examined
and appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Examination is always a smart idea: art is packed with
information, often hidden, about who made it, who valued it and
why. Appreciation is trickier. Nostalgia, which is what Parrish's
work is about, is a powerful emotion, feel-good seductive but also
potentially dangerous, and something to be particularly wary of at
a conservative, self-satisfied moment in American art and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maxfield Parrish, 1870-1966'' is a chance to check out both
sides of the coin. It's definitely a gas, and its hefty gift shop
should probably be considered part of the show. But what makes
Parrish interesting is that for more than a century Americans have
 &UR; found &LR;  him interesting. His work still has sweet-tooth pleasures
aplenty, but it is also a mirror on which, however briefly, to
dwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maxfield Parrish, 1870-1966'' opens Saturday at the
Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts, 118 N. Broad St.,
Philadelphia, (215) 972-7600, and remains through Sept. 25. The
exhibition is organized by the Academy and the American Federation
of Arts and sponsored by the Henry Luce Foundation and Mellon Bank.
The show travels to the Currier Gallery of Art in Manchester, N.H.
(Nov. 6 through Jan. 23, 2000); the Memorial Art Gallery of the
University of Rochester (Feb. 19 through April 30, 2000) and the
Brooklyn Museum of Art (May 26 through Aug. 6, 2000).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
