<HEADLINE>
DOC HOLLIDAY, EARPS WILL BE `TRIED' FOR MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a century after the gun smoke cleared, Americans still
are fascinated. Movies, books, Web sites _ all still wrestle with
the enduring controversy surrounding one of the most famous
shootouts in the Wild West.
</P>
<P>
   The gunfight at the OK Corral in Tombstone took 27 seconds and
about 30 shots. Three people died. Doc Holliday and Wyatt Earp were
arrested but never tried.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, prominent Arizona attorneys and judges will stage a
public ``trial'' to determine what really happened in that rowdy
southern Arizona mining town in 1881.
</P>
<P>
   An all-star legal team _ including Arizona's assistant U.S.
attorney and a 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals judge _ are
bringing the case to court at the Phoenician Resort on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   Holliday and Earp will be tried in the slaying of Tom McLaury.
Much of the testimony will be based on actual transcripts from an
official inquest held after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt Earp of Phoenix, the great grandnephew of Wyatt S. Earp _
and who is said to bear a strong physical resemblance to his
namesake _ will take the role of his famous ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Patricia Lee Refo, one of the trial organizers,
said prosecutors and defense attorneys have worked months to
prepare real strategies to argue a fictional civil suit filed by
McLaury's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the audience will act as the jury. They will issue a
verdict that could answer the century-old question: Who really
started the fight?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a zillion Web sites still today devoted to what
really happened at the OK Corral,'' Refo said. ``There are books
still being written about it, movies still being made about it and
arguments still being had over whose fault it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Counsel for Mrs. McLaury will be Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael
Johns and Flagstaff lawyer Deborah Fine. Phoenix attorneys Ed
Hendricks and Jeffrey Willis will represent the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses include Holliday's lady friend, Big Nose Kate, played
by Judge Bethany Hicks of Maricopa County Superior Court. Former
Phoenix Mayor Terry Goddard will testify as Ike Clanton. Patricia
White, dean of Arizona State University's School of Law, will be
the grieving Mrs. McLaury.
</P>
<P>
   Although the case will be as historically accurate as possible,
modern technology will bring it to life.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-generated animation will be used to re-enact the
shootout, and images of the exhibits will be displayed on courtroom
monitors. The jury members _ or audience _ will cast their votes
using interactive electronic technology.
</P>
<P>
   The half-day trial is part of the State Bar of Arizona's annual
convention. The public is welcome to attend; tickets are $125 and
may be purchased by calling (602) 340-7308. &QL; 
Victoria Harker can be reached at (602) 444-8058 or at
victoria.harker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
