</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GENERALSDAUGHTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIDEOUS KINKY: TASTELESS THRILLER WASTES FINE TRAVOLTA PERFORMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Travolta is so vivid an actor, and his emotional life in
movies is so deep that to see him do what he does in ``The
General's Daughter'' is almost a revelation. Walking through the
picture as Paul Brenner, a military intelligence officer
investigating the particularly outlandish murder of a female
captain who turns out to be the daughter of a general with
political aspirations, Travolta gives off a spirit of acceptance.
After a career of playing characters who feel deeply _ in some
cases, maybe too deeply _ Travolta for the first time acts with a
sense of showy nonchalance. In one exchange, he says, ``My father
was a drunk, a gambler and a womanizer. ... I worshipped him.''
He's never had the chance to dry out his material in this way
before. Not even in ``Get Shorty,'' where the role was as much
about his delivery as it was about the dialogue. Some of the lines
here are the best material he's ever had. He's doing Bogart.
</P>
<P>
   If Brenner had been written as a man of deep cynicism who was
using the military as a way to create a career for himself, maybe
``Daughter'' would seem less opportunistic, less a movie willing to
do anything for an effect. But instead, ``The General's Daughter''
takes the easy way out. Travolta goes on about integrity and honor,
and you wonder how he manages to make these speeches without
laughing. It's a garish and obscenely over-directed thriller/buddy
movie. In ``Daughter,'' the buddy is a woman _ somebody's idea of
enlightenment, no doubt _ Sarah Sunhill (Madeleine Stowe), another
Criminal Investigation Division officer. And the staging of the
murder is baroque. The victim, Capt. Elisabeth Campbell (Leslie
Stefanson) is found naked, spread-eagled and tied to stakes. It's
such a freakish crime scene that you may find it hard to
concentrate on anything else as the investigation takes place.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects are, of course, everybody in the movie, including
her father, Gen. Joe Campbell (James Cromwell). After Travolta and
Stowe bounce from one suspect to another, ``Daughter,'' set in the
sweltering South, attempts to blend the outrageousness of Tennessee
Williams with a murder mystery. James Woods is the victim's
commanding officer, who seems to be hiding enough information to
fill another movie. With his wolfish sneer and flamboyant contempt,
Woods, to quote a line used about him in the 1981 film
``Eyewitness,'' was born a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest scenes in the movie don't even revolve around the
climax, since the eventual reasons behind the murder are so
ridiculous. Instead, the most watchable scenes are between Travolta
and Woods, which are all about a perverse exhibit of machismo and
the psychological game of one-upmanship they play.
</P>
<P>
   Though much of the movie, as directed by Simon West (who
directed ``Con Air,'' perhaps one of the stupidest, most
ostentatious pictures ever made), has a lurid one-upmanship going
on as well. It's as if he's compelled to upstage the plot: e.g.,
``Daughter'' features one of the most insanely overdone rape scenes
ever committed to film _ it's as if rape isn't vile enough on its
own, and West has to raise the stakes. And the tacked-on legend
about life in the military for women is a real violation. As if,
with all of the news over the past few years of what women have had
to suffer at the hands of superior officers, we need half-baked
fiction to draw our attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The General's Daughter''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Simon West
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: John Travolta, Madeleine Stowe
</P>
<P>
   Length: 115 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language, violence, nudity and a rape scene
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
