<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINEMAN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY SINGER SWINGS THROUGH PANTHEON OF POP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Apart from their shared penchant for white shoes,
David Bowie and Burt Bacharach aren't exactly musical twin sons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in her impressive new cabaret act, Karen Fineman manages to
yoke the two icons, confiding that as a teen-ager her gods were the
Thin White Duke and the World's Coolest Man.
</P>
<P>
   Fineman's pantheistic approach to pop music serves her well. In
her too-brief run last week at the Cinegrill in Hollywood, she
neatly balanced breezy, romantic sophistication, a la Bacharach,
with the husky, hard-edged sensuality of a '70s rock 'n' roll bad
girl. Though a respiratory ailment forced the L.A.-bred singer to
cancel two shows, on Saturday Fineman fearlessly pushed her voice
toward high-pitched emotional disclosures before slamming on the
brakes and touching down for graceful landings.
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished Broadway musical performer (``Les Miserables,''
``City of Angels''), Fineman probably is best-known in her hometown
for playing opposite Jason Alexander in the 1997 Reprise! concert
version of the 1968 Bacharach-Hal David hit ``Promises, Promises.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Cinegrill, she reprised that show's title song, along
with ``I'll Never Fall in Love Again'' and ``Knowing When to
Leave,'' confidently handling Bacharach's tortuous time signatures
and imparting a sadder-but-wiser feel to these uptempo tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off with a resilient rendition of ``Something's
Coming,'' she rolled through a challenging, well-paced set that
suggested what the Broadway musical needs now isn't love, sweet
love, but more rhythmic muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the steady quartet of guitarist Jay Condiotti, drummer
Mark Z. Stevens, bassist Trey Henry and musical director Michael
Orland on piano, Fineman brought a wailing bluesiness to numbers
like ``I Dreamed a Dream,'' the quasi-rock anthem from ``Les Miz''
and a slow erotic sizzle to ``Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   She also demonstrated a welcome willingness to showcase
contemporary songwriters like Lindy Robbins and John Bochino, the
best of which was a suddenly single woman's poignantly ironic plea
to a Starbucks latte boy to ``bring me java, bring me joy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
