<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-HNS &LR;      06-17 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MEDIA COMPANY FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON, JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 and SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a move that could result in dramatic changes
in the media marketplace here, the owners of the San Francisco
Chronicle and KRON-TV have authorized the sale of the parent
company, Chronicle Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing had told its investment bankers ``to
explore the sale of all or some of the company,'' a spokesman said.
The statement was released after a 3 1/2-hour meeting of the
company's board of directors Wednesday in a conference room of the
134-year-old Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Editor Matt Wilson and Managing Editor Jerry Roberts,
meeting with the newspaper's staff soon afterward, said an
``incremental step'' had been taken in a process that would unfold
over several months, at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing consists of three newspapers, three
television stations, a cable television station, two book
publishing companies and an on-line information service. It employs
3,200 people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources familiar with the private deliberations Wednesday
said the vote to sell was 9 to 0, with one director absent. The
sources said the board expressed no preference as to whether the
company should be sold in its entirety or in parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no conflict. I think people have accepted this as an
inevitability,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   The investment banker authorized to sell the company, Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities of New York, said there were several
prospective buyers. They reportedly include the General Electric
Co., owner of the NBC television network; Fox; Gannett Co. Inc.;
Knight Ridder; the New York Times Co.; the News Corp.; and the
Hearst Corp., which owns San Francisco's evening newspaper, the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The source declined to cite an asking price but said it would be
closer to $2 billion than $3 billion. If the company were sold in
its entirety, Chronicle Publishing's 44 shareholders would have to
approve the sale, but individual assets may be sold at the board's
discretion, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Previous estimates of the value of the Chronicle Publishing Co.
have ranged from $1.5 billion to $3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Chronicle and the Examiner have shared all
business costs and split revenues while maintaining editorially
separate operations, under a joint operating agreement commonly
referred to as a JOA.
</P>
<P>
   The JOA grants Hearst the right of first refusal in any sale of
the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing's decision to hire Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette was announced May 10 by the company's chief executive
officer, John Sias.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good market now and a dynamic period,'' said
shareholder Francis A. ``Rani'' Martin II, who formerly headed
KRON-TV Channel 4, an NBC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   John Morton, president of Morton Research Inc., a Silver Spring,
Md., media consulting company, said: ``It's a seller's market. I
have no doubt the company would be snatched up. Nine times out 10,
this ends up in a sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette will now create a prospectus that
outlines Chronicle Publishing's financial condition, Morton said,
and companies will then be given a period of time to bid.
</P>
<P>
   A Chronicle shareholder who attended the board meeting Wednesday
and spoke on condition of anonymity said he would not let sentiment
stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never fall in love with a business,'' the shareholder
said. ``There comes a time to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff members had anticipated the development and they
took it in stride Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Steven Rubenstein said the mood of the newspaper's
staff of more than 350 was apprehensive but far from bleak. Many
people joked about their employer's fate and their own; many also
resolved to bring as much dedication to their jobs as they have in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Hall, a Chronicle reporter and president of the
journalists' union, the Newspaper Guild, believes it will be months
before a decision to sell is made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should all try to stay calm and do our jobs,'' Hall said.
``We have a union with solid agreements and strong protections
through 2005,'' when the JOA expires. ``The business realities and
legal and union realities are rather complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing is owned by descendants of co-founder
Michael H. de Young, or the legal trusts of those descendants. De
Young and his brother Charles founded the newspaper in San
Francisco in 1865, 22 years before William Randolph Hearst acquired
the Examiner, his first newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Chronicle and KRON-TV, the company owns ABC
and NBC affiliates in Wichita, Kan., and Omaha, Neb. It owns two
other newspapers, the Bloomington Pantagraph in Illinois and the
Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing also owns the on-line service SFGate, cable
news channel BayTV and two book publishers: MBI in Wisconsin and
Chronicle Books in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers have speculated that KRON-TV may command up
to $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the Chronicle newspaper is more speculative,
sources said, because of its binding legal and financial
relationship with Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Morton estimated that the newspaper could sell for $400 million
to $1 billion. He based his estimate on recent sales of other
properties with comparable circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Chronicle Publishing Co. and the Hearst Corp. are
privately owned and neither discloses its financial data, but the
publisher of company profiles, Hoover's, estimated that Chronicle
Publishing's sales totaled $485 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst _ one of the nation's largest media companies, with
holdings that include newspapers, magazines and television stations
_ has expressed a strong interest in acquiring its morning
newspaper competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say officials of both organizations have been in contact
for several years, discussing scenarios under which the Examiner
would acquire its rival.
</P>
<P>
   No deal has been made in the past, however, because Chronicle
Publishing shareholders controlling a majority of the company's
stock were believed to oppose such a sale. That has changed in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been generally recognized by people in the business that
two-thirds of Chronicle family members have been ready to sell if
the price is right,'' said Ben Bagdikian, dean emeritus of the
Graduate School of Journalism at the University of California at
Berkeley. ``These days, prices are super-right.''
</P>
<P>
   A sale to Hearst would be reviewed by the Department of Justice.
Federal antitrust laws generally require the divestment of multiple
media outlets in the same market, although Chronicle Publishing has
an exemption permitting it to own the newspaper and TV station.
</P>
<P>
   Paid circulation of the Chronicle for the six-month period
ending March 31 was 475,244 Monday through Friday, and 435,792 on
Saturday, according to the independent newspaper auditing company,
the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   Like many major metropolitan dailies, including the Examiner,
the Chronicle's circulation has declined in recent years. In 1986,
the Chronicle's paid circulation was 551,545 Monday through Friday
and 500,747 on Saturday, according to the ABC. The evening
Examiner's daily circulation is 121,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
