<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TARZAN-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-17 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARZAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TARZAN': MONKEY BUSINESS _ REWRITING THE JUNGLE BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every age gets the ``Tarzan'' it deserves, from the gung-ho
jungle swinger of Johnny Weissmuller's day to the culture-shocked
repatriated Englishman of the 1984 ``Greystoke: The Legend of
Tarzan, Lord of the Apes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for the Disney version: a supple long-haired hunk
who so benefits from inter-species adoption that he thinks of
himself as a differently abled ape. ``I'll be the best ape ever!''
this young Tarzan declares, courting the same A for attitude to
which the movie itself aspires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best ape ever'' is a tall order. But it's nothing compared
with the film's own challenge of bringing new life to such
overworked material (this is the 48th Tarzan movie) and escaping
the stock characters and increasingly ironclad formulas of recent
Disney animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' initially looks and sounds like more of the same, to
the point where Phil Collins is singing the words ``trust your
heart'' by the third line of his opening song. But it proves to be
one of the more exotic blooms in the Disney hothouse, what with
voluptuous flora, hordes of fauna, charming characters and
excitingly kinetic animation that gracefully incorporates
computer-generated motion.
</P>
<P>
   Though it relinquishes some of Disney's toehold on an adult
audience for animation, ``Tarzan'' is sprightly and likable in ways
that are hard to resist. The exultant agility of its jungle scenes
makes it clear that an animated version of this story really is
something new. No tweeting and rustling in the undergrowth to
simulate wildlife here; this is a movie that can send flocks of
parrots or hordes of blue baboons flying whenever it cares to, and
can turn Tarzan into a gloriously athletic creature capable of
hurtling along on the branches of trees. (The star animator Glen
Keane borrowed Tarzan's daredevil moves from his skateboarding
teen-age son.) And for better or worse, this is a version in which
the apes can say what's on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   In a film with more traumatic experiences than its G rating
indicates, two families have to be destroyed before the
lighthearted part begins. One family is simian and the other human,
but the film treats that as a difference only the small-minded
would notice. ``Kala, look at it,'' says the ape whose mate brings
home the orphaned baby boy. ``It's not our kind.'' But Kala, who
has the soothing voice of Glenn Close, prevails and joins Collins
in a rousing ode to motherhood (a catchy bit of Oscar-bait called
``You'll Be in My Heart'').
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, it's a relief this time to find the songs used as
background music rather than narrative devices. That way Tarzan
never has to sing a soliloquy about his secret hopes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Little Tarzan's upbringing is presented in ways meant to draw
chuckles of recognition from parents in the audience. And Rosie
O'Donnell provides more overt comic relief as the voice of his
wisecracking little ape cousin. (``Tell me I'm not lookin' at the
hairless wonder!'') Cute childhood antics, interspersed with the
occasional unmotivated leopard attack, keep the first half of the
film going until Tarzan morphs into manhood during an especially
deft and fluid montage. This time, in a film directed by Kevin Lima
and Chris Buck, the mixture of two-dimensional backgrounds and
freewheeling computer-generated camera movements succeeds
beautifully in giving a fresh, vigorous look to such fanciful
action.
</P>
<P>
   The grown-up Tarzan is a wonderfully nimble Adonis, combining a
vocabulary of human and animal movements with an ease that only
animation can achieve. With sharply angular features and the smooth
voice of Tony Goldwyn, the actor who also directed ``A Walk on the
Moon,'' he cuts a romantic figure even before chattering Jane
Porter arrives on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   With Sir Nigel Hawthorne as Professor Porter, Jane's father, and
much verve from Minnie Driver as Tarzan's adorably drawn dream
girl, the film finds many ways to contrast English scientists with
carefree jungle creatures, as in a jazzy musical sequence that
monkeys with the visitors' travel gear. One nice and not unexpected
touch, given the film's overall sensibility, is a smart,
resourceful Jane who has science on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Since Edgar Rice Burroughs' Tarzan was not headed for a happy
ending, the Disney version flails noticeably in finding a sunny
resolution for its story. But the young viewers for whom this film
will play best are liable to be more interested in hummable tunes,
splendiferous jungle scenes and the hero's total lack of body fat
than in wondering in which culture he really belongs.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TARZAN'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kevin Lima and Chris Buck; written by Tab Murphy,
Bob Tzudiker and Noni White, based on the story ``Tarzan of the
Apes,'' by Edgar Rice Burroughs; art director, Daniel St. Pierre;
edited by Gregory Perler; music by Mark Mancina, with songs by Phil
Collins; Tarzan character animator, Glen Keane; produced by Bonnie
Arnold; released by Walt Disney Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 88 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is rated G.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Tony Goldwyn (Tarzan), Minnie Driver (Jane),
Glenn Close (Kala), Alex D. Linz (Young Tarzan/Baby Tarzan), Rosie
O'Donnell (Terk), Brian Blessed (Clayton), Sir Nigel Hawthorne
(Porter), Lance Henriksen (Kerchak), Wayne Knight (Tantor) and
Taylor Dempsey (Young Tantor).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
