<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DWARF-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-17 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DWARF-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE RED DWARF': GROTESQUES AND CLOWNS IN SURREAL FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deep in the heart of every man, an angry, persecuted dwarf is
screaming for revenge. But once that lonely inner dwarf realizes
that everybody else also has a goblin trapped inside, redemption is
possible. After all, human proportion is in the eyes of the
beholder. And in the end, aren't all of us ``little'' people crying
out for recognition and dignity in the rough-and-tumble traveling
circus of life?
</P>
<P>
   That is the sentimental-verging-on-mawkish message of the
Belgian director Yvan Le Moine's first feature film, ``The Red
Dwarf.'' The black-and-white movie, adapted from a short story by
the French writer Michel Tournier, is a labored allegorical fantasy
that belongs to the sad-clown European tradition of ``Les Enfants
du Paradis'' and ``La Strada.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Red Dwarf'' never comes close to matching those
forerunners in emotional power or symbolic weight, it has enough
bizarre imagery and plot twists to keep you chasing after its
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a surreal present that resembles the 1940s in some scenes
and more recent decades in others, ``The Red Dwarf'' is the story
of Lucien Lhotte (Jean-Yves Thual), a dwarf-size law clerk in his
30s who has a job writing incriminating letters used as false
evidence in divorce cases. One day, the firm's most important
client, the Countess Paola Bendoni (Anita Ekberg), a mountainous
fading opera diva intent on divorcing her unfaithful husband, Bob
(Arno Chevrier), summons Lucien to her villa to go over some bogus
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   Impulsively, the love-starved law clerk bares himself naked to
the countess, who welcomes him into her bed as an intriguing sexual
novelty. The affair ends abruptly when Bob and Paola decide to
reconcile, leaving Lucien heartbroken. Stealing into the countess'
house while she is upstairs making love with Bob, Lucien gets
drunk, dons one of her blond wigs along with eye makeup and
lipstick, and in a flamboyantly operatic gesture strangles her when
she comes down the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Bob, fearing he'll be accused of the murder, disappears, while
Lucien, chafing under the contemptuous thumb of his employers,
misbehaves at work, dressing foppishly and doing bird and animal
imitations. Then with one outrageous scatological gesture, he
quits. Lucien ends up joining a local traveling circus in which he
has already befriended Isis Colombe (Dyna Gauzy), an angelic
12-year-old acrobat who offers innocent, unconditional love. Lucien
eventually helps Bob escape the country, and they team up to form a
hugely successful clown act in which the tiny Lucien regularly
clobbers his loutish circus partner.
</P>
<P>
   With its smudged cinematography, raucous circus music, abruptly
shifting perspective (some scenes are shot looking up and close-ups
turn faces into grotesque caricatures), ``The Red Dwarf'' aspires
toward an Expressionistic grandeur. Although the film has plenty of
narrative energy, what is glaringly missing in the film is a
compelling central performance.
</P>
<P>
   Wide-eyed and poker-faced, Thual's suffering Everyman, Lucien,
is an expressive cipher who runs the gamut of primal emotions from
blankness to boredom. A face that should be etched with all the
sorrows of the world is devoid of poetry. The actor is at his
liveliest executing circus stunts. Ms. Ekberg, last seen a decade
ago as herself in Fellini's ``Intervista,'' has metamorphosed into
the kind of devouring gargoyle that the term Felliniesque was
coined to describe.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE RED DWARF'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Yvan Le Moine; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Le Moine, based on the short story by Michel
Tournier; director of photography, Danny Elsen; edited by Ursula
Leziak; music by Alexei Shelegin and Daniel Brandt; production
designer, Philippe Graff; released by Samuel Goldwyn Films.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jean-Yves Thual (Lucien Lhotte), Dyna Gauzy (Isis
Colombe), Michel Peyrelon (the Circus Director), Arno Chevrier
(Bob), Anita Ekberg (Countess Paola Bendoni) and Carlo Colombaioni
(the Old Clown). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
