r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     06-17 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK THE ORIGINS OF WORLD'S FIRST PUBLICLY TRADED COMMERCIAL SPACE
COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All of the pieces for another technological revolution are
coming together. Just look to the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Between 400 and 1,200 miles above us is an area of space called
low-Earth orbit that is being developed for a high-tech
infrastructure that will make the Internet's current on-ground
cable system seem primitive.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't another space race between the U.S. and Soviet
governments. In fact, government has little to do with any of the
development.
</P>
<P>
   This is strictly a commercial endeavor. One with basic profit
motives. Some are calling it the Gold Rush of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The instruments linking this infrastructure have been around for
40 years but have only recently made great boosts in engineering
capabilities and cost reduction, primarily through the efforts of
one small, but brilliant, company.
</P>
<P>
   The company's name is Orbital Sciences Corp., the world's first
publicly traded commercial space company. Its main product stems
from its network of satellites. Orbital's story and that of its
celestial industry are revealed in the book ``Silicon Sky: How One
Small Start-Up Went Over the Top to Beat the Big Boys into
Satellite Heaven'' (Perseus Books, 332 pages, $26).
</P>
<P>
   The book is written by author Gary Dorsey, who spent hundreds of
hours with the company since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   It was just two years earlier when 35 young engineers built a
new kind of rocket they called Pegasus. Revolutionary in concept,
the small rocket was designed to be launched from a B-52 airplane
instead of from the ground. And it's a whopping 90 percent cheaper
than any rocket previously made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rocket ... was roundly dismissed as just another quirky,
blue-sky project when the concept was first unveiled,'' Dorsey
writes. ``But on April 5, 1990 ... the Orbital company ...
demonstrated the first successful expendable launch vehicle in this
country in twenty years. Not since the creation of the space
shuttle had any American company produced a new rocket that
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The rocket has been used in the past few years to launch a
series of 28 Orbital satellites. The satellites now cover the
globe. With that network, Orbital can design, manufacture, operate
and market total space systems, Dorsey writes. That includes
satellite services, sensors, Earth stations, satellite navigation
and communication products and Earth-imaging products.
</P>
<P>
   And customers are beating down its Virginia door. Orbital space
products will generate more than $1 billion in revenues this year.
Orbital recently became one of the 10 largest satellite-related
companies in North America, with 1998 earnings of $750 million,
Dorsey writes.
</P>
<P>
   This was a company that 10 years earlier kept its doors open by
three of its employees maxing out their credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Orbital is run by a brassy entrepreneur named David Thompson,
who is ``potentially as remarkable in the field of aerospace as
Steven Jobs in the business of personal computing,'' Dorsey
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, in effect, took the exorbitant aerospace world and
turned it on its ear. He invented a concept called ``Microspace''
to explain his business proposal. Microspace is ``finding a way to
provide a level of affordability and ease of use with space
products that make smaller systems attractive to a much larger and
more diverse customer base,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   Among those customers is VisionStar, which wants Orbital to
build two geostationary satellites for high-speed Internet
connections and broadcasting. Another 12-satellite constellation is
being built for mobile phone service. Orbital's PathMaster vehicle
navigation system is being used on snowplows and herbicide trucks
in four states.
</P>
<P>
   And Thompson and his group have recently introduced the world's
first portable Global Positioning System receiver, priced at less
than $100.
</P>
<P>
   A man with a vision, Thompson says the next revolution in
aerospace would happen, if ``you plug the energy of private capital
into space technology and then get out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The time to step aside _ and watch _ is now.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Rescued By Upgrading Your PC''
</P>
<P>
   By Kris Jamsa
</P>
<P>
   Jamsa Press, $26.95
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever thought that adding a CD-ROM or improving the
memory on your computer was beyond your capabilities, this book
might help. Now in its third edition, the book promises that you do
not have to be a computer genius to upgrade your computer. Diagrams
and simple English make the job look easy, whether you're
installing a sound card or upgrading your 486 to a Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Bloomberg's Smart Questions to Ask Your Financial Advisers''
</P>
<P>
   By Lynn Brenner
</P>
<P>
   Berkley Books, $12.95
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the right personal finance questions to ask is often
more important than having a broad understanding of the subject,
Newsday personal finance columnist Lynn Brenner suggests. This book
offers questions, and some answers, to eight areas of personal
finance, including investing; prenuptial and divorce agreements;
buying and selling a house; buying insurance; estate, tax and
retirement planning; and coping with the loss of a job.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Franchising and Licensing: Two Ways to Build Your Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew J. Sherman
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $45
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales from franchised outlets make up nearly 50 percent
of all retail sales in the United States, or about $850 billion,
and employ about 9 million people. This book, weighing in at 449
pages, is one of the definitive bibles of the industry since its
first edition in 1991. This second edition includes changes in the
regulations of franchising made in 1995, as well as the impact of
technology and takeovers in the franchising industry. Issues from
management systems to financial strategies to licensing are
included in this new edition as well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
