<SLUG> BC-FILM-REDVIOLIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS `VIOLIN' PLAYS A TRAGIC TUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Put your anger into your work,'' the violin maker Nicolo
(Carlo Cecchi) snarls at one of his apprentices. That chance
statement turns out to be tragically true in ``The Red Violin,''
the newest film from Canadian director Francois Girard, who last
flexed his muscles with the pleasing (if overdirected) ``Thirty-two
Short Films About Glenn Gould.'' After the death of his wife during
childbirth, Nicolo immerses his paintbrush in red and slowly takes
it to the violin he was making for his unborn child, a reminder of
the happiness he has lost.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the violin is cursed, sending a tragic slash through the
lives of those who touch it. Girard and his co-writer, Don McKellar
(who also acts in the film), use the violin for an anthological
touch, starting with Kaspar (Christoph Koncz), the young prodigy
who plays it after Nicolo's wife dies. Georges (Jean-Luc Bideau)
grabs the boy up, seeing a chance for fame and patronage if a
nobleman will take the child. After sawing away at the violin, his
little angel face silent with the strain, Kaspar finally gets an
opportunity to audition in the Royal Court.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of a few stories _ spanning the globe, as they
used to say on ``Wide World of Sports'' _ in ``Red Violin,'' as the
instrument passes from a tribe of Gypsies (one of whom looks way
too much like Yanni) to China, ending up at an auction house. Here,
Samuel L. Jackson stands, his stately edginess on point, as bids
for the prized violin go on around him. The real star is not
Jackson, nor the violin, but rather Girard's elegant visual
compositions. He provides a picture that moves with courtly poise.
That jittery hunger of his early work has been replaced by
something more self-conscious. By the time Greta Scacchi shows up,
you may have lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   Girard's talent may be to link himself to the personality of his
subject, and with the jumpy, eccentric Gould, he plunged himself
deep into the pianist's rising and falling states. Here, married to
a shifting series of protagonists, he is robbed of a consistent
point of view. His grasp is clearly evident, as the movie changes
tempo from story to story. It lacks a heart, though, despite the
ominous fortuneteller who knows all. (And, given the cliches
stirred up here, so do we.) In the end, we feel as if we're in the
gallery with Jackson, pacing and waiting for something to grab our
attention. The John Corigliano score is so compelling, though, that
it does a lot of the movie's work.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Red Violin''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Francois Girard
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Samuel L. Jackson, Greta Scacchi
</P>
<P>
   Length: 130 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Not rated: Contains adult language and sexuality; portions of
the film are subtitled
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-URIS-TEX     06-17 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-URIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URIS' LATEST BOOK CELEBRATES AMERICA AND A LONG CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Author Leon Uris isn't sure whether ``A God in Ruins''
(HarperCollins, $26), his latest novel, is also his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm old enough _ 74, 75 on Aug. 3 _ to think about gracefully
going out, retiring, like (hockey's) Wayne Gretzky and (football's)
John Elway,'' Uris mused in a phone interview from his home outside
New York City. ``If you've had a good long run, you don't want to
stay out in the public eye a little too long. It shouldn't be like
Frank Sinatra's first retirement, which, after a while, got to be a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1953, when he debuted on bestseller lists with ``Battle
Cry,'' Uris' writing career has been anything but a joke, though,
like Sinatra, he has had career peaks and valleys.
</P>
<P>
   One dip came after ``QB VII'' in 1970. It took Uris six years to
follow up with the mega-bestseller ``Trinity,'' which he still
counts as his favorite among 11 novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it, it became a renewal of my career,'' Uris says.
``My trip to Ireland to research that book was ethereal. The whole
experience made me realize I must have been Irish in a past life.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``A God in Ruins'' is special to Uris, too, and not only
because he isn't sure he'll ever tackle another book project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say I wrote `A God in Ruins' because I still have to pay my
bills, but the truth is, I needed to write this book,'' Uris says.
``The millennium is here, I've been around for three-quarters of a
century, and it's time to sum up how I feel about America.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Exodus'' to ``Topaz,'' Uris' previous history-based
novels have often had predominantly foreign settings. ``A God in
Ruins'' is specifically American, focusing on the U.S. political
system and national religious prejudices. Protagonist Quinn Patrick
O'Connell, a governor of Colorado, running for president, discovers
in the middle of the 2008 campaign that he is Jewish. This is only
one of the plot twists; others involve terrorists, campaign dirty
tricks and White House sexual high jinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the concept of this book came to me quickly,
researching it took a year and a half,'' Uris recalls. ``There's an
art to researching a book. When you do it over and over as I have,
you learn to avoid a lot of extra information you don't need.
Earlier in my career I tried to learn every damn thing about every
damn subject. A lot of time was wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even limiting research time hasn't prevented Uris' most recent
books from taking their toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research done correctly, exhaustively if need be, tears your
guts out,'' Uris says. ``You read the same things over and over,
and after a while it gets confusing. A writer has to wade through
differing opinions about moments in history and then, in print,
take a stance. It de-energizes you.''
</P>
<P>
   Once his research is completed, Uris says, the really hard work
begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell aspiring writers the same thing _ forget any glamour.
Writing is sitting down and working, working, working.''
</P>
<P>
   Uris realizes that each of his books is eagerly awaited by fans,
but he refuses to feel any pressure from high public expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope my readers know that I give them the best I can do at
all times,'' he says. ``That eliminates any sense of pressure from
the outside. I put the pressure on myself. And for that reason, for
me, for writers who care, each book destroys you a little bit. Each
ages you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Uris doesn't feel sorry for himself. He doesn't regret the
energy his books have drained from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big upside,'' Uris says. ``Look, I was a poor boy
from a poor Jewish family. It's amazing that I got to be where I
am. How can I in any way be dissatisfied? If, physically, some
results of a misspent youth are tumbling down on me, I'm not going
to complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not ``A God in Ruins'' is his literary swan song,
Uris says, he'd like his readers to know he has been grateful for
the chance to entertain and, he hopes, educate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has been wonderful,'' he says. ``Each writer has only
a few things to say, and I've tried to say my things as well as I
could.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
