<HEADER>
A9347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      06-17 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PIRATES OF SILICON VALLEY': TWO NERDS TRY TO TAKE OVER THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The swashbuckling title ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' is
absolutely right for a film about the birth of the computer age.
After all, the tale of the battle for dominance between Apple
Computer and Microsoft is brimming with those age-old elements of
high drama: invention, big bucks and backbiting.
</P>
<P>
   Apple founder Steve Jobs (savvily played by Noah Wyle) is the
visionary and rebel here, as comfortable with cosmic consciousness
as bytes of information. ``It's better to be a pirate than to run
the navy,'' he tells his employees.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft founder Bill Gates (Anthony Michael Hall), now
commonly known as the richest man in the world, is more plodding,
the prototype of the socially inept computer nerd. They are the
tortoise and the hare of the computer age. Improbably, this timid
movie makes them seem as dynamic as a turtle and a bunny.
</P>
<P>
   The meandering ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' doesn't have a clue
what it wants to be. At times it seems to be about Jobs' amazing
rise and fall. As the film depicts it, he starts Apple, becomes
immensely rich when it goes public, but is fired in the wake of his
own megalomania. The movie ends in 1996 with his return as an
executive to the company now partly owned by Gates. Or, is this the
story of a blood feud between the men and their companies?
</P>
<P>
   The film has a smashing opening scene that gives viewers false
hope. Ridley Scott (played by J.G. Hertzler) is directing his
eerily futuristic commercial for Apple based on the concept of
Orwell's ``1984.'' Jobs gazes into the camera with a seductive
sincerity that helps account for his success. ``I don't want you to
think of this as just a film,'' he says. He is talking to Scott
about the commercial, but of course he is also speaking directly to
us. ``We're creating a completely new consciousness, like an artist
or a poet,'' he says of Apple. ``We're rewriting the history of
human thought.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a grabber of a scene. The flamboyant commercial with its
clonelike humans and Big Brother on a giant screen contrasts with
the hypnotic allure of Wyle's close-up. ``Pirates of Silicon
Valley'' never comes close to such style or cleverness again.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the film is flashing back to the college days of Jobs and
Gates, cross-cutting between the two stories, skimming through
events in the superficial way that has made ``docudrama'' a foul
word.
</P>
<P>
   Each part of the story has its narrator. Jobs' is Steve Wozniak
(Joey Slotnik), who, in one of the more vivid scenes, helps start
Apple in Jobs' parents' garage. With his Hawaiian shirt and aviator
glasses, he is the picture of the California computer geek. Gates'
narrator is Steve Ballmer (John DiMaggio), his balding Harvard
classmate, whose colorless, bean-counting demeanor matches the
image of Microsoft. But if the Gates and Job characters had been
lifelike enough, the film would not have needed narrators to
explain them. And while the alternating structure suggests this is
the story of their competition, the real-life characters and the
casting yell that this should be Steven Jobs' tale.
</P>
<P>
   Though Wyle is famous for ``ER,'' he has also shown (in the film
``The Myth of Fingerprints'') that he can play characters more
complicated than John Carter. By turns high-spirited, sly and
evasive, he makes the most of this bafflingly underwritten role.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs briefly refers to his search for his birth parents, and
though the full story has been written about widely, it doesn't
come up here. (As an adult, he discovered that after he was given
up for adoption, his parents married and had a daughter, who became
the novelist Mona Simpson.) Yet the film's vague allusions to
adoption supposedly have something to do with the way Jobs cruelly
denies that he is the father of his girlfriend's child.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there is no accounting for his bizarre transformation
from quasi-hippie to Captain Queeg, who makes Apple employees work
90 hours a week and enjoys humiliating them. There is a fascinating
psychodrama in Jobs, but Wyle can't add the inner life the script
denies him.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who is still best known for his long-gone Brat Pack days,
doesn't even live up to the movie's slim possibilities. When Gates,
in a moment that counts for goofiness, speeds along the highway
singing ``My Way,'' the scene should be a lot funnier. At times he
is presented as the pathetic, greasy-haired loner, wounded when the
arrogant Jobs snubs him at a computer fair. Yet even then he
doesn't seem human. The film never strays far from Gates'
conflicted public image as a power-hungry animatron.
</P>
<P>
   The film's failure has to be traced to its writer and director,
Martyn Burke. Though this is the first movie he has directed, he is
an experienced writer who has diminished other juicy subjects in
films like HBO's ``Pentagon Wars,'' a dull-bladed satire about that
easiest of targets, government bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   This movie does have what every television movie needs today: a
soundtrack of familiar songs, which includes some refreshingly
appropriate choices like ``Synchronicity'' for the explosive '80s.
That doesn't help much. The last thing anyone needs from a film
called ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' is a script with the daring of
a scared rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   `PIRATES OF SILICON VALLEY'
</P>
<P>
   TNT, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Martyn Burke; Ossi Rawi, director of
photography; Leanne Moore, producer and unit production manager;
Jeff Ginn, production designer, Joseph Dougherty, co-executive
producer; music by Frank Fitzpatrick; Steven Haft and Nick
Lombardo, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Noah Wyle (Steve Jobs), Anthony Michael Hall (Bill Gates);
Joey Slotnick (Steve Wozniak), John DiMaggio (Steve Ballmer), Josh
Hopkins (Paul Allen), Gema Zamprogna (Arlene), J.G. Hertzler
(Ridley Scott) and Bodhi Pine Elfman (Gilmore). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
