<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     06-17 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: DELVING INTO THE LORE OF LUCITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Design groupies, hold on to your fauteuils: the great
decorator Elsie de Wolfe never designed a single piece of clear
plastic furniture. And certainly not the major example that is
continually attributed to her: a sparkling Lucite side chair with a
plume-shaped back and a seat of luxurious silk velvet printed like
an ocelot's pelt.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the opinion of Alan Moss, a New York furniture
dealer who specializes in midcentury chic. Forget the apocryphal
stories, various de Wolfe biographies and the chair's constant
appearance in photographs of de Wolfe interiors of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grosfeld House made the chair; Elsie de Wolfe just bought
them,'' said Moss, who knows his Lucite lore, top to bottom. He
once owned the makeup diva Helena Rubenstein's clear Lucite sleigh
bed, which was hubristically emblazoned with her cosmetics
company's logo. The headboard and footboard glowed, too, thanks to
concealed fluorescent lights.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast trays as clear as crystal, tables that look as if they
are floating in midair, chairs with legs like columns of spring
water: Lucite is everywhere. One reason for this ubiquity could be
the style world's continued embrace of all things from the Age of
Aquarius. Or perhaps it has something to do with the popularity of
Austin Powers, the superspy portrayed by Mike Myers in the mock
James Bond movie caper ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,''
which opened last week.
</P>
<P>
   While Powers' esthetic sense is dubious, he certainly would have
felt right at home at the recent Kips Bay Boys and Girls Club
Decorator Show House. Peter Vaughn outfitted his acid-green sitting
room there with multicolored acrylic nesting tables, perfect for
the leering lothario to stash a drink before making his move on a
miniskirted model.
</P>
<P>
   And should one of Powers' capers have taken him to the wilds of
North Carolina, the dentally challenged hero could have found the
perfect breakfast tray at the High Point International Furniture
Fair in April: a sleek, clear Lucite breakfast tray by a Texas
company, Creations at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, however, prefers the color-enhanced alternative. ``My
favorite thing about colored Lucite is its hard shine,'' he said.
``From a distance you'd almost think it's lacquer.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Parish-Hadley associate, he recently formed Albrizzi
Design and is reproducing furniture, trays, ice buckets and other
plastic paraphernalia from the archives of Baron Alessandro
Albrizzi, an Italian furniture designer whose candy-color
minimalism was a hit with hip young members of the international
jet set in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The newlyweds Duane and Mark Hampton, for instance, placed
Albrizzi's Lucite occasional tables in their mod Upper East Side
Manhattan apartment in 1966, and the Baron's designs were a firm
favorite with Hampton's employer at the time, the English decorator
David Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Though the ice-clear material is popularly associated with
disco-chic interiors of the late 1960s, Lucite was born more than
30 years earlier. In 1936 E.I. du Pont &AMP; Co. invented Lucite, the
trademark name for an acrylic resin formally known as polymethyl
methacrylate. Also known as Plexiglas and Perspex (in Britain), the
new acrylic resin was intended to be used for highway reflectors,
automobile taillights, radiator ornaments and airplane windshields,
said Scott Nelson, a spokesman for Du Pont.
</P>
<P>
   By 1938, according to an article in a Du Pont promotional
magazine of the day, Lucite had leapfrogged into the home, and
rarely for practical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``One well known designer,'' the article reported, was addicted
to Lucite, using it for ``doorways, framing pictures and in a
decorative fountain effect'' in her apartment. This unnamed woman
might well have been Cora Scovill, a New Yorker with a penchant for
designing Lucite furniture with bizarre ruffled edges and mirror
insets.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein's glow-in-the-dark bed was one of the campier of
Lucite renditions, although it pales beside some of Scovill's loopy
extravaganzas. In more cautious and considerate hands, the
synthetic material _ cold to look at but warm to the touch,
incredibly smooth, tougher than glass and able to be bent, poured
and molded into any decorative shape _ lent itself particularly
well to classical applications.
</P>
<P>
   A star of Moss' stock at his shop at 436 Lafayette St., at Astor
Place, is a majestic mahogany breakfront made by Grosfeld House in
the 1930s. Its sober neo-classical silhouette is jollied up with
all manner of crystalline plastic appliques: Greek-style helmets on
the mirrored lower doors, half-columns flanking the Lucite-grilled
upper doors and crowning it all a Lucite gallery. Now under
restoration, the breakfront will be priced at $15,500, Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other plastic treasures are a circa-1939
Directoire-style table with saber-style Lucite legs holding aloft a
gilt-and-mirror top, for $9,500, and a similarly dated side chair
with a carved Lucite splat, for $4,600.
</P>
<P>
   Few pieces of vintage Lucite furniture have survived the years
in perfect condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it was stylish but not very easy to maintain,''
Vaughn said. Vulnerable to scratches and scuffs, Lucite furniture,
even at the height of its popularity, was deemed a temporary vogue:
fun but not forever.
</P>
<P>
   But today there is Novus, a plastic polish and scratch remover
that Vaughn buys at Gracious Home and recommends to his clients.
The original Albrizzi designs cast an undeniably minimalist allure,
he admitted, but one of the main reasons ``I decided to reproduce
them was products like Novus,'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Products like that make Lucite a viable material
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
