<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-WINE-ART-2TAKES     06-17 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-WINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKEND EXCURSION: REFLECTIONS IN GLASS, WATER AND WINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for add photo note)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A treasury of priceless glass in a land of free-flowing wine:
how good an idea is this?
</P>
<P>
   Good enough, it turns out, if the combination pairs the
strikingly expanded Corning Museum of Glass in Corning, N.Y., and
the vineyard-ringed Finger Lakes. You can taste your way through
dozens of wineries hugging the hillsides along the sky-blue waters
and tour the world's most comprehensive collection of art glass and
high-tech exhibits in a new section, opening Saturday, of a $62
million glass-sheathed addition to the museum. (Or more prudently,
perhaps, you can do it the other way around.)
</P>
<P>
   Either way, when combined with visits to the region's other
attractions, it makes for a rewarding foray from New York City,
notwithstanding an almost five-hour drive. Corning, about 270 miles
northwest of Manhattan, is also home to the Rockwell Museum
enshrining the rich Western art and Carder Steuben glass
collections of a local magnate, Robert F. Rockwell Jr., and is
prettily bisected by the 19th-century throwback Market Street,
listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   Within short drives on blessedly uncrowded roads are Watkins
Glen with its waterfalls and car racing track; the National
Warplane Museum at the Elmira-Corning Regional Airport and other
aviation landmarks, and of course the lakes, more than 11 of them,
from Cayuga and Seneca (40 miles and 35 miles long, respectively)
to modest little fingerlings like Cayuta and Lamoka and Waneta,
clawed out of the earth as if by giant bear paws.
</P>
<P>
   Corning is New York state's third-biggest tourist attraction,
after New York City and Niagara Falls. It has been drawing growing
numbers of visitors since the Corning Glass Center opened in 1951,
becoming overnight a mecca for the Levittown generation happy to
pile into the station wagon for a scenic drive upstate and a free
(until 1981) tour of the glassworks.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a retro feel to the leisurely paced city and
resort region, from the old red-brick factory buildings and
push-button stoplights to the lakeview restaurants, tour boats,
dinner cruises and waving motor-boaters whose gentle wakes rock the
shorefront docks.
</P>
<P>
   But today's visitors to Corning coming off Route 17 onto 414 see
something new: tilting sheets of glass hung on delicate steel
spider supports, the crystal facade of a new entrance building and
galleries, designed by the Manhattan architectural firm
Smith-Miller &AMP; Hawkinson, that represent the second stage in a
three-part expansion under way since 1993 and set for completion
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how they make glass?'' I felt the need to ask our
8-year-old daughter as we drove up, determined, as parents are, to
turn everything into a Learning Experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They blow it,'' Sophie said, barely looking up from her Game
Boy. ``Don't act like I'm stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth I didn't really know myself how glass was made, except
that it came from sand. I didn't think much about glass at all in
fact, except when it held something potable. Like most people, I
looked through it, not at it.
</P>
<P>
   The museum set us straight. Glass isn't just one material, and
it isn't just made from sand. Glass is a hybrid of a solid and a
liquid, a glassy state of matter, and almost any material
(including metal) can be made into a glass by melting it so that
the molecules rearrange themselves randomly, as in a liquid, and
then rapidly cooling it so that it hardens before the molecules can
return to their regular positions.
</P>
<P>
   Nature makes glass in volcanos and from lightning strikes on
sand. Humans began making glass about 4,000 years ago; it's the
oldest man-made material after bronze.
</P>
<P>
   We could believe that after looking at some of the extraordinary
creations in the ``Treasures'' exhibition, a selection of 200 of
the finest and rarest objects in the museum's 30,000-piece
collection. It included the exquisite thumb-size head of a pharaoh
dated 1431 to 1411 B.C., once cobalt blue, now coated tan with age,
and a similarly coated tiny green glass Venus of Knidos, from the
first to second century A.D. There was a Roman ``cage cup'' from
about A.D. 300, carved almost impossibly intricately into a lacy
weave, and, on the large side, an 1878 French table assembled from
200 pieces of Baccarat glass. While my wife, Debbie, and I oohed
and aahed over the displays, Sophie was happily preoccupied with
one of the museum's ``explainers'' who specialize in entertaining
and informing young minds.
</P>
<P>
   In one new gallery devoted to windows _ shouldn't it have been
called ``Windows '99''? _ we saw how windows used to be made from
hand-blown glass bubbles spun rapidly into a disk, which explained
the wavy distortions of the glass in old houses. Although machines
were making flat glass by 1901, it was not until the late 1950s
that a British engineer, Sir Alastair Pilkington, figured out how
to create virtually endless sheets of perfectly flat glass by
floating molten glass on a river of liquid tin, a process that
helped revolutionize architecture.
</P>
<P>
   An egg-shaped theater was the setting for the story of the
struggle to make light bulbs once Edison harnessed electricity to
light. The first bulbs were hand blown from left-over blobs of
glass. When legions of glass blowers couldn't fill the huge demand
for light bulbs in the 1920s, a Corning worker developed a
mechanized process. (More than half the museum's 30 major exhibits
celebrate inventions outside Corning, and only a handful relate to
the company's products, which no longer include its name-brand
cookware.)
</P>
<P>
   No glass museum would be complete without glass blowing of
course, and Corning has a ``Hot Glass Show'' with orange-glowing
2,100-degree gas ovens where artisans melt glass at the end of long
steel pipes and blow and shape it into vases.
</P>
<P>
   We had booked accommodations at $330 for two nights with
breakfast in a Victorian bed and breakfast, the Rosewood Inn, an
1855 Greek Revival and English Tudor house on East First Street in
Corning, a few blocks from downtown and the museum. Children are
supposed to be 12 or older, but Suzanne Sanders, who runs the inn
with her husband, Stewart, was sympathetic when I told her over the
telephone that we had a young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lie to me,'' Mrs. Sanders urged. ``Tell me she's 10.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Our quarters were a parlor suite with its own entrance that had
once been a doctor's office. It had a canopy bed for us and a
daybed and television for Sophie and flounces and flocking galore.
(If we had been alone, we would have preferred one of the five
airier rooms upstairs.) The breakfasts were sumptuous affairs
served family style with other guests around a huge formal
Victorian dining table scattered with silk roses and strings of
costume pearls.
</P>
<P>
   It was a short walk to historic Market Street, five blocks of
old storefronts that called up words like ``dry goods'' and
``emporium'': the kind of street, Debbie said, ``where you call me
`ma' and you're `pa.''' We wandered into several glass galleries _
Noslo and Vitrix and Lost Angel Glass _ disappointed that the glass
blowers were off for the weekend and even more disappointed to find
that a nearby glass studio where you could blow your own glass,
Hands-on Glass on Baker Street, couldn't take us in the tight time
window we had available.
</P>
<P>
   We bought sweets at Heavenly Confections, where the gummy babies
were 2 cents apiece, and the saleswoman actually weighed out one
piece of pink grapefruit candy, costing 4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   After the glass museum, Corning's top attraction is the Rockwell
Museum, which is not named for Norman Rockwell but for the Corning
merchant who assembled the collection. The museum is unmissable
downtown in the towering 1893 former City Hall. With Sophie busying
herself making bookmarks and other handicrafts in what has to be
one of the best-equipped museum children's rooms anywhere, we
explored the extensive Western art and American Indian collection
of Rockwell, now retired, who ran a successful Americana-style
department store on Market Street: ``Ralph Lauren before Ralph
Lauren,'' in the words of the museum's director, Stuart A. Chase.
</P>
<P>
   There was one of Frederic S. Remington's last paintings, ``The
Winter Campaign,'' a beautifully lighted snowscape from 1909; an
N.C. Wyeth painting of an anxious prairie couple; canvases
romanticizing the noble Indian and cowboy (Western art for Eastern
audiences, Chase said), and, yes, an Indian hunting scene by Norman
Rockwell. From there we moved on to the glass collection, including
extraordinary pieces by Frederick Carder, whose Steuben (pronounced
stoo-BEN) Glass Works, later bought by Corning, produced some of
the most exquisite art treasures in glass.
</P>
<P>
   Fragile glassware safely behind us, we drove along the western
brow of Seneca Lake for wine tastings at the Castel Grisch Estate
Winery and Glenora Wine Cellars, returning to Watkins Glen at the
southern tip of the lake for an excellent dinner of shrimp, steak
and monkfish fillets in the new taupe-and-ivory Seasons restaurant
in the Watkins Hotel, a local landmark undergoing restoration.
</P>
<P>
   To Sophie's grave displeasure, we had to forgo an exploration of
the gorge with its waterfalls and 832 stone steps, as well as the
nearby race track.
</P>
<P>
   The next day we set off on another wine trail along the western
shore of Keuka Lake, stopping at Dr. Konstantin Frank's Vinifera
Wine Cellars, where some European grape varieties were first
successfully transplanted to the region, and Bully Hill Vineyards,
where a birthday celebration and wine tasting was in rollicking
progress.
</P>
<P>
   After exploring Hammondsport, with its postage-stamp village
green and several antiques shops, we dined on crab cakes, stuffed
lobster tail, steak and salad on the terrace of a lakeside
restaurant, Snug Harbor. We waved at passing boats, and Sophie went
down to the dock to leave bread for a creature she called a blue
heron or herring. We never got the story straight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
