<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE VISION: THE RETURN OF POWERS, AUSTIN POWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME
</P>
<P>
   Mike Myers, Heather Graham, Seth Green, Verne J. Troyer, Michael
York, Robert Wagner, Mindy Sterling, Will Ferrell, Elizabeth
Hurley, Rob Lowe &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jay Roach &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Glued to the Jerry Springer show on their surveillance screens,
NATO early-warning team members notice something truly alarming.
That bullet-headed nut case in the fistfight with the Ku Klux Klan
Grand Dragon looks suspiciously like Dr. Evil (Myers). Come to
think of it, bullet head's son, Scott Evil (Green), said it all
when he introduced the Springer segment: ``My Father Is Evil, and
He Wants to Take Over the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Unaware of Evil's escape from outer space (don't ask), Austin
Powers (Myers), the manic yellow-toothed international man of
mystery from the original Powers adventure (1997), parties on with
his bride, Vanessa (Ms. Hurley). Suddenly she reveals herself to be
Evil's robot, sprays him with bullets from her breasts, which turn
into machine guns, and detonates.
</P>
<P>
   That frees Austin to resume womanizing, which he celebrates with
a romp through a hotel wearing nothing but the simian hairdo
blanketing his chest. Charged with reapprehending Evil, he then
goes time traveling to 1969, where the Carnaby Street scene is
enlivened by the agent Felicity Shagwell (Ms. Graham).
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Evil schemes to destroy Washington with a laser
beam. ``Great plan, Einstein,'' says Scott Evil, a sarcastic
Generation X-er who accuses his father of a ``Star Wars'' rip-off.
The doctor also robs Austin of his ``mojo'' (this movie's version
of the Force), which fuels sexual appetite. Now there's a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Pure slapstick and always clearly so. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Continual references are part of the spoof. For example, a
rocket shaped like a penis inspires a long string of
double-entendres involving cameo appearances by guest stars. And
Austin prances nude, though not frontally so. It's silly stuff, but
where children are concerned it adds up to considerable sexual
content. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A stream of scatological references and related
obscenities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-10 Most parents will consider the film unsuitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 This is a borderline age. Individual parental
guidelines apply, but most children this age will be eager. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP There shouldn't be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   EXTREME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A two-dimensional (no glasses required) Imax film at the Sony
Imax Theater in Manhattan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jon Long &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No rating 44 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In a spectacle as huge as the eight-story Imax screen, surfers
and wind surfers, skiers and snow boarders and ice and rock
climbers perform under challenging circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Surfers on Oahu in Hawaii are towed by jet ski into seas too
heavy to paddle through. Left on their own, they rocket shoreward,
pursued by breaking walls of water 30 to 40 feet high. Skiers and
boarders plummet down near-vertical mountains, flying off cliffs
and artfully avoiding the mini-avalanches racing along with and
sometimes ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   On vertical (and occasionally beyond vertical) cliffs and ice
sheets, one man and several women claw their way to dizzying
perches hundreds of feet above. Who's got the sunscreen?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-10 They'll be enthralled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP They will, too, though some older children may
grow annoyed with wooden attempts to verbalize these exploits with
banalities like ``getting into who you are'' and going to ``a place
where time doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   LIMBO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, David Strathairn, Vanessa Martinez,
Kris Kristofferson, Casey Siemaszko &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Sayles &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 126 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, Donna (Ms. Mastrantonio), a talented, hard-pressed
club singer, is attracted to Joe (Strathairn), a quiet former
fisherman who now works as a handyman. That displeases Noelle (Ms.
Martinez), Donna's deeply troubled teen-age daughter, who is tired
of her mother's seemingly never-ending parade of disastrous
boyfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is a bookish, soft-spoken man with a mysteriously tragic air
about him who, it turns out, left the sea after a fatal accident 25
years earlier. It also happens that he and Noelle work for the same
employers and she even has a crush on him, which doesn't exactly
improve relations with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   All around them Alaska is being carved up by developers who
would allow the interior to be turned into a parking lot as long as
the spectacular coastal vistas are maintained to draw the floating
hotels for the elderly cruising north for a look at the proverbial
last frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Into the harder world of everyday Alaskans comes Joe's
half-brother Bobby (Siemaszko), a former resident who has gone
south for better pickings but has run into problems with some
associates over a boatload of drugs. To avoid these people Bobby
makes a run for it on his yacht through beautiful ice-flecked
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Unaware of Bobby's situation, Joe has taken Donna and Noelle
along for what they think will be a pleasurable sail. While
anchored one evening the three of them are below when they hear
shots on deck. Escaping through a forward hatch, they swim to shore
on a deserted island and hide, shivering in the forest while those
who dispatched Bobby search for them but finally leave.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 10 days they survive off the land and local waters,
huddle in the ruins of a fox farmer's shack and stoke a signal fire
that they hope will attract rescuers and not Bobby's attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Noelle, a fine writer herself, discovers a diary written years
ago by the fox farmer's daughter and reads excerpts by firelight.
</P>
<P>
   A depressing tale it is, too. But they persevere, confront and
comfort one another, giving rise to hope that they might make a
compatible unit once this is over. Then an aircraft engine is heard
in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Shots are heard but no violence is seen, nor is there
any in the rest of the film. Noelle, however, experiments with
self-mutilation, cutting herself slightly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Donna and Joe are shown in bed after love-making, and
embracing in the woods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A moderate amount, sparingly and tellingly employed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP Sayles (``The Secret of Roan Innish'') has made
another strong, thoughtful film about credible people under
pressure. Many older teen-agers will respond, and parents could
well decide that in this case the benefits outweigh the R rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
