<SLUG> BC-COURT-INVESTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRIPS FEDERAL JUDGES OF POWER OVER DEFENDANTS' ASSETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal judges cannot stop insolvent companies from
spending or giving away their assets while they are being sued by
investors trying to recoup their money, the Supreme Court ruled
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous decision, the court said that a U.S. District
Court judge in New York exceeded his authority when ordering a
consortium of Mexican companies not to transfer or assign their
primary asset _ $300 million in notes from the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district court had no authority to issue a preliminary
injunction preventing (the companies) from disposing of their
assets pending adjudication of (the investors') contract claim for
money damages,'' Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jay E. Grenig, an expert on financial law at
Marquette University in Milwaukee, Wis., the court's decision
increases the risk and cost associated with international
investments and will likely persuade some investors to avoid some
overseas opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this way of ensuring that their money is protected,
international investors will have to think twice about whether it
is worth it for them send their funds out of the country because
they might not get it back,'' Grenig said.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium, known as Grupo Mexicano de Desarrollo, took part
in the Mexican government's program to develop an intercity highway
network from 1990 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, the companies arranged private financing for
construction of the roads in return for the right to collect tolls.
When revenues from toll-road traffic fell in 1994 below anticipated
levels, the consortium sold notes to institutional investors _
including $82 million to 11 U.S. investors.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the consortium defaulted on an interest
payment on those notes, and the investors sued in federal court in
New York. The investors' lawyers told U.S. District Judge John
Martin Jr. that the consortium was favoring its Mexican creditors
by turning over to them some of its government money.
</P>
<P>
   Martin agreed, issuing a preliminary injunction that prohibited
the consortium from transferring or assigning its right to receive
some $300 million from the Mexican government in connection with
the road-building project.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit
affirmed the District Court's action.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling overturned that decision.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Scalia agreed that the rights of investors and
companies should be more clearly defined but said the courts were
not the place for that issue to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate concerning the formidable power over debtors should
be conducted and resolved where such issues belong in our
democracy: in the Congress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
