<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBUM OF THE WEEK: `ENEMA OF THE STATE' BY BLINK 182 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLINK 182: ``Enema of the State'' (MCA Records).
</P>
<P>
   The makers of Top 40 pop are thanking heaven for the little
girls whose appetite for generic Romeos is stimulating a
music-business boom. But what's a little boy to do? Most adolescent
males find the pinup boys repulsive. They need artists who
understand that girls are a drag, parents are worse, and sometimes
you're your own worst pimply-faced enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Blink 182 serves the gawky guy audience through speedy music
that frees frustration. This San Diego-based trio, weaned on sunny
Southern California hard-core punk, chases frisky melodies the way
its members dream of chasing girls. Blink 182 is tight and light on
its feet, as interested in getting its harmonies right as in
mastering super-fast chord changes.
</P>
<P>
   The title of the band's latest Top 10 release summarizes its
sense of humor, but beyond the cracks lies insight, if not
profundity. The bassist Mark Hoppus and the guitarist Tom DeLong,
who write the songs and trade vocals, play goofs more self-aware
than they should be.
</P>
<P>
   They get mad at the girls who reject them and the boys who clean
up after their romantic messes. ``I need a girl that I can train,''
sings DeLong on ``Dumpweed.`` It's a nasty idea but the rest of the
song makes it obvious he is the one at heel.
</P>
<P>
   Songs like the lovesick ``Going Away to College'' and the hit
``What's My Age Again?'' paint similar portraits of the male psyche
as a slapdash work in progress. Girls may find this band icky, and
parents may wish it had some manners, but Blink 182 showers its
fans with laddish love.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
