<HEADER>
A9406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     06-17 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tacking Down Two Musicals
</P>
<P>
   Summertime: slow and sultry and usually pretty darn silent on
Broadway. But in the comfort of air-conditioned offices, the
producers of two big-budget fall musicals have ironed out their
schedules and casts.
</P>
<P>
   First up is ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' the first Broadway revival of the
1948 Cole Porter musical. Previews begin Oct. 25 at the Martin Beck
Theater; opening night is Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   As long rumored, the show will be a reunion of two ``Ragtime''
alumni, Brian Stokes Mitchell and Marin Mazzie, who will portray
the bickering husband and ex-wife team of Fred Graham and Lili
Vanessi. Contract negotiations, which have dragged on for months,
were being wrapped up this week. Mitchell and Ms. Mazzie will be
joined by Amy Spanger and Michael Berresse as the romantic
sidekicks.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Berlind and Roger Horchow are the producers; Michael
Blakemore (``City of Angels'') directs.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the producer Cameron Mackintosh settled a knotty
casting problem by turning to one of his favorite actresses, Ruthie
Henshall, who is making her Broadway debut as Velma Kelly in
``Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Ms. Henshall, who is English, will go directly into
``Putting It Together,'' a revue of the work of Stephen Sondheim.
Ms. Henshall replaces Susan Egan, who opted out of ``Putting It
Together'' last month to take over the role of Sally Bowles in
``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   To make time for Ms. Henshall to finish her commitment to
``Chicago,'' Mackintosh has postponed the first preview until Oct.
29; opening night will be in mid-to-late November. Carol Burnett
headlines the cast, with George Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh said the recasting was serendipitous because Ms.
Henshall had been an early choice for the cast but had been unable
to do the show because of scheduling conflicts. ``I couldn't be
more delighted,'' Mackintosh said from London.
</P>
<P>
   Gone Fishing
</P>
<P>
   Good news: Ron Taylor, the star of `'It Ain't Nothin' but the
Blues'' who had a mild stroke late last week, was released from St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center on Wednesday. Taylor said doctors
had found a blood clot on his optical nerve, but that they expected
him to make a full recovery. He said he would take a four-week
break and rest at a friend's farm in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to sit at a fishing hole,'' Taylor said. ``And if I
don't catch anything, I will still come back with a smile on my
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Buzzing Off Broadway
</P>
<P>
   Like planes in a holding pattern, four plays have announced that
they will land in Off Broadway theaters soon. What they don't know
is where or in some cases when.
</P>
<P>
   The most peripatetic is ``The Vagina Monologues,'' which has
played at star-studded Valentine's Day benefits in London and New
York and has had stints in Athens, Berlin, Croatia and Jerusalem
and throughout the United States. Yet it has never had an
open-ended commercial run in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The piece was written by Eve Ensler and is a seriously funny
look at, well, the most feminine of topics. The monologues
developed from interviews with hundreds of women, and the show was
first performed by Ms. Ensler in 1996 at the nonprofit Here
performance space in the South Village.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sept. 21, Ms. Ensler will offer a reprise of the piece
at a mid-size Off Broadway theater, incorporating new material
gleaned from her travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans got the piece better than anybody,'' Ms. Ensler
laughed. ``The English took a few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Another well-traveled entry is ``An Almost Holy Picture,'' a
one-man drama by Heather McDonald about a lapsed Catholic priest
who finds solace in life as a groundskeeper.
</P>
<P>
   The play had a critically praised premiere in 1995 at La Jolla
Playhouse in San Diego and was produced a year later at the
McCarter Theater in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The New York production will retain the creative core of the
original, with direction by Michael Mayer and the acting handled by
David Morse, most recently seen in New York in ``How I Learned to
Drive.'' The show plans to open on Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Also looking for a berth in September is ``If Memory Serves,'' a
black comedy about show business by Jonathan Tolins (``Twilight of
the Golds''). Elizabeth Ashley is signed to star; Leonard Foglia
will direct.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there's ``The Exact Center of the Universe,'' which
closed a successful run with Frances Sternhagen at the Women's
Project's Theater Four in late April. Martin Markinson, the owner
of the Helen Hayes Theater, and Elsa Haft have picked up the option
and are looking for an Off Broadway theater for the early fall.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, producers say they have had serious talks with
theater owners, in some cases even putting down deposits. But most
of the top-shelf Off Broadway theaters _ like the Promenade, the
Lucille Lortel and the Century Center _ have shows running.
Theatrical courtesy and superstition hold that a producer must
never reveal his theater until its current tenant announces a
closing date. So as shows depart, anticipate a few arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Sound of Music,'' originally scheduled to close on June
27, will instead close on Sunday. Its producers and Actors' Equity
were unable to agree on the show's closing date and the starting
date of rehearsals for its national tour. Equity rules require a
six-week gap, but the show's producers wanted only a four-week gap.
They failed to work out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playwrights Horizons said this week that ``Goodnight Children
Everywhere'' by Richard Nelson would likely close on Sunday, unless
ticket sales improved. The company also said that ``The Dead,'' a
musical version of James Joyce's short story, with a book by
Nelson, would open its fall season, produced in conjunction with
Gregory Mosher and Arielle Tepper. Stephen Spinella, Alice Ripley
and Daisy Egan are cast.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tape,'' a play about two high school buddies with a secret
or two, has been extended through Thursday at the Access Theater,
at 380 Broadway in lower Manhattan. The play's director is Steve
Pickering, whose day job is playing Howard in the Broadway revival
of ``Death of a Salesman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9408 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIN-LACMA-LADN     06-17 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIN-LACMA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELEANOR ANTIN: PORTRAIT OF A CHAMELEON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _Throughout her innovative and resourceful career,
Eleanor Antin has frequently existed in some or other state of
exile, whether involuntary or slyly self-imposed.
</P>
<P>
   She has been a female artist in a male-dominated occupation, a
fervent but independent-minded feminist during the ``liberated''
'70s, and a bookish, Jewish ``New York brat'' transported to the
land of palm trees and blissed-out smiles.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, Antin has lived outside San Diego, where her
husband, David, accepted a teaching post at the University of
California campus in the late 1960s. Though she occasionally has
set the pace for certain aspects of the New York art scene, she has
chosen to stand slightly apart from that milieu, while making do
with minuscule budgets and rudimentary production values.
</P>
<P>
   So it was fitting when, a few weeks ago, Antin was spotted
wearing a ``Visitor'' sticker on her left hand while being feted as
the guest of honor at one of L.A.'s most prestigious cultural
venues.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the press preview of ``Eleanor Antin,'' the
first comprehensive survey of the pioneering feminist artist, at
the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Organized by Howard N. Fox,
LACMA curator of contemporary art, the exhibition tracks Antin's
multiple artistic and personal reinventions of the past 35 years, a
period during which she repeatedly found new ways to insert herself
and her various ``fictional personae'' into the often exclusionary
world of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying unity among all of (her work) is this
insistence upon telling stories,'' Fox says. ``And so she tells
them in every way you can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   She also tells them in ways that often undercut and interrogate
each other. For example, in one of her fictional personae projects,
she portrayed an impoverished ballerina in a comically poignant
performance titled ``The Little Match Girl Ballet'' (1975). LACMA's
survey supplies an additional layer of commentary by juxtaposing
still photographs of Antin seeming to execute perfect pirouettes
and arabesques with a video of the same routine that captures her
every stumble and misstep.
</P>
<P>
   It's a characteristically complex portrait, both boldly
individualistic in its expression of a private fantasy and
comically self-effacing at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but be a little subversive and ironic,'' the
artist says amiably. ``That's my nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Antin is referring specifically to the tongue-in-cheek subtitles
that appear in the witty, retro-Yiddish ``silent films'' she began
making in the early 1990s. But she could as easily be speaking of
the ``guerrillalike motivation to a lot of her methodology,'' as
Fox puts it, that has characterized her entire career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her work is almost Talmudic,'' Fox says. ``It's like
commentary upon commentary, or layer upon layer.''
</P>
<P>
   Structured chronologically, the exhibition undergoes what Fox
describes as ``a deepening and darkening of mood'' as it moves
toward the present.
</P>
<P>
   It begins in the early 1960s, when artists like Robert
Rauschenberg, Jasper Johns and Jim Dine were deflating the
self-importance of abstract expressionism by plastering their works
with found objects and other household detritus, just as the
dadaists had done 50 years before.
</P>
<P>
   Antin's early experiments in conceptual art are represented at
LACMA by ``Blood of a Poet Box'' (1965-68), for which Antin
persuaded 100 poets such as John Ashberry, John Cage and Allen
Ginsberg, several of them friends, to each contribute a drop of
blood that she preserved on microscopic slides.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition also includes the famous ``100 BOOTS'' (1971-73),
a narrative series of 51 postcards chronicling the ``journey'' of
50 pairs of posed black rubber boots traversing a path from the
Pacific Ocean to the Museum of Modern Art in New York, where they
were exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   Antin's explorations of gender and identity issues are
highlighted by the frequently exhibited ``Carving: A Traditional
Sculpture.'' In this 1972 series of 144 photographs, Antin
documented herself nude while in the process of losing 10 pounds
during a 36-day diet.
</P>
<P>
   This deadpan, pseudo-scientific skewering of conventional
notions of feminine beauty, along with other feminist-inspired
works by Antin, have been cited as major influences on their
careers by many subsequent female artists. (This aspect of Antin's
career is addressed in some detail in a catalog essay by Lisa E.
Bloom.)
</P>
<P>
   Antin also anticipated Cindy Sherman in her construction of
three distinct, made-up ``fictional personae'' _ the King, the
Nurse and the Ballerina _ which she acted out both in private and
public settings. Like some low-budget auteur operating on the
margins of Hollywood, Antin made all the costumes and props from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   As the King, Antin walked the streets of San Diego County,
collecting money in a tin cup and chatting with the locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little (leery), walking out there with a beard and a
bosom,'' she says. ``I think I was saved because I look kind of
like a Chaplin figure. I don't look scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The collective vision that emerges from these works is one in
which all the world's a kind of strange, tragic melodrama. We, the
hapless actors, ``are the comedy,'' Antin says.
</P>
<P>
   In person, in brown pullover and black pants, the petite artist,
at 64, has retained the slightly anonymous, Everywoman quality that
perfectly suits her identity-switching purposes. Only her
gunmetal-blue nail polish hints at the scrappiness within.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess in a sense I always prefer things when they're on the
downslope,'' she says, ``because to me that's a truer image of
life. I mean, the king's a loser, like I'm a loser, because the
king's my political self. I was always on the losing end. And
politically we're all losers, and we're all losers in life because
...''
</P>
<P>
   She lets the thought trail off, unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I guess the pathos is built in. You might as well enjoy it
while you're going downhill!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
