A9418 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-CLASH-LADN     06-17 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-CLASH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLAPSTICK VIEW FROM THE BORDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They've been married for, oh, about 150 years,
these strange, bilingual bedfellows with the wire fence running
smack down the middle of their nuptial resting place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, but you don't need me!'' the Mexican wife
complains bitterly to her English-speaking husband, who tries to
ignore her by pulling Old Glory over his head, as if it were an
electric blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a marriage counselor in the house? Or at least a NAFTA
negotiator?
</P>
<P>
   So goes life in the surreal no-man's land that separates San
Diego from its cross-border cousin, Tijuana and, by implication,
the smug, prosperous !bold!el norte!off! from poorer, oft-shunned
points south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, goes ``Culture Clash in Bordertown,'' the latest manic
exercise in slapstick sociology from the well-regarded L.A.-based
Chicano comic trio. Following several months of national tours, new
commissions and HBO specials, Richard Montoya, Ric Salinas and
Herbert Siguenza are back in their hometown, where they'll be holed
up for the next month at the Actors' Gang in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've just tuned in to this 15-year-old threesome,
Culture Clash came into being on Cinco de Mayo, 1984, as a kind of
agitprop clown show. In the following years, the group has kept its
ribald theatricality while adding narrative drive and political
nuance to its gender-reversing, ethnicity-swapping vaudeville
shtick. Grounded in the make-'em-yuk imperatives of stand-up
comedy, ``Bordertown'' is necessarily a hit-or-miss affair _ but
with a high ratio of the former to the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Carving its material into short, Brechtian !ital!actos!off! (as
El Teatro Campesino did), ``Bordertown'' scampers over more ground
in 1{ hours than an INS agent in a customized Range Rover. The
digressions and throwaway lines alone encompass Ralphs shopping
cards, Santeria, Carlos Santana, Octavio Paz, mural painting and
Gabriel Garcia Marquez novels. There are inside jokes about the
troupe's aborted HBO appearances and overly obscure ones about the
upcoming production of ``Hughie,'' with Al Pacino, at the Mark
Taper Forum (whose Latino Theatre Initiative is co-presenting
``Bordertown'').
</P>
<P>
   Taking its theme as whatever divides us _ culturally,
politically, sexually, even metaphysically _ ``Bordertown'' was
custom-built for the San Diego Repertory Theatre, where it
premiered. So we naturally meet Shuma the Sea World killer whale
(Salinas), San Diego's unofficial mascot, spilling his blubber to a
Teutonic psychotherapist (Montoya) and fretting because some
Mexican interloper whales are willing to work for fewer fish.
</P>
<P>
   In the bizarre universe of this metropolis of millions, parts of
which resemble ``a Hollywood version of a frontier town 100 years
ago,'' a wrap is another name for ``an overpriced, assimilated
burrito,'' and aging Chicano activists wistfully recall the good
ol' days of !bold!el movemiento!off!, when the people stood up to
the police and the bulldozers plowing under their homes in the name
of gentrification.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bordertown'' of the '90s, however, is a more complicated
place, inhabited not only by !ital!maquiladora!off! workers who
make Barbie doll accessories, and blissfully empty-headed Anglo
surfer dudes, but by openly gay Latino women and young Asian males
who affectionately call each other by a racist epithet for
``African-American.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the show's best-realized sequence, the trio don
priestly robes to recite an African prayer chant _ a not-unfamiliar
sound within San Diego's burgeoning Ethiopian enclave _ then strip
them off to reveal sailor suits underneath. Then they prance around
the stage like the happy-go-lucky guys on Manhattan shore leave in
``Wonderful Town,'' while the Village People belt out ``In the
Navy'' and one sailor grabs his fellow seamen's backsides.
 &UR; !ital!Machishmo!off! &LR; , anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ominous rumblings of the UFOs overhead, ready to
transport Heaven's Gate followers to a final frontier where ``there
are no borders,'' ``Bordertown'' is a show in which Angelenos are
sure to discern their own fragmented reflections. &UR;  &LR; We are all
aliens, ``Bordertown'' observes, lovers and enemies joined at the
hip in a mixed marriage from which there's no escape short of
death. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
