<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHANGING-FATHERHOOD-$     06-17 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANGING-FATHERHOOD-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW THEORIES GIVE DAD A MORE ACTIVE ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children learn by example, from what we do rather than what we
say, most parents and educators agree. Mimicking adults, watching
how they act in certain situations, children pick up clues as to
which behaviors work and which don't, and how to manipulate the
world to do one's bidding.
</P>
<P>
   This is conventional wisdom, certainly, but it is also the
underpinning of a revolution in thought about how fathers influence
their daughters, giving rise to new theories that grant the
paternal parent a greater role in developing daughters' self-esteem
and independence.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers, we are learning, may no longer be simply the ``other''
of traditional family psychology. According to standard Freudian
theory, fathers are supposed to be important to their daughters
simply because they are not mothers. As the first man, the first
person of the opposite gender, in a girl's life, a father in this
paradigm is the role model for later heterosexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is different from her, he makes her aware of her body
and teaches her about her femininity. And, by attracting her, he
serves as a counter to the potentially suffocating mother-child
relationship, basically by wooing her away from her mother and by
serving (again, loosely according to Freud) as a source of
conflict. It's a vital but secondary role: He influences her by
being different, by what he isn't, not by what he is.
</P>
<P>
   But a new school of researchers, psychiatrists, and theorists is
putting aside this sexuality-based theory to seek out more
comprehensive, positive models that fathers provide for their
children, particularly daughters. Their research is showing how
fathers, partly because of their societal gender roles and partly
because of biology, are more than ever before teaching daughters
how to live on their own. According to this emerging model, a
father's first lesson to a daughter is about independence.
</P>
<P>
   This is taught when daughters see that fathers can _ and do _
walk away from the family and safely return, their welcome home
assured. This freedom is not linked purely to the ideal of the
traditional American family structure, in which the father leaves
to work and the mother stays with the child. The quality of
``agency,'' that is the freedom to move in the world, explains
psychologist Virginia Goldner of New York's Ackerman Center for the
Family, exists in opposition to the primal physical bond a child
has with its mother. Unlike a father, however close, a mother for
nine months is there providing a constant physical presence, the
first that a baby knows.
</P>
<P>
   This bond _ and the father's very different role _ is, of
course, supported by societal standards. Fathers are still three
times less likely than mothers to take time off from work after a
birth or adoption under the 1993 federal Family and Medical Leave
Act. This is changing, certainly, as increasing numbers of fathers
take over the primary care duties of infants and children.
</P>
<P>
   But for now the care-giving mother and working father define our
cultural standard, explains psychoanalyst and author Jessica
Benjamin, and young children quickly pick up on these standard
roles. Fathers are, as Goldner puts it, the ``coming and going''
parent. They are free, as Benjamin explains, to realize their own
desires, without forfeiting security upon return. And that
combination of independence and security is just what a curious,
learning child wants. ``We think, `I love him because I want to be
like him. Free to come and go, says Goldner.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Such a simplification is not meant to downplay the great power
that mothers have in any child's life. Certainly a healthy
mother-daughter relationship enables a child to grow up strong and
independent. However, the relationships between mother and daughter
and father and daughter remain fundamentally different. ``Often
there's more of a companionate relationship from daughter to
mother,'' says Froma Walsh, a professor at the University of
Chicago and the author of ``Living Beyond Loss.'' ``There's also
the identification and the need to differentiate. That's less
strong between daughters and fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the father has a special power of pronouncing the
daughter worthy and acceptable,'' explains Terry Hargrave, a
Texas-based psychologist who specializes in family counseling.
``Women have mom more as a friend, but they depend on fathers more
in terms of who they are, in terms of identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of their particular role, fathers are in a unique
position to encourage children to learn about independence. They
are also in the position most likely to deny it. All parents are
reasonably wary about allowing children to make major decisions.
But fathers in particular, researchers agree, may have a hard time
allowing their daughters to explore, experiment, and venture into
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fathers are much more able to do this with sons than
daughters,'' says Goldner. ``They lend their agentic selves _
`You're like me' _ to boys more than girls.''
</P>
<P>
   When this identification and the freedom to act on it is denied,
she points out, the frustrated desire can surface in unhappy ways.
``Women can get in masochistic relationships (in which) they are in
love with the self they were forbidden to be,'' Goldner explains.
``Had there been a parent who acknowledged this concern, they would
be free of this, but only fathers can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   When fathers can encourage independence, however, the effect is
astounding. Discussions with women who have felt free to build
successful careers, particularly in male-dominated fields, clearly
recall the boost of paternal support. Boston lawyer Karen Berman
Cohen, for example, has established herself in the macho world of
litigation. ``My father,'' she says, ``was very accepting of us. He
basically gave us the feeling we could do anything if we tried.''
Key, perhaps, was his lack of gender stereotyping; he gave as much
encouragement to Berman Cohen's brother (a cardiologist) as to her
sister (a retail store manager) and his youngest child, Karen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the kids to be able to grow up and make their own
decisions and be strong personalities,'' says Marvin Berman.
``Karen was always a dynamic personality, a strong kid. That
strength was to be treasured, not controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the mother of two young daughters, Berman Cohen states her
intention of raising Margot and Briana with the same level of
encouragement, and her husband, Joel, concurs. ``We're always aware
of it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Brody, morning news anchor at WGBH-FM in Boston, is
another woman who has carved her niche in a competitive field. She
describes her career as one of words and opinions, both of which
were nurtured by her father, both explicitly and implicitly. ``The
only time in school I ever got in trouble was for mouthing off,''
says Brody. ``And I knew that he knew that he was supposed to be
angry with me. But he was so clearly proud of me. I knew that I had
his encouragement to tell off people who deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we probably took her side,'' recalls her father, Sam
Brody, laughing. Perhaps more to the point, he acknowledges that
both he and his wife, Eleanor, were careful to give Sharon, their
only daughter, the same encouragement and opportunities as they
gave their two sons. ``We worked very hard to treat the kids
equally,'' he now recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Women like Cohen and Brody, both in their 30s, are perhaps the
most obvious beneficiaries of such proactive fathering. They make
up what theorists call the hinge generation, women of the Baby Boom
and the lull just after. Brought up largely by stay-at-home moms
(unlike the up-and-coming Generation Xers) these 30- to
50-year-olds tend to hold jobs outside the homes, like their
fathers did. As a result, they often looked to dad more than mom as
they learned how to navigate day-to-day lives in a world shaped by
feminism and the modern economy.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers, rather than mothers, were the parents who could relate
to the particulars of job stress and boredom, the meetings and
deadlines and production quotas that these working women had to
meet, that often they were the first women in their families to
meet. If they were successful, often they credit their father's
farsighted and involved support.
</P>
<P>
   For today's fathers, coming after the first wave of feminism,
this historic change illuminates a new way to parent. Although
teaching freedom may go against a father's grain, current dads are
learning that it is their responsibility to raise strong, free
daughters. ``It all boils down to your child's confidence in
themselves and your willingness to trust them,'' says Joel Cohen.
``You have to take some chances. Self-esteem is something you have
to build.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Clea Simon is a member of the Globe Staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
