<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON DEFENDS ROLE OF GOVERNMENT IN PARIS SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, on the cusp of
launching her campaign for the U.S. Senate seat from New York,
defended the role of government Thursday and urged expanded
government action worldwide to give everyone a chance to succeed in
the high tech age.
</P>
<P>
   In hour-long remarks at the Sorbonne, Clinton urged governments
to invest in education, health care and child care to equip
citizens for fast changing economic developments.
</P>
<P>
   Without citing any group by name, Clinton said: ``There are
those, particularly in my country, who insist on assaulting
government, who claim that if we would only abolish or severely
weaken it, then everyone's freedom and prosperity would blossom.''
</P>
<P>
   That is ``a very mistaken notion,'' said Clinton, who is making
plans for her campaign to succeed retiring veteran Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need strong and efficient governments, not oppressive or
weak ones, that are able to empower citizens to help them take
responsibilities for their families and their communities,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton decried Apocalyptic pessimism and anti-government
sentiment that she said has propelled some unnamed commercial films
in which ``we have space aliens who are always blowing up
Washington, D.C., and the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Her audience included her daughter, Chelsea, U.S. Ambassador to
France Felix Rohaytn and French First Lady Bernadette Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention her personal political plans during her
remarks. She later flew to Fez, Morocco, to inaugurate a maternity
operating room and to participate in discussions about ways for
non-governmental humanitarian organizations to become more
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans an address on Friday in Palermo, Sicily, on ways
to build citizen action and activism before she flies to Cologne,
Germany, to join President Clinton for the annual summit of leaders
from the seven largest industrialized nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady defended her priorities against critics who, she
said, warn against the ``feminization of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some in my country and elsewhere who say once talk
turns to civil society _ to education, to life-long learning, to
health care, to empowering the voluntary sector _ that we have
strayed into soft politics that will lead to a feminization of
politics,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I prefer to think of this process as the humanization of
politics, the kind of kitchen table issues that are discussed by
parents in Paris and in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``By paying attention to these real life
political issues, we can reinvest in citizens and give them a stake
in their governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a glancing reference to her own ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the leadership that will come in the public
and the private sectors to create the kind of future that is worthy
of our past ideals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
