</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WALKER EVANS': PHOTOGRAPHER REMAINS IN THE SHADOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publications notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is to be done when a distinguished biographer dies suddenly
before his book is completed? Should the manuscript be preserved in
a library for researchers to use as reference? Should another
writer be commissioned to complete the work? Or should the
incomplete manuscript be published anyway?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of James R. Mellow, who died of a heart attack in
late 1997, the decision was made to publish his voluminous
unfinished work on one of this century's great American
photographers, Walker Evans. After all, Mellow was a noted critic
whose biographies include those of Gertrude Stein, F. Scott and
Zelda Fitzgerald and Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is a formidable artist who has remained as dauntingly
elusive as his work is sparingly direct. In 1995 Belinda Rathbone
published the first biography of Evans, who died in April 1975 at
71. She did not have access to Evans' personal papers: diaries,
letters, work logs and contact sheets; the Evans estate granted
that access to Mellow. The last chapter he wrote prior to his death
explored Evans' interactions with Robert Frank in the mid-1950s. It
is in the prologue, with its account of Mellow's 1974 interview
with a bleary-eyed and hard-drinking Evans, that a glimpse is
offered of the photographer's troubled late years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a generous and illuminating introduction by the critic
Hilton Kramer, Mellow's biography of Evans reads like a sprawling
work in progress awaiting judicious pruning and editing. Although
Mellow comes as close as anyone has to cracking the enigma that was
Evans, this is an exasperating book.
</P>
<P>
   It is plagued by the picayune, with Mellow seemingly believing
that the reader would be interested in every note and every list
that Evans ever wrote. Evans' student writings and translations in
Paris, which are not without charm, are treated as if they were
serious literary works.
</P>
<P>
   Mellow also tends to peel off and dwell at some length on the
background and accomplishments of the various people Evans came
into contact with. Or might have come into contact with. Or didn't
meet at all.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that Mellow sternly points out that ``there is
no evidence'' for this or that, he resorts to the frequent and
highly problematic use of ``it seems,'' ``may have,'' ``possibly,''
``probably,'' phrases like ``there is some reason for speculation
that'' or writing that something ``might or might not have been
true.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the subject of Evans' sexual adventures,
Mellow's passive-aggressive hedging can veer toward the
preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Evans formed close friendships with a number of men, including
the artists Hanns Skolle and Ben Shahn, the arts impresario and
critic Lincoln Kirstein, and the writers James Agee and John
Cheever. Mellow writes that it was during the early period of
Cheever's friendship with Evans, in the early 30s, that ``Cheever's
homosexual seduction by Walker Evans took place _ if, in fact, it
ever did take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a reader wading through all this is rewarded with a
tantalizing, often revealing portrait of one of photography's most
literary artists. A slight, fastidious, good-looking, charming man
with a domineering mother, Evans had gone to Paris in 1926, at 22,
intending to be a writer. The next year he was in New York, about
to begin his long career in photography.
</P>
<P>
   Mellow expertly charts the trajectory of Evans' soaring career
in the context of the times. Evans was a leading pioneer of what a
critic described as ``a pure photography without any romanticism.''
A 1929 photograph of a roadside gas sign, Mellow notes, ``has an
almost Abstract Expressionist quality, 20 years before the fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Evans took some of the most memorably empathetic
photographs of the rural poor during the Depression, he indicated
early on that he had no illusions about people. ``I think the human
race should be kicked around a great deal more than it is,'' he
wrote his friend Hanns Skolle in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   As far as exhibitions of his pictures were concerned, Mellow
writes, Evans ``had made all the right connections'' and cultivated
the mystique of the purist. He wouldn't go to his own openings or
allow publicity shots of himself to be used in publications. He
wouldn't photograph celebrities. He wouldn't politicize his mind or
his work, believing that an artist could reveal the human
condition, not directly alleviate it.
</P>
<P>
   Mellow portrays Evans in private life almost as a character out
of a Camus story: the perpetual disengaged observer. Evans'
romantic entanglements were the stuff of bad television soap
operas. Invariably the wife of a friend would become enamored of
him. In one terrible episode one such woman taunted her husband by
openly pursuing Evans, who coolly played along.
</P>
<P>
   Mellow also discusses at some length a bizarre sexual experiment
involving the notorious Agee; his wife, Alma, and Evans. Accounts
of the threesome in bed by Agee and his wife differ. Evans would
later attribute the sexual goings-on among his contemporaries to
the tenor of the times: ``Everybody by rote went to bed with
everybody else, and the result was an emotional desert and
confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 Evans finally married Jane Ninas, a woman with whom he
had carried on an on-and-off affair for some years. For a while,
from the letters he wrote when they were apart, he was quite the
besotted husband. (The marriage was to last 10 or so years.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Let Us Now Praise Famous Men,'' with text by Agee and
photographs of destitute tenant farmers by Evans, was published the
same year. Lionel Trilling commented on the ``perfect taste'' of
Evans' pictures, ``taking that word in its largest possible sense
to mean tact, delicacy, justness of feeling, complete awareness and
perfect respect.''
</P>
<P>
   In fewer than 100 pages toward the end of the biography, Mellow
goes quickly over Evans' two-year stint (1943-45) as a movie critic
at Time magazine and his taking a job as staff photographer and
writer at Fortune, where he worked until 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Among the extraordinary nuggets that Mellow unearths are
portions of a late 1947 interview for Time that was never used. In
it, Evans said: ``My work is like making love, if you'll forgive
me. It has to spring from the moment, from what I feel at the
moment. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WALKER EVANS'
</P>
<P>
   By James R. Mellow
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 654 pages. Basic Books. $40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROOKE-MUSIC-NYTR &LR;      06-17 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKE-MUSIC-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONATHA BROOKE'S INDEPENDENCE DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting dropped from MCA Records was a mixed blessing for
singer/songwriter Jonatha Brooke. While it meant less media
exposure, less radio play and a whole lot less money, the MCA boot
meant Brooke had to figure out how to do things for herself or go
back to waiting tables.
</P>
<P>
   She had to, perish the thought, grow up a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to be an artist who's cursed with somewhat of a
business sensibility,'' says the Boston-based performer, who's in
the middle of a solo tour. ``Or I like to think that I am. Perhaps
I'm fooling myself. But I've always been really involved in all the
aspects of what I do, so I kind of know the beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in 1998, Brooke started her own label, Bad Dog Records, and
sold 4,000 copies of ``Jonatha Brooke Live'' over the Internet.
``It's a tough one,'' says the 35-year-old musician, calling from a
Texas tour stop, ``because I do find myself overwhelmed from time
to time: `Oh my God, how much is that going to cost? There goes my
life savings!' '' Now available in stores, the album is doing a
brisk business.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' she says, ``I'm kind of enjoying the
education of it. I just have to really carve out time to shut the
phones off and put down that I'm creative, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a journalist father and a poet mother, Brooke
writes airy confessionals closer in spirit to dreamy Sarah
McLachlan than to strident Ani DiFranco, America's other
folksinger-turned-indie-mogul. A onetime ballet dancer, she began
her recording career in 1989 as frontwoman for the band The Story.
Six years and two critically acclaimed Story albums later, she went
out on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke's second solo collection, ``Ten Cent Wings,'' hit the
streets in November 1997, just as Seagram's, the liquor giant, was
buying MCA's parent company. Although the reviews were glowing
(said Billboard: `` `Ten Cent Wings' is essential, like taking a
deep breath after witnessing something magnificent''), the label _
or what was left of it _ failed to promote the album. In the middle
of a tour, Brooke received a pink slip.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much disagreement at the top about me and my
record,'' Brooke recalls. ``There was just no consolidated
consensus about who I was or what they were going to do, or what
they were willing to do. It was just a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   MCA first offered her a serious cut in pay _ and when she
refused, the ax fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you still have to hang onto the fact that they have not
touched your career _ you are completely intact. And once you get
out there in front of your fans, that's what's so clear. And that's
what was so reassuring about getting back on the road and making
this record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a daunting venture. I think if I weren't as established
as I am _ I have a pretty rabid following _ I wouldn't have been
able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   MCA wasn't the only major label doing serious housecleaning at
the time _ numerous established artists such as Me'Shell
Ndegeocello, Wendy &AMP; Lisa and Cowboy Junkies found themselves
without a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gazillion more people have been dumped since then,'' Brooke
explains. ``And I'm really happy to have been one of the first! So
that I could turn it around and do something positive immediately
and be kind of ahead of the curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weird thing is that I can't rule out any possibility for
the future. I'm going to make a record over the summer, certainly
make it myself, and make it exactly what I want it to be. And then
make the decision what to do with it. Because you know, if a label
really has some heart and soul, and they really believe in you,
you're the luckiest girl in the world. And I can't compete with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke grew up with mixed musical influences: While her two
brothers wore the grooves out of Rolling Stones and Who albums, her
mother played and sang hymns on the family piano. ``She'd put on
Rachmaninoff and walk around the house weeping to this beautiful
music,'' Brooke remembers. ``And so from an early age I connected
deep emotion to music.'' From her father, she learned to love
words, to ask questions and actually listen to the answers. He also
played a little trumpet.
</P>
<P>
   Young Jonatha's own taste's ran to soundtrack albums for ``The
Sound of Music,'' ``Godspell'' and ``Hair.''
</P>
<P>
   For a success blueprint, Brooke says she wouldn't mind looking
to her longtime friend Shawn Colvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, as I get older I'm happier and happier with
exactly what I have,'' she says. ``I appreciate it for what it is.
When I got to Austin yesterday, `Sunny Came Home' was playing in
the airport. And I wondered what it's like for her to finally, when
she was 40, have this kind of ironic success. After working her ass
off forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that will probably happen to me, like some fluky
weird thing will happen and all of a sudden one of my songs will
finally be recognized. I can laugh about it, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainseville, Fla., Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
