<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9482 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-PASSENGERS-H     06-17 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-PASSENGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE INDUSTRY AGREES TO IMPROVE CUSTOMER SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to ward off congressional action, the
nation's major airlines promised Thursday to improve customer
service by giving passengers more information about fares and
delayed flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have felt the whip from Congress; we've heard the bell ring
from the flying public,'' said Gerald Greenwald, chairman of United
Airlines and head of the Air Transport Association Executive
Committee, an airline industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Some frequent-flyers _ including Senate Commerce Committee
Chairman John McCain, R-Ariz., and House Transportation Committee
Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa. _ were so irritated at the industry
that in February they introduced ``passenger rights'' legislation
mandating better customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Their move came in the wake of a highly publicized incident in
January when Northwest Airlines passengers had to sit on runways in
Detroit for as long as eight hours without access to food or usable
restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald said the threat of action from Congress and the
public's feeling ``that the airlines just don't care'' forced the
industry to agree on its own customer service plan.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal _ which apparently staves off, for now, a stronger
measure by Congress _ was announced after several months of
negotiations among the industry, the Department of Transportation
and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   It would require airlines to offer the lowest fare available on
any given flight and allow people to hold a reservation up to 24
hours without paying for it. Airlines would also have to give
up-to-date and accurate information about delayed and canceled
flights as well as establish clear policies for accommodating
passengers who are delayed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The plan requires airlines to ``make every reasonable effort to
provide food, water, restroom facilities and access to medical
treatment for passengers abroad an aircraft that is on the ground
for an extended period of time without access to the terminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald admitted that parts of the plan, such as holding a
reservation for 24 hours without payment, are already followed by
many airlines.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said at a news conference he was not completely satisfied
with the industry proposal. He said he wants a provision that would
require airlines to notify passengers when flights are overbooked.
He also plans to push legislation that would require the Department
of Transportation to report to Congress periodically on whether the
industry is following its customer service program.
</P>
<P>
   After McCain spoke, Greenwald said the industry would agree to
that measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be watching very, very carefully,'' said Sen.
John D. ``Jay'' Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., one of the lawmakers who
negotiated the plan with the airlines. ``If this doesn't work, then
we'll have to move to a mandatory approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald warned that the plan ``is not a panacea for every ill
everyday that's out there, but it does provide a solid and
unprecedented effort by this industry address key issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster called the plan a ``big step in the right direction,''
but said Congress must still consider ``whether federal legislation
is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Galloway, president of the American Society of Travel
Agents, a trade group, said he thinks it is needed. ``Most of this
proposal is merely a restatement of existing policy, though not of
existing practice,'' he said. ``It reflects little new or
innovative in the way airlines treat customers.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at (202)-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
