<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLLECTING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO COLLECTING: A CURIOUS POSTSCRIPT TO A PROUD BRAND'S TALE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ore., Ohio, Ariz.)  (editors: optional sidebar in 2nd take) 
 (bl)  
 By PAUL DUCHENE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASCO, Wash. _ In 1955, on the verge of collapse, Packard _ the
luxury automaker that was sometimes called America's Rolls-Royce _
designed an elegant show car in response to loyal customers'
requests for a Packard that resembled the ones of old. The $20,000
prototype was enthusiastically received but never made it into
production.
</P>
<P>
   When the company was shut down by Studebaker in 1958, it was
assumed that the only existing model of that show car _ the Request
_ had been consigned to the scrap heap. It was, in fact, driven out
of the factory in Detroit in broad daylight, rumored to have been
given to an executive's mistress.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to 1973: the car reappeared, damaged and rusting,
in a backyard in Portland, Ore., where Larry Dopps, a reclusive
collector from Pasco, bought it.
</P>
<P>
   Dopps rebuilt the car as an investment _ at one time asking
$325,000 for it. As Packard aficionados continued to debate its
value in the intervening years, the Request's public exposure was
limited to articles is a few specialty magazines and an appearance
at a car show in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, as Packard lovers celebrate the company's 100th
anniversary, the marque will be featured at the Pebble Beach
Concours in August, and the two main owners' clubs _ Packard
Automobile Classics and Packards International _ are planning
celebrations at Packard's birthplace in Warren, Ohio. A museum is
opening July 4, and the clubs have invited landmark cars, including
the Request, to a show on July 6.
</P>
<P>
   While Dopps, 62, will not be able to attend because of his
health, he is convinced the Request is an important piece of
American automotive history. After more than 25 years as its owner,
he is preparing to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't sell it to Europe or Japan,'' he said, ``even if
they offered me half a million dollars. It's American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a show car, the Request differed surprisingly
little from the 1955 Four Hundred coupe it was based on (unlike
Packard's last show car, the 1956 Predictor, which looked as if it
were patched together from a 1958 Lincoln and a 1961 Cadillac).
</P>
<P>
   But the Request's front-end styling still stuns enthusiasts. The
designer, Richard Teague, revived the classic upright Packard
grille of the 1930s and found a way to fit it to the new model.
</P>
<P>
   Teague, who died in 1991, was a major player in Detroit. He
worked for Packard from 1951-58 and then for American Motors until
1984. His 1963 Rambler Classic redesign was the Motor Trend car of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, General Motors developed dream cars to draw
people to auto shows. Although these show cars seldom made it to
full production, some of the ideas they featured were incorporated
in humbler vehicles. Packard's show cars included the Pan American
in 1952, the Balboa hardtop in 1953 and the Panther in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   For 1955, Packard had overhauled its line with new models, and
Teague was asked to develop a show car to match.
</P>
<P>
   Because time and money were problems, Teague took a cue from the
flood of letters from dealers and owners longing for the
traditional Packard touch. He grabbed the third new Four Hundred
coupe off the assembly line (No. 5587-1003) and sent it to Creative
Industries of Detroit, which specialized in building show cars.
</P>
<P>
   In less than 90 days, Creative produced a show car in pearl
white and copper to Teague's design. Its fiberglass hood featured a
distinctive badge and the words ``Packard Request'' in script on
the hood, trunk and fenders. Front bumpers were cast in huge loops
on each side of the tall grille, which curved underneath the car. A
salmon-and-cream interior and cloisonne hubcaps from a 1948 Custom
Eight topped off the chrome wire wheels. The rear fenders were
peaked with lead points to resemble the Packard Caribbean, the top
of the production lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 400 pounds of front bumpers, the new self-leveling
torsion-bar suspension was able to balance the Request, though the
space between the grille and the road was less than 6 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership cannot be traced further than Walter King of Portland,
who bought the Request for $1,500 in 1959 and owned it until 1973.
Merle Wolfer, a Portland collector, recalled that King wanted
$2,500 for the Request when he inquired about it in the late 1960s.
It had been through two crashes and was off the road several years
when Dopps first looked at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the bumpers was broken; we had to have it repaired, and
we were missing some grille bars and the grille surround,'' Dopps
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Dopps is disappointed that he will not make the trip to Ohio,
but he basked in the glow of Packard enthusiasts as least once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when we went to the Packard National in Oakland,
Calif., with the car in 1983,'' he said. ``We were definitely the
poor relations there, but when we drove the car in, they gave us a
standing ovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dopps keeps the Request in a tent garage in eastern Washington.
Beneath the dust, paint shines, chrome glitters and the
352-cubic-inch V8 engine still runs smoothly. With only 14,805
miles, it has plenty of life.
</P>
<P>
   And it still displays evidence of its show-car origins. There is
no body number on the fire wall, which was never painted and still
wears primer. The paint and trim plaque on the door jamb is also
blank.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that No. 1003 was indeed one of the first
1955's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the shifter,'' Dopps said. ``See how it's bent? That's
from trying to get it out of parking gear. The pawl was too long.
They fixed it early in the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Williams of the Blackhawk Collection estimated the car's
value at around $50,000. ``There'll be some interest,'' he said.
``There's always interest in dream cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles Morris, vice president of Christie's International
Motorcars, remembered the Request.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Dick Teague's design, isn't it?'' he asked, estimating
its value at $50,000 to $80,000. He quickly added, ``We'd be
interested in selling it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS in 2nd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While collectors seem to love the idea of driving a new
Duesenberg or Stutz, when revived classic marques are delivered,
they usually disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the 1970s General Motors coupes that were turned into
Stutzes. How about those huge Ford V8s with automatic transmissions
in Duesenberg clones.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the company that decides to make as many original
parts as it can only to discover what it must charge to make money.
There is a company that makes elegant copies of Talbot-Lago
Streamliners, but start counting out $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   And face it, most faux classics simply don't look right; their
proportions are seldom as refined as the originals'.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Roy Gullickson, a Phoenix businessman, is betting on a new
Packard. Promoted as ``an ultra luxury automobile,'' it is equipped
like a Cadillac Seville ($47,850), Lexus LS400 ($53,800) or Jaguar
sedan ($64,300). A spokesman confirmed the car has all-wheel drive
and a V12 engine. There is only one prototype, but the projected
price is $135,000 to $150,000, comparable with Mercedes and
Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   The design falls into an area known as contemporary classic _
old styling cues stamped on a modern profile. The front resembles
the Packard Phantom show car, while the sides have fade-away
fenders like a Pontiac Grand Am. You can see it at
www.packardmotorcar.com/intro.htm.
</P>
<P>
   What do classic car experts think?
</P>
<P>
   Allen Stephens organized the Forest Grove Concours in Oregon, a
big West Coast classic car gathering, for 25 years. ``It's
admirable somebody wants to bring back the Packard name,'' he said,
``but that's all he's going to be bringing back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
