<SLUG> BC-BKN-COHN-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JORDAN WON THOSE TITLES, NOT JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LOWELL COHN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excuse me for not getting all hot and worked up over the
appointment of Phil Jackson as Lakers coach.
</P>
<P>
   To read about this guy, you'd think a combination of Gandhi and
General George Patton had just set down in L.A. In newspapers and
on the radio, people keep referring to Jackson as: the Zen Master,
a former hippie, a philosopher. I don't know about any of that,
although if I'm in the market for a philosopher I go with Plato
over Phil Jackson any day of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I'm sure Jackson is a nice man, and a fine
and wonderful basketball coach. But I don't for a minute believe
he's responsible for those six NBA championships the Bulls won with
him in charge. He had a pretty good player on his team named
Michael Jordan. I bet Jordan made all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why I come to that conclusion. There's a clear pattern to
the last eight years of Jackson's coaching career. When he had
Jordan he won championships. When he didn't have Jordan, he didn't
win diddly.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan Bulls won the NBA title in 1991, 1992 and 1993. Then,
as you recall, Jordan decided to play minor-league baseball.
Without Jordan in the 1993-1994 season, the Bulls got eliminated in
the Eastern Conference semifinals. The next season, when they had
Jordan for only 17 regular-season games, the Bulls again lost in
the conference semifinals. Both seasons they failed to finish on
top of their division.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the Zen wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to the next three seasons, all with Jordan. The Bulls won
three championships in a row. Do we attribute that success to the
magical return of Zen, or the return of Michael? You tell me.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the last time Jordan ever played. It was the sixth
game of the NBA Finals, Bulls against Jazz. If you want to know the
truth, Jordan won the title all by himself. With 20 seconds to go,
Utah led, 86-85. Karl Malone got the ball down low, but Jordan
flashed to Malone's blind side and stole the ball. He then sank the
winning shot with 5.2 seconds to go. All in all, he scored 45 of
the Bulls' 87 points.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson really had his Zen working in that game.
</P>
<P>
   So here's what I want to say. No player in the history of
basketball ever equaled Jordan's impact. The Chicago Bulls didn't
need Jackson to win all those championships. They could have gone
to the store and purchased an inflatable dummy for 20 bucks and
made him the coach. The dummy's job would have been real simple:
Keep your mouth shut, dummy, and get the ball to Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the dummy couldn't actually say, ``Get the ball to
Michael.'' So the trainer, or some other Bulls insider, would have
taped a note to the dummy's chest: ``Get the ball to Michael.''
During timeouts, the players would read the note and remember the
Bulls strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, other teams would have seen the note, too. So the
Bulls could have taped misleading sentences to the dummy to keep
the other team in the dark. These could have said, ``Get the ball
to Ike,'' or ``Get the ball to Izzie,'' or ``Get the ball to
You-Know-Who.'' It really didn't matter if the other team knew,
anyway. They couldn't stop Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   We can be relatively certain that, because he is no dummy,
Jackson's coaching philosophy was the same as the inflatable
dummy's: ``Get the ball to Michael.'' Jackson probably went to bed
chanting that mantra, and woke up reciting it.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also had the sense always to stay on Jordan's good side,
which meant he knew not to louse up a good thing. In return, Jordan
gave Jackson the illusion the coach was running the show.
</P>
<P>
   All that's changed. Starting next season, Jackson will have to
coach the Lakers on his own because there won't be a Michael.
Somehow Jackson will have to create a unified squad in spite of all
those egos veering in opposite directions _ the Shaquille O'Neal
ego and the Kobe Bryant ego immediately come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Then we'll learn if Jackson actually can coach, and we'll see
how far Zen can take you in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   (Lowell Cohn is a sports columnist for The Press Democrat in
Santa Rosa, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
