<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATIONS TAKE YOU TO ANOTHER WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, June 24)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do you need out of a vacation? On my vacation I want
assurance that I am absolutely somewhere else. I want to be a
landed version of an astronaut on a lifeline floating around the
moon, looking back at Earth. I want something a little unexpected,
even a little surreal, to remind me that I am truly far, far from
home, like in some remote corner of Spain or France.
</P>
<P>
   The wind came up, not just any ordinary flutter but something
that toppled tables and shoved metal chairs so hard they scraped
like fingernails on the sidewalk. We were at an outdoor restaurant
in the border town of Portbou on the Spanish-French border on the
Mediterranean coast. The maitre d' said these winds come out of the
Pyrenees and can last for three days. He said they are like the
mistral winds in France that drive some people mad. He mentioned
that Salvador Dali had once lived here, as if there were a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   The wind did seem to have an effect. People picked up their
children and left the streets. Two waiters suddenly started
scuffling. All night the wind screamed and banged shutters, but in
the morning it was clear and people filled the square selling
pieces of salted cod at one table and women's underwear at another.
</P>
<P>
   The guidebook suggests that the mountaintop town of Alquezar in
northern central Spain is a good bet for people who like back
roads. It didn't say that the road itself ends in Alquezar and once
you finally reach it you may need to ask around for accommodations.
A guy sitting on a bench said he could help, squeezed into our car
and threaded us through the stone village on an impossible road,
where, seemingly, only goats dared to tread, and had us stop at the
back of a house. The woman inside provided her spare room and
quoted a price less than that day's lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The night delivered a full moon against the outline of a castle
along with strange animal sounds, which we never identified,
something between a convention of starlings and tiny pigs facing
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk, as we sat in the square eating cheese with slices of
dried ham, a small white horse appeared. Unsaddled and
unaccompanied, it stood and stared and then went back down the
hill, past a 16th century church.
</P>
<P>
   A wedding reception was finishing up in a rose-filled garden of
an inn in the French country town of Saveterre-de-Bearn. The woman
who ran the inn didn't want names or passports, just gave us a
large skeleton key and nodded toward the red-carpeted wide
staircase. The bed was lumpy, the toilet shuddered in protest and
the one bath towel was as thin as a scarf. It would never qualify
for a B&AMP;B rating in California, but in terms of faded grandeur it
was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Given our own umbrella table and pitchers of red wine, we
watched the families kiss and tease each other, the little girls in
dresses and little boys in short pants shouting in singsong French,
everyone coming together for photos against some moss-covered tower
and finally collecting at long tables to take on platters of food.
</P>
<P>
   I kept thinking that if this were a movie and I were watching
I'd want to be in it. We met up with old friends in Mallorca who 12
years ago went in with others to buy a crumbling stone house
outside the village of Sant Joan. This is not the Mallorca where
Michael Douglas and Claudia Schiffer frolic but the hot, flat
middle of the island. For two months every summer they leave
teaching jobs in San Diego and live here without electricity or hot
water. Their well is in their living room. When they bought the
house it was a few walls and part of a roof, and so each summer
there is a building project. At night they walk into the village
and drink beer and eat ice cream with the locals. They are happily
without access to e-mail, CNN and English-language newspapers and
don't have a phone.
</P>
<P>
   We traveled with friends who were trying to locate relatives in
the Basque country in northern Spain. There was supposed to be an
old aunt in the fishing port of Bermeo but some men in a tavern
told them she had died. Our hostess, however, who runs a small
hotel in the nearby town of Mundaka, was not convinced. Quietly she
took it upon herself to further investigate and made a few phone
calls. By that night she had resurrected the aunt, who had been ill
but is alive enough to have a sweet reunion with her California
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it went. And oh, yes, only one person had
anything anti-American to say. It was the Spaniard who found us a
room for the night in Alquezar. He called the U.S. a bully and
pretty much blamed the Yugoslav war on America. But he thought we
were OK.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
