<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEX-TIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS REVIVE DRIVE FOR WORKPLACE FLEX TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Republican senators introduced a bill Thursday
that would allow wage earners to choose time off instead of
overtime pay and to arrange with their bosses to work more flexible
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, endorsed by business groups, faces an almost
certain challenge from Democrats, who two years ago blocked a
similar bill on the grounds that it undermined labor laws and
risked the abuse of workers by their employers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., said the Family Friendly Workplace
Act would help hourly workers better balance the competing demands
and tensions of work and home. Federal and salaried employees have
benefited from such flexible scheduling for decades, said Ashcroft,
who is sponsoring the bill with Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flexible job schedules could allow a working mother to leave
work early on Friday for a child's doctor's appointment, and then
make up the missed time next week without suffering a loss of
pay,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said employers and workers should be able to hash out
their own scheduling agreements, ``but there's a government hand
that says you can't do this,'' she said, referring to the Fair
Labor Standards Act. Enacted in 1938, the law requires that
employers pay hourly wage earners overtime if they work more than
40 hours in one week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time that we let hourly workers who are often the most
stressed have the relief that they say they need,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   The senators cited a Rutgers University study released in March
that surveyed 1,000 adult workers and found that 87 percent rated
flexible work hours as important.
</P>
<P>
   The Ashcroft-Hutchison proposal, which is co-sponsored by 31
other Republicans, would allow employers and workers to structure a
two-week period such that an employee could work up to 50 hours in
one week and 30 the other. A worker also could choose compensation
at the rate of time-and-a-half off instead of time-and-a-half pay
for each hour of overtime worked.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is supported by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and
the National Federation of Independent Business, which represents
small business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., led a filibuster of similar
legislation in 1997, saying it amounted to an assault on the
traditional work week, undermined labor law and could have resulted
in employers forcing workers to accept time off instead of overtime
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft and Hutchison said this bill would be more popular
because it includes changes such as stiffer penalties to prevent
employers from coercing workers into accepting time off instead of
overtime pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
