<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9542 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEND-GETAWAY20-COX     06-17 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-GETAWAY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Resending to correct the price of adult admission to
Savannah's Juliette Gordon Low Girl Scout National Center. It is
$6.
 &HT;    Scouting out Savannah's history
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ John Berendt's ``Midnight in the Garden of Good
and Evil'' may have created the appetite for stories about the
bizarre side of life in Savannah, but it doesn't hold a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Even tourists being ushered through the 19th century birthplace
home of Juliette Gordon Low, founder of the Girl Scouts, hear the
unusual story of how she became deaf.
</P>
<P>
   One ear went bad when she contracted an ear infection as a
child, and the doctor treated it with silver nitrate, says Jim
Varnedoe, one of several docents who give tours of Low's home.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at her wedding, a grain of rice lodged in her good ear,
and became infected. A different doctor, trying to remove it,
punctured her eardrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said it was so much trouble to listen to other people that
she just did all the talking,'' says Varnedoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible story,'' says Sharon Katsos with a laugh,
adding that it's a story almost everyone who tours the home
remembers. She just finished a trip with 15 Girl Scout Cadettes
from Leesburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd been on a train all night, so you can imagine how much
sleep they got,'' Katsos says. ``But they were just entranced with
the lifestyle, even though they're teenagers.''
</P>
<P>
   Savannah as a whole can have that effect on visitors, even
though Low's home _ now officially the Juliette Gordon Low Girl
Scout National Center _ is just a small part of Savannah, one
antebellum mansion nestled under red oaks and Spanish moss at the
corner of Bull and Oglethorpe streets.
</P>
<P>
   And it's definitely not just for Girl Scouts. One recent day,
the tour groups were primarily two busloads of senior citizens and
a mob of French tourists, who brought their own translator, so that
Varnedoe would pause after every sentence of his practiced spiel
and wait for the French version.
</P>
<P>
   Low, who was born to a wealthy Savannah family, was only 3 years
old when Gen. William Sherman invaded the city in 1864, and she
could remember him paying a courtesy call to her parents (her
father ran a cotton brokerage) and holding her on his lap.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told (Low told it herself, true or not) that she
saw one of Sherman's soldiers missing an arm and asked him where it
was. ``Got it shot off by a rebel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose my father did it,'' the tyke supposedly replied.
``He's shot lots of Yankees!''
</P>
<P>
   Juliette, who was nicknamed Daisy (hence the youngest Girl
Scouts being called Daisies today), married William Low, the son of
a prosperous British shipping magnate, and the two spent much of
their life in England and Scotland. There she became friends with
Sir Robert Baden-Powell, founder of the fledgling Boy Scout
movement, who told her of the thousands of girls who had asked to
join the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Low returned to Savannah in 1912, widowed, childless, 52 years
old, feeling her life had been a failure, and founded the Girl
Scouts, who held their first meeting in the Low house.
</P>
<P>
   The history of Girl Scouts permeates the antiques-filled,
four-story, Regency-style house. In the family parlor is a bust of
Daisy Gordon Lawrence, Low's niece, whom Low registered as the
first official Girl Scout (Daisy, slightly peeved, felt her aunt
should have asked her first). Low was an artist and her oil
paintings hang on the walls of most of the rooms. The painted
porcelain plates in the dining room china cabinet _ depicting
wildlife and flowers _ are by her as well. She even took a ladies'
blacksmithing course and fashioned a set of wrought-iron gates that
stand in the garden behind the house, where Girl Scout troops
sometimes hold ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The house is not wheelchair-friendly (the first stage was built
between 1818 and '21), and the signage outside directing visitors
could be better (go downstairs under the porch to buy tickets
before you wait in line). But while everyone else in Savannah looks
for signs of the Lady Chablis or the statue from the ``Midnight''
cover, at least some go looking for the founder of Girl Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: The Juliette Gordon Low Girl Scout National
Center. 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays (closed Wednesdays),
12:30-4:30 p.m. Sundays. Admission: $6 adults, $3 Girl Scouts,
$5.50 AARP members. 142 Bull St., Savannah. 912-233-4501.If you go
to Savannah . . .
</P>
<P>
   Getting here
</P>
<P>
   It's a four-hour drive from Atlanta. Take I-75 to Macon, then
I-16 to Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   Savannah is famous for the many bed-and-breakfasts in and around
its Historic District, and anyone who's settled into a good one
knows it's a pleasant way to stay here. (Check about air
conditioning when you make the reservation, though; not all
bed-and-breakfasts have it.) The Savannah Convention and Visitors
Bureau (number follows) can help with a selection.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative is to stay on Tybee Island, a strip of land about
4 miles long that borders the Atlantic Ocean and is linked to the
mainland by U.S. 80. Tybee is unlikely to impress visitors who want
to live in luxury, but for the budget-minded, young families, and
people who want to combine some serious beach time with their
Savannah trip, it's worth a try.
</P>
<P>
   While Savannah celebrates its past, from its founding through
the Civil War, through the events of ``Midnight in the Garden,''
Tybee is more like it's stuck in a time-warp of the late '50s to
mid-'60s. As you drive over several bridges to get there, you
wonder if maybe your car radio will revert to AM only.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny, slow-moving ``downtown'' (about four blocks long) has
an old-fashioned dime store called Chu's that's packed to the
rafters with everything imaginable; a place to rent bikes for $10 a
day; several restaurants that don't look as if they've been visited
by the Mobil Guide; and a few hotels. But the beach is enormous,
well-packed and very clean.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing is available from an old-fashioned pier. Some visitors
go to the Tybee lighthouse, which was built in the 1880s, with
stairs going all the way to the top (and landings on which to pause
and catch your breath).
</P>
<P>
   More information: Tybee Island Visitors' Center, 912-786-5444.
On the Web at www.tybeeisland.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around
</P>
<P>
   Savannah was voted one of the 10 Most Walkable Cities in America
by Walking magazine: small-scale, lots of shade and benches, and
James Oglethorpe's original design of town squares full of green
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most enjoyable ways to learn about the city and its
history is through the many walking tours. There are at least three
groups that offer them, and the largest is Savannah Walks
(1-888-728-9255, or www.savwalks.com/).
</P>
<P>
   There are several tours that concentrate on graveyards and ghost
stories (for best effect, do one after dark) and several that
concentrate on ``Midnight in the Garden.'' Tours generally cost
$10-$13 per person (less for children and senior citizens) and take
90 minutes to two hours. A good guide (and guides vary) will be
humorous, dramatic, filled with historical trivia, able to answer
questions, and won't let the occasional fact get in the way of a
really good yarn.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to walking tours, there are horse-drawn carriage
tours, bus tours, and guys who drive bicycle rickshaws.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   Like the bed-and-breakfast industry, Savannah is loaded with
good restaurants, the most famous of which is Elizabeth on 37th
(105 E. 37th St.; 912-236-5447). While Elizabeth's high-class
cuisine is worth a trip, if your plastic doesn't have much room,
there are lower-priced alternatives worth a stop.
</P>
<P>
   The 606 East Cafe (319 W. Congress St., 912-233-2887) is a funky
joint serving burgers, beers, onion rings (stacked by the foot) and
tasty bar food. But most visitors remember the decor, which makes
your typical TGI Fridays look minimalist. The crammed, kitschy
collection includes tons of cow-motif items, an overhead
clothesline, murals and aquariums. Even the waitresses apparently
must be multiple-tattooed before they are hired.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill's Pub (9 Drayton St.; 912-232-8501) had a brief scene
in the movie version of ``Midnight,'' but don't hold that against
it. The building dates to 1850, and although Churchill never came
near the place, the bar itself was shipped over from a British pub
in the 1920s. Traditional pub food includes bubble and squeak (a
casserole of mashed potatoes, cabbage, turkey and ham) and
shepherd's pie (ground beef and mixed veggies under a crust), and
the beers are a mix of British, American and European. Nothing is
more than $7.
</P>
<P>
   Information
</P>
<P>
   Savannah Convention and Visitors Bureau, 1-877-728-2662. Or on
the Web at www.savcvb.com/.
</P>
<P>
   _Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
