<HEADER>
A9550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-17 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT MOVIE REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The (star) word should be replaced with the symbol)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in
New York City. (star) denotes a highly recommended film or series.
Ratings and running times are in parentheses.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``AFTER LIFE,'' starring Arata, Taketoshi Naito and Erika
Oda. Directed by Hirokazu Kore-eda (not rated, 118 minutes). Much
of this transcendently compassionate, gently humorous Japanese film
is set in a drab office building where courteous caseworkers
welcome the week's new clients.
</P>
<P>
   The place turns out not to be a social service agency but a
metaphysical way station where the newcomers are people of all ages
and types who have just died and have three days to select one
memory to take with them into eternity. Before they depart, those
memories will be filmed.
</P>
<P>
   As they tell their stories and make their choices (those who
can't choose remain at the processing center as caseworkers), the
movie becomes a profound meditation on life's meaning and value and
the relationship of movies, memories and dreams (Stephen Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``ANALYZE THIS,'' starring Robert De Niro and Billy
Crystal. Directed by Harold Ramis (R, 110 minutes). The title,
concept and teaming of these co-stars are all funny before the
lights go down, so think of this comedy as an offer you can't
refuse. Cast as a mobster whose confidence is shaken, De Niro is
hilarious simply by playing his role halfway straight, in classic
goodfella style.
</P>
<P>
   His mobster finds just the right comic foil in Crystal as the
psychiatrist who utters the immortal, ``When I got into family
therapy, this wasn't the family I had in mind.'' There's a lot more
where that came from in this breezy comedic treat (Janet Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME,'' starring Mike Myers,
Heather Graham and Elizabeth Hurley. Directed by Jay Roach (PG-13,
95 minutes). There may come a time when even Austin Powers tires of
the words ``Oh, behave!,'' but it isn't here yet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sequel is several love beads short of its
predecessor and more than a few scenes play like outtakes, this is
still a crafty, intermittently hilarious comedy. Myers' neo-Sellers
multiple-personality act is fab even when the material is less so,
and this sequel makes the most of Dr. Evil, his most inspired
creation.
</P>
<P>
   A scatological Scotsman, the film's walking id and bathroom
joke, is more of an acquired taste. Costumes and pop references are
still a hoot, as is the adorably benighted Austin. Ms. Graham makes
terrific eye candy, but doesn't share Ms. Hurley's quick-witted air
of being in on the joke (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``ELECTION,'' starring Matthew Broderick and Reese
Witherspoon. Directed by Alexander Payne (R, 105 minutes). From the
acerbically funny director of ``Citizen Ruth'' comes this caustic
satire of the American electoral process in a high school setting.
</P>
<P>
   Its leading candidate, Tracy Flick, played tartly by Ms.
Witherspoon, has a mother who sought tactical advice for Tracy from
Connie Chung and Elizabeth Dole. Broderick plays the hapless
good-guy teacher who thinks this wicked little front-runner needs
to be stopped. And the hunky newcomer Chris Klein plays Tracy's
reluctant opponent in a style best described as early Keanu.
</P>
<P>
   With a lovely ear for hypocritical conversation, the screenplay
specializes in keeping all the characters a few beats off what they
actually mean (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``ENTRAPMENT,'' starring Sean Connery and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
Directed by Jon Amiel (PG-13, 105 minutes). This glossy caper
summons the days when being a thief was the profession of choice
among debonair movie heroes. And heroines: as the great-looking
insurance investigator who is supposedly investigating Connery's
glamorous super-burglar, Ms. Zeta-Jones makes a smashing gymnast
and heist expert in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   No need to believe the outlandish details of the story; there's
enough verve and charisma to the stars to make the escapade easy on
the eyes. The action sequence, in which the stars hang off the side
of the world's largest skyscraper, is a vertiginous show stopper.
And here's a nice bonus: nobody gets killed (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``LIMBO,'' starring Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio and David
Strathairn. Directed by John Sayles (R, 126 minutes). Part
survivalist drama, part satirical portrait of contemporary Alaska,
Sayles' powerful new film is almost as vast as the great outdoors
it contemplates.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mastrantonio, as a well-traveled folk-rock singer working
Alaskan lounges, and Strathairn, as the brooding local fisherman
with whom she becomes involved, make one of the most compelling
adult couples to be seen in an American film in quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   When they find themselves castaways along with her teen-age
daughter on a remote Alaskan island, the movie becomes both a
suspense thriller and a sorrowful meditation on survivalism,
civilization and the ties that bind. Though marred by an abrupt
ending and glaring literary devices, ``Limbo'' is eminently
worthwhile (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MATRIX,'' starring Keanu Reeves and Laurence Fishburne.
Directed by Andy and Larry Wachowski (R, 120 minutes). The
time-traveling story steeped in virtual reality will be all but
incomprehensible to anyone but techno freaks. And the film borrows
unapologetically from other sci-fi extravaganzas, with a big debt
to ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   But the storytelling is intricately bizarre and the special
effects are indeed special, notably when it comes to midair martial
arts with a gravity-defying gusto. And Reeves shows that you can
look like a Prada model while behaving like an action hero.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main stars here is Bill Pope, an inventive
cinematographer. He and the Wachowskis provide a couch-potato
epiphany; while the characters seem to be performing marvelous
feats, they're often lying stock-still in the grip of virtual
reality (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM,'' starring Rupert Everett, Calista
Flockhart, Kevin Kline and Michelle Pfeiffer. Directed by Michael
Hoffman (PG-13, 115 minutes). This is potluck Shakespeare, with a
wildly uneven range of performances and no clear style holding them
together. Rather than wonder why the actors are wrestling with
bicycles in 19th-century Tuscany (a setting used much less
enchantingly than it might have been), it's best to focus on the
most comfortably Shakespearean performances and not wonder what Ms.
Flockhart is doing here.
</P>
<P>
   Kline makes a perfect Bottom, Everett slinks seductively through
Oberon's role and Ms. Pfeiffer makes an appropriately gorgeous
fairy queen. The younger cast members are largely used as window
dressing for the Leo-Does-Romeo set (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``NOTTING HILL,'' starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant.
Directed by Roger Michell (PG-13, 105 minutes). The most romantic
notion here may be that a Hollywood star as famous as Ms. Roberts
might be out, unassisted, browsing for a book. But it's enough to
bring her together with Grant's bashful bookseller and let two
extraordinarily charming actors play out an intelligent flirtation.
</P>
<P>
   As written by Richard Curtis with frequent wit and welcome
echoes of his ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' this is a bright,
winsome romantic comedy that's as teasing as the characters
themselves, inviting the audience to ponder the movie star's
burdens of being world famous and desperately attractive (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE RED VIOLIN,'' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Jason Flemying,
Greta Scacchi and Don McKellar. Directed by Francois Girard (not
rated, 130 minutes). ``The Red Violin'' follows the colorful
300-plus-year journey of a priceless violin from its construction
in an Italian workshop in 1681 to a contemporary auction in
Montreal. As it makes its way from Vienna to England to Communist
China, the instrument becomes the inspiration for some richly
photographed historical tableaux.
</P>
<P>
   If the movie's narrative energy is undermined by a plodding
screenplay and wooden acting, the music, composed by John
Corigliano and played by Joshua Bell and the London Philharmonia
Orchestra, is sublime (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``RETURN WITH HONOR,'' a documentary directed by Freida Lee Mock
and Terry Sanders (not rated, 102 minutes). This moving story, in
which American pilots captured by the North Vietnamese and held
prisoner for as long as eight and a half years recount their
experiences, rides the wave of patriotism signaled by the successes
of ``Saving Private Ryan'' and Tom Brokaw's ``Greatest
Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The film doesn't question the rightness or wrongness of the
Vietnam War or investigate the prisoners' wartime activities before
they were captured. But as they describe enduring years of torture
and deprivation, their spirits intact, they emerge as traditional
American heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed include Sen. John R. McCain and the former
vice presidential candidate James B. Stockdale (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,'' starring Joseph Fiennes and
Gwyneth Paltrow. Directed by John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty,
sexy and merrily literate delight, with an exhilaratingly clever
premise that only gets better as the film unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm and
turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp dialogue, dares to imagine
whatever it likes about the link between Shakespeare's artistic
passions and his mad yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty.
Meanwhile, this tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an
Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting and conniving
we enjoy today and has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo
and Juliet,'' glitches and all.
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a fine, tempestuous duo, and she
gives the first great, fully realized starring performance of her
career (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,'' starring
Liam Neeson. Directed by George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes).
Stripped of hype and breathless expectations, Lucas' first
installment offers a happy surprise: it's up to snuff. It sustains
the gee-whiz spirit of the series and offers a swashbuckling
extra-galactic getaway, creating illusions that are even more
plausible than the kitchen-raiding raptors of ``Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   While the human stars here are indeed reduced to playing action
figures, they are upstaged by amazing backdrops and hordes of
crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis Carroll in Lucas is
given free rein. The ``Star Wars'' franchise was funnier and
scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't capable of this
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``TEA WITH MUSSOLINI,'' starring Cher, Dame Judi Dench, Joan
Plowright, Dame Maggie Smith and Lily Tomlin. Directed by Franco
Zeffirelli (PG, 117 minutes). The screen divas (especially Dame
Maggie) who give ``Tea With Mussolini'' a patina of class obviously
relish chewing the scenery in this sudsy historical drama (adapted
from a chapter of Zeffirelli's autobiography) about a circle of
English expatriate women living in Florence on the eve of World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Maggie, a quintessential British snob, is the leader of the
pack, nicknamed the Scorpioni, whose comfortable lives are
shattered when the Fascists rise to power and they find themselves
carted off to another city where they are held under house arrest.
Cher is her usual likable self as a free-spending, free-loving
wealthy American heiress and art collector who befriends the group
(Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``THE WINSLOW BOY,'' starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca
Pidgeon and Jeremy Northam. Directed by David Mamet (G, 110
minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's trial
that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down to its
essentials in this adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   Played with unusually effective restraint by a fine cast, it
works as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family
of a cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the
consequences of that accusation. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch
acting style sets the film's tone and gives her suffragist
character a sharp edge (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``BORDERLINE: PAUL ROBESON AND FILM.'' The film career of Paul
Robeson (1898-1976) is the subject of this series opening Friday at
the Museum of Modern Art. The series, which includes all 11 of
Robeson's fiction features, as well as trailers, concert films,
documentaries and newsreels, is a complement to the museum's
exhibition ``Paul Robeson: Artist and Citizen.'' This comprehensive
retrospective traces Robeson's career beginning with his debut in
1925 in ``Body and Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   In that film, directed by Oscar Michaeux and scheduled to be
shown at 1 p.m. Saturday, Robeson stars in a dual role as twin
brothers, one a demonic escaped convict posing as a minister, the
other an unassuming aspiring inventor. The series, which also
includes ``The Emperor Jones'' (1933), ``King Solomon's Mines''
(1937) and ``Tales of Manhattan'' (1942), opens at 6:30 Friday
night with ``Show Boat'' (1936), in which Robeson sings ``Ol' Man
River,'' which became his signature.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing through July 5 at the museum in Manhattan, the series
is free with museum admission: $9.50 for adults, $6.50 for students
and people 65 or older; free for visitors under 16 accompanied by
an adult. Pay what you wish on Fridays from 4:30 to 8:15 p.m.
Information: (212) 708-9400 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
