<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-FESTIVAL-ART-3TA     06-17 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-FESTIVAL-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 BEYOND BOSSA NOVA: NOTES FROM TODAY'S BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(dw) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Take it as coincidence or take it as synchronicity or
take it as one more affirmation of the ways musicians tune in ideas
across boundaries and decades. The JVC Jazz Festival, which starts
its major concerts Friday night and runs through June 27, has two
threads that connect its most promising events, two pervasive
influences that should intersect at many different angles for 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   One is the ever expanding recognition of Brazilian music, past
and present, as more American listeners break the language barrier
and more Brazilian musicians travel internationally. The second is
the lasting influence of Miles Davis, who spawned entire schools of
jazz with each phase of his music from the 1940s well into the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem improbable that Brazilian music and the Davis
legacy would have any bearing on each other. But they keep
intertwining. What Davis shared with Brazilian taste _ a deep
respect for melody, a connoisseurship of rhythm and an appreciation
for subtleties of harmony, texture and mood _ has drawn jazz
musicians to the Brazilian repertory and Brazilian songwriters to
jazz. Both, of course, are creating Afro-Euro-American music,
mongrel styles constantly adapting to the new world. They draw from
everything they meet, including each other.
</P>
<P>
   Among both American and Brazilian performers this year, another
name besides Miles Davis keeps popping up as a model: Joao
Gilberto, the bossa nova singer and guitarist who is a grandmaster
of understatement. The Davis who created the serene, haunted
austerity of ``Kind of Blue'' (which is to be performed by a
tribute group on Tuesday) and the Gilberto who whisper-sang Antonio
Carlos Jobim's sketches of yearning and loss both have qualities
that have all but disappeared from public discourse: discretion and
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better than this there's only silence,'' Caetano Veloso sings
on ``Livro,'' his new album. ``And better than silence only Joao.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the likely pinnacles of the festival are concerts at the
Beacon Theater by songwriters from the Brazilian state of Bahia:
Veloso (on June 27), who has been making groundbreaking music since
the 1960s, and the New York debut of Carlinhos Brown (on Thursday),
a percussionist, songwriter, band leader and producer who has
galvanized Brazilian music in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian culture prides itself on a metaphoric cannibalism,
swallowing and digesting ideas from abroad, and Veloso has been one
of Brazil's most adept syncretists. Along with Gilberto Gil and
other songwriters and singers, he was a leader of the musical
movement called tropicalia, which conceived of Brazil as a
hot-wired nexus of musical information. ``What we did in the late
1960s was a very complicated _ not so sophisticated but complicated
_ comment on the history of the music of Brazil,'' Veloso said by
telephone from Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   The tropicalists tossed together Afro-Brazilian rhythms and rock
guitars, modernist poetry and advertising jingles, bossa novas and
psychedelia; deliberately and gleefully they warped history and
geography. Veloso has sustained and refined his inspiration through
the following decades with a gift for melody, an ear for unexpected
combinations and a preternatural grace in his gentle voice.
</P>
<P>
   His concert on June 27 revolves around one more pan-American
blend. Veloso will be featuring songs from ``Livro,'' which unites
two strands of his broad musical erudition: the Afro-Brazilian
percussion of Bahia and the airy, allusive arrangements that Gil
Evans did for Davis in the late 1940s and 1950s on albums like
``Birth of the Cool,'' ``Sketches of Spain'' and ``Porgy and
Bess.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Veloso's songs range through history and ideas:
there's a song about Alexander the Great, a lighthearted bit of
12-tone music, and ``Manhata,'' a limpid ballad that imagines
Manhattan as an Indian girl and a legendary goddess, ``that
beautiful girl biting the apple.''
</P>
<P>
   The title song of ``Livro'' is about the satisfying physical
presence of books: ``Books are transcendental things,'' Veloso
sings, ``but we can love them with our hands.'' He finished the
album after writing his autobiography, ``Verdade Tropical''
(``Tropical Truth''); Alfred A. Knopf is to publish a translation
next year. The music sets out to bridge his past and his present.
``The cool jazz thing is from the very beginning of my deepest
connection with music,'' Veloso said. He rediscovered it on tour in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were listening on the bus to the old albums by Miles Davis
with Gil Evans, and I was thinking of how much I used to love those
records, and how much I still love them. I think it's Miles' best
period. This new street percussion, from Bahia, from Salvador, is
something that I am living just now. As I composed the songs for
``Livro'' I was thinking of this mixture. I like the tension.''
</P>
<P>
   One song on the album, ``Navio Negreiro'' (``Slave Ship''),
reunites Veloso with Carlinhos Brown, who spent five years as the
percussionist in his band. ``I was amazed by his personal rhythm,
by his mind and by the way he played,'' Veloso said. ``He is a
leader, he has a sense of history, he knows everything about Bahian
carnival and he knows how to make comments on the past and to
create things for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's new album is called ``Omelete Man.'' It is a
declaration, he says, that he is a ``man of mixtures,'' like the
culture he comes from. ``In Brazil, we are already mature in the
mixture of races,'' he said through a translator. ``We learned
through our pain and our happy moments that it is the great way to
peace. Being mixed makes you like the other person a lot more,
because then you start believing that the other person really is
your brother because he has your blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's album includes funk paced by Bahian percussion, sultry
ballads, reggae, revved-up carnival music, old-fashioned samba,
Portuguese fado, a brass band waltz, even a tune steeped in the
Beatles; the lyrics toss in some English with the Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to speak a language that Babel didn't have,'' he
said through a translator. ``In my original culture, the dialect is
already gone. We have Yoruba origins, and we were a nation in
Africa, and here we got mixed. They destroyed the way we used to
speak, but they didn't destroy our discourse because we kept a lot
of things in our collective unconscious. Now I'm looking for newer
forms of communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, Brown deploys guitars, horns and plenty of percussion;
taking turns on various instruments and leading the group in fierce
funk workouts, he can seem like a Brazilian answer to Prince. Like
Prince or George Clinton, he keeps generating spinoff groups. He
discovered and encouraged Lactomia, a group of teen-age
percussionists who play instruments made from buckets, cans and
bottle caps. He introduced Timbalada, a percussion-driven Bahian
pop band that performs in tribal-style face paint. Ogans, a New
York-based band of Bahian drummers that appears most Saturdays at
SOB's, largely models itself on Timbalada.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is also rebuilding Candeal, the poor neighborhood in
Salvador where he lives; along with his own studio and outdoor
performance area, he is sponsoring the construction of housing, a
health center and a music school. ``Through music we can form great
citizens,'' he said. ``Music always comes out of the community, not
one person.''
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
   Another major Brazilian songwriter is to perform through Sunday
at the Blue Note: Ivan Lins, a master of melody and labyrinthine
harmonies whose songs have been championed by American singers from
Sarah Vaughan to Manhattan Transfer (which is also headlining a
festival concert, on Tuesday at Avery Fisher Hall).
</P>
<P>
   He, too, has a heritage of mixtures. The Lins family moved to
Boston in 1947, when he was 2, and stayed for three years before
returning to Brazil. ``The first songs I remember were Stephen
Foster songs and Walt Disney songs,'' Lins said. Back in Brazil, he
was drawn to big-band music and then, when bossa nova arrived, to
jazz, which got him started playing piano. The guitars of the rock
era were too out of tune for him; he preferred bands like Blood,
Sweat and Tears or Chicago, which harked back to big bands. But he
also learned from songwriters like Milton Nascimento and the
tropicalia songwriters, and lately he, too, has been rediscovering
the bossa nova. ``Jobim influenced me dramatically, and it's coming
out much more now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks that harmony is the most important thing in
my music,'' Lins complained good-naturedly. ``But it's not; it's
the melody. When I start to write a song it's to tell a story
melodically. I try to be as simple as I can because that's what
moves me more, when the melody flows easily. But behind this melody
I need to put something like a soundtrack, and that's what the
harmony starts to do. It's like scoring films, to create some
atmosphere.'' Diana Krall's Bossa Nova
</P>
<P>
   Bossa nova, which gave American jazz one of its commercial peaks
in the 1960s, is easing into the music again. Diana Krall, the
pianist and singer who is to make her Carnegie Hall debut on
Wednesday, has been topping jazz charts by singing standards in her
breathy, gently tousled voice. Before making her new album, ``When
I Look in Your Eyes,'' she began listening seriously to Gilberto.
Her producer, Tommy LiPuma, had also produced Gilberto's 1977
album, ``Amoroso,'' which let a hushed orchestra waft chords above
his syncopated guitar. Hearing it led to her making bossa nova
versions of ``Let's Face the Music and Dance'' and ``I've Got You
Under My Skin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the album for quite a while, but I didn't really get
into it until three or four years ago,'' Ms. Krall said. ``There's
a time when you find something and it moves you, and you're glad it
did. I'm not an authority on Brazilian music, but all I really
needed was Joao, and Frank Sinatra singing with Antonio Carlos
Jobim. I might not understand the language, but I understand the
feel. There's a goose bump factor, just like there is when I listen
to opera, like Jussi Bjoerling singing `The Pearl Fishers' with all
that passion. Voices like Joao and Willie Nelson _ with that kind
of quiet _ are a tremendous influence. One day at sound check we
were doing `I've Got You Under My Skin.' I said, `Let's take the
tempo down,' and I realized that by changing a tempo and mood, you
can change the story a little bit without changing the lyrics. It's
fun to take things into a different context.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is to receive one tribute on Tuesday at Symphony Space
with `` `Kind of Blue' at 40,'' when a generation-crossing sextet
plays all the compositions from the 1959 album that established the
idea of modal jazz. The group includes Jimmy Cobb on drums, the
only surviving musician from the original album, and the tenor
saxophonist Ravi Coltrane, whose father, John Coltrane, was in
Davis' group for the album. Wallace Roney on trumpet, Vincent
Herring on alto saxophone, Geri Allen on piano and Buster Williams
on bass complete the sextet.
</P>
<P>
   To make ``Kind of Blue,'' Davis purposefully surprised the
group. ``We didn't have no kind of rehearsal,'' Cobb said. ``He was
like that. He liked to change things up.'' Davis handed the
musicians sketches that called not for songs with defined chord
changes, but for tunes that led to improvisations on modal scales,
which are more open-ended. ``He said, `A lot is up to you,''' Cobb
said.
</P>
<P>
   The music's radical simplicity was a liberation and a challenge,
and ``Kind of Blue'' emerged with a tentative, searching tone
that's also immensely romantic. The album became a durable hit.
``Lots of jazz guys try to make crossover records,'' Cobb said.
``This one just happened by itself. It was just a date that came up
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Davis Tribute
</P>
<P>
   Another Davis tribute takes place Saturday night at Carnegie
Hall, when Cassandra Wilson sings material from her album
``Traveling Miles'' _ selections that span Davis' repertory from
standards to funk, some with Ms. Wilson's own lyrics _ on a bill
with one of the very few singers Davis ever endorsed, Shirley Horn.
While Ms. Horn plays piano in her own poised jazz trio, Ms. Wilson
leads a mutable group including slide guitar and vibraphone. Both
women learned from Davis how to bring a pensive and profound
delicacy to their songs, letting implications linger in their
unhurried phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' reverberations at the festival don't stop there. John
McLaughlin, whose electric guitar work on ``Bitches Brew'' helped
Davis cut through to a rock audience, is performing on June 27 at
Symphony Space, playing acoustic guitar with Indian musicians. Dave
Holland, the bassist when Davis' groups made the transition from
acoustic to electric instruments, has long since returned to
acoustic jazz; he is to lead his quintet on Wednesday at Symphony
Space, sharing a bill with the pianist Brad Mehldau.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the JVC Jazz Festival is another tribute. The trumpeter
and composer Mark Isham, a longtime Davis emulator whose day job is
writing film soundtracks, made his homage official with his most
recent album, ``The Silent Way Project,'' which delves into Davis'
spooky late-1960s funk; he will be performing compositions from
that era on Wednesday and Thursday at the Knitting Factory.
</P>
<P>
   In a major jazz festival concert tonight, two members of Davis'
great mid-1960s quintet, the pianist Herbie Hancock and the
saxophonist Wayne Shorter, are performing as a duo tonight at
Carnegie Hall. Shorter, particularly in his years with Weather
Report and on his solo albums, has long recognized a kinship
between his own sinuous, harmonically ingenious compositions and
Brazilian music. Hancock was part of the studio group for Shorter's
1974 album, ``Native Dancer,'' which introduced many American
listeners to the music of Nascimento, one of Brazil's most
celebrated songwriters. Melody and nuance have a way of getting
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot nationalize music,'' Lins said. ``I understand
music to be like science. A scientist in one place makes a
discovery and finds a cure for a virus, and then later another
scientist uses his discovery to heal something else. Great
musicians give their contributions for the planet, not for one
country.''
</P>
<P>
   From Brubeck to Tropicalia: A Schedule &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The JVC Jazz Festival runs through June 27 at various Manhattan
locations, as well as in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., and Englewood,
N.J. Information: (212) 501-1390; Web site,
www.festivalproductions.net. Tickets are available through
Centercharge, (212) 721-6500; Carnegie Charge, (212) 247-7800;
Ticketmaster, (212) 307-7171, and at concert sites. More than 20
clubs are offering a limited number of two-for-one admissions to
those holding JVC ticket stubs; admission is first come, first
served and is good only on the night on the ticket stub for the
second show on weeknights and the third show on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Lectures are planned at the New School for Social Research, 66
West 12th Street, Greenwich Village; information: (212) 229-5615.
Music and a panel discussion are planned at the Manhattan School of
Music, Broadway and 122d Street, Morningside Heights; information:
(212) 749-2802, extension 524. There will also be a
rhythm-and-blues festival at Metrotech in downtown Brooklyn,
sponsored by the Brooklyn Academy of Music; information: (718)
636-4100. The performances at the Blue Note and the Knitting
Factory are not part of the JVC Festival.
</P>
</TEXT>
