<P>
   COKE-BELGIUM _ The Belgian government is expected today to
decide whether Coca-Cola Co. can resume operations in the company
following a health scare. Following other developments in the
matter. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) Financial and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   w/COKE-IVESTER _ After days of no public reaction to the crises
facing his company overseas, Coca-Cola Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer M. Douglas Ivester sought to reassure Europeans that his
company is ``taking all necessary steps to ensure that all our
products meet the highest quality standards.'' The question we pose
to crisis management experts is, ``Did Ivester wait too late to try
allay customer fears?'' (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-RECREATE _ Delta Air Lines is offering us a seat on a
special flight June 17 in a restored 1931 Travel Air plane. This is
the same type of 5-passenger plane with which Delta began service
as an airline on June 17, 1929. It will fly the same
Dallas-Shreveport-Monroe-Jackson route that a Delta Travel Air flew
that day. Scott Thurston will ride along for a color piece on how
much things have changed on the route over the years. (Thurston,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). TENTATIVE 35.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES _ The airline industry and Senator John McCain,
chairman of a key Senate transportation committee, unveiled
voluntary reforms that would provide more consumer protections for
air passengers. The Air Transport Association, which represents the
largest U.S. airlines, said the plan would give passengers at least
24 hours to decide whether to buy a ticket after it's reserved and
guarantee that mishandled bags are returned within a day. It also
would give passengers the most recent details available on delays,
and provides for some amenities for stranded travelers. Looking for
local reax from passengers at Hartsfield, Delta and consumer
activists. (Joyner/Shelton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONALTOW _ WESY PALM BEACH _A fledgling firm in Boynton Beach
is working to create a national brand in towing, starting with a
name that should be easy to remember, 1-800-AutoTow. The company
was founded two years ago and owns towing companies in three states
- Florida, Texas and Pennsylvania. (Pounds, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
