</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early clouds and a few sprinkles near the Northeast coast will
yield to increasing sunshine as a front moves slowly east off the
Atlantic Seaboard. Most of the day across the Northeast will have a
mixture of sunshine and puffy clouds with temperatures several
degrees below the seasonal average. Scattered afternoon showers
will form over the mountains of northern New England. High pressure
will crest over the region Friday night. As a result, clear skies
and calm winds will allow for rapid cooling tonight, especially in
rural areas of the interior Northeast where isolated frost is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will linger near the Southeast coast as breezes northeast
in the wake of a cold front continue to import moist air. Clouds
and bands of thundershowers will occur near the front from central
and southern Florida to the waters east of the Carolinas. Much of
the interior Southeast will be dry and cool for the season,
however, a few showers will form near the southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   A band of clouds and broken areas of thundershowers marking the
transition zone between the cool air in the East and much warmer
west in the interior west. will cover much of the central and
eastern Plains. Breezes from the south will draw increasingly humid
air north setting the stage for some locally heavy thundershowers
in parts of the central Plains late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be very warm with ample sunshine. Isolated
afternoon thunderstorms will form over some mountain peaks.
Meanwhile, the Pacific Northwest will be cooler with clouds and a
few sprinkles near the coast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Black Blizzards &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, visibilities near Tuscon fell to near zero in
blowing dust, a sign that the season of black blizzards is arriving
in the deserts of the Southwest. Strong solar heating leads to
invisible updrafts, precursors of desert storms. Each year during
the early summer, the air around 15,000 feet moistens providing
fuel for thunderstorms, while air near the surface remains rather
dry. Often, rain falling from the thunderstorms evaporates in the
dry air near the ground. Then, blasts of wind cooled by evaporation
raise palls of dust the so-called ``black blizzards'' that roam the
desert floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
