<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-SPEED-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARS KEEP GETTING FASTER IN NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR is about speed, and no one demonstrated that better than
Dale Jarrett did Sunday when he whipped his Ford around Michigan
Speedway at a track record 173.997 mph to win the Kmart 400.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Jarrett's speed a Michigan record, it was the
fastest stock car race ever run at any track outside of Daytona,
Fla., or Talladega, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1988 when restrictor plates became mandatory at those
two tracks, it was faster than any race run anywhere except
Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   There have been four restrictor plate races at Talladega faster
than Jarrett's run Sunday, Mark Martin setting the record when he
won Talladega's Winston 500 May 10, 1997, with a speed of 188.354
mph, in a race that had no caution flags.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Jarrett ran in a caution-free event Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Daytona and Talladega have been NASCAR's fastest
tracks because they are the biggest at 2.5 and 2.66 miles,
respectively, and also the most steeply banked in the turns except
for the Bristol Motor Speedway in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But Bristol, a half-mile oval, doesn't have nearly as much
straightaway speed as the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictor plates, which reduce horsepower by limiting the
air-fuel mixture reaching the engine, became mandatory at Daytona
and Talladega after the cars began turning laps at well over 200
mph.
</P>
<P>
   And with speeds on the rise again, they have been mentioned as a
possible way to slow the cars down at tracks such as Michigan,
Charlotte and Atlanta. Michigan is two miles in length, Atlanta and
Charlotte are 1.5 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   While Jarrett's run Sunday was an eye opener, the number of
caution flags and the length of the cautions can obscure how fast
cars are going in any given race.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying gives a better indication because it involves a
single car, set up purely to run fast, on the track by itself. Bill
Elliott holds the fastest qualifying time ever, a 212.809 mph lap
prior to Talladega's Winston 500 in May 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Already this season, drivers have shattered qualifying records
at seven of the 13 tracks they have run. There was no qualifying at
California because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy's Paul Andrews, who began the year as Jeremy Mayfield's
crew chief and now holds the same job for Steve Park, thinks NASCAR
rule changes have helped increase speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR gave us more spoiler and valence for the last race last
year at Atlanta and allowed us to keep those rules this year,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the valence _ an air dam that runs under the front of
the car and prevents air from getting under it, causing lift _ and
spoiler _ a metal strip across the back of the car that forces air
down on the rear deck _ creates more downforce, which means faster
corner speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that simple,'' Andrews said. ``We aren't going any faster
in the straightaways. Our increases are all in the corners.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's Rusty Wallace agrees, and adds that ``we're creating more
horsepower than ever and the Goodyear guys are building as durable
and fast a race tire as has ever been built.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace also says that ``we're using setups in qualifying that
were unheard of a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Various spring-shock setups affect qualifying speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Another major factor is aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Either by themselves or by banding together in research and
development groups, the top teams are constantly reshaping pieces
on the car to get the slickest body possible.
</P>
<P>
   And some tracks, such as Michigan, allow for faster racing
because of their design or because they have recently been repaved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver can do a lot to adjust the race car on the track,''
Pontiac's Ward Burton, who finished fourth Sunday, said of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   If a driver is running tight _ where the car doesn't want to
turn _ they can adjust and run lower, Burton said. Or, if the car
is loose _ where the back of the car wants to come around _ the
driver can run higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those places where the driver can adjust the car
just by trying a different line,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Jarrett found the fastest lines. But the cars have been
fast everywhere, and there's no sign they're going to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
