<SLUG> BC-GORE-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AIDE SAYS GOP ATTACKS ON MRS. CLINTON HELP DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK, N.Y. _ Republican attacks on First Lady Hillary
Clinton will galvanize women voters to support her likely bid for
the U.S. Senate as well as Vice President Al Gore's presidential
hopes in the Empire State, Gore's campaign manager said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encourage the Republicans to attack her,'' said Tony Coehlo,
who is directing Gore's White House bid in the 2000 election. ``I
encourage it because not only will women in New York be upset, but
women all over the country will be upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Coehlo spoke to reporters during the second day of a campaign
swing that began Wednesday in Carthage, Tenn., where Gore
officially kicked off his presidential campaign before making brief
visits to Iowa, New Hampshire and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself had little to say about the prospect of a Clinton
Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already addressed that issue,'' Gore told reporters.
``I'm all for it. It will generate enthusiasm (in New York) and
around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   It was left to Coehlo to try to make Republican attacks on
Clinton into a plus for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Led by New York City's feisty mayor, Rudolph Giuliani,
Republicans have criticized Clinton for seeking a Senate seat from
a state where she has never lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Republicans going after Hillary,'' Coehlo said.
``The Republicans want to beat up on Hillary, that's fine. She's
going to activate the Democratic base. I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho dismissed speculation that the Gore campaign dreads a
Clinton Senate candidacy because it would keep the first lady away
from helping the Gore campaign, soak up Democratic campaign
contributions and attract more media attention than Gore's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is far along on its fundraising and won't
compete with Clinton's financing efforts, Coelho said. Clinton's
possible assistance to Gore is ``not an issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Gore campaign cannot survive without Hillary Clinton,
then it is doomed to fail anyway, Coelho said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a job to educate the American public on who Al Gore
is,'' he said. ``And Hillary is not a factor in that. If we can't
relate to the American people, we're not gonna last.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican attacks on Clinton will help not only Clinton and
Gore, but women Democratic Senate candidates in 2000 as well, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans reacted with disdain to Coehlo's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mercurio, a New York political consultant who is a
spokesman for the New York County Republican Committee, teed off on
her lack of a New York background.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is only an issue because it's an issue with
voters,'' he said, citing polls showing that nearly half of New
York's voters are concerned about Clinton's lack of a New York
background. Clinton was born and raised in a Chicago suburb and
lived in Arkansas with then-Gov. Bill Clinton before he became
president in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's down a million votes because she's a carpetbagger,
there's not that many votes she's going to get from a heavy turnout
of women,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
