<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-WALTRIP-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL WALTRIP: CLOSE, BUT STILL A 408-RACE LOSING STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a record Michael Waltrip has learned to live with, a
constant in his life he cannot get away from.
</P>
<P>
   During his Winston Cup career, which began in 1985, Waltrip, 36,
has run 408 races.
</P>
<P>
   He has never won.
</P>
<P>
   That is unmatched except by ageless Dave Marcis. Marcis, 58, has
gone 445 races without victory, but he has won, the last time at
Richmond in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Waltrip has come to winning was in 1996, when he
took NASCAR's all-star race, The Winston.
</P>
<P>
   But The Winston is not an official race and run under a
different format than a regular event. So it does not count.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '90s, I almost won a couple of races,'' said
Waltrip, whose brother, Darrell, is one of NASCAR's all-time win
leaders with 84.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat on a couple of poles. I just really felt that everything
was right there for me, like I was just an inch away from cashing
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got away from me,'' Waltrip said. ``It didn't happen. We
went from close to getting kind of away from it, and now I feel
like I'm close again, and that's an exciting feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Waltrip, the losing streak isn't all his fault.
For the most part, he's never been in a car capable of winning.
</P>
<P>
   His current car owner, Jim Mattei, has never won. Waltrip drove
eight years for Chuck Rider, who has never won, either. Neither did
his first car owner, Dick Bahre.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Wood brothers, for whom Waltrip drove from 1996 to 98,
had fielded a winning entry in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the confidence I need to win. It's just putting all the
pieces of the puzzle together,'' Waltrip said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who you are or how good you can drive or how
good you can set up a car if you and the team don't work closely
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really what I'm focusing on this year, trying to have a
relationship with my crew chief and my car owner and my team so we
all think alike and we do the same things to the race car and we
know what we want out of it. That's the key to getting to victory
lane,'' Waltrip commented.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip knows he needs to win. When teams don't win, they change
drivers, and the longer you go without winning, the harder it is to
get a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started this year before the Daytona 500 thinking this could
be my last season,'' Waltrip said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a great ride, a great team, a great sponsor. If I
don't win races and run well, I might not be able to get a ride
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's reality. That's what I'm faced with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth listening to everybody remind me that I've never
won a race just so I can get to do what I want to do,'' Waltrip
said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9578 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-17 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANGE OF HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Do constituents really expect members of Congress
to keep their word or are people so jaded from years of partisan
hyperbole that they are cynically resigned to hypocrisy in public
office?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, voters are inconsistent. Which way they go depends on
the significance of the promise being broken and the importance of
the whatever group is most intensely offended. It also matters how
much, deep down, they really like the politician in spite of
everything.
</P>
<P>
   By those criteria, Republican Rep. George Nethercutt of
Washington state certainly is, in President George Bush's famous
expression in another context, down in deep doo-doo. He's got a lot
of explaining to do.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt was hailed as a hero in 1994 for defeating House
Speaker Thomas Foley, a congressional veteran of more than three
decades, largely by championing term limits. Nethercutt scoffed at
Foley's long experience, promised to serve only three terms and
announced that ``if I can't effect some change in six years, maybe
I'm in the wrong place.''
</P>
<P>
   By painting Foley as an out-of-touch career politician and
himself as a fresh outsider, Nethercutt won by a slim margin of
fewer than 4,000 votes out of more than 215,000 cast.
</P>
<P>
   Now that his ardent support for term limits collides with his
own political survival, however, Nethercutt sees it differently. He
has discovered the advantages of seniority. An outsider no more, he
says lamely, ``I made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitter laughter from the U.S. embassy in Tokyo, where Foley
is now our ambassador, can be heard all the way to Washington. What
goes around comes around.
</P>
<P>
   It's standard political practice these days for candidates _
from Vice President Al Gore to every Republican ever invented _ to
blame a perceived decline in American ethics, truth-telling and
moral values on President Clinton's bad example. But Nethercutt
couldn't get away with that if he tried.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman not only gave his word that he would serve only
six years but made a big deal out of it. And for selfish reasons
he's now trying to weasel out of his promise. It's his character on
the line, nobody else's.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Nethercutt's campaign got $300,000 from U.S. Term
Limits, the leading advocacy group for that cause. The support was,
needless to say, very helpful. Foley had angered the organization
by challenging the term limits idea, which he correctly viewed as
stupid, unnecessary and potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Now U.S. Term Limits is angry at Nethercutt, whose defection
reinforces the fact that term limits was never a legitimate
philosophical issue but merely a political tool for candidates to
use against incumbents they were trying to replace.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Term Limits threatens to spend $1 million to defeat
Nethercutt. It has already spent $100,000 in his district on ads,
which Nethercutt has ignored, warning, ``Keep Your Word, George.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman now dismisses the group as ``an outside''
organization with no business meddling in his district. For some
mysterious reason, he didn't care about its non-local nature when
he took its campaign money to defeat Foley. His change of heart is
no doubt due to some uplifting epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders of the term limits movement are not kidding even
though Ross Perot has fallen silent on the cause and so have most
presidential candidates. The call for term limits is still in the
GOP platform.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's election may be the turning point that determines
whether the concept dies a deserved, overdue death or remains alive
to bedevil future incumbents. If Nethercutt can get away with
trashing it, others can too. The pledge becomes meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of Congress in addition to Nethercutt are seeking
re-election next year although their time is up under their term
limit pledges. They are Reps. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., and Scott
McInnis, R-Colo. They think their constituents don't care. We'll
see.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., leans toward running but has not yet
announced. Six others, all Republicans, facing similar deadlines
are sticking to their promise.
</P>
<P>
   The term-limits concept has been gradually falling from favor
since the Republicans took over Congress in 1994 and realized the
restrictions might apply to them rather than the Democrats who used
to have control. After the House twice failed to mandate term
limits with a constitutional amendment, the movement's backers have
concentrated on pushing state laws instead.
</P>
<P>
   We are only now seeing the early impact on states that fell for
this foolishness. In Michigan, for instance, a term-limits law
forced out 64 state legislators last year, prompting fears that too
much crucial institutional memory and power have passed from
elected officials to lobbyists, staff members and bureaucrats. U.S.
Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., himself a Washington veteran of more
than four decades, complains that the state has sentenced itself to
be ``run by pygmies.''
</P>
<P>
   Silly as the term-limits concept is, the fact remains that
Nethercutt professed to believe in it so long as it applied to
others. He was an opportunist, seizing on an issue to gain power
for himself. Does that make him no different from any other
ambitious politician or an unreliable fast-talker not worthy of
re-election? Washington state voters have to decide.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail,
at means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
