<HEADLINE>
`TARZAN' A DEPARTURE FROM DISNEY'S RECENT FORMULAIC ANIMATED
MUSICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most critics believe the cycle of Disney animated musicals that
began with ``The Little Mermaid'' in 1989 peaked with ``The Lion
King'' in 1994. The follow-ups _ ``Pocahontas,'' ``Hercules'' and
``Hunchback of Notre Dame'' _ have been profitable but
progressively formulaic and underwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the company _ inspired by the competition from DreamWorks,
Fox and other studio animation wings _ may be edging toward a
comeback. Last summer's ``Mulan'' (minus its offensive and
intrusive Eddie Murphy sequences) was both a moving fable and a
stunning cartoon evocation of ancient China.
</P>
<P>
   And this summer's ``Tarzan'' is even more impressive. It not
only breaks the formula even further, it's a buoyant, often
thrilling piece of animation that more or less does for the Central
African rainforest what ``The Lion King'' did for the East African
savannah.
</P>
<P>
   It's basically the same old Tarzan-the-ape-man story that's been
endlessly recycled in every movie generation since Edgar Rice
Burroughs first wrote it _ though the animators have tried to take
the myth back to its roots with some of the purity of Hugh Hudson's
1984 ``Greystoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, an English family is shipwrecked on the African coast and
the parents are killed by pirates. Their infant son _ later dubbed
Tarzan _ is raised by a group of friendly mountain gorillas and
grows to hunky manhood while walking around on all fours.
</P>
<P>
   One day, an expedition stumbles into this impenetrable corner of
the jungle _ a scientist (Nigel Hawthorne), his daughter, Jane
(Minnie Driver), and a cad of a white hunter (Brian Blessed) _ so
Tarzan (Tony Goldwyn) is suddenly confronted with the culture shock
of his own kind.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie has Tarzan emotionally split between, on
the one hand, his growing sense of human identity and his love for
Jane; and, on the other, his loyalty to his adoptive ape family _
his ``mother,'' Kala (Glenn Close), the stern ape leader Kerchak
(Lance Henriksen) and his boyhood pal Terk (Rosie O'Donnell).
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Mulan'' and all the other recent Disney animated
features, the drawback of the film is its clumsy and unnecessary
comedy-relief secondary characters, who seem thrown in as an excuse
to sell toy figurines _ most prominently, the Rosie O'Donnell-ape
and a bumbling elephant (Wayne Knight, of TV's ``Seinfeld'').
</P>
<P>
   Still, this animated ``Tarzan'' mostly underplays the comic
schtick, and the script does a surprisingly good job of building
its hero's growing internal conflict _ thereby giving the film a
reasonably serious dimension and a theme to which anyone can
relate: the need to find the society in which we truly belong.
</P>
<P>
   The music is by Phil Collins, and his succession of distinctive
pop songs also represents a welcome change of pace from the Andrew
Lloyd Webber-ish style of Alan Menken (and his various lyricists)
that have dominated the scores of the animated musical genre since
the beginning of the cycle in the late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   And the movie definitely delivers in the animation department.
The long opening, which tells the whole story of Tarzan's
upbringing, may be the most rhapsodic and breathtaking animated
sequence the studio has ever created. Elsewhere, the design
imaginatively evokes the magical, idealized Africa of the Burroughs
novels.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzan. Directed by Kevin Lima and Chris Buck. Screenplay by Tab
Murphy, Bob Tzudiker and Noni White. Animated. Voices: Tony
Goldwyn, Minnie Driver, Glenn Close, Nigel Hawthorne, Rosie
O'Donnell. Disney. 88 minutes. Rated G, suitable for all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
