<SLUG> BC-FILM-VIOLIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RED VIOLIN' NEVER REALLY BUILDS UP TO EMOTIONAL MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 25th Seattle International Film Festival is history, but its
spirit will linger over the next year as many of its 200 debuts
return for a regular run. This weekend, two of the higher profile
entries are already back _ both, coincidentally, with a music
theme.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian drama, ``The Red Violin'' was the runner-up in the
best-film competition (it lost to ``Run Lola Run'') and its
director, Francois Girard, placed fifth in the best-director
competition.
</P>
<P>
   It borrows the basic story premise of the 1964 film, ``The
Yellow Rolls Royce,'' only instead of a luxurious yellow
automobile, an acoustically perfect red violin is the device used
to link the stories of the various owners through the years.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with the tale of the 17th-century Italian
craftsman who made the violin as a tribute to his lovely young
wife, then follows the instrument as it passes into the hands of
Austrian monks, a child prodigy, a band of Gypsies, a
self-indulgent British virtuoso, several owners in China over
nearly a century and a Montreal auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its heady SIFF reception and notwithstanding the eight
Genies (Canadian Oscars) it won (including best picture and best
director), the individual stories vary widely in quality and
dramatic interest, and the film never really builds the kind of
emotional momentum that might make its device seem more than a
storytelling gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   But the symphonic score (by John Corigliano) offers a
bittersweet counterpoint to the stories, the performances of Samuel
L. Jackson, Sylvia Chang, Christoph Koncz and Jean-Luc Bideau are
standouts; the Chinese segment (set mostly in Shanghai during the
Cultural Revolution) is strong enough to stand on its own; and the
script builds to a powerful, surprising ending.
</P>
<P>
   The other musical SIFF offering back this weekend for a regular
theatrical engagement is ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' a Cuban-music
concert film directed by Germany's Wim Wenders, which won the
Golden Space Needle Award for best documentary.
</P>
<P>
   It's an account of guitarist Ry Cooder's follow-up journey to
Havana after his Grammy-winning album, ``Buena Vista Social Club,''
revived the careers of a horde of aged Cuban musicians whose
careers had declined or even collapsed after the Castro Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows Cooder as he records a new solo album with
legendary singer Ibrahim Ferrer, intercut with talking-head
interviews with the various ``Buena Vista Social Club'' band
members (some in their 90s), plus footage from a concert in
Amsterdam and the band's 1998 (farewell) performance in Carnegie
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The music is ebullient and addictive, the musicians are
delightfully hammy and the movie is mostly great fun, though it
could definitely use some background narrative on Cuban music and
how it lost its way. And the film's numerous white subtitles
against white backgrounds are often impossible to read.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Violin. Directed by Francois Girard. Written by Don
McKellar and Girard. Cast: Samuel L. Jackson, Greta Scacchi, Sylvia
Chang, Don McKellar. Lions Gate. In English, French, German,
Italian and Mandarin, with English subtitles. 126 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Buena Vista Social Club. Directed by Wim Wenders. Produced by
Ulrich Felsberg. Photographed by Robby Muller and Jurg Widmer.
Documentary. Artisan. 101 minutes. Partly in Spanish with English
subtitles. Rated G, suitable for all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
