<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPRECIATING THE FULL MONTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Good, bad or indifferent, I set out to do a
Full Monty.
</P>
<P>
   And I did, all 4 hours 25 minutes of it. From the birdie at one
through the birdie at 18, and through the many aggravating holes
in-between, wherever Monty went, I went. In the morning mist. In
the mid-morning rain. In the afternoon clouds. Monty swung. I
watched. He doesn't know it, but I am his biggest stateside fan.
</P>
<P>
   I love Colin Montgomerie, every Tuna-looking inch of him. He's
real. He emotes. He says what he thinks. There is no filter. He's
been known to snap at fans. When he plays, there is always the
possibility of a heckler, hence the 18-hole presence of a statie.
``We look after marquee players,'' confided Trooper Walker of the
North Carolina Highway Patrol. ``Monty doesn't always think we're
behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's Colin Montgomerie is also a bright fellow, and
there's something else I like: he is not obsessed with the game.
When he's home, he says, he doesn't play golf. ``That's possibly
why I've been as successful as I have, that I can get away from it
and don't miss it,'' he maintains.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Monty is The Man. Check the Ryder Cup standings. If
there's one guy we know will be at The Country Club representing
the Europeans on the final week in September, it's Colin
Montgomerie. Across the pond, he is royalty. He has won in
Portugal, The Netherlands, Spain, England, Germany, Ireland, and
Dubai, among other locales. The one place he hasn't won is the
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   He played 18 holes of US Open golf at Pinehurst No. 2 Thursday
and he didn't get one break. He was magnificent off the tee. He
struck his irons crisply. But if there was a difference between a
good bounce and a bad bounce, he invariably got the latter. Combine
that with a dicey putting day, and as he walked to the 17th tee he
was 4 over.
</P>
<P>
   But then he birdied the 191-yard par-3 17th with a superb tee
shot and an 8-footer. That was nice, but he wasn't through. He
likewise birdied the 18th, rolling in a 15-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was delighted to finish birdie-birdie,'' he said. ``That
will make dinner taste better; I can assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   He was all smiles at that point, but the post-round interview
session had almost been short-circuited before it started. A TV
sort, anchored to a spot while waiting for the world to present
itself for his perusal, had confused Monty with the following
opening query: ``What did you shoot?''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't what he expected. After a pause, he flashed a rueful
smile and announced that it had been a 72. Later he said, ``I
couldn't believe that question. What if I had shot 80?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a revealing round of golf, speaking, as it did, to the
vagaries of this fascinating course. His driving was robotically
pure. His second shots invariably looked good. But they didn't
always play well. On 4, 6, and 9 he hit what appeared to one and
all to be excellent shots. Each landed on the green. And each
rolled back off the green, as far as 25 feet in arrears. The most
excruciating was on No. 9, a 179-yard par 3. When the tee shot took
flight, things looked very well. But by the time the ball stopped
rolling backward, Monty was stuck with a delicate uphill approach
if he intended to salvage par.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous, that!'' he declared after watching the ball roll
to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a shot that looked as if it might be a hole-in-one at
the US Open, and, my word, it winds up 30 yards away from the
hole,'' he would later say.
</P>
<P>
   The round was incident-free _ or so I thought. But there was a
rumor something had happened at 1. Somebody is supposed to have
said something. There was another story that Monty had stared down
a woman as he left the ninth green. I dunno. Like Sgt. Schultz, I
neither saw nor heard nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with Vijay Singh and Jeff Sluman, Monty mostly kept
company with his caddy, although there were occasional chatty
moments with the man from Fiji. He is a pleasure to watch because
he doesn't fool around. He steps up to the ball, waggles and fires
away. It's the same when he putts. He lines it up quickly and hits
the ball. It wasn't his fault the round took damn near 4 1/2 hours.
His group spent a great deal of time waiting for someone in the
Jose Maria Olazabal-Tom Lehman-Nick Price group ahead of him to
take a shot every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   At least one somebody out there likes him. As he walked off the
10th, having just posted his fifth bogey, a man called out,
``C'mon, Monty, put it together. Let's Go!''
</P>
<P>
   He got his share of polite applause after hitting some nice
second shots, but I got the feeling a man standing near the 18th
green was more representative of his American audience. Informed
that he had birdied 17 and now had a good chance to do the same at
18, the patron said, ``I don't like the man, so I don't really
care.''
</P>
<P>
   The man obviously needs more time to work up an appreciation of
Monty's to rival mine, but time is on Monty's side. He's only 36.
He'll be coming back to play in our big ones for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   And he could have been a lot worse off Thursday without those
chirping birds on 17 and 18. ``You can't win a tournament on
Thursday,'' he says, ``but you can lose it.'' He hasn't lost it
yet. The sun will be out today, and you can forget about seeing a
lot of those 67s on Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
