<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9601 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GENERAL-SPI &LR;      06-17 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GENERAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER' IS A WASHOUT FROM THE START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Producer Mace Neufeld has had great success turning Tom Clancy's
military-themed best sellers (``The Hunt for Red October,'' ``Clear
and Present Danger,'' ``Patriot Games'') into a profitable and
critically acclaimed movie franchise.
</P>
<P>
   With ``The General's Daughter,'' he tries to do the same with a
military-themed best seller by Nelson DeMille, but has considerably
less success. The movie is so bloated, self-righteous and
exploitative, it's hard to imagine anyone staying to the end, much
less demanding a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of Paul Brenner (John Travolta), a warrant
officer and investigator for the U.S. Army's Criminal Investigation
Division, who, while on an undercover assignment on a base in North
Carolina, happens on the rape-murder of a beautiful captain (Leslie
Stefanson).
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the victim was the only daughter of the Army's top
general (James Cromwell), a hero of the Gulf War, a U.S.
presidential contender and Brenner's personal hero. But,
incredibly, the general and his aide (Clarence Williams III)
basically want him to cover up the crime.
</P>
<P>
   And when Brenner and his partner, a rape investigation
specialist (Madeleine Stowe), discover the general's daughter was
having sex with almost every man on the base, as well as making
kinky sex videos in a secret dungeon in her house, the plot
thickens even further.
</P>
<P>
   As it does, there are a couple of unexpected twists and turns,
but as a murder mystery, most of it is highly predictable and, as a
military drama, it gets increasingly implausible, slanderous (to
the Army) and dumb as it rushes toward its not-so-surprising
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The script was co-written by William Goldman, but his
contribution seems to be in the way of pumping up several scenes
with his distinctively combative and ironic dialogue _ making them
seem contrived and glaringly out of sync with the rest of the
film's style.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Hollywood movies that deal with kinky sex (``8 mm''
springs to kind), it plays it both ways: It asks us to abhor the
violence and indignity of rape while it rubs our faces in it with
such explicit, full-frontal glee that it's pretty obvious somebody
behind the camera is turned on.
</P>
<P>
   The direction of Simon West is very much in the Jerry
Bruckheimer-inspired, overblown, sell-every-scene style of his
first film, ``Con-Air.'' Not a single scene or character rings
true, and shame on anyone who can't pick out the murderer in the
first reel.
</P>
<P>
   The cast _ Travolta, Cromwell, James Woods and Timothy Hutton _
is as competent as the script allows it to be, but Stowe is
criminally wasted in a part that requires her to stand around
making bimbo-ish statements or improbably interviewing potential
rapists in a men's locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The General's Daughter. Directed by Simon West. Screenplay by
Christopher Bertolini and William Goldman. Cast: John Travolta,
Madeleine Stowe, James Cromwell, Timothy Hutton. 115 minutes. Rated
R for violence and rape theme.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
