A9602 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PIRATES-SPI &LR;      06-17 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PIRATES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PIRATES OF SILICON VALLEY' A ROLLICKING RIDE SHOWING RISE OF
GATES, JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's all about power.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jobs says so in the early moments of ``Pirates of Silicon
Valley.'' And he's not kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, somewhere along the line from golden Apple to
wormy Apple, he seems to have forgotten his own mantra, believing
simply that being better would be enough to stay ahead of the
Microsoft/IBM duumvirate in the personal-computer game.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning moments of the film, Bill Gates says to a
prospective dead-end Jobs: ``You don't get it, Steve. That doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   How true.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it is all about power. And, as any pirate will admit
when not testifying before a Justice Department tribunal, having a
better ship might get you to Treasure Island first, but being more
devious will usually get you the buried treasure.
</P>
<P>
   As a film, ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' is a rollicking ride
with punchy performances by the principal players, Noah Wyle and
Anthony Michael Hall. But it might have even more value as a primer
on how to succeed in business without really lying. It seems
stealing is easier and more effective.
</P>
<P>
   As Apple co-founder Jobs, Wyle plays a megalomaniac who takes
everything personally. As Microsoft co-founder Gates, Hall plays a
megalomaniac who takes nothing personally. In other words, sticks
and stones may break his bones, but his Windows will never shatter.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the film, writer/director Martyn Burke takes viewers
on an illuminating journey along parallel tracks, spanning about 15
years from the early '70s to the mid '80s, when Jobs, Gates and
their collaborators reinvented the computer business with a little
bit of genius and a lot of guile. Aside from the standard
``artistic license'' disclaimer as to specific times, places and
personalities, Burke vouches for the authenticity of everything in
the movie, right down to the bulldozer race between Gates and Chris
Larson (Marc Worden) in the early days of Microsoft and the nut-out
that Jobs had after his best friend, computer whiz Steve Wozniak,
decided to leave Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Wozniak is one of the few supporting players given a decent
portrayal in the film. Joey Slotnick paints him bright with
youthful innocence, and adds subtle brush strokes to convey a sense
of conscience. Microsofties Paul Allen and Steve Ballmer don't fare
as well. Josh Hopkins' Allen is more wooden than the real article,
and John DiMaggio's interpretation of the effervescent Ballmer is
more cartoon than character study.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Pirates of Silicon Valley,'' premiering Sunday at 8 on
TNT, is a good exploration of the so-called revolution that changed
the high-tech pecking order. And it's fascinating to see that, as
with so many other revolutions, ``power to the people'' is just a
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates of Silicon Valley. Two-hour cable movie about the rise
of the personal-computer industry on the skill and guile of Steve
Jobs and Bill Gates. Starring Noah Wyle, Anthony Michael Hall, Joey
Slotnick and John DiMaggio. Sunday at 8 p.m., 10 p.m. and midnight,
TNT. Repeats Wednesday, 8 p.m.; Friday, 12:30 a.m.; June 26, 8
p.m.; June 27, 1 p.m. and 11 p.m. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
