A9604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FOX-NYT &LR;      06-17 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX BROADCASTING'S CHAIRMAN TO HEAD NEW SPORTS GROUP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Hill, chairman of the Fox Broadcasting Co., is leaving
that post to become the chairman of a new entity, the Fox Sports
Television Group, which will oversee all the worldwide sports media
operations controlled by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Those include not only the Fox television network, which
broadcasts the games of Major League Baseball and the National
Football League, but also the Fox Sports Net, a consortium of 22
regional sports cable channels like MSG and Fox Sports West. Hill
will also be an adviser with international sports operations owned
by the Fox parent company, the News Corp. Those include Sky Sports,
a division of the British-based Sky Television, and ESPN Star
Sports, a satellite sports operation based in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Hill is returning to day-to-day control of Fox's
growing empire in sports. But Hill emphasized he would not have any
involvement with the teams owned, or partly owned, by Fox
Entertainment Group, which include the Los Angeles Dodgers and the
New York Knicks and Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement had been anticipated for months. Hill has long
been expected to return eventually to sports, where he had spent
his entire career until three years ago when he was asked by the
Fox chairman, Rupert Murdoch, to take control of Fox Broadcasting.
In that capacity, he has been in charge of all the operations of
the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   No replacement was named for Hill in his position at Fox
Broadcasting. Fox executives have denied in recent months that the
network leadership will be assumed by Sandy Grushow, the head of
Fox's studio, 20th Century Fox Television. One Fox executive said
Thursday that initially at least Peter Chernin, the president of
the Fox Entertainment Group, would assume more responsibilities for
the network.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who is 53, said he was ``absolutely thrilled'' to be
returning to a job exclusively connected to sports. He is credited
with establishing Fox as a credible sports broadcaster, starting
almost from scratch when the network first acquired the rights to
National Football League games five years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
