A9614 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-FATHERS-DAY-NYT     06-17 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-FATHERS-DAY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONOR THY FATHER IF YOU WOULD HONOR GOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RABBI ELI HECHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   We celebrate the third Sunday in June as Father's Day. Roses are
the Father's Day flowers; red is to be worn for a living father and
white if the father is deceased.
</P>
<P>
   But what does a child do if he or she doesn't have a living or
dead father? How can that be? you wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Bio-ethical dilemmas are on the increase. With the awesome
strides and discoveries made in the medical field we are now facing
fascinating and perplexing problems.
</P>
<P>
   A woman wanting a child may go to a sperm bank. She may use her
own eggs or someone else's. She might use a donor egg and a donor
sperm, have an in vitro fertilization procedure and become a
surrogate mother.
</P>
<P>
   Now, does that child have a father? Will he or she ever
celebrate Father's Day?
</P>
<P>
   I am very sensitive to the couples who want children and must
employ artificial methods to achieve their goals. ``God bless
them,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   My concern is about those who are using these methods because
they do not want to marry or have children in the conventional
manner.
</P>
<P>
   What does Jewish tradition have to offer in the way of
enlightenment? I look toward the Ten Commandments and I realize
that
</P>
<P>
   there are two tablets. On one side it speaks about man and God
while the other side speaks about man and man.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the tablets speak about God, the greatness of
God the relationship of man to God.
</P>
<P>
   The second tablet speaks about inter-human relationships, the
admonitions not to kill, covet, etc.
</P>
<P>
   One would expect the commandment to honor your parents to be on
the second tablet.
</P>
<P>
   I have wondered for many years why it was included in the first
group, where it speaks about the commandments of God? The answer
may be that the child/parent relationship is like God and man's
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   There are three partners to every birth -- God, father and
mother. The material substance is derived from the parents while
God grants spirit and soul, the vital form of man.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the fifth commandment is on the first tablet is to
show that there is a connection between God and man. Awareness of
the parents' role as creative agents leads to contemplation and
recognition of the third partner, the Almighty God, provider of
all. For this reason, God Himself gives honor to parents by
including the commandment of honoring your parents on the first
tablet.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth commandment is a religious principle as well as a
social one.
</P>
<P>
   Proper behavior toward parents is seen as a logical rung in the
ladder leading to the proper behavior toward God. As the saying
goes, ``He who heeds the parent will learn to heed other religious
obligations too.''
</P>
<P>
   If honor due to parents is on the same tablet that speaks of
honoring God, then we need parents who honor God.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Father's Day prayer created by the great Hassidic
master, Rabbi Nachman of Breslov (1772-1810) ``Dear God, teach me
to embody those ideals I would want my children to learn from me.
Let me communicate with my children wisely -- in ways that will
draw their hearts to kindness, to decency and to true wisdom. Dear
God, let me pass on to my children only the good; let them find in
me the values and the behavior I hope to see in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Children with good behavior bring honor to their fathers. A
happy Father's Day to you all.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
