<P>
   SURREALISM-GUGGENHEIM (New York) _ Surrealism, generally thought
of as melting watches and men in bowler hats descending from the
sky, began as a literary movement. The movement in its heyday
always had a literary bent _ a wide angle, in fact, to judge by the
large number of remarkable book illustrations and covers on view in
``Surrealism: Two Private Eyes,'' an exhibition at the Guggenheim
Museum running through Sept. 12. By Vicki Goldberg. (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   BEATLES-COLLECTORS (Undated) _ Respectability has come late to
Beatles collecting. By Allan Kozinn. (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND-MUSIC (Undated) _ Franz Welser-Moest's scheduled
ascendance in 2002 to music director of the Cleveland Orchestra is
hopeful news. Conductors and orchestras are sometimes about
individual and collective personalities, but in some places,
Cleveland among them, the subject is chemistry. By Bernard Holland.
(Moved)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-DISKS (Undated) _ For 20 years home video has thrived on a
simple process: choose a movie, watch it, engage in some thought
and discussion, move on. Now, though, operating on the principle
that nothing gets simpler, along comes the digital video disk (DVD)
to immerse one in films to a degree that will intrigue some and
repel others. DVD invites the average viewer to become a film buff,
defined as one who wants to know all about how the movie was made
and by whom. By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   CHOPIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Music history has its myths and its
debunkers of myths. Beethoven wasn't quite the political idealist
he seems in the story about tearing up the ``Eroica'' dedication
when Napoleon crowned himself Emperor; Schubert wasn't a cheerful
bohemian who died unknown. In the case of Chopin, it is so obvious
that his melodies and arabesques sound like the `bel canto'' opera
of his day that the conventional wisdom has him ``influenced'' by
opera. By Will Crutchfield. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TV-CRITICS (Undated) _ Jeff MacGregor bemoans the life of a
television critic. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ART-VANDYCK(Undated) _ Sometimes his royal patron was slow to
pay, but in the main England was good to Anthony Van Dyck. He first
crossed the Channel at age 21, summoned to the court of James I as
the outstanding disciple of the magisterial Rubens and already a
star in his own right. That brief stay, from late 1620 into early
1621, was a prelude to his reign as ``principalle Paynter in
ordinary their Majesties,'' beginning in 1632. Apart from an
interval back home in Brabant from early 1634 to early 1635, Van
Dyck remained in England for the rest of his too brief life. Death
claimed him at home in Blackfriars in 1641. His bones lie at St.
Paul's. Not that Antwerp ever neglected or forgot him. By Matthew
Gurewitsch. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ART-NY-GALLERY (New York) _ The rich and various history of art
in New York in the 1960s and '70s is being rewritten _ not at any
of the universities where graduate students avidly pore over the
origins of Pop, Minimal and Conceptual Art, nor at the uptown
museums that seem content to keep reinvestigating acknowledged
masters like Jasper Johns and Ellsworth Kelly, but at a
hole-in-the-wall storefront gallery on Thompson Street. By Barry
Schwabsky. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-OPHULS (New York) _ Whatever the summer movies may bring,
it is a safe bet that the most ravishing, romantic images onscreen
this season will be at the Max Ophuls retrospective, starting on
June 25 and running through July 15 at the Film Society of Lincoln
Center's Walter Reade Theater. By Phillip Lopate. (Moved).
</P>
