<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PANEL APPROVES INDIAN MUSEUM ON MALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Commission of Fine Arts gave the Smithsonian
Institution final approval Thursday to build a museum dedicated to
the American Indian on the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extraordinarily significant, at the foot of Capitol
Hill,'' said J. Carter Brown, chairman of the four-member
commission, shortly before it voted unanimously in favor of the
museum's final design. The commission, created by Congress, has the
last word on all designs for buildings in Washington's monument
area.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, to be called the National Museum of the American
Indian, will be built on the last vacant site on the Mall, just
east of the Smithsonian's Hirshhorn Museum.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the Smithsonian dismissed the project's original
architect, Douglas Cardinal, because of delays and contractual
disagreements. The Smithsonian then hired the Polshek Partnership
and Tobey &AMP; Davis, as well as four other design firms with Indians
as principals, to complete the project. The Smithsonian's own
architects also worked on the plans.
</P>
<P>
   In April the commission rejected the Smithsonian's completion of
the design because it did not follow the concept developed by
Cardinal, a noted architect who is of Blackfoot Indian ancestry. In
particular the commission objected to a column that had been placed
in the design to support an overhang that had been a free-standing
cantilevered structure in Cardinal's original version.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian again revised the plans, and that revision was
the design approved Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got rid of that ugly column,'' Brown said in an interview
after the commission voted. He said the Smithsonian's consultants
were confident the overhang would not fall without the column.
</P>
<P>
   The four-member team that made Thursday's presentation of the
revised design included three Indians. One, Donna House, a Navajo
and Oneida from New Mexico, said 30 percent of the museum site
would be forested and 30 percent would be a wetland growing
cattails, which have roles in many Indian ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. House said part of the site would be used to raise crops,
including ancient corn, to indicate the Indian contribution to the
present world's diet.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle will be what is essentially the museum building of
Cardinal's original design, a structure with undulating walls of
rough-hewn limestone, meant to resemble cliffs carved away.
Openings will be aligned so that sunlight will fall upon sacred
objects at the winter and summer solstices.
</P>
<P>
   In deference to Indian culture, Ms. House said, she wanted to
avoid marking the rocks, trees and lanes outside the building with
signs explaining their significance, a concept endorsed by Emily
Malino Scheuer, a designer who is a commission member. Many
Indians, Ms. House said, regard rocks as people. ``We thought that
would be rude'' to attach signs to rocks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the Smithsonian's consultants, Johnpaul Jones, a
Choctaw and Cherokee from Seattle, told the commission that the
museum's restaurant would serve ``an entirely native diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian chief executive officer I. Michael Heyman, who has
announced that he will retire this year, said that the museum was
``clearly going to cost somewhat more'' than the $110 million
originally planned, but that Thursday's approval by the commission
assured that it would be built. The museum is scheduled to open in
2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
