<HEADER>
A9618 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HALL-SPI &LR;      06-17 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HALL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING ABOUT GATES BECAME A MISSION FOR ANTHONY MICHAEL HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's got it down. The awkward hand gestures. The horrible
posture. The back-and-forth rocking motion. The nasal,
all-in-the-head voice.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Michael Hall became so wrapped up in playing the world's
richest man that, six months after finishing ``Pirates of Silicon
Valley,'' he was still seeking out material to learn more about
Bill Gates and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when ``Pirates'' was screened at the Seattle
International Film Festival, Hall admitted during a quick lunch
that he was halfway through Gates' newest book, ``Business  &LR;  the
Speed of Thought: Using a Digital Nervous System.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one resource that wasn't available to him during filming in
Los Angeles last October and November. Nearly everything else
written by or about Gates had found its way into Hall's personal
collection of research material.
</P>
<P>
   Martyn Burke, who wrote and directed the film, jokes now that
``the actor is way farther ahead than the writer/director.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hall, certainly more famous in the mid-'80s after appearing
in the films ``Sixteen Candles'' and ``The Breakfast Club and as a
regular on ``Saturday Night Live,'' admits that Gates has had a
salubrious effect on his life. He says that having played the
Wizard of Windows, he feels a new energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really invigorated my own appreciation for what I do,''
Hall said. ``It sort of gave me a new beginning to do due
diligence, to really make an investment in a performance and not
just show up ... and read the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall theorizes it's because Gates is not a historical figure,
but someone who still walks among us, at least metaphorically, and
fascinates most of us because he's incredibly rich and incredibly
smart.
</P>
<P>
   Even his research into Gates' round-shouldered approach to life
was illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from analyzing photos that he took on a whole
different physicality,'' Hall said of Gates' transition from geeky
college kid to corporate heavyweight. ``It's almost like from the
neck down he's a much older man.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pirates,'' which premieres Sunday at 8 p.m. on TNT, Hall
plays Gates in those early years. As the title suggests, he and his
rival at Apple Computer, Steve Jobs, were masters of _ how shall we
put this? _ assimilating the technogical achievements of others. At
the beginning of the film, both are enthusiastic young
entrepreneurs with lots of brains and even more brass. By the end,
neither is covered in glory.
</P>
<P>
   It means Hall had to portray an enigmatic sort of technocrat.
Or, in the words of director Burke, with Bill Gates, what you you
see is not what you get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael had to capture something that's so hard,'' Burke said.
``A kind of innocence, almost a fecklessness on the outside, but
inside there's this voracious creature that had to keep moving
ahead to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the prospect of playing such a character was
absolutely daunting. But he's thrilled to have had the opportunity.
Now 31, the same age at which Gates became a billionaire after
taking Microsoft public, Hall said, ``It's absolutely the most
incredible thing that's happened in my career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
