<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, June 18. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ As Yugoslav forces completed
their withdrawal from the south of Kosovo and thousands of Serbs
continued to flee the province in long convoys, NATO and church
leaders intensified their appeals for Serbs to remain. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Qyshk, Yugoslavia) _ The accounts in this tiny
corner of Kosovo suggest that the death toll and the carnage may be
even greater than has previously been known. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-VOTE (Kuwait City) _ Until three weeks ago, the law that
laid out who could vote and seek office began ``Each Kuwaiti man.''
Subject to ratification by the next Parliament, it now begins `Each
Kuwaiti.'' The change, which shocked even its supporters, would
bring an end to an era in which political life has been an all-male
preserve. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Congressional action: A tense House
began considering its most significant gun control legislation in
five years, with advocates and opponents locked in a
down-to-the-wire struggle over a dozen proposals including
competing measures to regulate the sales of weapons at guns shows.
In a significant victory for cultural conservatives earlier
Thursday, the House voted 248-180 to include in the legislation a
provision giving the states the right to allow the display of the
Ten Commandants in public places including schools. By Alison
Mitchell and Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   PAYDAY-LOANS (Kokomo, Ind.) _ An unexpected product of the
nation's most prosperous peacetime decade in this century, payday
lending companies are sprouting up all over the country, having
increased in number from 300 seven years ago to nearly 8,000 today.
Operating under names like Check Into Cash, Check 'n Go and Fast
Cash, payday lenders grant loans to workers against their next
paychecks. In return, the companies charge a ``fee,'' typically $15
to $35. At annual rates, the fees normally exceed 300 percent and
400 percent and in some cases they reach four digits. By Peter
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EINSTEIN-BRAIN (Undated) _ The first study of Einstein's
entire brain, 44 years after the intellectual giant's death, has
identified a key region that was significantly larger than the same
area among people with normal intelligence. Scientists say the
anomaly may explain his genius. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-BABIES (Brownsville, Texas) _ Griselda Vidrio thought
there was something oddly familiar about the smile on the infant a
Honduran woman was clutching in her arms at the Border Patrol's
illegal-alien processing center in Brownsville. Sure enough, when
officials looked into it they discovered that the same baby had
been used as a prop by phony parents on at least three and probably
many more occasions. Smugglers had discovered an inadvertent,
humanitarian loophole in the increasingly difficult game of begging
people across the Rio Grande and into the United States. By Rick
Lyman.
</P>
</TEXT>
