<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9620 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREZINSKI-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      06-17 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREZINSKI-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CARTER AIDE SAYS KOSOVO ACCORD FACES CRUCIAL TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The fragile peace agreement in Kosovo faces a
critical test this weekend when the last Yugoslav forces are
scheduled to leave the province, former President Jimmy Carter's
national security adviser said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal of President Slobodan Milosevic's army to leave the
northern zone that borders Serbia could lead to a further crisis
with Russia if their forces team up to gain leverage with NATO,
said Zbigniew Brezinski, still an influential voice on foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a peace agreement Belgrade accepted last
week, Milosevic's forces are to withdraw in phases from Kosovo, a
Serbian province about the size of Connecticut. Troops in the
southern, eastern and western sections of the province have been
departing as NATO forces have moved in.
</P>
<P>
   But the area in northern Kosovo, which is to be under the
control of French forces, ``is the one zone, which conceivably
through Serbian and Russian collusion, a last-minute effort could
be made to somehow alter the arrangement'' by refusing to leave the
area, said Brezinski, who is associated with the non-partisan
Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The region holds particular importance for Belgrade because it
is home to many Serbian Orthodox shrines and most of the province's
ethnic Serbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical time both for evacuating Kosovo and for resolving
some of the differences between NATO and Russia will be Saturday to
Sunday,'' Brezinski said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any surprises are to develop, (this weekend) would be the
time,'' he said. ``We do know already from experience that
surprises have taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   Brezinski was referring to the events of last week, when after
Russia successfully brokered a peace agreement, Moscow dispatched
200 paratroopers to the main airport at Pristina, the capital of
Kosovo, ahead of NATO forces. That happened after Moscow assured
the alliance it would not do so.
</P>
<P>
   The move has sparked high-level concern in Western capitals of a
possible confrontation between NATO and Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and NATO have had a fractious relationship over the
11-week NATO bombing of Yugoslavia that began March 24. Russia
initially sided with Yugoslavia, historically an ally, and then was
instrumental in persuading Milosevic to withdraw his troops from
Kosovo, where they were attacking the ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of States Madeleine Albright and Defense Secretary
William Cohen met in Helsinki Thursday with Russian Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov in an
effort to resolve the airport standoff and Russia's overall role in
the British-led security force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The talks have been snagged over a key Moscow demand that
Russian troops be assigned a sector to patrol as part of an
international peacekeeping force. The United States has objected,
fearing that such a deal could lead to the partition of Kosovo much
like the division of Germany after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, which will eventually deploy 50,000 troops in Kosovo, has
divided the province into five sectors controlled by the France,
Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, said Brezinski, the White House will need to
strike a delicate balance between punishing Russia when its foreign
policy collides with the West's as it has over Moscow's role in
Kosovo and accommodating Russian demands to prevent collisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is particularly dangerous with a power which might be
tempted to repeatedly engage in nuclear brink politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
