<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0618-C     06-17 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON FOCUSED ON BALKANS REBUILDING, BRINGING RUSSIA ALONG ON
KOSOVO
 &HT;    With HILLARY-BALKANS-0618; KOSOVO-KLA-0618.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ President Clinton said he and his
counterparts from six other industrial powers would focus on
rebuilding the war-shattered Balkans in a weekend of talks opening
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The way forward remained occluded late Thursday, however, as
U.S. and Russian negotiators failed after a second day of
negotiations in Helsinki, Finland, to end a week-long squabble over
what role Russian troops might play in NATO peacekeeping operations
in the Serb province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't resolved all the issues,'' Clinton told reporters
in Paris, just before leaving for Cologne. ``The next day or so I
think we'll get it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Defense Secretary
William Cohen are expected to resume negotiations with their
Russian counterparts, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The officials resolved key issues of how Russian troops would
fit into the NATO command and control structure and over control of
the Pristina airport, where some 200 Russian troops took up
postings last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point, however, is Russia's insistence on having
its own sector to patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and NATO reject that approach, fearing it
might lead to a de facto partition of Kosovo by carving out a
territory where only Russia's historic kin, the Serbs, would feel
welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon, in Helsinki with Cohen,
said the two sides' technical experts were working overnight
``refining the details'' of a possible deal. Cohen said there was
no deadline for the negotiations, but the U.S. delegation planned
to leave on Friday for talks with NATO allies in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Topping a crowded agenda before the so-called Group of Seven, or
G-7, is the issue of how the United States and its global partners
will pay the multibillion-dollar tab for the immediate
reconstruction needs in Kosovo and the longer range requirement to
stitch the Balkan countries into the rapidly modernizing fabric of
central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't want the Balkans and Southeastern Europe to be
torn apart in the future by ancient religious and ethnic hatreds,
we have to give them a better tomorrow to work for,'' Clinton said,
adding that he expects a joint G-7 statement on Friday to
underscore the point. ``We are strongly committed to doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Paris, Clinton ruled out using NATO forces to try to
apprehend Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia,
who has been indicted as an alleged war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that we not mislead people about what happens
next,'' Clinton said. ``I do not believe that the NATO allies can
invade Belgrade to try to deliver the indictment, if you will.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been indicted by the United Nations tribunal
investigating war crimes in the Balkans. Milosevic is charged with
three counts of crimes against humanity and a single count of
violating the Geneva Conventions in connection with his role as
commander in chief of Serb forces charged with a long and
lengthening list of alleged atrocities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights workers, returning refugees and NATO peacekeepers
continued to turn up mounting evidence of war crimes inside Kosovo
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Just six days into the NATO peacekeeping mission in Kosovo,
officials have discovered so many mass graves and killing sites and
heard so many wrenching accounts of atrocities that they now
estimate at least 10,000 people were killed in the Serb crackdown
against Kosovar Albanians which began shortly before NATO began its
air bombardment March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, though, that so long as Milosevic remains in power
in Belgrade, his chances of arrest on war crimes charges appear
slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he remains inside the confines of Serbia, presumably he's
beyond the reach of the extradition powers of the other
governments,'' Clinton said in response to a reporter's question
during a news conference with French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does not mean that this is not an important thing, or
that there won't someday be a trial,'' said Clinton. ``But we need
to focus on our obligations, our fundamental humanitarian
obligations to get the Kosovars home and to continue to uncover
whatever evidence of war crimes there is in Kosovo as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Chirac spoke with reporters on the sun-dappled lawn
of the Elysee Palace, where the two leaders met to take up Kosovo
and a host of other issues during the lead-up to the annual summit
of G-7 leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the summit has focused on global economic issues,
a subject to be touched upon here Friday as well. The G-7 leaders
will discuss, for instance, a plan to provide billions of dollars
in debt relief to four dozen of the world's most heavily indebted
poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, the meeting amounts to something akin to a
victory meeting for the key members of the military alliance that
forced Milosevic to yield Kosovo to NATO control after a 78-day
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The G-7 nations are the United States, Britain, Canada, France,
Germany, Italy and Japan. All except Japan are NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
