<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MITROVICA-0618     06-17 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MITROVICA-0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MITROVICA: SERBS LIVE ROUTINELY; ALBANIANS FLOUNDER IN DEATH,
DESTRUCTION
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-KLA-0618; CLINTON-KOSOVO-0618.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ NATO troops opened Mitrovica Thursday to
reveal a community of Serbs almost normal in the routine of life,
and a second city of devastation, death and fearful ethnic
Albanians just blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the two halves of the city, said to be the
pivot point of brutality exported to villages all around, was
formidable.
</P>
<P>
   The face of Mitrovica showed this conflict was not a war of
battling opponents, but a case of one people in power who held the
armaments and wielded them with abandon against undefended
civilians whose community was decimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just now we are getting out a little,'' said Nazmi Idrizi, 38,
who was walking with her three children down the main shopping
street in the Serbian district. There shops were open with window
displays of clothes or shoes, stores had food to sell, and people
strolled in the sunny afternoon licking at ice cream cones.
</P>
<P>
   Idrizi's children had no ice cream, however, because she said
she doesn't have enough money even to buy basic foodstuffs since
her husband was grabbed in a round-up of Kosovar Albanian men in
April and then sent off to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   A few ethnic Albanians ventured out this day because the French
peacekeeping troops of NATO rolled in Thursday morning in the push
to secure all of Kosovo. Tanks were stationed at key intersections
and soldiers warily watched their Serb counterparts who have not
yet withdrawn from this central sector of Kosovo, as they must do
by Sunday under the military agreement approved by the United
Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb troops mostly lounged around kiosks, but gunmen out of
sight periodically ripped off rounds of rat-a-tat-tat that sent
shudders at least through Albanian children of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Over on the Albanian side, there were no shops open and precious
few intact. Homes, too, have been blasted by grenades or shot up by
automatic weapons, and almost every building wears scars of assault
-- busted windows, holes blasted in roofs and walls, blackened
imprints from tongues of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the stores and some homes have been looted and trashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is only on that side where there are Serbs,'' said Zenel
Potoku, 34, who hunkered down in his home during more than 10 weeks
of intense ethnic cleansing by Yugoslav forces and Serb police and
paramilitary gangs. He spent a week in prison just before the Serb
troops agreed to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Potoku said he heard people -- especially men -- who ventured to
the Serb side often had their documents taken or were beaten. He
never went himself.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the sights here is a different experience altogether than
on the Serbian side.
</P>
<P>
   Potoku and his relative Abedon Potoku, 51, showed a burnt house
that was torched just Wednesday night amid a torrent of gunfire.
Some Serbs live in this half of the town that the older man
estimated has 70 percent ethnic Albanian population, and he said he
recognized one of the arsonists as a neighborhood resident.
</P>
<P>
   Telltale clouds of smoke puffed into the sky not far away,
suggesting other buildings had been set afire Thursday and still
were burning.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the Potokus walked two news correspondents another 20
yards into the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   There in the garden of the mosque were found the too familiar
mounds of dirt marked by sticks. They are graves. The men said 18
neighbors perished in those 10 weeks, most killed by Serb forces,
though four were old men who died from lack of food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some other neighbors and I collected the bodies,'' said Abedon
Potoku. ``We went to take the bodies at night.''
</P>
<P>
   They were afraid of being shot in the daytime, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most were found in their homes, and many had been mutilated,
said Abedon Potoku. Some had a cross cut into the face, others had
ears struck off.
</P>
<P>
   The Potokus and others spoke of larger numbers of dead in the
villages surrounding Mitrovica, but warned that the areas are
believed to be heavily mined.
</P>
<P>
   The death and even possible massacres in this area fit the
pattern emerging from around Kosovo. The British government on
Thursday estimated at least 10,000 ethnic Albanians were killed in
this latest round of Balkan conflict, and NATO troops were said to
have found around 100 sites of massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Risley, spokesman for the war crimes tribunal at The Hague,
said Thursday in Pristina that NATO is watching the sites
identified until they can be forensically studied for possible
trial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scope and scale of atrocities that happened to date
greatly exceeded our belief of what had occurred,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been too many incidents ``to write off as accidents
of war,'' he said, and investigators will try both to prove those
crimes happened and also document the chain of command leading back
to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
