<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-BALKANS-0618-     06-17 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-BALKANS-0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST LADY: GLOBALIZATION MUST ADDRESS NEED FOR CIVIL SOCIETY
 &HT;    With CLINTON-KOSOVO-0618.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton took her plea for
nurturing civil society to one of the incubators of Western thought
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the Sorbonne -- the University of Paris, which
traces its academic roots to the 11th Century -- Mrs. Clinton
addressed a crowd that included several hundred students, faculty
and her daughter, Chelsea, U.S. Ambassador to France Felix Rohaytn
and French First Lady Bernadette Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   If globalization -- economic, political and social -- is to
shape the next millennium, Mrs. Clinton said, world leaders have an
obligation to fashion the shape of that globalization, so as to
extend its benefits to the widest possible array of people.
</P>
<P>
   In the most moving part of a speech that lasted nearly an hour,
Mrs. Clinton recounted a story told to her last month by an ethnic
Albanian living in a refugee camp in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   While herded by Serb forces into a railroad station at Kosovo's
provincial capital of Pristina, Mrs. Clinton said, the woman had
lost the grip of three of her children's hands, and thus lost the
children.
</P>
<P>
   In such a world, Mrs. Clinton said, the need to nurture civil
societies -- where tolerance and rule of law win out over hatred
and violence -- is at least as important as harnessing the new
technologies behind accelerating globalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it mean, in a world where cell phones connect us, if
a mother loses three of her children because of a forced
expulsion?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to absorb what we are now learning about mass
graves,'' said Mrs. Clinton. ``It is hard to imagine that this
still goes on, but I can, in my mind's eye, see a little hand
slipping out of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton left Paris for a visit to Palermo, Sicily, where
she was to pay tribute to community efforts to transform a violent
area into a magnet for tourism. She planned to join President
Clinton at the Group of Seven leaders' summit in Cologne, Germany
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is expected to announce soon her candidacy for the
U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
