<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9663 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CHINESE-ATHLETE-H     06-17 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CHINESE-ATHLETE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE WORLD CUP ATHLETE STRIKES A DIPLOMATIC GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ China's Gao Hong, the Charles Barkley of
women's soccer, fearlessly jumped into the political fray. She took
on questions as if they were shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Did she worry about playing the Women's World Cup in America,
given the frosty state of relations between this country and hers?
What did she think of the U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade? And, by the way, what does she think of the food in
Silicon Valley?
</P>
<P>
   ``The food isn't good,'' her interpreter said, ``but she doesn't
know if it's true it's related to the politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Gao had obviously been well-coached on the subject. Her initial
reply was: ``We are always nervous before a big game.'' But the
food line was all her own. To paraphrase the typical sports scout,
you can't coach wit.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, like Sir Charles, maybe Gao will run for governor of
Alabama. Right now, she is here to play a game. She and her
teammates, seeded first in the World Cup, take on Sweden at San
Jose State on Saturday at 5 p.m. The whole world will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Gao will probably be laughing.
</P>
<P>
   She is 31, media-savvy and irrepressible. At Wednesday's news
conference, while 11 other people sat stiffly at the dais,
delivering careful, dull answers, Gao whispered in her coach's ear
a couple of times, giggling openly.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese team has been training in seclusion down in Silicon
Valley, forbidding interviews to American reporters. One observer,
however, has watched practices and noted that when the coach
delivers his stern instructions to the team, Gao usually drops in a
remark that sends her teammates into fits of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, her interpreters had a hard time doing their jobs.
She'd finish talking, and they'd laugh. Even a question as simple
as how she began playing soccer brought on smiles. One interpreter
gave a dry version of the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why,'' a reporter asked, ``was that so funny?''
</P>
<P>
   The interpreter explained: ``It was how she said it. She made it
into a poem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' I thought, ``another athlete who wants to be a rapper.''
</P>
<P>
   Gao turned seriously political for a few seconds. When she was
asked whether women were treated as second-class athletes in China,
much as they have in the United States, she started nodding her
head before the translator was finished posing the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the problem of women all over the world,'' the
interpreter said, distilling Gao's long, impassioned reply.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that she had been a Christian for the last 10
years, that she considered the opportunity to play in the World Cup
a gift from God. She could have been Charlie Ward on his way into
the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be the point of international sports, to
strip away assumptions that we are all so different. The Chinese
team reportedly never considered a boycott of the World Cup, even
though the host country bombed one of its embassies, purportedly by
accident, and launched accusations about stealing military secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe sports transcend these squabbles, leading to more
understanding. Or maybe every country on Earth has become so
sports-crazed that no disagreement can impede the athletic mission.
</P>
<P>
   Win, smile, wink, nod, win, smile, nod, wink, raise an index
finger, sell a few more Nikes. We are the world.
</P>
<P>
   Gao fits neatly into this global village. Her charm will carry
her anywhere. ``OK?'' she asked reporters in English, near the end
of the interviews. ``It's OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Gao did say something mildly critical of the host country, but
even then it was a subtle dig. ``She felt very shocked'' that the
U.S. would bomb the embassy, an interpreter said, ``especially
since the U.S. is a country that respects human rights so much.''
</P>
<P>
   As the interpreter translated that answer, a woman stepped up to
the press table and asked Gao to pose for a picture. She flashed a
huge smile and raised her right hand in the air, two fingers
splayed. She was giving the peace sign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
