<SLUG> BC-BKN-DUNCAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIM DUNCAN EARNS THE ACCOLADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tim Duncan drew a lot of attention and a lot of
praise Thursday. Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy called Duncan ``the
best player in the NBA'' and the modest Spur, while acknowledging
he is comfortable on the court, suggested he also was still
``pretty boring'' off it.
</P>
<P>
   When you score 33 points, collect 16 rebounds, block 2 shots and
lead your team to victory, accolades are going to come your way.
But in Van Gundy's mind, Duncan was Duncan in San Antonio's 89-77
win in Game 1 and that's exactly what he expected.
</P>
<P>
   The coach did not expect his team to get into quick foul trouble
or get scorched from the perimeter by Jaren Jackson. That makes you
wonder if Van Gundy has been paying attention to the Spurs as they
have steamrolled through the playoffs, which continue Friday night
at the Alamodome with Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   They are where they are in large part because of Duncan, but
also because of their perimeter sharpshooters, who take turns
sharing the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need it,'' Duncan said Thursday, referring to the outside
shooting needed to balance his inside game. ``Their confidence has
grown more and more and different people are stepping up. We don't
have just one guy who does it every night. But we do need those
guys to hit those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was the guy in Game 1, hitting five 3-pointers and
scoring 17 points. At other times, it has been Mario Elie, Steve
Kerr, Avery Johnson, or Sean Elliott. It is the recipe for success
in the NBA these days when you have a low-post presence, something
the Rockets did to perfection in winning their two titles in 1994
and 1995 with snipers such as Kenny Smith, Vernon Maxwell, Robert
Horry, Clyde Drexler, and even Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, coaches will let the perimeter players try to beat you
and work hard to stop the inside game. The Knicks couldn't stop
Duncan, couldn't stop David Robinson, and then had to watch Jackson
knock down all those treys, a couple of which were right out of the
World B. Free School.
</P>
<P>
   The perimeter was a major source of concern for the Spurs this
season. Coach Gregg Popovich felt San Antonio lost its series to
Utah last year because of inconsistent perimeter shooting (although
the team, as a whole, shot well in that series). He worked to
address that and brought in Kerr and Elie to join a rehabilitated
Elliott and an improved Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Vive la difference. Elliott has been a big contributor and
basically won Game 2 of the conference finals against Portland with
six treys, including the one known locally as the Memorial Day
Miracle. He didn't play in the postseason last year because of
injuries, but killed Portland with 47 percent 3-point shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr and Elie have come up huge in NBA Finals for other teams;
both have struggled this season. Jackson basically exists in the
league for his 3-point shooting and he had a huge series against
the Lakers (10 of 23 from international waters).
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' Robinson said, ``it was a pitch out and a guess.
You pitched it out to the shooters and hoped the made it. I don't
think we were as confident as we are now. Even Jaren wasn't this
good last year. The confidence level wasn't flowing. This year,
it's just a different feeling when I kick it out now. Even Steve
Kerr, whose struggling, I'll give it to him anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps, of course, to have two big men in the post who not
only like to pass, but are very good at it. Robinson had seven
assists in Game 1, many of them inside feeds to Duncan. Asked
specifically about Duncan, Van Gundy said, ``The way he's playing
now, there's not one man on the planet who can stop him. Even if
you double him, he's still going to get his 25. He wasn't the
reason we lost. We lost because of foul trouble and Jaren
Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, but it's also defining the Spurs to a tee.
Friday night, it could be Robinson and Elliott. Or Duncan and
Johnson. The Spurs have their constants and their unknowns. The
combination has been deadly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
