<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OK'S POSTING OF COMMANDMENTS IN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House, continuing to distance itself from the
Senate's recent approval of several tough gun control measures,
Thursday sought a religious solution to violent juvenile crime,
approving legislation that allows the Ten Commandments to be posted
in schools.
</P>
<P>
   The chief sponsor of the ``Ten Commandments Defense Act
Amendment,'' Representative Robert Aderholt, said the measure
``will not change the moral character of our nation overnight.''
But, the Alabama Republican said, ``it is an important step to
promote morality, and an end of children killing children.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved by 248-180, was castigated by groups such
as the Americans United for the Separation of Church and State as
an unconstitutional blow to religious freedom. The organization's
executive director, the Rev. Barry Lynn of the United Church of
Christ, called the measure ``frighteningly silly,'' adding in an
interview: ``Congress always seems to turn to religion as a
political football when they can't solve the problem they are
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn said the Supreme Court previously has ruled that it is
unconstitutional to post the Ten Commandments in schools due to the
constitutional separation of church and state. But Aderholt
disagreed, saying that his amendment protects the posting of a
``religious symbol'' and does not endorse a specific religion.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the measure came as gun control opponents expressed
optimism that the House would not back Senate-passed legislation
that requires a three-day background check on gun show purchases.
The Senate last month approved that measure with a tie-breaking
vote from Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the House was preparing to vote late on a proposal
backed by the National Rifle Association and sponsored by
Representative John Dingell, a Michigan Democrat and former NRA
board member. The measure would provide a 24-hour waiting period
for gun show purchases, which the Justice Department says is too
brief to perform an adequate investigation of potential purchasers.
Dingell predicted Thursday that his measure would pass and that he
would have the support of perhaps 50 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The potential of such a large defection was a blow to the
Democratic Party and drew the ire of President Clinton. In a
last-ditch effort to stop approval of the Dingell amendment,
Clinton Thursday called at least four Democrats on the phone while
traveling aboard Air Force One during a European trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something in which we have a profound disagreement,''
Clinton told reporters. ``And I believe that John Dingell believes
he's doing the right thing. But I know that most members of
Congress in both parties agree that the gun show loophole, if
closed, would keep more guns out of the hands of criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that while the majority of Americans tell pollsters
that they back gun control, the NRA has used its political
contributions and influence to stop legislation. In the wake of the
Senate's surprising approval of the three-day background check for
gun show purhcases, the NRA has launched an all-out assault on the
legislation in an effort to kill it in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House's effort to pass gun control legislation may
have been hurt inadvertently by Gore, who on Monday asserted that
anyone under 21 years old can walk into a store and buy a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredibly, while these 18 to 20 year olds cannot legally buy
a beer, cannot purchase a bottle of wine, cannot order a drink in a
bar, they can walk into any gun shop, pawn shop, or gun show in
America and buy a handgun,'' Gore said, according to a White House
press release.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides later acknowledged that Gore was mistaken because a
federal law prohibits anyone under 21 years from buying a handgun
at a gun shop, although they can possess firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's statement provided an opening for the NRA to charge that
the White House campaign for gun control is based in
misinformation. ``Members of Congress don't like being misled any
more than the American people,'' NRA executive vice president Wayne
LaPierre said, referring to Gore's comments. ``And this is a matter
of important public policy and a constitutional right. This is not
a time to play fast and loose with the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Carolyn McCarthy, a New York Democrat who was
elected to Congress after a gunman on a Long Island train killed
her husband, led the fight to pass a three-day waiting period for
gun shows. McCarthy, urging the House to adopt a measure similar to
that passed by the Senate, cited the success of a Boston program in
curtailing juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're trying to do, save lives,'' McCarthy said.
``Please don't forget that's what we're trying to do, is save
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The approval of the Ten Commandments amendment marked a success
for Republicans who have been trying to shift the blame from guns
to cultural issues, saying violent images in the media, coupled
with a spiritual vacuum in today's youths, were the root causes of
juvenile violence.
</P>
<P>
   The vote earlier Thursday on the Ten Commandments amendment
prompted debate over whether proponents were abridging religious
freedom. Representative Jerrold Nadler, Democrat of New York,
stressed that there are numerous interpretations of the Ten
Commandments and questioned which one would be posted in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose Ten Commandments? Which version?'' Nadler said. ``The
Catholic version? The Protestant version, or the Jewish version?
They are different, you know. The Hebrew words are the same, but
the translations are very different, reflecting different religious
traditions and different religious beliefs...It was precisely to
avoid divisive questions like this that the First Amendment
commands no establishment of religion, and that is what this
ignorant amendment would overturn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
