u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUWAIT-VOTE-2TAKES-NY     06-17 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-VOTE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING WOMEN THE RIGHT TO VOTE TURNS INTO HOT ISSUE IN KUWAIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT CITY _ Under floodlights in these sweltering nights, the
men who gather to talk politics in outdoor tents are talking now
about whether Kuwait will ever be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Until three weeks ago, the law that laid out who could vote and
seek office in Kuwait began ``Each Kuwaiti man ....'' Subject to
ratification by the next Parliament, it now begins ``Each Kuwaiti
....''
</P>
<P>
   The change, which shocked even its supporters, would bring an
end to an era in which political life in Kuwait has remained an
all-male preserve. Announced in an edict by the emir, Sheik Ahmed
al-Jaber al-Sabah, it has left some Kuwaitis jubilant, many others
aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has to remind the people that this change is against
Islamic law,'' said Mahmoud al-Hobeshi, 43, a businessman, who sees
all-male parliamentary elections for next month as a referendum and
is trying to rally support for candidates who would try to block
the emir's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The religious issue, in fact, is open to interpretation. Sunni
Muslims, prevalent in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, cite a Koranic
injunction against women holding leadership positions. In Iran,
home of the Shiite branch, which has an influential minority in
Kuwait, women can vote and hold office.
</P>
<P>
   With its tradition of a raucous, elected Parliament and a record
of accomplishment for women, Kuwait comes closer than any other
Arab gulf monarchy to being free and democratic. Many people had
expected Jaber, the reclusive 73-year-old leader, to extend the
franchise to women after the Persian Gulf War of 1991, but years of
inaction had raised doubts in many circles about whether it would
ever happen.
</P>
<P>
   In an outpouring of delight, scores of Kuwaiti women flocked to
the emir's palace after his decision to thank him in person. At
least seven women have already announced plans to run for
Parliament in 2003, the first year they would be eligible. But even
in Kuwait, conservatism may yet act as a brake.
</P>
<P>
   In the windows of Villa Moda, a fashionable women's shop along
the Gulf Road, the mannequins hold aloft signs saying, ``Yes to
women's voting.'' But at campaign tents of candidates like Walid
Tubtabai, a strict Islamist, the answer has been a powerful no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do they write, no, no, no,'' said Youssef
al-Falakawi, a Kuwait University professor who has been polling
voters at the nightly gatherings, a staple of Kuwait's highly
personal political system, ``but they tell me, `You've got to tell
the people this is a bad idea.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait may be small, with a population of just 2 million, but
the emir's initiative is being closely watched as a test of Arab
willingness to move further toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, among many American politicians who prodded
Kuwait for years to take the step, welcomed the emir's edict with a
congratulatory letter. Arab and Islamic countries like Egypt, Iran,
Pakistan and Indonesia, where women already play prominent roles,
have also hailed the step.
</P>
<P>
   But from Kuwait's neighbors, including Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates, there has been mostly silence. Among Arab
gulf states, only Qatar has allowed women to vote, in a municipal
election in March. In Oman, two women, elected indirectly, sit on
the Consultative Council.
</P>
<P>
   With a directly elected Parliament, Kuwait was already several
steps ahead of the rest, and the idea that it should now go
further, by allowing women to take part, is likely to unsettle the
Saudis in particular, where women are still quietly crusading for
the right to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Already Kuwaiti women represent 31 percent of the work force;
the prominent positions held by women include rector of Kuwait
University, head of the Kuwait News Agency and ambassador to
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Most Kuwaitis, from both ends of the political spectrum, say
they expect the new Parliament to ratify at least the idea of
allowing women to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a majority of the 50 members to be elected on July 3
turn out to be opposed to the idea, the government would have
insurance because under the Kuwaiti system, another dozen or so
members of the royally appointed Cabinet would also be allowed to
take part in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   To reject the edict outright would also be an extraordinary act
of defiance against the emir, who has remained in the background of
Kuwaiti politics but whose family has ruled Kuwait for more than
200 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that a new Parliament may be willing to
go along with only a half-measure, with members trying to draw the
line at allowing women to hold office. Most Islamist candidates
strongly oppose the idea of women holding office, as do most
candidates from Kuwait's powerful rural tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any problem with giving women the vote, but for a
woman to be a member of Parliament, this is refused,'' said Falih
al-Azab, 34, a police investigator, as he sat among 2,000 other men
on Astroturf and rugs at an outdoor rally for opposition
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment worries women like Fatima al-Abdali, who has
declared herself a candidate in 2003. ``Halfway is not enough,''
said Ms. Abdali, a 40-year-old environmental engineer who has spent
the last 10 years campaigning for a woman's right not only to vote
but also to hold office.
</P>
<P>
   By tradition, Kuwait's elections are held in October, when the
evenings are pleasantly balmy. This election is a rare departure,
brought on by the government's abrupt dismissal in early May of
what it denounced as a do-nothing Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   With daytime temperatures routinely in excess of 115 degrees,
and evening temperatures still in the high 90s, the nightly
politicking now takes place in a kind of perpetual sauna, in which
cold water and lemon juice, not the usual coffee and sticky sweets,
are the favored repast.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the biggest political battles in Kuwait have
been fought over what critics have cast as litmus tests of Islamic
faith: the mixing of the sexes at Kuwait University and the
distribution of un-Islamic books and misprinted copies of the
Koran. To most Kuwaitis, the issues are peripheral, but the effect
of the fights has been a political stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   With the focus now shifted to women's rights, the government has
plunged deliberately into a politically hot issue, one that neither
it nor its allies in Parliament had previously been willing to take
on for themselves, for what may well have been sound political
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kuwaiti conservatives are going to vote now for people who
will not let the ladies vote,'' said Duwaij al-Shammery, a
prominent Islamist whose regular Saturday night open house has
become a setting for even more spirited political talk.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Kuwaitis say they welcome the emir's unexpected
boldness, seeing it as a welcome change from the years of passivity
that followed the Gulf War. They say it reflects not only the
emir's frustration at the legislative standoff, but a decision to
sideline, at least for now, the crown prince and prime minister,
Sheik Saad al-Abdullah, who is the emir's brother and has a
reputation for indecisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   According to diplomats and prominent Kuwaitis, the government is
now effectively run by the deputy prime minister, Sheik Sabah
al-Ahmed al-Jaber al-Sabah, a cousin from the emir's branch of the
family. Sabah, who is also foreign minister, had led a committee
that recommended voting rights for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was coming,'' said Ahmad E. Bishara, a leading Kuwaiti
liberal. ``Kuwaiti women had achieved, de facto, everything there
was to achieve in the professional world. But this was the final
wall they had to cross, and the fact that they have had to wait so
long has been frustrating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-17 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART WORLD NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ancient Egypt Still Thrives
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one years after New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art
created a sensation with its ``Treasures of Tutankhamen'' _ a
blockbuster exhibition that set the Met's all-time attendance
record, with more than 1.2 million visitors _ the museum is bracing
for a repeat performance. ``Egyptian Art in the Age of the
Pyramids,'' a landmark show that has been four years in the making,
opens Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Met isn't the only museum capitalizing on the fascination
with Egyptian art. The Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and the
Virginia Museum of Fine Arts in Richmond, Va., have also scheduled
Egyptian shows. But the Met, which has always had exceptionally
rich Egyptian holdings as well as an exhibition program devoted to
the subject, is considered the leader in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit by the Met, the Reunion des Musees Nationaux in
Paris and the Royal Ontario Museum in Toronto will include about
230 works compiled from private collections and 30 museums
worldwide. Many have not been seen publicly for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fantastic exhibition that marks a seminal moment, the
start of it all,'' said Met director Philippe de Montebello.
``Everything we know about Egypt began here.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is on view through July 12 at the Grand Palais in
Paris, where it has been highly praised by art critics and
particularly well attended.
</P>
<P>
   The show explores the formative time of ancient Egyptian
culture, the Old Kingdom period between about 2650 and 2150 B.C.,
when artists working in all mediums created images that have come
to define Egyptian art.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting new scholarship about dating some objects, exhibition
will include examples of mediums including wood, stone, precious
metals, paintings, reliefs and statuary intended for temples and
tombs.
</P>
<P>
   The Met's installation will include a group of ``reserve
heads,'' three-dimensional portraits excavated from the tombs of
high officials who served King Khufu, the builder of the largest of
the Great Pyramids at Giza. Only 32 of these carvings are known to
exist, and 4 will be on view.
</P>
<P>
   The show will also include a monumental seated statue
representing Khufu's relative Hemiunu, who is thought to be the
architect of one of the Great Pyramids at Giza; a painted stele
depicting Prince Wepemnofret, who was the overseer of the royal
scribes, and a group of heads representing King Khafre, builder of
the second Great Pyramid at Giza.
</P>
<P>
   The show closes at the Met on Jan. 9 and travels to the Royal
Ontario Museum in Toronto, where it will be from Feb. 12 to May 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Met is lending about 16 objects from its collection to
``Pharaohs of the Sun: Akhenaten, Nefertiti, Tutankhamen,'' opening
at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston on Nov. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The show includes 250 pieces _ sculpture, reliefs, ceramics,
jewelry, clothing, tools and furniture _ from the Boston museum's
collection as well as from 35 museums and private collections
around the world. It runs through Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit then moves to the Los Angeles County Museum of Art,
the Art Institute of Chicago and the Rijksmuseum Leiden in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   A third exhibition, ``Splendors of Egypt,'' at the Virginia
Museum of Fine Art through Nov. 28, includes more than 200 works
from 5,000 years ago, compiled from the Pelizaeus Museum in
Hildesheim, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   A Home Run
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Whitney Museum of American Art redefined its
collecting mission 20 years ago, focusing exclusively on
20th-century art and particularly on the work of living Americans.
Yet it still owns a few outstanding examples of folk art and
19th-century paintings.
</P>
<P>
   In January at Sotheby's it sold a group of 23 folk-art paintings
given to the museum in the late 1960s by Edgar William Garbisch and
his wife, Bernice Chrysler Garbisch. But some works that do not fit
the museum's mission remain. One is the sculpture ``Baseball
Player,'' by Samuel Robb, which depicts a mustachioed figure with a
baseball bat resting on his shoulder. The Whitney received it from
the Haffenreffer Collection in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an icon of American folk art, and it was important to me
that it end up in a museum,'' said Whitney director Maxwell
Anderson. So he called Gerard Wertkin, director of the Museum of
American Folk Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max knew we were in the middle of building our collection in
anticipation of our new building,'' Wertkin said. ``We knew the
`Baseball Player' well. It had been in a show in 1986, organized by
us, that was at the IBM Gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   But because the Museum of American Folk Art is busy raising $30
million for its new building, at 45-47 W. 53rd St. in Manhattan, it
wasn't a good time to try to buy the sculpture, which experts value
at between $300,000 and $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wertkin approached William and Mildred Gladstone, collectors of
baseball art and major supporters of the folk-art museum. They
bought the piece from the Whitney for an undisclosed sum and will
let the Museum of American Folk Art show it whenever it likes. The
Gladstones keep the sculpture when it is not on view. Ultimately,
it will go into the museum's collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those arrangements where everyone benefits,''
Wertkin said. ``The Gladstones, the museum and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Richard Koshalek, who has been director of the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles for 19 years, has been named the
president of the Arts Center College of Design in Pasadena, Calif.
He succeeds David R. Brown, who had run the school since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Koshalek said he expected a major expansion. ``My goal is to
make the school a center of international dialogue for the arts and
design,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
