<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING YOU NEED TO KNOW FOR FATHER'S DAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Paul Fleiss &LR; , father of Hollywood Madam  &UR; Heidi &LR; , was  &UR; Leonardo &LR; 
 &UR; DiCaprio &LR; 's pediatrician;  &UR; Robert Redford &LR; 's father was a milkman
in Edinburgh, Scotland;  &UR; Michael Moriarty &LR; 's father was a surgeon
for the Detroit Police Department;  &UR; David Duchovny &LR; 's father wrote
a book called ``The Wisdom of  &UR; Spiro Agnew &LR; '';  &UR; Jerry Stiller &LR; 's
father was a taxi driver;  &UR; Elizabeth McGovern &LR; 's father is a law
professor at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore,  &UR; Kim Basinger &LR; 's father managed a loan company;
 &UR; Jeremy Irons &LR; ' father was an accountant;  &UR; Christina Ricci &LR; 's father
is a primal scream therapist; New Yorker editor  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Remnick &LR; 's father was a dentist;  &UR; Jane Seymour &LR; 's father fled
Poland when the Germans invaded;  &UR; Ted Danson &LR; ,  &UR; Nancy Reagan &LR;  and
 &UR; Steven Jobs &LR;  are adopted;  &UR; David Lee Roth &LR; 's father was an eye
surgeon;  &UR; Jacob Dylan &LR; 's records outsell his father's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NEW MATINEE IDOL IS KING-SIZE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Brian Dennehy &LR; , who won a Tony last week for his performance in
the current New York production of ``Death of a Salesman,'' is
Manhattan's unlikely new sex symbol, reports the New York Observer.
Sixty-year-old Dennehy, who the Observer says ``could eat  &UR; Dustin
Hoffman  &LR; for breakfast,'' appeals to women of a certain age, but
women younger than that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe his appeal, one fan, who had seen ``Salesman''
three times, said, ``I would characterize it as steam heat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about f_ time,'' Dennehy's agent,  &UR; Susan Smith &LR; , told the
weekly. ``We've got this idea of a matinee idol all ass-backwards.
It's been these 12-year-old boys with no brains in their heads who
emote nothing. Brian is that old-fashioned sense of what a man
is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT THE FEET OF AN ARTIST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The BBC says that Italian newspapers report _ we're two tongues
away from the sole of this matter _ that  &UR; Daniel &LR; 
 &UR; Day-Lewis &LR;  is working as a shoemaker's apprentice in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   Day-Lewis is said to be apprenticed to  &UR; Stefano Bemer  &LR; in the
art of making shoes, which should call to mind using the finest
leather and other materials _ oh, grosgrain, velvet, satin _ to
create fabulous footwear, quite a different image from replacing
the Vibram soles on your worn hiking boots.
</P>
<P>
   All this is happening in Florence, where the actor lives with
his wife,  &UR; Rebecca &LR; , and their 1-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ George Stephanopoulos &LR;  is the new anchor of ABC's ``World
News Now,'' which airs after midnight, but media critic  &UR; Marvin &LR; 
 &UR; Kalb &LR;  told the Washington Post it's a terrible idea. ``You're not a
journalist simply because you're a star,'' he said. ``I find all of
this profoundly upsetting, but certainly consistent with the trend
in television news.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mancow Muller &LR; , the disc jockey who left San Francisco after
a stunt on the Bay Bridge resulted in hours of commuting delays and
multiple lawsuits, is being sued for $110 million by the wife of a
rival in Chicago, where he's star of a morning show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Janet Dahl &LR; , whose husband,  &UR; Steve &LR; , presides over a show
that's on at the same time as Muller's, claims that Muller defamed
her, invaded her privacy and intentionally inflicted emotional
distress by ``repeatedly and falsely (referring) to (her) as
engaging in adultery, fornication and sexual promiscuity in the
vilest of terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller said recently, when rumors of the suit were rampant, that
Dahl, who often appeared on her husband's show, is a public figure
and thus is harder to legally defame.
</P>
<P>
   _ MSNBC reports that &UR; Dan Quayle &LR;  uses M.A.C. cosmetics to get
ready for public appearances, a revelation that puffs the chest of
 &UR; John Demsey &LR; , president of the company. ``Isn't this country
wonderful,'' he asked, ``where  &UR; RuPaul &LR;  and Dan Quayle both use
M.A.C. cosmetics?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ C.P. Braestrup &LR; , who rode on an Aspen ski lift last January
with a Disney executive, says the movie man was delighted to tell
him that ``Tarzan'' is the first Disney animated character with
nipples.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Barry Levinson &LR; , who produced ``Homicide,'' turned up at the
Marin JCC this week to hear a talk by  &UR; Richard Belzer &LR; , one of the
stars of the canceled show and author of ``UFOs, JFK and Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``(The basins') half-round hollowed-out shape takes us back to
the myths and purification rituals at the roots of Western
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Architect Michael Graves telling House Beautiful about the
sink _ which is sink-shaped _ in his new line of plumbing fixtures,
as gleaned by Angela Weber.
</P>
</TEXT>
