 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SOCIAL CLUB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Buena Vista Social Club'' communicates the rapture
of Ry Cooder over the bubbling fusion of Afro-Cuban music in a
single scene. The camera tracks across a field to where Cooder sits
on a concrete abutment, which seems to be deteriorating before our
eyes. His head is down, down, he's puffing on one of Havana's
finest smokes, his eyes are closed and his head nods to a lovely,
rhythmic throb. As the camera closes in and enters the area, we see
a bassist and percussionist at work, slapping out a beguiling and
elegant beat. That's just one instance in which ``Buena Vista
Social Club'' shows that it's steeped in a sense of pleasure that
is rare in documentaries. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GENERALS DAUGHTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ John Travolta is so vivid an actor, and his emotional
life in movies is so deep that to see him do what he does in ``The
General's Daughter'' is almost a revelation. Walking through the
picture as Paul Brenner, a military intelligence officer
investigating the particularly outlandish murder of a female
captain who turns out to be the daughter of a general with
political aspirations, Travolta gives off a spirit of acceptance.
After a career of playing characters who feel deeply _ in some
cases, maybe too deeply _ Travolta for the first time acts with a
sense of showy nonchalance. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TARZAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ From the first few beats of tribal drums beneath Walt
Disney Pictures' familiar Cinderella castle logo, you know you're
in for something special. ``Tarzan'' immediately immerses you in
its world, where we're introduced to two different families _ an
enterprising couple and their baby trying to survive in the jungle
after a violent shipwreck, as well as a group of gorillas led by
the imposing Silverback, Kerchak. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RED VIOLIN_FT:UNDATED _ ``Put your anger into your work,''
the violin maker Nicolo (Carlo Cecchi) snarls at one of his
apprentices. And that chance statement turns out to be tragically
true in ``The Red Violin,'' the newest film from Canadian director
Francois Girard, who last flexed his muscles with the pleasing (if
overdirected) ``Thirty-two Short Films About Glenn Gould.'' 500
Elvis Mitchell. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-URIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Author Leon Uris isn't sure whether ``A God in Ruins''
(HarperCollins, $26), his latest novel, is also his last. ``I'm old
enough _ 74, 75 on Aug. 3 _ to think about gracefully going out,
retiring, like (hockey's) Wayne Gretzky and (football's) John
Elway,'' Uris mused in a phone interview from his home outside New
York City. ``If you've had a good long run, you don't want to stay
out in the public eye a little too long. It shouldn't be like Frank
Sinatra's first retirement, which, after a while, got to be a
joke.'' By JEFF GUINN. Story has moved in ``e''s entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ All of the pieces for another technological revolution
are coming together. Just look to the heavens. Between 400 and
1,200 miles above us is an area of space called low-Earth orbit
that is being developed for a high-tech infrastructure that will
make the Internet's current on-ground cable system seem primitive.
The instruments linking this infrastructure have been around for 40
years but have only recently made great boosts in engineering
capabilities and cost reduction, primarily through the efforts of
one small, but brilliant, company. The company's name is Orbital
Sciences Corp., the world's first publicly traded commercial space
company. Its story and that of its celestial industry are revealed
in the book ``Silicon Sky: How One Small Start-Up Went Over the Top
to Beat the Big Boys into Satellite Heaven'' (Perseus Books, 332
pages, $26). By TERESA MCUSIC. Story has moved in ``f'' financial
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Finally, the truth has come out about Gov. George W.
Bush's rebel past. He got busted in Midland, Texas. Not once. Three
times. Busted with a paddle, that is. At 9, young George was nabbed
for disrupting the peace in his fourth-grade classroom _ by using a
ballpoint pen to draw himself a mustache and matching sideburns. In
1956, that landed Bush in the principal's office for a brief lesson
in personal responsibility and three whacks from the feared ``board
of education.'' By BUD KENNEDY. Story has moved in ``k'' commentary
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
