<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICAL VIEW SUITS THE REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ The Revolution are not compiling many points,
either for style or in the Major League Soccer standings. But they
are establishing an identity as pragmatists.
</P>
<P>
   Aesthetic values are out, but so also are the lengthy losing
spells that marked the team in 1997 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the primary concern of player-coach Walter
Zenga as the Revolution prepare for a third match in seven days at
Tampa Bay Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, we have 20 players now,'' Zenga said after the
Revolution tied Columbus, 1-1, then lost the shootout Wednesday
night. ``When we started the season, six or eight players were
always out and we had to work every week with 13 or 14 players.
Now, we have good choices on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three games this week, and it was very hot at Sunday's
game, so it is better for some players to rest. But now we can have
a rotation of players.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga left midfielders Paulo Dos Santos, Edwin Gorter, Jair, and
Kris Kelderman out of the lineup against Columbus. They traveled
with the team, as Zenga brought the entire roster on a trip that
continued to Tampa Thursday. But the Revolution went with a direct
style of play against the Crew, and most of the available
substitutes were likely to only redouble effort rather than help
control the pace of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Zenga and assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi are only
confirming a style that seems to fit the predilections of most of
the Revolution players. There was little attempt at subtlety with
John Harkes directing the midfield. Harkes is the most direct of
midfielders, and most of the Revolution seemed comfortable with his
methods.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Harkes and Joe-Max Moore provided some excellent
opportunities for Jamar Beasley as the Revolution nearly pulled off
an upset. Instead of collapsing near the end of the contest, as
they often have in compiling a 3-12 record against the Crew, the
Revolution assumed the role of the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   This was a sign of changing disposition of the Revolution, who
have endured MLS-record nine-game losing streaks the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy about the personality of the team,'' Zenga said.
``It's not easy to change a team's mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining possession still does not seem to be a Revolution
priority, so the team often must resort to chasing the game, then
attempting to strike quickly. If Beasley can continue to improve,
this style could be effective at times.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley, 19, had three excellent scoring chances after replacing
Giovanni Savarese in the 58th minute. Beasley botched the first and
third of those opportunities, but on the second one he carried the
ball into the penalty area, protected it, and fired an excellent
shot just wide of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley has now played 10 MLS games without scoring, indicating
he is not a pure goal-scorer in the mold of, say, Savarese, who
converted for the Revolution against Columbus. But Beasley has the
ability to create chances, especially as a substitute, even when
the Revolution offense is struggling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
