   LA-SEWAGE (Los Angeles) _ In the first Y2K preparation glitch so
far in Los Angeles, nearly 4 million gallons of sewage spilled into
the Sepulveda Basin when a planned power outage uncovered a
computer program mistake. Workers cleaned up the sewage, but a
swath of a popular park could be closed into next week to ensure
the public's health. By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SLA-FUGITIVE (Los Angeles) _ As former Symbionese Liberation
Army member Kathleen Soliah faces extradition Thursday in
Minnesota, details are emerging about how this Palmdale High School
student turned radical. But a lingering question is: Twenty three
years later, does enough evidence exist to prosecute her, and will
a jury even know what the SLA was? By Phillip Browne and Charles
Bostwick. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHIMP-BABE (Los Angeles) _ The chimpanzees are making monkeys
out of their keepers at the Los Angeles Zoo, as a third surprise
pregnancy yielded another baby Thursday. And guess what? No one
knows who the father could be. Paternity still has not been
determined for another baby that died last month. Widespread
smoking by patrons is apparently having no effect on the fertility
of monkeys. By Lee Condon. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD-ALLSTATE (Los Angeles) _ Allstate Insurance Co. on
Thursday sued nine medical clinics in the Los Angeles area as part
of a sweeping crackdown on what the carrier claims is widespread
medical fraud. The suit seeks a total of $15 million in damages but
the company hopes to settle the case without a trial. One of the
clinics is in Van Nuys. By Gregory J. Wilcox. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FORCE-DIGITAL (Los Angeles) _ The digital revolution starts
today in beautiful downtown Burbank. The AMC 14 will join three
other theaters in the nation in showing a filmless version of
``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace'' to paying audiences for
the first time _ an advancement its backers say ranks on the order
of 1927 showings of ``The Jazz Singer,'' the first movie with
sound. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-PRODUCTS (Los Angeles) _ Mark November has the Pope's
blessing to help put together a licensing and merchandising program
for linens, lamp shades, and furniture based on art objects and
artifacts in the Vatican Treasury Museum. November, a partner with
Los Angeles-based licensing and marketing consulting firm November
Lazar Scher Inc., is also helping set up a chain of stores called
the Vatican Treasury Collection. By Enrique Rivero. (Will move in
the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
