<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina) _ As Yugoslav forces completed their
withdrawal from the south of Kosovo, the NATO-led peacekeeping
forces have been slow to move into the west of the province,
creating a vacuum of authority and the mass reverse exodus of Serb
civilians fearing revenge from the Kosovo Liberation Army. But
after the Bishop of Rasca and Prizren fled the city for his safety
on Wednesday, despite the presence of German troops, NATO and
United Nations officials today moved into higher gear to try to
contain the damage to their reputation for impartiality. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Helsinki, Finland) _ Secretaries Albright and
Cohen continue talks with their Russian counterparts trying to
agree on a Russian peackeeping role in Kosovo. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Cologne, Germany) _ Still trying to sort out the
untidy aftermath of the Kosovo war, President Clinton suggests that
the indictment of Slobodan Milosevic by the war crimes tribunal
would serve to isolate Serbia on the international stage but would
not immediately affect Mr. Milosevic's personal position in
Belgrade. He also urged patience on what the ultimate outcome of
Mr. Milosevic's indictment would be. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Qysky) _ In a little over two hours of wandering
in three small villages near the city of Pec, it became clear that
anyone you asked could point you to graves or places where Kosovo's
Albanian civilians had been killed by Serbs. The accounts in this
tiny corner of Kosovo, emerging as Kosovo Albanians return to their
homes and as journalists and human rights workers begin to range
through the shattered province, suggest that the death toll and the
carnage may be even greater than previously known. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ China calls ``unconvincing'' the
explanation of the NATO bombing of its emabssy in Belgrade offered
during a visit here by Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of
state. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Vermitca) _ Aid workers put up two big signs
with red skulls at the border here today, and they are thinking
about showing a videotape of a cow exploding in a mine field. But
nothing, it seems, can dam the flow of Kosovar refugees: Ignoring
all dangers, more than 13,000 refugees today squeezed through the
crowded crossing point here on the way, finally, home. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Podujevo) _ A jumbled line of tractors, horse
carts and broken-down tanks stretched for nearly six miles into
Serbia from Kosovo today, bringing thousands more displaced Serbs
and a potentially troublesome burden for the Belgrade government.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SHORT (Paris) _ In a telephone interview, Lt. Gen.
Michael Short, who ran the air war, says the West should not expect
another operation like this with no casualties. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PATROL (Dateline to kum) _ On patrol with U.S. troops
helicoptering into the villages of Kosovo; plus a look at how NATO
tries to establish its presence. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
