<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN20-COX     06-17 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On a day for fathers, sons have their special memories
 &HT;    EMBARGOED for Sunday, June 20
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To showcase their dad's colorful character, our
daughters would have chosen a dramatic family moment.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the time he scoffed at our warnings _ and those of
firefighters the world over _ not to burn a Christmas tree in the
fireplace, or the night he helped a rancher deliver a calf by
Caesarean section, or the Christmas Eve he nailed a brass plaque to
the living room mantle to memorialize ``Baby Doe,'' the family's
black Labrador, hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   But sons and their fathers are different. Maybe it's because
dads call on sons more to help ``fix'' things _ cars, stereos,
mowers, whatever. What John Jr. remembered as evidence of his dad's
unique qualities was the knotted fishing line.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trivial ``fix it'' incident my son shared as part of a
toast to his dad at a party given by friends when we moved from
Colorado back to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   John Jr. had stopped by home with his date on the way to a
movie. It was during the three years my husband John and I were
commuting. I was working in Atlanta and he was practicing medicine
in Denver. John Jr. had just returned from a year in Europe after
college, and he was ``batching it'' with his dad for a while.
</P>
<P>
   As our son recalled the story, it was a Saturday afternoon and
my husband was fresh from a fishing trip on the North Platte River.
Before putting away his gear, he decided to untangle a line that
any reasonable person would have tossed. He asked John Jr. to hold
one end, twisting it this way and that, then told him to help
stretch the tangled mess out across the living room floor. My son
and his girlfriend escaped to the movie only after contributing
tediously to the maddening effort _ leaving my husband totally
absorbed in untying multiple knots, one by one.
</P>
<P>
   When John Jr. returned, about three hours later, his father
hadn't budged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, my dad could have bought a new fishing line at the tackle
store or the hardware 15 minutes from home for a few bucks,'' John
Jr. recounted with a chuckle. ``But he didn't. And you know what I
learned from that?''
</P>
<P>
   My oldest daughter and I rolled our eyes. That his father was
stubborn as a mule? Frugal to a fault? Incapable of throwing
anything away? Able to ruin a great outing by obsessing over a
stupid fishing line?
</P>
<P>
   ``That details are important,'' my son declared. ``That details
are very important if you want to succeed in life.''
</P>
<P>
   The story made me think about the things my husband absorbed
from his father. They relate to the values parents convey
unknowingly _ a scary thought for dads and moms.
</P>
<P>
   For John, a surgeon, details are everything. For my
father-in-law, a farmer and a military man, honoring the land, the
living and the dead were primary. Those values were ingrained in
his children. To this day, John is a master at making squash mounds
in the vegetable garden. And he reads every war story he can get
his hands on.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a columnist for the local paper in Clayton, where my
late father-in-law farmed, wrote about passing the Ezzard farm
several years ago in a funeral procession. She looked across the
field and saw a man climb down from his tractor, take off his hat
and bow his head. Col. Ezzard had stopped plowing until the
procession moved past.
</P>
<P>
   Stories of sons and dads abound, like those in our family. Some
are captured in photos, some in family lore, and some in memories
that surface only on Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
