<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FURTHER DEFINES HIMSELF AS A CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK, N.Y._ Vice President Al Gore sought Thursday to bask
in the Clinton administration's years of prosperity while insisting
that the country needs ``a brand new agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of his 2000 presidential campaign, Gore seemed
less interested in distancing himself from President Clinton, as he
did in small ways on Wednesday, than in using his experience as
Clinton's second-in-command to promote his own vision of where the
nation should be in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, campaigning in Manchester, N.H., Gore called for
tax cuts for businesses that invest in high-tech research and said
he would ``invest aggressively'' to create information-age jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to contrast himself with Republican presidential
frontrunner George W. Bush, who has often spoken in generalities,
Gore said, ``I'm going to be talking about my economic ideas in
real specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of his program to spur job growth in the next century was a
restatement of themes he has favored as vice president: continuing
a strong economy, keeping budgets balanced and making
``revolutionary improvements'' in public education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore talked about hooking classrooms up to the Internet _
something he has spearheaded in the Clinton administration _ and
giving tax incentives to workers who set up savings accounts to
help pay for job training.
</P>
<P>
   On Air Force Two, flying between Manchester and New York, Gore
told reporters that the issues of 2001 _ the year the next
president will be inaugurated _ are different from those in 1992
when he first ran with Clinton. A key issue then was the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But now ``our country needs a brand new agenda for dramatic
changes in order to prepare for this brand new era,'' Gore said.
``That's what I represent: new priorities, a new approach while
continuing the prosperity'' that has occurred in the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was only natural that he would want to differentiate
himself from Clinton. ``Any two people are different and I don't
think the American people find that to be a mystery,'' Gore said.
``Certainly the president and I are different.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he has spent the last six years ``trying to help
(Clinton) be the best president he can possibly be.'' Now, however,
Gore said he is ``focused on presenting an agenda for change for
our country as I campaign in my own right, and I'm enjoying it
tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore's campaign manager Tony Coelho insisted that in
distinguishing himself from Clinton, Gore is not seeking to divorce
himself from the president,
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton understands that Al Gore needs to go out and say
who he is,'' Coelho said. ``It's a step we need to take to identify
who this guy is, and Bill Clinton has no problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho dismissed a suggestion that Gore was turning his back on
Clinton by mentioning ``my own values of faith and family'' in his
speeches Wednesday as well as earlier criticizing Clinton's
behavior in the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore talked about his disappointment with the president,
but the president talked about his disappointment with himself,''
Coelho said. ``There's not a lot of difference there.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in New York, standing in front of historic Federal Hall in
the city's financial district, Gore offered more campaign pledges
including pre-schooling for every child, improved teacher quality,
Medicare coverage of senior citizens' prescription drugs, and
``more cops walking the beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a theme he offered Wednesday when he officially
announced his candidacy, Gore said national prosperity and people's
material possessions alone are not the barometer of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we will ultimately be judged by whether we have
strengthened or weakened the families that are the hope and soul of
America,'' he said. ``I am not satisfied. Indeed, I am restless. I
believe we can do better. I believe we must build on our success,
not rest on it.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did Wednesday, Gore found a strong Republican
counterattack. He was greeted Thursday morning in New Hampshire by
a full page newspaper ad paid for by the Republican National
Committee accusing the vice president, a staunch environmentalist,
of wanting ``to eliminate the automobile as we know it.'' The ad
also asked why, after the House voted to impeach Clinton last year,
Gore called him ``one of our greatest presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS activists, as they did Wednesday, dogged his steps,
accusing him of not doing enough to get anti-AIDS medicines to poor
people overseas. In Manchester, they unfurled a banner proclaiming
``AIDS drugs for Africa'' behind the podium where Gore was
speaking. Four protesters were escorted out by police as they
chanted ``Gore's greed kills! Gore's greed kills!''
</P>
<P>
   Here in New York, AIDS activists blew whistles and chanted
similar slogans as Gore was speaking. As he did Wednesday, he said
he was grateful for the First Amendment that guarantees free
speech. He also called for applause for ``those who are exercising
their First Amendment rights.'' Amid the cheers, six demonstrators
were led away by police.
</P>
</TEXT>
