<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO _ PARIS - President Clinton, meeting with French
President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin here
Thursday, said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will likely
escape being brought to trial on war crimes in Kosovo as long as
he's in Serbia because no one has the authority to go in and get
him. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia _ The estimated 4,000 Serbs in
this town were fleeing the American Zone in Kosovo Thursday after
Kosovo Liberation Army rebels began kidnapping members of prominent
Serb families. Hundreds of heavily-armed U.S. 82nd Airborne
Division soldiers rushed to the town and began the dangerous job of
going from one KLA-controlled building to another in an attempt to
locate and release kidnap victims. In one instance, the U.S. forces
found KLA soldiers beating an elderly Serb man who was bound and
helpless. In another case, U.S. soldiers pounced on a KLA rebel who
they feared was about to toss a hand grenade near the American
commander of the American Zone. Thursday's dramatic events here
show the task American and other peacekeeping forces face in trying
to control revenge-minded KLA guerrillas. (Albright, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-QUAKE _ PUEBLA, Mexico _ Many of the buildings damaged
here in Tuesday's earthquake are colonial architectural jewels that
date back hundreds of years. The temblar raises questions about the
future of structures in Puebla and other cities. Loosened by the
earthquake, chunks of brick and plaster were thrown from the
baroque cupolas' graceful arches, landing on a cracked floor at the
state university of Puebla. Stunned by the death of 17 people in
the region _ a toll that was expected to rise _ residents of this
city of 1.2 million also mourned the damage to buildings whose
baroque, renaissance and Arabic-influenced architecture have been a
source of pride and a draw for tourists from around the world.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-REFUGEES _ MIAMI _ They employ rickety rafts or pay
smugglers who use night-vision goggles and even global positioning
satellite systems. Whatever they have to do, they're getting to
Florida. Since last October, 1,440 illegal Cuban immigrants have
reached Florida shores, compared to only 615 who arrived in all of
fiscal 1998. Just last weekend, the U.S. Coast Guard picked up more
than 100 Cubans. The upswing in Cuban boat people has brought about
rumblings of another Mariel boat lift. We look at the reasons for
the upswing, and whether such a boat lift is a real possibility.
(Emling, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   w/CUBA-BOX _ MIAMI _ The latest figures on Cuban refugees trying
to get to the United States. (Emling, Cox News Service). 6.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BELGIUM _ The Belgian government is expected today to
decide whether Coca-Cola Co. can resume operations in the company
following a health scare. Following other developments in the
matter. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) Financial and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ WASHINGTON _ Coverage of House gun control debate.
(Moving toward a showdown on gun restrictions, the House considers
a measure that would permit the Ten Commandments to be posted in
public schools and government buildings, sponsored by Rep. Robert
Aderholt, R-Ala.) (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COMMANDMENTS _ WASHINGTON _ The House votes overwhelmingly to
put the Ten Commandments back in the classroom. By 248-180, House
members approved Rep. Robert Aderholt's amendment to allow states
to decide whether to permit such displays on government property.
House also approves measures allowing religious commemorations in
schools as part of a juvenile justice bill. (Foskett/Manuel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN2000 _ 1) The Common Sense Leadership Fund, the Good
Government for America political action committee (PAC) and the
House Majority Fund have one thing in common, apart from their
unobjectionable names. They belong to Georgians in Congress who use
these PACs to enhance their influence among their colleagues. 2)
U.S. Term Limits has a made-to-order test of effectiveness in a
Washington congressional district. Rep. George Nethercutt who used
a promise of three terms to help oust Speaker Tom Foley in 1994 has
reneged on his pledge. 3) The media's dream match of Hillary vs.
Rudy may not come to pass if a Long Island congressman has his way.
Rep. Rick Lazio is giving every indication that he will join the
race for the Republican nomination for the Senate and with his
solidly Republican base, he could pose a threat to New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. 4) It's been all Bush and Gore on the campaign
trail this week, meaning the other candidates for president have to
shout even louder to be heard in the fast-paced 2000 campaign.
(Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   TXDEM-RESIGNATIONS _ AUSTIN, Texas _The Texas Democratic Party,
looking for a return to its glory days, is also looking for
replacements for three top officials who had been working on that
mission. The party's executive director, finance director and
communications director all quit in recent weeks. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-PREGNANCY _ ATLANTA _ Black women are four times more
likely to die of pregnancy complications as white women, according
to a report issued Thursday by the CDC. That ratio also holds true
for Georgia, where 20 black women died in pregnancy for every 5
white women from 1987-1996. The disparity, which has not improved
in 10 years and is one of the worst racial differences in public
health, is due partly to lower access to health care and partly to
diseases such as hypertension to which blacks are more vulnerable.
(McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FAULDER EXECUTION _ HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Candadian Joseph Stanley
Faulder is scheduled to be executed after 7 p.m. EDT today.
News-Journal staffers in Huntsville are Becky Bell, reporter, and
Kevin Green, photographer. Neither will witness the execution but
will be outside with protestors. Family members of murder victim
Inez Phillips have told us they will issue a prepared statement
only after Faulder's death. A number of her family will witness the
execution. (Bell, Longview News-Journal). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTHOUSE _ BUXTON, N.C. _ When Outer Banks native Dewey Parr
ponders the future of the crook-shaped island of Hatteras, he looks
not at the majestic striped lighthouse, poised for a historic move
starting today. Parr foresees changes potentially more monumental
than the rescue of the 208-foot-tall beacon of granite and rosy-red
brick from threatening waves. Many residents who opposed the Cape
Hatteras Lighthouse's move now worry what will happen once the
129-year-old federally owned landmark is no longer perched over the
Atlantic. If the three manmade barriers which held back the sea are
allowed to deteriorate, townsfolk fear tides already eroding the
dunes would creep toward the motels, fishing tackle shops and
cottages of Buxton. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLA-LOTTO _ Gov. Jeb Bush taps an Ohio Lottery executive to head
Florida's lottery at a time the GMAE is suffering declining sales.
David Griffin, a former captain of Penn's basketball team, becomes
the first man to head the state's 10-year-old lottery and the
second highest ranking black in the Bush administration. (Elmore,
Palm Beach Post). 10.
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-PLUNGE _ LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ It nearly killed him last
year, but Mayor Tom Ramiccio vows he'll again make the annual July
4 trek across what he calls Palm Beach County's biggest toilet: the
Intracoastal Waterway. This time, though, he'll take the seventh
annual one-mile ``Plunge Against the Grunge'' in a donated plastic
bubble. (McCabe, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-ANTS _ AUSTIN, Texas _Watch out, imported fire ants: Your
historic antagonists from the old country are settling in in South
Texas. Gnat-sized flies, imported from Brazil, bred in Austin, and
released in February near Laredo, seem to be thriving. Despite heat
and drought, they are reproducing on their own and attacking
imported fire ants every day. (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HIT-ROADRAGE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A driver was so angry at
a pedestrian who cursed her that she turned her car around, ran
into the woman and then made another U-turn to ram the pedestrian
head-on, investigators said. (Scharnhorst, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHOR-RAISED _ JUPITER, Fla. _ Two barnacle-encrusted cannons
and an anchor from the wrecked Spanish ship San Miguel de Archangel
were raised recently from the sandy bottom of Jupiter Inlet, where
they had lain awaiting restoration. (Brogan, Palm Beach Post).
MOVED.
</P>
