<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EINSTEIN-BRAIN-BOS &LR;      06-17 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EINSTEIN-BRAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW THEORY ON EINSTEIN BRAIN MEETS SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What about Einstein's brain made him a genius?
</P>
<P>
   In a study in the latest medical journal Lancet, a Canadian
neuroscientist and her colleagues say they have detected
significant differences in the structure of Einstein's brain that
might help account for his superior intellect, supporting findings
from a 1985 study by California researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Einstein died in 1955 from a ruptured abdominal
aneurysm, and his brain taken out during an autopsy by pathologist
Thomas Harvey, it has been the subject of fascination. Einstein's
family did not give permission for his brain to be excised at the
time, and only later consented.
</P>
<P>
   At least three groups of researchers have analyzed Einstein's
brain and found differences, including the 1985 California study, a
1996 Alabama study and the new Lancet study, written by
neuroscientist Sandra Witelson, Harvey, and a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest analysis, the researchers report that a part of
Einstein's brain _ the inferior parietal region, long considered
the seat of mathematical thought and visual and spatial ability _
was 15 percent wider when compared with the brains of people with
normal intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein's brain was also unique for not having a groove, called
a sulcus, that normally runs through this part of the brain. The
researchers theorize that that absence of a groove may have allowed
more neurons _ the brain cells that do the thinking _ to establish
connections between each other.
</P>
<P>
   But other scientists were critical of these findings, deploring
the circumstances of the brain being taken out without the family's
permission nearly 45 years ago, and questioning the effect of the
chemicals the tissue has been steeped in all this time. One even
called the examination of Einstein's brain ``macabre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A case could be made that it was stolen, and it caused anguish
to the family that this was done,'' said Gerald Holton, a Harvard
professor of physics and the history of science, who has written
several books about Einstein and his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are medically informed might say that there is some
merit in doing it. I myself could not say that. I just maintain my
suspicion,'' said Holton, adding that to him, the pursuit is ``a
macabre business.''
</P>
<P>
   The study in Lancet is just the latest example of mankind's
fascination with trying to understand the brain, particularly that
of Einstein and other exceptional people.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1800s, there was the ``science'' of phrenology, or the
attempt at understanding a person's character by examining bumps on
the skull. Today, there are magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and
positron emission tomography (PET) scans of living brains in
action, in the continued attempt to match brain structure with
function.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J. Allan Hobson, a Harvard psychiatrist and
neurophysiologist who has also written about Einstein, raised
questions about these findings as well. ``We've been burned so many
times by strong claims of concrete correlation between area X and
symptom Y. It's phrenology revisited. `He's got a parietal bump,
therefore he's a genius.' I'd be very cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the authors of the 1985 California paper,
neuroscientist Marian Diamond, said these latest findings support
what she and her colleagues found _ an unusually large number of
glial cells, which nourish the neurons that do the thinking _ in
the same inferior parietal region of Einstein's brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we found our differences,'' said Diamond, who is
a professor at the University of California at Berkeley. She
co-authored the paper with her husband, Arnold B. Scheibel, a UCLA
professor of neurobiology and psychiatry, pathologist Harvey and
another colleague.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Canadian-led group found the significant
difference in both the left and right inferior parietal regions,
Diamond said her group found a statistically significant difference
in the glial cells only in the left side. Nonetheless, she said,
``it's saying essentially the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the researchers who have found the differences in
Einstein's brain say that does not prove why he was so much smarter
than everyone else, however. The Canadian-led group writes in the
Lancet that ``this report clearly does not resolve the
long-standing issue of the neuroanatomical substrate of
intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Harvard physics professor Holton, who is on the editorial
board of a Boston University project editing Einstein's papers,
``If you want to talk about the brain of Einstein, you ought to
talk about what went on in that brain, what historians of science
and scientists are interested in. On that, we have a great deal of
information. He published enormously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
