<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     06-17 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROOVY KIND OF LIFE  
 A FREE AGENT  
 SEEKING TOLERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Four years ago, Jay Roach was a somewhat struggling
cinematographer and screenwriter who yearned to direct movies. His
wife, Susanna Hoffs, a singer, was close friends with Robin Ruzan,
the wife of comedian Mike Myers. Every few weeks the couples would
get together at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of discussions about everything from Mel Brooks
to Kafka,'' Roach recalled. ``We were both students of Joseph
Campbell, we talked about him a lot and the idea that storytelling
was a universal experience, that everyone is connected by the need
to tell stories. It got pretty heady. We also laughed our heads off
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers showed Roach his script for ``Austin Powers: International
Man of Mystery,'' and asked for his thoughts. Roach also began
suggesting possible directors. After several months of seeking a
director, Myers approached New Line Cinema, the producers, and
asked that Roach take over. Top executives were appalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it without telling me,'' Roach said. ``New Line said,
quite justifiably, `Who is this guy?'''
</P>
<P>
   Roach put together a reel of some of the projects he had worked
on, and perhaps more important, a separate reel of excerpts from
some 1960s films that was meant to convey what he called ``the kind
of exaggerated, overly composed, Pop Art style that evoked that
moment.'' The films included James Bond movies, ``Beyond the Valley
of the Dolls,'' ``In Like Flint'' and more obscure Italian and
French comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Roach recalled his final meeting with Robert Shaye, co-chairman
of New Line, who said, ``Nothing in your reel suggests you're funny
and can direct a comedy.'' Expecting this, Roach presented a
scene-by-scene breakdown, or storyboard, of the film, showed
way-out costume designs and performed scenes with Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the meeting Shaye was laughing,'' Roach said.
``He said, `OK, you have the job.'''
</P>
<P>
   Roach doesn't have to worry anymore about jobs; he is now one of
the hottest filmmakers in town. The success of the first Austin
Powers film, which was released in 1997, as well as the latest one,
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' still amazes him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible act of blind faith on the part of Mike,''
Roach, 42, said. ``He put his whole career on the line for me. And
to New Line's credit, they trusted Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Roach's next film, ``Mystery, Alaska,'' written by David E.
Kelley, the creator of the television shows ``Ally McBeal'' and
``The Practice,'' is to be released by Disney in October. He has
been swamped with offers to direct other movies, being handed good
scripts and introduced to people he has always wanted to meet. He
is trying to savor the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Roach earned a master's degree in film production at the
University of Southern California. After making a short film that
was nominated for a student Academy Award, he directed a play at a
small theater in Hollywood; wrote the story for the film ``Blown
Away,'' which starred Jeff Bridges and Tommy Lee Jones, and was the
co-writer, co-producer and second-unit director of a futuristic
television film for Fox, ``Life Pod,'' an update of the Hitchcock
classic ``Lifeboat.''
</P>
<P>
   Roach said he knew last Friday night that the new Austin Powers
film was a hit when he went to a Los Angeles theater showing the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the 10:15,'' he said. ``People of all ages were
coming out of the theater. There were people dressed up like Austin
Powers, people shouting the lines. And when I went into the
theater, which was then packed with college kids, they were having
this great time. The audience was caught up in the pure fun of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `This is going to be good,''' Roach said.
``I went home and went to sleep for 12 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   A Free Agent
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Ron Shelton has never quite fit into a studio
mold. His films, like ``Bull Durham,'' ``White Men Can't Jump,''
``Cobb'' and ``Tin Cup,'' dealt with sports themes and studios were
often reluctant to make them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My films have always been one foot in and one foot out of the
studio,'' Shelton said. ``I've done very well making movies at
arm's length from studios. But in the last few years it's been
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   So Shelton formed his own company, Shanghai'd Films, with a
partner, Stephen Chin, a former Washington lawyer who has been
involved in producing independent movies. The new company's first
venture is ``Play It to the Bone,'' Shelton's new film, about
boxing, with Woody Harrelson and Antonio Banderas.
</P>
<P>
   Successful directors of studio films usually do not go the
independent route, but Shelton said he felt he had little choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an audience for the kinds of films I make,'' said
Shelton, a former minor-league baseball player. ``But, for me at
least, the studios don't know how to be a partner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios used to be in the moviemaking business, but now
they are part of giant corporations run by committees and
bureaucracies,'' he continued. ``It's simply very difficult to move
things along. I've had three pictures fall apart since `Tin Cup.'
They were on the verge of going, but studio budgets kept shifting,
and they took a very narrow view of casting. There are only about
three stars that everyone wants. It was all corporate politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Chin said independent films were far less expensive than studio
movies because of lower overhead and stars willing to work for
lower fees. Independence from a studio also gave Shelton almost
complete creative control.
</P>
<P>
   Chin and Shelton met only a few years ago. ``We'd have a drink
every now and then and we'd exchange war stories,'' Chin said. ``We
come from totally dissimilar backgrounds. I'm a short Chinese guy
and Ron's a big white athlete. I went to law school and did
financial training and Ron was in professional baseball. He was
studio and I came out of edgy independent films. But there was an
odd vibe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we both come from extremely religious, devout Baptist
families,'' he continued. ``Both of us pursued the arts after being
involved in other lines of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Beside Shelton's movies, the new company plans to release a few
other films each year costing anywhere from $14 million to $25
million each. The company will seek out studios to acquire its
movies for distribution. Disney is releasing the latest Shelton
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide the studio distribution system with the kind of
movie they need but don't make,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Seeking Tolerance
</P>
<P>
   A Pakistani family in an industrial town in northern England.
The father is a hard-working taxi driver who has happily provided
his 20-something son with every Western trapping. But the youth
abruptly drops his English fiancee, sells his possessions and _ to
his father's puzzlement and amazement _ turns to Islamic
fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it's a naughty film that deals with tolerance,''
said Rachel Griffiths , one of the stars of ``My Son the Fanatic,''
a modest film to be released by Miramax on June 25. ``It's about
how we use God's name to hate people, but it's also a very moving
story about the power of what people can experience when they
surrender their prejudices.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on a short story in The New Yorker by Hanif
Kureishi, who also wrote the screenplay. Kureishi's first film, in
1985, was ``My Beautiful Laundrette.'' The cast of the new film,
directed by Udayan Prasad, includes Om Puri, an acclaimed Indian
actor, who plays the taxi driver, and Ms. Griffiths, who was
nominated for an Academy Award for ``Hilary and Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current film, Ms. Griffiths plays a prostitute who,
against her better judgment, falls in love with the married taxi
driver.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Griffiths said that before filming began in northern
England, she met with some prostitutes to research her role and was
struck by their defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They refused to see themselves the way society sees them,''
she said. ``These women also have a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress said that at one point a hostile crowd was watching
the filming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear I was an actor, but I was dressed for the role,''
she said. ``People yelled things at me. They were fundamentalists.
There was a hatred there that I've never felt. They didn't think a
woman should have this freedom. They hated my autonomy, they hated
my way of life, they hated my power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt this kind of extraordinary hatred,'' Ms.
Griffiths continued.
</P>
<P>
   The actress is now in Hollywood to meet studio executives,
directors and producers. At home in Australia she is a well-known
stage and film star. In Hollywood she is relatively unknown.
</P>
<P>
   What has been the response so far?
</P>
<P>
   She laughed: ``I walk into the room and they fall at their feet
and say, `We thought you'd never come.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then she followed with, ``No, no. The general reaction is
really, `Rachel who?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
