<HEADER>
A9709 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKATING-BAIUL-SPI &LR;      06-17 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATING-BAIUL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOBRIETY BRINGS A NEW FIRE ON THE ICE FOR OKSANA BAIUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They were only three years apart, but the contrast
between the two events could not have been more dramatic for Oksana
Baiul.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the 16-year-old figure skater from Ukraine won the gold
medal at the Winter Olympics in Lillehammer, Norway. The sprite
with so much style and expressiveness on ice was the youngest woman
to win the gold since the immortal Sonja Henie in 1928 and she was
suddenly the toast of the sporting world.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Baiul was in the headlines again, this time for driving
almost 100 mph and crashing her Mercedes into a grove of trees in
Connecticut, sustaining a concussion and also being charged for
driving under the influence of alcohol. Community service and an
alcohol class led to dismissal of the charge, but the troubled
Baiul seemed destined to become yet another young athlete who
burned out in the blaze of sudden fame, even with her 10-week stint
in alcohol rehab.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to a few weeks ago when Baiul was surprised by her
skating compatriots in the Champions on Ice tour, who rallied
around her to celebrate (without alcohol) the anniversary of her
first year of sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a nice thing for them to do,'' Baiul said this
week from Salt Lake City. ``I was drinking tea with lemon, my
favorite drink now, and having them all with me meant a lot. It
meant that I have their respect and that they love me and that I
feel like I'm a part of them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Champions on Ice rolls into Seattle on Saturday night, with its
usual complement of skating superstars, including Michelle Kwan,
Elvis Stojko, Surya Bonaly, Brian Boitano, Victor Petrenko, Nicole
Bobek and Todd Eldredge. This will be the last stop on the 45-city
summer tour of Champions on Ice, but one skater who will not be
glad to see it end is the rejuvenated Baiul.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there will be a big sadness on Saturday,'' Baiul said.
``I love to be on tour with everybody, love to be on the road, love
to travel and I love to perform. I try to skate the best I can
every time I go on the ice. I face each performance as if it was my
last performance, which has been a trick of mine, and I try to do
everything I can to please those in the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a distinct sprightliness in the voice of Baiul, who has
lived in the United States for several years and speaks English
without hesitation. But long gone now is the diminutive figure that
so many people remember pulling
</P>
<P>
   off the upset win over Nancy Kerrigan at Lillehammer.
</P>
<P>
   Baiul has grown up. She is more than 6 inches taller and pounds
heavier than she was as a teen champion. Her good looks have turned
adult, as has her outlook, especially about her perilous fall.
</P>
<P>
   The self-discipline that helped her become a world champion at
such a young age is now helping her battle back from alcoholism to
what seems to her a much more normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that before I won the gold medal,'' Baiul stressed.
``But after that, my head was spinning and everything was
different. Now I have a normal lifestyle _ I wish I could have done
that earlier. But, thank God, I only had three years of a
screwed-up life. Having two such different lifestyles were
definitely not good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Baiul has settled back into skating again, both in ice shows and
in competition, while she lives in Delaware with coach Natalia
Linichuk, a fellow gold medalist. Baiul has her own line of skating
attire and has penned two books, one about her life, another about
skating technique.
</P>
<P>
   What the skater longs for, surprisingly, is the chance to
compete in the Olympics again, she hopes in the 2002 games in Salt
Lake City. Her pro status precludes that under current rules, but
Baiul clings to the hope that Olympic figure skating will be
broadened to include professionals, as have many other Olympic
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Baiul does not expect to leave the limelight any time soon. Her
Olympic gold was followed by a TV movie, which dramatized her climb
to stardom against a host of personal setbacks _ her father who
left the family when she was 2, her mother who died of cancer when
she was 13, her later life with the family of her skating coach who
also left her when he moved to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Later came Baiul's bout with alcoholism, thoughts of suicide, or
at least quitting skating forever. But through it all, she has not
grown weary of being a celebrity whose ups and downs have taken
place under a public microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to hide anything from my public,'' Baiul
emphasized. ``I am a performer, and I am addicted to the public. It
truly is a form of addiction. I like to be in the public eye and
have been since I was 15, and I'm now 21. What I do not like to be
is a dishonest person. I like to tell the truth _ that's my
problem. My mouth is too loud, but I can't hide my feelings. What I
feel I have to say, I say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
