<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIGHTHOUSE18-COX     06-17 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Historic lighthouse move more a dud
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUXTON, N.C. _ The Cape Hatteras Lighthouse has begun its
historic move, but nobody in Thursday's crowd could tell for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lighthouse is officially moved 4 inches,'' National Park
Service manager Dan McClarren told several hundred rain-soaked
onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled under umbrellas in the blustery afternoon, the crowd had
little choice but to take the park ranger's word for it.
</P>
<P>
   The initial move was so slow that not even the five officials
atop the 208-foot-tall beacon felt the move, powered by hydraulic
rams pushing the 4,800 tons of brick and granite.
</P>
<P>
   Some onlookers had waited since early morning on the stormy
eastern tip of North Carolina's Outer Banks, hoping to glimpse the
start of the federal government's $11.8 million rescue of the
black-and-white striped landmark from pounding Atlantic waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping they would give us more of a countdown,'' said
Peggy Granger, wearing a pale-green T-shirt emblazoned, ``I swear I
saw it move.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, she did not. But she said, ``It was worth it. It
was history.''
</P>
<P>
   Many left disappointed, but not altogether surprised that the
outset of the beacon's long-awaited journey would be such a visual
dud. Officials of the park service and the moving contractors had
warned that the initial move of a few inches would be nearly
impossible to see. And there was some dispute over just how far the
first push took the lighthouse. One of the movers said later that
it was actually 5 inches _ not 4.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation of the move proved more exciting for the crowd
gathered in a sandy parking lot 100 yards from the crews making
final preparations amid the grid of steel guiding the lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Three men joked they had arrived to help pull the rope that
would drag the tower. An elderly couple pondered whether they
should yell ``timber'' or ``lighthouse'' if it began to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it is not moving yet,'' park service volunteer Nancy
Giannotti repeated again and again to passersby.
</P>
<P>
   Mud-covered members of the work crew had given advance notice of
the move, but an unexpected crimp in a hydraulics hose delayed it.
</P>
<P>
   The rain fell so hard that some people took refuge in their
cars. They came out after a worker shouted, ``Any minute now.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial move of 5 inches _ or 4 _ was designed as a test of
the sophisticated hydraulics system that last week hoisted the
lighthouse 5 feet 4 inches above its sandy hole. Over the next
month, it will propel the beacon to its new foundation 2,900 feet
inland, supposedly a safe perch for the next hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday afternoon, the lighthouse had been moved an
estimated 9 feet 7 inches. The contractors said they were pleased
by the day's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did what it was supposed to do,'' said Joe Kakubik, project
manager for contractor International Chimney Corp. of Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The park service allowed the last lighthouse keeper's
granddaughter, Terry Jennette Ponton, a final trip up to the
iron-railed balcony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was flying,'' she said after her final look
across the rough gray sea, a view Unaka Benjamin Jennette had
promised his young granddaughter years ago would last forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather always said, `The ocean will never take her,'''
Ponton said. ```It will always be there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
