<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      06-17 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC SAFE FROM PROSECUTION IN SERBIA, CLINTON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, GERMANY _ President Clinton Thursday said that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic is probably safe from arrest for war
crimes in Kosovo as long as he remains in Serbia. He said NATO's
focus would be on getting the ``Kosovars back home to safety''
rather than hauling the indicted Serbian leader into court.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who arrived here Thursday for a weekend meeting with
the heads of the leading industrial nations and Russia, made the
comments during a joint appearance with French President Jacques
Chirac before leaving Paris, the second stop on a weeklong trip to
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo will be high on the agenda when the leaders meet,
particularly the return of ethnic Albanians to Kosovo and
implementation of an aid plan to rebuild the bomb-damaged Serbian
province and southeastern Europe neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say they hope to have resolved the confusion
over Russia's role in implementing the NATO-led peacekeeping force
by the time the summit opens here Friday, although negotiations
continued Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Defense Secretary William Cohen and
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, joined Thursday by
Secretary of State Madeline Albright, had resolved several sticking
points and were continuing to talk, despite some reports that
Russian officials had left the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton expressed optimism that the talks taking
place in Helsinki over Russia's role in the peacekeeping efforts _
after its forces took up position last week at the airport near
Kosovo's capital, Pristina, ahead of NATO troops _ would yield
satisfactory results for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major stumbling blocks is NATO's demand _ resisted by
Russia _ that all countries participating in peacekeeping in Kosovo
operate under a single NATO-led command. Another is Russia's desire
for its own geographic ``zone of responsibility'' within a section
of Kosovo. The United States opposes this, fearing it would amount
to partioning of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Paris, Clinton said he had been updated on the
talks. ``They have made pretty good progress,'' he said. ``I think
we'll bring this to a successful conclusion in the next little
while _ the next day or so I think we'll get it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the president was more specific. ``They have worked out
command and control, they have worked out arrangements for the
airport. But they still need to work out the sector,'' he said.
``Everybody will see it is a very elegant solution.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I don't know if they'll finish it today and then
take the weekend to announce it.'' And he said that what they will
have worked out ``is something that is satisfactory to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials said that Russian President Boris Yeltsin, whose
attendance on Sunday, the final day of the industrial leaders'
meeting, has been unconfirmed, was indeed planning to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Russia aside, Clinton said at the appearance with Chirac in
Paris, ``It's important that we not in any way mislead people about
what happens next,'' in Kosovo, adding that NATO's ``heaviest
responsibility'' was ensuring the safe return and automony of
refugees, and rebuilding the region.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if Milosevic, who has been indicted as a war
criminal by an international tribunal in the Netherlands, ``remains
inside the confines of Serbia, persumably he's beyond the reach of
the extradition powers of the other governments. But sometimes
these things take a good while to bear fruit. I think we'll just
have to wait and see how that develops.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I do not believe that the NATO allies can invade
Belgrade to try to deliver the indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Chirac, however, agreed that Belgrade should not
receive reconstruction aid as long as Milosevic remains in power.
``Development aid is one thing; humanitarian aid is a different
thing,'' Chirac said. He said that Serbs also were victims of
NATO's 78 days of bombing, ``Hence, humanitarian aid, yes;
development aid, economic aid, no.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Chirac and Socialist Prime Minster Lionel
Jospin on Kosovo, and a round of last-minute lobbying by phone
members of Congress to pass a proposal to require background checks
on gun show purchases, Clinton arrived here behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   With First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton flying on to Italy for a
few days, Clinton spent his last hours in Paris shopping and
sightseeing. His outing delighted shopkeepers and visiting
Americans, but aggravated Parisian motorists _ who saw their
traffic ensnarled by his motorcade. At several points,
white-helmeted paparrazzi on motorcycles weaved in and out of the
official line of cars traveling with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Tired and jetlagged when he arrived in Cologne, Clinton,
nonetheless went for a dinner of highly seasoned German-style beef,
with apple puree and dumplings, with a small group of White House
reporters. He held forth on variety of subjects _ movies, novels,
food and a board game called ``Upwards,'' he brought along and
often plays with the first lady, and which he described as a
five-level version of Scrabble.
</P>
<P>
   But asked about the first lady's possible run for the Senate in
New York, the president demurred, ``I really don't know if she's
going to run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
