<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9732 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-LAYOFFS-HNS &LR;      06-17 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-LAYOFFS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ COMPUTER LOSSES TO RESULT IN LAYOFFS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Stung by tough competition, plunging prices and its
own inefficiencies, Compaq Computer Corp. on Thursday said it will
lose money this quarter and launched a reorganization that will
result in layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq executives said they expect to post a loss for the
quarter ending June 30 of up to 15 cents a share. Wall Street
analysts had been projecting a profit of about 20 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based computer maker will realign its core
businesses into three different groups _ combined enterprise and
services, business PCs and consumer _ and whack more than $2
billion in costs.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving those cuts will require layoffs. When that would
happen, and how many people would be let go, has not yet been
determined, said Michael Capellas, Compaq's acting chief operating
officer, during a conference call Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the most extensive realignment of the
company since 1991,'' said Benjamin Rosen, Compaq's board chairman
and acting chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The pain will continue into the third quarter, when Compaq will
take a ``substantial'' charge because of the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent Compaq's stock on a roller coaster ride Thursday,
at one point dropping as much as 2 1/4 to as low as 20. It closed
at 22 9/16, up 5/16 on a volume of 36 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second quarter in a row in which Compaq has warned
analysts to dramatically lower their expectations. Compaq is
scheduled to report its second-quarter earnings July 28.
</P>
<P>
   In April, former Chief Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer said the
company would only make half the profit in the first quarter that
Wall Street was expecting. Less than two weeks later, Pfeiffer was
forced out of his job, and a slew of key executives since have
followed him out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Compaq has been caught flat-footed by changes in
the computer industry at a time when it is also trying to digest
its $9 billion acquisition of Digital Equipment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Computer prices are dropping quickly, and as a result
manufacturers' profit margins are getting slimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with efficient operations _ such as Dell Computer
Corp. of Round Rock, Texas _ are driving the changes. But Compaq is
having a hard time weathering this storm because its own internal
structures are too complex, Rosen acknowledged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pricing pressures in the PC segment, inadequate revenue
growth, and a noncompetitive cost structure are the contributing
factors to our expected shortfall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to streamline, the company will move operations
that are now separate entities into each of the three new product
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, marketing currently its own division. But Compaq
will give the enterprise/services, PCs and consumer divisions their
own marketing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said each division will be responsible for its products
``from end to end'' _ from concept and design to delivery of the
finished goods. This should enable Compaq to respond more quickly
to market changes, as well as being able to get finished goods to
market quicker, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some operations, such as the global sales force, manufacturing
and other components, will remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   And Capellas stressed that the sales force will not change.
Customers will still deal with their current sale representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq will create a customer advocate division that will act as
a kind of ombudsman for its customers, as well as a group dedicated
to the company's online sales initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also will strive to sell more of its computers directly
to customers. Currently, most of its products are sold via a
network of resellers. The company announced last month that it was
cutting the number of those resellers from 40 down to 4.
</P>
<P>
   To further its direct sales, Compaq will open 17 call centers
around the world, and it will expand its Internet-based sales.
Capellas said the company expects to sell 25 percent of its
computers directly by the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new structure, Enrico Pesatori will head the combined
enterprise and services group. This group will sell the
high-dollar, high-powered products it got in the acquisitions of
Digital and Tandem Computer, as well as Compaq's own PC-based
servers. Services refers to everything from customer support to
running entire computer departments on behalf of big companies.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Winkler will continue to head up the PC products group,
responsible for desktop and portable personal computers for
business.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Blackmore was named senior vice president, sales and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Larson will remain as the chief of the consumer
division, which sells the Presario line of home PCs. Larson took
over earlier this year from Rod Schrock, who is now the president
of the AltaVista Co., a subsidiary built around the search engine
of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference Thursday, Rosen said Compaq still intends
to spin off AltaVista as a public company, but added: ``In the
world of the Internet, anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen also said that Compaq's search for a new chief executive
was going well, and that a new CEO should be announced ``in the
not-too-distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the news of Compaq's expected loss and reorganization
was the fact that yet another top-level executive is leaving.
Andreas Barth, who was general manager of Europe, the Middle East
and Africa, is retiring effective June 30. He will be replaced by
Werner Koepf, who previously was a vice president responsible for
managing Compaq's business in 11 European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally said the moves should help Compaq overcome
its problems, but that a lot more needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   William Conroy, an analyst in Houston with Sanders Morris Mundy,
said Compaq needs to further streamline the buying process for its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq does not make this process straightforward'' because of
its reliance on resellers,`` he said. ''There's this problem for
the buyer of, `What can I buy and where can I buy it?'``
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar, an analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray in
Minneapolis, predicted June 8 that Compaq would post a loss for
this quarter. Kumar said Thursday that the company is hampered by
the complexity it took on when it acquired Digital, which was known
for its internal bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq was a company that was struggling; Digital was a
company that was struggling,'' he said. ``It was a marriage made in
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Neff, an analyst with Bear Stearns in New York, said
Compaq could follow the lead of Apple Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Like Compaq, Apple was reeling from changes in the market but
was debt-free and had plenty of cash in the bank, Neff said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jobs, Apple's co-founder, returned to the company and
turned it around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped to simplify the model,'' Neff said. ``Compaq needs
to figure out a way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
