<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOYCE-MAYNARD-SPEAKS-     06-17 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOYCE-MAYNARD-SPEAKS-OUT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWER OF LETTERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    ------------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    In the following TIMELY commentary, writer Joyce Maynard
responds to the controversy surrounding her decision to sell 14
letters written to her by J.D. Salinger when she was 18 years old.
The letters are scheduled to be auctioned off at Sotheby's on Tue.,
June 22.
 &HT;    ------------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' commentary, contact New York
Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 EDITORS: IF PURCHASED, THIS ARTICLE CAN BE PUBLISHED STARTING
SUNDAY, JUNE 20, 1999, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER.  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted three times _ into
the ``a'' general news, ``l'' lifestyle and ``k'' commentary
files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JOYCE MAYNARD  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Next Tuesday, Sotheby's will auction 14 letters by J.D. Salinger
written to me when I was 18 years old.
 &HT;    When I first read these letters, and for many years after, I
believed they represented the heartfelt expressions of the most
tenderly devoted soul mate. Later I learned that I was one of many
teen-aged recipients of such letters.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, my choice to break a quarter-century-long silence
concerning my relationship with Salinger has unleashed accusations
of exploitation and betrayal made all the more outrageous, in the
eyes of my critics, because the one whose privacy I am charged with
violating is a man whose reclusiveness has become an American
legend.
 &HT;    The debate has raised questions about what constitutes invasion
of privacy and exploitation, alleged victimization versus personal
responsibility. It speaks to the heart of an issue every writer I
know struggles with: How much of my story do I have a right to
tell? Above all, it speaks to the experience of countless young
girls and women drawn into relationships with vastly more powerful
older men, the obligation placed upon these women to protect those
men's secrets, and the enduring consequences.
 &HT;    With the sale of Salinger's letters, I mean to lay to rest an
event that has haunted me all my adult life. Before I close this
chapter, though, I want to explain my actions.
 &HT;    Twenty seven years later, I can still bring myself back to the
moment in the spring of 1972 when I opened and read that first
letter J.D. Salinger wrote to me. I was a freshman at Yale and had
received hundreds of pieces of mail in response to an article I had
just published in The New York Times Magazine.
 &HT;    In a voice so distinct and funny and wise that I could almost
hear him talking, the author expressed the view that he and I were
kindred spirits.
 &HT;    That idea struck at my heart's core. Like so many readers of
``Catcher in the Rye'' I felt this man understood me as nobody ever
had. We began to correspond.
 &HT;    For the remainder of that semester, everything else fell away. I
made Jerry my religion, the only one I ever had. I withdrew from
Yale and moved in with him, leaving no forwarding address. I
believed _ despite he 35 years separating our ages _ that we'd be
together always.
 &HT;    From the moment the relationship took on a physical reality away
from the page, it began to fray. The same things he had once loved
about me _ my naivete, my eagerness for experience _ now made him
angry and impatient. He said I acted like a teen-ager. I was 19.
 &HT;    In the spring of 1973, Jerry and I took a trip with his
children. On the beach in Florida he told me with chilling
abruptness to fly back to New Hampshire, clear my things out of his
house and be gone before he and the children returned.
 &HT;    In the years that followed, I fell in love, married, had three
children. Throughout my 20s and 30s _ years in which I wrote
novels, tended my children, witnessed the deaths of my parents and
the end of my marriage _ hardly a week went by that someone didn't
ask about Salinger.
 &HT;    Rumors that I'd lived with him had been around for years. I kept
my silence, even with friends, even with my husband, and never
mentioned Salinger in any of my published work.
 &HT;    But though I didn't speak of him or reread those letters from
him for two decades, my knowledge that I had once been adored by a
great man, and later condemned by him, remained a source of deep
shame.
 &HT;    There is something about the mythologies we create when we're
young that remains more powerful than any we construct in later
life. If I'd seen Jerry Salinger again with the eyes of a mature
woman, I might have been able to view him with a less purely
reverential eye, and to reshape my image of him to one of more
realistic and human proportions.
 &HT;    The same holds true, I suspect, for the legions of worshippers
for whom the name Salinger and the concept of his legendary privacy
continues to remain sacred, in the absence of any information that
might call the mythology into question.
 &HT;    The process of re-evaluating my obligation to protect the
Salinger legend began one night when a woman I'd never met
approached me (pregnant with my third child) and said, lightly,
``Oh, you're the one who got letters from J.D. Salinger. I had an
au pair girl who had a bunch of letters from him too.''
 &HT;    All those years I'd held onto the notion that I was once his
soul mate unlike any other. If that wasn't true, what else should I
question?
 &HT;    Over the years stories kept coming back to me, of other girls
with letters from Salinger, other avowals of unmatched kinship and
connection.
 &HT;    Three years ago, when my own daughter reached the age that I was
when Jerry Salinger wrote to me, I found myself exploring the
profound effects, on a young person, of the kinds of the
all-too-common experiences I had gone through at her age. I didn't
set out, then, to write about Salinger, only to write about myself.
But there was no way to explore my story without speaking of the
crucial role he played in it.
 &HT;    After my book ``At Home in the World'' was published last fall,
two more women who also had relationships with Salinger when they
were 18 wrote to me, describing correspondences and subsequent
rejection eerily like my own.
 &HT;    Before I parted with his letters to me, I read them one more
time. I could still see humor, tenderness and utter originality in
the voice that rose from the pages. I saw something else too:
psychological manipulation and a form of emotional seduction.
 &HT;    His demand for privacy, viewed by many as evidence of his purity
of character, seemed now like the cloak of a man well aware of the
fact that his activities, viewed in the light of day, might not
reflect favorably on him.
 &HT;    I didn't weep, reading Salinger's words to my 18-year-old self,
until I came to the passage in one of his first letters, warning of
the extraordinary danger of letters from strangers, and the power
of words on the page. He was right _ a letter can be a dangerous
thing, as I now know well.
 &HT;    Ironically, no letter I ever received exerted a more destructive
force than the one I was then holding in my hand.
 &HT;    I will not feel moved to tears when my letters from Salinger go
up for bid. My decision to sell them is grounded in the practical
realities of one whose two younger children are now approaching
college.
 &HT;    I am not selling the letters as an act of vengeance, but neither
do I feel compelled not to sell them as an act of loyalty. For me
now, Salinger's letters constitute nothing but the record of a
damaging experience. But to admirers of one of the most important
literary voices of the century, they provide a rare glimpse of a
deservedly celebrated writer.
 &HT;    Some will say that the virtues of loyalty, fidelity and good
taste require that for the rest of her life a woman must tenderly
protect the secrets of a man who has demonstrated something
considerably less than tender protection toward her. As for me, I
believe the letters are better entrusted to a lover of Salinger's
prose than they are to one who made the costly mistake of trying to
live out fictions best left on the page.
 &HT;    _______ 
 (Joyce Maynard's most recent book is the memoir ``At Home in the
World'' (Picador USA). She can be reached at her Web site at
www.joycemaynard.com.)  
 c.1999 Joyce Maynard  
