<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SERBIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS NATO SHOULD NOT SEIZE MILOSEVIC IN SERBIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Even as new Serb atrocities were uncovered in
Kosovo, President Clinton made it clear Thursday that NATO's
priority should be returning ethnic Albanian refugees to the
province and not seizing President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
so he can be tried for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he remains in Serbia, inside the confines of Serbia,
presumably he's beyond the reach of the extradition powers of the
other governments,'' Clinton said. ``I do not believe that the NATO
allies can invade Belgrade to try to deliver the indictment, if you
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came in Paris, after a meeting with French
President Jacques Chirac and before he flew to this city on the
Rhine for the weekend meeting of Russia and the world's leading
economic democracies. The summit is expected to be dominated by the
Kosovo conflict and its contentious aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Progress was reported Thursday in the standoff over Russian
insistence that its military be given a distinct role in the Kosovo
occupation force being led by NATO, the old Soviet nemesis. Clinton
and his NATO colleagues contend they welcome Russian participation
but insist that the Russian detachment at the airport in the
Kosovar capital of Pristina stand down.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official traveling with the president said the talks
were going well. ``They have worked out command and control, they
have worked out arrangements for the airport, but they still need
to work out the sector.'' The Russians have said they want their
own sector of the province to police. ``Everybody will see it is a
very elegant solution,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and four top aides were indicted for war crimes May 27
by the international war crimes tribunal at The Hague, Netherlands.
Clinton praised the action at the time and repeated that view
Thursday as he stood by Chirac on the lush back lawn of Elysee
Palace, the French president's working residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I strongly support the decision of the war crimes
tribunal ... , I think it's important that we not in any way
mislead people about what happens next,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's heaviest responsibility, Clinton said, ``is to get the
Kosovars back home in safety, and then to give them self
government, autonomy, and rebuilding assistance and then work on
the region.''
</P>
<P>
   As Serb troops withdraw from Kosovo and NATO forces move in,
grisly evidence of mass killings of ethnic Albanians continued to
come to light. Residents of the village of Poklek said Thursday
that Serbs herded 62 people into a room April 17 and tossed in a
grenade, finishing off survivors with gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that trying Milosevic for such crimes would
be particularly difficult if he chose not to leave Yugoslavia. He
said NATO member nations were not prepared to use their military
forces in the region to invade Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, and
attempt to capture him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's soft-pedaling of the issue contrasted with the strong
denunciation of the Milosevic regime that Hillary Rodham Clinton
gave moments later in a speech at the University of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nations, our leaders, our citizens stood up to a giant
evil,'' the first lady said in the 19th-century grandeur of the
Sorbonne's amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are some who, I know, would quibble with my use of
that word, but I think that it fully describes the conflict we have
been waging these last months,'' she said. ``We will not turn away
if human beings are being cruelly expelled. When crimes against
humanity rear their ugly heads, we have to send a message as an
international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac, who fielded questions from the media alongside the U.S.
president, sidestepped the issue of how forcefully the NATO
countries should be in attempting to apprehend Milosevic and bring
him to trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the French leader did agree with White House policy that one
of the ways to ostracize Milosevic was to deny his country any
reconstruction aid as long as he holds power.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac reiterated the NATO stand that Serbia, the central
Yugoslav region, should receive only humanitarian aid and not funds
to allow it to rebuild an infrastructure devastated by almost three
months of alliance bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no economic development aid to a regime which is
not democratic and whose present leader, furthermore, has been
indicted with crimes against humanity by the international war
crimes court,'' Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of what kind of financial assistance and how to
administer it will be on the agenda as Clinton and Chirac meet with
other world leaders Friday in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also must deal with their latest dust-up with
Russia, which is demanding a bigger role in peacekeeping efforts in
Kosovo. Talks in Helsinki, Finland, between Defense Secretary
William Cohen and Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev have not
resolved the matter. Clinton said he believed progress was being
made as the two sides discuss several options acceptable to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Russians to be involved in this mission in a
comprehensive way,'' he said. ``But we also think it is important
that we maintain clear unity of command'' under the NATO
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
