<HEADLINE>
HELMS'S LATEST HOSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One blessing of American democracy is the system's diffusion of
power. That same system of checks and balances, however, tempts
individual officeholders to exercise every last ounce of power that
may be institutionally accessible to them.
</P>
<P>
   This is a temptation that the chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, Jesse Helms of North Carolina, has often
failed to resist, and his current cat-and-mouse game with Richard
Holbrooke's nomination to be ambassador to the United Nations
demonstrates the mischief one senator can cause if he is determined
to magnify the powers inherent in his position.
</P>
<P>
   William Weld, the former Massachusetts governor, learned last
year how impotent a would-be ambassador can become when his
nomination falls victim to the caprices of the hyper-conservative
Helms. Although logic might suggest that Helms ought to have been
happy to have a fellow Republican serve as ambassador to Mexico,
Weld found to his chagrin that party loyalty was no match for
Chairman Helms's will to avenge perceived slights.
</P>
<P>
   Helms has been hinting that if he is not satisfied on certain
points, he will prevent a Senate vote on Holbrooke's nomination, as
he did with Weld. Nobody questions Helms's institutional
entitlement to entomb an ambassadorial nomination in this way, but
there is a crucial difference between what a powerful senator is
entitled to do with his powers and what he ought to do.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has settled a dispute about diplomatic contacts he
used just after he returned to the private sector, a misstep that
hardly disqualifies him to represent this country at the UN. The
other matter Helms has said he will raise in hearings on
Holbrooke's nomination is ``his role and responsibility for this
administration's misguided policy of appeasing Slobodan
Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   This charge is either absurd or disingenuous. Holbrooke
outbullied Milosevic at the Dayton peace conference and was, if
anything, too hawkish in pushing the administration toward bombing
Yugoslavia. Helms should not subordinate principles of fairness to
a capricious demonstration of power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
