<HEADER>
A9755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-BOMBING-BOS     06-17 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S PYRRHIC VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an aura of self-congratulation emanating from
Washington following the administration's air war in the Balkans.
Although NATO's forces ultimately prevailed at virtually no cost of
life to its own troops, Madeleine Albright's war was the result of
a blatant diplomatic failure. The Rambouillet agreement was so
fatally flawed that it helped precipitate what it was meant to
prevent _ the ethnic cleansing of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Biship Artemija, the head of the Serbian Orthodox Church, which
has called on Slobodan Milosevic to step down as president,
published an open letter recently saying that ``the bombs gave the
pretext to the expulsion of a great number of Albanians and gave
the pretext to the exodus of the Serbs.'' And democratic forces in
Serbia are now almost nonexistent, and Milosevic is triumphant in
his phantom victory, and there is a lot of anti-Western feeling
among Serbs that will stop democratic processes.
</P>
<P>
   We may never know to what extent the air war made things worse
for the Kosovar Albanians. Milosevic had already begun a vicious
campaign of repression in his rebellious province before the
bombing. But Western reporters in Kosovo have written that once the
bombings began, the Serbian paramilitaries went on a rampage and
the bombing made the ethnic cleansing worse. The cause of
containing Milosevic was just, but the execution was lacking.
</P>
<P>
   A smarter diplomatic approach that kept the monitors of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe on the ground
and engaged the two sides in a genuine political negotiation might
have prevented much of the Kosovo catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, both Kosovo and much of the rest of Yugoslavia
have been smashed, with hundreds and thousands of livelihoods
ruined. Surrounding countries have been destabilized. It is true
that to be successful against an evil such as Milosevic, diplomacy
needs force to back it up. But in the case of Kosovo, brute force
prevailed over diplomatic skills that might have won the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
