<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-JACKSON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson never relaxing
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Jaren Jackson has arrived. The post-game national
TV interview Wednesday night said so. The horde of media around him
Thursday afternoon said so. The attention the New York Knicks will
pay him tonight surely says so.
</P>
<P>
   Such notoriety is a far cry from where Jackson has been much of
his career _ one that's taken him to eight NBA teams in four years
_ and a long and accomplished career in the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   So to be in media demand and the subject of a team's defensive
game plan is a mark of Jackson's perseverance as much the five
three-pointers he made in the San Antonio Spurs' 89-77 NBA Finals
victory in Game 1 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a matter of believing in yourself,'' said Jackson, a
former Georgetown star. ``I've been through a lot. I've gotten cut
a lot. But in this business you have to understand that's a part of
it. I didn't complain. I just made sure that when my time came that
I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   It'll be interesting to see how ready Jackson is tonight, for
the Knicks are hellbent on not letting him get 10 open three-point
shots as he did Wednesday. With Tim Duncan and David Robinson
commanding so much attention in the low post, the Knicks must
double team the Twin Towers _ just not with the man who's guarding
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised he shot the ball so well,'' said Latrell
Sprewell, who left Jackson open as he attempted to double-team
either of the big men. ``He was huge for them. We have to change
some things. If Jaren gets it going again, you won't see me coming
off him at all.''
</P>
<P>
   All the dreams Jackson had about a solid NBA career finally
materialized this season. He was signed as a free agent ``to be a
defensive guy on two guards,'' coach Gregg Popovich said. ``But we
got him in here and saw how he shot the ball and said, 'Let's go
for it.' And he's loved the role as that guy taking the open
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is a beloved member of the Spurs for more than what he's
done in the their remarkable post-season run. (Jackson was huge
against the Lakers and Portland, too.) Through getting cut by seven
NBA teams, Jackson found a determination that he carries on the
court each time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect him a great deal,'' Popovich said. ``I'm thrilled
for him. When something like this finally happens for a guy who
took the long road, who worked hard and never quit, never stopped
trying, you have to feel good about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he feels good about what he's accomplished, but
he's not satisfied. ``I always believed it would happen for me,''
he said. ``I've been cut a lot, played in the CBA and won two
championships, won a championship in the WBL. And I appreciate
those experiences. It's all helped me. But if I've learned one
thing it's to not get relaxed. There's still more work to do, so
I'm not celebrating. Not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
