<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-SPRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCEAN SPRAY CEO TO STEP DOWN AFTER ONLY THREE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid a cranberry glut that is hurting the entire industry, Ocean
Spray Cranberries Inc. said Thursday chief executive Thomas E.
Bullock, 53, will step down next year after only three years at the
top job. Bullock is the third Ocean Spray executive to announce his
departure this year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ocean Spray, Bullock, an 18-year company veteran,
presented a ``major transition plan'' to the Lakeville, Mass.
cooperative's board of directors that will have him assist in the
search for his successor before leaving sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the challenges I've faced _ and one my successor will
face _ is continuing to create value for our grower-owners, who are
suffering from lower-than-expected returns due to crop surpluses
and low prices,'' Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   One challenge Bullock couldn't meet, outsiders said, was to
transform Ocean Spray from a one-time monopoly into a company that
could nimbly defend its turf from new rivals.
</P>
<P>
   As Bullock prepares to leave, he said Ocean Spray is ``a very
strong brand.'' Over the last 18 years, revenues have risen from
$300 million to $1.48 billion. As top achievements, he cited
increased efforts to launch new products and efficiency measures
that could save the company up to $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray claims its trouble is caused by several years of
bumper crops and surpluses that have hurt the entire industry.
Since 1997, Ocean Spray has eliminated about 500 jobs, or about 20
percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders offered some different views.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its recent history, Ocean Spray was a veritable
monopoly. In the mid-1990s, however, Ocean Spray's dominance was
challenged by new competitors, and, some say, it didn't know how to
react.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a monopoly for many years,'' said John Decas, head
of rival Decas Cranberry Products Inc. of Wareham, Mass. ``Now it's
a competitive environment, and it's not an environment they're
comfortable in.''
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1930, Ocean Spray is a cooperative of cranberry and
citrus growers. One of its goals is to shield its members from the
price fluctuations that affect many agricultural commodities by
offering its growers a set price for their fruit.
</P>
<P>
   In recent times, that system has worked well, but with the
industry enduring what Bullock described as the worst cranberry
surplus in 25 years, the cooperative is under strain.
</P>
<P>
   As the surplus grew and Ocean Spray engaged in price wars with
rivals, some Ocean Spray growers began to feel short-changed by the
prices they were paid for their berries.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray members are required to buy stock in the privately
held cooperative, which they redeem when they retire or leave.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Ocean Spray has cashed out the stock of departing
growers in annual installments, but this year, citing tough times,
Ocean Spray suspended those payments. Many growers rely on those
payments for retirement, and some felt betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray is ``like an unfaithful spouse,'' said Paul Rinta, a
third-generation cranberry grower from Wareham. ``They promise you
the world, and then they don't come home at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Bullock's departure, Rinta said, ``He should have
left Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bullock of the growers, ``They're upset, and I understand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of his tenure, Bullock was a big part of Ocean Spray's
marketing efforts to convince US consumers that cranberries were a
lot more than a Thanksgiving side dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crave the wave'' ad campaigns and studies that showed
cranberry juice could help curb bladder infections helped Ocean
Spray rapidly grow its sales.
</P>
<P>
   But Ocean Spray's success may have encouraged rivals. In the
mid-1990s, Northland Cranberries Inc. of Wisconsin, the first
publicly traded cranberry company, began marketing a premium line
of 100 percent cranberry juice.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ocean Spray uses fructose corn sweetners, its beverages
are technically ``juice drinks,'' not juices.
</P>
<P>
   If Northland aimed at the top of the market, other rivals
squeezed Ocean Spray from the bottom. They bought berries from
independent growers, often at higher prices. These berries were
used to make private-label juice drinks that big supermarket chains
sell at lower prices than Ocean Spray beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray did not mount ``a rational response'' to those new
challenges, said George S. Dahlman, a US Bancorp Piper Jaffray
analyst who follows Northland. ``They didn't know how to deal with
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray initiated ``price wars of various sorts'' that wound
up hurting Ocean Spray more than Northland, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In taking on Northland, Ocean Spray launched its own 100 percent
juice line called Wellfleet Farms.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Ocean Spray said it would ``relaunch'' the line under a
new name. A separate beverage line fortified with vitamins and
calcium is also being readied for market.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray faces other difficulties. It had contracted with
PepsiCo Inc. to distribute its single-serve beverages to
convenience stores. But last year Pepsi announced plans to buy
Tropicana, an Ocean Spray rival. Ocean Spray is now suing Pepsi _
and looking for a new distributor.
</P>
<P>
   For its last fiscal year, which ended Aug. 31, Ocean Spray said
revenues rose 3 percent. Proceeds, the word it uses for profits,
were $280 million, up from $273 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberries are estimated to be a $200 million industry in
Massachusetts; only Wisconsin harvests more berries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
