<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Congressional action: A tense House
began considering its most significant gun control legislation in
five years, with advocates and opponents locked in a
down-to-the-wire struggle over a dozen proposals including
competing measures to regulate the sales of weapons at guns shows.
In a significant victory for cultural conservatives earlier
Thursday, the House voted 248-180 to include in the legislation a
provision giving the states the right to allow the display of the
Ten Commandants in public places including schools. By Alison
Mitchell and Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PAYDAY-LOANS (Kokomo, Ind.) _ An unexpected product of the
nation's most prosperous peacetime decade in this century, payday
lending companies are sprouting up all over the country, having
increased in number from 300 seven years ago to nearly 8,000 today.
Operating under names like Check Into Cash, Check 'n Go and Fast
Cash, payday lenders grant loans to workers against their next
paychecks. In return, the companies charge a ``fee,'' typically $15
to $35. At annual rates, the fees normally exceed 300 percent and
400 percent and in some cases they reach four digits. By Peter
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
