<HEADER>
A9762 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANCIENT-RUBBER-BOS &LR;      06-17 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANCIENT-RUBBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYANS DEVELOPED RUBBER, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody thought that the process for making rubber was
invented in Europe in the mid-19th century. But everybody was
wrong. In fact, they were off by about 3,500 years, according to a
new report from MIT archeologists.
</P>
<P>
   When Spanish explorers first encountered Mayan cities in Central
America in the 1500s, one of the most astonishing sights they found
was a complicated, highly ritualized ball game played on
stone-rimmed courts as long as a football field, which sometimes
ended with human sacrifices (nobody is quite sure whether it was
the winners or the losers). What amazed the invaders most was the
large bouncy ball used in the game.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the only kind of balls the Europeans knew how to
make were made of leather and stuffed with feathers, and they
didn't bounce much. The sight of the huge, bouncing rubber balls
the Mayans used _ some were a foot in diameter, made of solid
rubber, and weighed more than 15 pounds _ intrigued them. They
brought a few samples, and even a whole team for a demonstration
game, back to Spain to present to King Carlos V.
</P>
<P>
   But centuries passed before the secret of how to make rubber was
re-invented. And somehow, even though the Mayan ball games have
been well known to archeologists, nobody had thought to investigate
just what the balls were made of.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until three years ago, when MIT freshman Michael
Terkanian of Brockton, Mass. heard a description of the ancient
games in an introductory archeology course taught by Dorothy
Hosler. He raised his hand to ask how the balls were made, and
Hosler _ a specialist in Mesoamerican archeology _ was stumped. She
suggested he investigate the question as a research project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought about it,'' Hosler explained in an interview.
``It was just one of those obvious questions that nobody asked.''
</P>
<P>
   So it turned out that nobody knew the answer, and that was the
beginning of a research project that continued for the last three
years and culminated in the publication in the journal Science of a
description of the discovery of the ancient rubber-making method.
The paper was co-authored by Hosler, MIT materials scientist Sandra
Burkett, and Terkanian, who is now a junior _ a highly unusual
achievement for an undergraduate.
</P>
<P>
   After three trips to Mayan archeological sites in Mexico,
Terkanian and Hosler found that Mayans in the region still know how
to produce rubber in the ancient way. The key discovery was a
precise mixture of two different plant substances.
</P>
<P>
   The main ingredient of rubber is latex, derived from the rubber
tree by making diagonal slashes in the bark and collecting the
sticky sap. But this material, by itself, is virtually useless. It
is too sticky to handle, and when it dries it becomes brittle
instead of rubbery.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Goodyear is credited with inventing the process to
transform latex into a usable rubber by a heat and sulfur process
in the late 19th century. A similar process had been patented in
England in 1843. But it turns out these latter-day rubber barons
were just reinventing the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the Mayan process was adding juice from a morning
glory vine, which also grows in the region. After the mixture is
stirred vigorously for 15 minutes, it reaches a consistency that
can be easily handled and shaped, and which dries to a bouncy,
durable rubber. The vine, the archeologists found, contains sulfur
compounds, and the process only works in hot weather, so the
process is closely analogous to modern rubbermaking.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of this process made it possible to make the
bouncy balls, which in turn led to the elaborate ball games that
were so central to Mayan society, which thrived from at least 2000
BC until the Spanish conquest.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no record of exactly how the game was played,
illustrations on Mayan pottery, the ballfields themselves, and
reports by explorers provide clues. In one version, a smaller ball
was hit with a stick. In another, it had to be thrown through an
overhead hoop.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the Mayans made other things out of rubber as well,
and many of these artifacts, including hollow human figures and
wide rubber bands for attaching stone ax blades to shafts, have
recently been recovered from swampy sites where oxygen-free
conditions preserved the rubber.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the ancient rubber-processing method is the
latest achievement for MIT's unique Center for Materials Research
in Archeology and Ethnology, the only such department in the world,
which focuses on how ancient peoples processed the materials that
were crucial to their civilizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
