<HEADER>
A9765 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-PREGNANCY18-COX     06-17 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-PREGNANCY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pregnancy complications high amoung black women
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black women are almost four times more likely than white women
to die from complications of pregnancy, one of the sharpest racial
disparities in public health, the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year study shows black women were more likely to die than
white women in every state in which death-certificate data could be
collected and compared, the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   In 26 states including Georgia, the risk black women would die
while producing a living child ranged from twice that of whites for
young women to six times the risk run by whites for women older
than 40.
</P>
<P>
   No single cause could be pinpointed, said Dr. Lynne Wilcox, the
study's author, but key factors may include black women's more
limited access to health care and greater vulnerability to some
health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really struck us is how much we don't know,'' said
Wilcox, who is director of the division of reproductive health at
the CDC's National Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health
Promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between death rates persisted even when women of
different races were in the same social class, had similar access
to prenatal care or were diagnosed with the same conditions such as
diabetes or high blood pressure, Wilcox said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1996, reports indicate 3,086 women in the United
States died of pregnancy complications, the CDC said. But the true
number might be as much as three times higher, the agency
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   The gap in Georgia mirrors the national problem. ``Access to
care is something we are still struggling with in Georgia, as well
as appropriateness of care, managing high-risk conditions,'' said
Rosalyn Bacon, the state's director of family health.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 69.6 percent of black pregnant women in Georgia see a
physician regularly from the first trimester to delivery, she said.
In contrast, 83.1 percent of white pregnant women visit a doctor
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC research signals how deep health differences remain
between the races, said Dr. Stephen Thomas, director of the
Institute for Minority Health Research at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these gaps persist at the same time that we are
increasing the amount that medicine can do, we should be
concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
