<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9766 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-HICKMAN18-COX     06-17 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HICKMAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-NASA engineer creates his own space
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up in the West Virginia mining town of Coalwood, Homer
Hickam Jr. spent his childhood as a science fiction fan who liked
to read about the stars.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 14, he started reaching for them.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the launch of the Soviet Union's Sputnik, Hickam and
some of his friends taught themselves how to build rockets. Defying
his father, who wanted him to become a mining engineer, Hickam went
on to win a top prize in the National Science Fair in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Hickam described his Frank Capra-esque triumph in his
best-selling 1998 memoir ``Rocket Boys,'' which was renamed and
filmed as ``October Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the ex-NASA engineer's second career has taken off like,
well, a rocket. His first novel, ``Back to the Moon'' (Delacorte,
$23.95), has just been published, and Hickam is well into another
memoir, ``Last Christmas in Coalwood,'' about his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to write the novel because the memoir required me to
dig deep in my soul and get all my emotions,'' says Hickam, 56, who
lives in Huntsville, Ala. ``With this novel, I could have the
characters do anything I wanted them to. I've been working in the
space business for 30 years, and it was a great thing to take the
space shuttle and send it anywhere I wanted to without the
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the novel, engineer Jack Medaris and two employees skyjack
the space shuttle to the moon to retrieve an isotope called
Helium-3, which would provide a powerful new source of energy.
Nothing goes according to plan, however, and Jack ends up with an
unexpected passenger: a beautiful, troublesome biologist and author
named Penny High Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote the book so I could create two interesting characters,
Jack and Penny, going to a very exotic location. And what could be
more exotic than the moon?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Hickam says, the government isn't interested in
the moon anymore. He contends that rocket fuel systems are
hopelessly outdated and the International Space Station is nothing
more than an expensive public works project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at new propulsion systems based on fission or
fusion, new ways of getting out into space. These new experimental
engines can really scat with huge cargoes, zip to the moon in
hours, jump out to Mars in days. We need somebody like a John F.
Kennedy to enunciate a new purpose that is greater than ourselves.
It would be so helpful to children. They need something to aspire
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickam will sign his book at 7 p.m. Friday at Chapter 11 at
Peachtree Battle Shopping Center, 2345-A Peachtree Road N.E.,
404-237-7199.
</P>
<P>
   PORTRAIT OF A MARRIAGE: When Vicki and Dennis Covington decided
to write a book together, the idea was to describe their
humanitarian project of drilling water wells in the undeveloped
areas of Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Then the unexpected happened: The Birmingham literary couple
discovered that each was involved in an adulterous relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That caused us a crisis, not only personally, but
professionally,'' says Dennis, author of ``Salvation on Sand
Mountain,'' a nonfiction account of his encounter with religious
snake handlers. ``Should we tell the truth in the book? We decided,
as writers, that was our job.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Cleaving: The Story of a Marriage'' (North Point
Press, $22), a brutally honest account _ of alcoholism, drug use
and affairs _ that has created a firestorm of controversy in their
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the idea of writing about your marriage is a frightening
possibility,'' says Dennis, 50. ``It's much more difficult than
picking up rattlesnakes. It was an ordeal. In Vicki's case, I think
it was the best writing she's done.''
</P>
<P>
   But the writing wasn't easy. Vicki, 46, the author of critically
acclaimed novels ``Night Ride Home'' and ``The Last Hotel for
Women,'' lost both parents and suffered a heart attack during the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The most painful part for both authors was explaining everything
to their daughters, Ashley, 14, and Laura, 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very supportive, as were most of our friends and
other writers,'' Dennis says. Pat Conroy, who thinly disguised his
own family woes in his fiction, called them regularly to tell them
what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Conroy's warning, the Covingtons were unprepared for the
controversy that erupted when the book was published. Some friends
shunned them, and the Southside Baptist Church in Birmingham asked
them to resign their positions as deacons and Sunday school
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither regrets writing the book, and they have been encouraged
by the receptions they've received on their national book tour.
``We've had big crowds,'' Vicki says. ``People want to talk about
marriage and why it does or doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   And why are they still married after all their problems?
</P>
<P>
   Says Vicki: ``Because we love each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Covingtons will sign their book at 7:30 tonight at Borders
Books &AMP; Music in Buckhead, 3637 Peachtree Road N.E., 404-237-
</P>
<P>
   0707 .
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY COLLECTIBLES: If you're looking for something beyond
the current best sellers, take a gander at some of the first
editions being offered this weekend at the Georgia Antiquarian Book
Fair. Among the selections are an autograph book signed by Abraham
Lincoln and Frederick Douglass for $30,000, the first American
edition of ``Frankenstein'' for $35,000, and a first edition of
Zora Neale Hurston's novel ``Jonah's Gourd Vine'' for $12,500. Also
for sale are four hand-lettered, gold-illuminated medieval Bibles
expected to bring $250,000. Other books range from $5 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   The book fair will be held at the Gwinnett Civic Center, off
I-85 north at Exit 42A. Admission is $7 for preview night Friday
(5:30-9:30 p.m.) and Saturday (10 a.m.-5 p.m.), or $5 for Saturday
only. Information: 770-457-2919.
</P>
<P>
   Email: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
