<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Hannibal' author maintains his silence
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tracking down Thomas Harris is almost as difficult as catching
up with the elusive Hannibal Lecter. The 58-year-old author refuses
to do interviews. When he has talked to the press, it's been only
to explain why he doesn't want to talk about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think really everything that I know is in my books,'' Harris
told a reporter in Waco, Texas, 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most friends from his college and newspaper years have lost
touch with him. The few who keep up social contact with him at his
homes in Miami and Sag Harbor, N.Y., portray the divorced author as
a soft-spoken Southern gentleman who lives with his longtime
girlfriend, Pace Barnes; loves to travel; and savors gourmet food
and fine wines. Sort of like Hannibal Lecter, up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism background
</P>
<P>
   Before he became the best-selling author of ``Red Dragon'' and
``The Silence of the Lambs,'' Harris spent a bookish childhood in
Rich, Miss., reading works by Ernest Hemingway and Thomas Wolfe
while his mother taught high school biology and his father farmed.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Baylor University with a degree in
English, Harris worked as a reporter for the Waco News-Tribune and
later joined The Associated Press in New York, where he teamed up
with two co-workers, Sam Maull and Dick Riley, to write the
thriller ``Black Sunday'' in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1991 interview, Maull recalled Harris as a man who had
``tremendous insights into human nature. He was a real stickler for
detail. He's never appeared to be someone who has hidden demons who
could go off at any time. What you're reading is imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harris was fascinated with serial killers from early on,
says Charlie Reynolds, a journalism professor at Tarleton State
University in Stephenville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clipped everything he could find on them,'' says Reynolds,
63, who taught Harris at Baylor and worked with him at the Waco
Herald-Tribune in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good writer even then. He was a lot of fun when you
got to know him. He rode to work on a motorcycle and he enjoyed
having drinks after work and socializing. Mostly he sat and
listened to what everybody else said. He told me one time that he
wanted to make a million dollars and go off and not have to talk to
anybody. I guess he's accomplished that.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously. With 1.2 million copies of ``Hannibal'' in print and
a $9 million movie deal with Dino de Laurentiis, Harris can be as
silent as a lamb for as long as he likes.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
