A9769 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUENA-COODER18-COX     06-17 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUENA-COODER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Ry Cooder, Cuban music is strummable magic
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guitarist Ry Cooder, whose musical obsessions have taken him
deep into such varied traditions as Hawaiian slack-key guitar,
Tex-Mex balladry and American country blues, has been involved in
an ongoing Cuban adventure since the 1996 sessions that initiated
the ``Buena Vista Social Club'' project.
</P>
<P>
   That this huge phenomenon in world music _ the revival of Cuba's
pre-revolutionary son form as a Grammy-winning mainstream American
success story _ happened at all is a fluke that Cooder likens to an
``X-Files'' episode. When a Havana summit meeting among Cooder, a
group of African musicians and various Cuban performers fell
through (the Africans, he explains, ``were diverted''), producers
had to find additional local musicians to salvage the project. A
studio was waiting. The players were there. Magic happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you think it's the luck of the draw,'' says Cooder,
52. ``But in this case I have to say I see the hand of fate
writing, and that's all there is to it.''
</P>
<P>
   We quizzed Cooder, who continues to play and record with the
``Buena Vista'' musicians, about the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So some of the musicians who appear in the movie were thought
to have been dead?
</P>
<P>
   A: They were not necessarily known to be alive. Compay Segundo
we knew was supposed to be around. He was a very famous guy because
of his age. Ruben Gonzalez on piano was on the list. First, people
say he's dead, we haven't seen him in 10 years. Then somebody said,
``He's not dead, he's just got arthritis and can't play.'' Well,
none of it was true, and yet another person we asked for had died
six months before. In the '90s, it doesn't take a genius to figure
this out: People are dropping like flies. If there's any of them
left at all, it's a miracle. It was a different story in the '70s.
In the '70s you could have seen anybody who was still around from
the tradition. Twenty-five-odd years later, it's getting harder to
do this kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the secret of the music's appeal?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's beautiful music. With the African rhythm structure, with
the colonial-era French and Spanish melodies over the top. It's a
very beautiful combination, very unique in the world. It's the
greatest geographic synthesis of cultural mix I've ever heard.
There's nothing to compare it to. This has been very well worked
out over 150 years. They've crafted this stuff. It starts with
poetry, and the poetry is terrific. Cubans are very poetical;
poetry is a big deal down there. The lyrics are, like, specific and
complicated and universal, but tiny, miniature screenplays.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens next?
</P>
<P>
   A: Time changes everything, and we see now that the acceleration
of history is so intense. Cuba's coming on, coming on with force.
You're going to see economic and political and social issues coming
up. This was a backwater. Cuba was really just a little spot. And
then, during the revolution, it was off-limits and nobody knew
anything about it. This is going to change overnight. It may mean
that they get thermometers in hospitals and medicine for sick
people and some food. The people won't change, but their
circumstances will change, and it's bound to be drastic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
