<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-INNOCENCE18-CO     06-17 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-INNOCENCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A lost opportunity for emotional depth resonance
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'' loses its way all too often,
but it never completely loses its audience.
</P>
<P>
   Disconnected and dreamlike, this film from director Mike Figgis
(``Leaving Las Vegas'') is, by turns, maddeningly self-indulgent
and disturbingly primal. You may not like everything about it, but
you certainly won't forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its elliptical, episodic structure, this is one of
those movies where it really helps to know what's going on going
in. Essentially, it centers on Nic (Julian Sands), a British
filmmaker in Tunisia with a skeleton crew. During the shoot, which
takes him and his group to some very remote areas, he thinks back
on earlier incarnations of himself. As a wide-eyed 5-year-old in
Kenya who accidentally stumbles upon a moment of colonial-style
sexual fetishism. As a 12-year-old fat boy humiliated in gym class.
As a slim but still awkward 16-year-old whose hot-and-fumbled
necking session with his willing girlfriend is interrupted by her
dying father. Even as his adult self, attempting a sexual
connection with his sad-eyed wife.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, interspersed with these outtakes from Nic's life
is a parallel story in which a very black, very muscular Adam and a
very white, very anorexic Eve play out their Garden of Eden tragedy
on the grounds of a decaying estate. Before tasting forbidden
fruit, they watch each other urinate and try eating grass.
</P>
<P>
   It's not what you'd call profound.
</P>
<P>
   Give Figgis credit, however, for his ravishing images (courtesy
of Benoit Delhomme, who shot ``The Scent of Green Papaya'') and his
expressive outbursts of emotional power.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned teen-lust situation is an almost universal
embarrassment _ a well-meaning parent who walks in at the wrong
time. That the parent is in pain and visibly unwell gives the
sequence an entirely unexpected twist. Likewise, a scene in which a
blind woman's guide dog attracts the sexual attention of some
strays starts out almost comically, then veers into something cruel
and terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis is dealing with more than the loss of sexual innocence.
Rather, he's looking at the loss of innocence, period, which, in
his terms, usually means defilement and desecration.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this is a movie of moments _ some transcendently
powerful, others taxingly silly (the Garden of Eden part too often
recalls ``The Blue Lagoon'' at its ripest). Figgis' ``Loss'' is no
loser, but it's no winner, either. It's too shapeless and
unfocused.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say that this audaciously personal film is aimed at
moviegoers prepared to fill in the blanks for the filmmaker. And
for the adventurous movie lover, that's not necessarily a bad
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Loss
</P>
<P>
   of Sexual
</P>
<P>
   Innocence''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julian Sands. Directed by Mike Figgis. Rated R for sex,
nudity, language and violence. At Lefont Plaza. 1 hour, 41 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Loses its way a lot, but manages to keep its power.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
