<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS18-     06-17 2630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Jill
Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa's
</P>
<P>
   Elephant Kingdom'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary
</P>
<P>
   It has some eye-poppingly large pachyderms, but it isn't as
visually astounding as ``Everest.'' Still, this IMAX film has its
share of lovely images, including time-lapse shots of the sun
setting on the dusty horizon and a massive storm whirling across
the plain. (SM) 40 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers: The Spy
</P>
<P>
   Who Shagged Me'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mike Myers
</P>
<P>
   and Heather Graham.
</P>
<P>
   As the world's fave dentally impaired British superspy, Mike
Myers goes back to the '60s to save his mojo from Dr. Evil and a
giant slob in a kilt (Myers and Myers, respectively). Shaggy but
still shagadelic, this worthy sequel also stars Heather Graham as a
curvy CIA operative, Seth Green as Dr. Evil's brooding son Scott
and Jerry Springer (don't ask). (SM)
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 35 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' R (brief nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Thandie Newton
</P>
<P>
   and David Thewlis.
</P>
<P>
   An art movie for the MTV generation. Made for Italian TV, it's
about a reclusive Brit (David Thewlis) who lives in a huge villa in
Rome and his relationship with his housekeeper (Thandie Newton), a
proud African beauty who mops by day and studies pre-med by night.
Full of exquisite touches, but it can come off as overblown
emotional shorthand. (ERG)
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 34 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Buena Vista Social Club'' G
</P>
<P>
   A documentary
</P>
<P>
   by Wim Wenders.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not already a fan of the crossover hit record, ``Buena
Vista Social Club,'' you might feel lost during this documentary.
Shot low-key and almost defiantly shapeless by German auteur Wim
Wenders, the movie follows musician Ry Cooder and his son Joachim
back to Cuba, where he rediscovered the near-forgotten musical
artists of the pre-Castro era. The music saves the movie. (SM) 1
hour, 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' R (profanity, sexuality and drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Broderick
</P>
<P>
   and Reese Witherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   In this cruelly funny satire, high school teacher Matthew
Broderick schemes to thwart perky student Reese Witherspoon in her
bid for the student government presidency. The second feature from
``Citizen Ruth'' director Alexander Payne may sound like a bouncy
comedy. But it's really a
</P>
<P>
   bittersweet ode to the everyday lies people tell themselves to
justify their actions. (SM) 1 hour, 44 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Endurance'' G
</P>
<P>
   Starring Haile Gebrselassie.
</P>
<P>
   A peculiar but engaging blend of travelogue, docudrama and
sports film. It's the tale of wind-swift runner Haile Gebrselassie,
who plays himself, and his journey from a life of poverty in
Ethiopia to gold medalist at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. (SM) 1
hour, 27 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment'' PG-13 (violence and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean Connery
</P>
<P>
   and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   A thriller with no thrills. A he/she sexual pas de deux with
little
</P>
<P>
   chemistry. Sean Connery plays Max, a dapper thief swiping
priceless works of art and computer chips. A shapely insurance
agent (Catherine Zeta-Jones) slinks into the picture and
``Entrapment'' becomes a cat-and-mouse game with lots of twists and
turns. Sadly, it's almost always a bore. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 50
minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by David Breashears.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story IMAX
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' David
Breashears'
</P>
<P>
   documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm that
killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' (SM) 44 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' PG-13 (profanity, sexuality, drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sandra Bullock
</P>
<P>
   and Ben Affleck.
</P>
<P>
   Opposites attract as strait-laced Ben Affleck heads to his
wedding and is tempted by free spirit Sandra Bullock. Like ``My
Best Friend's Wedding,'' it's a savvy blend of romantic-comedy
formula and wise '90s updates. (SM) At area discount theaters. 1
hour, 41 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The General's Daughter'' R (profanity, violence, rape,
</P>
<P>
   sadomasochism)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Travolta,
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Stowe
</P>
<P>
   and James Woods.
</P>
<P>
   As a warrant officer investigating the mysterious slaying of a
female captain, John Travolta bolts on screen, barking his lines
and spitting his machismo all over the place. He's got to.
Somebody's got to turn this mess into a movie. Shot in Savannah and
disguised as an A-grade film, ``General's Daughter'' is a slick,
over-directed, over-written and ultimately underwhelming whodunit
B-grade thriller. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 55 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' R (profanity, adult sexual issues)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Silverstone
</P>
<P>
   and Brad Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   Needs to get over itself. This gay-themed film about two British
male teens and their coming-out conflicts might have been of some
interest 15 years ago. Now, it's so obvious that the only ones
who'll be interested are gay 15-year-olds. As is, ``Get Real''
bravely goes where too many films have gone before. (ERG) 1 hour,
48 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct'' R (intense violent behavior)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Anthony Hopkins
</P>
<P>
   and Cuba Gooding Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Resist your instinct to see it. Oscar winner Anthony Hopkins
plays an anthropologist locked up in a psychiatric prison
surrounded by ``colorful'' inmates. It seems that, after living for
months with gorillas in the African wilds, he went berserk and
killed two natives. Why? It's up to a psychiatry student (Oscar
winner Cuba Gooding Jr.) to pick his mind. It's twaddle. (SM) 2
hours, 4 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Life'' R (language, sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eddie Murphy
</P>
<P>
   and Martin Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence bicker for more than 60 years
in this sometimes hilarious and racially poignant prison comedy.
How they landed in a Mississippi correctional facility with life
sentences isn't nearly as important as the knack these talented
performers have for taking turns at
</P>
<P>
   generating laughs out of a throwaway script. (Bob Longino). 1
hour, 49 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' R (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Strathairn
</P>
<P>
   and Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio.
</P>
<P>
   Independent filmmaker John Sayles is at his most
independent-minded in this intriguing and inherently honorable
movie whose parts don't add up to a satisfying whole. It's as if he
set out to make one film _ a tender, middle-aged romance told
against the backdrop of encroaching tourism in Alaska _ and then
got interested in something totally different: an unsettling
metaphysical survival tale. (ERG) 2 hours, 6 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Loss
</P>
<P>
   of Sexual Innocence'' R (violence, profanity, sex and nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julian Sands.
</P>
<P>
   Loses its way all too often, but never loses its audience.
Disconnected and dreamlike, Mike Figgis' film is as self-indulgent
as it is disturbingly primal. A British filmmaker (Julian Sands) in
Tunisia reflects on various former selves _ a little boy in Kenya;
a fat boy in gym class; a lust-filled teen. Meanwhile, a very black
Adam and a very white Eve act out their Garden-of-Eden tragedy on a
decaying estate. (ERG) 1 hour, 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kate Capshaw,
</P>
<P>
   Tom Everett Scott
</P>
<P>
   and Tom Selleck.
</P>
<P>
   Not lovable, but generally likable. An anonymous love letter
circulates among the residents of a small New England town setting
off rendezvous, revelations and romantic misunderstandings. The
film has two problems: It flirts with a serious case of the cutes
and Kate Capshaw, sexually appealing and adorably flustered, never
quite takes over her own star vehicle. Still, it has enough charm
to keep you interested. (ERG) 1 hour, 29 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix'' R (sci-fi violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves,
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Fishburne
</P>
<P>
   and Carrie-Anne Moss.
</P>
<P>
   A knockout sci-fi flick. Writer-directors Andy and Larry
Wachowski bring their sharp storytelling and visual showmanship to
an adventure
</P>
<P>
   starring Keanu Reeves that should please comic book fanatics and
mainstream moviegoers. Balancing intelligence with stunning special
effects and action, it's a movie that earns its explosions, high
kicks and cascades of spent
</P>
<P>
   bullets. (SM) 2 hours, 15 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy'' PG-13 (pervasive adventure violence
</P>
<P>
   and partial nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brendan Fraser
</P>
<P>
   and Rachel Weisz.
</P>
<P>
   Mummy, make it stop! Please! Just because a movie has desert
scenery, a hunky action hero (Brendan Fraser), hissable bad guys
and supernatural hoodoo doesn't make it an Indiana Jones flick.
You'll miss Steven Spielberg's masterful touch watching ``The
Mummy,'' a petrified mixture of retro adventure, clumsy slapstick
and minimal chills. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   At metro theaters. 2 hours, 4 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Never Been Kissed'' PG-13 (profanity, drug use,
</P>
<P>
   sexual references)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Drew Barrymore
</P>
<P>
   and David Arquette.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore is Josie Geller, a newspaper copy editor in her
mid-20s and former high school dweeb (``Josie Grossie,'' they
called her) who goes back to teenville as an undercover reporter,
promptly relives high school hell and pretty much bumbles her way
to popularity. Everything about her career is implausible. The
movie's jokes are lame, its situations loopy. But Barrymore does
make a go of it. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 47 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Hugh Grant
</P>
<P>
   and Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Boy gets movie star, boy loses movie star, etc. Hugh Grant plays
a decent London bookseller and Julia Roberts a version of herself
(worldwide movie star) in this romantic comedy. The latest from the
writer of ``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' is old-fashioned hokum,
short on surprise but very long on charm. (SM) 2 hours, 4 minutes.
B
</P>
<P>
   ``October Sky'' PG (profanity, sensuality, alcohol use,
</P>
<P>
   some thematic elements)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jake Gyllenhaal,
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cooper and Laura Dern.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply satisfying tale of West Virginia teenager Homer (Jake
Gyllenhaal) and three friends who, in the 1950s, began to build and
shoot off model rockets. Their goal: to win a science fair, which
could help them escape a future of working in the coal mine of
their small town. Based on Homer Hickam's autobiography ``Rocket
Boys,'' it makes the process of learning seem as exciting as a
special FX-driven action flick. (SM) 1 hour, 48 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode I
</P>
<P>
   _ The Phantom Menace'' PG (sci-fi action/violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liam Neeson,
</P>
<P>
   Ewan McGregor and Natalie Portman.
</P>
<P>
   Is George Lucas' new movie visually amazing? Yes. Exciting?
Sometimes. Emotionally involving? Almost never. As a technological
Mount Everest (and the Mount McKinley of marketing), ``Menace'' is
a
</P>
<P>
   remarkable achievement. Too bad writer-director Lucas left out
the gee-whiz enthusiasm of the original movies. He also left out
memorable characters. He left out the fun. (SM) 2 hours, 11
minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' G
</P>
<P>
   Animated film with voices
</P>
<P>
   by Tony Goldwyn, Minnie Driver,
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Close and Nigel Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's animated ``Tarzan'' really swings. This long-haired
dude confidently surfs through Africa's immense rain forest. He
glides barefoot on never-ending, moss-covered tree limbs like the
coolest Rollerblader you've ever seen. His feet never fail him. His
movie doesn't either. Both a little scary and a lot funny, kids
will no doubt lap this movie up. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 28 minutes.
B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Mussolini'' PG
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joan Plowright,
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Smith and Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Known in 1930s Florence as ``the scorpioni,'' thanks to their
collective sting, a band of British and American expatriate women
become surrogate mothers of a young boy named Luca. Based on his
autobiography, director Franco Zeffirelli's film is an uneven but
enjoyable tale of a boy growing up in Black Shirt Italy, entrusted
to a handful of Auntie Mames. (SM) 1 hour, 58 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thirteenth Floor'' R (profanity, sex and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Craig Bierko,
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Mol
</P>
<P>
   and Armin Mueller-Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   A ``what is reality?'' sci-fi thriller that doesn't measure up
to earlier and better films such as ``The Matrix'' and ``Dark
City.'' It's about a modern-day computer whiz team that creates,
then walks around in, a digitized version of 1937 Los Angeles.
Murder, intrigue and too much flat acting follow. Your ultimate
warning: The movie's from some of the creative team that earlier
flubbed ``Godzilla.'' (Bob Longino) 2 hours. C
</P>
<P>
   ``T. rex: Back to the Cretaceous'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liz Stauber
</P>
<P>
   and Peter Horton.
</P>
<P>
   The IMAX film has awesome special effects but, as a fictional
story, is too short. Ally Hayden (Liz Stauber) is a budding teenage
paleontologist who wants to go on a dig with her dino-hunting dad
(Peter Horton). When her dad brings what could be a dinosaur egg
into his lab, Ally accidentally cracks it and is thrust back in
time 65 million years, when the big beasts roamed the Earth. (ERG)
40 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Trippin''' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Deon Richmond
</P>
<P>
   and Donald Adeosun Faison.
</P>
<P>
   It keeps trippin' up on its own mixed message. Deon Richmond
plays Greg, a high school senior whose plans for college keep
getting waylaid by his fantasies of living the phat life,
surrounded by gorgeous women whose sole goal in life is to show him
their breasts. The movie has flashes of charm and heart, but
they're undermined by the filmmakers' pandering to the basic
instincts of its target teen audience. (SM) 1 hour, 32 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice Upon
</P>
<P>
   a Yesterday'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Douglas Henshall
</P>
<P>
   and Lena Headey.
</P>
<P>
   This romantic fantasy starts out with flat-footed awkwardness
but gradually grows deeper, nimbler. Its ideas about love and
destiny gleam with promise, even if the movie never quite finds the
structure to show them off properly. It's a near miss. (SM) 1 hour,
35 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``William Shakespeare's
</P>
<P>
   A Midsummer
</P>
<P>
   Night's Dream'' PG-13 (sensuality and nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, magic doesn't happen. A sexy cast, a classic play,
the
</P>
<P>
   sensuous Tuscany countryside. How could ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' misfire? Blame it on director Michael Hoffman, whose
</P>
<P>
   picturesque but pedestrian approach dims the sparkle of William
Shakespeare's script. (SM) 1 hour, 55 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Winslow Boy'' G
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nigel Hawthorne
</P>
<P>
   and Jeremy Northam.
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet proves an unexpectedly good match for Terence
Rattigan's 1946 play loosely based on a true story of an Edwardian
patriarch's risky and costly fight to clear his 13-year-old son's
name when the boy is expelled from a prestigious school for
stealing pocket change. Mamet brings care, thoughtfulness and even
a theatrical spark to the material. Nigel Hawthorne and Jeremy
Northam lead an excellent cast. (ERG) 1 hour, 44 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves''
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Not as visually stunning as some IMAX films, this is a highly
instructive look at the once nearly vanquished gray wolf's gradual
reintroduction to Yellowstone National Park and other parts of the
American West. Covers a bit too much ground, historically and
geographically; the best parts show wolves ranging from adult pack
leaders to newborn cubs exploring and adjusting to the wild again.
(Jill Vejnoska) 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Jill
Vejnoska write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
