<HEADER>
A9778 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIRATES-HALL/WYLE18-C     06-17 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRATES-HALL/WYLE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tale of two boys and their PC toys
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Noah Wyle stars as the freewheeling Steve Jobs and Anthony
Michael Hall as the geekily focused Bill Gates in the made-for-TNT
movie, ``Pirates of Silicon Valley,'' airing Sunday night at 8. The
actors talked a bit with staff writer Drew Jubera about their roles
in the movie, which dramatizes the race between Apple Computer and
Microsoft for computer age dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY MICHAEL HALL
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at the Flying Biscuit in Candler Park wearing Alain
Mikli designer glasses that seemed to say, very deliberately, so
they would not be misunderstood: ``I've changed. I'm not the
teenage nerd you remember me as. I've moved on. I suggest you do
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Michael Hall _ former nerd-playing Brat Pack star of
such '80s teen signposts as ``Sixteen Candles'' and ``The Breakfast
Club'' _ went from geek poster boy to a year on ``Saturday Night
Live'' to drinking a quart of vodka a day to dropping off the
public radar. Hall, 31, clearly sees his role as Bill Gates in
Sunday's ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' on TNT as a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why Gates?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was an opportunity to change my life. I was asked to
prepare four scenes and I really wanted to impress the will to win,
that desire. I didn't just do a reading and leave; I wasn't just
performing for suits. This time I really wanted to deliver. It made
me reinvest in my own craft. I felt like I was the richest actor in
the world the day I got the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How'd you prepare?
</P>
<P>
   A: I transferred all the documentary interviews on Gates to
audiocassette and walked around listening to them on my Walkman. I
walked around the set with it on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sounds kinda . . . nerdy.
</P>
<P>
   A: I wanted to be convincing as (Gates) _ make people forget
they were watching this kid from the '80s. I understand the
correlation people make to the nerd thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The nerd thing. You're a star at 15, then you basically
disappear . . .
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a lot harder to get work than people think. I'm humble
about the process _ only I know how many meetings I've been to.
I've been in 29 movies and I've probably taken 2,000 meetings. The
challenge is to survive all the pitfalls and cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Pitfalls and cliches?
</P>
<P>
   A: Death and addiction. I was able to view it firsthand. It took
a long time to see it all. I took that time in my 20s. Where in the
past I took this for granted, now I have more respect.
</P>
<P>
   NOAH WYLE
</P>
<P>
   Taking an off-season break from his role as Dr. John Carter on
NBC's ``ER,'' Noah Wyle talked recently about transforming himself
into Apple Computer co-founder Steve Jobs for Sunday's ``Pirates of
Silicon Valley'' on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why play Jobs?
</P>
<P>
   A: They sent me the script and enclosed a documentary that was
on PBS, ``Triumph of the Nerds,'' a history of the PC industry. It
was cued to Jobs' '94 introduction at an Apple (stockholders
convention). So I popped it in the VCR, and there was something
unbelievably charismatic about him. He was complicated,
interesting, contradictory, and I thought, ``If I don't play him
I'll kick myself for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're a dead ringer for him. It's kinda weird.
</P>
<P>
   A: In the last scene, when I'm wearing a sweater vest and his
round glasses, there's a photo from that time from the exact same
Boston convention, and when I put the two next to each other, I
giggled. I looked at myself and said, ``That's him.'' Pretty damned
scary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How'd you approach playing the guy?
</P>
<P>
   A: I made sure I never hit the same note twice with him, to
belay a constant sense of evolution. Every time he's speaking, he's
only saying about a tenth of what he's thinking. I attacked Jobs
more from the standpoint of a Shakespearean hero: He should
succeed, but because of innate traits, he can't possibly succeed.
If he'd died when (Apple) fired him, that would hold true. But the
fact that he was successful with Pixar (the computer animation
company) and came back to Apple, it contradicts that philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you talk to him, or to people who know him?
</P>
<P>
   A: I spoke to people associated with him. The way they described
him was, ``Consummate salesman, horrible boss.'' He's an incredible
motivator, visionary _ part carnival huckster, part Zen monk. I
doubt I even scratched the surface on him, but I got an indication
of how deep the well was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Zen monk?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was a wonderful quote I read about his approach to Zen.
In monasteries, there was one monk called the Zen Crazy, who had
license to walk about and be belligerent and not bathe. He could
not be more un-Zen. He was there to keep all the other monks on
their toes, to galvanize their faith by constantly challenging
them. And there was Jobs, skulking the halls, surprising people at
their desks, challenging their work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How's he different from Gates?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both are master chess players. I call Gates ruthless, but to
a very fixed and defined point. Whatever his definition of success
is, he's unwavering in his approach. Jobs is more inconsistent,
more a dreamer, prone to flights of fancy. He takes three wrong
steps to come around to the right path. He's not as good a chess
player (as Gates).
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitutition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
