<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collins revs up `Tarzan' soundtrack
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any time Walt Disney Pictures pokes its paintbrushes into the
jungle, whether it's 1967's ``The Jungle Book'' or 1994's ``The
Lion King,'' it comes up with a hit. So when the animation giant
tapped Phil Collins to produce five new songs for ``Tarzan,'' it
was a tall order _ this also is the first Disney animated film to
predominantly feature a single vocalist throughout, and the former
Genesis singer and drummer does not disappoint. Whether it's the
driving rhythm of the film's majestic opening number, ``Two
Worlds,'' or the radio-ready ballad ``You'll Be in My Heart,''
Collins' music cuts an impressive swath through the animated
underbrush.Only the foot-tapping ``Son of Man'' contains more than
a faint whiff of Collins' pop successes, and composer Mark Mancina,
who scored the action flicks ``Twister'' and ``Speed,'' expertly
mixes African rhythms and instrumentation to create a lush
soundscape for the most dramatic sequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Collins. Walt Disney Records.
</P>
<P>
   14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   A successful romp in the
</P>
<P>
   wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard L. Eldredge writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
