<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVOLTA18-COX     06-17 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVOLTA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talking with Travolta
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  A few things about John Travolta
</P>
<P>
   (``The General's Daughter''):
</P>
<P>
   He's a movie star. During a recent visit to Atlanta, a
photographer is required to show him Polaroid proofs before he'll
agree to let her snap a roll of portrait shots. The lighting has to
be just so. And the makeup woman in the corner is there not just
for touch-ups, but to point out if his tie has slipped, exposing
the buttons of his charcoal-gray shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta knows the power of image, whether it's the white
leisure suit that drove him into disco fame in ``Saturday Night
Fever'' or the greasy hit-man hair of Vincent Vega, the ``Pulp
Fiction'' role that microwaved his Hollywood career after 10 tepid
years. He takes possession of an Atlanta hotel conference room with
the shambling grace of a royal bear, a bear dressed very well and
beautifully groomed. And when he speaks, it's in a low, soft rumble
that makes you lean in a little.
</P>
<P>
   Some other things: He's 45, a Scientologist, married to actress
Kelly Preston (their son, Jett, is 7), and he's a pilot who loves
to fly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the two months he spent in sweltering Savannah last summer,
shooting ``Daughter'':
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it, actually. I didn't mind the weather. I lived in
Florida for six years, so the weather was not a big deal. There was
a cigar club that I went to, and a couple of restaurants that were
quite nice. I stayed in this lovely house, so mostly I stayed home
after work, went to the movies a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  As an actor who's emptied his share of machine guns
(``Face/Off''), what about the post-Columbine High School debate
about Hollywood violence?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we underestimate the correlation to those incidents
and street drugs or prescription drugs. You know, I grew up in the
'60s, and when things happened like Manson and all that, they were
on LSD, it altered their state of mind. These days it's just a
little more disguised, you know. So I think that's not looked at
perhaps enough. There have been violent movies around for 100
years, since movies started. And it's all your state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid could be subjected to a Playboy and be fine. Another,
it might send him on a roll of pornography. Another child may be
able to watch a violent movie, but another one may come home
wanting to break up the house. That's personal judgment there. It's
always (caused by) a bunch of things, and I think it's wrong to try
to blame one area. There's always this heated rush to find some one
`why,' when it may be a mix of things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biggest indulgence:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm famous for food being an indulgence. I think I'm
famous for aviation, flying, travel. It's extroverting for me. It
makes me feel focused.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biggest fear:
</P>
<P>
   ``Heartbreak with people. I get disappointed easily. It's never
too much about my family; it's mostly been with friends and working
situations. It is my nature to want an ascent in life. I want to go
up. I'm a romantic, what can I tell you? I want things to be ideal,
I want the joys and pleasures in life to be what I know they can
be. But to expect that from other people, it's a little
unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two things I was thinking about today. One was the
song from `Cabaret' ... `The sun will rise and the moon will set,
sooner or later you'll settle for what you get.' But I've never
settled, really. Even though I've been hurt or heartbroken, I've
never accepted the idea of settling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there's a line that once in a while creeps in: `Most men
lead lives of quiet desperation.' I refuse it. I just don't agree
with it. I don't want to agree with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His next project:
</P>
<P>
   ``Battlefield Earth,'' based on a novel by Scientology founder
L. Ron Hubbard, which starts filming in Montreal next month. ``I
play a 9-foot alien. Man is an endangered species, and these aliens
have taken over the Earth. Man is just hunted for sport and for
slavery. They think of them as rats, basically. I play this wicked,
evil guy that is very full of himself and very arrogant and thinks
of himself as some sort of royalty. It's hilarious. It's the
cruelest humor I've ever seen. It's so cruel it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't feel bad _ Travolta hasn't nailed down his New Year's
Eve plans, either:
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbra Streisand asked me to sing with her on New Year's (in
her Las Vegas concert). I was very honored, the Chosen One, kind
of. But I don't know. I have to see if I want to really live that
pressure for six months. And also, do I want to be doing that for
the millennium? Do you make a little bit of history with the diva
of the century, or do you have your own view of what should happen
on that night?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had planned to fly around the world and try to catch as many
time zones as I could. Kind of a James Bond-y New Year's. Then when
I found out that my favorite airplane, the 707, was gonna be in
inspection in December of '99, I wasn't as interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta video must-sees
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Carrie'' (1976; Rated R). Playing one of telekinetic teen
Sissy Spacek's tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Saturday Night Fever'' (1977; Rated R). Strutting down the
street toward his first Oscar nomination and into pop-culture
history.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Grease'' (1978; Rated PG). Doing the hand-jive with Olivia
Newton-John.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Blow Out'' (1981; Rated R). Uncovering a murder in Brian De
Palma's paranoid thriller.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Pulp Fiction'' (1994; Rated R). Dancing with Uma Thurman,
killing people and landing another Oscar nod.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Get Shorty'' (1995; Rated R). Making a smooth transition
from hoodlum to Hollywood producer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Face/Off'' (1997; Rated R). Changing faces, and
personalities, with Nicolas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Travolta video must-
</P>
<P>
   avoids: Anything made between 1981 and 1994. Oh, and also 1978's
``Moment by Moment'' (Rated R).
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
