<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-17 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE OF KOSOVO ATROCITIES MOUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN AND MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ NATO troops ``by the hour'' are uncovering
evidence of savage, wartime atrocities _ mass murder, rapes, and
torture _ carried out against ethnic Albanian civilians by Serb
soldiers and police in Kosovo, British officials said Thursday.
They estimated more than 10,000 Kosovars were killed in at least
100 separate massacres.
</P>
<P>
   As ethnic Albanian refugees who left Kosovo in the Europe's
largest human displacment since World War II stream back to their
towns, their worst nightmares are coming true. Roads on Kosovo's
southern and western tier reek of death and destruction. In the
once-bustling city of Pec, nearly every house and store has been
burned or bombed out. Family members are missing, and NATO say they
have identified or have heard of 90 mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   In one gruesome scene in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, British
soldiers discovered what officials called a ``torture chamber''
inside a five-story police headquarters. They found knives, rubber
and wooden batons, baseball bats inscribed with Serb slogans, a
wooden crate of brass knuckles, ``savage'' pornography, and drugs
used presumably to sedate victims, said Geoffrey Hoon, Minister of
the British Foreign office. A stack of condoms was also found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still hard to credit that our fellow human beings could
be guilty of machine-gunning children, systematic rape of young
women and girls, digging mass graves, and burning bodies to try and
conceal the evidence of murder,'' Hoon said in London. ``But this
has happened in Kosovo, fresh evidence is being found all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the police headquarters, Hoon said, the British troops
followed a trail of charred paper to an incinerator where Serb
authorities appeared to have burned evidence of the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, President Clinton said he was ``moved'' to see
soldiers finding hard evidence of long-suspected atrocities, and he
said that along with resettling Kosovar refugees, the highest
priority for NATO should be documenting the war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to focus on our obligations _ fundamental humanitarian
obligations to get the Kosovars home and to continue to uncover
whatever evidence of war crimes there is in Kosovo,'' Clinton said
during a news conference with French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of atrocities and confirmation of deaths by
returning refugees is likely to put pressure on the NATO allies to
seize Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, who has been indicted
by the international war crimes tribunal in The Hague. But Clinton
said peacekeepers will take a ``wait and see'' approach toward
Milosevic's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   A team of forensic investigators from the UN court will arrive
in Kosovo Friday to begin documenting the alleged war crimes. They
will concentrate on mapping and photographing suspected sites and
try to substantiate reports of rape, murder, and torture by Serb
forces, said Jim Landane, a spokesman for the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another drama was unfolding as fearful Serb
civilians, carrying their belongings in packed cars and tractors,
formed a column that stretched for miles and moved slowly north
from the southeastern region of Urosevac in Kosovo toward the
Serbian border. The UN World Food Program reported that 50,000
Serbs have left since last week's peace agreement that sent NATO
troops into Kosovo and required all Serb military and police forces
to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's ruling Socialist Party appealed Serbs to stay in
Kosovo, to ``secure the survival of Serbia in this territory.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO officials said allied peacekeeping troops, now
numbering 15,000 are making headway into Kosovo and patrolling
parts of the province. But it will be at least a month before the
full force of 50,000 is in place, spokesman Jamie Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   US and Russian officials meeting in Helsinki failed Thursday to
agree to a plan for integrating Russian troops into the NATO-led
force, but Defense Secretary William Cohen said progress had been
made, and the talks would resume Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The pullout of Serb military units from Kosovo is on schedule
and should be completed Sunday, NATO officials said. Of the 41,000
Serb forces in Kosovo, 26,000 already have withdrawn, along with at
least half of their tanks, artillery pieces, and armored personnel
carriers. The demilitarization of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army
is not going as smoothly yet, the officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, two KLA rebels were brought into Pec with gunshot
wounds, presumably the victims of Serb snipers. Italy's ANSA news
agency reported violent clashes between Serb paramilitary groups
and KLA fighters in Klina, near Pec, where Italian peacekeeping
forces are headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   In Pec, Italian troops watched passively from tanks as KLA
soldiers checked cars. Under a midday rainshower, young rebel
guards confiscated two hand grenades from a Serbian driving a
silver Mercedes _ one from the pocket of his pants and the other
from under a box of cookies in the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Kosovo is open and under control by peacekeeping forces
_ with the visible assistance of the KLA _ the effort to account
for the missing has begun in earnest. Terrible reports are coming
from Kosovars who stayed behind.
</P>
<P>
   The road into Pec is clogged with dead horses and farm animals.
It smells of rotting carcasses and recently burned buildings. The
few locals left say the Serb paramilitary set fires as late as
Thursday, when they made their final pullout.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of Pec, where is now nearly a ghost town,
appears to have been organized and calculated. Even the small
kiosks on the street were subject to the selection process:
Albanian newsstands are shells of blackened metal, while the Serb
kiosks were left untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Houses spray-painted with the word ``Serbia'' _ meaning they
were owned by Serbs who may also have fled _ were intact. Next
door, the homes of their Albanian neighbors were demolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I survived. I was hiding all the time,
running from house to house,'' said Ram Belagu, 24, the only member
of his family to remain in Pec. ``They burned even today,'' Belagu
said. ``They (peacekeepers) didn't do anything. They thought the
paramilitary were gone. I guess they were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   During his nearly three months in hiding, Belagu said, he once
went for four days without a meal, eating grass to stay alive.
Ashamed, Belagu said he had to take food from burned and looted
houses of his neighbors to have something to eat. ``You can't
imagine what it was like,'' the gaunt Belagu said.
</P>
<P>
   In Djakovica, residents speak of a mass grave holding as many as
150 bodies, near a lake in town. The area is off-limits because of
the danger of landmines, so no one has ventured near the site. The
fate of some 1,200 men rounded up by the Serbs is still unknown;
the most hopeful theory is that they were taken to a prison in
upper Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Contributing to this report were Milligan and Globe correspondent
Kurt Pitzer from Pec, Leonard from Washington, and Globe staff
reporter Ann Scales from Paris. Wire service material was used in
its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
