u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-2000-HNS &LR;      06-17 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CLAIMS PARTIAL CREDIT FOR BOOMING U.S. ECONOMY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Standing at a historic building on Wall Street, Vice
President Al Gore claimed partial credit Thursday for the nation's
economic boom _ and encountered some of the trip wires of New York
politics.
</P>
<P>
   On tour to announce his candidacy for president, Gore spoke at a
campaign rally from the steps of Federal Hall in the heart of
Manhattan's financial district, where gains in the stock market
have transformed the economy. He declared that the nation is
enjoying its strongest economy ever ``under the policies President
Clinton and I have proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the nation's prosperity was seeded by the
policies of GOP presidents Reagan and Bush. But Gore said it was
not until seven years ago, when the Democrats took over the White
House, that the nation started achieving unprecedented job growth
and the erasure of the federal government's budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remember what it was like seven years ago. And I never ever
want to go back,'' Gore said in a refrain he has developed for his
presidential campaign. It refers not only to Republican economic
policies in general, but to the administration of George Bush,
father of the front-runner for the 2000 presidential nomination,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Enhancing the symbols for Gore's message, one supporter at the
rally held a sign saying ``Keep the Bull Market, Vote Gore.'' A
group of children held Gore campaign signs while wearing caps
embossed with the words ``Lehman Brothers,'' an investment banking
firm.
</P>
<P>
   But economic prosperity aside, Gore is fighting for political
attention in New York with another Clinton Democrat, first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton. She is raising money for a possible run for
a U.S. Senate seat from New York, and her potential match-up
against Republican New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has sometimes
made the budding presidential race a mere sideshow for Democrats
here.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about the first lady's possible candidacy, Gore
told reporters on the flight to New York, ``I've already addressed
that issue; I'm all for it.'' He said her campaign would generate
enthusiasm among Democratic voters in New York and across the
country, benefiting the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, Gore's speech was interrupted by the shouts and
whistle-blowing of six protestors claiming that he has protected
U.S. drug manufacturers by opposing production of cheaper, generic
AIDS drug in Africa. Small groups pushing the same issue disrupted
Gore's speeches earlier Thursday in New Hampshire and Wednesday in
Carthage, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   This time, mindful that Manhattan's Federal Hall was where the
Constitutional Congress met and George Washington took the oath of
office as president, Gore shouted back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our First Amendment was born right here on this spot. We honor
it,'' he said. ``Let's give a hand to those who are exercising
their First Amendment rights . . . make it louder! Let's hear it
for the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of a few thousand, which had treated Gore's speech
with more quiet curiosity than cheers, complied by drowning out the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   New York is where Gore's first campaign for president, in 1988,
ran out of gas. Then a U.S. senator from Tennessee, he withdrew
from the Democratic presidential contest after a weak third-place
showing in the New York primary, his campaign $1.6 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   This time his party primary foe has a New York connection and is
from New Jersey, just across the Hudson River: former U.S. Sen.
Bill Bradley, who was a star for the New York Knicks basketball
team.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Manchester, N.H., Gore proposed business tax cuts,
new trade policies and government-funded training for the expansion
of the Internet and high technology.
</P>
<P>
   It was a two-pronged campaign statement: New Hampshire is
recovering from economic problems thanks to the growth of computer
industry jobs and is also the site of the first presidential
primary next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are my proposals to spur innovation for the 21st
century,'' Gore said, in character as a technology and science buff
who promotes those subjects well beyond their usual limit in
campaign politics.
</P>
<P>
   But also to keep part of the focus on his formal announcement as
a presidential candidate, made Wednesday, Gore talked to the
audience at a forum at Hesser College about his theme of family
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask for your help to strengthen family life in America,'' he
said. ``And I make you this pledge: if you entrust me with the
presidency, I will marshal its authority, its resources and its
moral leadership to fight for America's families.''
</P>
<P>
   Moral leadership is one of President Clinton's biggest
weaknesses in the eyes of most voters, and Gore has set out as a
candidate to distance himself from Clinton on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Four AIDS protestors came within a few feet of the vice
president at the forum as they shouted jeers. Law enforcement
officers escorted them from the college.
</P>
<P>
   The African ``crisis of AIDS'' was ignored too long, Gore said,
but now the United States is leading the way in providing
assistance to fight the disease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
