<HEADER>
A9787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IDEAL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-17 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDEAL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AN IDEAL HUSBAND': WILDE AS SENSITIVE GUY, SO WISE AND
INSIGHTFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Political blackmail, insider trading, incriminating documents,
sex as a bargaining tool, potential trial by tabloid and
sanctimonious public oratory masking frantic behind-the-scenes
wheeling and dealing. In some ways, the world of Oscar Wilde's 1895
play ``An Ideal Husband'' seems awfully familiar.
</P>
<P>
   As Oliver Parker's likable, handsome but diluted film adaptation
of Wilde's melodramatic comedy enfolds you in a dream world of
grand Belgravia houses swarming with Victorian London's beautiful
people, madly flirting and exchanging bons mots, it's easy to sink
into a ``Masterpiece Theater'' fantasy of traveling back to a more
civilized time and place. Life at the top has rarely looked or
sounded more fabulously elegant.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' begins with a grand, formal reception at
which the dashing Sir Robert Chiltern (Jeremy Northam) is accosted
by Mrs. Cheveley (Julianne Moore), a beautiful expatriate
adventurer who has traveled all the way from her home in Vienna to
make him an offer he can't refuse. If Robert will reverse his
position in Parliament and support a risky, highly questionable
Argentine canal project in which she has invested all her money,
she will return an incriminating letter he wrote 18 years ago. If
he doesn't, she warns coyly, she will take the letter to the
newspapers and ruin his career.
</P>
<P>
   The letter reveals that Robert once provided an Austrian baron
and close friend of Mrs. Cheveley's with secret information from
the British Foreign Office regarding shares in the Suez Canal. The
baron subsequently gave a percentage of the fortune he reaped from
this privileged information to Robert. The money became the
foundation of Robert's own fortune and brilliant career in
government.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is not only Robert's political career but also his
ecstatically happy marriage to his beautiful and moralistic wife,
Gertrude (Cate Blanchett), who worships him as a paragon of virtue.
If Gertrude were to discover that he was less than perfect, he
confides to his best friend, Lord Arthur Goring (Rupert Everett),
she would be devastated and their marriage destroyed. Arthur, a
cynical, indolent playboy (and Wilde surrogate) who was once
romantically involved with Mrs. Cheveley, advises Robert to confess
everything to his wife and seek her forgiveness and support. But
Robert, fearing Gertrude's inflexibility, balks.
</P>
<P>
   This elaborate setup is much richer than its neatly contrived
resolution, which involves people listening behind doors and a
high-stakes wager between Arthur and Mrs. Cheveley that shifts the
emphasis of the story away from politics toward romance. Also
hanging around waiting for Arthur to notice her is Robert's plucky
sister, Mabel (Minnie Driver, in a terribly underwritten role).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, greed turns out to be no match against charm. The
repository of that charm is Arthur, the ultimate catch, who is
presented as the late-Victorian equivalent of Warren Beatty or John
F. Kennedy Jr. in their bachelor days. Far from being a silly, idle
twit, Arthur reveals previously undisclosed reserves of wisdom,
insight and moral consistency. The dandy who jokes that ``to love
oneself is the beginning of a lifelong romance'' also turns out to
have been waiting all along for Miss Right. He is the only major
character to emerge untainted by hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   In adapting the play, Parker has streamlined and rewritten
Wilde's dialogue, keeping some (but not all) of Wilde's biting
epigrams and scraping off a lot (perhaps too much) of the Victorian
crust. As the movie zips along (especially in its second half), the
drama begins to thin as the all's-well-that-ends-well mechanics go
into motion. The movie's final scenes seem rushed, hollow and
stagy, the passionate kisses unearned.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's Arthur is the subtlest and deepest performance in an
ensemble that meshes fairly well while never quite finding the
seamless groove of a first-rate stage production. Instead of
adopting a conventional Wildean posture and tossing off epigrams
like a self-satisfied fop ostentatiously strewing flowers from his
buttonholes, Everett's Arthur is a sullen, secretive gentleman
rebel concealing his sensitivity beneath a facade of blase
rakishness. Because the clever words leak out of him instead of
being launched like missiles, what he says is all the more truthful
and personal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blanchett's Gertrude strikes a winning balance between
prudery and warmth with her performance of a hopelessly dated
Victorian stereotype, revealing still another side of the actress'
chameleon skills. Northam's Robert is every inch the dashing
Victorian hero, perfect but for one crucial blemish. Ms. Moore's
slightly too sweet Mrs. Cheveley and Ms. Driver's mugging,
eye-rolling Mabel just miss hitting the right sour and comic notes.
</P>
<P>
   If ``An Ideal Husband'' transports us back to a world that seems
more refined than ours, it also flatters us, as Wilde flattered the
play's fin de siecle audience, by arriving at a
plain-as-the-nose-on-your-face piece of wisdom that after all the
preceding badinage may seem more profound than it really is.
Hollywood couldn't come up with a tidier feel-good ending _ one
that gets everybody off the hook _ than ``An Ideal Husband's''
concluding moral: Nobody's perfect.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AN IDEAL HUSBAND'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Oliver Parker; based on the play by
Oscar Wilde; director of photography, David Johnson; edited by Guy
Bensley; music by Charlie Mole; production designer, Michael
Howells; produced by Barnaby Thompson, Uri Fruchtmann and Bruce
Davey; released by Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 97 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: ``An Ideal Husband'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). The dialogue includes sexual innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Cate Blanchett (Gertrude), Minnie Driver (Mabel), Rupert
Everett (Lord Goring), Julianne Moore (Mrs. Cheveley), Jeremy
Northam (Sir Robert), John Wood (Lord Caversham), Lindsay Duncan
(Lady Markby), Peter Vaughan (Phipps) and Jeroen Krabbe (Baron
Arnheim).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-POLAND-NYT &LR;      06-17 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-POLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POPE'S LAST DAY IN POLAND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRAKOW, Poland _ Bidding farewell to Poland, Pope John Paul II
made a stop Thursday at his and his country's most venerated
shrine, the Black Madonna of Czestochowa, a medieval icon of the
Virgin Mary that for Poles also carries vast patriotic
significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got used to coming here and bringing our personal and
family matters, as well as the vital issues of the nation,'' the
pope said after praying at the shrine, in a monastery on a hill in
central Poland. He asked the Madonna, who Poles believe have
protected their country throughout every threat, from 13th-century
Tatars to the Nazis and then the Communists, to see Poland safely
into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, 79, who fell ill for a day on his eighth and longest
visit to Poland, made a more personal stop before returning to
Rome, praying at the grave of his parents at Rakowice cemetery near
here. He also celebrated a Mass and kissed the relics of St.
Stanislaw, an 11th-century bishop and martyr, at the Cathedral on
Wawel Hill, where almost every Polish hero, king and martyr is
buried.
</P>
<P>
   Huge, ecstatic crowds have greeted him at every stop, recreating
some of the euphoria that his presence sparked in trips when Poland
was still under Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   Every stop _ from his arrival at Gdansk, where 20 years ago he
helped set off the Solidarity movement that toppled Communism, to
his nostalgic visit on Wednesday to his hometown, Wadowice _ has
resonated with the extraordinary twin fates of Poland and his
pontificate over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But John Paul has used this voyage to extend his countrymen's
memories, linking the recent past with the last 1,000 years of
Polish history. In his vision, Poland's history and survival are
inseparably entwined with its Christian faith, and he wants a new
generation of Poles to keep that legacy paramount as they grapple
with the secular temptations of their new democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding farewell at the airport, he said, ``During this
pilgrimage, on the eve of the Great Jubilee of the year 2,000, it
has been granted to us to return to the places, events and people
who bear eloquent witness to the fact that during the thousand
tears of the church's life in our homeland, the mystery of the
Incarnation of the Son of God and his redeeming work has penetrated
deeply into its history.''
</P>
<P>
   His message has been solemn, but the pope, despite a fever that
forced him to cancel appearances on Tuesday, has seemed happy and
lighthearted, joking with crowds. Thursday, at a surprise stop in
Gliwice, a town in the industrial region of Silesia, to make up for
canceling his scheduled appearance on Tuesday, he hinted that this
was not a valedictory tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until next time,'' he told several hundred thousand people
cheering him on. ``Thank God for your holy patience with the pope _
one can see that a Silesian is patient and sturdy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself wouldn't put up with such a pope,'' he said. ``When
the pope is supposed to come, he doesn't, and when he is not
supposed to come, he arrives.'' The crowd chanted a Polish
expression of forgiveness that translates, ``No harm done.'' The
pope replied, ``I go to Rome with a peaceful conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   As he grows older and frailer, the pope's memories of his youth
seem to grow stronger. In Wadowice, he remembered street names,
bakeries, school plays and old friends in a cheerful stream of
consciousness that delighted the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   World War II and the suffering of Poles under Nazi occupation
have also been a theme of the Pope's trip. Before the war, Wadowice
was 20 percent Jewish, and unlike many Polish communities then, it
had little overt anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   As he commemorated Polish suffering during the war, he has also
sought to remind Poles also of the fate of the Jews during the
Holocaust. But his efforts at reconciliation have repeatedly been
interrupted by vivid reminders that the wounds of World War II are
still fresh in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   In Warsaw, the grand rabbi of Poland breached protocol in a
reception line to implore the pope to instruct his church to remove
the last remaining cross at Auschwitz. That issue has divided
Catholics and Jews in Poland since the cross was placed outside the
camp walls in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-LABOR-NYT &LR;      06-17 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILO ADOPTS TREAT AIMED AT ABOLISHING WORST FORMS OF CHILD LABOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Germany, The Netherlands, Canada, Norway, Denmark
and France)   By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The International Labor Organization Thursday adopted a
treaty meant to abolish the worst forms of child labor, one that
includes a contested provision allowing people under 18 to serve in
the military. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pact hopes to end the exploitation of millions of children,
who are involved in pornography, prostitution, slavery, hazardous
work and forced recruitment as child soldiers. Drawing attention to
the treaty, President Clinton addressed the delegates, the first
American president to do so. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adopted unanimously by delegates from the 174 country members of
the ILO, the convention aims to protect those under 18 but does not
provide an across-the-board ban on child labor. The treaty's text
does not prohibit people under 18 from voluntarily enlisting in the
military, an omission which non-governmental groups and some
governments believe weakens the document. A compromise was adopted
after insistence by the United States that there be no bar to such
military service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A number of countries, including the United States, Britain,
Germany and the Netherlands, recruit 17-year-olds into their
armies. The United States, among others, requires parental consent.
U.S. officials estimated that the American military services have
fewer than 10,000 enlistees per year under 18. Of these, fewer than
100 are involved in combat units, and those are in the Balkan
region, officials said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The compromise treaty language now bars ``forced or compulsory
recruitment of children for use in armed conflict.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trade unions, along with a diverse group of countries, including
Canada, Norway, Denmark and France, had urged tougher provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it's not appropriate for people under age 18 to be
involved in the military,'' said Tim Noonan, of the International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions, which supported a blanket
prohibition on child labor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defending the administration's position, the American Labor
Secretary, Alexis Herman, said, ``We wanted to make sure the
emphasis was on forced, compulsory child labor.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Martin McPherson, of Amnesty International, disagreed. ``In
the end, it makes no difference whether the person has gone
voluntarily or compulsorily,'' he said. ``Military service is
hazardous - regardless.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Noonan said trade unions wanted a flat ban, the
compromise was agreed to because ``our primary concern was children
in Uganda and Sudan _ the 10- and 12 year-olds with guns.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, who declined to be named, said many countries
allow 17-year-olds to serve voluntarily. ``Our concern is about the
use of the younger ones being abducted and coerced by
paramilitaries and militias,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty says there are an estimated 300,000 such child soldiers
worldwide. They are among the estimated 250 million children under
age 14 who, according to ILO statistics, work in developing
countries, mainly in Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   An ILO treaty adopted in 1973 that set a minimum age for child
labor, has been ratified by 74 countries. The United States is not
among them, although Clinton promised he would quickly send the
treaty to the Senate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
