<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-RECORDS18-COX     06-17 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RECORDS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Olympic officials aim to restrict records access
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After initially pledging full cooperation, Atlanta
Olympic officials now want to restrict federal investigators from
photocopying certain documents among eight boxes of papers they
want to keep out of the public's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing Olympic officials have refused to give U.S.
House Commerce Committee investigators unrestricted access to the
documents, which they consider private and sensitive. The lawyers
contend the records do not relate directly to information sought by
the committee.
</P>
<P>
   However, the congressional investigators think the disputed
records are pertinent and want permission to photocopy anything
they deem necessary.
</P>
<P>
   After first refusing to allow the investigators to copy anything
from the restricted boxes, Olympic officials then asked them to
flag specific sensitive documents they want to copy. Each requested
document then would be considered individually.
</P>
<P>
   But that process was unacceptable to the congressional
investigators, who insist on unfettered access. The papers at issue
were purged from the bid files that Olympic officials say they
eventually will open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the documents which we have said many times pertain
to the established rights to privacy of the Olympic volunteers and
donors, and we continue to believe that these documents legally
have a right to remain private,'' said Lee Echols, spokesman for
the Georgia Amateur Athletics Federation. The GAAF is the group
that successfully bid for the '96 Olympic Games and claims
ownership of the documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not withholding these documents from the committee's
investigators,'' he said, ``but we've been discussing the merits of
what to copy from these documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, any documents in the possession of Congress
eventually could be made available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional committee, which is investigating whether
Atlanta Olympic officials violated federal fraud and bribery laws,
could subpoena the records if Olympic officials decline to turn the
records over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
