<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAULDER-EXECUTION-COX     06-17 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAULDER-EXECUTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canadian killer is executed in Texas
 &HT;    By Jerry Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE _ Joseph Stanley Faulder's 24-year battle for his
life ended Thursday in the Texas death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   He was pronounced dead at 6:18 p.m. after being convicted of
capital murder in the July 9, 1975, slaying of Inez Phillips, 75,
of Gladewater.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Phillips was killed during a robbery in her home. She was
impaled with a butcher knife, which was plunged into her chest and
exited from her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 24-year fight is over. And it is about time,'' Gregg County
District Attorney Bill Jennings said upon learning of Faulder's
death. ``It is hard to believe that it is over Faulder, 61, was
arrested two years after the murder, and his attorneys successfully
postponed his execution nine times. Thursday was his 10th and last
execution date.
</P>
<P>
   His execution came just three weeks shy of the 24th anniversary
of Mrs. Phillips' death.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Sandra Babcock of Minneapolis, during the past two
weeks, filed a flurry of motions, petitions, writs and lawsuits.
One was pending before the U.S. Supreme Court as late as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She succeeded in halting his execution with 30 minutes to spare
last Dec. 10, when the Supreme Court granted a stay of execution,
which it vacated a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   But Babcock's efforts were to no avail Thursday, and Faulder
died with a fatal injection of poison into his veins in Texas'
death chamber at the Walls Unit of the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice Institutional Division in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder was the 178th person to die since Texas resumed
executions in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He was the 14th executed this year. Eleven others have execution
dates set, and 462 are on death row, according to prison
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed on the Texas death row 8,221 days (22.52 years),
second only to Robert Excel White, who was executed March 30 after
8,977 days (24 years, six months) on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Mrs. Phillips were dismayed and disgusted that
Faulder had evaded the executioner nine times. The 10th execution
date affected Faulder, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why don't you guys just go ahead and kill me or cut me free,''
prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said Faulder told him two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   As he was being ready for the trip into the death chamber
Thursday, Faulder told prison officials, ''I'm at peace with my
maker. I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulder was born in Canada, and his case attracted massive media
attention in his native land, which abolished the death penalty in
1976. He became the first Canadian since 1952 to be executed in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues Babcock raised in her numerous writs was the
failure of local officers to notify the Canadian consulate that he
had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna Convention on Consular Affairs, a treaty signed by
the United States, requires local officials to notify a foreign
country's consular office anytime a person from the foreign country
is arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Local officers said they were unaware of the treaty, and did not
know Faulder was a Canadian citizen because he had a Texas drivers
license at the time of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in New Orleans brushed the
complaint aside. In a written opinion, the court said if the consul
had been notified, the consul could have done nothing more than was
done by Faulder's court-appointed attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court in effect endorsed that decision when it
refused to hear an appeal on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright asked Gov. George W.
Bush to grant clemency because of concerns over the consular
matter. Bush declined Thursday to grant a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock also contended that Faulder suffered head injuries which
changed his personality when he fell out of a moving car at age 3.
She argued the jury should have been told about the injury, but
appellate courts declined to grant a new trial on those grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Babcock filed suit contending Faulder should be
granted clemency because officials had subjected him to
psychological torture by scheduling his execution 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   The courts discarded that theory with the observation that so
many execution dates were set because he had successfully obtained
stays so that the courts could consider other legal issues he had
raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not forget that the Phillips family has figuratively
been to death row on those nine previous occasions as well. Last
December, when justice and the jury's verdict were only a half hour
away, a last-minute stay snatched justice from their grasp one more
time,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often after the verdict is read and the jury spoken, we
forget the survivors. We must not forget that this has been a
24-year ordeal for the Phillips family as well,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until Faulder was declared dead was justice finally
rendered for Faulder, Inez Phillips, her family and the citizens of
the state of Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings noted that Faulder was tried before two different
juries and the 24 collective jurors ``thought that Joseph Stanley
Faulder was guilty and the crime so heinous that nothing less than
a death sentence was warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings expressed thanks to all the officials and officers who
helped push the case through to the end and to ``the Phillips
family who patiently endured 24-years of a judicial process
designed to protect the rights of an accused murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham writes for the Longview News-Journal, Longview, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9809 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-17 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BARAK IN A HARD PLACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ If you want to understand why Israel's Ehud
Barak has had such a hard time forming a new government after
winning a landslide victory last month, you can reduce it to one
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Israel's new Knesset, its parliament, was sworn in. At
the start of the ceremony all members were asked to stand and sing
``Hatikva,'' the Israeli national anthem. Nearly 30 of the 120
members of the Knesset weren't singing. These were the non-Zionist
members, ranging from Israeli Arabs to ultra-Orthodox Jews, who
share an ambivalence toward the secular Israeli state.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to form a government from such pieces _ one that can
simultaneously implement Barak's domestic agenda and the peace
process _ is turning out to be Barak's Rubik's Cube. Every time he
thinks he's got all the squares right, one pops up that doesn't
fit.
</P>
<P>
   To have a majority to pursue the peace process, Barak wants the
ultra-Orthodox Sephardi party, Shas, which has 17 seats and is now
the third-largest party, in his Cabinet. Shas cares about its
schools and social service networks and would go along with any
peace deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But if Barak brings in Shas he will probably lose Meretz and
Shinui, ultra-secular, pork-eating parties that won record votes by
vowing to strip Shas of government aid and to force Shas boys to
serve in the army. And Barak needs Meretz and Shinui to implement
his domestic agenda _ creating a bill of rights and shifting
spending from the ultra-Orthodox to secular schools and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, who Barak chooses to include in his government
should indicate which priority he will focus on first: the peace
process or domestic reform. It appears he is going to opt to bring
in Shas and focus first on the peace process, because as complex as
that is, domestic reform is even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess right now is that Barak is going to go for the easy
stuff _ dealing with Hafez al-Assad,'' quipped Haaretz diplomatic
correspondent David Makovsky.
</P>
<P>
   That's not surprising. After all, what the Israeli election
revealed was that there is now a widening consensus in Israel on
how to live apart from the Arabs _ there is going to be a
demilitarized Palestinian state _ but there is still no Israeli
consensus on how to live together with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what is on the minds of most Israelis today is the size
of their children's school classes, not the size of Israeli
sovereignty in the West Bank. What's on their minds is the divide
between the secular Jews of South Jerusalem and the ultra-Orthodox
Jews of North Jerusalem, not the divide between the Arabs of East
Jerusalem and the Jews of West Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   As such, even if he wants to start with the peace process, it is
only a matter of time before Barak will be conducting two
mega-negotiations at once _ one between Arabs and Jews over what
size Israel, and the other between Jews and Jews over what kind of
Israel _ in particular, what will be the relationship between the
secular, liberal majority and the fundamentalist, traditional
minorities and underclasses led by Shas.
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs Shas to give him cover for a deal with the Arabs and
to be his main partner for a deal among the Jews. Forget about the
Likud. It's dying as a significant party. Shas is now the real
alternative to the secular, free-market, liberal, democratic vision
represented by Labor, Meretz and Shinui.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Barak years could be very interesting. Both the
hibernating peace process, which will assert itself, and the
domestic agenda, which Israelis are clamoring to have addressed,
have ripened to the point where incrementalism or delay are no
longer possible.
</P>
<P>
   The next stage of peace talks will involve giving up land and
settlements. The next stage of domestic reform will be about
whether or not the state is going to continue subsidizing the
ultra-Orthodox, absenting them from army service and letting them
snub the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Barak may not be able to close the gaps on these issues, but
unlike his predecessor, he is going to make an honest effort, with
a real strategy. We are now going to find out exactly what is and
is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the Barak years will either mark the birth of the
Second Israeli Republic, when a new set of basic rules for
Arab-Israeli and Israeli-Israeli relations began to be forged, or
they will be the years when both Arab-Israeli and Israeli-Israeli
relations exploded at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Caution: Big Decisions Ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BELGIUM18-COX     06-17 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BELGIUM18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    European governments keep partial ban on Coke products
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. can resume selling some of its drinks in
Belgium, but not its key brands of Coke, Sprite and Fanta.
</P>
<P>
   The government is keeping a partial ban in place because it is
still not satisfied with the Atlanta-based company's explanation of
what caused illnesses in more than 100 consumers of its soft
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the basis of the elements presented by Coca-Cola ... it is
not possible at this stage to explain in a pacifying and
satisfactory way the outbreak of these symptoms of illness,'' the
Belgian Health Ministry said Thursday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola said the contamination arose from two separate causes:
defective carbon dioxide injected into drinks at a plant in
Antwerp, Belgium, and an offensive odor on the outside bottom of
cans produced at a plant in Dunkirk, France. The company said the
odor originated from a fungicide sprayed on wooden pallets carrying
cans that were sent to Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials in both Belgium and France appear to be
focusing on whether the fungicide alone could have been responsible
for the illnesses linked to the Dunkirk cans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to meeting with the (Belgian) ministry on
Friday so that we can present further evidence that we hope will
convince the minister to allow us to resume distribution of our
entire product line,'' said Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   The French government said Thursday it has commissioned tests to
see if something besides the fungicide may have contributed to the
sicknesses. Coca-Cola also has conducted tests.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said the company was pleased that it can return many of
its products to the shelves in Belgium, but disappointed that the
government has not allowed a full return of its brands.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's developments mean the company remains embroiled in a
public relations nightmare that is spreading in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland on Thursday joined several other European nations
that have either removed the company's products from their shelves
or restricted shipments from the bottling plants involved in the
illnesses. Those nations include Luxembourg, France, Spain, Germany
and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is concern because this thing has dragged out,'' said
Manny Goldman, a global beverage analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``Coke
has never had to go through something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the company's biggest recall in its 113 years of
operation. But most industry analysts believe the world's largest
beverage company will be able to restore public confidence and its
image over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be clear. Coke has a marketing machine, and once they
push the button they'll have the full array of brands back in the
distribution network,'' said Scott Wilkins, a beverage analyst for
Deutsche Bank. ``The ability to regain confidence with the consumer
is easier when there's not been a severe illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's health minister said Thursday that there was no
established link between drinking Coca-Cola products and the
reported cases of hemolysis, a condition that destroys red blood
cells. Most of the ill in Belgium were students suffering from
nausea, vomiting or stomach aches.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola said it would reimburse the medical costs of anyone in
Belgium with a doctor's certificate showing the illness was caused
by drinking one of the company's products.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the French consumer affairs minister said there was no
definitive proof that Coca-Cola drinks caused sickness among 80
people who live near the Dunkirk plant.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Coca-Cola's stock closed up 68 3/4 cents at
$64.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-COKE-BELGIUM18     06-17 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-COKE-BELGIUM18 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
