<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP? SOUNDS LIKE A KICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: What could possibly be more boring than
watching soccer on TV?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Watching women's soccer on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, smart guy. But not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd argue that it's a much more fun sport to watch than men's
soccer,'' said Geoff Mason, the executive producer for ABC and
ESPN's total coverage of the FIFA Women's World Cup that begins
Saturday with the U.S.-Denmark match at noon on Channel 7.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's not going too far out on a limb to say just about
(begin ital)anything(end ital) would be more enjoyable than
watching a ball poked around on a large grass field and, if by
accident, finding its way into the oversized net for a goal.
</P>
<P>
   But women's kickball, especially at this level, will be a
different TV drama altogether. Different, as in better.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Mason points out the women players talk much more on
the field to each other. Could it be true _ women express
themselves more verbally than men?
</P>
<P>
   To prove it, ABC and ESPN's coverage will turn up the volume on
the sounds of the game, said Mason, best known for his years behind
making ABC's ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is an easy sport to televise and a difficult sport to
televise well,'' said Mason. ``Soccer purists would have us do it
with just one camera _ and there's validity to that. But it's not
as simple for us to bring the viewer into the event with just that.
So what our focus will be is on audio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone once said that a camera lets you see it, but a
microphone lets you feel it. We'll give it a dimension that's more
real.''
</P>
<P>
   After NBC ignored U.S. women's soccer in the '96 Olympics, ABC
and ESPN will do the opposite here.
</P>
<P>
   During a time on a sports calendar when the NBA Finals, Stanley
Cup Finals, U.S. Open golf tournament and Wimbledon elbow for
attention, the Women's World Cup telecast will make viewers care
about this group of athletes who aren't playing for the money, but
for the love of the sport. Much like viewers saw with the women's
gold-medal winning softball team in the '96 Olympics and hockey
team in the '98 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   And much unlike the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll have to work hard to sell this sport and
the U.S. team,'' Mason said. ``All we really have to do is capture
what they're doing. Just look at the faces and you'll feel their
excitement, charisma and passion. And a winning U.S. team doesn't
need any hype at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting home: Los Angeles-based ESPN reporter Shelley Smith has
a much more personal perspective to add to the upcoming ``Outside
the Lines'' installment entitled ``High School Athletes: Do Jocks
Rule The School?'' that'll debut Monday at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   With the friction between athletes and non-athletes reportedly
having played a role in the April 20 shooting tragedy at Columbine
High in Littleton, Colo., Smith, who was born and raised in Denver,
has watched her father, a principal at another high school in the
same Jefferson County district, struggle with this issue for years.
Smith also has a 13-year-old daughter who starts junior high next
year and is involved in soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Littleton and then at Conyers, Ga., has
scared the hell out of me because it shows how little we really
know about what's going on in our kids' schools,'' said Smith, who
passed this year on covering her favorite sport, the NBA playoffs,
so she could work on this story and companion piece for ESPN's
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour show wants to avoid trivializing the Columbine
incident yet use it as a hook for a story that's always been
present in high schools but in the last two months has taken on a
greater focus.
</P>
<P>
   It's an issue that isn't bigger or smaller in any particular
region of the country, Smith found out. Her interview trail took
her locally to Loyola High in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One student (at Loyola) was a musician who said he and his
friends have been constantly teased by football players and it's
been painful for him,'' said Smith, who also admitted many students
did not want to go on the record on the show for fear of
retaliation against them and their families.
</P>
<P>
   How the media has contributed to this _ the ESPN's and Fox
Sports Nets of the cable world that have boosted the coverage of
high school athletics _ isn't covered much in the special, producer
George Lazarus admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound like the company line, but I'm not sure ESPN
necessarily makes sports more important,'' Lazarus said.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Smith: ``Sure, it's a factor, but it's not the most
compelling reason. We tried to find how the feelings are
transferred and what allows them to feel they can pick on other
kids, what gives them that entitlement.''
</P>
<P>
   A Chilton Poll that ESPN conducted with high schoolers for the
show revealed 72 percent felt there was at least some tension
between athletes and non-athletes in their schools, 78 percent feel
athletes are given preferential treatment by teachers or school
administrators and 60 percent believe athletes feel superior to
non-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   There's also this chilling quote in the special from Lisa Kaune,
a student from Bernardsville, N.J.: ``When I first heard about the
Columbine thing, I kind of thought it was really bad, you know,
because people died. But then I thought it's a victory for the kids
who are different. It's a horrible thing to happen, but in a way,
good came out of it 'cause it kind of scared the rest of the kids
who had to back down, and maybe cause kids in our school to think
that we're going to do something like that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   _Now that we've got him back _ and only on Pac-10 games _ ABC's
Keith Jackson might !ital!never leave. Whoa... you know the rest.
Said the 71-year-old Jackson: ``In this town, you've got in a sense
two old-timers who are glorious to listen to. (Vin) Scully, he'll
go on forever. And you've got Chick (Hearn) sitting over there _
you might have to shoot him. I don't begin to think I'm in their
class, but I'd like to be. You know, the main problem with being a
legend _ it also means you're not far from being an ancestor. You
have to shake the day and squeeze all you can get out of it.'' &QL; 
_Ah, remember the times when the Lakers played in June? They do
again in an ESPN Classic NBA Finals 15-game marathon that runs from
9 a.m. Saturday through 2:30 p.m. Sunday. It starts with the '70
Lakers-Knicks Game 7 (Saturday, 9 to 11:30 a.m., with Jerry West
vs. Phil Jackson as players) and includes early-Sunday-morning
views of these three in a row: '84 Lakers-Celtics Game 4 (4 a.m.);
'85 Lakers-Celtics Game 4 (6:30 a.m.) and '87 Lakers-Celtics Game 4
(8:30 a.m.). It ends with two of the early Jackson masterpieces
with the '92 Chicago-Portland Game 6 (10:30 a.m.) and the '93
Chicago-Phoenix Game 6 (12:30 p.m.). &QL; 
_A recent issue of Entertainment Weekly cleared up the question:
Who does the hilariously cliche call of the podrace in ``Phanton
Menace''? It's comedian Greg Proops, often seen on ABC's ``Whose
Line Is It Anyway?'' Proops tells EW that he based the voice on Ron
Fairly, the Seattle Mariners' play-by-play man. ``He tends to get
things wrong a lot,'' said Proops of Fairly. ``I took his voice
because I always thought he was hilarious.'' Hasn't Proops heard
Rick Monday?
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   _The excuse NBC has used for not scheduling any of the NBA
Finals games this year on a weekend. By starting with Game 1
Wednesday and putting Game 2 Friday (and avoiding ``Must See
Thursday'' rerun lineup), Game 3 of the Spurs-Knicks from New York
is bumped to Monday. That gives the players more time to rest, NBC
spokesman Ed Markey told Bloomberg News. But when has NBC or the
NBA been concerned about the players' rest time, especially after
cramming in a 50-games-in-80 days regular season? Conveniently,
this arrangement allows NBC to avoid crashing head to head with
CBS' highly rated Sunday night lineup of ``60 Minutes'' and
``Touched by an Angel'' in the East, although the network brass
won't admit it. An NBA Final that started Tuesday-Thursday in San
Antonio and went to Sunday-Tuesday-Thursday in New York and finish
(yeah, right) with Saturday-Sunday back in San Antonio would have
been the norm. Just ask Lakers fans who remember their team having
to endure such a schedule in the past. The reason there was no NBA
game last Sunday _ which could have been Game 1 of the NBA Finals,
even though the Eastern Conference finals ended Friday _ was the
East didn't go a full seven. &QL; 
_NBC's Ahmad Rashad made the prediction Monday on the ``Tonight
Show'' with Jay Leno that the winner of the NBA Finals will be
``either San Antonio or the Knicks.'' &QL; 
_The all-too-overused phrase: ``ESPN's (fill in the beat reporter)
has confirmed that....'' Too many times lately, all that means is
they have access to newspapers and wire services that have already
reported it, and they've just doublechecked it. ESPN has been
disguising this to viewers as breaking news. It just ain't so.
Breaking news is more like what Fox Sports News has done with the
hiring of Phil Jackson and the restructured contract of Shaquille
O'Neal in the past week.
</P>
