<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED HIGH COURT RULES AGAINST NASA IN UNION REPRESENTATION CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court ruled Thursday that
employees of NASA, and other federal departments, are entitled to
union representation when being questioned by their agency's
inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's 5-4 decision marked a defeat for the space
agency, which had argued that federal law provides for union
participation only when employees are grilled by an agency
``representative.'' A presidentially appointed inspector general,
by contrast, does not represent an agency but rather serves as an
independent ombudsman within a department, trying to uncover
negligence and corruption inside, NASA said.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices rejected the agency's argument, ruling that
inspectors general, though independent, are essentially agents of
the departments to which they are assigned and on whose behalf they
conduct investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration had no comment
on the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The case the justices decided arose in 1993 when NASA's Office
of Inspector General sought to question an employee at the agency's
George C. Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala. The
employee, identified only as ``P'' in court papers, was suspected
of sending messages in which he threatened to assault co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   A representative from the employee's union, American Federation
of Government Employees, was present when one of the investigators
questioned the worker. But the investigator told the union official
that he could only witness the interrogation and could be called as
a government witness should criminal charges be filed.
</P>
<P>
   The union then filed a grievance with the Federal Labor
Relations Authority, alleging that the inspector general had
violated U.S. law governing labor-management relations by
restricting the union's ability to represent the employee. NASA
countered that the inspector general, because he does not represent
the agency, need not comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   But the FLRA ruled for the union and ordered the space agency
and its inspector general to let union representatives actively
defend employees being interrogated. The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta upheld the authority's order, ruling that
inspectors general are representatives of the agencies to which
they are assigned.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department then appealed to the Supreme Court on
NASA's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing with the 11th Circuit's decision, the high court said
inspectors general and their staff are ``unquestionably
representatives'' of the agencies at which they are investigating
potential missteps. For example, an inspector general can sound
much like an agency supervisor in warning an employee that he or
she could be fired for refusing to answer questions, Justice John
Paul Stevens wrote in the court's majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Stevens' opinion in NASA vs. FLRA were Justices Anthony
M. Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   But dissenting Justice Clarence Thomas assailed the court for
failing to give enough deference to the inspectors general's
statutory responsibility to be independent overseers of federal
agencies. Unlike agency representatives, the inspectors have
unbridled authority to ignore the wishes of department heads in
conducting investigations, Thomas wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Thomas' dissent were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist,
Sandra Day O'Connor and Antonin Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
