<SLUG> BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES FIGHTING THROUGH PAIN OF BREAKING UP OLD COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Painful as it may be, go back to Jan. 2, to the
moments just after the favored Cowboys dropped a 20-7 decision to
the Arizona Cardinals in a wild-card playoff game that symbolized
the ailments of an old team.
</P>
<P>
   In the losing locker room, a somber Troy Aikman wrapped up the
sentiments of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he said, ``there is a tendency to look at some of
the guys that have been here through the better years and think
that this is the same Cowboys team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not,'' he added, ``the same team.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose translation: Some of us can't do it like we used to.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones has been faced with this reality since
the club won its last Super Bowl, after the 1995 season. The hard
part is dealing with it. Once Jones comes to terms with the reality
that some of his superstars aren't as effective as they once were,
he must deal accordingly. The consequences for the ``has-been''
superstar often mean a pay cut, a benching or release from the
team.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes particularly tough if that player has long been an
integral part of the organization's success. But that's Jones' job,
to bypass loyalty issues and separate what was from what is, to, he
said, ``separate what happened in 1992 to what's happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past two off-seasons, Jones has had to make some
pretty tough decisions regarding the ``ugly side of the game.'' To
Jones, not re-signing popular locker-room leaders such as Bill
Bates, Tony Tolbert and Nate Newton must have felt like abandoning
his own sons. Playing financial hardball with Michael Irvin and
Daryl Johnston must feel like denying those sons the use of the
family car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with the professional relationships I have,''
Jones said yesterday as the club wrapped up the final session of a
three-day minicamp. ``Sometimes, when you've got to address
productivity, and what's best to win the games, then it doesn't
feel good, and it can cause you to get a knot in your stomach. Yet
I can reconcile with that. And really, most of the time, in the
case of players or coaches, they know where I'm coming from. They
might not like it. But we all know it has nothing to do with the
past. We're talking about the future here. And you have to be
realistic about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In deciding when to sever relationships with brand-name players
who have, in some cases, been with the Cowboys as long as 10 years,
Jones is lucky that Chan Gailey is his coach. When Gailey was hired
in 1998, the loyalty issue went on the back burner. From afar,
Gailey knew about the past achievements of the Cowboys. Yet the
Troy Aikmans, the Emmitt Smiths, the Michael Irvins, the Deion
Sanderses and the Darren Woodsons had to prove themselves all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Some did. Some didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotion is a factor, but it doesn't override business,''
Gailey said. ``That's true whether you are talking about IBM,
Burlington Northern or whomever. Business takes precedent over the
loyalty factor, right, wrong, good or bad. That's just the way it
is. You've got to weigh the good and the bad about anyone and make
a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The way it has been is that with all of the big-name stars sent
packing the past few years, the Cowboys could add to their Ring of
Honor. Tolbert, Bates, Newton, the late Mark Tuinei, Jay Novacek
and Charles Haley were household names who became a part of the
housecleaning.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, isn't the first time a great Cowboys dynasty
has been faced with big decisions about aging stars. The Tom
Landry-Tex Schramm-Gil Brandt regime probably didn't part fast
enough with their established veterans and compounded the problem
by not bringing in enough talented players who could keep the club
from bottoming out in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones' Cowboys are to avoid the same mistake, the club owner
must continue to aggressively and, more important, accurately
evaluate the talents of the players who have three Super Bowl
rings.
</P>
<P>
   You can argue with some of the moves Jones has made regarding
his old pros. But at least he is trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, over my life, I'd like to think I've made realistic
decisions by saying that maybe a guy is not the player he was in
1990, and that we can take our resources and get better,'' Jones
said, never once mentioning a specific player. ``Look, we're not
robots. We're human beings. You are going to have feelings for the
people you work with. But we all know the reason we are here. The
only reason we get an opportunity to have anybody interested in
what we are doing is to win the football game. Ultimately, you have
to make decisions to win the football game as best as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if, as Jones is finding out, the decisions are about people
you call friends.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
