<SLUG> BC-GLF-MICKELSON-OPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF BABY BEEP GOES OFF, MICKELSON GOES BYE-BYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Phil Mickelson has a spot atop the leader
board at the U.S. Open ... and a private plane waiting to whisk him
away at a moment's notice, in case something more important
develops.
</P>
<P>
   For Mickelson, that would be a call from his wife, Amy, alerting
him that she has gone into labor with the couple's first child.
Such a call, when placed to the beeper of caddie Jim McKay with the
proper secret code, would trigger an immediate withdrawal by a
player who shot himself into contention yesterday at Pinehurst
Resort and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a U.S. Open every year. Your first child is only born
once,'' Mickelson said. ``I want to be there. That's the most
important thing, as far as my family is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, in Mickelson's estimation, than the 67 he fired
in the opening round to take a share of the lead with three other
golfers. More important, he insists, than trying to protect a
five-stroke lead during Sunday's final round _ scheduled,
appropriately enough, on Father's Day _ if the beeper goes off and
Mickelson must choose between wrapping up his first major
championship or welcoming Amanda Mickelson into the world.
</P>
<P>
   Prenatal tests have determined the unborn child is a girl, and
the couple wasted no time in selecting a name. A test on Tuesday at
an obstetrician's office in Phoenix also indicated that Amy is
unlikely to be born before the June 30 due date, which convinced
the father-to-be to keep his tee time at the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing only one practice round at Pinehurst, Mickelson
put together a five-birdie, two-bogey effort that included a
chip-in for birdie at No. 5 and a 30-foot birdie putt at No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Mickelson said playing with the knowledge he could
leave at any moment relaxes him on the course because it provides
``something to take my mind off a major championship.'' A 13-event
winner on the PGA Tour, Mickelson also has adopted more of a
go-for-broke mentality this week than at any of his 27 previous
majors, none of which he has won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to attack and see if I can win. Otherwise, it's not
worth my time. I'd rather be home with my wife,'' said Mickelson,
29.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Mickelson _ a licensed pilot _ has a private
plane and a co-pilot waiting at the Pinehurst airport. By his
calculations, he could make it from Pinehurst No. 2 to the hospital
in Phoenix where Amy will deliver in 5 hours, 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If McKay receives a beeper message with the secret code,
Mickelson said he will confirm with a call to Amy's cellular phone.
After that, Mickelson said, he's grabbing the first golf cart
headed to the parking lot, regardless of his position on the leader
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care more for my wife and daughter than I ever would about
the game of golf,'' Mickelson said. ``When I was 19 or 20, I would
have had a hard time envisioning that. But in the cycle of life,
things change. If that beeper goes off, I'm out of here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
