</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH LEADERS URGE SERBS TO STOP FLIGHT FROM KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ At the Gracanica monastery, the holiest
site in eastern Kosovo, leaders of the Serbian Orthodox Church and
a NATO general joined Thursday night to implore some 2,000 anxious
Serbs to remain in Kosovo rather than follow the thousands who have
fled in long convoys behind withdrawing Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Patriarch Pavle, Serbian Orthodoxy's highest-ranking cleric,
urged Serbs not to sacrifice the efforts of their forebears to keep
Kosovo Serbian under the Ottoman occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Artemije of Rasca and Prizren called on them to trust
in the peacekeeping forces, known as KFOR, to be patient and to
remain at home for a few days, saying: ``So my message is that our
national interest is to stay in our homes and in our churches and
in our towns and in our Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining them, with a priest translating from the balcony, was a
British major general, John Drewienkiewicz, who said: ``KFOR is
here for all the communities of Kosovo, and that means every one of
you. You live here, and you belong here.'' He promised that an
agreement being worked out ``would lead to the demilitarization of
the so-called KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Drewienkiewicz was chief of operations of the Kosovo
Verification Mission, run by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As Yugoslav forces completed their withdrawal from the south of
Kosovo, the NATO-led peacekeeping forces have been slow to move
into the west of the province, near the Albanian border, creating a
vacuum of authority that has led Serbian civilians to flee, fearing
revenge from the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Artemije himself fled the city on Wednesday, despite the
presence of German troops, NATO and U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting here Thursday with the bishop and the patriarch,
the foreign military and political leaders promised all possible
efforts to show their evenhandedness and to convince the minority
Serbs that they will be protected.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Michael Jackson, the commander of KFOR, and Sergio Vieira
de Mello, the special representative of the U.N. secretary general,
apparently failed to convince Bishop Artemije to return immediately
to Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   But he promised Thursday that he would return when security
improves. He was sharply critical of NATO, nonetheless, for
allowing attacks on Serbs fleeing from Prizren, saying: ``Armed
members of the KLA in uniform in the center of the town disarmed
Serbs, kidnapped them and mistreated them,'' and he said that a
priest was arrested by the KLA ``and we don't know where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Vieira de Mello also appeared on Kosovo state
television with local leaders to reassure the Serbs and answer
questions from viewers.
</P>
<P>
   They have met with Albanian political leaders of all stripes,
including Jakup Krasniqi, the political spokesman for the KLA,
urging patience, calm and reconciliation, even as the military is
working out an understanding with the insurgents on how they will
be demilitarized.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Vieira de Mello, who is in charge of
the civilian life of Kosovo, said that the future of the KLA is
political, not military.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no point engaging in this whole operation unless the
ultimate objective is to transform Kosovo into a model of
multiparty democracy that settles arguments without guns,'' he
said. ``So the KLA will become a political force with whatever name
it chooses, while its fighters will presumably demobilize.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the insurgents would form the backbone of a new police
force, Vieira de Mello said that there would be an international
police force set up with some 3,000 foreigners, who would recruit
and train a multiethnic police force. That force would, at least
initially, put Serbian police in Serbian areas and Albanian and
other Muslim minorities as police in their own areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those fighters who wish to apply for the new Kosovo police
force we will set up and train will be welcome to apply,'' he said
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Part of Vieira de Mello's problems are bureaucratic and
institutional. The United Nations is still trying to decide what
``interim civil authority'' means in the Security Council
resolution that governs the Kosovo settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a state within a state, giving Vieira de Mello and his
permanent successor full executive and administrative power here,
like a czar? Or is it a weaker idea, with effective power to be
shared with Belgrade, Yugoslavia, and its designated local leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The presumption here is that the United Nations will opt for a
stronger authority to keep order while a local census, elections
and institutions can be built over time to give Kosovo real
self-government and autonomy within Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For now, Vieira de Mello says he is operating with a skeleton
staff of 20 policy professionals and 10 support people, including
security, all of whom were seconded from other agencies. But now
that the United Nations, only on Monday, advanced its Kosovo
mission some $200 million, he is able to start hiring.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of the U.N. high commissioner for refugees has only
another 20 people to start, and various charities, like the World
Food Program and Doctors of the World, are beginning to work here
in earnest. They delivered emergency food supplies Thursday
morning, for example, to blasted Albanian villages like Stimlje and
Petrovo, where the Mother Theresa Society, the local Albanian
charity, will distribute aid to the needy, including refugees
returning home from the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is now a heavier KFOR presence along that road, which has
been the scene of heavy KLA sniping and where German and British
journalists have been wounded over the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   Fehmi Baftiu, the head of the Mother Theresa chapter in Stimlje,
said the Albanians appreciated all aid, but needed more substantial
supplies of flour, cooking oil, sugar, beans, macaroni, blankets
and even spoons and forks. ``Our reserves are spent and we could do
no planting at all,'' he said. ``We don't have milk. The Serbs even
stole our cattle and our corn.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke in a medical clinic that was looted by Serbian forces,
who took all the medicines, beds and diagnostic equipment,
including an EKG machine. About 60 percent of the town of 13,000
people was burned the first night of the NATO bombing, March 24,
Baftiu said. ``That night they started to burn and shoot, whether
people were in their houses or not.'' The rampage lasted five days,
leaving Stimlje a ruin and its population mostly dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with Kosovo's reconstruction, which will be the bulk of
the world's commitment here, U.N. agencies will handle the issue of
aid; the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe will
probably handle democracy training and institution-building; the
European Union will handle and pay for reconstruction of homes,
roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations will be in charge, Vieira de Mello
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The trickiest issue, he said, is how to handle civil
administration. For example, who pays the civil servants here,
Belgrade or the United Nations? What happens to local taxes? Who
collects the garbage or runs the water system? Will the Yugoslav
dinar remain the local currency, or will the informal currency
here, the German mark, become the formal one? Does Belgrade
continue to get the profits from electricity supply and from state
industries like vineyards and coal mining?
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One of Vieira de Mello's earliest tasks will be to appoint five
district commissioners and 29 municipal administrators to help him
run Kosovo. Each municipality will have a U.N. police commissioner
to set up the initial police force of 3,000 foreigners to take over
local policing from KFOR troops.
</P>
<P>
   The municipal administrators will appoint civil-liaison
officers, who will themselves set up local advisory councils, to
deal with residents, local leaders and civic needs and services.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is lots of work to do, more than in Bosnia or
Cambodia,'' Vieira de Mello said.
</P>
<P>
   The uncovering of the horrors of the Serbian battle against the
Albanian population here continued, with reporters finding more
gravesites even as the first forensic team from the U.N.'s
International Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia prepared to come
to Kosovo on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In towns like Poklek, Bruznik, Berisht and Vlastica, journalists
were shown or told of a series of killings of Albanians by the
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Lt. Col. Robin Clifford Thursday urged
journalists not to use ``emotive words like mass graves'' before
any proper forensic investigation. ``There are fresh burial
sites,'' he said. ``But remember there was a war here. It's up to
the tribunal to investigate.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said that 26,000 of Yugoslavia's 40,000 troops and police had
withdrawn from Kosovo on schedule. All Serb forces must be gone by
Sunday night, while several hundred will return to guard border
posts and holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   British troops also brought journalists on a guided tour of an
interrogation center at police headquarters here. The cellar
contained knives, batons, batteries, baseball bats, brass knuckles,
a box of condoms and a sword. After the display, they cordoned the
building off for tribunal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials said it was odd that the police would have
cleared the building of every file and lightbulb but left a
so-called ``torture chamber'' to be discovered, complete with even
a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   But KFOR's biggest victory Thursday was finally restoring the
water supply to Pristina after three hot summer days. Serbian
workers at four pumping stations fled after failing to get the
protection they sought from KFOR, and some of them disabled the
stations.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of changing times, the first two KLA soldiers
showed up at the Grand Hotel, where the Serbian army and police
often ate and worked. They were not authentic Kosovo Albanians,
however, but an English mercenary and an American Albanian who came
to offer themselves for interviews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
