<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAST-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DAY OF THE BEAST': A SPANISH PRIEST SEEKS THE INFANT
ANTICHRIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Quentin Tarantino had gotten his directorial hands on
``Rosemary's Baby'' or ``The Exorcist,'' the results might very
well have resembled ``The Day of the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Part black comedy, part lurid cartoon, part paranoid theological
melodrama with a heavy-metal undercurrent, this subtitled Spanish
film has won half a dozen Goyas, the Spanish equivalents of Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, for best director, honored Alex de la Iglesia, who
collaborated with Jorge Guerricaechavarria in writing this
hyperthyroid tale of a scholarly priest, Father Angel (Alex
Angula), whose studies of the Apocrypha have convinced him that the
Antichrist is to be born in Madrid before dawn on Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, ``The Day of the Beast'' is comic in a casually
brutal visual way, performed as if it matters, and never allows its
swift pace to flag; at its least admirable, it loses its early
comic touch and seems to revel in bloody violence that is all too
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   With only hours to spare, in a city where babies have been
disappearing, graves have been desecrated and roving bands have
been beating and burning the homeless, the priest sets out to make
contact with Satan, mortifying his flesh and selling his soul to
try to find and kill the infant Antichrist and save humanity before
the Devil can appear and establish his dominion.
</P>
<P>
   To this end, the priest, played by Angula with a beguiling
mixture of wide-eyed innocence and relentless determination,
enlists the hulking, shaggy, body-pierced, tattooed Jose Maria
(Santiago Segura), the owner of a heavy-metal record shop, and,
after some painful persuasion, Professor Cavan (Armando de Razza),
a Mephistophelean-looking author and the host of ``The Dark Zone,''
a popular television program devoted to the occult.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, in the boarding house owned by Jose Maria's
shotgun-packing, cleaver-whacking mama, Rosario (Terele Pavez), the
priest encounters her country-girl servant, Mina (Nathalie Sesena)
and Rosario's frontally nude, mute father. And the plot calls upon
the clergyman to draw blood from the virginal Mina, do in Rosario
and suffer various beatings, a shotgun wound that shreds his ear
and the music of a band called Satannica in a seething hellish
dance club.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to overlook the capture of Susana (Maria Grazia
Cucinotta), Cavan's voluptuous girlfriend; the beating and binding
of Cavan, and a hair-raising escape along the side of a skyscraper
from an early encounter with the Beast.
</P>
<P>
   Some of de la Iglesia's characters rebound like cartoon
creatures from the mayhem visited on them; others remain very dead
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   As theological adventures go, the over-the-top ``Day of the
Beast'' adds up to a mixed blessing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DAY OF THE BEAST'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alex de la Iglesia; written (in Spanish, with
English subtitles) by Jorge Guerricaechevarria and de la Iglesia;
director of photography, Flavio Martinez Labiano; edited by Teresa
Font; music by Battista Lena; produced by Ms. Font; released by
Trimark Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 104 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: ``The Day of the Beast'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It involves bloody
violence, nudity and coarse language.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Alex Angulo (Priest), Armando de Razza (Professor Cavan),
Santiago Segura (Jose Maria), Terele Pavez (Rosario), Nathalie
Sesena (Mina) and Maria Grazia Cucinotta (Susana).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      06-17 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENCE IN FED SPARKS GAIN IN DOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices moved higher Thursday as investors and
traders grew increasingly confident that the Federal Reserve will
decide the economy needs little more than a tap on the brakes to
keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the market opened, Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman,
told the Joint Economic Committee of Congress that ``modest
pre-emptive actions can obviate the need of more drastic actions at
a later date.'' The stock and bond markets, regarding this as an
unusually clear signal of a likely one-time rate increase on June
30, promptly rallied and continued to rise for most of the session.
</P>
<P>
   At the close, in a stepped-down version of Wednesday's pattern,
the Nasdaq composite index was up 26.32 points, or 1.05 percent, to
2,544.15, and the Dow Jones industrial average was up 56.68 points,
or 0.5 percent, to 10,841.63. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
rose 9.49 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,339.90.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds did even better, soaring by amounts that cut yields by an
average of about one-eighth of a percentage point, one of the best
performances of the year. The yield of the benchmark 30-year bond,
which was at 6.16 percent last Friday, retreated below 6 percent
and finished at 5.96 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a calm that the Fed is aware of what's going on and
doesn't see a runaway inflation,'' said John R. Peluso, head of
listed equity trading at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the government's surprisingly benign inflation
report on Wednesday, Abby Joseph Cohen, chief strategist at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. maintained her bullish stance despite
contending that the S&AMP;P 500 is now ``modestly'' overvalued by about
5 percent. Earlier in the year, when rates were lower, Ms. Cohen
found stocks undervalued by about that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ugly inflation news associated with higher oil prices
seems to have ended,'' she said in an advisory, adding that
second-quarter profits are shaping up well and the markets should
be able to ``easily tolerate'' it if the Fed raises the overnight
interest rate a notch, a move already anticipated by the futures
market.
</P>
<P>
   She referred to such a move as a ``flu shot,'' not unlike
Greenspan's ``pre-emptive'' strike.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy J. Morris, chief investment officer at Bessemer Trust,
agreed that corporate earnings, which will begin to pour in for the
second quarter next month, are likely to support further
stock-market gains.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that operating earnings of S&AMP;P 500 companies will
climb by more than 10 percent for the year, well ahead of the 6
percent to 8 percent gain he projected at the end of March and the
3 percent to 5 percent gain when 1999 began.
</P>
<P>
   Such improvement, he suggested, helps explain the stock market's
relatively mild setback in the face of the recent sharp rise in
interest rates. With Thursday's gain, the Dow stands just 2.4
percent below its May 13 record close and is up 18.1 percent for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks turned in another strong performance Thursday,
joined by drugs and many high-technology issues. Paper and airline
shares slumped. Microsoft had the biggest positive effect on the
S&AMP;P 500. The software giant gained 1 7/8, to 82 7/8, followed by
General Electric, up 1 5/8, to 108 7/16, and America Online, up 4
3/16, to 110 11/16. Intel, down 1 11/16, to 58, and Wal-Mart, down
three-quarters, to 43 5/8, were the biggest drags.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Dow components, 18 issues advanced while 12 declined.
Alcoa was the biggest gainer, rising 2 7/16, to 67 3/8, a new
52-week high. Another cyclical issue, however, International Paper,
was one of the Dow's biggest losers, falling 2 3/16, to 53 5/16,
more than six points off its high reached two months ago. Boeing,
which announced a $1.4 billion order for 25 planes, gained
seven-eights, to 43 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Prices could prove unusually volatile Friday, traders cautioned,
because it is a so-called triple-witching session, when stock
options, index options and index futures contracts all expire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
