<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9832 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-2TAKES-     06-17 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BACKS 10 COMMANDMENTS IN SCHOOLS, THEN TURNS AGAIN TO GUN
CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted Thursday to allow the Ten
Commandments to be posted in schools, and then turned to a tense
debate over the most significant gun control legislation to come
before it in in five years.
</P>
<P>
   With both parties searching for an answer to school violence,
gun regulation came center-stage after two long days of sometimes
impassioned clashes over God, values, the entertainment industry
and the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In a significant victory for social conservatives, the House
voted 248-180 to include in the crime bill an amendment sponsored
by Rep. Robert Aderholt, R-Ala., giving states the right to allow
the display of the Ten Commandments in public places, including
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, the House turned to a separate bill on gun
control, which is the preferred political ground of the Democrats.
A dozen separate gun amendments were under consideration, running a
gamut from a measure requiring child safety devices to be sold with
handguns to a proposal to repeal the District of Columbia's ban on
the possession of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant showdown was over rival measures of varying
strictness to regulate sales of weapons at gun shows, at which
collectors and hobbyists selling firearms are not currently
required to conduct the kinds of background checks on buyers that
licensed dealers are.
</P>
<P>
   In a fierce lobbying blitz, President Clinton arose at 5 a.m. in
Paris to telephone four wavering Democrats: Gary Conduit and Mike
Thompson of California, Marion Berry of Arkansas and Ron Kind of
Wisconsin to urge them to vote for a gun show amendment sponsored
by Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., whose husband was shot to death
by a gunman on the Long Island Railroad in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy for the United States to be the only advanced
country in the world that doesn't take comprehensive, sensible,
thorough steps to keep handguns out of the hands of criminals,''
Clinton told reporters in Paris. ``It's just _ it doesn't make any
sense.'' To hammer home the point, the White House sent Attorney
General Janet Reno to the Capitol late Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and Rep. Tom DeLay, the majority
whip of Texas, shored up support among conservatives for a weaker
version sponsored by another Democrat, Rep. John Dingell of
Michigan, who is a former member of the NRA board.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell _ whose victory would be a blow to the president and the
Democratic congressional leadership _ insisted that he was going to
win. He said that Clinton would not make headway with conservative
Democrats because ``he cost us control of the House and a lot of
people remember that.'' The Republicans won the majority in 1994,
months after Congress enacted a ban on assault weapons avidly
sought by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the NRA has largely held sway on Capitol Hill. But
after the shocking school shooting in Littleton, Colo., the Senate
last month _ with Vice President Gore casting the tie-breaking vote
_ approved a proposal that would compel all vendors at gun shows,
licensed or unlicensed, to run such checks. Law enforcement
officials are given three business days to complete the checks.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell's version on gun shows is much less stringent. It
narrowly defines what constitutes a gun show, and only 24 hours
would be allotted for background checks. Mrs. McCarthy's version
largely mirrors the Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the procedures for the debate, Dingell's measure was to be
considered first, and both sides considered it the most likely to
pass. But even a majority vote does not guarantee its survival. If
Mrs. McCarthy's amendment also wins a majority vote, it trumps the
Dingell proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday afternoon, Reps. McCarthy, Nita M. Lowey of New
York and Rosa DeLauro of Connecticut made last-ditch phone calls to
undecided colleagues from Mrs. McCarthy's office. And Mrs. McCarthy
and Ms. Lowey even agonized over the order of the speech-making to
come on the floor, as if that might decide the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats expected about 45 of their members from the South and
West to vote with Dingell. Gun control advocates thought they had
30 Republicans firmly on their side. That left the outcome of the
vote in the hands of about two dozen wavering lawmakers, most of
them Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of this debate have become so convoluted that no
matter which gun show measure prevails, final passage of a gun
control bill remains in doubt. No one could predict whether
conservatives _ even those who join Dingell to water down gun shows
language _ will vote for the legislation if any other gun
restrictions also prevail. Liberals, on the other hand, are likely
to bolt if Mrs. McCarthy's proposal fails.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The two parties were already preparing to blame each other if an
odd coalition of conservatives and liberals caused the legislation
to collapse. ``If Republicans cynically vote for Dingell and
against the bill then their strategy is no gun safety,'' charged
Rep. Stenny Hoyer, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said of the final bill, ``the less gun control, the more
apt it is to pass.'' And Dingell refused to say whether he would
vote for the final measure if his amendment prevailed, but other
gun control provisions like a child safety device or a raise in the
minimum age for all handgun purchases from 18 to 21 also were
approved.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday and early Thursday the House approved a variety
of measures signaling support, sometimes symbolic and sometimes
more concrete, for public expressions of religion. The debate over
the Ten Commandments was the most spirited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that simply posting the Ten Commandments will not
instantly change the moral character of our nation,'' Aderholt, the
measure's sponsor, said just before midnight Wednesday. ``However,
it is an important step to promote morality and an end of children
killing children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., displayed the copy of the Ten Commandments
he hangs in his office. He repeatedly mentioned God and argued that
display of the commandments did not _ as his critics charged _
violate the Constitutional guarantee of separation of church and
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in these Ten Commandments that reaches out
and grabs somebody and forces them to abide by any particular
religious belief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of Congress disagreed. ``This amendment seeks to
elevate one particular religion over all others,'' said Rep. Robert
Scott, D-Va. ``This singling out of one religion is contrary to the
American ideal of religious tolerance and is blatantly
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler of New York City also raised constitutional
questions. ``Whose Ten Commandments?'' he asked. ``Which version?
The Catholic version? The Protestant version? Or the Jewish
version?''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court in 1980 declared unconstitutional a Kentucky
law requiring that a copy of the Ten Commandments be posted in
every public school classroom. The court held that the law violated
the constitutional separation of church and state, serving neither
a ``secular legislative purpose'' nor an educational function.
</P>
<P>
   In other votes touching on religion, the House overwhelmingly
approved measures allowing the use of religious language in
memorials on school grounds and allowing religious organization to
compete for government social service contracts.
</P>
<P>
   A day after rejecting an effort to impose a prison term on those
selling violent entertainment to teenagers, lawmakers also debated
and approved several measures that served primarily to make
Congress' displeasure with the entertainment industry known. One of
these proposals directed the surgeon general to prepare a report on
the effects of interactive video games on youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   The House also overwhelming approved a non-binding resolution by
Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, R-Mo., calling the entertainment industry
irresponsible in its marketing to youth and urging it to curtail
``portrays of pointless acts of brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can there be any doubt at all that the entertainment industry
has contributed to the culture of violence that has manifested
itself in Colorado, in Georgia, in Jonesboro, Arkansas?'' asked
Rep. Joe Knollenberg, R-Mich., listing sites of recent school
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats complained that the resolution was too
broad. ``Don't condem a whole industry,'' said Rep. Howard Berman
of California, protesting ``blanket guilt by association.'' Rep.
Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., shot back sarcastically, ``I suppose the
Democrats would never condemn an entire industry'' _ an implied
reference to Democratic attacks on tobacco and gun manufacturers.
</P>
</TEXT>
