<HEADER>
A9834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMANDMENTS18-COX     06-17 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMANDMENTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Posting Ten Commandments in schools OK, House says
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. House of Representatives approved
legislation Thursday to give states the authority to post the Ten
Commandments in government buildings, including schools.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, attached to a massive juvenile crime bill, was
applauded by religious conservatives. But legal analysts said it
would do little to change prohibitions the courts have adopted
barring certain religious symbols on public property.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was a personal victory for its sponsor, Alabama
Republican Rep. Robert Aderholt. In 1995, Etowah County Circuit
Judge Roy Moore refused an order to remove a redwood tablet of the
Ten Commandments from his courtroom wall in Aderholt's district.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Fob James threatened to call out the National Guard if
anyone tried to remove the display from behind the judge's bench,
igniting a showdown that drew national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud to see that people are waking up to the real
problem in our society, and that's the loss of morality,'' Moore
said Thursday after the House vote.
</P>
<P>
   Moore has campaigned with Aderholt and makes speeches nearly
every week about the Ten Commandments display.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Schroeder, a legislative analyst with the American Civil
Liberties Union in Washington, said the language of Aderholt's
amendment was similar to a ``sense of the Congress'' resolution: It
carries no penalties and has ``no legal teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   The case law on the issue won't change, Schroeder said, and
governments and school districts that post the Ten Commandments
will be subject to the same court challenges as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote came on the second day of a fractious debate over
teens and violence, sparked by recent school shootings in Colorado
and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Aderholt conceded his Ten Commandments provision would not
``change the moral character of our nation overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However, it is one step that states can take to promote
morality and work toward an end of children killing children,'' the
congressman said. ``The states we represent deserve the opportunity
to decide for themselves whether they want to display the Ten
Commandments.''
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 248 to 180 in favor of Aderholt's amendment to a
$1.5 billion juvenile crime bill. Democrats John Lewis and Cynthia
McKinney were the only Georgia lawmakers to vote against the
proposal, which attracted 45 Democratic votes and 203 Republican
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who voted against the measure said it was
unconstitutional. In 1980 the U.S. Supreme Court struck down a
Kentucky law that required the posting of the Ten Commandments in
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This singling out of one particular religion is contrary to
the American ideal of religious tolerance and is blatantly
unconstitutional,'' said Rep. Bobby Scott (D-Va.).
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler (D-N.Y.) noted the Ten Commandments has
numerous translations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose Ten Commandments?'' Nadler asked. ``The Catholic
version? The Protestant version. ... Are our public buildings to be
Catholic because the local Catholic majority votes that the
Catholic version ... should be in the public buildings?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), who recently suggested the shootings at
Heritage High would not have happened if the Ten Commandments had
been on display at the Rockdale County school, spoke in favor of
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some on the other side of the aisle keep saying that
Republicans are working on behalf of the NRA,'' said Barr, a
National Rifle Association board member. ``Their irrational
argument against something as simple and nonsectarian as displaying
the Ten Commandments proves that many in the Democrat party are
paid for by the trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobb County, the heart of Barr's 7th District, spent $100,000 in
an unsuccessful bid to keep the Ten Commandments on a courtroom
wall four years ago. Fred Bentley Jr., the county attorney who
litigated the matter, said the House vote ``opens up the door for
the county to revisit its position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Principally, what this recognizes is that the people of the
United States are demanding safe communities and a return to
morality and just good, old-fashioned, safe, earlier times,''
Bentley said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Lumpkin County's sole commissioner, Charlie Ridley,
gave in to the ACLU and other groups who opposed a Ten Commandments
display in the North Georgia county courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's congressional action is ``something that should have
happened a long time ago,'' Ridley said. ``I only hope the
president and both sides move ahead. I think it's something that
needs to be in the schools and it's something that needs to be
displayed in public buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Gerry Davis, pastor of the Dahlonega United Methodist
Church, said the Ten Commandments display at the Lumpkin County
courthouse fractured the local religioius community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to use law as a means to get people to follow
God,'' Davis said. ``There is the doctrine of free will churches
embrace. God does not force us to love him, to follow him, to
believe in him. So why should I as an American citizen ask
legislatures to adopt laws that basically try to force people to
believe in God?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
