<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-FED-ART-NYT     06-17 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-FED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN INDICATES HE IS LEANING TOWARD MODEST INTEREST RATE
RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, gave
the clearest indication yet Thursday that the central bank will
raise interest rates by a quarter percentage point later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a congressional committee, Greenspan acknowledged
that inflation is currently negligible, as shown by the report on
Wednesday that the Consumer Price Index did not rise at all last
month.
</P>
<P>
   But to applause from many economists _ and in the face of
skepticism from politicians of both parties who have grown
increasingly convinced of the economy's ability to expand at a
robust pace without much risk of accelerating prices _ he laid out
a case for why the Federal Reserve sometimes needed to act well
before inflation takes root.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding more like the Greenspan of old, a hard-line advocate of
price stability, than his more recent incarnation as apostle of a
new, technology-driven economy, the fed chairman said that growth
was on an ``unsustainable trend,'' and warned somewhat ominously
that the excesses of human nature have brought all expansions to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said that continued strong growth _ fueled in part by
booms in the stock market and in housing prices _ could soon lead
to a shortage of workers, a condition that has historically set off
a spiral of rising wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan did not flatly say he would call for a rate increase
when the Federal Reserve meets to set policy on June 29 and 30.
Instead, he coupled his warning about the brewing inflationary
pressures with a call for the central bank to act sooner rather
than later when it spots strains that could derail the economy
further down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we can be pre-emptive we should be, because modest
pre-emptive actions can obviate the need of more drastic actions at
a later date that could destabilize the economy,'' Greenspan told
the Joint Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts connected the dots and concluded that Greenspan was all
but guaranteeing a quarter-point increase in rates at the end of
the month. That would bring the benchmark federal funds target rate
to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan gave little guidance, though, about whether the
central bank would tighten policy further later in the year.
Economists said that he wanted to keep his options open while he
waits to see whether growth slows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to put some measure of financial restraint in place
to moderate demand early enough to head off a significant
problem,'' said Robert V. DiClemente, an economist at Salomon Smith
Barney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's testimony appeared to bring to an end speculation
that the Federal Reserve had adopted a ``Bunker Hill'' strategy of
waiting to fire until inflation was staring it in the face,
DiClemente said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has been a proponent of the view that huge investments
in computers and telecommunications are revolutionizing American
business and making it much more productive. But Thursday he seemed
to be signaling that his faith in new technology should not be
confused with his willingness to take early and perhaps unpopular
action to squelch the fed's old nemesis, inflation.
</P>
<P>
   He even provided a simple bit of arithmetic to back up his case
for an early tightening. The economy, he said, has grown 4 percent
a year for the last three years. Of that, improvements in
productivity, or output for each hour worked, account for 2
percentage points. Another percentage point represents the growth
in the working-age population.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining percentage point, he said, was accounted for by
dipping ever deeper into the pool of available workers, a trend
that could not be sustained much longer given the low unemployment
rate, which is now 4.2 percent. The smaller the pool of available
workers, the greater the pressure on wages, and ultimately prices.
</P>
<P>
   With growth remaining strong and the global financial crisis
having receded, the Federal Reserve signaled last month that it
might soon begin reversing the three rate cuts _ each a
quarter-point _ it made last fall. Since the May meeting of the
Fed's policy making Federal Open Market Committee _ when members
adopted and announced a formal bias toward a tighter monetary
policy _ Fed officials have gradually prepared investors for the
likelihood of a rate increase this month. Thus, Greenspan's
statements did not shock anyone on Wall Street.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
