<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-FED-ART-2ND     06-17 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-FED-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: on Wall Street.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apparently interpreting Greenspan to be suggesting that one rate
hike might be enough, the bond market rallied, sending the yield on
the 30-year Treasury bond back below 6 percent. Stocks rose
modestly, with the Dow Jones industrial average finishing 56.68
points higher, at 10,841.63.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to the need to soothe Wall Street, where higher
interest rates tend to be bad news over the long run for both
stocks and bonds, Greenspan reassured investors that the Fed's goal
was not to end the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betting against markets is usually precarious at best,''
Greenspan said, adding that monetary policy should focus on price
stability for goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   The Depression in the United States and the problems of recent
years in Japan were not caused by the bursting of asset bubbles,
Greenspan said, but by bad economic policy in the years following
the market crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should volatile asset prices cause problems, policy is
probably best positioned to address the consequences when the
economy is working from a base of stable product prices,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has won widespread acclaim for his management of
monetary policy for the last 12 years. But his broad hints Thursday
about his intention to raise rates drew quick responses from
politicians of both parties, who questioned the justification for
tightening policy in the absence of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's argument in favor of an early tightening drew
skepticism and in one case pointed criticism from Democrats who
heard him testify before the Joint Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maurice Hinchey, D-N.Y., said that raising rates now would
send a signal that the Fed's policy is to put an end to strong
growth just as all working Americans are benefiting from plentiful
jobs and higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that's not what you want to do,'' Hinchey told
Greenspan, who tried in vain to cut him off. ``But that will be the
effect if you give in to this notion that interest rates need to be
raised now.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, who is running for the Republican presidential
nomination, also warned Greenspan against raising rates now. In a
statement issued in Iowa, where farmers have been hard hit by
falling prices for agricultural products, he said that the real
threat was deflation, not inflation, and suggested that Greenspan
could become a political issue if he enacted a series of rate
increases as the presidential campaign proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of resurgent inflation exists only in the fevered
minds of the Federal Reserve and the Clinton-Gore Treasury
Department,'' Forbes said. ``Jacking up interest rates now would be
a pre-emptive strike against American prosperity, not against
inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan defended the need to attack inflation before it became
a problem. The combination of strong growth and low unemployment,
he said, had not yet put the expansion at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``But should labor markets continue to tighten, significant
increases in wages, in excess of productivity growth, will
inevitably emerge, absent the unlikely repeal of the law of supply
and demand,'' Greenspan said. ``Because monetary policy operates
with a significant lag, we have to make judgments, not only about
the current degree of balance in the economy, but about how the
economy is likely to fare a year or more in the future under the
current policy stance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
