<HEADER>
A9840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-17 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ It was a scene filled with more than just a touch of
irony as Phil Jackson's face dominated TV screens from coast to
coast in the moments before the Spurs and Knicks played Game 1 of
the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Dr. Jerry Buss of the Lakers had just spent $30
million to hire a coach for NBC's team, and the peacock network
wouldn't miss an opportunity to strut that fact proudly, already
beating the drum for next season's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But there is still the matter of the championship match of the
season at hand to play, and one can't help but notice the team _
San Antonio _ that took one step closer to winning it all is being
directed by a man who is the anti-Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Popovich probably couldn't spell Zen if you spotted him
the ``Z'' and the ``e,'' and he wouldn't know Confucius from Conway
Twitty.
</P>
<P>
   While so much of Wednesday was filled with the news that the
erstwhile coach of the former Chicago dynasty was coming down from
the mount with stone tablets that would show Shaq and Kobe the way
to the promised land, it became almost an afterthought that the
Spurs won again, an NBA-record-tying 11th straight playoff victory.
</P>
<P>
   If Popovich had as much ego as Jackson had lint in the
professorial beard he recently shaved off, he would have stepped up
to the podium Thursday and pointed out he got David Robinson to
place his focus elsewhere, thereby allowing Tim Duncan to shine. He
might have said it was his idea to re-sign the itinerant Jaren
Jackson and to reacquire Sean Elliott in a trade. He could have
pointed out he discovered Malik Rose and brought in Mario Elie and
Steve Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when Popovich was asked how he has changed as a coach
since giving himself the position in December 1996, he half-smiled,
half-snorted into the microphone: ``I read a book and got smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson doesn't have to read books when there are divine
thoughts constantly entering his mind. He has the way, the plan,
the path to hoop enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, of course, is the perfect setting for this, a place
of myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's needed is, obviously, experience in a system
I have,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   You'll note he didn't mention ``his'' offensive system is one
taught to the Bulls by assistant coach Tex Winter.
</P>
<P>
   One might also note Jackson somehow has managed to portray
himself as Leonard Bernstein, the maestro leading the orchestra,
while a certain Michael Jordan might as well have been sitting in
the last row playing the tuba.
</P>
<P>
   To see the reaction of a giddy Los Angeles, part of his contract
must also call for Jackson to end smog and traffic, along with
winning the next few NBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   While a gruff, no-nonsense, uncharismatic man like Popovich has
the Spurs playing unselfishly and ferociously and harmoniously with
few visible signs of weakness, Jackson, the Zen phony, has LA
believing this team that was swept by San Antonio will turn it
around because he'll drop a few pithy sayings in the Lakers' midst
and maybe turn the locker room into an American Indian sweat lodge,
where Shaq and Kobe can mend their differences by puffing on a
peace pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich's is not an entertaining style of management, but it
works because his players know he doesn't care about getting the
credit. Jackson's style is all entertainment, and it worked because
he had Jordan to do all of the heavy lifting. He has cultivated
greatness by association and turned it into a $6 million-a-year
gig.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson wanted to show us he is truly a Zen master, he would
have taken a job with the Clippers or Nets. If he wanted to show us
he has the secret to turning an uphill battle into success, he
would have stuck with his buddy Bill Bradley's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was a decent coach who befriended Jordan, won his
loyalty and then hitched a ride on M.J.'s talent to become a
new-age philosopher and hoop guru. Popovich doesn't care if
Robinson likes him after turning over the main offensive focus to
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches have long been a part of the show, and the slick ones
have turned showmanship into a marketable commodity. Popovich can't
recite those lines from the script. But by not even trying, he does
not sell himself out.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the Lakers be in a year or two if Shaq and Kobe never
discover Jordan's unteachable, uncoachable, unstoppable will to
win? Will the Zen master at least teach them to be at peace with
early-round playoff losses?
</P>
<P>
   And Popovich? He'll act then the way he acts now, gruffly,
uncomplicated, as himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
