<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONUS-BMW-ART-NYT &LR;      06-17 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONUS-BMW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY WAY TO KEEP EMPLOYEES HAPPY: GIVE THEM A BMW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ga., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLMDEL, N.J. _ Forget dental benefits and stock options. When
Al Galdi was searching for a perk to inspire employee loyalty, he
wanted something a bit more, well, dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Galdi, chief executive of Arcnet, which designs and
builds wireless communications systems, handed keys to 28 new BMWs
to company workers ranging from administrative assistants to
architects. Under a new company policy, every employee on the job
at least a year gets a leased BMW, plus fully paid insurance.
Turnover has been such that of 57 workers, only half qualified. But
the other half can taste it.
</P>
<P>
   This dramatic gesture, which some might call extravagant in the
extreme, was anything but that to Galdi, who told of constantly
losing trained people to rivals. Weighing the cost of recruiting,
retraining and lost business, he estimated that the $15
million-a-year, privately held company had been spending nearly $1
million a year just to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran the numbers and this made sense because it gave us
something that made us stand out from the crowd,'' he said. ``It is
going to be better than a raise, because every time they turn that
ignition key, they will think of me and the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The new perk turned what was by most measures a happy shop into
an ecstatic one, said Lauren Catalano, an administrative assistant
for the last 19 months. She was standing next to her silver BMW,
lined up with the other new cars in the company parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The bestowing of keys took on a carnival atmosphere, with Galdi,
36, as the chief barker. Family members sat in balloon-festooned
bleachers, hot dogs were cooked under a tent and employees drove
their BMWs around the parking lot in a horn-honking caravan.
</P>
<P>
   While unusual, Galdi's gesture is not singular. At least two
other small companies, Revenue Systems Inc. of Alpharetta, Ga., and
Net2000 Communications of McLean, Va., have provided a range of
workers with a luxury BMW. And according to Michael Carter, vice
president of Hay Group, a human resources consulting firm, it fits
in with employers' need for dramatic moves to counter the triple
woes of a tight, competitive job market in highly technical fields;
decreased loyalty, and lingering cynicism in the wake of the
mega-layoffs of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a super-flashy, extreme version of a far less dramatic
trend among employers who are trying to do different and unusual
things to distinguish themselves,'' said Carter, whose firm surveys
trends in benefits packages.
</P>
<P>
   More common, less costly moves, Carter said, included signing
bonuses, ``work-life benefits'' like telecommuting, flexible hours,
job-sharing arrangements and ``convenience benefits'' like
on-premises dry cleaning pickup. But none, he said, can dazzle like
a free BMW.
</P>
<P>
   Dazzling was precisely what Galdi had in mind when he
appropriated the idea from Revenue Systems. Bill Glover, that
company's chief executive, said he too was drowning in headhunter
and retraining costs when he hit on the idea of providing each
employee with a choice of the 3 series BMW or the Z3 Roadster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all the benefits that you could expect, from full
medical and dental to 401(k), but we still didn't have the
visibility we wanted to attract the kind of people we needed,''
said Glover, whose 70-person company provides software for
government revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
   Galdi echoed those sentiments Thursday as he told employees he
wanted to give them the ``ultimate benefit.'' And in an interview
he acknowledged that the publicity was likely to expose his firm to
a host of potential employees who are not among that ``homogenized
group of currently unemployed'' job seekers but ``the stable,
longtime employed'' with other firms.
</P>
<P>
   The lease on each $31,000 car runs about $7,000 a year, while
insurance is about $2,000. (And employees must pay tax on this
added income.) The total cost of the first batch, Galdi said, is
about $270,000 a year. This compared ``very favorably,'' he said,
with the roughly $900,000 he had spent on recruitment and training
over the last, turnover-filled 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   George Slocum, a 51-year-old purchase order coordinator who came
to the company three years ago after being ``downsized'' by a large
heating oil distributor, said that before the BMW offer he might
have entertained other job offers, but not now. He has sold his
Mercury Grand Marquis, happily settled into his forest green BMW
with the tan interior, and plans to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   A new employee, Barton Stabler, 41, who came on as
communications and marketing director about a week ago, also plans
on staying the ``11 months, 27 days, three hours'' he says it will
take to get his car. The car offer was not his reason for applying
to the company, he said, but he conceded that it had a lot to do
with his decision to take the job after being self-employed for 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Catalano said she felt like one of those running, screaming,
jumping winners on ``The Price Is Right.'' Perhaps the only
downside, she said, came after her photo appeared with an article
about the plan in the local paper. After she went into a local BMW
dealer to order her car, several men she did not know started
persistently calling her at the office asking her out on dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe they wanted me for my car,'' she said with mock
horror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
