<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFECTIOUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME RUNNING OUT TO CONTROL INFECTIOUS DISEASES, WHO SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A window of opportunity to control infectious diseases may be
closing, the World Health Organization warned Thursday, due to
growing antibiotic resistance, emerging new diseases, and a global
explosion in urban populations and travel.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said the means are at hand to curb infections, which
now kill 1,500 children and adults every hour, often at a cost of
less than 35 cents per person in the most heavily affected
countries. But those opportunities may soon slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The progress that the world can make today against infectious
diseases may not be possible a decade from now,'' the WHO declared
in a report that the agency's director, Dr. Gro Harlem Brundtland,
said is intended as ``a wake-up to the world's governments,
decision-makers, and the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, a private group called the Global
Health Council released a survey showing that most Americans are
worried about global infectious diseases, ranking the problem
higher than environmental concerns and regional wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to understand that the best way to fight disease
is at its source in Third World countries,'' said Nils Daulaire,
president of the Vermont-based Global Health Council.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-page WHO report said smallpox, the only infectious
disease to have been eradicated, offers a striking example of how
timing can make all the difference between success and failure.
</P>
<P>
   If smallpox had not been defeated in 1977, the variola virus
which causes it _ the deadliest microbe in human history _ could
still be causing a million deaths a year and costing billions of
dollars in health care, WHO analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because AIDS emerged as an important disease just after
smallpox was eliminated. Since the human immunodeficiency virus
(HIV) impairs its victims' immune systems, the live-virus smallpox
vaccine would have been fatal to many HIV-infected individuals,
blocking mass-vaccination campaigns and preserving a reservoir of
smallpox infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few years delay and global eradication of smallpox may
have become impossible without discovery of a new vaccine,'' the
WHO said.
</P>
<P>
   The WHO warned that ``medicines are losing their
effectiveness,'' leaving more people defenseless against diseases
that were on their way to being controlled. For instance, 45
percent of malaria cases in Thailand are resistant to the two
front-line drugs used to treat it.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, 60 percent of staph infections are resistant to
multiple antibiotics, while in the United States, 60 percent of
hospital infections are caused by resistant microbes and 14,000
hospital patients die every year from resistant infections.
</P>
<P>
   The Global Health Council survey found that four out of five
Americans are worried about mounting drug resistance, and most know
that antibiotic overuse is a major cause.
</P>
<P>
   The WHO also warns that ``new'' diseases are gaining strength,
such as hepatitis C virus (first identified in 1989, now thought to
infect 170 million people), Legionnaire's disease and ebola virus
(identified in 1976), Hanta virus in the US Southwest (1993), and a
new variant of Creutzfeld-Jacob, the infectious protein that causes
``mad cow'' disease (1996).
</P>
<P>
   All is not gloom and doom in the WHO report, however. The agency
notes that polio, leprosy, neonatal tetanus and Guinea worm disease
have nearly been eliminated. It also recounts many recent success
stories in controlling epidemics in the poorest countries, at a
cost of 27 cents to $10 per capita.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
