<HEADER>
A9845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN200018-COX     06-17 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN200018-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley, Dole canvass California
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The campaign travels of Vice President Al Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush this week have forced the other
candidates for president to struggle even harder for attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat and Republican who run second in most polls are
spending the week trying to improve their standing in California,
the richest prize in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley is on a nine-day tour of the
state, a distinctly un-modern political swing in an era when
candidates try to cover the state with television. Conventional
wisdom is that one-on-one politicking works better in Iowa and New
Hampshire, where voters have come to expect candidate coffees and
farm visits.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley trails Gore by 30 points in California, a new Los
Angeles Times poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   Former cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole spent three days
traveling from San Diego to San Francisco in search of money for
her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And in San Jose, she once again dismissed the notion that she is
really running for the second spot behind the heavily favored Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in it to win,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   New New York tune?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary vs. Rick just doesn't sing, but it may have to do.
</P>
<P>
   The media's dream match of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
against New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the U.S. Senate may not
come to pass if Rep. Rick Lazio (R-N.Y.) has his way.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio says he most likely will announce his candidacy this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   But what chance would a little-known Long Islander have against
the mayor of New York?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Long Island is the GOP base in New York. For
another, upstate New York voters may not be in love with Democrats,
but they surely do not like the New York City or its mayor. Lastly,
Lazio probably would have the support of New York's Republican
governor, George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani backed Pataki's Democratic opponent, then-Gov. Mario
Cuomo, in 1994. The governor has not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Gore watch
</P>
<P>
   Republicans (again) jumped on Gore this week when he (again)
uttered a public statement that was somewhat at odds with the
facts.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans to talk to the nation's mayors Monday, Gore said
18-to-20-year-olds can walk into gun shows, pawnshops and gun
stores and purchase handguns. In fact, federal law already makes
that illegal in pawnshops and gun stores.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's office put out a correction the same day. Gore favors
extending the ban to gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia PACS
</P>
<P>
   The Common Sense Leadership Fund, the Good Government for
America political action committee and the House Majority Fund have
one thing in common, apart from their unobjectionable names. Their
members include Georgians in Congress who use these PACs to enhance
their influence among colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Rep. Saxby Chambliss has The Common Sense fund and
Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell controls the Good Government PAC.
Democratic Rep. John Lewis, the chief deputy whip for the minority
party in the House, maintains the hopefully named House Majority
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss and Lewis each gave $34,000 from their PACs to
candidates for Congress in last year's election. Coverdell
dispensed $29,000.
</P>
<P>
   The standard for such contributions is Republican Rep. Tom DeLay
of Texas, whose leadership PAC gave so prodigiously to Republican
candidates in 1994 that he won the gratitude and votes of his
colleagues for House Majority Whip when the Republicans took
control of Congress in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The PACs have one other function. They often serve as legal
vehicles to accept campaign contributions in excess of what
individuals or other PACs can give the candidates. Chambliss's PAC,
for example, received $5,000 contributions from at least five
people who also gave the maximum $1,000 per election to Chambliss's
campaign account.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
