<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARPERCOLLINS-BOOK-NY     06-17 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARPERCOLLINS-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CORP. AGREES TO BUY TWO PUBLISHERS FROM HEARST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   BY DOREEN CARVAJAL and GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intensifying the consolidation of the nation's top book
publishers, News Corp. announced a deal Thursday to expand
HarperCollins with the purchase of the Hearst Corp.'s Avon Books
and William Morrow &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition, estimated at less than $180 million,
HarperCollins will remain the nation's second-ranking trade
publisher of popular titles, but will expand its share of the $8
billion consumer book market to more than 10 percent. Together,
Avon and Morrow are ranked eighth among trade publishers.
</P>
<P>
   The new combination will increase the popular commercial
presence of HarperCollins, which publishes writers like Barbara
Kingsolver and John Gray, and extend its reach into the mass market
through Avon Books, the second oldest paperback publisher in the
United States. The potential union also will deepen its children's
offerings through Morrow, which was founded in 1926, and publishes
best-selling children's authors like Beverly Cleary.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of HarperCollins, which is second in size to
Bertelsmann's Random House, comes in a market for popular books
that has been roiled by consolidation within the ranks of the top
10 trade publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   With this deal, few publishing giants remain that are ripe for
future sales, but consolidation is quickening in other categories
of publishing and reaching the second tier of mid-level companies
that have remained independent thus far. The interest comes not
just from publishers. Distributors are buying small presses, for
instance. Even the nation's largest bookstore chain, Barnes &AMP;
Noble, has become one of the leading suitors for Friedman/Fairfax
Publishers, a New York company specializing in nonfiction and
illustrated gardening and home decorating books, according to a
person with knowledge of the negotiations. A Barnes &AMP; Noble
spokesman, Mary Ellen Keating, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the educational and professional publisher John Wiley
&AMP; Sons announced that it had closed its $82 million acquisition of
the San Francisco publisher Jossey-Bass, a deal that followed its
$58 million purchase of a list of 60 college titles from Pearson
PLC _ which sold the titles and Jossey-Bass as part of its purchase
and break-up of a large part of Simon &AMP; Schuster last year.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, News Corp. considered selling HarperCollins,
but having kept it, it is now trying to expand, a move that spreads
the heavy costs of operating over a broader base. HarperCollins,
which got $200 million of its total $737 million in sales last year
from Britain, also is said to be involved in discussions to
increase its clout abroad through a possible merger of its foreign
operations in Britain with Penguin/Putnam, which is owned by
Pearson, or W.H. Smith, Britain's largest book retailer which
bought a large stake in the British publisher Hodder Headline.
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins' announcement of its planned purchase drew mixed
reviews, but it appeared that the expansion was not big enough to
prompt any organized effort to challenge it for anti-competitive
reasons and executives expect the deal to be completed within about
30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Authors Guild, which took its challenge of
Bertelsmann's purchase of Random House last year and its union with
Bantam Doubleday Dell to federal regulators, said it probably would
not follow the same strategy in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Letty Cottin Pogrebin, the president of the organization, said
that HarperCollins was not expanding enough to satisfy requirements
for a federal review for antitrust violations. She noted, however,
that she remained wary about the union of more imprints under
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. because of a 1998 incident in which
HarperCollins dropped the publication of a book by Chris Patten,
the last British governor of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Murdoch blamed the cancellation on publishing
executives who ``screwed it up'' although the decision was widely
attributed to Murdoch's desire to avoid antagonizing the leaders of
China, where he has large media investments.
</P>
<P>
   At HarperCollins, the company's chief executive, Jane Friedman,
said that the planned purchase of Avon and Morrow was News Corp.'s
``stamp of approval'' of the effort to turn around HarperCollins.
HarperCollins struggled through a bleak period in 1997 when it
canceled about 100 book contracts and took a $270 million charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled, I'm thankful and this says that we are here to
stay,'' Ms. Friedman said. ``And to be here, to stay in this
competitive environment one has to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that it was too early to answer whether any of
HarperCollins' imprints will be merged with the publishing units of
Morrow and Avon, which between them have 22 imprints and publish
1,000 books annually. Both Morrow and HarperCollins, for example,
each have six children's book imprints.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of the union, Ms. Friedman said, is that ``you've got
a bigger market share and you've got economies of scale, which of
course we all are looking for.'' She added, ``We are obviously
going to be looking at some consolidation, but nothing to speculate
on at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   William M. Wright, the chief executive of the Hearst Book Group,
which is the unit that will preside over Avon and William Morrow,
will remain a Hearst employee, but will participate in the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about potential job reductions, Ms. Friedman said she
could not comment because she first needs to ``get to know
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But some literary agents remained concerned about the potential
consolidation. On the one hand, the company's expansion could
increase advances for established commercial writers because
HarperCollins will have more resources to compete for authors in
high demand within the industry, said Robert Gottlieb, a literary
agent and executive vice president of the William Morris Agency.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, he said: ``It makes my job much more
difficult. There are fewer places now to grow new writers. Whenever
these companies make new acquisitions, the first thing they say is
that it's going to be business as usual. But the reality is that
they try to create a greater level of production and greater
margins, by cutting down on their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind all this activity is the reality that most publishing
companies have single-digit profit margins, hovering around eight
percent while educational publishers are more profitable with
margins of 17 to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, trade publishers are sold for lower multiples than
other types of publishers, usually for one to 1.2 times sales
revenues. News Corp. is buying Morrow and Avon for less than $180
million _ a price that is not a premium one because the companies'
sales revenues last year totaled about that amount. The price is
also less than the $220 million that they were asking for six years
ago when MCA's Putnam Berkeley Group considered buying the
companies then.
</P>
<P>
   By merging, a buyer gets saving on warehousing, distributing,
order processing and marketing, all of which can be spread across a
broader number of books.
</P>
<P>
   Using that logic, some analysts believe that Time Warner, which
owns Warner Books and Little Brown &AMP; Co., might be interested in
acquiring Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   However, a person close to Time Warner said that the company had
no intention of expanding its publishing business dramatically.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
