<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-FRANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS' MENU TAKES MIDDLE ROAD AT DINNER IN PARIS WITH CHIRACS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ President Clinton asked for a slice of life, and if it
included a slice of lamb, well, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   In arranging the president's only night out in Paris on his
weeklong European trip, U.S. officials told their French
counterparts the president wasn't interested in a three-star
gourmet experience. Something more typical, ``s'il vous plait.''
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton were whisked
away Wednesday night in their bulletproof car (``l'immense
limousine,'' noted Agence France-Presse) to the unassuming Chez
l'Ami Louis. It's in the middle-class third ``arrondissement,'' one
of the 20 numbered zones of the French capital _ each with a
certain character and cachet, or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   On the doorstep of the plain 70-year-old establishment on the
Rue du Vertbois waited the first couple's dining companions,
President Jacques Chirac and his wife, Bernadette.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac kissed Ms. Clinton. Clinton shook Ms. Chirac's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant owner Louis Gadby was ready with hearty fare from the
southwest of France.
</P>
<P>
   For starters there was air-cured ham and that terror of
cardiologists, ``foie gras,'' or perhaps buttery snails (``escargot
Bourgogne''). Then again, what about some rich preserved duck
(``confit d'canard'') or fancy frog (``grenouilles a la
provenale'')?
</P>
<P>
   Then on to the main course. Gadby recommended roasted young lamb
(``agneau de lait roti'') with potatoes (``pommes bearnaise'').
There was also beef or mutton, quail or a bit of roasted pigeon or
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Elysee Palace, the French White House, Clinton
chose the ham-``foie gras'' combo and the lamb. The wine was a 1990
St. Julien. Dessert was described as ``red fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the menu that amused French political wags. Even
though Chirac was once mayor of Paris, they offered wagers on the
last time the French president had dined in ``the third.'' It's an
area known for, well, not much. Street after street is lined with
aging apartment buildings of the solid bourgeois sort, with offices
and stores here and there.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-class choice of neighborhood prompted a touch of
sneering Thursday from morning radio commentators who found it a
little too calculatedly egalitarian.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac must have tucked in pretty good, because the button on
his dark blue suit looked a touch tight Thursday as he appeared
with Clinton before reporters on the exquisitely manicured lawn of
the Elysee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very pleasant dinner,'' Chirac said. ``I can't say
that we worked a great deal ... to tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a wonderful dinner,'' Clinton said. ``We had a terrific
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons drove to the restaurant from the residence of the
U.S. ambassador on the ever-smart Rue du Faubourg Saint Honore (in
the second ``arrondissement,'' a mixed district that includes some
of Paris' most stylishly elegant and grittiest neighborhoods).
</P>
<P>
   As the motorcade formed, there was an impromptu moment that
White House planners try desperately to avoid. Across the street,
in a large French window, appeared a well-fed matron, decked out in
skirt, earrings and white brassiere.
</P>
<P>
   A true Parisian, she nonchalantly removed curlers from her hair
and stepped out onto her balcony and into the warm late spring
evening _ grabbing a silk blouse and clutching it to her front only
when photographers waiting for Clinton started snapping her
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Her unabashed husband soon appeared beside her, taking off his
pants, which left him in briefs, shirt and tie.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was not about to say whether Clinton had seen
the little exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Food was still on the American president's mind Thursday when he
took a break from official meetings and did a bit of sightseeing _
an homage to his first trip to Paris 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Among his stops was a shop selling the top-rated Berthillon ice
cream. A shop assistant tried to press the prune flavor on Clinton
but had no luck. Two scoops of strawberry was the presidential
decree. Clinton was ready to pay with some francs, but the clerk
sniffily refused, insisting it was gratis.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service agents tried to keep control over a crush of
people, many of them fellow American tourists intent on getting a
look at the president. One reporter heard an agent push people out
of the way with the warning, ``I'm armed.''
</P>
<P>
   That did not intimidate a slim woman in a one-shouldered black
dress who demanded, and got, a Continental kiss on each cheek from
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a beautiful man,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A more robust matron in orange begged for a hug.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton complied, she squealed: ``Now I can die happy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
