<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CALLS U.S. EXPLANATION FOR EMBASSY BOMBING `UNCONVINCING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ One day after Under Secretary of State Thomas
Pickering presented Chinese officials with a detailed explanation
of how NATO warplanes could have accidentally bombed the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade last month, the Chinese government rejected it
Thursday as ``unconvincing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering spent hours on Wednesday briefing Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan and other officials about the conclusions of an
investigation into the bombing, which killed three Chinese and set
off angry anti-American protests here.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the report's findings were featured on state-run
television and carried by the official New China News Agency _
along with a detailed Chinese government analysis concluding that
the American explanations were inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This irrelevant explanation only shows that the United States
lacks any sincerity,'' said People's Daily, the Communist Party
newspaper, in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's rejection of the American version of events marked
another setback for Chinese-American relations, which were at a low
point at the time of the bombing, but recently had seemed to be
mending somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an opportunity here to move forward on WTO and other
big issues, but instead something in the Chinese foreign
policy-making process made them want to rachet this up again,''
said David Zweig, a China expert at the Hong Kong University of
Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But some Chinese were more optimistic, seeing the exchanges on
this issue as a first step in a healing process.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Chinese perspective the explanation is not
convincing,'' said Jia Qingguo, a professor of international
politics at Beijing University. ``But I think China wants further
clarification so it can get over its doubts, so that it can move on
in the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Chinese have been convinced from the start that the United
States intentionally bombed the embassy, though few can say why the
United States would want to do that. Many believe it was intended
to test China's resolve or to punish China for its vocal opposition
to the NATO air campaign in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has promised to provide a fuller
briefing to Congress and news organizations when Pickering returns
to Washington next week, James Foley, the deputy State Department
spokesman, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've seen Chinese spokesmen on television this
morning indicating that they were not fully satisfied with the
report.'' Foley said. ``I would like to point out, though, that
from our perspective, we believe that the information Ambassador
Pickering provided is sufficient to demonstrate that the bombing
was a terrible mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   An administration official, who spoke only on condition that he
not be identified, suggested that the hostile Chinese response to
the explanation may be partly for internal consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Although American officials refused to discuss the contents of
Pickering's presentation, Chinese news outlets gave detailed
reports Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The New China News Agency said that Pickering told the Chinese
that the intended target was the Yugoslav Federal Directorate for
Supply and Procurement, but that these errors resulted in striking
the embassy instead:
</P>
<P>
   _ American intelligence used three maps, two produced in
Yugoslavia and one by a U.S. government agency in 1997, none of
which specifically identified the directorate or the correct
location of the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   _ An American intelligence officer _ ``in breach of operational
rules'' _ preliminarily located the target by extrapolating from
``the pattern and numbering system'' of parallel streets. He
mistakenly picked out the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Military and targeting databases had not been updated and
contained an old address for the Chinese Embassy, so the error was
not detected.
</P>
<P>
   _ Targeting reviews also failed to pick up the mistake, and the
air crew, flying high and at night, could not see identifying
markers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
