<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-CLASH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WARSHIP PATROLS SOUTH KOREAN WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ A US Navy warship sailed into South Korean waters
Thursday to help restore calm, two days after a brief but deadly
gunbattle between North and South Korean vessels.
</P>
<P>
   But the shootout that sank a North Korean warship, killing an
estimated 30 sailors aboard, has left analysts here wondering why
North Korea would provoke the worst naval clash between the divided
neighbors since the Korean War _ less than a week before
long-awaited talks between the enemy nations.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings planned for Monday in Beijing will be the first
direct government contact between the two Koreas in 14 months, and
the gunbattle is sure to sour the negotiating climate.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul says the clash began when Northern vessels crossed into
Southern waters and fired, capping a nine-day standoff between
warships protecting crab-fishing vessels on either side.
</P>
<P>
   The incident comes while the Communist North and capitalist
South _ separated by the world's most militarized border _ have
been hard at work developing business contacts and opening limited
tourism to the hermetically sealed North.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say North Korea's unpredictable and contradictory
behavior is part of a two-pronged strategy. It is improving social
and economic relations with Seoul to extract desperately needed aid
_ while at the same time flexing military muscle to pressure
Washington into signing a final peace treaty to end the Korean War
and decrease its huge military presence in the South.
</P>
<P>
   An armistice halted the 1950-53 conflict, which claimed 50,000
American lives.
</P>
<P>
   The North's Jekyll-and-Hyde strategy may seem bizarre to
outsiders. But Pyongyang's isolated, Stalinist leadership regards
South Korea as a puppet state controlled by Washington and has long
wanted to negotiate directly with the United States for the
withdrawal of 37,000 American troops deployed in the South, as well
as for the lifting of US economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether South Korea's president, Kim Dae
Jung, who has pursued a controversial engagement policy toward the
North since early last year, can continue to indulge the North's
mercurial behavior without suffering political backlash from
domestic hawks. Similarly, the United States, which has pursued a
limited engagement strategy and recently sent US presidential envoy
William J. Perry to talk with North Korean leaders, could
eventually lose patience with the hot-and-cold response.
</P>
<P>
   Perry is expected to propose to Congress and the White House
that the US lift economic sanctions in exchange for promises by
Pyongyang to freeze nuclear weapons development and halt missile
testing and proliferation. The CIA says North Korea is the world's
largest exporter of ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``For North Korea, being very aggressive to South Korea on one
hand and being positive to the US on the other is a traditional
negotiating strategy _ it's a two-track policy'' to drive a wedge
in the close alliance between Seoul and Washington, said Park
Young-Ho, a senior fellow at the Korea Institute for National
Unification, a government think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Sparking a sea battle before scheduled talks next week is also
likely an attempt by Pyongyang to shift the agreed-upon agenda from
food aid and cross-border family reunification to security issues,
and to try to frighten Washington with the supposed military
prowess of the North, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Seoul seems eager to play down the incident. This week,
cruise ships filled with Southern tourists sailed to the North as
scheduled, Seoul delivered shipments of donated fertilizer as
promised, and a business trip to Pyongyang by Samsung officials
went ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to our intelligence sources,'' a South Korean
official said, ``North Korea is not preparing for war...They may be
provoking us in order to get more (concessions) in Beijing. We want
peace, so if they provoke, they think the South will give more.
They often do this before conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Japanese media quoted US military sources saying that
North Korea began in April conducting propulsion tests on a
long-range missile that could reach Alaska. The sources said the
missile launch pad has been enlarged and fuel transported to
storehouses, but that a launch did not appear imminent. The South
Korean defense ministry could not confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, analysts here say, the cat and mouse strategy shows
Pyongyang's underlying weakness and desperation. North Korea's
economy has shrunk every year since the collapse of the Soviet
Union, its onetime benefactor, and aid workers estimate 2 million
people have died from starvation brought on by drought and state
farm mismanagement in the last four years. That leaves the North
with few options but to negotiate in exchange for aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to maintain social cohesion, North Korea needs a
common enemy and a certain tension,'' said Koh Il-Dong, a North
Korea expert at the Korea Development Institute. ``Every time they
need to make a deal, they pull out a new card to exploit to get
more concessions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
