<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDELITY-SUBSCRIBE-BO     06-17 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-SUBSCRIBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY UPS SIZE OF BOND OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Institutional investors jumped Thursday at a rare
chance to own a piece of the action at Fidelity Investments,
prompting the mutual fund behemoth to increase its landmark bond
offering to $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Fidelity told investors not to start thinking about owning
Fidelity stock one day. The nation's largest fund firm, privately
owned and closely held, said it had no intention of becoming a
publicly traded company, with shares listed on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, in an unusual move to tap markets for cash, boosted
its $750 million corporate bond offering by one third to meet a
crush of demand from New York investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   The debt offering, the largest in the Boston firm's 53-year
history, gave investors not just the highest rated bonds of any
asset management company, but also securities in one of the money
world's most profitable businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fidelity name was extremely well received by the
marketplace,'' said Bill White, head of US syndication at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, the investment bank that led the offering.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity said it would use proceeds from the borrowing for
internal purposes, the uncommon cash-raising venture spurred
speculation that the firm might be testing the waters for a stock
offering. Because it is privately owned, with 49 percent of its
shares in the hands of the Johnson family of Boston, whose
billionaire patriarch, Edward C. ``Ned'' Johnson III, runs the
firm, Fidelity is not required under law to reveal much about its
inner workings.
</P>
<P>
   But in line with securities industry disclosure rules, the bond
offering document provided a treasure trove of financial details.
The confidential memorandum, a copy of which was obtained Thursday
by the Globe, confirmed reports that show Fidelity doing a booming
business amid a record bull market. The document's profit, cash
flow, and other information fueled industry talk that Fidelity
wanted to see how investors would assess the company's financial
details as a warm-up to drafting the tell-all documents required
for issuing stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be seeing how Wall Street's going to react, and this
is a way to get some information out into the public,'' said
Nikolas Lanyi, editor of the independent Fidelity Insight
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Rubbish, said Fidelity spokesman Thomas Eidson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you categorically that we have no interest in going
public,'' Eidson said. ``We're going to use the money from the
offering for general corporate purposes.'' The Johnson family has
said it has no intention of selling the firm, which industry
observers speculate could fetch at least $24 billion and possibly
more than $35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On other fronts, Fidelity's bond document provided a rare
glimpse into one of the investment world's most powerful yet
inscrutable companies.
</P>
<P>
   One section stated that Fidelity reduced its charitable giving
last quarter while increasing compensation and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Another part suggested Fidelity thought that cheap on-line
trading _ a goal for many traditional money management firms these
days _ might not produce happy results. ``Although Fidelity has
experienced a significant increase in on-line trading since it
reduced its commissions,'' the document said, ``the long-term
effect on net commission revenues has not yet been determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, which manages $805 billion in assets, sells mutual
funds to individual and institutional investors and operates an
on-line brokerage. As Fidelity customers migrated to fast and
inexpensive on-line trading services, offered by Fidelity and
others, commissions per trade had suffered and revenue from
brokerage commissions had declined, the document said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fidelity _ whose skipper, Johnson, is a technology addict
_ would probably use some of the proceeds from Thursday's bond
offering to help beef up the firm's technology, including at the
on-line brokerage, Lanyi said. Fidelity spends $500 million a year
on technology projects. The document said the firm expected to
invest in property and equipment, make strategic investments in new
technologies and products, and seek ``attractive opportunities''
for its venture capital unit property.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's bond offering injected new life into a corporate bond
market that has been jittery about possible interest rate hikes.
Fidelity sold $750 million in 30-year notes at 7.57 percent and
$250 million in 20-year notes at 7.49 percent, all in a private
placement to four investment banks and Fidelity's capital markets
division, White said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
