<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-IVESTER18-COX     06-17 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-IVESTER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Owning up' can cut the damage
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite vigorous efforts to cooperate with health
officials and analyze the production problems that have bedeviled
its soft drinks in Europe, Coca-Cola Co. has so far failed to calm
health fears that sprang up a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the hours fly by, the precious Coca-Cola brand is threatened,
with one country and then another registering levels of concern
about the beverages.
</P>
<P>
   The alarms at Coke's Atlanta headquarters were first set off
last week when schoolchildren became ill in Belgium after consuming
bottled Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola officials have been working with health agencies and
others in Europe to try to isolate the problems of contamination
that have produced illness and fears from Belgium to France,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bill Casey, president of Coca-Cola Europe, and Randy
Donaldson, vice president for global communications, flew to Europe
to take personal charge of developments and public relations.
</P>
<P>
   A team of technical specialists from the United States and
Europe have been working with European bottlers to address
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman M. Douglas Ivester issued his first public statement on
the crisis Wednesday, apologizing to European customers for the
problems and pledging that the company ``is taking all necessary
steps to ensure that all our products meet the highest quality
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   While Belgium announced Thursday it was allowing Coca-Cola to
resume the sale of some products, sale of the signature soft drinks
was still suspended _ all pending some clear and satisfying
explanation of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Experts praised the early action by Coke to take the complaint
seriously and remove products. In doing so, said the London Times
newspaper, the company may have sidestepped the worse mistakes of
Perrier, the mineral water company that stalled and dragged its
feet in 1990 when its products were found to be contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Coke is undoubtedly terrified that things might spiral
out of control, it has acted coolly and slickly in seeking to
contain damage,'' said the London newspaper. ``Branding experts say
it has done all the right things, owning up to the problem and
taking prompt action,'' the paper continued, echoing the views of
many American analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the public concerns do not subside.
</P>
<P>
   There are some views that probably should have spoken sooner,
perhaps even gone to Europe himself as a symbolic show of personal
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Holmes, editor and publisher of Reputation Management
Magazine, which studies and reports on corporate image problems,
said, ``In an age of global media, when any threat _ whether true
or unfounded _ is aimed at your brand's reputation, you must react
immediately from the highest levels within the organization, no
matter where in the world the threat is being launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Coke's case, waiting several days to issue a response (from
Ivester) from corporate headquarters in the United States raised
serious questions about the company's sensitivity to customer
safety concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   From all appearances, of course, internally at Coca-Cola there
has been deep concern, though a kind of domino effect among the
European nations has escalated the scope of the public fears.
</P>
<P>
   Though Coca-Cola has been busy and not indulging in denial, as
time drags along without turning the corner and without a clear
bill of health, there could be an erosion of consumer confidence
among jittery Europeans not unlike the Perrier problem of nine
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perrier danced and dodged before finally pulling the products
from shelves. But in the bargain, the company lost substantial
market share, which it has not fully regained to this day, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Perrier, of course, was paraded as a health product before being
brought low by its problems.
</P>
<P>
   Coke, quite differently, is a chemical product, marketed
unabashedly as a fun drink. The product has lagged in sales in
recent months, held down mostly by economic problems in Asia,
Russia and Latin America, and shares in the company have been
lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot less fun than usual lately in Atlanta, and
there clearly is an urgent need for some breakthrough in confidence
in Europe for the Coke products.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
