<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMERS-CONFIRM-ART-N     06-17 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERS-CONFIRM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS MAKE RUBIN'S PROBABLE SUCCESSOR SUFFER A BIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Okla., N.Y., Alaska)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the height of the Mexican peso crisis in
1995, Lawrence Summers was the favorite target of the Senate
Finance Committee. He was viewed as the scheming architect of an
end-run around Congress that resulted in the $12 billion Mexican
bailout. Some Republicans called for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, virtually all the members of the same committee
said they expected Summers, the Harvard economist whom President
Clinton nominated last month to succeed Robert Rubin, to easily win
approval as the 71st treasury secretary of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But first they wanted him to suffer a little.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-hour confirmation hearing, Summers twice apologized
for saying over lunch with a small group of reporters in 1997 that
Republicans wanted to cut estate taxes because of ``selfishness.''
(``What I said there was wrong,'' Summers said. ``It is always
wrong to impugn motives in these kinds of policy debates.'')
</P>
<P>
   He sparred at length with an angry Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.,
about the administration's plans for financing Social Security.
Pressed on the question of whether the administration would raise
payroll taxes, he would say only that Clinton would not raise
``payroll tax rates,'' leaving open the possibility that the
administration could find other ways to raise revenue, including
increasing the ceiling on incomes that are subject to the tax.
Currently, it applies to the first $72,000 in income.
</P>
<P>
   And then Summers and Kerrey entered a lengthy debate on the
question of how the government would pay to convert into cash
Treasury bonds that Clinton proposes to place in the Social
Security trust fund so that it does not run out of money. Summers
ducked and dodged a bit until Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D--N.Y., the ranking Democrat on the committee, exclaimed: ``Larry,
it's taxes!''
</P>
<P>
   Summers later acknowledged that the general revenue pool of the
government would have to be tapped to liquidate the bonds, leading
Kerrey to conclude that the president's solution to saving Social
Security was no solution at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the president's answer to the problem,'' Kerrey said.
``Take the current problem that we have of using more individual
and corporate income taxes to pay Social Security beneficiaries and
consider it to be a virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would see it differently,'' said Summers, clearly trying to
obey the unwritten mandate that nominees should never engage in
lengthy arguments with senators voting on their confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   For all the heat of the exchanges, there was never any real
question that Summers is likely to be confirmed. The last real
obstacle was surmounted on Wednesday, when the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott, announced that he had negotiated a deal that
would lift a freeze on all Senate confirmations. The freeze had
been declared, under the rules of senatorial privilege, by Sen.
James Inhofe, R-Okla. Inhofe said he was outraged that Clinton had
issued a recess appointment for James Hormel as ambassador to
Luxembourg. Hormel is a gay businessman, and the appointment was
made when the Senate was out of session to avoid opposition to his
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Summers had clearly trained for Thursday's hearing, suppressing
his occasional tendency to respond to questions with a quick and
sometimes cutting quip, and an attitude that demonstrated he knew
far more about a subject than the questioner. It was this approach
that contributed to his troubles in 1995. Nonetheless, on Thursday
one of the senators who was most vocal in opposing the Mexican
bailout, Frank Murkowski, D-Alaska, conceded that he had been
wrong. ``I think it is fair to say that you and Secretary Rubin
proved that you were on a correct path,'' Murkowski said, an
acknowledgment that Mexico both recovered and repaid its loans from
the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
