A9863 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES18-COX     06-17 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airlines take reform pledge
 &HT;    By Shannon Shelton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Waiting out delay at Hartsfield International Airport
is a routine part of life for Clyde Fones of Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Fones, who often flies Delta Air Lines for business trips, was
sitting Thursday afternoon at a Delta gate again, hoping his latest
stay wouldn't strand him too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the third time in two weeks I've been delayed,'' he
said after arriving from Hartford, Conn. ``I was supposed to leave
at 3:40, but I'm going to be delayed at least until 4:10.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to reduce the frequency of such complaints, the U.S.
airline industry Thursday unveiled voluntary reforms designed to
provide more consumer protections for air passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The measures, which include promises of low fare quotes and
increased liability for lost baggage, are expected to halt
congressional moves for a passenger ``bill of rights.'' Air
Transport Association President Carol Hallett said the picture of
uncaring airlines was not accurate, but ``we all need and want to
do a better job'' and ``when Congress gets our attention, that's
when we really do react.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta, the focus of Fones' agitation, had no objections to the
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta wholeheartedly supports this plan,'' spokeswoman Kay
Horner said Thursday. ``It's good for consumers and airlines. It
addresses the concerns of passengers and enables airlines to
compete in a healthy, competitive environment.'' Orlando,
Fla.-based AirTran said it would lay out its guidelines after
further review of the plan. ``Once we do that, we are going to work
on a plan of our own passenger bill of rights,'' spokeswoman Shelia
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Smith, a Roseland, N.J., resident, also waiting at
Hartsfield for a delayed Continental Airlines flight to Newark, was
skeptical about the vows of reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea, but I don't think the airlines will
follow it,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to take such steps came after much-publicized incidents
during a storm last winter when passengers flying Northwest
Airlines were forced to sit seven or more hours on runways in
Detroit without food and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers like Fones think reforms can't arrive too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're footing the bill for the airlines and taking it in the
neck,'' Fones said
</P>
<P>
   VOLUNTARY REFORMS
</P>
<P>
   _ Quote the lowest available fare for each flight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Notify customers at the airport and on board the aircraft with
the ``best available'' information on delays, cancellations and
flight re-routings. In addition, each carrier would have to
establish a set policy for passengers stranded overnight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give consumers a 24-hour window after reserving a ticket to
decide whether to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   _ Support a Department of Transportation proposal to increase
the current liability limit of $1,250 per bag.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide prompt refunds, accommodate disabled passengers and
meet customer needs during long on-aircraft delays.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
