<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS &LR;      06-17 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY CHALLENGES FOR EARLY LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ They used to point out that nothing could be
finer than to be in Carolina, but after four days of rainy and
overcast conditions that threatened to put a damper on the 99th US
Open at the No. 2 course at Pinehurst, the sun broke through
briefly Thursday, and there was an interesting leaderboard after
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   After John Daly put aside memories of the six putts he took on
the 18th green in the first round of the Memorial, which prompted
his withdrawal, he threatened to take the lead. Then he hit a tee
shot so far left on 18 that it nearly ended up in Southern Pines or
Aberdeen. He did manage to gouge out a bogey 5, and only trails by
one stroke entering the second round.
</P>
<P>
   When Rocco Mediate suffered a double bogey on 18, when he had
the opportunity to take the lead, and the round was history, there
was a four-way tie at the top. Phil Mickelson, an expectant father
who will leave if wife Amy goes into labor with their first child,
heads the group at 3-under 67. He's joined there by David Duval,
who burned his right hand in a kitchen mishap, Billy Mayfair, and
Paul Goydos.
</P>
<P>
   The five lodged at 69 were Daly, Tiger Woods, who birded the
final two holes, last year's runner-up, Payne Stewart, David
Berganio of the Nike Tour, and Kaname Yokoo of Japan, who has
participated in 10 events on the Japanese Tour, six on the PGA
Tour, and is playing in his first US Open.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, 28, who has knocked on the door at the major
championships but has yet to win one, said his wife is due June 30.
Should his caddie's beeper go off, Mickelson will head home _ even
if he's in the lead. ``That's something I don't want to miss,'' he
said. ``The US Open takes place every year. If she punches in the
code, I'm getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   The round over the course designed by Donald Ross and modified
for the first US Open by Rees Jones included five birdies and
bogeys on the sixth and seventh. The birdies came on the second
(7-iron, 18 feet), fourth (pitching wedge, 8 feet), a chip-in on
the fifth (from 25 feet), the 13th (8-iron, 30 feet), and 14th
(9-iron, 8 feet), and he had to make a putt from 12 feet on the
18th to cling to the lead. This is a course he enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really excited heading in,'' Mickelson said. ``I'm
really excited about the setup of the golf course. I think it's the
best test of golf that I've ever played in a major championship. It
tests every area of your game. It tests every shot. Past Opens have
not really tested you off the tee as well with the driver. Every
player has an opportunity to hit any club he wants to off the tee,
and this year there's a lot of emphasis placed on the short game.
It's an integral part of this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who has won four times this year and is still ranked No.
1 on the world list, is in the same situation as Mickelson. He
hasn't won a major. He had three birdies in his bogey-free round.
He birdied the second (7-iron, 8 feet), the par-3 15th (5-iron, 2
feet), and par-3 17th (7-iron, 10 feet), and saved three pars. ``I
wasn't able to practice,'' he said, ``but at the same time there's
times when that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   The course everybody expected to be hard and fast after a dry
stretch has been softened by the rains. ``It makes the greens a lot
more receptive,'' said Duval. ``We're in a position where we're
having to hit anywhere from two to three clubs more into the
greens. I think it's going to get more difficult as the week
progresses. I was pretty pleased with all of my game today. I'd be
content to do it three more days.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair, who won twice last year in a comeback and beat Woods in
a playoff at Los Angeles, birdied the ninth (6-iron, 20 feet) and
10th (4-iron, 20 feet) to get to 3 under and then finished with
eight consecutive pars. ``It was raining pretty hard when we teed
off,'' he said. ``The golf course is actually the most susceptible
of birdies we'll see all week because of the wetness. I went out
today and did exactly what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Goydos has won just once, in 1996 at Bay Hill and actually
worked as a school teacher in Long Beach, Calif., where he won the
Long Beach Open in 1990. He saved pars on five holes to put him
into the thick of the hunt. ``I'm a firm believer that if you're
playing well, every course kind of sets up for you,'' said Goydos.
``If you're playing bad, none of them do.'' For the four tied for
the lead, nothing could be finer than to be in Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
