A9865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      06-17 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ COMPUTER PREDICTS $237 MILLION SHORTFALL IN 2ND QUARTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first comment on its business prospects since dismissing
its chief executive, Eckhard Pfeiffer, two months ago, the Compaq
Computer Corp. said Thursday that it would lose as much as 15 cents
a share, or $237 million, in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin M. Rosen, the company's longtime chairman and acting
chief executive, also announced a sweeping reorganization meant to
save $2 billion a year. Last year, total expenses were $34 billion.
The company will lay off thousands of employees and take a charge
to earnings in the third quarter to cover the costs of the
restructuring, but it would not quantify either the layoffs or the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been losing both money and market share in the face
of Dell Computer's more efficient and flexible method of selling
directly to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, which now gets 85 percent of its sales from local
dealers, wants to increase its direct sales to consumers to 25
percent of total sales by the end of this year. The company is
building 17 call centers to take orders over the telephone, and is
upgrading its Internet site to give customers more options in how
they buy computers directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-commerce is starting to drive the computer business,''
Michael D. Capellas, the company's acting chief operating officer,
said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Compaq was pinning much of its hopes for growth in
the future on developing small, specialized computers that
consumers would use mainly to surf the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company attributed its continued earnings problems to
bloated costs, competitive pricing for personal computers and slow
sales growth. It said it no longer faced losses from write-downs of
bloated inventory, a problem that had tripped the company up
several times over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen declined to predict how long the lean times would last.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major structural change for Compaq,'' he said. ``We
want to restore our historical profitability and growth, but we are
not prepared to make forecasts about when.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praised the reorganization and cost-cutting moves but
said they would do little to address the company's long-term
problems, including the complexity of its acquisitions of the
Digital Equipment Corp. and Tandem Computers, both of which make
powerful computers for large companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq still has lots of problems at the high end, although
not everything is hunky dory in PC land either,'' said Steven
Milunovich, an analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   In published forecasts, analysts had estimated that Compaq would
earn 20 cents a share in the second quarter, or $317 million,
according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors appeared to take the news in stride, perhaps
because Compaq's stock had taken such a beating in recent months.
The company's shares closed up 25 cents Thursday, at $22.50,
substantially off the 52-week high of $51.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be a miracle if they made money this
quarter,'' said Andrew J. Neff, an analyst with Bear Sterns. ``But
the issue is not what they are going to earn next quarter but
whether they can turn the company around.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq announced a streamlined organization structure, based on
three global product groups, that will handle product development,
sales and marketing. In the past, these functions were split among
a much more complex organization, which had some divisions focused
on products, others on geographic areas and yet others on
functional areas like marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each group will be focused on a single market, have clear
accountability and understanding of who its competition is,''
Capellas said.
</P>
<P>
   The company will merge its high-end computer division and its
division that provides services like custom programming and
installation help into a single enterprise solutions and services
group, headed by Enrico Pesatori. An expanded personal computer
division will continue to be run by Mike Winkler. The consumer
products group, the most successful part of the company now, will
continue to be run by Michael J. Larson.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pfeiffer was dismissed, seven of 15 top executives have
left.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most important management change was not announced
Thursday. Rosen said the search for a new chief executive ``is well
along'' but he declined to say when the appointment would be
announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
