u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-JEWS-ARRESTS-NYT     06-17 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-JEWS-ARRESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARREST OF 13 IRANIAN JEWS AS SPIES DIVIDES FACTIONS IN TEHERAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ The arrest of 13 Iranian Jews on charges of
spying for the United States and Israel has emerged as a new focal
point in the struggle between moderates and conservatives in
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said by telephone from the Iranian capital Thursday
that they suspected that the case was being used to try to block
better relations between Iran and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian Jews, who are from the southern cities of Shiraz and
Isfahan, may be executed if convicted, Iranian officials say, but
the leader of Iran's Jews is demanding that they receive a fair
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Manouchehr Elias, the leader of Iran's 27,000-member Jewish
community, has said that the suspects should be punished if guilty,
but that ``if the opposite is true, they should be released
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no indication as to how the suspects have
responded to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Ayatollah Mohammed Yazdi, the head of Iran's judicial system,
struck a hard line in a prayer sermon last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish spies for Israel will be tried for treason
according to Islamic law and they may be sentenced to death _ not
once but several times,'' Yazdi said. A crowd of thousands shouted
for ``the traitors'' to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has denounced the arrests as ``unacceptable''
and has called for the immediate release of the suspects, who were
arrested in February and March and who include rabbis, religious
teachers and community activists.
</P>
<P>
   But Jomhuri Islami, a newspaper opposed to President Mohammad
Khatami, a relative moderate, has served notice that conservatives
intend to draw a hard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington's support of the spies shows that the United States
is still the enemy of the Iranian people, and this should be a
lesson for all those in Iran who support a normalization of
relations with the United States,'' the newspaper said in a recent
editorial.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, who has been trying to improve Iran's relations with
the West, has not commented publicly about the arrests, which took
place in March but were not disclosed by Iranian officials until
this month. But he has not tried hard to disguise a sense of
exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are using almost any method to ruin the plans of
the government,'' Khatami said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election two years ago, Khatami has been battling
constantly with the conservatives who still hold the main levers of
power. He has seen allies jailed, supportive newspapers shuttered
and top aides impeached, but the popular appeal behind his victory
seems only to have increased, as was evident in the triumph that
his supporters scored in municipal elections this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the conservatives, the dominant political force in Iran
since the 1979 revolution, have not backed away. Their harsh
reaction to criticism over the arrest of the Jews suggests a belief
that they see the issue as a way to reinforce popular suspicions
over links to the West.
</P>
<P>
   That hard line has been reinforced by Iran's mission to the
United Nations, which said in a statement last week that those
arrested had come from a ``Zionist'' spy network in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has condemned the arrests in harsh terms, and the Rev.
Jesse Jackson has said he has been in touch with the Iranian
authorities in the hope of visiting Tehran, apparently in the hope
of brokering a prisoner release.
</P>
<P>
   Israel maintained warm relations with Iran before the 1979
Islamic revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
