<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-17 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ROBINSON AND SPURS ARE ON TOP OF WORLD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Imagine what it's like to be 7 feet 1 inch and
looking down on the world from the highest of professional and
personal posts. What a perspective to have gained on basketball,
and life.
</P>
<P>
   What a blessing for a religious man to have reached the point of
contentment, of being exactly where he wishes to be. David Robinson
is in the city he considers home, in a position where he can help
those less fortunate, and at the high post in the San Antonio
Spurs' offense, from where he can take his man off the dribble and
hit the jumper and assist his teammates cutting to the rim. From
where he can see the big picture and appreciate the brilliance of
another young man who has relieved him of a role that was cutting
him down and wearing him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's talent is a little more obvious than mine,'' said
Robinson, a judicious man in a fortuitous place.
</P>
<P>
   In his 10th year as a pro basketball player, during the first
post-Michael Jordan season, Robinson has had the best view in
America, watching Tim Duncan suddenly become the most dominant
player in the game, claiming the very space in the lane that
Robinson once owned. Watching Duncan's eye-opening variety of
low-post moves and knowing only a fool could have resisted the ride
that has brought him to within three victories of his primary
vocational dream. Watching, yet understanding that he has become
more of a teammate, no less a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, you think you can get it all done by yourself, but
then you realize you can't,'' Robinson said Thursday after the
Spurs prepared for Game 2 of the NBA finals, for an ornery albeit
battered bunch of Knicks who are trailing in this season's playoffs
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   From the high post in Game 1 Wednesday night, Robinson generated
seven assists - four more than any Knick. He could clearly see how
all the disappointments of his early pro years and all the back
pain of the more recent ones could soon culminate in the first
championship for team and town. Robinson high. Duncan low. This is
the blueprint, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, there is so much basketball left to be played,'' Robinson
said, cheerfully rejecting the notion of the Spurs in control, as
if it were a Charlie Ward layup, floating like a beach ball toward
the rim.
</P>
<P>
   This was just another prime vantage point, part of that
expansive view from the high post. Don't count out the Knicks, and
while we're at it, stop making too much of his so-called sacrifices
to accommodate the new kid on the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how you look at it,'' Robinson said, ``you have to
use Tim's abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Parish stepped outside years ago in Boston to accommodate
Kevin McHale. Ralph Sampson realized he was better suited to facing
the basket the minute Hakeem Olajuwon touched down in Houston.
Robinson knows he was never the classic post-up player. The story
here is less about setting examples for the more selfishly inclined
and more about not kicking a gift horse in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   So many of these opportunities are serendipity, a chain of
events no one foresees. When Robinson missed most of the season two
years ago with an ailing back and a broken foot, his career seemed
on the way down and the Spurs on their way out. Even as the finals
go on, there are reports of the team's ownership in talks with
officials from Baltimore and Anaheim, Calif., about relocating from
a small television market and an unfashionable dome built by a
previous owner for a football team the city never got.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association could do worse than to
financially assist in the building of a new arena, following the
National Football League's lead in the New England case. It would
be a shame for pro basketball to lose this charming and boisterous
outpost, rich in history and fan support. It would be a blow to
Robinson, who set up shop in south Texas with the idea of leaving
more than statistical records behind.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Valerie, started the David Robinson Foundation
seven years ago, administering to a variety of programs benefiting
students, babies, the homeless and the hungry. Two years ago, the
Robinsons gave $5 million to the expansion of a local cultural
center. He has always maintained that he never wanted to play for
another team, in another town.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do well, they're going to find a way to keep us here,''
he said. ``I can't see us playing anyplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   From the high post, three victories from the title, Robinson's
eyes are fixed on the prize. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
