<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-DALY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSERVERENCE PAYS FOR JOHN DALY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ He was in the woods. But that's the story of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   He could have played it safe, but that's not the story of his
life. So John Daly did what he always does. He gripped, he ripped,
he took on trouble.
</P>
<P>
   And somehow, someway, he perservered. He shot 2-under 68
Thursday in the first round of the US Open at Pinehurst No. 2. How,
he was asked, was that possible? Hadn't he just fallen to the
depths of despair once again, a six-putt debacle from 8 feet at the
Memorial? How had he come back this time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to it, I guess,'' said Daly. ``It's been
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't talking about the drive at No. 4 that went left into
the woods, or the drive on No. 10 that sprayed right into the
woods. He wasn't even talking about the drive at 18 that was
shanked right, hit a tree, and ended up a mere 80-90 yards from the
tee, in the woods, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Those are merely bad golf shots and aren't even on the radar
screen when it comes to what Daly has to deal with. He is a
recovering alcoholic. That was Thursday's battle. It will be
today's battle. Tomorrow's battle, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I'm playing good, it's hard ... the cravings are
there. You can't imagine what I'm going through when I'm playing
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The play of late has been worse than bad. He scored a 10 on that
18th hole at Memorial, shot 82, and withdrew from a tournament for
the third time this year. He has also missed five cuts. Playing in
his eighth straight tournament, there was no reason to expect
anything from Daly.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew. I'm about as much in shock as everybody else is
right now. I didn't have any confidence or any expectations coming
in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, it was suggested to Daly, he feels confident on this
course, having finished third here in the Tour Championship in
1991. Not possible, he said. ``I think I played so drunk here in
'91 I don't even remember the holes. I honestly don't. They told me
I finished 1-under.''
</P>
<P>
   So honest, so sadly honest, Daly conceded, but it is such a huge
part of his life, which has been an open book ever since that
magical weekend in 1991 when he burst upon the scene at the PGA
Championship. He ate Crooked Stick and washed it down with booze.
Then he quit drinking, won the British Open in 1995, and started
drinking again. It got so bad he wanted to kill himself during a
hotel rampage at The Players Championship in 1997, a scene so ugly
that those who know the details don't like to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   Daly couldn't play in the '97 Masters, then had to withdraw from
the US Open at Congressional, battling shakes that were
uncontrollable. Tiger Woods or no Tiger Woods, he remained No. 1
with galleries, though at times they could only look on helplessly.
Like the time the shakes came again, and Daly began to cry,
consoled by Corey Pavin.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the roars started early as Daly opened birdie-birdie.
Then he nearly drove the 335-yard par 4 third and went to 3-under.
When he registered his fourth straight one-putt, this to save a par
5 at the fourth, his name was atop the leaderboard and he had it
going. Right? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in total shock,'' said Daly. ``It was weird. I just kept
fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 610-yard 10th hole, moments after a triple-breaking
birdie putt at the ninth, Daly flew his drive into the woods. He
was on hard sand, 269 yards from the pin and the gallery moved
slightly, assuming a pitch-out was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Move back further, they were told. Back more. Back even more.
</P>
<P>
   It was on the third request that they realized that the man in
the woods was John Daly and John Daly meets trouble head on. He was
going for the green, some 269 yards in the distance. ``Cut a 3-wood
out of there,'' he said. But he didn't quite catch it flush, so it
only reached the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The crowd loved it. And though he kept looking
straight ahead, through a pair of sunglasses with orange lenses
(``I was in so many bunkers at Augusta, my eyes were squinting so
bad''), and puffing on a cigarette, Daly heard the support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the greatest feeling in the world. Fans have stuck
with me through think and thin, and it was so nice to give them a
good round today. I haven't figured out why they do it, but I sure
love it and I love them for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he finished with a bogey to fall out of a share of the
lead, Daly had put up the round of the day. So how to celebrate?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go eat about six cheeseburgers at McDonald's,
probably have a bag of Oreos and a big thing of milk, then watch
Sports Center and hopefully see myself on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   He will like what he sees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
