<SLUG> BC-KOREA-CONFRONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH AND SOUTH KOREA WATCH EACH OTHER IN YELLOW SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Ships from North and South Korea circled
cautiously Thursday in the Yellow Sea, where the two sides recently
skirmished, but American ships were streaming toward the area in a
display of force.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean government officials seem to be playing down the
effects of the gun battle, in which they sank a North Korean
torpedo boat and killed a number of North Koreans on board. At
least 20 North Koreans may have died in the firefight, which took
place early Tuesday morning after the two sides had been taunting
each other for days in disputed waters in the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, it seems as though it has subsided,'' said Kim
Hyon-du, a spokesman for the South Korean Ministry of Unification.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, North Korea suspended visits by South Koreans to
Pyongyang, endangering two-way talks that are scheduled for Monday
in Beijing. They would be the first official negotiations in 14
months, and South Korea is worried now that North Korea may not
show up.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions are still running high. When asked at a news conference
Thursday whether the firefight threatened the talks, Brig. Gen. Cha
Young-koo, a spokesman for South Korea's defense ministry, said:
``Even husbands and wives get closer after they fight.'' Cha was
fired later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has not put any of its troops in the region on
alert. But it is moving military ships and aircraft in a show of
force. The Aegis-class cruiser Vincennes was headed this way
Thursday, and the guided-missile destroyer Mobile Bay was moving
toward the region as well.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was also sending out four Navy reconnaissance
aircraft, the EA-6 electronic warfare aircraft, from Whidbey Island
in Washington, and those aircraft will go to Japan, American
military officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two nuclear-powered submarines, the Kamehameha and the Buffalo,
were also at a Korean naval base for training as part of a routine
port call, according to reports by the Associated Press, the Korean
state-owned Yonhap News Agency and the Korea Broadcasting System.
American and South Korean officials did not deny the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Yonhap also reported that nuclear submarines often come to South
Korea for training and that these two would also be leaving soon.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has not had an aircraft carrier in the region
since the Kitty Hawk was sent to the Persian Gulf. But it has had
18 F-15 aircraft here for a month, as well as AC-130 gunships for
two months. Moreover, the nuclear aircraft carrier Constellation is
expected to head to the region from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation between the North and the South began 10 days
ago, when North Korean naval vessels escorted fishing boats south
of the ``northern limit line,'' the customary line of demarcation
separating the seas of the two Koreas. The North does not recognize
the line, and has often sent ships south of it, but they normally
retreat when ordered back by South Korean patrol boats.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, the North Korean vessels refused to back off,
and on Friday, South Korean vessels began to ram the North Korean
boats.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the standoff exploded in gunfire. South Korean
patrol boats sank a North Korean torpedo ship and damaged at least
five other North Korean vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Two South Korean patrol boats were damaged and seven South
Korean sailors were slightly wounded. South Korea has put its
entire armed forces on a combat level of alert, which is a state of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials will not officially comment on the
suspension of visits to Pyongyang. But such restrictions are not
likely to have a large effect on travel to the North, for only a
handful of South Koreans typically travel to Pyongyang. Other areas
do not seem to be affected by the suspension.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the firefight took place, there were 1,970 South
Koreans in the North, and most of them were in the tourist area of
Mount Kumgang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
