<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAMAL18-C     06-17 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAMAL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson: `I don't want to be traded _ I'm a Falcon'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few days ago, Falcons running back Jamal Anderson
decided he would skip the start of the team's attendance-optional
passing camp. Anderson's agent, Jim Sims, said the All-Pro back was
staying home in Salt Lake City ``unless we have some sort of show
of good faith'' from the team on contract extension talks. Sims
even said he might ask the Falcons to trade Anderson. Anderson, 26,
planned to keep quiet, but he places a premium on the way he is
perceived in public. So he called AJC writer Matt Winkeljohn.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: So, what's going on with the contract situation?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I'm not holding out of anything. This passing camp is
not a mandatory thing. I've always missed days. (Quarterback) Chris
(Chandler) won't be there every day. One thing I'm not is selfish.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Your agent said you need a ``show of good faith'' in order
to show up. Considering the Falcons started these talks in November
and there is an offer on the table for a five-year contract worth
about $26 million, what's that mean? That money is enough to be
considered one of the five highest-paid backs.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I'm just trying to get market value. There's a lot we
need to establish. Am I top five? Top three? You also have to take
into account how important a team considers a running back to its
scheme. There are reports I've turned down $5.2 million per year.
That's hogwash. I haven't turned down anything. ... We could just
as easily say the Falcons have turned down some of our
(counterproposals). These are negotiations; this is how
negotiations go. The big sticking point is the signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: The Falcons likely are offering a bonus of around $6
million. Your agent said the recent signing bonus of $8.84 million
given by the Saints to No. 5 draft choice Ricky Williams is a
starting point. True?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I've given (five) years of service to the Falcons, and
all the bonus I've ever gotten is the $23,000 when I signed (as a
seventh-rounder in 1994). We did not create the market. I would be
ruining the market if I came in lower than (Williams). No matter
what we project (for him), he hasn't carried the ball yet. And
Edgerrin James (the No. 4 pick of the Colts) is going to get $9
million. Really, the signing bonuses the top rookies have
perpetuated (create) a bigger need for veteran signing bonuses to
increase.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Williams got the big money up front but has very low
salaries and needs to reach lofty incentives to earn sizable
salaries. If the Falcons were willing to increase the signing bonus
substantially, would you consider more of a play-for-pay contract?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: The numbers would have to be tremendous up front. I'm
not stupid. Let's be real. I play running back. How long can I
play?
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What about your image, considering all this is happening
while you are still under contract?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I have never said a word. If I was selfish, last year
I would have gone, `OK, guys, (to) hell with the NFC championship;
the Falcons need to re-sign me.' Check around the nation, and I
don't have a bad relationship with any writers except one. This is
like two guys who do the exact same job for IBM and Microsoft. Say
they're just as good as each other, but the guy at IBM is making
$30,000 a year and the guy at Microsoft is making $75,000. The guy
at IBM, wouldn't he try and go get more money?
</P>
<P>
   AJC: But what good is it to have your agent talking about lack
of good faith and pushing for a trade?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I don't want to be traded. I'm a Falcon. That's just
part of all this. You know how this goes; it's like a game. My
agent is inflaming things. He's doing a good job, but I think for
myself.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Is your absence doing any good?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I don't think this helps or hurts (negotiations). I
know the system like the back of my hand. I haven't ruled out
coming. This just happens to be where my mind is at right now.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Will you come to the mandatory portion of passing camp,
July 7-9? And what about training camp July 29?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I don't know what I'll do when it's mandatory. Every
day, I'm in a different mood. I know I miss my teammates. I talk to
(center Robbie) Tobeck, (defensive tackle) Travis (Hall) almost
every day. I've talked to (linebacker Keith) Brooking, (defensive
end) Chuck (Smith), (defensive tackle Ben) Huff, (offensive tackle)
Bob (Whitfield).
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What about coach Dan Reeves? He tried to call you earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: I haven't hooked up with Dan. I saw his funny comments
about my Web site and e-mail. Maybe I'll send him an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Do you trust in Dan?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: This is not that serious; I want everybody to see
that. I live here ... and people think I'm absolutely in love with
Salt Lake City. That's just not true. I love Atlanta, but I've
never felt stability there. And my (18-month-old) daughter is here.
In '95, I had to sign the minimum tender the Falcons offered, and
then in October of '96 they signed me to an extension that
increased my salary but had no bonus. ...In '97, going into the
last game (at Arizona), Dan said he was going to try to get (rookie
running back) Byron (Hanspard) more into the rotation to see if he
could carry the load. What's that say to me? It says I'm
expendable. That was a rocky year. I began to prepare myself for (a
possible departure). Dan and I went back and forth about carries,
rotation and so forth. If I sign a contract extension now, it will
be the first time I really felt like I was on solid ground. Then,
I'll move (to Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   AJC: So, you're on shaky ground with Reeves? You ran for 152
yards that day against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: Yeah, I was killing the Cardinals in the first
quarter, and to Dan's credit, he kept giving me the ball, and I was
able to get 1,000 yards for the season. I love playing for Dan. He
played the game and coaches it the way it's supposed to be played.
I've got jerseys from some of the guys, and a picture of Dan I'm
going to put on my wall, a Falcons Hall of Fame. I've got no
problem at all with Dan.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: So why aren't you working out in Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: The thing is, this is going to happen. This is just
the way these things go. Tomorrow, I'll wake up with a smile on my
face. It'll get done. I'm a Falcon, and I want to stay a Falcon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
