<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT &LR;      06-17 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PULL OF HOME OUTWEIGHS HAZARDS FOR KOSOVOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By IAN FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERMITCA, Kosovo _ Aid workers put up two big signs with red
skulls at the border here Thursday, and they are thinking about
showing a videotape of a cow exploding in a mine field. But
nothing, it seems, can dam the flow of Kosovo refugees: Ignoring
all dangers, more than 13,000 refugees on Thursday squeezed through
the crowded crossing point here on the way, finally, home.
</P>
<P>
   In just three days, 46,000 refugees have left Albania, to go to
their burned-out villages, where there is little food and a real
danger from mines, booby traps and unexploded bombs. That is a 10th
of the 450,000 Kosovo refugees in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed definitely caught us all by surprise,'' said Rupert
Colville, a spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``By jumping the gun they are making it more
difficult for themselves, more difficult for the people inside
Kosovo and, worst of all, putting themselves at great risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, you can understand why they are doing it,''
Colville added.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest example of the risks, an Albanian boy died on
Wednesday after plugging in a booby-trapped videotape player he
stole from a Serbian family that fled, NATO officials in Prizren
said Thursday. The machine was rigged with explosives.
</P>
<P>
   But the pull toward home is strong _ so strong, in fact, that no
one in the Maharremi family seemed at all nervous being driven back
over the border Thursday by Liridon, their 12-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I die, at least I will die there!'' barked Liridon from
behind the steering wheel, which reached the height of his
determined eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   The number of refugees crossing Thursday was lower than on
Wednesday, when 18,000 refugees went back to Kosovo, Colville said.
The number would have been higher, except that military officials
effectively closed the border around 6 p.m. to let traffic flow
into Albania from Kosovo. Starting Friday, the way into Kosovo will
be open from the early morning to the evening; at night, the road
will be open to traffic into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two days, the number of returning refugees has
created huge traffic jams on the road from here to the city of
Prizren, 15 miles away; one bottleneck at the town of Zhur is
caused by an enormous crater from a NATO bomb, maybe 15 feet deep,
that narrows the road.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic is also worsened by the number of Kosovo men who
left Albania over the last few days and are now returning to pick
up their families after looking over their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the house and it's all burned out,'' Rrustem Kicaj, a
50-year-old farmer from Grejkovce, said as he rode back into Kosovo
with his family. ``But I found my cows. I want to guard my house
and take care of the cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Colville said aid officials are trying whatever they can to
persuade refugees not to go home until NATO and other groups can
make Kosovo minimally habitable. A television crew filmed a cow as
it stepped on a land mine, and Colville said his agency is
considering showing the footage to refugees in the camps to deter
them from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from explosives, some officials are also worried about the
amount of food inside Kosovo. In Prizren, where nearly all the
refugees flow through on their way north, basic food supplies
disappear from shelves and shops by afternoon. Thursday morning,
Kosovars who had never left lined up downtown for food being
distributed by relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some food but we don't have any way to buy it,'' said
Nakie Morina, 28, who waited in line for an hour and a half for
food for her and her two children. But the food ran out before she
reached the front of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Di Lellio, a spokeswoman for the U.N. World Food Program,
said the flow of food into Kosovo has been slow, in part because of
the traffic out of Albania. But she said the agency is still
getting 7,000 loaves of bread into Kosovo every day, along with
canned meat and fish, wheat flour and rice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, the program is handing out huge rations
to refugees leaving Albania, including 110 pounds of wheat flour,
which she said will effectively bring large amounts of food into
Kosovo along with the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such an enormous influx of food,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But many refugees interviewed said they had not seen the relief
food and were traveling with very little. Rrustem, for example,
said he only had two loaves of bread for seven members of his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Hysen Sertoli, a 52-year-old construction worker, said he would
go to Kosovo ``with food or without food, no matter what happens.''
Traveling on a tractor with a sign praising NATO wedged between two
mattresses, he said he had been living in an apartment building in
Kukes, Albania, with 1,200 other refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Kosovars left,'' he said. ``So I left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
