<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-CAP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winning creates free-agent mess
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once a team makes it to the Super Bowl, as the Falcons
did last season, times get tougher for the team's bookkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Teams win big because players have big years, and then the
players ask for big compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams, Arizona and Baltimore, have more money under the
2000 salary cap than the Falcons' $23 million, but Atlanta general
manager Harold Richardson isn't dancing about those numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen projected starters have contracts that expire this
season, including 10 unrestricted free agents _ center Robbie
Tobeck, guard Gene Williams, receiver Terance Mathis, running back
Jamal Anderson, fullback Bob Christian, linebacker Jessie Tuggle,
defensive ends Chuck Smith and Lester Archambeau, defensive tackle
Shane Dronett and safety Eugene Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, I'd like to keep all of them, and is it possible?
Yes,'' said Richardson, who began managing salary caps when he was
administrative assistant to Broncos coach Wade Phillips in 1993.
``But herein lies the rub: All 10 of them aren't going to get what
they consider the giant contract. ...We can't pay them all the
market value.'' The Falcons have about $1.5 million under this
year's cap, enough to sign their rookies and have about $400,000
left. But it won't be enough to consider extending most of the
potential unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions are Tuggle, who will count more against the cap
than any of the Falcons at $3.85 million; Anderson, who is second
at $3.6 million; and perhaps Smith, at $2.8 million. Their numbers
are high enough that new contracts would drop their charges against
this year's cap.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is trying to get Anderson's contract extended, which
would create more than $1 million in additional cap room. That
could create room to maneuver with some of the lower-paid
unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Despite complaints from players that the Falcons have been slow
to begin contract talks, Richardson vows to get busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never finished a season with that many (potential free
agents),'' he said, ``and I don't anticipate finishing this season
with that many.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
