<SLUG> BC-NBA-FINALS-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New York's Sprewell plans to stay on attack
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ He played 46 minutes, took 24 shots, and yet the
Knicks' Latrell Sprewell did not get to the foul line once in Game
1 of the NBA Finals. That must change in tonight's Game 2 at the
Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was attacking, but their big guys made a difference,''
Sprewell said. ``You know their big guys are there. Their presence
definitely effected some shots. But that's not going to stop me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel I'm going to get to the basket. It's important to
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in Wednesday's game, whenever Sprewell got past the initial
defender, he was cut off by Tim Duncan or David Robinson before he
could elevate toward the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to keep attacking,'' Sprewell said. ``When
they block my shot, it just motivates me more to go back in there.
'You got me this time, but I'm coming back to get you.' But I've
got to go more aggressively. I think I need to go for the dunk at
times instead of layups. Take it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sprewell denied statements attributed to him in
``Sports Illustrated'' that he would not play for coach Jeff Van
Gundy next year and that he wanted to play in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say it,'' Sprewell said. ``And at this point in time,
it's all about winning a championship. My future is here. Anything
that could happen in the summer is so far from where my mind is.
I'm totally focused on the Knicks. I'm happy with the Knicks. I
want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston calling
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino took the Boston Celtics coaching job two years ago
because he believed the Celtics would get the first pick in the NBA
lottery and, therefore, the rights to Duncan. But San Antonio ended
up winning the pick and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not stop Pitino from seeking the top choice via
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five minutes after the lottery,'' San Antonio coach and
general manager Gregg Popovich said, ``Rick Pitino called. He said,
'What to you want (for the No. 1 pick)? Whatever it is, you've got
it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, 'I can't imagine doing anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Duncan's a Spur and widely considered the best player in
the NBA. The Celtics? They were in the lottery again this year.
Game 2 blues
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have tied an NBA record with 11 consecutive playoff
wins. But Game 2s have not been the best for San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' only postseason loss this season came against
Minnesota in Game 2 of the first round. And in Game 2 of each of
the next two rounds, the Spurs needed key baskets, by Duncan
against the Lakers and a Sean Elliott last-second 3-pointer against
Portland, to pull out victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we have problems with Game 2,'' Popovich
said. ``Maybe because there's so much emphasis put on Game 1 that
there's a letdown. But the only way to guard against it is to be
aware of it. We have to come out strong, like our backs are against
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
