</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SHORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR WARS WON'T ALL BE RISK-FREE, U.S. GENERAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The American general who ran the NATO air war over
Kosovo warned Thursday that it would be a mistake to think that
just because the allies lost no lives in this one that future wars
fought from the air would be risk-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid some people will draw lessons from this conflict,
and the shorter conflict in Bosnia in 1994 and 1995, and conclude
that you can conduct an air war without losses,'' Lt. Gen. Michael
C. Short said in a telephone interview from the allied air
operations center in Vicenza, Italy, where he ran the 78-day
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little stomach for young infantrymen and other
soldiers coming home in body bags, and it's very difficult to fight
any sort of ground conflict without having casualties,'' Short
said. ``There are some people who will continue to believe that
airstrikes are surgical, that casualties do not occur, and that you
can bring down an enemy without inflicting civilian casualties or
suffering losses yourself. We all know that not to be correct, but
some people will draw the wrong lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``I believe air power established itself in this
campaign,'' the general said on his last day in the operations
center before returning to peacetime duty as commander of the U.S.
16th Air Force in Aviano and of Allied Air Forces, Southern Europe,
in Naples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought Milosevic to the bargaining table,'' he said,
crediting sustained air attacks with getting President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia to withdraw 40,000 police, military and
paramilitary forces from Kosovo and let 50,000 NATO peacekeepers go
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO got every one of the terms it had stipulated in
Rambouillet and beyond Rambouillet,'' he said, referring to the
peace agreement negotiated in France that Milosevic had refused to
sign before the bombing began last March, ``and I credit this as a
victory for air power.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, he said, had suffered estimated damage of $40
billion from the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   American warplanes flew 60 percent of the 35,000 allied
missions, he said, and probably a higher percentage of the 10,000
bombing runs, because the United States had most of the planes and
most of the alliance's precision targeting equipment, using
satellite data to hit targets even in bad weather or at night.
</P>
<P>
   But superior American numbers also meant that when bombs went
off target and caused civilian casualties, they were bombs dropped
from American planes. ``It's pure percentage,'' he said. ``It was
just the odds. I'd like to give you a more scientific explanation,
but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can ever ensure that you will never make a
mistake, as long as there are human beings in the loop,'' he
observed, citing the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade by
an American B-2 stealth bomber on May 7. That resulted from an
intelligence error that misidentified the embassy site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to assure you that it never turns out that
something like that will happen again, but I can't,'' Short said.
All he could do, he said, was to promise that intelligence experts,
pilots and military commanders would do the best they could to
avoid making such mistakes in a future conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The New York Times in May, Short had hinted
at disagreement with the relative restraint of the first few days
of the bombing, when the main targets were Yugoslav anti-aircraft
defense systems and military targets, none of them initially close
to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had airmen been in charge, it would have been done
differently, but that's water under the bridge,'' he said Thursday.
``I felt that on the first night, the power should have gone off,
and major bridges around Belgrade should have gone into the Danube,
and the water should be cut off so that the next morning the
leading citizens of Belgrade would have got up and asked, `Why are
we doing this?' and asked Milosevic the same question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise in the campaign, he said, was the relative
ineffectiveness of the Serbian anti-aircraft missile defense
system, which had been reputed to be one of the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serb air defenses chose to survive, as opposed to fight,''
he said. ``They lost close to 700 surface-to-air missiles of
various types, but I venture to say that not more than a handful of
those were guided. That was reflective of their determination to
survive _ they didn't turn on the radar.''
</P>
<P>
   To guide SA-3 or SA-6 missiles to hit allied planes, the general
said, Serbian anti-aircraft crews would have had to keep guidance
radars turned on for a certain time, but the longer they did, the
easier it would have been for allied missiles to track the radar
signals and destroy the missile systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our analysis was that there weren't many Serb defenders
willing to die for Slobodan Milosevic,'' he said. ``My guess is
that they had talked to the Iraqis, and knew how effective we had
been against these systems during the Gulf War. We had air
superiority wherever we wanted, and whenever we wanted it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that would be the case in the next war, wherever that
is, is another question. ``Any would-be adversaries will certainly
analyze this campaign to see if we have weaknesses that they can
exploit,'' he concluded. ``I come out of this pretty pleased with
the way air power performed, both U.S. and NATO.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
