<HEADER>
A9896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-SERBS-ART-31     06-17 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-SERBS-ART-310&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB REFUGEES STREAMING OUT OF KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct art note; there is a photo, but no
graphic.)  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(bl) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERDARE, Yugoslavia _ A jumbled line of tractors, horse carts
and broken down tanks stretched for nearly six miles from Kosovo
into an adjoining part of Serbia on Thursday, bringing thousands
more displaced Serbs and a potentially troublesome burden for the
Belgrade government.
</P>
<P>
   All along the roads of southern Serbia, Kosovo Serbs have
arrived with household possessions piled on the roofs of their
cars, trundling slowly up the highway to Belgrade. Many have pulled
over to the shoulder to camp among the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents watched them pass, remembering previous tides of
Serbian refugees from other wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not happy about anything to do with this war,'' said
one resident of the town of Krusevac, who gave her name only as
Sanje and said she herself was a refugee from Bosnia. ``And now we
are seeing a lot of buses and cars of refugees. We feel nothing
good at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Belgrade government has played down the exodus of Serbs from
Kosovo on state television and has not offered any estimate of the
numbers of people fleeing. The Yugoslav Red Cross has counted some
40,000. NATO puts the number at 80,000 over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the actual number, they come in addition to about
70,000 other Serbs who fled Kosovo over the last two months of NATO
bombing. Where these people will live and work, whether they will
return to Kosovo, and how they will be fed and cared for are the
latest ripples of the Kosovo problem to confront Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's beleaguered government.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, many of the refugees say they have little doubt who
they blame for the debacle in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all Milosevic's fault,'' said Zlate Djordjevic, a lawyer.
``He gave everything to the Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Serbian refugees appear more resigned than angry, and
do not look likely to march on Belgrade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday, many huddled under plastic sheeting as a great thunder
storm broke overhead, drowning out their words. Asked where they
would go, most answered: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have no relatives to stay with are being directed to
collective centers in schools and public buildings. They are
joining tens of thousands of Serbian refugees from wars in Croatia
and Bosnia over the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Those previous waves Serbian refugees have ended up nearly
forgotten, living in depressed conditions throughout Serbia,
surviving on meager food handouts but mostly left to fend for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these new arrivals will be turning to the government for
food and shelter. Asked how they will survive, one said: ``We'll go
to the refugee center and register. We are not refugees, because we
are in our own country, but we'll be living on humanitarian aid.''
</P>
<P>
   The road just north of the border with Kosovo at Merdare was
blocked solid with new arrivals Thursday. Soldiers mingled with
peasant farmers, white collar workers from the cities and dozens of
Gypsy families.
</P>
<P>
   One young reservist named Slavise was still in his uniform but
accompanying his old mother out of Kosovo, where her family has
lived for centuries. He said he did not know where they would go,
but he said he knew he would not be going back.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Serbs and Albanians could live together after what had
happened over the last two months in Kosovo, he answered no.
</P>
<P>
   A group of other men gathered around him said they were fleeing
the Kosovo Liberation Army, but not their Albanian neighbors, and
said they would stay in Kosovo only if NATO could guarantee their
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not afraid of ordinary Albanians,'' said Djordjevic,
the lawyer. ``I will return in a few weeks I hope when it is more
secure.''
</P>
<P>
   But others, when pressed, said they thought they would never be
able to return. And asked if Albanians would nurture hatred for the
Serbs after what had happened in the last two months, the men stood
in glum silence.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Serbs offered various wild conspiracy theories about
what has gone wrong in Kosovo, but nearly all those leaving agree
on one thing _ that for whatever reason, the policies of recent
years have proved disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Most still blame the KLA and Albanian extremists who want
independence from Serbia. But they equally blame the leadership in
Belgrade for not crushing the separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Many at first try to deny that ``ethnic cleansing'' or any
organized killing of Albanian civilians occurred in Kosovo, but
when confronted with strong evidence even they admit that things
happened.
</P>
<P>
   A few not only admit that atrocities occurred, but agree that
such violence has forever made it impossible for Serbs to live in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have lived with our Albanian neighbors, but not with
the guerrillas,'' said Slobodan Filipovic, a storekeeper from
Prizren. ``I left my apartment keys with our Albanian neighbors.
They were crying. They wanted us to stay. They wanted to protect us
but they couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking dazed and weary, he sat at the wheel of a tiny Fiat car,
piled high with bedding and luggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not like it that the Albanians had to go, but they were
asking for independence for Kosovo and we were defending the
state,'' said his wife, Jovanka, a retired factory worker. But
asked if it was the violent campaign against the Albanians that had
precipitated their own exodus, she replied: ``Yes,'' nodding her
head firmly. ``Yes, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all this nationalism that was the cause of it all,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
