u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGAPORE-BANK-DEAL-N     06-17 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGAPORE-BANK-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS STOCK FALLS, SINGAPORE BANK DISAPPOINTS IRISH INVESTOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Japan, The Netherlands)   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ A major banking deal that at first looked like a
clear-cut victory in Singapore's effort to become a financial
center of Southeast Asia is now getting mixed reviews among
investors and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks ago, Allied Irish Banks PLC said it would buy
roughly 25 percent of Singapore's smallest bank, Keppel Tatlee Bank
Ltd., paying about $1.5 billion (Singapore) _ currently $880
million (United States) _ over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks announced the deal after Singapore's government
opened its financial industry to more foreign investment as part of
broader changes intended to make the banking industry more
transparent and competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In return for capital and expertise from Allied Irish, Ireland's
largest banking group, Keppel Tatlee stands to give its new partner
a base from which to exploit resurgent Asian financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But shares in Keppel Tatlee have fallen 7 percent since the
announcement, and the rating agency Standard &AMP; Poor's says it is
considering downgrading Allied Irish's credit to reflect its
expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest example of a push by Western banks to buy
a share of the market in Asia in anticipation of a new financial
landscape that many expect will come with recovery. Under these
assumptions, retail banking would take on greater importance than
corporate banking.
</P>
<P>
   American and European banks are seeking out cheap takeover
targets in the region, and Allied Irish was only one of several
European banks in recent weeks to bet on an Asian recovery.
Standard Chartered PLC of Britain has agreed to take control of a
bank in Thailand and another in Indonesia. ABN Amro of the
Netherlands has taken a majority stake in another Thai bank.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the Irish investment probably does not presage a
wholesale invasion of Singapore by foreign bankers. Instead, it is
likely to hasten a government-sanctioned consolidation among four
remaining local rivals as they steel themselves for more foreign
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger banks will have to re-examine their strategy and
ask themselves, `Can I compete with this smaller competitor with
deeper pockets?''' said Terry Chan, director of Standard &AMP; Poor's
office here.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Irish said when it announced the deal that it had opted
for a partner in Singapore rather than a bank elsewhere in the
region because of Singapore's relatively strong economy and
regulatory standards. ``If you want to get involved in the whole
region, you need to have a really solid base,'' Michael Buckley,
managing director of AIB Capital Markets, told reporters earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Singapore officials have been saying since the
Asian financial crisis began in 1997. Not only has Singapore been
spared much of the region's tumult but officials have also been at
pains to remind investors and traders that unlike some neighbors,
Singapore is freeing up its markets on its own initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, the authorities here began preparing for an
overhaul of what was a fairly protected and sleepy financial
system. Their aim is to make Singapore a financial center along the
lines of New York, London, Tokyo and Hong Kong. But that means
throwing the city open to foreign banks, with their more advanced
technology and bewildering blend of financial services.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare, Singapore's Monetary Authority is shaking up
insurers, mutual funds and securities markets. The government is
making banks disclose bad loans to shareholders for the first time.
The end to limits on foreign ownership has forced Singapore banks
to dismantle a class of shares for foreign investors that because
of their relative scarcity had typically traded at a premium to
local shares. Banks are now offering to swap every foreign share
for a slightly higher amount of common stock.
</P>
<P>
   More big news appears likely: Hinting at a tougher future, the
Monetary Authority's chairman, who is also a Deputy Prime Minister
and the son of Singapore's founding prime minister, Lee Kuan Yew,
has maintained that Singapore is only big enough for two local
banks.
</P>
<P>
   That the government-controlled Keppel Tatlee was the first to
experiment with foreign shareholdings came as only a mild surprise;
the bank's stock had sharply risen in the days leading up to the
Allied Irish announcement in expectation that it was a takeover
target. The bank was the product of a 1988 merger between the
Keppel Bank Ltd. and the Tat Lee Bank Ltd. It began discussions
with potential foreigner investors late last year and said it had
chosen Allied Irish because senior managers got along well.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, analysts say the specifics of the deal disappointed
investors. Allied Irish will buy just $350 million (Singapore) _ or
$205 million _ worth of Keppel Tatlee bonds paying 1 percent
annually. Attached to the bonds are warrants that can be used any
time in the next three years to buy 350 million Keppel Tatlee
shares for roughly $1.5 billion (Singapore).
</P>
<P>
   A higher price would presumably have made investors happier,
given that the new shares will dilute the value of existing stock.
There is also concern that warrants leave Allied Irish the option
of walking away, should the relationship sour, and beyond that,
there is talk of potential clashes between the managers of Allied
Irish and Keppel Tatlee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cultural change and I don't think the banks have a
willingness to experiment,'' said John Doyle, an analyst at Salomon
Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Asian nations' recovery is far from assured,
and the financial crisis has not left Keppel Tatlee and its
Singapore peers unscathed. Almost a quarter of the $30.3 billion
(Singapore) worth of outstanding loans by banks here to Southeast
Asian borrowers as of March was classified as nonperforming.
</P>
<P>
   Keppel Tatlee says it has its nonperforming loans under control,
having set aside more than enough to cover the $704 million
(Singapore) in bad debt it still has in Southeast Asia. Some
analysts say that the drop in the bank's stock price is temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Some local brokers said they like the new combination. Keppel
Tatlee ``looks a lot better with AIB as a partner than without,''
said David Lum, director of banking and strategy at
Prudential-Bache Securities Asia Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
