<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chastain gets some exposure
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERNARDS TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ The provocative skinsuit Brandi
Chastain displayed in a recent sportsgear magazine photo spread has
confirmed David Letterman's long-held belief that the U.S. women's
soccer team is ``Babe City.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the gap-toothed talk-show host invited Chastain onto his
show Wednesday, the starting left defender, with one of the lower
profiles on the team, wasn't sure how to gauge the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if `special' was the word, because it was like
being in an accident,'' Chastain said. ``I saw it coming but I
couldn't stop it, and I wasn't ready for it until it was over. I
was kind of shaking when I got off the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   While that might sound like a Jerry Springer moment, Chastain
also was charmed. ``It was exciting,'' she said. ``He was really
very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, 30, has been with the U.S. team since 1988, but hasn't
generated the attention of some of her teammates. She appeared in
the magazine with fellow Nike endorsers Gabrielle Reece and Michael
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to be in the kind of a magazine where I was
going to be exposing myself,'' she said. ``But I did tell my
parents maybe it wasn't such a good idea to show it to Grandma and
Grandpa.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost a sellout
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday morning, only 1,200 tickets remained for the
opening doubleheader at Giants Stadium, the U.S.-Denmark match at 3
p.m. and Brazil-Mexico at 5:30.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 76,516 tickets sold are in American hands, giving
the U.S. team an overwhelming home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   For the World Cup, more than 465,000 tickets have been sold, an
average of 27,000 for each of the 17 doubleheaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have as many spectators in our country for what we
will see here,'' Denmark coach Jorgen Hvidemose said, referring to
the crowd his team have to contend with on Saturday. ``They don't
all have to come to one game, do they?''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's twinbill in San Jose _ co-favorite China
against Sweden and Japan facing Canada _ has sold between 18,000 to
20,000, with Spartan Stadium holding 26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican team a 'curiosity'
</P>
<P>
   His team might be one of the biggest longshots in the World Cup,
but Mexico coach Leo Cuellar thinks his first-time qualifiers have
scaled a notable obstacle in a country where soccer is considered a
male pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are something of a curiosity,'' Cuellar said. He and nearly
half his roster live in the United States, primarily Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican soccer federation formed a women's team only last
year, and Cuellar quickly infused it with U.S.-based talent.
Captain Laurie Hill was a star at UC-Santa Barbara, and forward
Monica Gerardo is Notre Dame's all-time scoring leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico is the weakling in a tough Group B field that
includes Germany, Italy and Brazil, their opponent Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
