<HEADLINE>
EISNER REACHES OUT TO RALLY RANK AND FILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Buck up, Mouseketeers.
</P>
<P>
   That was the essence of an uncommon, corporatewide e-mail sent
out Thursday to employees of The Walt Disney Co. by Chairman
Michael Eisner, the Los Angeles Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, saying he was taking on the role of company cheerleader,
said he sent out the message partly to counteract the
higher-than-normal amount of negative publicity that the
entertainment giant has received recently. He told employees they
should focus on the positive and stressed strong prospects for
``Tarzan,'' the studio's 37th animated movie, which opens
nationwide today.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, who has headed Disney since 1984, also indicated he
would now regularly send e-mail messages to employees across the
company. Officials at Burbank-based Disney refused to comment on
the e-mail or release a copy of Eisner's letter, but portions of
the note was read to the Daily News by several Disney employees who
requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Good news has been rare at Disney recently. Earlier this month,
Eisner imposed a corporatewide hiring freeze and tightened the use
of temporary workers. He ordered a cost-savings review in late
April after Disney reported a 30percent drop in quarterly profits.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, meanwhile, has been harping on Eisner over the
performance of Disney shares, which are down 29percent from their
all-time high of $42.375 set in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is one of 30 companies that comprise the Dow Jones
industrial average, the nation's most heavily watched stock market
index.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Eisner is under growing pressure to boost Disney's
stock price due to strong performances by rival entertainment
conglomerates and other blue chip companies. His sterling
reputation _ which was built on the impressive run-up of Disney
shares in the middle of the decade _ has been hurt by the stock's
slide.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he was the nation's top-paid corporate executive, as
he cashed more than $500million in options. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-MIAHAMM18-COX     06-17 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MIAHAMM18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. team's self-effacing Hamm magnet for spotlight
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERNARDS TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ Ask Mia Hamm about soccer, her friends
on the U.S. national team and the Women's World Cup, and you'll
discover a straightforward young woman who says all the right
things and presents herself in stark contrast to the crude profile
of the American sports superstar these days.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her about herself, and the phenomenon that has sprung up
around her as the glamour girl for her sport, and her face quickly
flushes red with embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to outgoing personalities, Hamm can't hold a
candle to some of the others around her. For an outpouring of
gutty, inspiring resilience, there's 33-year-old veteran Michelle
Akers. Midfielder Julie Foudy, the glib, merry prankster, has
yukked it up with comedy talk show hosts Conan O'Brien and Craig
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   And for sheer outrageous behavior, try topping goalkeeper Briana
Scurry, who lost a bet at the 1996 Olympics and dashed naked down a
street in Athens in the middle of the night after the Americans won
the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a soccer player, and I really don't do much else,'' Hamm
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the three years since the U.S. women electrified a packed
Sanford Stadium, Hamm's impact has moved far beyond the field,
where she recently established an international record with 109
goals and counting. The 27-year-old forward has become a largely
media-driven icon for a sport that was virtually unknown to the
American sports public.
</P>
<P>
   Considered the most marketable female athlete in the country, as
determined by a sports marketing survey last year, Hamm accepts her
role for the sake of promoting women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it comes to certain aspects of her game, Hamm is
uncomfortable talking about herself, particularly when she went
through an eight-game goalless streak that finally ended in a 7-0
rout of Japan last month in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's 87 assists are an American record, and she's just as
adept at lofting a delicate cross for a teammate in scoring
position as she is putting on the finishing touches herself. After
the U.S. lost to China in April, she expressed displeasure with her
defensive effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very passionate player,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said
earlier this week. ``You see her true personality come out on the
soccer field.''
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the burden
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. prepares for its World Cup opener Saturday against
Denmark, newspaper and magazine articles have recounted at length
Hamm's legendary yearning for privacy. On Thursday morning at the
team's training ground, she spent half an hour patiently answering
questions she has heard dozens of times before. When they veer
toward the internal, she backpedals, especially when queried about
why she rose so quickly to sports celebrity status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Hamm said, her voice trailing off, searching
for a more communal reply. ``People have rallied around this team.
There's something great here. So many young girls play soccer, and
it's great that they can grow up and want to be like Julie Foudy or
Michelle Akers or Kristine Lilly. We didn't have that, and I think
it's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the Olympics, it was Hamm that caught Madison Avenue's
eye. People magazine dubbed her one of its ``50 Most Beautiful
People.'' That spawned a host of product endorsements, most notably
Nike, which has used her girl-next-door image to soften some of its
own hard edges and go after legions of teen-age girls who shriek
her name after catching a glimpse of her firsthand. Hamm, like her
teammates, earns a living primarily from endorsements and pulls
down somewhere between $500,000 and $1 million annually, far and
away tops among female athletes in team sports.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Nike unveiled a new building on its Beaverton,
Ore., campus bearing Hamm's name _ and larger than the one
constructed in honor of Michael Jordan. Naturally, she shuddered at
the attention. ``It was never a goal to have a building named after
me,'' Hamm said, sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   More than just one player
</P>
<P>
   Hamm, the daughter of an Air Force colonel and the wife of a
U.S. Marine Corps pilot currently on duty in Asia, volunteers
little about her life away from soccer. She has a 12-handicap in
golf and established a foundation in memory of her adopted brother
Garrett, who died of a blood disease in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It was Garrett Hamm who introduced his younger sister to soccer,
and, as the family moved around, it became her most abiding
constant, even though she played other sports.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent series of Gatorade commercials she challenges Jordan
to one-on-one duels in such sports as fencing, running, and karate.
In the last sequence, Hamm gets the last laugh, throwing Jordan
over her shoulder and onto the mat flat on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they even bring up the glamor,'' Hamm said.
``And that's what I like about them.''
</P>
<P>
   She also revels in her teammates getting on camera. When
defender Brandi Chastain returned to the team hotel Wednesday after
appearing on David Letterman's show, Hamm was ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said to me, `You were just awesome,' `` Chastain said.
``It's good for Mia to sit back and enjoy what we've been enjoying
all these years, which is seeing our sport promoted in a positive
way.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the lens gazing away from her, if only for a moment.
The World Cup will unfold over the next month, and Hamm hopes the
spotlight on women's soccer will be much bigger than the one that
has been enveloping her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tournament is a success on its own because there are so
many great personalities on these teams, so many great players,''
Hamm said. ``It wouldn't have gotten as big as it has because of
just one player.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
