<SLUG> BC-SIEMENS-FUJITSU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIEMENS AND FUJITSU TO JOIN EUROPEAN COMPUTER UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Hoping to close the gap with bigger
American computer rivals, Siemens of Germany and Fujitsu of Japan
said Thursday they that would combine their European computer
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The new entity, with total annual revenue of more than $6
billion, would rank as the world's fifth-largest computer maker
after Compaq, Dell Computer, IBM and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Fujitsu and Siemens said they hoped to cut expenses, mainly by
obtaining more bargaining power with suppliers and by spreading
research and development costs over a broader base. The deal also
gives Fujitsu access to a better distribution network in Europe,
which it has long needed.
</P>
<P>
   For Siemens, of Munich, the move represents the latest step in a
corporate overhaul aimed at streamlining the company. Siemens is
currently spinning off its semiconductor business, with annual
revenue around $3.5 billion, through a public stock offering early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   It is also pushing deeper into the Internet business, having
recently reached agreements to acquire three young American
software companies.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens appears to be contributing far more to the deal than
Fujitsu. Its computer division has about $4.2 billion in annual
sales and 8,000 employees, while Fujitsu Computers Europe has sales
of $2.1 billion and 1,600 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies glossed over the apparent imbalance, suggesting
that Fujitsu had contributed more valuable assets and has a
stronger focus on information technology.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich von Pierer, chairman of Siemens, had originally hoped
to sell Siemens' personal computer business to Acer of Taiwan. But
that deal fell through last year, when the Asian financial crisis
forced Acer to back out.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal could help Siemens achieve enough volume to keep up
with bruising price competition. Siemens, though the biggest
personal computer manufacturer in Germany, produced only 1.5
million units last year. The combined entity plans to produce more
than four million.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens and Fujitsu also sell a fairly broad range of other
equipment, from computer networks and servers to big mainframe
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has generated meaningful profit from computers, said
Frank Alexander Rothauge, head of the technology group at
Oppenheimer &AMP; Co. here.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the merger should strengthen their ability to
make money even as computer prices come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantages are mainly on the cost side,'' Rothauge said.
``The challenge is really to make use of the scale in order to
actually reduce costs of purchasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts had speculated that Siemens might simply sell its
entire computer business, and there were some signs that investors
were disappointed that such a divestiture had not taken place.
Siemens shares, after surging to a record high of 73.30 euros in
midday trading here, settled back to close at 71.45 euros, up 1.59
percent. Reaction was far more positive for Fujitsu shares, which
rose 110 yen, or 5 percent, in Tokyo to a record 2,290 yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an exit strategy for Siemens _ it is quite the
opposite,'' von Pierer said.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies predicted that the new venture would increase
annual sales to about $8 billion in the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
