A9904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTES18-CO     06-17 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech teammates have rough 1st-round start
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ So much for Kooch-mania.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Matt Kuchar's second U.S. Open isn't the smile festival
it became a year ago at the Olympic Club. The 20-year-old former
U.S. Amateur champion from Georgia Tech started Thursday's first
round with a double-bogey 6, found himself 5-over par after five
holes and was fortunate to eventually finish at 6-over 76.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of Tech's collegiate season, teammate Bryce Molder found
himself in a better position at Pinehurst No. 2. Playing in his
first pro event, Molder, 20, who made the field from the East Lake
qualifier, followed his front-nine 40 with a 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still around where I can make the cut,'' said Kuchar, of
Lake Mary, Fla., who tied for 14th at last year's U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't shoot myself out of it,'' said Molder, of Conway,
Ark., who spent most of the college season as the nation's
top-ranked men's player, ``and I did the first nine holes. But I
played really great the last six or seven holes.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``quitting on a 6-iron'' from 182 yards at the 485-yard
eighth hole and eventually making double-bogey on a missed 4-foot
putt, Molder regrouped with birdies at 14 and 15, on approaches of
6 and 9 feet, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Molder said he did not experience the nervousness he
anticipated, aided by the presence of teammate/roommate Wes Latimer
of Woodstock on his bag. Both players beat Kuchar by five shots at
the recent NCAA Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably played as many rounds with Wes as anyone the
last two years,'' Molder said.
</P>
<P>
   Molder said he isn't paying Latimer, who volunteered his
services, ``but I got his hotel and most of his dinners.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else playing No. 2 Thursday in soft,
scoring-friendly conditions, Kuchar realized an opportunity
squandered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever a day to take advantage of the course, this
was it,'' Kuchar said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Tech players fared better Thursday, with David Duval
sharing the lead at 3-under 67 and Duluth's Stewart Cink in decent
position with a 72. The normally straight-driving Cink hit only six
of 14 fairways.
</P>
<P>
   ``My driver was really off,'' he said. ``I hit the fairway with
all the clubs other than my driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus out of focus
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus' chances to make the cut at age 59 basically ended
with the rains came Wednesday. On a soft, longer Pinehurst No. 2,
Nicklaus, still regaining his strength after January hip
replacement surgery, was outmatched and shot a 78. ``Guys are
hitting 8- and 9-irons and I'm hitting 2 and 3 irons,'' Nicklaus
said. ``I guess I'm getting some of my own medicine. I had it the
other way for years.'' Teeing off at 7:20 a.m. on an overcast day,
Nicklaus ``couldn't see at all'' and typically has a problem with
low light. ``My caddie read my putts on the first three greens,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly...
</P>
<P>
   Colin Montgomerie was justifiably irked when after birdieing the
last two holes for 72 and showing up in the interview area, he was
asked, ``What did you shoot?'' (Most reporters consider it
insulting to the player not to have that information in their
possession). ``Is that the first question? What did I shoot? That's
the best one yet.'' Later, he said, ``Could you believe that? What
if I'd shot 80?'' ... On the rainy morning weather, Monty said,
``In fact, the weather's better in Scotland, and warmer.'' ...
Tiger Woods has had better driving days. He missed one fairway on
the front nine with a 4-iron. ... Jose Maria Olazabal's wayward
driver reappeared, accounting for nine missed fairways in a 75. ``I
hit the ball all over the place,'' said the Masters champ, ``and
there's no way you can score like that.'' ... Mark O'Meara's caddie
this week is his instructor, Hank Haney. They combined for a 71
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
