<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-2006-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING 2006 OLYMPIC SITE A SOMBER EVENT AFTER REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No champagne and caviar this time. No calfskin luggage, no
Waterford keepsakes, no five-figure ``humanitarian aid'' offers
from jostling bid cities. And no more balloting that resembles the
1924 Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   When the International Olympic Committee convenes in Seoul
Friday to choose the site of the 2006 Winter Games from among six
European candidates, it will do so without the lavish lobbying that
the Lords of the Rings have come to regret -- and with only two
options to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the handout scandal surrounding Salt Lake City's
2002 bid, with its expulsions, resignations and worldwide calls for
reform, the IOC banned its members from visiting candidate cities
and stopped cities from giving them anything more than trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any kind of gifts, any kind of bribes,'' Marco San
Pietro, international relations director for the Turin bid
committee, said by phone Thursday from Seoul. ``Everything is
forbidden. You can't even give a pen.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time in its history, the IOC is allowing
outsiders to help choose a host city. A special 15-member
``selection college,'' including three athletes and two
representatives from the winter sports federations and national
Olympic committees, will narrow the field from the six bidders
(Sion, Switzerland; Turin; Helsinki; Klagenfurt, Austria; Zakopane,
Poland and Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia) to two finalists. Then, shortly
after midnight in the United States, the full IOC will choose the
victor.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new system, which the IOC says is experimental, is
designed to limit the suspicious horse-trading between bidders and
members that marked previous elections, it has undeniable flaws. It
gives a distinct advantage to Sion, which hosted dozens of IOC
members when it was bidding for the 2002 Games. And it forces
voters to rely for information on hour-long presentations, a report
from the IOC's site evaluation commission and on piles of brochures
and CD-ROMs (``virtual visits'') from cities they've never seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you fall in love with a lady without seeing her, just by
reading a book about her?'' complained Vitaly Smirnov, an IOC
member from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The travel ban fell hardest on Klagenfurt, which is offering a
unique ``bid without borders'' that includes nearby venues in Italy
and Slovenia. ``Some IOC members think we have very long
distances,'' says bid leader Michael Ausserwinkler. ``It would have
been fantastic to show them that a citizen of Klagenfurt leaves his
job at 5 o'clock and at 6 he is eating dinner in Slovenia.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Sion is the clear favorite, observers have been
whispering about a possible anti-Swiss backlash directed at Marc
Hodler, the IOC member from Switzerland who fueled the scandal in
December by claiming that at least a quarter of his colleagues had
been taking payoffs from bid cities for years.
</P>
<P>
   But the most obvious backlash is being directed at the
Americans, whom some members accuse of creating the worst scandal
in IOC history by seducing them with cash and gifts then demanding
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem inherent to corruption was born from people of
Salt Lake City,'' said IOC member Mario Vasquez Rana of Mexico.
``I'm sorry to say this is something that comes from that wonderful
country, the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporter Indira Lakshmanan contributed to this report
from Seoul.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2148EDT &QL; 
