<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JUNE 18
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-POPE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June
16, about Pope John Paul II's recollections of Jewish friends in
his hometown, Wadowice, Poland, and their suffering in World War II
misstated the name of a boyhood friend in some copies. He was Jerzy
Kluger, not Jurek Kruger.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BUSH-CONN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 15,
about Gov. George W. Bush's Presidential campaign referred
imprecisely to a response by Elizabeth Dole to his comments about
who should be appointed to judgeships. After Mr. Bush said that
opposition to abortion would not be a litmus test for judicial
nominees if he became President, a spokesman for Mrs. Dole said her
appointees would have to share her ``general philosophy.'' The
spokesman explained that although Mrs. Dole opposed abortion except
in cases of incest, rape or danger to the pregnant woman's life,
the candidate had not specifically cited abortion as an issue on
which she and an appointee would have to agree.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incorrectly to Mrs. Dole's attitude
toward Mr. Bush's stance. Her spokesman said Mrs. Dole did not
criticize Mr. Bush's position, but agreed with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
