<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS PRODS HOLBROOKE AND RECEIVES A CONCESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse
Helms said Thursday that he believed that Richard Holbrooke,
President Clinton's nominee as chief diplomat to the United
Nations, had ``violated the law several times.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long-awaited showdown on Capitol Hill between the
conservative senator and the longtime diplomat, Holbrooke tried to
satisfy Helms by quickly apologizing to the Senate and
acknowledging that his carelessness had led to ``misconceptions''
about his ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials suggested that Holbrooke's contrition
might have rescued his nomination. Other senators on the panel,
Democrats and Republicans alike, expressed support for Holbrooke on
Thursday as his confirmation hearings began.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination, announced a year ago, has been stalled by
allegations that Holbrooke skirted federal ethics laws in his
revolving-door career between the State Department and Wall Street.
Just as things appeared to be looking up for him, another senator
announced that he would temporarily block any vote on the
nomination on the Senate floor as a result of a controversy
involving the suspension of a State Department employee at the U.S.
mission to the United Nations, Linda Shenwick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not against Mr. Holbrooke,'' said the lawmaker, Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who is seeking Ms. Shenwick's
reinstatement. ``This is a message to the State Department. Linda
Shenwick is a patriotic public servant trying to do her job and
exposing a lot of things that are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms, R-N.C., who is the Senate's most outspoken critic of the
United Nations, has left unclear what he would ultimately do with
Holbrooke's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The senator had left open the possibility that he would kill the
nomination through procedural tactics even though Holbrooke appears
to enjoy widespread _ except for Helms _ possibly unanimous support
on the Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials said Thursday that Holbrooke's
willingness to concede that he should have been ``much more
sensitive'' to appearances of conflict of interest might have
satisfied Helms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the law and I was careful to follow it,'' Holbrooke
said. ``But I should have been more sensitive, much more sensitive,
to the appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With regret,'' he added, ``I must say that carelessness on
occasion on my part contributed to these misconceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke also committed himself to making the streamlining of
the United Nations, the senator's longstanding goal, ``my highest
sustained priority.'' Holbrooke described himself as ``a hard-line
hawk on the issue of bureaucratic bloat, whether it's in Washington
or New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his remarks after Helms had opened the hearing with a
lengthy attack on what he described as Holbrooke's failure to
adhere to ethics laws that bar former officials from trying to
profit off their government work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time and again, the evidence shows Mr. Holbrooke either chose
not to seek ethics advice or to ignore it when it was given,'' the
senator said, facing Holbrooke across the witness table. ``I agree
that you have served with distinction, and certainly with
sincerity. But I also believe that it's apparent that you have
violated the law several times.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his nomination was announced last June, Holbrooke
became the subject of an ethics investigation by the Justice
Department and the State Department inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry, prompted by an anonymous letter, ended in February,
when Holbrooke agreed to pay $5,000 to settle civil charges that he
had violated a law that bars former government officials from
lobbying their former colleagues for a year, a so-called
cooling-off period.
</P>
<P>
   After Holbrooke's remarks, Helms said, ``I believe we're getting
somewhere.'' ``The most important thing that the nominee has said
this morning is, in effect, that he has made some mistakes and
regrets that,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley's threat to hold up the nomination was a surprise to
the State Department, which had no comment on the move. In the
past, the department has described Ms. Shenwick, the employee at
the U.N. mission, as insubordinate, and she has been told that she
is being suspended from her duties as of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Victoria Toensing, said Ms. Shenwick had exposed
waste and fraud at the United Nations and in the mission. ``They're
getting rid of a whistle-blower,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
