<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATIONS ON THE ROLE OF RUSSIA INTENSIFY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ With the key issue of the distribution of
Russian forces in Kosovo still unsettled, American and Russian
negotiators returned to the table on Thursday night, with orders to
work through the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian defense minister, Igor D. Sergeyev, and the foreign
minister, Igor S. Ivanov, told their American counterparts early
Thursday evening that they would return to Moscow for consultations
on Thursday night. But they were persuaded instead to press ahead
with work on a complex agreement defining Russia's role in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sees the outcome as a test of its standing as an
independent albeit weakened player on the world stage. For NATO,
Russia's integration into the security force is a test of its
ability to manage a tenuous peace in a province wracked by violence
and hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are under pressure to resolve the issue before this
weekend's summit meeting in Cologne, Germany, which will be
attended by leaders of the seven major industrial nations and by
President Boris Yeltsin of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they decided to stay is encouraging,'' said the
Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, speaking to reporters outside
the Presidential Palace, where the two delegations have been
holding talks for two days.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Yeltsin said he had instructed Sergeyev to stick to a
demand for a Russian sector in Kosovo, where allied forces have
been steadily increasing their presence as Serbian troops pull out.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials, negotiating on behalf of NATO, have
rejected a separate Russian sector, fearing a de facto partition of
Kosovo. In their latest proposal, the Americans reportedly offered
an alternative that would distribute Russian troops in sectors
already controlled by the United States, France, Germany, Italy and
Britain. The number of Russian troops has not yet been decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been putting forward different ideas, all designed to
meet our `red lines,''' said James Rubin, the spokesman for
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who arrived here on
Thursday. Those red lines, he said, include a unified command
structure, with Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain, the commander
of the allied troops, holding ``ultimate authority.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Russian news reports, one compromise may involve
having a senior Russian officer serve in the force's top command.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Thursday evening, Ivanov said Russia was
not looking for special treatment but for parity with the other
members of the force, which was approved by the U.N. Security
Council earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a rope-pulling competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia caught the allies off guard last week with a sudden
deployment of 200 troops at the airport outside Pristina, the
capital of Kosovo. The Russians had been ordered from Bosnia, where
they are serving with the peacekeeping force there, by the Russian
General Staff. According to Russian news reports, Yeltsin approved
the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president made it perfectly clear that Russia
favors equality and equal participation in the peacekeeping
operations,'' Ivanov said. ``The only conditions we have are the
same conditions as the other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said the negotiations had already produced an
``understanding'' on two key issues: a unified command structure
and the distribution of functions at the Pristina airport.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would publicly outline the interim agreements. But
a Clinton administration official described the tentative agreement
on a unified command structure as ``very analogous'' to the
arrangement in Bosnia, where 1,300 Russian troops serve in a sector
that is under American command.
</P>
<P>
   But, the official cautioned, everything will depend on the
contents of the final agreement. ``There is a command on top, and
command on the technical level,'' he said. ``Until you work out the
geography of deployment, you haven't worked out anything on the
technical level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These talks are military, not political,'' he added. ``Until
you get all of it done, you have no agreement. That's why half a
loaf is no loaf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
