<HEADER>
A9914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-17 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Russia: IMF Measure Rejected
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The lower house of Parliament rejected a proposed
gasoline tax, a linchpin of an economic reform package that the
International Monetary Fund has sought as a condition for resuming
loans to the near-bankrupt government. The 291-101 defeat raised
questions about whether any form of a gas tax could be passed this
year; however, IMF officials indicated this week that they might
approve new loans even if the bulk of the economic overhaul stalls
in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: `Bloody Sunday' Anonymity
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ The High Court ruled that 17 soldiers due to appear
before a judicial inquiry into the ``Bloody Sunday'' killings of 14
unarmed Catholic civil rights demonstrators in Londonderry in 1972
could remain publicly anonymous. The soldiers had protested a
decision ordering them to identify themselves, saying it might
expose them to retaliation. The inquiry is a review of a speedy and
widely disparaged investigation the same year that exonerated the
paratroopers and faulted the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland: Body Search Lags
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bertie Ahern said police were scaling back their
search for the remains of eight people executed as traitors and
buried in the 1970s and '80s by the IRA. Acting on information
provided by the IRA, police have been digging in several areas, but
have found only one body. The action by the IRA, which has refused
appeals to provide additional details, was widely seen as a
backfired attempt to improve its image and that of its political
wing, Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Progress on Slave Workers
</P>
<P>
   Just a week after lawyers for Holocaust victims walked out of
talks with German industry over a fund to compensate Nazi-era slave
workers, American and German officials said they were again making
progress. ``We restored the trust that had been somewhat
fractured,'' said Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat. German
officials said U.S. lawyers appeared to have agreed on the need to
shield companies from further litigation after the fund was under
way.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: 36 New Pinochet Charges
</P>
<P>
   Judge Baltasar Garzon added 36 new charges of torture against
Gen. Augusto Pinochet, making a total of 108. The former Chilean
dictator has been under house arrest in London since October on
Garzon's warrant, and extradition hearings are set for Sept. 27 in
London to determine if he must stand trial in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Human Rights Furor
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups criticized Arturo Montiel, the gubernatorial
candidate in the state of Mexico from the governing party, known as
the PRI, for saying ``human rights are for humans, not for rats,''
in a campaign ad pledging a harsh crackdown on crime. ``The rats
are in the PRI,'' responded Jose Luis Duran, the candidate of
National Action, a pro-business party. Montiel holds a modest lead
over Duran three weeks before the July 4 vote. The state, which
surrounds the capital, is Mexico's most populous, with 11 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   East Timor: U.N.'s Costs
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. spent $52.5 million on its mission in East Timor
between May 5 and Aug. 31, Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in a
report to the General Assembly. That covers the cost of recruiting
242 international officials, 425 volunteers, 274 civilian police,
50 military liaison officers and some 3,645 local agents involved
in an Aug. 8 referendum in which some 400,000 people will be asked
to choose between independence and autonomy under Indonesia. What a
U.N. official called ``concerns about security'' could still delay
the vote, but Annan's spokesman said no decision to delay had been
made.
</P>
<P>
   India, Bangladesh: New Bus Service
</P>
<P>
   India and Bangladesh signed an agreement to start a direct bus
service between Calcutta and Dhaka. Service will start on June 29,
with buses running six times a week between each city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
