A9915 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES18-CO     06-17 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astrodome's plate eats up two Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A hard home plate area at the Astrodome has taken its
toll on Braves first basemen this series, resulting in injuries to
Randall Simon and Brian Hunter after sliding to score.
</P>
<P>
   The more serious injury is Hunter's sprained ankle, which got
caught on the plate as he slid home in the sixth inning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no top layer of dirt,'' Hunter said. ``It's like
cement with a plate in the middle of it.''
</P>
<P>
   X-rays taken Thursday on Hunter were negative, and he said he
might return in a couple days. Manager Bobby Cox isn't quite as
optimistic. ``I wanted to play him against (Arizona left-handers
Omar) Daal and (Randy) Johnson,'' Cox said. ``But I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the disabled list is a possibility unless Hunter heals
significantly in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter started Wednesday's game over Simon against the
right-handed Sean Bergman because Simon had a sore knee from his
slide home Tuesday when he scored on a Craig Biggio error. Simon
was back in the lineup Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   So long, `Eighth Wonder'
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a possible postseason trip here, Thursday
was the Braves' last game in the Astrodome, which opened in 1965 as
the ``Eighth Wonder of the World,'' the first domed stadium in
baseball. The artifical surface here is where the term
``Astroturf'' originated.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will move into Enron Stadium, a new open-air facility
with a grass field and a retractable roof, in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as domes go, I've always enjoyed playing here,'' Cox
said. ``It really was a spectacle when it first opened, with the
scoreboard (fireworks) _ it was rocking and rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are 144-142 at the Astrodome, including 7-2 when the
Braves franchise was in Milwaukee and 38-16 since 1991. Two
pitchers who'll be sorry to see it go are Tom Glavine and Greg
Maddux. In 10 starts here since Sept. 1991, Glavine is 8-0 with a
1.35 ERA. In his career, Maddux is 9-3 in the Astrodome with a 1.85
ERA in 16 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Boone's progress
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone, who has seen his batting average dip from .288 to
.257 in June, ended an 0-for-20 streak with a double his first time
up Wednesday. It was one hit in five at-bats on the night but he
had another two hard hit balls caught in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough stretch for me,'' Boone said. ``My swing got
a little long for some reason, but I don't feel that way now.''
</P>
<P>
   To help shorten his swing again, Boone said he approached every
pitch like it was coming with two strikes against him.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ozzie Guillen has started at shortstop for injured Walt
Weiss, his batting average has climbed from .152 to .210, helped by
his three hits Wednesday. ... Maddux's 2-for-3 night at the plate
Wednesday was his second multi-hit game of the year. He was 2-for-3
April 6 against the Phillies, including one of his two home runs
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
