<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars' Hull returns to lineup, sees limited action
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Brett Hull, who presumably has a groin injury, returned
to the lineup for the Dallas Stars Thursday night, but skated only
on the team's fourth line with Benoit Hogue and Brian Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said before the game that Hull ``is
not 100 percent but he's a heck of a lot better than he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Hull, who missed Game 4, could not skate a full
shift because, ``It's an easy game when you're on the move all the
time. But the way these two teams play, the game is not played on
the move. There's a lot of stop and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Hitchcock clearly is getting all the questions about
his team's injuries, most of which have centered on Dallas's
refusal to publicly confirm that Mike Modano is playing with a
fractured hand.
</P>
<P>
   Following Thursday's skate-around, Hitchcock began to answer a
reporter's question with, ``You're assuming it's just a groin.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: ``Yeah, you're right. I shouldn't assume anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock: ``You're right. You just answered the question. You
shouldn't assume anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: ``Is there more than that?''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock: ``He might have a shoulder, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Postscript: Fox TV analyst John Davidson said Hull also was
wearing a knee brace. But we won't assume that.
</P>
<P>
   Sneak peak
</P>
<P>
   Dixon Ward has been one of Buffalo's best players in the
post-season (7 goals, five assists, plus-seven in 19 games). But
Ward came very close to being in Nashville this year, as one of the
players left unprotected during the expansion draft. The Predators
instead opted for defenseman Bob Boughner. Ward may be left
unprotected for the Thrashers June 25, but his age (30) and
contract status (one year remaining) could lead general manager Don
Waddell elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said of Ward: ``Obviously we thought
there would be a chance he would be taken (by Nashville). It's
going to happen again this year. Dixon has been a good player for
us and we're going to lose another good player. We didn't want to
lose Bob Boughner. He was kind of the heart and soul in the back
end for us. But obviously with young guys coming (up), you have got
to expose guys who you think in a year or two may not be here any
more, guys who are going to become unrestricted free agents,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt players resented the expansion draft, Ruff
said, ``I think the players understand expansion means more jobs.
Although you're losing a teammate, players look at it that another
30 jobs have been created and two years from now another 60 jobs.
Instead of players playing four or five years, they'll probably
stretch it to eight or nine. In that sense players are happy about
expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   This was the 16th time in Stanley Cup Finals history the teams
were tied at 2-2. In the previous 15, the team that won Game 5 won
the series 12 times. The last time a team bucked the trend came in
1971, when Montreal lost the fifth game to Chicago but won the next
two. ... Buffalo's Dominik Hasek and Dallas's Ed Belfour are the
first two finals goalies in the expansion era (since 1967) to both
have sub 2.00-goals against averages through the entire playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
