Berry/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ATLANTA -- June 17, 1999 -- FOOD-FATHERS-1-COX, 06-17 --
A bison burger made by Kevin Rathbun of the restaurant Nava. Based
in Atlanta, U.S. Bison, a company Ted Turner founded in 1997, has
signed the services of the well-known Atlanta chef to develop
recipes and offer culinary advice to chefs and home cooks on using
the unfamiliar bison products. (William Berry/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ALPHARETTA, Ga. -- June 17, 1999 -- RECLINERS-2-COX,
06-17 -- Rob Mehal relaxing in a Catnapper recliner with his
one-year-old son, Maddux. To his left is a La-Z-Boy and to his
right is a Benchcraft recliner. Today, the trend in recliners is
toward smaller-scale chairs that don't look like recliners and that
don't take up as much space as the room-eating monsters of a decade
ago. (Phil Skinner/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ALPHARETTA, Ga. -- June 17, 1999 -- RECLINERS-1-COX,
06-17 -- Allen Williams, a 46-year-old advertising salesman,
testing Catnapper's leather-like recliner, complete with heated
massage, speakerphone and storage units. He and his 17-year-old
daughter, Nicole, both agreed ``it's great for Super Bowl
watching.'' (Phil Skinner/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) JONESBORO, Ga. -- June 17, 1999 -- INNOCENT-COX, 06-17
-- Walking away from the Clayton County Courthouse, an exonerated
Calvin Johnson Jr. puts his arm around the shoulder of his father,
Calvin Johnson Sr. Johnson Jr. spent the last 16 years in prison
for a rape that DNA tests proved he did not commit. (Johnny
Crawford/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- June 17, 1999 -- BOOKS-INNER-GOLF-COX, 06-17
-- ``Chicken Soup for the Golfer's Soul,'' is the latest from the
ultra-successful, ultra-ubiquitous ``Chicken Soup'' franchise. ``I
think it's opening up a whole new genre,'' says Chrissy Donnelly, a
co-author and avid golfer. ``People are really linking up to the
idea that golf is a metaphor for life and that you can learn all of
life's lessons out there.'' (Jean Shifrin/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. -- June 17, 199 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 20 -- TRAVEL-INN-2-COX, 06-17 -- With its gray Nantucket
shingles, Elizabeth Pointe Lodge on Amelia Island resembles an old
New England captain's house. Elizabeth Pointe stands out because
the island is developed primarily with older beach homes, condo
resorts, such as the Amelia Island Plantation, and the Ritz-Carlton
hotel. (Elizabeth Pointe Lodge/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DESTIN, Fla. -- June 17, 199 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 20
-- TRAVEL-INN-1-COX, 06-17 -- Henderson Park Inn is adjacent to
Henderson Beach State Recreation area, one of the few undisturbed
ocean front sites in the Florida Panhandle. Bed-and-breakfasts are
springing up in beach towns, providing guests that charming
countryside feel while offering all the sun-drenched opportunities
that go along with being at the beach. (Courtesy Henderson Park
Inn/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CORNING, N.Y. -- June 17, 1999 -- GLASS-WINE-2, 6-17 --
The new entrance to the Corning Museum of Glass is modern, while
much of the area has an old-time look. The world's most
comprehensive collection of art glass and high-tech exhibits can be
seen in a new section, opening Saturday, of a $62 million
glass-sheathed addition to the museum. (Michael Okoniewski/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CORNING, N.Y. -- June 17, 1999 -- GLASS-WINE-1, 6-17 --
Erwin Eisch's ``Heads of Harvey Littleton'' in a new Corning Museum
gallery. You can taste your way through dozens of wineries hugging
the hillsides along the sky-blue waters and tour the world's most
comprehensive collection of art glass and high-tech exhibits in a
new section, opening Saturday, of a $62 million glass-sheathed
addition to the museum. (Michael Okoniewski/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
