<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     06-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BEWARE THE AILING DUVAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas)   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Keep your head down. Slow backswing. Follow
through. Those are three of golf's commandments for duffers who
want to do what the pros do, but David Duval has now created
another commandment: burn your right thumb and forefinger.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the world's No. 1-ranked golfer did a week ago
Thursday when he grabbed the handle of a teapot of boiling water on
the gas range in his new Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla., home. He wasn't
sure how well he would be able to play in the 99th U.S. Open here
at Pinehurst No. 2, but after his three-under-par 67 in Thursday's
first round, look for duffers everywhere to hold a lighted match to
their right thumb and forefinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This must be the secret,'' all those duffers will be saying.
``Burn, baby, burn.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing too serious, mind you. Just enough to create small
blisters from second-degree burns. Don't forget to slice those
blisters open, as Duval did Monday. When all those duffers arrive
at their first tee this weekend, look for each one to have a strip
of white adhesive tape on both the right thumb and forefinger, as
Duval did throughout Thursday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some tenderness in my forefinger,'' he acknowledged,
``but nothing bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing that kept Duval from justifying one of golf's oldest
warnings: beware the ailing golfer. Especially in the U.S. Open, a
tournament won every so often by ailing golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Venturi, wobbling with heat prostration, won in 1964 at
Congressional with a doctor watching his every step.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan, his legs weak and weary only 16 months after the
head-on collision with a bus on a Texas highway that nearly killed
him, won in 1950 at Merion in an 18-hole playoff with Lloyd Mangrum
and George Fazio.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Wood, wearing a corset to ease a back problem, won in 1941
at Colonial after opening with a double-bogey 7 on his first hole.
</P>
<P>
   Olin Dutra, ill with amoebic dysentery after two rounds when he
trailed by eight strokes, recovered to win in 1934 at Merion.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Guldahl, despite a two-stroke lead on the tee of what in
1937 was then a par-5 final hole at Oakland Hills, was suddenly so
nervous he turned to Harry Cooper and asked, ``What should I do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just don't drop dead,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Guldahl soon calmed down. When he got to the green, he combed
his hair before putting out from 15 feet for a par that won by two
strokes. But why had he combed his hair?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the photographers were going to take my picture,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Payne Stewart, who had to wear a neck brace for
six weeks earlier in the year because of a herniated disk in his
back, won in 1991 at Hazeltine in an 18-hole playoff with Scott
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Now, not just another ailing golfer, but also the world's No. 1
ailing golfer, David Duval, threatens to win the Open after the
lowest of his 28 rounds dating to his Open debut as an amateur in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purely for ball-striking,'' he said, ``it's probably the best
Open round I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   With two late birdie-2's from 2 feet after a 5-iron on the
202-yard 15th hole and from 10 feet after a 7-iron on the 191-yard
17th hole, he did it like he does everything. Quietly,
unemotionally, steadily.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I try to play,'' he said with a slow smile. ``I
find it less stressful.''
</P>
<P>
   After his fingers were burned last Friday, he didn't hit balls
until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I packed, worked out, played with my cat, watched TV,'' he
said. ``That's what I did. Pretty boring, I guess, but I rather
enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Until late 1997, Duval hadn't won a PGA Tour event. Now he has
won 11, but not a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that the anticipation for the first tour win was
greater than the anticipation for the first win in a major,'' he
said. ``I think when you go on tour you're not quite sure, although
I felt pretty confident about it. But as I've continued to excel
and win some tournaments, I think it's a matter of time now, so I'm
not very nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he nervous about grabbing the handle of a teapot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same old, same old,'' he said. ``Just not on gas stoves.''
</P>
<P>
   But that won't stop all those duffers from trying to burn their
fingers. Anything to help them shoot a 67 or even a 97.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
