A9934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-HOME-NYT &LR;      06-17 0208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN MAY NOTE JEWISH OWNER OF POPE'S CHILDHOOD HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRAKOW, Poland _ A long bypassed Jewish claim to ownership of
the childhood home of John Paul II in Wadowice, now a papal museum,
may be on the verge of official recognition after the pope
mentioned it on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Balamuth, the grandson of Yechiel Balamuth, the pope's
landlord when he was a youth who later died in a Nazi death camp,
complained that the surviving family members had been unsuccessful
in petitioning the Vatican, local church and government officials
for title to the house. They are also seeking a plaque to
commemorate the murders of the owners in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the Balamuths are Wadowiceans. We cordially remember
them,'' a town official, Stanislaw Kotarba, said when asked if a
plaque would be possible. ``Also the pope cherishes their memory.
So I can see no obstacles. There should be no fears about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The house, Kotarba said, ``belongs to Balamuth,'' adding, ``The
pope himself acknowledged it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican was more guarded Thursday, noting that a decision on
a plaque or returning the property was up to local officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
