<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-PETS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCESSORIES FOR THE KENNEL TRADE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LESLEY HAZLETON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saab says its research has found that 60 percent of its American
customers are pet owners _ the highest percentage in the auto
industry. And when these Saab owners take to the road, they say
there is a good chance their Saint Bernard or Siamese will go along
for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   To make such trips safer, Saab has developed special gear, which
is available through dealers or its merchandise catalogue. The
equipment, which ranges from a $19.95 restraint that works with
existing three-point safety belts to a $49.95 leash that attaches
to Saab's cargo-track system, was developed with the Humane Society
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The society has tested, approved and licensed the equipment and
gets a 10 percent royalty on each item sold.
</P>
<P>
   Other items include a black aluminum compartment divider to
separate pets safely from cargo, a spill-proof food bowl, a
pet-travel guide and assorted packs and bags.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Janisse, a spokesman for Saab Cars USA, a unit of the
Swedish auto maker, said the gear was specifically designed for use
in Saab vehicles, though much of the equipment could be adapted for
other makes.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Thrift, a vice president of the Humane Society of the
United States, said that while there were no data on pets injured
or killed in car accidents, dogs were particularly at risk when
improperly restrained in cars.
</P>
<P>
   He said Saab and the society were planning to expand their
efforts, especially in safety education. Expect to see the
society's pet first-aid book (issued with the American Red Cross)
added to the Saab pet-gear line, along with a pet first-aid kit.
</P>
<P>
   Thrift said the organization and the car maker were also looking
into new products, like car cages suitable for small dogs and cats.
</P>
<P>
   And Saab will get behind the society's Give Wildlife a Break
program, aimed at helping drivers avoid deer, raccoons, skunks and
other animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
