<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9943 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-SAAB-ART-$     06-17 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SAAB-ART-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAAB 9-5 STATION WAGON: A SWEDISH EXCURSION INTO A MIDSIZE NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20)  
 (af)  
 By LEONARD M. APCAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Swedes make good cars. Quick. Name a Swedish automobile maker!
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you'd say Volvo, and that has a lot to do with its
distinctive image. Like them or hate them, most everybody knows
what Volvos look like, and that they have a reputation for
durability and safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the other Swedish car company is Saab. Quick! What image
comes to mind?
</P>
<P>
   You might know that Saab also makes sturdy, safe cars. But
chances are you'd be hard pressed to describe their different sort
of look. Not surprisingly, Volvo outsells Saab in the United States
by 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   If folks at Saab had their way, Americans would know Saabs are
reliable, spirited cars of good value. With handling that rivals
good German sedans, a fastidiousness about safety on a par with
Volvo and turbo-charged acceleration that quickens the pulse, Saabs
have a loyal _ but limited _ following.
</P>
<P>
   Since the introduction of its top-of-the-line 9-5 sedan last
year, Saab has tried to get the performance-safety-value message
across by offering stylish cars that stand out from the pack. The
goal is to give Saab an appealing identity, bolster sales and turn
a profit, something that Saab AB is about to accomplish for the
first time in years.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the company rolled out the 9-5 wagon, Saab's first
wagon in more than 20 years. And it has arrived just as the market
for sporty, midsize luxury wagons is blooming. Audi, BMW, Mercedes,
Volvo and now Saab have unveiled ``sport wagons'' aimed at buyers
who want a little more than a trunk but would rather walk than ride
in a four-wheel drive Exterminator, or whatever Detroit is calling
its latest brute ute.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-5 wagon is not just about room. While the cargo space
behind the back seats exceeds that of the BMW and Audi A6 wagons,
its turbo-charged four-cylinder engine, the base power plant, has
170 horsepower and 207 foot-pounds of torque, virtually tying the
get-up-and-go of the BMW and the Audi, and exceeding the standard
engine's in the basic Volvo V70 wagon.
</P>
<P>
   All those rivals have six-cylinder engines except Volvo, which
has five. (The Saab has an optional turbo-charged V6 that gets 200
horsepower.)
</P>
<P>
   The Saab has impressive takeoff _ maneuvering in city traffic,
accelerating onto highways and passing on country roads. Unlike
traditional turbos, there is almost no waiting from the moment you
hit the accelerator until the extra boost kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with the standard 2.3-liter four-cylinder engine, the
maximum torque is achieved at a modest 1,800 revolutions a minute.
In other words, you can have exceptional pickup well within city
speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   When I first drove it, I did not determine if I was driving the
standard four or the optional six. After a trip into Manhattan, I
looked at the sticker hidden in the glove box and was stunned to
discover that I had been driving the smaller engine. Surely a
misprint, I thought. So I opened the hood, but there was no
mistake: only four cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   At high speeds, the Saab moved seamlessly in the twists and
turns of a country road, with almost no leaning. A firm suspension
produced neat cornering and impressive road feel. It was also
supple enough to absorb the bump and grind without jarring my back
and bones. Steering was precise and confident. Wind noise was low.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, that kind of performance and handling cost dearly.
While Volvo wagons start at less than $30,000, the grander
performance machines _ BMW 528i, Audi A6 Avant _ begin at $37,000
to $41,000, and a Mercedes costs even more.
</P>
<P>
   Saab wanted to make a splash with a sticker that begins at
$32,500 with a turbo and a five-speed manual transmission. The car
I tested, which was nicely equipped with a power, glass sunroof,
in-dash CD player, leather seats and an automatic gearbox _ with
sport, winter and normal drive modes _ topped off at $35,895. Both
the front and rear seats were heated _ Swedes clearly know about
driving in winter _ and the two front seats were vented.
</P>
<P>
   Vented seats? Pay attention, this is big: Each front seat has
two fans beneath it that draw the warm air trapped between the seat
and your lower back through perforations in the leather. The
sensation was wonderfully cooling on a warm day's drive.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is also an exceptionally elegant cup holder that pops out
of the dash like a ballerina taking a bow.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere inside, Saab had good legroom and headroom. My
6-foot-5 friend could easily slide behind the wheel, which is not
always the case in cars with sunroofs. The interior also had two
trademark quirks.
</P>
<P>
   Saab made airplanes before it made cars, and its dashboards
resemble a pilot's cockpit with the instrument panel angled toward
the driver. The ignition switch, following Saab tradition, is on
the console that divides the two front seats, not on the steering
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   There are two air bags up front and two in the sides of the
front seats that are designed to cushion both the head and the
chest in side impacts. All five headrests adjust, and there are lap
and shoulder belts for every passenger. The headrests are designed
to sense a collision and automatically move forward to stabilize an
occupant's head to minimize whiplash.
</P>
<P>
   It is a very nice feature, but the headrests reduce rear
visibility. Better to borrow a page from Mercedes, which has a
button on the dash that can retract the rear headrests when they
are extended but not in use.
</P>
<P>
   The storage area in back includes a 12-volt power outlet for
tailgating. With the back seat up, the space easily accommodated my
golf bag and later a load of camping gear for two adults and three
boys. Saab offers retractable floor that extends about 18 inches
from the tailgate and allows you to load heavy, bulky items and
then roll them into the car, easing muscle strain.
</P>
<P>
   With the back seats folded down and the headrests cleverly
stowed, the hauling area exceeds 73 cubic feet, second only to the
Mercedes wagon. The tailgate is one piece, instead of the more
convenient two, but it was easy to close.
</P>
<P>
   Saab does not offer a four-wheel-drive version because its
Swedish bosses don't think Americans really need it. They're right,
of course, but Saab's American managers know that will hurt them.
Traction control, a sensible alternative that slows wheels that are
slipping and sends power to those that are gripping, is available
on Saab wagons with V6 engines. (On the camping trip, the 9-5 wagon
easily climbed the rutted, dirt road we crossed with front-wheel
drive.)
</P>
<P>
   Saab is also passing on another feature that could lift sales.
While the 9-5 wagon is engineered to accommodate a small third seat
in the rear, Saab decided against it because it believes that it is
not a safe seat for children. Right again. No wonder these guys
have always seemed a little different.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A mainstream wagon from the folks outside the
mainstream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
