u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-SKETCH-     06-17 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-SKETCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE MANEUVERING BEFORE GUN-CONTROL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Night was approaching and time was growing short to
change the hearts and minds of lawmakers as three Democrats
gathered for another of the week's relentless publicity offerings
on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   With reporters listening and a photographer snapping away, Reps.
Nita Lowey and Carolyn McCarthy of New York and Rosa DeLauro of
Connecticut began making phone calls to fellow members on Capitol
Hill, to persuade them to support the most stringent version of the
gun control proposals that finally loomed for floor debate Thursday
night _ very late Thursday night, beyond the waking attention of
most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, my friend, how are you?'' Ms. DeLauro cheerily began one
call across from Ms. Lowey, who apparently had already received a
rebuff from her target. ``No, that isn't good,'' she said somberly
into the phone.
</P>
<P>
   In making a show of their intramural lobbying, the three only
underlined the political ballet _ of building a defensible record
for the next elections _ that plays about the debate's essential
question of what to do about the national rampage of school
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCarthy seemed to acknowledge the theatrical curtain that
is a ubiquitous part of Capitol politics when she looked down the
phone list and smiled mischievously at her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Barr, anyone?'' she inquired, referring to the Georgia
lawmaker who is one of the Republicans' most scathing debaters and
dedicated supporters of the National Rifle Association. They spared
Barr and themselves a colloquy.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the debating chamber, Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., suddenly
interrupted his own words of praise for bipartisanship to dash onto
the House floor. He voted electronically in 10 seconds flat on one
of the 56 culture-debate amendments that made much of the day's
legislative business seem like a slow-motion indictment of virtual
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then up rises Dingell!'' exulted Foley, re-emerging to resume
a corridor interview and his point about the fortuitous beauty of
bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was beaming at the electioneering inoculation of the gun
control debate that the Republican Party has found single-handedly
delivered by John Dingell, D-Mich., who is the respected dean of
the House. The thoroughly democratic Dingell, long an opponent of
gun control, proudly served as point man Thursday night for the
NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gephardt's got to be twisting over this,'' said Foley of the
House minority leader, Dick Gephardt. The leader has indeed had to
field endless questions about the comfort his friend and frequent
ally, Dingell, has delivered to the NRA by trying to weaken the
police checks on purchases at gun shows passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you've noticed, President Clinton has suddenly stopped
mentioning the NRA and Republicans in his criticism,'' added Foley,
judging that the Democrats have been confounded and deprived of the
slam-dunk score on gun control they were hoping to carry into the
national elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   For all the concern House members have been putting on the
record about gunfire mayhem among students, the subtext this week
of publicity offerings and corridor conversations alike has been
about the debate's crucial political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to Dingell, nobody can blame any Republican necessarily
for the failure of the gun bill,'' said Foley, grateful for
political complexity and cover even as he said he favored stronger
checks on purchases at gun shows than the Dingell proposal would
permit.
</P>
<P>
   Foley has been an active participant in the debate, scoring a
victory in the culture-war face-offs when he attacked as
unconstitutional the proposal of a Republican colleague, Henry Hyde
of Illinois, to censor entertainment violence for minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least the public will be able to say we're inching
forward,'' said Foley, accurately characterizing a debate that, for
all the storm and fury over the gun slaughter of innocents, has
been marked by low expectations among many lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels a little bit like a shell game,'' Rep. Thomas
Barrett, D-Wis., said of the melange of culture issues and gun
control options Republican leaders arranged like a political
smorgasbord. ``The amazing part for me is that we are not taking
dramatic measures here,'' added Barrett, who favored far tougher
gun controls in reaction to the school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop of limited expectations, debaters consumed
much of their time in exchanges of salvos on the relative efforts
of the gun and entertainment industries to entice the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're Gonna Die!'' blared one lurid looking advertisement for
a computer game displayed in the House. ``Why, you can download the
blood-splatter!'' complained an outraged Zach Wamp, R-Tenn., in
urging mandatory warnings about the harm these games might pose for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start 'Em Young!'' blared another advertisement, this from a
gun magazine depicting a boy fondly brandishing his first pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Families of summer tourists watched mutely from the galleries.
Fewer than a dozen lawmakers participated below in what amounted to
a time-killing passage through the day's cultural agenda to the
gun-control measures of the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
