<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM FLASH TO FOCUS FOR JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The spotlights faded Thursday and the Lakers' newly
anointed savior retreated to the background, trading pomp and
circumstance for the nitty-gritty business of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The day after his glitzy introduction to Los Angeles, new coach
Phil Jackson spent four hours with Lakers brass, plotting the next
steps for a franchise in transition. But with Jackson due to return
to his Montana home today, the changes will have to wait a while.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson plans to return sometime next week and begin assembling
his coaching staff and planning for the June 30 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson met briefly with Lakers assistants Larry Drew and Bill
Bertka but has yet to speak with outgoing coach Kurt Rambis. All
three want to join his staff, but Jackson wants to speak with them
all at length before making any decisions. Former Jackson
assistants Tex Winter, Jim Cleamons, Jimmy Rodgers and Frank
Hamblen all remain in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   All indications are that Jackson will make his hires soon after
returning to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Jackson was introduced Thursday to other new
members of the Lakers family, the downtown Staples Center and the
new practice facility in El Segundo. He toured both construction
sites with executive vice president Jerry West and general manager
Mitch Kupchak.
</P>
<P>
   The trio also had lunch with owner Jerry Buss and spent time
watching the workouts of two pro prospects _ Quincy Lewis of
Minnesota and Stais Boseman, formerly of USC.
</P>
<P>
   Several personnel issues face the new coach and Lakers brass,
from shoring up the power forward position to tabbing a starting
point guard to settling the contract situations of Glen Rice and
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has an opt-out clause but has financial incentive to stay
and now has Jackson, a coach he's eager to play for. O'Neal has
four years and $81 million remaining on his contract but would only
be able to make a starting salary of $11 million with another team
under the NBA's new labor deal.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, O'Neal could choose to opt out and re-sign for up
to seven years with the Lakers. He would sacrifice a few million in
the first four years of the deal but would gain long-term security
_ up to $151 million over seven years, an average of $21.66 million
per year.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has until June 25 to exercise his option, but the Lakers
feel he will stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the place for him,'' Kupchak said. ``I think
he believes that. Subjectively speaking, I don't think he can
continue to run from team to team. Sooner or later, you've got to
plant a tent and say, `I'm going to be here with Phil for five
years, seven years, whatever.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have until July 1 to exercise a one-year, $7.1
million option on Rice, who prefers to become a free agent and
negotiate a new deal starting at the maximum of $14 million. He
might still be used in a sign-and-trade deal to obtain a point
guard or power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Glen, there's really only one thing we can do,'' Kupchak
said. ``If we don't exercise the option, then we risk losing him
for nothing. I don't know why we'd do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Under NBA rules, the Lakers can't discuss new contracts with
Rice or O'Neal or free agents Derek Fisher, J.R. Reid, Rick Fox and
Ruben Patterson until July 1. New deals cannot be announced or
signed until Aug. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990617.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      06-17 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE RETURNS TO THE SCENE OF A FLOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Gore returned to New York as an official candidate
for President Thursday, hoping to reverse the fortunes of his last
such outing, in 1988, when the state's primary drove him from the
race and frayed his relations with his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent that New York race in the shadow of Mayor Ed Koch,
his exuberant booster. The vice president's campaign hopes that if
he ends up this time in the shadow of Hillary Rodham Clinton and
her likely run for the Senate, it will work to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the Republicans' beating up on her,'' Tony
Coelho, Gore's campaign manager, told reporters. ``I know she won't
be happy to hear me say that, but they will beat up on her so much
so that you're going to have a lot of women in New York and a lot
of women all over the country who are going to deeply resent what
they say and how they say it. And as a result of that, we are going
to benefit as a party, and Al and Tipper Gore will benefit because
of what the Republicans try to do to Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho said Mrs. Clinton ``can stand on her own and she can be
tough and she will be very effective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said, ``I encourage the Republicans to take her
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was not eager Thursday to discuss the assessment of some
political analysts that a candidacy by the first lady would compete
with the Gore campaign for cash in a state that customarily
bankrolls Democratic presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already addressed that issue,'' Gore told reporters on a
flight to New York from New Hampshire. Of Mrs. Clinton's candidacy,
he said, ``I'm all for it,'' and added, without elaborating, that
he thought it would help him because it would ``generate
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore appears better situated this time around than in 1988 to
capture New York's delegates to the Democratic nominating
convention next year. At two fund-raising events at the Pierre
Hotel Thursday night, Gore was expected to pull in $900,000 from
about 800 people.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1988, he demonstrated little appeal outside the South.
Then in a bruising New York primary, he alienated Jews and blacks
and ended up with 10 percent of the vote, losing to Gov. Michael
Dukakis, the eventual nominee, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's sole rival this time around for the Democratic nomination
is former Sen. Bill Bradley, who is from neighboring New Jersey
and, perhaps more important, was a star player for the champion New
York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Adler, a Democratic consultant, said that Gore had lined
up endorsements from most of the state's leading Democrats and
that, barring some unforeseen circumstance, he expected they would
activate their machines for Gore next year.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee Miringhoff, director of the Marist Institute for Public
Opinion, said his most recent poll, in March, showed that while
Gore was leading Bradley in New York by 47 percent to 30 percent,
he saw room for growth. ``I assume, given that Bradley is doing
better nationally than he was at that point, that New York is now
within striking distance for Bradley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls from Quinnipiac College show that New York
voters view Gore and Bradley equally favorably _ 43 percent have a
favorable opinion of both. But where 24 percent view Gore
unfavorably, only 6 percent view Bradley unfavorably, although 40
percent say they do not know Bradley, while only 9 percent do not
know Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a state Bradley will focus on because it's a good state
for him, potentially,'' Miringhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it was unclear at this point what effect Mrs.
Clinton's likely entry into the Senate race would have on Gore but
that so far it had completely overshadowed the presidential race
among New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Gore is not punching through,'' Miringhoff said.
``The fact that these other questions are out there _ if Hillary is
running and can't campaign for him, it's sinking Gore's chances _
shows he's not holding down a lot of real estate. He's not defining
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore mentioned none of this Thursday as he held an outdoor rally
under gray skies on Wall Street, where hundreds of people jammed
into the intersection at Nassau Street in front of Federal Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeated the official campaign announcement he first gave
on Wednesday in Tennessee, highlighting his own moral authority,
his proposals to make preschool available to everyone and his
promise to help parents save for college tuition. He also claimed
Thursday, as he has for months, a special knowledge that would
enable him to continue the economic expansion of the last eight
years. ``I know what works,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was on Wall Street, he also gave a nod _ twice _ to the
role of Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, the former co-chairman of
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., in creating the economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, he promised to keep Internet commerce free
of international taxes. In just four years, more than $1.4 trillion
has been spent on goods through cyberspace. ``I want to keep the
Internet a duty-free, global free-trading zone,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
