<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-SERVICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES OFFER PASSENGERS SOME REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ore.)  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's airlines on Thursday appeared to slow
the momentum for ``passengers' rights'' laws by announcing a
package of modest reforms, including offering customers who call
for tickets the lowest fare for which they are eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement at a Capitol Hill news conference won praise
from the chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee and the chairman
and ranking minority member of its aviation subcommittee, who had
been backing such laws. But other members of Congress called the
promises vague and said some areas were not addressed, including
notice of overbooking.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are promising that by later this year they will
notify passengers of delays, cancellations and diversions whenever
they can, ``make every reasonable effort'' to deliver lost bags
within 24 hours, and designate an executive to answer such
complaints within 60 days. They also said they would support an
increase in their liability for lost bags, from the $1,250 that has
been in force since 1984. They did not specify a figure, but
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said he wanted the figure
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard the bell ring, we have felt the whip,'' Gerald
Greenwald, chairman of the industry's trade association and the
chief executive of United Airlines, said in announcing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said the announcement Thursday was at least a
partial cure. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is chairman of the
Commerce Committee and a co-author of one passenger rights bill,
congratulated Greenwald on ``some very significant steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Some airlines, including Continental and United, said they would
have to adjust certain practices, notably to conform with a promise
to hold reservations for 24 hours at no charge. But many airlines
said the new commitments were a confirmation of existing practices.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and others listed several issues that they said should
still be addressed, including telling passengers when flights were
overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's co-sponsor, Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said airlines
should have to tell more about frequent flier programs. The
airlines promised to issue annual reports, but Wyden said that
among other steps, he wanted information on how many seats on each
flight were available for customers trying to spend frequent flier
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is a system for auditing the airlines' compliance.
Some lawmakers want regular reports from the government, but the
airlines are resisting.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Slater said, ``I'm glad to see that
under some pressure, and proposed legislation by the administration
and Congress, airlines have decided to put the passengers first.''
</P>
<P>
   At the American Society of Travel Agents, Paul Rudin, the senior
vice president, described the promises as ``a string of zzzz's.''
Referring to the promise to quote callers the lowest fare, he said,
``The top item is, `We're going to tell you the truth.'''
</P>
<P>
   David Messing, a spokesman for Continental, said, ``We see a lot
of the value coming from the standardization that this achieves
between airlines.'' Passengers will know what they can expect,
which is good for the industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At American Airlines, Chris Chiames, a spokesman, said the
airline was reviewing many aspects of its operation. In general, he
said, airline ticket agents are trained to listen to a customer and
respond to the questions asked. ``Unprompted, they might not say,
`If you can leave two hours later, I can get you a better fare,'''
Chiames said.
</P>
<P>
   Continental will have to change a practice to conform with a new
policy that will allow customers to hold a telephone reservation
without payment for 24 hours or cancel a ticket within that period
without penalty. The policy is meant to allow comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   On holding reservations, Messing said, ``We'll do that now, but
the fare isn't guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   The package includes only the most limited action on two issues
of great concern to business travelers: ``back to back'' ticketing
and ``hidden city'' ticketing. In the former, a traveler making a
quick round trip buys two round-trip tickets, each including a
Saturday night stay-over, to get the benefit of the discounts that
airlines offer for such trips. The traveler then throws away half
of each round-trip ticket and completes the journey for less cost
than buying one full-fare round trip. In the second practice,
travelers bound for a hub airport can sometimes fly there more
cheaply by buying a ticket that includes a stop there, and simply
walking off the airplane at what is supposed to be an intermediate
stop.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines retaliate by canceling the remaining reservations
of a passenger who skips some segments. Under the changes, the
industry will disclose its policies on back-to-back and hidden city
ticketing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
