<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9949 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-H     06-17 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Most every story told about New York Knicks forward
Latrell Sprewell has a familiar ring to it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter what he does, Sprewell always will be remembered for
throttling his coach. Sprewell's choking of Golden State coach P.J.
Carlesimo in late 1997 and subsequent 68-game suspension have been
well-documented, so it's understandable almost everyone associates
the fiery 6-5 Knick with that incident.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy has followed Sprewell, 28, for years. His history
includes numerous confrontations with teammates, like when he went
after Jerome Kersey with a two-by-four when the two were teammates
with the Warriors in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   But with New York playing the San Antonio Spurs in Game 2 of the
NBA Finals tonight at the Alamodome, Sprewell hopes his play with
the Knicks has erased at least some of the negative perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that has,'' Sprewell said. ``I think that for some
people, this has changed (their perception). They probably heard a
bunch of stuff that wasn't true, and now that they've had an
opportunity to see myself and the team, and the way that I've
played, I think that's changed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some people are always going to say I'm a bad guy and
some people are going to always think that I'm a bad guy, but I
think that's just something I'm going to have to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with the Knicks in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation for trouble surfaced again recently when Sports
Illustrated published an article that shot down the notion Sprewell
and Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy have settled their differences and
are getting along. The story reported Sprewell will demand a trade
next season should the Knicks keep Van Gundy as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said that,'' Sprewell said Thursday. ``Something like
that at this point I don't know what to say about it. I don't know
who put it out there. What can you say? Maybe my name sells papers
or Sports Illustrateds or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell did not dodge the questions, even though he easily
could have refused to answer anything unrelated to the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that with everything I've had to go through, dealing
with the media because of the suspension and everything, has kind
of prepared me for what I'm going through right now,'' Sprewell
said. ``Do I enjoy it? Well I'm getting better at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs point guard Avery Johnson, who is friendly with Sprewell,
understands why Sprewell seems to always be answering such
questions. Johnson's introduction to Sprewell was less than
desirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, my first impression of him was that in my first practice
he got in a fight with Byron Houston,'' Johnson said of Sprewell,
with whom he played with the Warriors in the 1992-93 season. ``I
had just signed that day, so I was like, `Man, what am I in for?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard some things about him, but going to that practice
and seeing those guys really get into it like they did, I said,
`Man .' But after things settled down, he and I really developed a
good relationship over the course of the year. We spent a lot of
time together, and I found out that he really loved the game of
basketball just as much as I do. So we developed a great
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Sprewell has done with his Knicks teammates _ even
though it took time. Sprewell, a former All-Star, looked like
anything but early this season, but he has come around, one of the
main reasons the Knicks are in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what his athletic ability is, what he's capable of
doing,'' said Knicks assistant coach Don Chaney. ``The reason why
he is so productive now is that he is playing within the framework
of the team concept. In other words, he's doing his thing, but he's
also involving everybody else. Early on, I thought he was just
doing his thing and was sort of blind to the other guys. Not on a
selfish note, that was just his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's learning that other guys are capable of scoring as
well and he can make them better by dishing and drawing attention
to the defense. I think he's really developing into a complete
player. To me, the true makings of a superstar is when you can
involve and make everybody else better. It's good to make yourself
better; you have the God-given talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put up numbers. But when you can get numbers and help
other guys get numbers, to me, then you're in the superstar
category.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's putting them up as a starter now, after coming off the
bench for much of the regular season. Sprewell disagreed with that
role, and often spoke his mind when asked about it. But if there's
one thing life's lessons have taught Sprewell, it's acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accepted my role because I know that's the way it is
going to be; I can't change it,'' Sprewell said this week. ``So I
mean, that's just the way it is. You know some things in life and
some things you can't change, you just have to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means Sprewell also accepts that he will be treated like
public enemy No. 1 almost everywhere he goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I use to help me get going,'' Sprewell said
with a smile. ``When the fans are all over you, the other team
knows that you're pretty good. It puts the pressure on you to make
something happen. I want to hopefully try to quiet them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
