<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: STOCK OF 3COM, MAKER OF PALM PILOT, IS SAGGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATT RICHTEL with SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a trade show presentation a few weeks ago, Dr. Robert
Metcalfe, a co-founder of 3Com Corp., and Eric Benhamou, the chief
executive, engaged in a brief discussion over who was older.
Metcalfe, it turned out, was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Benhamou told the crowd, ``but I'm aging faster.''
</P>
<P>
   The embattled executive whose job it is to infuse new life into
3Com's maturing products has reason to feel that he has added a few
years and gray hairs in recent months. The once-ballyhooed company
stunned investors with a weak earnings report in March, and many
analysts say 3Com must find an overall focus for its diverse
businesses and manage its products better if it is to regain its
old momentum and reputation as a high-growth company.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the company splits its attention among four distinct
product lines: modems, Palm Pilot handheld organizers, adapter
boards that hook computers to the Internet, and network equipment
for big corporations and communications carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, 3Com plans to announce that it is starting yet another
business, one that would provide wireless phones, pagers and
advanced handheld computers with access to Internet data, including
news, stock quotes and sports scores.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture, called Opensky, in one respect is the most
radical departure yet for 3Com. While other 3Com businesses involve
selling hardware, Opensky will be a service provider. At the same
time, it may signal that the popular Palm Pilot will become the
centerpiece of a newly defined 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even investors who see the Palm Pilot and supporting
businesses as the company's possible savior have grown impatient
with the company's disappointing stock performance. The big blow
came in March when 3Com acknowledged that fully 45 percent of its
business was in sectors that were no longer growing. The previous
month, the company announced that it was cutting the prices of the
Palm Pilot, a move that will eat into profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has plunged, closing Thursday at $28.0625, well off
the $51.125 it hit in late December. The slipping stock price has
led to speculation that the company might be sold in whole or in
parts.
</P>
<P>
   3Com is scheduled to report fourth-quarter earnings Tuesday, and
the Wall Street consensus calls for 23 cents a share. That would be
down from 24 cents a share the previous quarter, which in turn was
down sharply from 35 cents three months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company's bread and butter remains enterprise networking
equipment, like routers, hubs and switches, which represent about
40 percent of overall revenue. The good news is that revenue in
this unit continues to grow 10 percent to 20 percent a year, said
Paul Johnson, senior technology stock analyst with BancBoston
Robertson Stephens. 3Com makes it difficult to verify such
estimates because it does not discuss performance by individual
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The other businesses present far greater management challenges.
Perhaps the most intriguing is the Palm Pilot. Though it is getting
some competition from Microsoft and Psion, Palm is a clear industry
leader, with more than 65 percent of the worldwide market for
personal companion devices in 1998, according to IDC, a market
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Pilot generates only about 10 percent of the $5.8
billion in revenue that 3Com is on track to report for this fiscal
year, but it is in a sexy category (certainly sexier than a router
or a hub) that could be used to enhance shareholder value. In
recent interviews, Benhamou has played up the Pilot, saying 3Com
intends to define it as a platform for Internet connectivity and as
a symbol of the company's commitment to ``connect people and
organizations to information.'' Indeed, this appears to be his
explanation of the rubric that defines 3Com, and he has said that
``the soul of the company is all about'' networking.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have not been impressed. ``That's a little amorphous,''
Johnson of BancBoston said about Benhamou's explanation. ``You
still have to sell something.'' Still, Johnson says the stock could
hit $50 by the end of the year if the company lives up to its
potential.
</P>
<P>
   For the Opensky project, 3Com is joining with Aether
Technologies, a small wireless technology developer, and declined
to say how much it is investing. Michael Dolbec, a 3Com vice
president for business development, said the effort was meant to
encourage sales of hand-held devices like the Palm Pilot. (Opensky
will also support competitors' devices, including those based on
Microsoft's Windows CE operating system.)
</P>
<P>
   The Opensky deal may end speculation that 3Com might spin off
all or part of its Palm Pilot unit. Analysts say that such a move
could mean a short-term boon to the stock price but would be offset
by a loss of control. ``If I were in their shoes, and I weren't
breaking the company up, the last thing I'd want to sell is Palm,''
said Luke T. Szymczak of Prudential Securities. ``There's a lot of
good stuff happening there.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a more lucrative alternative would be to sell the unit
that makes products for telecommunications companies and big
corporate customers. That business could be attractive to makers of
communications gear.
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer options for modems, which represent fully 20
percent of 3Com's revenue. The company got into the field in 1997
by buying U S Robotics, the world's leading maker of modems, which
connect computers to the Internet through telephone dial-up
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Even 3Com has conceded that the once red-hot modem business is
losing out to higher-speed connections, like cable-based Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 3Com has said that its business in adapter boards,
which are used to connect personal computers to a network, is in a
mature market and facing stiff competition from the likes of Intel.
</P>
<P>
   But the company contends that it is regenerating. In March, the
company said it had reduced its inventory 36 percent in the last
year, while cutting long-term debt 15 percent and raising cash on
hand to $1.7 billion from $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company only hopes that the wireless network and the
financial figures to be released Tuesday will steady the nerves of
a few more investors. Then, perhaps, Benhamou's aging process will
steady, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
