u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PATROL-ART-NYT     06-17 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PATROL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELICATELY, AMERICANS PATROL THE PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KACANIK, Yugoslavia _ The two Black Hawk helicopters had not
been in the air more than a few minutes on Thursday afternoon when
the order came to check out a report that the Kosovo Liberation
Army had set up a roadblock outside a hamlet called Pagonavic.
</P>
<P>
   As one hovered overhead, the other landed in a river gully, and
eight soldiers from the second platoon, Company C, 307th Engineer
Battalion of the 82d Airborne Division lumbered out not more than a
100 feet from a makeshift checkpoint at a small bridge. Rifles held
across their waists, they made their way to the road in a ragged
column.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Orlando L. Tagaloquin Jr., the platoon leader,
stopped short of three men and reached out to shake their hands.
They were dressed in civilian clothes but stood beneath the
red-and-black flag of the Kosovo Liberation Army. They did not
understand a word he was saying. So like a tourist lost in a
foreign land, he resorted to gesturing emphatically, pointing to
his rifle and loudly asking if they had their own.
</P>
<P>
   They shook their heads, but he ordered his men to search a hut
at the end of the bridge anyway. There they found three AK-47's,
hidden under a chair. Tagaloquin then pointed to the rifles, to
himself and to the sky. ``What I was trying to say,'' he explained
later, ``was, `These are going with me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 minutes, the second platoon was gone aboard its Black
Hawk. The checkpoint was still there, though for the time unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's operation in Kosovo entered its sixth day, patrols
like Tagaloquin's have become critical to expanding the security
presence NATO commanders pledged to provide. With no agreement yet
for disbanding the Kosovo Liberation Army, the patrols have become
a cat-and-mouse game with the rebels for preeminence, especially in
villages and towns dominated by Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a third of the 50,000 troops NATO will eventually
deploy in Kosovo having arrived so far, NATO officials have
acknowledged the limits of their reach, something that Serbian
civilians have cited as they flee Kosovo in fear of retribution
from the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 3,000 American troops who have arrived in Kosovo _
including soldiers from the Army's 82d Airborne and First Infantry
Division and the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit _ are slowly
expanding their control over what will become the American sector
in the southeast part of the province. From two hilltop bases about
10 miles apart, the Army and Marines have begun to extend their
presence beyond the main roads and cities. ``It's really just a
show of force,'' Lt. Robert J. Schexnayder, commander of air
operations for the Army's contingent in Kosovo, said. In most
cases, the rebl army has got there first.
</P>
<P>
   From Pagonavic, the second platoon flew to Kacanik, a
predominantly Albanian town that until the last day or two was
deserted. One after the other, the Black Hawks landed on a field in
the town's center, and the members of the second platoon climbed
down, lying in a defensive circle as a small crowd of Albanians
gathered nearby on a foot bridge to watch the helicopters leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``One. Two. Three. Four.'' Capt. Terrence L. Johnson, the
company's deputy operations officer, began to count the men on the
bridge wearing the uniforms or berets of the army of Albanian
rebels. ``Two more back there,'' he said as the platoon climbed a
berm to the city's main road. ``That's six. Seven.''
</P>
<P>
   As they rounded an apartment building, Sgt. James R. Kettner
barked at Pvt. Second Class Jacob E. Nelson to be mindful of
snipers. No one in the village seemed threatening, and most
Albanians have welcomed the American and NATO troops like
liberating heroes, but Thursday's patrol came a day after the
Marines stopped a company of rebels, detained their leaders and
seized a cache of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After crossing over a bridge and then circling back underneath
it, the platoon moved into the city's center. As they rounded a
corner, they encountered another rebel position, this one manned by
uniformed, but unarmed rebels. A banner strung across the street
and inscribed with the rebel force's Albanian initials said, ``Mire
Se Vini,'' or ``Welcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
