u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIETNAM-HONOR-TOMB-NY     06-17 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-HONOR-TOMB-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: Mo.)  
 INSCRIPTION AT TOMB WILL HONOR VIETNAM MIAs  
 (af)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans missing in action from the Vietnam War
will be honored by an inscription on an empty crypt at the Tomb of
the Unknowns in Arlington National Cemetery, the Pentagon said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The inscription will read, ``Honoring and keeping faith with
America's missing servicemen,'' Under Secretary of Defense Rudy De
Leon said in announcing that no new remains from Vietnam would be
interred at the tomb for now, or perhaps ever.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes a year after a few pieces of bone
interred at the tomb in 1984 to honor the unknown dead from Vietnam
were identified as those of 1st Lt. Michael J. Blassie, whose Air
Force plane was shot down on May 11, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Since the disinterment of Blassie's remains in May 1998, for
reburial near his boyhood home outside St. Louis, there have been
discussions within the Pentagon on what to do about the now-empty
Vietnam War crypt. It had been known for months that Defense
Department officials were leaning against placing a new set of
remains there, since scientists can now identify even the tiniest
human remnants through DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   American remains found in the rice paddies or jungles of
Southeast Asia are taken to the Army's Central Identification
Laboratory in Hawaii, which now has more than 120 sets of remains
and hopes to identify each eventually.
</P>
<P>
   De Leon acknowledged the advances in science when he was asked
if there were any remains at the laboratory that were positively
unidentifiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there is no candidate,'' he said. ``Indeed, given
the advances in science, and with the commitment to a full
accounting'' of the missing, it is possible that the Vietnam War
crypt will be forever empty.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of Blassie's bones left the remains of three
servicemen at the Tomb of the Unknowns _ one each from World War I,
World War II and the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   De Leon said Defense Secretary William S. Cohen would dedicate
the new inscription on the Vietnam crypt on Sept. 17, the date when
American prisoners of war and missing in action are honored.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Greer, who works in the Pentagon office dealing with
missing servicemen, said that at last count, 2,060 from the Vietnam
War remained unaccounted for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
