<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four tied atop Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ That's it, fellas. That's the end of the grace
period. No more flying the ball at the flagstick and finding soft
surroundings. Forget the flop shot and return to the bump-and-run.
The sun is finally out at Pinehurst No. 2, which is firming up as
we speak, and birdies are about to become scarce around here as
skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the bad news for the field of 156 players in the 99th
U.S. Open. Even with No. 2 at its most defenseless in Thursday's
first round _ receptive greens, wimpy rough and hardly a breath of
wind _ only 23 players broke par.
</P>
<P>
   Four players share the lead at 3-under-par 67 _ David Duval,
Phil Mickelson, Billy Mayfair and Paul Goydos _ and most of them
probably would take even-par from here on in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course played as easy as it will play because of the
rain,'' Mickelson said, ``but it's a tribute to the golf course to
how difficult it is, because there aren't really any low scores....
It's not a golf course where 4-, 5- or 6-under even enters your
mind.... I think we're going to be in for a long weekend if the
greens were to dry out.''
</P>
<P>
   One shot off the lead, the mix really becomes interesting. With
68s were Tiger Woods, Dave Berganio Jr., 1991 champion Payne
Stewart, Japan's Kaname Yokoo and John Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus' Larry Mize was in group at 69 that included PGA
champion Vijay Singh, former Marietta resident Bob Tway, Jim Furyk
and Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III opened with an even-par 70, shooting
2-under on the back nine despite two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Lee Janzen had a 74 _ four shots better than
Jack Nicklaus, playing in his 43rd Open.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Bryce Molder, appearing in his first event with
the world's top professionals, managed a respectable 73, three
shots better than teammate Matt Kuchar, who struggled after
double-bogeying his first hole.
</P>
<P>
   Of the leaders, Mickelson's story is the most compelling. With
wife Amy two weeks from delivery back in Scottsdale, Ariz.,
Mickelson has pledged to exit Pinehurst regardless where he stands,
if she unexpectedly goes into labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate to be able to have a child,'' Mickelson
said. ``We thought we were going to have problems and it came very
easily. That's something I don't want to miss. I have a once in a
lifetime opportunity to be there, whereas the U.S. Open takes place
every year. . . It's not worth a tournament. This is the most
important thing as far as our family is concerned and she will call
me and let me know. I'll be very disappointed if she were to go
into labor and not call me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson has a beeper in the bag, with caddie Jim MacKay of
Athens standing by for alarming sounds. The jet is at the airport,
ready to taxi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a little code in case somebody calls (the number)
accidentally or gets a wrong number and beeps us accidentally,''
Mickelson said. ``So if she punches in that code, I'm getting out.
I'm getting a car as soon as I can and getting to the airport. . .
I figure I'll have about five hours and 15 minutes from the time I
get the beep and I arrive at the hospital . .I've got a plane
standing by and, as you know, I'm a pilot. I've got my co-pilot
ready to file (the flight plan), and we'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after burning his right thumb and forefinger on a hot
pot, Duval heated up his game. He went to 3-under with a masterful
fade 7-iron at the 191-yard, par-3 17th and a 10-footer for birdie.
Steadier than the barometer, the former Georgia Tech player made
three birdies and no bogeys. The nearly clean cuffs of his white
slacks told the story -- only two missed fairways from the world's
no. 1-ranked player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can hit it in the fairway and not 3-putt this week,''
said Duval, ``I think I'll be in here Sunday night talking to you,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from closing birdies at 17 and 18, Woods mostly continued
the scrambling act he displayed in an impressive win at the
Memorial, posting his best first-round score in five U.S. Opens by
six shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw me play today,'' said Woods, ``you'd say there's no
way he could have shot the number he shot. It was not a pretty
round, but I scored.''
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for the next couple of days is for sunny, warm
conditions. No. 2 will play shorter, but with sharper angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If if firms up,'' said Duval, ``I don't think you're going to
see too may balls close to the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
