</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWNING YOUR SUCCESSOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., N.Y., Nev.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I've been promoted, and one of my first new tasks is finding
someone to fill my old job as a department head. The people in the
department work well together and are technically all equals, but
they see a definite pecking order. My first choice for the job,
however, is not the person they all assume is in line for it.
Should I go with the better candidate, knowing that she and I will
be resented, or suffer with a less capable manager in order to
preserve group harmony? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Always go with talent. Otherwise, your short-term fear of
workplace friction will undermine the department's performance over
the long haul _ and that ultimately reflects poorly on you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to think of this in a long-term perspective,'' said
John Hawkins, president of Leadership Edge, a consulting firm in
Durham, N.C. ``This will help orient you toward a choice that has
the most potential for development, growth and accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you should make every effort to minimize fallout.
Take time to explain your logic to the troops, said Aminata Njeri,
chief operating officer of Dynamics of Leadership, a leadership
training company in Brooklyn, N.Y. ``When people have an
understanding of your reasoning,'' she said, ``it reduces the
possibility of them resenting your decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But be careful how you approach the subject. Don't point out
that you know your choice was not the expected one, advised Mary
Shurtleff, a management consultant based in Las Vegas. Instead,
focus on how you expect the strengths and abilities of the new
department head to benefit the team.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how eloquent your explanation, however, you should
hope for the best and prepare for the worst, Hawkins warned. To be
safe, he said, explain your decision to your boss _ in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, if the troops start grumbling and circumvent you and
go to your supervisor, your supervisor will know what's going on,''
he added. The boss will also be better prepared to support your
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Your new appointee can also take steps to smooth the transition,
Ms. Shurtleff said, by asking her workers for ideas on dealing with
the group's challenges. But encourage her to follow up on the
suggestions, or she'll be headed for real trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not just say, `I want input,' then put it away in a
drawer,'' Ms. Shurtleff added. ``That's the worst thing you can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, remember that your decision will send a message to the
department's employees about the qualities you consider important
in a leader. ``It seems as though the group has a misconstrued
notion of what makes someone promotable,'' Hawkins said. And that
gives you an opportunity to do some re-education.
</P>
<P>
   It's important, he said, for employees to know ``that people
don't get ahead based just on seniority or who screams the loudest
in meetings or who is the squeakiest wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
