<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-TOW18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fledgling firm gears up expansion to get 100 trucks in tow
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOYNTON BEACH, Fla. _ A fledgling firm in Boynton Beach is
working to create a national brand in towing, starting with a name
that should be easy to remember, 1-800-AutoTow.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded two years ago and owns towing companies
in three states _ Florida, Texas and Pennsylvania. But now it's
planning to close this month on deals for eight more towing
companies, one in Texas and seven in Florida, including one in West
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The company employs 30 people, with five in Boynton Beach. It
has about 30 trucks at three companies it owns _ two in Tampa and
one in Pittsburgh. It will have 100 trucks if all the deals are
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Chairman and Chief Executive Joel Nagelmann declined to
disclose the company's sales, whether it's profitable and the names
of the companies it's buying. But he said, if all eight deals go
through, 1-800-AutoTow will generate about $13 million a year in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we will be profitable,'' Nagelmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in 1997 when three businessmen read a
Success magazine story about Vince Gelormine's idea of
consolidating towing companies. They called Gelormine, a former
business development manager at Boca Raton-based HotOffice
Technologies, about joining him.
</P>
<P>
   The three are Nagelmann, a business consultant and former
marketing employee for IBM; Chief Operating Officer Eugene Iarocci,
the former transportation director for Union Carbide; and Josh
Konigsberg, a health services and Internet entrepreneur. Gelormine
is AutoTow's vice president of business development.
</P>
<P>
   The group started with slightly less than $1 million in seed
money from family, friends and small investors. The partners took a
year to study how to integrate small companies into one large
towing business, what kind of technology to use to increase
efficiency and how to put together commercial contracts with other
companies with large fleets.
</P>
<P>
   They began to buy towing companies last year.
</P>
<P>
   They are using a combination of stock (OTC-BB: AUTW, 61 cents),
cash and debt to complete the deals, Gelormine said. In some cases,
the company also assumes debt.
</P>
<P>
   AutoTow has hired an investment bank to find investors for the
company and to put together financing to buy trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to stand out through technology, using
satellite tracking to keep tabs on its trucks and communicating
with drivers on two-way pagers. Ultimately, it wants to put
computers in tow truck cabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can give customers a real (estimated time of arrival),''
Gelormine said. ``That's the key. If you call and they say they'll
be there in 30 minutes, a lot of times it takes an hour and 30
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
