A9972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-NICKLAUS18-C     06-17 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-NICKLAUS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicklaus still seen as the best
 &HT;    By Woody Peele
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ There was a day when Jack Nicklaus' presence
on the golf course at a major tournament was enough to make other
competitors tremble.
</P>
<P>
   But at age 59 and just six months after hip replacement surgery,
Nicklaus is but a shadow of his former self. Thursday he struggled
to an 8-over par 78 _ tied for 146th in the 156-player field _ in
the first round of the U.S. Open which began at the fabled
Pinehurst No. 2 course.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, when he walked up the 18th fairway to the green, the
gallery in the grandstands gave him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time on the day, Nicklaus doffed his cap in
acknowledgement. He followed that with a modest wave of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be the Jack of yesteryear, but he's still regarded as
one of the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play very well,'' Nicklaus said afterwards. ``That's
about all I can say. I didn't drive the ball very well. My iron
game was not very good and my putting wasn't very good either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, I was fine,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in an early morning drizzle and fog, Nicklaus said he
had trouble focusing on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see very well anymore in low light,'' the four-time
Open champion said. ``I was over a pitch on the second hole, and I
couldn't focus where the ball was. I had my caddy read the first
three greens for me, because I couldn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   With sunshine expected today, and a near-noon starting time,
Nicklaus said that could make a big difference in his game.
</P>
<P>
   The dampness made the course too long for him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hit it far enough any more to play under these
conditions,'' Nicklaus said. ``I was hoping for a hard, fast golf
course and I didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the way it goes. I'm still not back yet, ready to
play, but I'm doing my best. I feel fine, I'm just not that strong
and that was pretty obvious today. On a heavy day, I just didn't
have the strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, who had just one birdie on the round, missed more
greens than he made _ 12 missed, six made.
</P>
<P>
   He first made the green in regulation at the third hole, but
three-putted to fall three over par. At four, however, he made the
green and collected his first par, raising his hands in salute of
the ovation of a large gallery which followed him all day, despite
his play.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus made another par at seven, where he missed the green,
but used his putter from well off the putting surface to get close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time,'' Nicklaus said when asked how often he used his
putter when off the green. Some of those shots were from 15 yards
out or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pin placements were pretty tough,'' he said. ``They didn't
spare any of the horse. If the greens had gotten quick, we'd have
had 8 to 10 shots that would have rolled off the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus used that roll to get his only birdie of the day. At
the dogleg-right eighth hole, he hit his tee shot into the rough at
the corner. Then, he followed with a long, low shot that hit in
front of the green, rolled up and bumped the pin, bouncing back a
couple of inches.
</P>
<P>
   But by and large, Nicklaus was easily outdriven by his two
companions _ Hal Sutton, who shot a one-under 69, and former Open
champ Curtis Strange, who was all over the course and also finished
with a 78.
</P>
<P>
   The drizzle that fell on the trio subsided at the turn and,
although the sun didn't come out, the course began to get better.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus wants it to dry quickly and get a lot faster. With
that, he hopes to be able to make the cut when today's play comes
to an end. At this point, that's an iffy situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harder, faster: That's the only chance I have of playing,''
Nicklaus said. ``If the course is fast, it would make up for some
of my lack of strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``A heavy golf course makes a par 70 a long golf course for
me,'' he continued. ``I used woods off (the fairways) of par fours
today four times and that makes the game a little harder.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I didn't get it there then.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were playing 8- or 9-irons and I'm playing 2's and
3's. I guess I'm getting a little bit of my own medicine. I had it
that way for years,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's all right. I'll get stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
