u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-17 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS: ORRIN HATCH AND DAN QUAYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Miss., S.C.)   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Presidential Talk, and Hatch Is Listening
</P>
<P>
   The hot political talk in Utah is that Sen. Orrin Hatch has not
given up on the idea of seeking the Republican presidential
nomination next year and, in fact, has pretty well made up his mind
to form one of those ``exploratory committees'' to test the lay of
the political land.
</P>
<P>
   The 65-year-old senior senator from Utah says he is
``courteously listening'' to all the talk, but otherwise refuses to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are long that a hard-right conservative like Hatch
could win the nomination, given the momentum building behind Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and given, too, the number of other hard-right
conservatives already off and running. As the senator put it the
other day: ``I'd be the longest of long shots. I know that. It's
very late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, The Salt Lake Tribune said Thursday, without naming any
names, that Hatch's ``closest aides and friends'' are expecting
that he will announce the formation of a committee ``as soon as
next week.''
</P>
<P>
   That development came on the heels of reports that the senator
has hired a pollster to test his national standing with voters, and
is looking to hire some political professionals to help him put
together a national campaign organization that, for starters, will
open offices in Iowa and New Hampshire, the two states that
traditionally start the quadrennial nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Hatch seeks the presidency, he faces a
re-election race next year for a fifth term in the Senate, a race
he is heavily favored to win. Spencer Stokes, who is managing that
campaign, cautions that while many people close to the senator
believe he is poised to jump into the presidential race, ``only one
person really knows if he is, and that's Orrin Hatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a new Utah law, Hatch can run for both offices at the same
time. The law was pushed through the state Legislature earlier this
year by Hatch supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Funny Things Happen to Quayle in Dixie
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Dan Quayle should give up on scheduling trips to the Deep
South to raise money for his quest for the Republican presidential
nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   First, the former vice president planned to hold a fund-raiser
in Jackson, Miss., on June 23, figuring his family-values pitch
would be a real money-maker with the state's heavily conservative
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Come on down, by all means, said Gov. Kirk Fordice, an old
friend who had earlier been appointed as one of the Quayle
campaign's national chairmen. But then came the disclosure that the
governor had slipped off to Europe for a vacation with a woman who
is not his wife, and upon his return _ a stormy return when
reporters showed up _ had demanded a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Fordice remains one of Quayle's campaign chairmen, and the
candidate says he is ``pleased to have his support.'' But the
fund-raiser has been postponed _ for a reason, or reasons, that the
campaign refuses to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's schedule also calls for him to travel to South Carolina
on July 7 for a fund-raiser and golf tournament in Columbia. The
hosts for that visit, according to an announcement from Quayle
headquarters, will be Lou Holtz, the head football coach at the
University of South Carolina who won a national championship when
he coached at Notre Dame, and former Gov. Carroll Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful that two of my longtime friends are joining me,''
Quayle says in the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   This is no small deal. In football-crazed South Carolina, Holtz
is almost as revered as the Good Lord. And Campbell is not far
behind, at least with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But wait _
</P>
<P>
   The former governor insists that this is all news to him. Or, as
he told The Columbia State on Wednesday, it is ``completely an
overstatement.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he has many ``good friends'' running in the Republican
presidential race and is sitting on the sidelines at this point,
just watching, not scheduling any events, totally uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   He will make up his mind in his own good time, Campbell says,
adding that in the meantime, he's not going to be ``pushed into a
corner and trapped.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jim Merrill, the director of the Quayle campaign in
South Carolina, Quayle would not ``presume'' to speak for Campbell.
Still, Merrill says, hanging in there, Quayle ``appreciates'' the
former governor's assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
