<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-JUVENILES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES MEASURE TO ALLOW TEN COMMANDMENTS IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move apparently aimed at the hearts and minds
of the nation's youth, the Republican-controlled House approved a
controversial measure Thursday that would allow the Ten
Commandments to be posted in the nation's public schools and
government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, offered as an amendment to a sweeping juvenile
justice bill designed to crack down on minors who commit violent
crimes, was approved 248-180 over the objections of opponents who
called it a ``clear violation'' of the constitutional separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   But the amendment's chief sponsor, Rep. Robert Aderhalt, R-Ala.,
insisted that a display of the Ten Commandments would help instill
``the right values'' in children and help calm the atmosphere of
violence that he said is so prevalent today in the nation's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent shootings in Littleton, Colorado, provide an
unfortunate picture of the terror infested in our schools today,
children killing children in the halls of our schools, children who
do not understand the basic principles of humankind,'' Aderhalt
said. His legislation would allow the posting of a well-known
``religious symbol'' but would not endorse a specific faith, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He called on colleagues to take a stronger stand on promoting
traditional values and discipline, and said that while posting the
Ten Commandments ``will not change the moral character of our
nation overnight ... it is an an important step to promote morality
and an end of children killing children.''
</P>
<P>
   Aderhalt's effort to impose a religious-based solution on youth
violence won the support of 45 Democrats and 203 Republicans. Only
15 Republicans opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All 13 GOP members of the Texas delegation voted for the
amendment, as did Democrats Gene Green of Houston, Ralph Hall of
Rockwall, Max Sandlin of Marshall, Charles Stenholm of Abilene, Jim
Turner of Crockett and Solomon Ortiz of Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill was one of several amendments sponsored by conservative
Republicans aimed at broadening the role of religion in public
places. Another measure approved with the help of conservative
Democrats would also allow religious symbols to be placed on
memorials on school grounds that honor victims of school violence.
One amendment passed paved the way for faith-based groups to
administer juvenile justice programs as long they do not ``preach
their religious beliefs,'' as one lawmaker put it.
</P>
<P>
   And taking a step that was highly critical of Hollywood, the
House also approved a resolution sponsored by Rep. Jo Ann Emerson,
R-Mo., urging the entertainment industry to curtail ``portrayals of
pointless acts of brutality'' in movies and video games.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson accused the industry of actively marketing violence to
young people and said that tweaking the gun laws would not stop
teen-agers intent on killing. She said it was time for Congress to
help parents win back ``a sense of security and control'' in their
schools and homes to help prevent future tragedies like the April
shooting and bombing incident at Columbine High School that killed
14 students and one teacher.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her call for congressional action on the ``cultural
problems'' confronting America, Emerson acknowledged that Congress
``can't legislate behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ten Commandments measure and Emerson's resolution were just
two of 43 amendments offered to a larger $1.5 billion juvenile
justice bill approved by the House late Thursday before it turned
its attention to a variety of gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The gun-control amendments, including competing measures that
would close a loophole in federal law allowing gun show dealers to
sell weapons without conducting background checks on buyers, was
expected to ignite a heated debate over the amount of time allowed
to conduct the checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has approved a bill requiring background checks at
all gun shows and pawn shops and setting a three-business day
deadline on completing the checks to determine whether a buyer has
a criminal record or is under age.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., a former board member of the
National Rifle Association, and other anti-gun control advocates
introduced a weaker version of the gun show legislation requiring
that checks on transactions be completed within 24 hours. If the
checks couldn't be done in that time, the buyer would get his gun
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Dingell bill also would weaken existing background check
regulations for licensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the Dingell measure, which appeared likely, would
represent a major victory for conservative House Republicans led by
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who seized on the Dingell measure
as a way to ``take the air out of the gun control lobby,'' as one
GOP aide put it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dingell measure was expected to pick up the support of 45
Democrats and most Republicans who fear that voting for tougher
gun-control legislation could hurt them in next year's elections,
as it did in 1994 when Democrats were targeted by the NRA because
they voted for a ban on assault-style weapons.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, with the NRA's backing, actively lobbied Republicans to
vote for the Dingell bill and offered reassurances that it
represented ``a safe vote'' that won't haunt them next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dingell measure is designed to undercut not only the Senate
bill but a similar amendment set for debate late Thursday that
would require background checks at gun shows and flea markets with
three business days to complete them.
</P>
<P>
   The competing amendment is sponsored by Rep. Carolyn McCarthy,
D-N.Y., whose husband was shot and killed on a commuter train.
McCarthy and Democratic leaders, including President Clinton,
worked Thursday to gain support for her measure, but it appeared on
the verge of being voted down.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in Europe for a meeting of the world's largest
industrialized nations, was up early Thursday morning calling
wavering Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope and pray that Congress will do the right thing,''
Clinton told reporters, after seeking them out to voice his concern
about the Dingell amendment. He called on lawmakers to think
``about those children (in Littleton) and other children that we
can still save.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Dingell was intentionally trying to undercut
the administration and his party leaders on the gun-control issue,
Clinton said he thought the senior congressman was doing ``what he
believes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Dingell, however, was less kind in assessing the president's
attempts to defeat his amendment, and claimed that the president
was responsible for the loss of the House by the Democrats in 1994
because he encouraged Democrats to support gun-control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president with his machinations in 1993 on gun control
cost us the control of the House and a lot of people here
remember,'' Dingell told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
D-Mo., spent much of Thursday lobbying Democrats that a strong
position on gun control would not hurt them at the polls because
public attitudes have changed.
</P>
<P>
   As the late debate on gun control began, Gephardt reminded
colleagues that children were dying everyday because of guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost more kids yesterday (to gun violence) than we lost in
Kosovo or in Bosnia,'' he said. ``Thirteen kids a day go down to
school violence,'' he said, citing government studies. ``This is a
national crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said he
``couldn't agree more'' with Gephardt's appeal to members to help
prevent the violence.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``Oh, my God, the problem _ it goes far beyond
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
