<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COMPANIES, IT CAN PAY TO RECOGNIZE THE NEEDS OF PROFESSIONAL
WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Debby Hopkins, 44, is senior vice president and chief
financial officer at The Boeing Co., which makes her one of the
most powerful and highest-ranking female executives in the country.
</P>
<P>
   She's also a mom.
</P>
<P>
   As such, she knows the only thing more challenging than keeping
watch over the balance sheets of one of the largest corporations in
the world, is guarding the balance between her work and family
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Women (and men) everywhere are trying to strike a magical
equilibrium that allows for both career growth and a real life.
</P>
<P>
   But that balance can shift depending on where a woman is in her
life, according to a survey by Deloitte &AMP; Touche. Recognizing those
shifts can help companies better design programs to keep and
attract talented women.
</P>
<P>
   ``As younger women continue to assume more leadership positions,
we wanted to look at the trends and patterns of professional women
at varying stages of their career,'' said Trish Zuccotti, a
director at Deloitte &AMP; Touche, and organizer of the study. ``We
were curious to learn whether women in their 20s, 30s, 40s, and 50s
have more similarities or differences when it comes to workplace
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche surveyed 111 professional women in Washington
to see how their career values changed at different ages.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that women in their 20s and 40s share some
career values. Women in their 20s are looking for opportunity and
women in their 40s want both income and change.
</P>
<P>
   Women in their 30s, many of whom are starting families, value
job stability and flexible hours above income and change.
</P>
<P>
   And for women in their 50s, job satisfaction is the primary
career motivator.
</P>
<P>
   These are generalizations, but they are also useful reminders
that women (and men) have different needs at different times in
their lives, Zuccotti said.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping women has been a growing challenge for many companies,
she said. Six years ago, for example, Deloitte &AMP; Touche realized
women at the accounting firm weren't always getting the same plum
assignments as men and thus weren't getting the same opportunities
for advancement. Since then, the company has started a mentoring
program and other initiatives aimed at meeting women's needs.
</P>
<P>
   It's paid off. The company is keeping more women and its overall
turnover rate has fallen from about 24 percent to about 17 percent,
she said. ``All the things we're doing to retain women _ the
work-life balance programs _ also benefit men.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart companies work to attract, develop and retain talented
women, Boeing's Hopkins said. And in that kind of environment,
women can go as high as they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barriers (to advancement) are pretty limited at this point
in time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Giving women opportunities to expand their skills in different
departments is especially critical for women who want to advance to
senior positions in companies, said Hopkins, who has held a variety
of positions at General Motors, Unisys Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get out of your functional area,'' she said.
``If you're in finance, get an opportunity to work in sales or
marketing so you're seeing a different part of the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   That breadth makes a woman more valuable to the company, and
gives her more opportunity to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins has managed her own rise while raising a son, now 18,
and daughter, 13.
</P>
<P>
   Just after her son was born, she was working for a ``Fortune
10'' company and being asked to work overtime for the sake of
working overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to leave, even though it was a strong career
environment for me at the time,'' she said. ``It was important to
me that I wasn't working every Saturday just for the purpose of
saying I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she still works to balance time with her family with the
demands of Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins drags a ``briefcase that looks like a suitcase'' home
with her, but she has dinner with her husband and time with her
kids in the evenings before wrapping up her paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to make a connection at one end of the day,'' she
said. ``That's the model that works for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The way people get their work done is less important than the
quality of the work they do, she said. She tries to give her own
employees the flexibility they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger issue is to focus on what that person delivers vs.
whether they deliver it in the same way you always have,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins' advice to other women? ``It's the same thing my mother
said to me: You can do anything you want to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the same message she's passed to her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Hopkins was telling her daughter she'd be a great
reporter on CNN someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Mom, I'm gonna own CNN.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
