<HEADER>
A9978 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS_SFC     06-17 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 WORKWAYS/ILANA DEBARE  &HT;     Slacker Boss Skips Out Of Work 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I work in a very small off-site department for a fairly large
corporation. The only employees are myself (an hourly employee), my
manager (a salaried employee) and one on-call employee. The
problem: My manager seems to be fiercely abusing the corporate
``time off'' policy. He leaves the office on personal business for
long stretches of time, which sometimes leaves me overwhelmed with
work. Since ours is an off-site location, none of his superiors is
in a position to notice. I'm afraid of retaliation from him if I
tell the company. How should I handle this?
<P>
   A: When companies are reluctant to approve telecommuting
arrangements, this is precisely the scenario they fear _ employees
who take advantage of their invisibility to slack off or stop
working altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It is not common. But when it happens, as you are seeing
firsthand, it can be a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   You should start by talking to your manager. Do not criticize
his absences directly. Instead, describe the crunch they create for
your own workload and the office's productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him about the issues that come up when he's not around
and how you have trouble getting your work done,'' suggested
Marcelle Bolding, a human resources consultant in Oakland. ``Ask
him to help figure out how to resolve those problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps your manager will take the hint and spend more of his
time on the job. If not, maybe he will come up with some other way
to help you out, such as increasing the hours of your on-call
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   If talking to your boss directly does not work, your only option
is to approach someone at headquarters. If there are people in
management who you know and trust, start with them.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways that the company can focus a little extra
scrutiny on your boss without letting him know you blew the whistle
_ for instance, by having someone from headquarters stop by the
field offices occasionally without advance warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vice president used to call me his eyes and ears,'' said
Emily Elliott, a human resources consultant in Walnut Creek who
used to work in HR for a company with out-of-town satellite
offices. ``I'd go to the branch offices to do training in some new
system. But while I was there, I'd always talk with people about
how things were going, and what was or wasn't working.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Union Accountability
</P>
<P>
   Q: I work at a unionized company where I pay nearly $1,000 a
year in union dues. I have never seen any information about the
union's budget and have no idea what my hard-earned cash is spent
on. I'm also curious about things like travel guidelines for the
union leadership. Am I legally entitled to this information and, if
so, how do I go about getting it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unions representing private-sector workers are covered by the
Labor Management Reporting and Disclosure Act, according to Carl
Biers of the Association for Union Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   That federal law requires would require  &LR; your union to file an
annual report called an LM2, which should include some budgetary
information such as the group's assets, liabilities and officers'
salaries. You can get a copy by calling your local office of the
U.S. Department of Labor and asking for the Office of Labor
Management Standards.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some unions are required by their constitutions to
issue financial reports to their members. However, neither an LM2
nor an annual report is likely to go into the level of financial
detail, such as travel spending, that you're seeking  &LR; you seek.
</P>
<P>
   Your first step should be the most obvious one _ asking your
union representative for answers to your questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're an honest, open union, they will make this
information readily available,'' said Biers. ``But if a union is
stealing money from its members, it's going to do its best to bury
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, if the union is misusing your money and covering up
its finances, the only way to change things may be to put together
a reform group and run for union office yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Want some help? Contact the Association for Union Democracy, a
nonprofit in New York that counsels union members in their
democratic rights. They can be reached on the Web at
 &LR; www.uniondemocracy.com  &LR; or through their West Coast office at
(415) 621-8468.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Early Warning Penalty
</P>
<P>
   Q: A co-worker gave two weeks' notice. Our boss then informed
him that he would only need to work one week. Is he eligible to be
paid for the entire two weeks?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Nope. Unless your colleague was covered by a union
contract or individual employment contract, he was most likely an
at-will employee.
</P>
<P>
   And at-will employment means that either the worker or the
company can terminate the relationship at any time, for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   Your colleague did the ethical, courteous thing by giving two
weeks' notice before leaving. It would have been nice if the
company had thanked him for the advance notice rather than
terminating him even earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But nice or not, his dismissal is still probably legal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
