<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9980 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPTIONS-OPTIONS_SFCHR     06-17 1552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPTIONS-OPTIONS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 GRABBING A PIECE OF THE PIE  &HT;     By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Binay Cahn, a lifelong lover of animals, was thrilled to get three
job offers this spring from e-commerce companies selling pet
supplies. But she was perplexed about how to compare the three
offers _ especially the part that involved stock options.
<P>
   ``I had a couple of different offers, and it was really hard for
me to figure out what they meant,'' said Cahn, who started work
this week as director of corporate communications for Petstore.com
in Emeryville. ``I kept asking my friends, `Just tell me how many
options I should ask for.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cahn wasn't alone in her uncertainty. Stock options have become
a common part of job offers in Silicon Valley. Savvy applicants now
realize that a hefty option grant from a fast-growing tech firm can
lead to a windfall of $100,000 or even $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   So an increasing number of Bay Area employees are trying to
figure out how to negotiate for stock options _ how many options
they should seek and what different option packages might be worth.
</P>
<P>
   Some valley veterans already have worked at enough startups to
be confident, knowledgeable option negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Cahn, who are newcomers to the startup world
feel like they are groping in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is complicated by the fact that there is no simple
yardstick for option grants: Offers vary widely from firm to firm
and job to job. And unlike salaries, there are no surveys of
``average'' option grants available in print or on the Web to the
average job seeker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations get very hot and very heavy because employers are
trying to hold on to a great deal of equity and employees are
trying to get equity,'' said Ted Ganchiff, founder of a Santa Clara
startup called TalkNetRadio. ``The problem is that there's not a
lot of information out there. Applicants are asking for numbers (of
options) that are vastly different from what the founders are
saying. People are coming into this entirely uneducated _ both on
the employee side and the founder side.''
</P>
<P>
   How do stock options work? In a nutshell, they give someone the
right to buy a certain number of shares of stock at the current
price, at a specified date in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If the value of the company and its stock rises during that time
period, the option holder can make a profit. If the value falls or
stays flat, however, the options are worthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get burned if the market goes flat, but you can really
make money if the market goes up,'' said Matt Ward, a compensation
consultant with WestWard Pay Strategies in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options have long been a perk for chief executives and
other top managers. But in the 1990s, more and more firms started
extending option grants to mid- and low-level employees., too. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  A 1997 survey of 1,100 public companies by the American
Electronics Association found that 53 percent offered options to
all their employees. Among startup technology firms that have not
yet  &LR; gone public, the figure probably is closer to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, Silicon Valley is the country's stock option
mecca. Employees are not the only ones getting options here: Many
startups also offer options in lieu of cash to their outside
lawyers, accountants or marketing consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside the valley, salary and benefits are people's No.1
concern, but in the valley, it's stock,'' said Greg Hampton, CEO of
a Sunnyvale startup called Clairvoyant Software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here even receptionists come in and ask, `What's my option
package?''' said Bruce Bourne, an independent financial adviser to
startups in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
How Much Is `More?'
</P>
<P>
   Startup firms typically offer options to their employees to make
up for lower-than-average salaries and an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   So one general rule of thumb is: The newer and riskier the
venture, the more stock options you should expect. If you are
willing to work at a steeply discounted salary, you should expect
even more options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier you join a firm, the more you should get _ but how
much is `more'?'' said Steve Patchel, a senior compensation
consultant with Watson Wyatt. ``That's a number that's virtually
impossible to quantify.''
</P>
<P>
   Compensation experts say it is a mistake simply to compare the
number of options offered by two employers _ to grab automatically
for 10,000 options at Company A rather than 5,000 options at
Company B.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, job applicants should try to figure out what percentage
of the company they are being given through their options. The
bigger the ownership stake, the greater the potential gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five thousand shares of a company with 1 million shares
outstanding is not as good as 5,000 shares of a company with 50,000
shares outstanding,'' Patchel said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, applicants should assess how much they expect the
company's stock to rise in value. Will your $2 options rise to a
market price of $5 or $50 by the time your vesting date arrives? Or
will the price flounder at $2.50 or (heaven forbid) plummet to 50
cents?
</P>
<P>
   This requires guesswork, but at least you can do some informed
guesswork. Look at how comparable companies in your industry have
performed in the market. Read what analysts say about the company's
prospects. And if the company is not yet public, find out how many
more rounds of outside investment it expects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a company secures an additional level of financing,
it causes dilution of the stock,'' said Claudia Lindquist, a
recruiter with TechniQuest in San Jose. ``You may have a terrific
option price, but if the company has to bring in more investors, it
will dilute the value of your package.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Benchmarking
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you have come up with an estimate of what you think an
option offer is worth.
</P>
<P>
   How do you know if that is enough _ or whether you should ask
for more?
</P>
<P>
   First, consider the compensation at your last job. If you had
options before, you should be getting a package that is more
valuable than what you had there.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to friends in comparable positions, too. ``The easiest way
to know competitive option practices is to call around to your
buddies and find out if they're willing to share what they've
gotten,'' said Linda Amuso of iQuantic, a San Francisco firm that
advises companies on their stock option plans.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is some general benchmarking you can do.
</P>
<P>
   Companies usually set aside certain ranges of option grants for
different kinds of positions. CEOs of early stage startups
typically get options worth 5 to 10 percent of the outstanding
shares. Other top executives, such as the chief financial officer,
may get options worth up to 3 or 4 percent of the company.
Nonexecutive employees typically get less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you are dealing with a public company, it will have filed
proxy statements saying how many options were given to top
executives. That can help you figure out how much you can
realistically seek.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a midlevel manager, for instance, do not set your
sights on the same number of options as the CEO. But within a lower
range, you probably have some room to push for a better package.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples: Compensation consultant Dee DiPietro surveyed
technology startups and found that individual senior engineers
earning $100,000 receive options worth anywhere from 0.123 percent
to 1.390 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, midlevel engineers earning $78,000 receive options
worth anywhere from 0.016 percent to 1.044 percent of the company,
said DiPietro, president of Advanced HR Inc. in Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies very frequently allow negotiating room,'' said Bill
Metzger, a compensation consultant with Assets Unlimited in
Campbell. ``If they typically pay a position 20,000 shares, they
may lower their initial offer 20 percent to give themselves some
bargaining room.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Only One Factor
</P>
<P>
   The upshot? Yes, you can negotiate for more options. But
remember that options are only one factor among many to consider in
taking a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see guys with three young kids haggling over 200 shares of
stock when maybe they should be haggling over the amount of
vacation they'll get,'' said Lindquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to think about how you're going to feel two years
from now if the stock doesn't go anywhere,'' said Marianne
Adoradio, a career consultant who leads workshops on salary
negotiations at the Career Action Center in Cupertino. ``Will you
feel OK with the job, with the salary and with what you've learned
on the job?''
</P>
<P>
   In Binay Cahn's case, she gave herself a crash course in how
options work. She read articles about options and spent more than
an hour interrogating a friend who founded a startup.
</P>
<P>
   Cahn ended up deciding to join Petstore.com, not because of the
option package, but because of her overall confidence in the
company and its business strategy. Even so, her new knowledge about
options came in handy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing to me was to go with a company that I
deemed successful and a winner in its category,'' Cahn said.
``Then, in the end, I believed in the company so much that I
negotiated a package that had higher options and lower salary.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
