<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBATTACK-WEBATTACK </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Trying to Take Tedium Out of Web Conference   &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
More than 900 executives turned out for an Internet marketing
circus yesterday at Fort Mason that included Dennis Rodman, but
failed to produce a promised camel.
<P>
   The Web Attack conference _ which promised ``No boring panels!''
_ was billed as an attempt to teach online marketers to think
creatively.
</P>
<P>
   By adding entertainment to the two-day affair, the event's
producer and emcee, Michael Tchong, tried to appeal to busy
executives who would rather analyze a 12-page clickstream data
report than attend another mind-numbing tech conference.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Rodman _ and camels _ have nothing to do with
the Internet. And never mind that conferences on identical topics
are held almost weekly. Tchong's M.O. seems to be: You gotta have a
gimmick _ or better yet, a pavilion full of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tech business is notoriously lame when it comes to
marketing,'' especially in comparison with consumer brands like
Calvin Klein and Taco Bell, said Tchong, whose main business is
Iconocast, a weekly e-mail newsletter that is considered the
leading authority in Web marketing. ``That, to me, is where it has
to head.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tchong recruited Rodman (``A perfect example of
self-branding!'') as his keynote speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of promotional brochures, Tchong sent out glossy posters
featuring a fire-breathing monster under the headline, ``Web
Attack! The Ultimate Internet Marketing Event.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep heads from nodding, Tchong recruited attendees to play a
Web trivia show on stage. He also put his stamp on last night's
official conference dinner _ a ``2001 Arabian Nights'' harem party
complete with belly dancers. Fort Mason officials put the kibosh on
Tchong's plans to beef up the ambience with a rented camel.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Tchong, who grew up in Aruba and graduated from
Fordham University, was the omnipresent emcee. In the world of Web
self-promotion, he rivals Tiffany Schlain, organizer of the Webby
awards, who wheeled her infirm grandmother on stage at this year's
show to sing a song about the Webbies and ``Tiffy.''
</P>
<P>
   While the conference's gimmickry was as blatant as the 14-foot
Web Attack lizard towering over the stage, content was also given
its due. Tchong's staff edited the presentations to make sure they
included insights or helpful facts and figures, rather than the
typical dull sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees at yesterday's events had mixed feelings about Web
Attack, which continues today. Kate Delhagen, an analyst with
Forrester Research, noted that Rodman pulled up on his motorcycle
25 minutes late and then didn't have much to say. ``He's a
resounding thud as a brand, he's more of a bland,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the conference is ``hugely well attended, so
it's high on the schmooze scale,'' said Delhagen, who enjoyed
touches such as a stock ticker, featuring Web stocks, scrolling
above the stage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Casey Taylor, a programming analyst with America Online, took
lots of notes during the conference and loved the appearance of
Rodman, who Tchong recruited after finding him registered for the
domain name Rodzilla; the conference initially had been dubbed
Webzilla.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also liked the audience participation and the
not-your-father's-conference atmosphere. ``I begged my boss to let
me come,'' said Taylor, an avid Iconocast fan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Behind the harem girls and the giant lizard, Web Attack is
ultimately a promotional vehicle for the Iconocast newsletter. This
year's event probably will not make a profit, although black ink is
more likely in future years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're No.1 a publisher, and the No.1 goal of this event is to
reach (potential subscribers)'' said Tchong, a former advertising
executive and founder of the now-defunct MacWeek magazine. ``This
is an opportunity to create a default home page for all
marketers.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old Iconocast, which is free, currently has 45,000
subscribers and aims to recruit 69,000 by December and 150,000
eventually, Tchong said. There is a waiting list for its six ad
slots, which sell for up to $3,600 a pop, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Web Attack, Iconocast has a strong entertainment element,
specifically a gossip column by Tchong's adolescent alter ego, the
Jacobyte, who floats industry rumors and dishes dirt. For example,
Jaco reported that Disney had acquired the rights to the domain
name ``Mybigstiffy.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Web Attack, Jaco has his fans and his detractors. ``I
always read Iconocast as soon as I get it, but I could live without
Jacobyte,'' said Manish Bhatia, vice president of interactive
services for Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bhatia, Jaco/Tchong once reported that Bhatia was
ready to leave Nielsen and was job-hunting _ something Bhatia
swears is not true. Tchong didn't run the item past Bhatia before
printing it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tchong is at the forefront of the hot interactive
marketing sector, which is estimated to reach $31.4 billion in
2002, according to C.E. Unterberg, Towbin. Tchong's next
conference, slated to take place in New York next May, ``will have
3,000 people, guaranteed,'' he promised.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
