r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROVIDIAN-PROVIDIAN_S     06-17 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-PROVIDIAN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S.F.'s Providian Scrutinizing Sales Tactics  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Facing lawsuits and a probe by the San Francisco district
attorney's office, Providian Financial Corp. says it is carrying
out a top-to-bottom review of its high-pressure sales tactics.
<P>
   The concession has taken some of the heat off the giant San
Francisco credit card company. But observers wonder whether
Providian's spectacular profit growth will slow if it cleans up its
act.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how much of Providian's profits are based on sales
techniques the company will be forced to halt, such as telephone
pitches for credit insurance that consumer groups have called
misleading. Ending such practices, some industry experts warn,
could take a large bite out of Providian's sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to understand why it wouldn't affect
revenue,'' said Robert McKinley, chief executive of CardWeb.com, a
Maryland company that tracks credit cards. ``It ought to lower
it.``
</P>
<P>
   Providian, which specializes in offering credit cards to people
who have previously had problems paying off debts, said the
controversy will have little effect on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game is customer satisfaction,'' said
spokesman Marc Loewenthal. ``If our customers are satisfied, the
revenue growth will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of slower revenue and profit growth are big worries
for investors already spooked by possible legal action against the
nation's ninth-largest credit card issuer. Once a high-flying
stock, the company's shares have swooned 30 percent since the
district attorney's probe was disclosed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Providian's revenue and profits jumped to $2.4
billion and $296 million respectively, up more than 50 percent from
1997. Much of that gain came from soaring fee income, which more
than tripled in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies and consumer groups are now questioning
how Providian generated those fees.
</P>
<P>
   They have received hundreds of complaints from people who say
Providian sold them products they did not want, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to do is send you out our Welcome Package with
all the information so you can look it over at your convenience,''
reads one script used by telemarketers to sell credit protection,
which allows customers to skip payments for a year if they become
unemployed or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   If the customers said yes, that was treated as a sale. Customers
have complained they did not understand the sales disclosures that
accompanied the pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they would sell a small fraction of their credit
protection if consumers understood what it really is,'' said Linda
Sherry, a financial services specialist for Consumer Action, a San
Francisco advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   After news reports that the district attorney's office was
investigating such practices, Providian said it was reviewing its
marketing language. The company also said it would give refunds to
customers who believed they had been charged improper fees.
</P>
<P>
   And, in response to complaints that it failed to post payments
on time, Providian extended deadlines two days and hired the
accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young to examine its payment-processing
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company repeated previous projections that
per-share earnings would rise from $2.04 in 1998 to $3.50 in 1999
and $4.72 in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said Providian has been quietly telling
them it does not expect to significantly alter the way it does
business. Analysts are divided on whether that view is realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look for them to make material changes,'' said
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette analyst Moshe Orenbuch, who forecasts
only a marginal loss of revenue. Meanwhile, Orenbuch noted,
Providian has accounting tools to prop up earnings, such as setting
aside less money to cover credit losses.
</P>
<P>
   But Friedman, Billings, Ramsey analyst Todd Pitsinger looks for
a slowdown in sales of credit protection and an overall $60 million
decline in fee revenue next year from levels the company otherwise
would have reached.
</P>
<P>
   One thing analysts agree on is that Providian's situation is
volatile and unpredictable. Said Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods analyst
David Berry: ``The real answer is that nobody knows what will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
