A9983 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-3COM-3COM_SFCHRON &LR;      06-17 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-3COM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 3Com Forming Wireless Net Access Firm  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Santa Clara's 3Com Corp. is joining with Aether Technologies today
to create a new company to provide wireless access to e-mail and
the Internet for people on the go.
<P>
   OpenSkycq &LR; , a joint venture to be based in Palo Alto, will act
as a wireless data service provider, allowing users with
specialized cell phones, handheld electronic organizers and pagers
to surf the Web, access e-mail and view corporate intranets.
</P>
<P>
   3Com hopes to capitalize on the demand for handheld wireless
Internet devices, which is expected to explode during the next two
years. More than 3 million people already use wireless Internet
devices, and that number is expected to grow about 50 percent by
2000, according to industry watchers.
</P>
<P>
   To take advantage of this developing market, 3Com and Aether of
Owings Mills, Md., are rolling out something akin to a wireless
Internet service provider. Like America Online or Excite AtHome,
OpenSky will provide content, as well as e-mail and an Internet
connection, but for wireless users. It will let customers share
files and access corporate intranets.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies also are trying to cash in on the wireless
Internet wave with plans similar to OpenSky's. Last year, Microsoft
and Qualcomm formed a joint venture called Wireless Knowledge,
which will give cell phone users the ability to access the Internet
and wirelessly tap into corporate networks. Cisco and Motorola also
have teamed up to do something similar.
</P>
<P>
   OpenSky will employ the same technology that the new PalmPilot
VII uses to surf the Internet. But although the company is jointly
owned by 3Com, which makes the popular Palm personal digital
assistant, OpenSky plans to offer its service on a variety of
mobile devices _ including those that use Palm's rival technology,
Windows CE.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said that's important because not everybody
will use a Palm device to access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a huge market but with lots of different
devices,'' said Albert Lin, who follows the wireless industry for
the Abernathy Group in San Francisco. ``There are different groups
that need information in a mobile environment,'' and not all those
groups use the Palm devices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the company has not announced any agreements yet, OpenSky
officials said they are working with a number of wireless carriers
and other companies who are interested in offering the service.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans a nationwide launch by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   OpenSky will use 3Com's Web-clipping technology, which allows
users to get specific bits of information from various sites. Right
now, those sites include ABCNews.com, E-Trade and Moviefone. The
company also will use Aether's AIM.net technology, which will allow
OpenSky's service to work on a variety of networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What OpenSky does is put all the pieces together,'' said
Patrick McVeigh, the former vice president of worldwide sales for
3Com's Palm division who will be OpenSky's CEO. ``We take
responsibility for customer billing and care ... and we understand
how applications and data need to be formatted for small devices.''
</P>
<P>
   OpenSky plans to sell its service to individual consumers, as
well as wireless carriers and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like UPS or FedEx, for example, could sign up with
OpenSky and give their workers the ability to access corporate
intranet sites, company e-mail and other services while on the
road. Individual carriers like Nextel or Sprint PCS also could sign
up with OpenSky and offer the service to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wiggins, who follows the wireless data market for the
Yankee Group in Boston, said OpenSky's business plan makes sense
because wireless Internet users will want more than just a gateway
to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is focused around content delivery to handheld
devices enabled by the Internet,'' Wiggins said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
