<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS' DUNCAN DOMINATES OPPONENTS, KEEPS QUIET ABOUT IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tim Duncan has the emotion of Tom Landry and all
the charisma of Styrofoam.
</P>
<P>
   And, in case you've been too bored by his Vanilla Nice game to
notice, he also appears to have the New York Knicks at his mercy
and the entire NBA in the palm of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   During a 33-point, 16-rebound performance in San Antonio's Game
1 victory in the NBA Finals, the Spurs' 7-footer shrunk one of the
NBA's 50 Greatest Players (teammate David Robinson) into a
role-playing Robin and melted the macho Knicks defense into a speed
bump. Most impressive, he did it without a single ``look at me!''
dunk, without any oohs or aahs from the crowd, and with only a
rumor that he broke a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a person on the planet that can stop him
one-on-one,'' said beleaguered Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, whose
team takes another shot at slowing down Duncan in tonight's Game 2
at The Alamodome. ``Whatever we do, he's going to have big numbers
all series.''
</P>
<P>
   If the undermanned and overmatched Knicks are to avoid getting
swept out of the Finals, they must find a way to defend the
league's best, most boring player. Working as hard as a mosh-pit
bouncer to get position, then catching the ball in traffic as if it
were a butterfly and finally turning into a ballerina around the
basket, Duncan scored at will over smaller, weaker New York
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Without even a hint of tongue-wagging or camera-mugging, he took
turns schooling New York's Kurt Thomas, Larry Johnson and Chris
Dudley with an arsenal of moves. He scored with a 20-foot jumper,
fadeaways spinning both left and right, layups with each hand, a
rebound tip-in, a head-fake dribble drive on the baseline, a
12-foot bank shot and even a finger-roll layup.
</P>
<P>
   In a league that likes its leading men much more animated, ``The
Big Easy'' is more Brad Daugherty than Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a star, he's a superstar,'' said Robinson, the passer
on several high-low post sets that resulted in easy Duncan hoops.
``When he's on a roll like that, you just keep passing it into him
and then jog back down court to play some defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Though yesterday he typically ho-hummed the performance, Duncan
joined the Rockets' Hakeem Olajuwon as the only players this decade
with Finals games of at least 30 points and 15 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect 33 points, honestly,'' Duncan said. ``I'm sure
they're going to change it up and attack us more in the post. It's
nice to get numbers like that, but when I woke up this morning I
was still a pretty boring guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but those who know Duncan best say he's closer to
eccentric than boring.
</P>
<P>
   He's got an expansive knife collection, a passion for paint
ball, tattoos on his back (a joker) and chest (a dribbling Merlin)
and a knack for pick-pocketing unsuspecting teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really plays up this `Dull 'ol me' stuff,'' said teammate
and best friend Antonio Daniels, ``but he's really a prankster.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to his textbook footwork on the court, Duncan's mind
can be downright quirky. His idol is the psychologically probing
Matt Damon character in ``Good Will Hunting'', he always wears his
practice shorts backward and he has this crazy idea for his own
clothing line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to sell stuff with surprise blemishes,'' he said. ``You
know, like pants that turn pink after one wash, or a shirt with one
sleeve cut out. You won't know what it is until you open the box or
wear it a couple of times. I'll call it `Ultimate Rejects.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With more games like Wednesday's, Duncan will become as big a
star here as he is in his homeland of St. Croix, Virgin Islands. It
was there that Duncan was one of the world's top 14-year-old
freestyle swimming prospects until Hurricane Hugo destroyed the
Virgin Islands' only indoor pool in '89. Unwilling to train in the
ocean because of a fear of sharks, Duncan only then turned to
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like our king,'' said Dominic Rauges, one of 165 natives
of St. Croix who have flown in for the Finals' first two games.
``The new gym is named after him, his picture is everywhere. He
even got a 100 percent tax break on his sports bar.''
</P>
<P>
   With his unassuming personality, long arms and ears so big Duke
fans called him ``Spock'' while at Wake Forest, Duncan is quietly
taking over the NBA as he did his island homeland. He is yet to be
late for practice, laughs at the thought of doing a rap album,
doesn't whine for the ball, stayed quiet during the lockout and is
mum on his possible free-agent departure after next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``His shyness is part of his charm,'' said Nova Lanktree,
director of the Sports Celebrity Network advertising firm. ``He has
something most athletes don't, and that's an elegance about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Spurs coach Gregg Popovich, ``MTV won't be running after
him because he's old school. Stuff can be swirling all around him,
but he stays focused and relaxed. I call that being on island
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's image is Spurfect for San Antonio and the NBA.
Opponents probably wouldn't pay to see him play, but they would
certainly cough it up to avoid playing against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's impressive to say the least,'' Dudley said. ``We banged
on him pretty good, but he's just oblivious to it all. He just goes
about his business quietly, then all of the sudden you're exhausted
and he has 33 points.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
