<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-TEX </SLUG>
 
FOUR SHARE OPEN LEAD WITH 67s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ In terms of medical marvels at the U.S. Open,
David Duval and his blistered right hand pale in comparison with a
limping Ben Hogan winning in 1950 after his rehabilitation from a
near-fatal car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't even rate with a dehydrated Ken Venturi staggering
down the final fairways before hoisting the trophy in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   But if Duval keeps hitting shots the way he did in Thursday's
opening round at Pinehurst Resort and Country Club, the world's
top-ranked golfer predicted he will soon join the list of Open
champions who overcame physical afflictions during tournament week.
</P>
<P>
   With his right forefinger and thumb taped because of
second-degree burns suffered in a household accident last week,
Duval shot a bogey-free 67 at Pinehurst No. 2. He joins Phil
Mickelson, Billy Mayfair and Paul Goydos atop the leader board on a
day when the par-70 layout was softened by overnight rains, yet
induced a scoring average of 72.9 from the 156 starters.
</P>
<P>
   Duval got there by avoiding three-putts, splitting 10 of 14
fairways and finishing with a stress-free effort of 3 under par.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purely off ball-striking, this is probably the best round I've
ever had at the Open,'' said Duval, who burned his hand on a pot
while boiling water. ``I had no expectations when I started. But if
I keep hitting it in the fairway and avoid three-putts, I think
I'll be back in here Sunday night, talking to you again.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, remains 54 holes in the future. But Duval
joined a high-profile group of players in taking advantage of soft
scoring conditions on a day when Pinehurst, in the estimation of
Tom Lehman, ``gave you as much as it will ever give you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, you had to worry about sucking the ball back off
the greens, they were so soft. Not exactly your typical Open
conditions,'' said Lehman, who has played in the final group on
Sunday at the past four Opens.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman failed to capitalize Thursday, soaring to a 73. But five
players, including Tiger Woods, Payne Stewart and John Daly, stand
in a group one stroke behind the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 156 starters, 23 broke par. Only Duval and Mayfair
completed their rounds without bogeys, but they did so in
remarkably different fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Duval covered the flagsticks with his approach shots. His three
birdie putts traveled a combined 20 feet, matching the shortest of
three birdie bombs holed by Mayfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to death. I went out and did exactly what I
wanted to do,'' said Mayfair, who made matching 20-foot birdie
putts at Nos. 1, 9 and 10. ``You have a lot of long irons into
these greens. If you're going to score, you have to make some long
putts to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless your name is David Duval, of course. Duval, winner of
four events on the PGA Tour this season, had birdie putts of two
and 10 feet at two of the par-3 holes. He knocked an approach to
eight feet for birdie at No. 2 and spit out birdie putts from 10
and 18 feet on two other holes.
</P>
<P>
   Duval found himself in greater control of his destiny than
playing partner Mickelson, who scrambled to a share of the lead
with a five-birdie, two-bogey effort. Included was a chip-in for
birdie from 25 feet at No. 5, a 30-foot birdie putt at No. 13 and
an 18-footer at No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Although pleased with his fast start, Mickelson _ who began play
at 6:30 a.m. CDT _ said he was surprised he was not passed by
another player as the first round unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tribute to how difficult this course is,'' Mickelson
said. ``For 3 under to be hanging up on top of the leader board,
with the course playing as easy as it can, I think we're going to
be in for a long weekend if the greens dry out.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of the players with Tarrant County ties makes it to
the weekend rounds remains unclear. Burleson resident Greg Gregory,
a former UT-Arlington player, had the lowest score of the bunch, a
3-over 73. Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks shot 74 and former TCU
golfer Alberto Ochoa shot a 77.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
