<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMPAQ PROJECTS A LOSS AND PLANS A REORGANIZATION
</P>
<P>
   In its first comment on its prospects since dismissing its chief
executive two months ago, Compaq Computer said that it would lose
as much as $237 million in the second quarter and announced a
sweeping reorganization, which will include thousands of layoffs,
meant to save $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been losing money and market share in the face of
Dell Computer's more efficient and flexible method of selling
directly to customers, and Compaq plans to increase its direct
sales to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK AND BOND PRICES RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Stock and bond prices moved higher as investors and traders grew
increasingly confident that the Federal Reserve will not embark on
a series of interest rate increases. The Nasdaq composite index
rose 26.32 points, or 1.05 percent, to 2,544.15, and the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 56.68 points, to 10,841.63. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 9.49 points, to 1,339.90. The
yield on the 30-year Treasury fell below 6 percent, finishing at
5.96 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CONFIRMATION SEEN FOR SUMMERS
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the members of the Senate Finance Committee said
they expected Lawrence H. Summers, whom President Clinton nominated
last month to succeed Robert E. Rubin, to easily win approval as
the 71st Treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   FRONTIER BACKS GLOBAL CROSSING DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Frontier said that its board had discussed and took no action
regarding a $13 billion unsolicited offer made by Qwest
Communications International, reaffirming its commitment to a
merger agreement already agreed to with Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   GILLETTE EXPECTS WEAK QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed, Gillette said that its second-quarter
results would be weaker than expected because of disappointing
sales of its Braun, stationery and toiletries products and a slow
recovery in overseas markets. In after-hours trading, its shares
fell 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT SAID TO SEEK NEXABIT
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, continuing its push into the market for
Internet equipment, is near a deal to acquire Nexabit Networks,
executives close to the talks said. The two companies declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   FIDELITY GIVES LOOK AT FINANCES
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments sold $1 billion in long-term debt after
strong demand from institutions, which for the first time got a
detailed look at the fund company's finances. Documents suggested
its total market value would top $30 billion if it were publicly
traded. The bond sale has prompted speculation that Fidelity wants
to assess its potential value if its chairman, Edward C. Johnson
III, ever wants to take the company public or sell a piece. A
public offering could make it easier for Johnson's daughter Abigail
to take control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   FORD NARROWS PRODUCTIVITY GAP
</P>
<P>
   The big difference in labor productivity between American and
Japanese auto makers in the 1980s, then a matter of considerable
dismay in the United States, has been sharply reduced by Ford, but
General Motors and DaimlerChrysler still lag, a study says.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES OFFER PASSENGERS REFORMS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's airlines appeared to slow the momentum in Congress
for ``passengers rights'' laws by announcing modest reforms.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT CHANGES AD AGENCIES
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft abruptly ended its five-year relationship with Wieden
&AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore., shifting its corporate brand account,
with billings estimated at $100 million, to McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
