<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DALLAS-KNICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS NATIVES JOHNSON, THOMAS NOW FRIENDS, KNICKS TEAMMATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Larry Johnson has a vivid memory of his first
encounter with Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1995, just before Thomas' rookie NBA season. Johnson
was working out on the SMU track, and Thomas was also there,
boasting about leading the NCAA in scoring and rebounding as a TCU
senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt's got a mouth on him,'' Johnson said yesterday. ``He was
hyped and was saying, `I'll bust your ... I'll bust your ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about to run around the track,'' Johnson said. ``But
Kurt made me go home and get my shoes, and we went to the gym and I
put a smashing on his butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas remembers that incident as if it happened yesterday.
Nowadays, though, he and Johnson have fun talking about the long
odds of their being from the same city and winding up as New York
Knicks teammates while playing in the NBA Finals for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and San Antonio Spurs will play Game 2 of the NBA
Finals at 8 tonight at the Alamodome. The Spurs won Game 1, 89-77,
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who entered the NBA in 1991, grew up in the Dixon
Circle area of South Dallas and graduated from Skyline High School.
Thomas graduated from Hillcrest High School, and Johnson reminded
one and all that Thomas grew up with a finer pedigree than he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt's talking about he's from Oak Cliff, but Kurt's from
North Dallas,'' Johnson said, while laughing. ``He didn't grow up
in the 'hood.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been so attached to Dixon Circle _ one of Dallas'
more depressed areas _ that he has purchased a lot of property
there. He also helped finance the Larry Johnson Recreation Center,
which opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some Dallasites have criticized Thomas for going back on his
word after he told Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson he
was going to sign a one-year, $1 million contract with the
Mavericks in January. Thomas instead signed a two-year, $3.67
million contract with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, whose career has been riddled with injuries, said the
Mavericks should have offered him a more lucrative contract. As
evidence, he cited the six-year, $33 million contract the Mavericks
gave point guard Steve Nash, and the six-year, $14.2 million deal
they awarded Erick Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   ``\R(The Mavericks\S take chances and pay guys $33 million,''
Thomas said. ``No names need to be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another guy \RStrickland\S that they took a chance on,
and he got 14-something million dollars. You just can't find
6-foot-9 players who can do the things that I can do out there on
the floor, offensively and defensively, and not be willing to take
a chance with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he wouldn't mind coming back to the Mavericks and
playing for Nelson, Thomas said: ``I don't really know if Nellie is
going to be in Dallas. But I'm going to always be in Dallas, even
if they hate me in Dallas. I have too much family and too much love
for the city, so they can't kick me out.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Thomas and Johnson both tried to contain the Spurs'
Tim Duncan, but to no avail. Duncan finished with 33 points and 16
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas shined in other areas, with 13 points and 16 rebounds.
Meanwhile, Johnson played on a bad right knee and was limited to
five points and one rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thomas and Johnson have become fast friends as they
experience the finest moment of their basketball careers. They even
have the same personal trainer, Ken Roberson of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go up to the Redbird gym and watch him play against
all of the other guys,'' Thomas said of Johnson. ``When I first
really met him, we did get to play and he kicked my butt, and I
learned from that and just continued to work on my game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
