<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9994 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-BABIES-1STLD-W     06-17 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-BABIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSE AT BORDER: BORROWED CHILDREN EASE ILLEGAL PASSAGE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to replace phrase ``aliens'' with ``illegal immigrants''
throughout story; subs 19th graf for insert concerning whereabouts
of baby used in ruse; subs headline) (sw) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Agent Griselda Vidrio had just wandered
into the U.S. Border Patrol's processing center after several hours
patroling the weed-girded Rio Grande when she caught sight of the
young Honduran couple and the seven-month-old baby in their arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how it is with a baby, you see one and you go up to
them,'' Ms. Vidrio, a border agent, said. ``The baby looked at me
and smiled and something struck me. I knew that baby. I had held it
in my arms. I thought, no, this baby has already been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vidrio's memory flash on March 31 led to uncovering a
smuggling network that, U.S. officials said, had been doing
something they had suspected was occurring with increasing
frequency along the border _ the use of infants and young children,
perhaps kidnapped, perhaps rented from impoverished parents, as
living props to bamboozle border agents.
</P>
<P>
   The baby ruse is just the latest wrinkle in the game of
cat-and-mouse between border agents and illegal-immigrant
smugglers, a game that has only intensified following recent
federal crackdowns and dramatic rises in the number of agents along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Smugglers, it seems, have discovered an inadvertent loophole on
the U.S. border. If illegal immigrants are taken in custody and
claim to be a family, especially with babies or young children,
they are simply cut loose and asked to report for a later court
date, as there are no facilities for housing families on the border
and agents say they do not want to split up families.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of letting families go began several years ago, but
has become more frequent since thousands of Central Americans have
tried to get into the United States in in the wake of Hurricane
Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that most of them don't show up for their court
date, but we do it for humanitarian reasons, because we don't have
the facilities and it's better than breaking up the family,
especially one that's already suffered something like Hurricane
Mitch,'' said Fernando Quiroja, who initially spearheaded the baby
investigation in Brownsville until it was transferred to the
federal antismuggling unit in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   This latest, particularly ugly wrinkle in the struggle between
smugglers and border agents picked up steam after a recent U.S.
crackdown along the border that has seen agents grow in number in
some stations by threefold. In Brownsville, the 18-month-old
Operation Rio Grande has increased the size of the locally based
force to more than 350. When Quiroja first joined the Brownsville
station a dozen years ago, there were fewer than 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Border Patrol is without doubt a more formidable presence
around here,'' said Ivan Welker, Brownsville's assistant city
manager. ``Back before Operation Rio Grande, down at the municipal
golf course near the border, golfers would routinely see groups of
people who had crossed the river coming out of the trees and
trotting across the golf course. You'd always be seeing groups of
people downtown who looked like maybe they didn't belong in
downtown Brownsville. Now, you don't see that. You don't see that
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Already last summer, when South Texas and much of the nation was
caught in a vicious drought and heat wave, border agents received
gruesome evidence of the desperate lengths smugglers were forced to
go in the form of the corpses of dozens of illegal immigrants who
had been led across the border in increasingly remote areas and
died from heat and lack of water.
</P>
<P>
   In Brownsville, illegal immigrants arrested in the last year
have reported that the price of being brought across the border had
risen from an average of $300 to $500 a few years ago to an average
of $1,400 to $1,800 today. And that is for Mexican nationals coming
across. Those traveling from farther away, like Hurricane Mitch
victims, must often pay much more.
</P>
<P>
   Border agents found themselves investigating g more cases
involving the use of unexpected and expensive modes of
transportation, including planes chartered out of Brownsville's
airport. A new route sprang up to bring illegal immigrants up the
Gulf coast from Mexico using a network of boats and ferries that
connected northern Mexico with Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   All along the border, from El Paso to the Rio Grande's mouth
near Brownsville, border agents have seen smugglers make increasing
use of the 18-wheel semis that are moving back and forth across the
border by the thousands since passage of the North American Free
Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't search every semi,'' Quiroja said. ``You'd back up
the whole border, and they know that. So they corrupt a few,
individual truck drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent, very typical case, a truck was found with 101
illegal immigrants hidden in its trailer. ``In cases like that, a
driver might make $100 to $500 a head,'' Quiroja said. ``Do the
math. That's $10,000 to $50,000, a lot of money. And the smugglers
are probably keeping $1,000 a head.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vidrio said she became convinced there was something fishy
about the mud-streaked infant when she spotted a turquoise and
red-bead bracelet on its right wrist, triggering the recent memory
of another Honduran illegal immigrant, a man claiming he had been
left alone with this very same infant when his wife was killed
during Hurricane Mitch. She peppered the young couple with
questions. In short order, the scheme unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The woman admitted, border officials said, that she had given
$1,000 to a smuggler in Matamoros, Mexico, just across from
Brownsville. The man had paid $1,050. They were both Honduran, but
had not known one another before they met at the smuggler's safe
house that day. They were given the baby, which they had never seen
before, and told to swim across the Rio Grande just upstream from
Brownsville and immediately give themselves up to border agents.
When being processed, they were to tell officials that they were a
family. Once given their court date and released, they were to
travel by bus to Houston and call the smuggler's accomplice from
the bus station.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was federal agents who called the number from the
Houston bus station. They arrested two men who arrived in response
to the call, both of whom were identified by the illegal
immigrants, now material witnesses in the federal probe, as among
the smugglers they had seen in Matamoros. The investigation led to
a Houston apartment where another woman was taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the couple who are the apparent real parents of
the infant walked into a Houston police station to report their
child kidnapped. They were taken into custody, and federal
officials suspect that they had actually rented the baby several
times to the smugglers, probably for as little as a few hundred
dollars. The baby is now with Child Protective Services in
Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury has been hearing the case in Houston and
was expected to hand down indictments, perhaps including the
infant's mother, as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials say they have uncovered at least three
instances in which this particular infant was used by smugglers,
but suspect it had been used even more often _ just as they suspect
that the same ruse, involving other children, is being used with
increasing frequency up and down the border, partly in response to
the federal crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vidrio said she was particularly incensed by the callous way
the baby was treated. In none of the three known cases, did the
phony parents carry extra diapers or a change of clothes for the
infant, or more than one bottle of infant formula. And they just
hopped into the Rio Grande and swam across the river with the baby.
``You can imagine what that baby must have gone through,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is apparently worth it to the smugglers who must find new
ways to circumvent the federal crackdown along the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of when you build a better mousetrap, the mice
have to get smarter,'' Quiroja said.
</P>
</TEXT>
