<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY RAISES $1 BILLION IN BOND SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments sold $1 billion in long-term debt Thursday
amid strong demand from institutions, which for the first time got
a detailed look at the giant fund company's finances.
</P>
<P>
   The bond sale, which was raised by $250 million from the
original $750 million, was priced so Fidelity will pay an interest
rate about 150 basis points higher than comparable Treasury bonds,
a yield reflecting investor confidence in the company, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   In documents circulated to prospective investors before the
sale, the company, which normally discloses little detail about its
operations, provided financial information that financial analysts
said suggested its total market value if it were publicly traded
would top $30 billion. Among the disclosures was that the company's
cash flow this year could be more than $2 billion before interest,
taxes, depreciation and amortization.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking perhaps is that Fidelity's fast-growing brokerage
business could garner a market valuation approaching that of the
company's core mutual fund and money-management business.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage business, with 2.6 million online accounts and an
average of 75,000 online transactions a day, is on pace to generate
more than $1 billion in revenue this year. If that revenue were
valued along the same lines as the revenues of Charles Schwab Co.
or E(ASTERISK)Trade Group, the Fidelity unit could have a
stand-alone market value of $12 billion to $15 billion, analysts
said, even after the 40 percent decline in online brokerage stocks
the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the luck of the draw, that brokerage business is worth
significantly more than the money management business, on a
multiple basis,'' said Dean Eberling, research director at Putnam,
Lovell, de Guardiola and Thornton in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's money-management business would be worth $15 billion
to $25 billion, analysts said, or 2 to 3 percent of its $800
billion in assets based on the valuations of public mutual fund
companies. Its majority stake in Colt Telecom Group PLC, a British
telecommunications concern that is publicly traded, is worth an
estimated $7.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Fidelity's offering were first reported in The Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   The bond sale has prompted speculation that Fidelity wants to
assess its potential valuation if chairman Edward C. Johnson III,
whose family owns about 49 percent of Fidelity's voting stock, ever
wants to take the company public or sell a piece to a large bank or
Wall Sreet firm. A public offering, analysts noted, could help
retain key employees who have equity stakes. It could also make it
easier for Johnson's daughter Abigail to take control of the
company, though Ms. Johnson, a senior Fidelity executive, already
owns 24.5 percent of the voting stock.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity officials reiterated Thursday that there were no plans
to sell anything. ``We really do like our private status,'' said
Tom Eidson, a company spokesman. ``We have absolutely no intention
of going public or selling off parts of the company, merging, or
making a large acquisition. It's just not in the cards.''
</P>
<P>
   In the debt offering led by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Fidelity
issued $750 million worth of 30-year bonds priced to yield 7.57
percent, and $250 million of 20-year bonds at 7.49 percent, yields
that compare with blue-chip financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, which has had about $1.5 billion in capital
expenditures in the last three years, has earmarked the funds for
technology, Internet operations and an expansion of its Texas
back-office operations, which is expected to cost several hundred
million dollars alone, according to people close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the factors driving this debt offering is the fact that
this can no longer be viewed as an industry that is not capital
intensive,'' said Burton Greenwald, a mutual-fund industry
consultant in Philadelphia. Companies like Fidelity, he said, are
now ``playing in a global environment and competing against a
handful of giant financial services organizations, driving the need
for capital for both more technology and marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line trading ventures have grabbed some of the spotlight in
recent months away from the mutual fund industry. But Fidelity's
ability to place this debt on fairly favorable terms,'' Greenwald
said, ``certainly suggests that some very sophisticated investors
are still extremely optimistic about the future of the fund
industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
