<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTER-JET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING DEFENDS WORK ON NAVY SUPER HORNET AGAINST CRITICAL GAO
REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A top Boeing executive took issue Thursday with a
General Accounting Office report that identified 84 deficiencies in
Boeing's new F/A-18E/F Super Hornet.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Wednesday, said the problems could cause
the attack fighter to fail its ongoing operational evaluation with
the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   It recommended the Defense Department not award Boeing an $8
billion multiyear contract for 222 of the new fighters until all
the deficiencies have been corrected, incorporated into the fighter
design and successfully tested.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sears, president of Boeing's Military Aircraft and Missile
System group in St. Louis, said the attack fighter has met all its
requirements, it should pass the operational evaluation, and
multiyear funding should be approved.
</P>
<P>
   If the multiyear contract is delayed, he said, taxpayers will be
the losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This multiyear buy saves the government nearly three quarters
of a billion dollars,'' Sears told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer
in an interview at the Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was telling a congressman, this is the Navy being a good
business manager, running their business well, saying, `We know we
are going to take these airplanes ... everything is going well ...
let's commit to the multiyear (deal) and save three quarters of a
billion dollars.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Super Hornet recently finished an extensive flight test
program and late last month began a six-month operational
evaluation. Based on that evaluation, the Pentagon is to decide in
March whether to begin full production.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the Navy, the F/A-18E/F is meeting all
performance,'' the GAO report said. ``We do not agree.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said the operational test schedule does not leave
enough time to fix the deficiencies before the full-rate production
decision is made.
</P>
<P>
   It identified deficiencies in the plane's performance as well as
its ability to detect enemy missiles during combat maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Hornet has the Navy's highest acquisition priority.
The Navy wants to buy 548 of the jets for an estimated $46 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A recommendation to award Boeing the multiyear Super Hornet
contract was made in an April memo to Defense Secretary William
Cohen from Jacques Gansler, the Pentagon's acquisition chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Testing to date has been very successful and so far looks very
promising for a future multiyear buy,'' Gansler wrote to Cohen and
Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler said a five-year purchase of 222 Super Hornets for $8.8
billion would save the Navy more than $700 million from 2002
through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The multiyear buy requires congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   Even a year's delay in approving the contract would amount to a
``significant'' amount of lost savings, Sears said. That's because
earlier production planes are the most expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The multiyear contract, similar to what Boeing received to
supply 120 of its C-17 cargo transport planes to the Air Force,
would ensure production of the company's most important fighter
plane for the life of the contract. It would protect the program
against possible cuts in defense spending for fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Hornet, which is now in low-rate production in St.
Louis, is a bigger and more advanced version of the F-18C/D Hornet,
the Navy's mainstay carrier fighter.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Hornet's fuselage is 4 feet loner than the F/A-18 C/D,
its wing is 25 percent larger to store more fuel, and it has
upgraded engines.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Hornet was designed to have a longer range and be able
to carry more weapons for either air-to-air combat or bombing
ground targets.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Hornet is one of the military's biggest arms programs
and one of Boeing's most important military airplane projects.
</P>
<P>
   Production of the Super Hornet is starting just as production is
winding down for Boeing's F-18C/D Hornet and the F-15 flown by the
Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 Boeing workers build the wings and forward fuselage
of the Super Hornet in St. Louis, where final assembly takes place.
Subcontractor Northrop Grumman builds aft and center fuselage
sections in California.
</P>
<P>
   At peak production, Boeing expects to make about 48 Super
Hornets a year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gansler's memo said the Super Hornet has met or
exceeded all key performance goals, the plane's flight test program
was not without problems.
</P>
<P>
   Something called ``wing drop'' first appeared on test flights in
early 1996. The jet would lose lift and unexpectedly roll to the
left or right during certain high-speed dogfighting maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Wing drop was just one of 29 deficiencies in the Super Hornet
cited in an operational test report last summer. All those
deficiencies have been corrected, the Navy has said.
</P>
<P>
   Sears said that in the fall of 1991, a program was put in place
to take the Super Hornet from development into production, and in
the process go through all the critical milestones that are part of
the acquisition process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single one of those milestones over the last seven and a
half years have been met, every single one,'' Sears said. ``The
airplane is meeting every technical requirement .... So if you look
at that data and say, `What is the risk of having a problem during
Opeval' (operational evaluation)?' you would have to say it is
small, because for seven and a half years, we have met every
milestone along the way. This (operational evaluation) is just one
more milestone in a very disclipined acquisition process.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the respected publication Defense Daily reported
that the Super Hornet had received approval for several minor
temporary waivers for technical issues that needed to be solved in
additional testing.
</P>
<P>
   On issue cited by Defense Daily is a strobe light that must
still be installed under the jet to identify it as an E/F, rather
than the C/D Hornet. The light will permit carrier landing
personnel to correctly set deck mechanisms for the proper airplane
weight.
</P>
<P>
   None of the issues, Defense Daily reported, involve changes in
the Pentagon's five requirements for the aircraft: increased range,
increased weapons carriage, increased growth potential, increased
survivability and increased bringback.
</P>
<P>
   Survivability refers to the plane's stealth. Bringback refers to
the ability of the plane to return with its weapons and fuel loads
to the carrier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
