<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVEST DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is a Stock Offering Near At an On-Line Magazine? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is Forbes Inc., publisher of the glossy business magazine,
planning to sell its Internet jewels to the public through an
initial offering?
</P>
<P>
   According to an internal memo dated May 7, Timothy Forbes, chief
operating officer, said the company was ``in discussion with
investment bankers exploring possibilities for our Internet
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some Internet analysts, a possible offering of
Forbes.com, which includes sites for several Forbes magazines,
raises the chances that other business or investment magazines,
like Smart Money, will spin off their on-line divisions as initial
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, this is a business where maintaining a talent
base is predicated on the ability to build equity,'' said Patrick
Keane, an analyst at Jupiter Communications, a research firm in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes declined to comment on a possible offering of Forbes.com.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the company said that the site _ which is free
and generally attracts a younger audience than Forbes magazine _
had about 3.3 million visitors during the 30 days that ended in
mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes.com is a rival of TheStreet.com, an on-line service in
which The New York Times Co. owns a minority stake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sana Siwolop &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Springtime for Hedge Funds &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been a profitable spring for many hedge fund managers. In
May, hedge funds outperformed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index, the second month in a row that they have done so, according
to Van Hedge Fund Advisors International, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds returned 1.2 percent, on average, for the month
while the S&AMP;P 500 lost 2.4 percent. For the first five months of
the year, the average hedge fund has returned 10.7 percent, versus
6.5 percent for the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, hedge funds are shining in the current market
environment,'' said George P. Van, chairman of the firm. ``If the
year continues to be volatile, hedge funds could produce superior
returns and provide valuable downside protection in traditional
long-only portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   Among United States hedge funds, the best-performing types in
May were the so-called opportunistic funds, which can use a variety
of investment approaches. Those returned 4.6 percent for the month.
The worst performers were the market timers, which switch in and
out of various asset classes to take advantage of upturns and
selloffs. They lost 3.6 percent, on average.
</P>
<P>
   For the year through May, the best class was the ``macro''
funds, which use a top-down approach to take advantage of changes
in international interest rates or currencies. Those funds returned
18.8 percent, on average, for the five months. The worst were
short-selling funds, which returned just 1.3 percent, on average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Market-Neutral Funds: A Category Stuck in Reverse? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the newer varieties of mutual funds is called ``market
neutral.'' Such funds keep half their portfolios in stocks, usually
chosen because of attractive valuations. The other half is sold
short, meaning that the manager borrows shares and resells them,
hoping they will fall in price so they can be replaced at a lower
cost.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to produce positive returns regardless of the
market's direction.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher, tracks five
market-neutral funds, none of them more than two years old. But
according to a Morningstar study, each fund has lost money from its
inception through April.
</P>
<P>
   The causes, according to Morningstar, are annual expense ratios
that top 2.0 percent on average, portfolio turnover of more than
200 percent, and poor stock-picking.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
