<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDREGON MOVES QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cruz Pedregon is proving to be as fast off the drag strip as he
ever was on.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1992 National Hot Rod Association Funny Car
champion parted company with Joe Gibbs Racing just three weeks ago,
he has already begun to form a new team and is expecting to compete
at the All-Star Winston No-Bull Showdown in early July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have seemed like it then, but it really wasn't a bad
thing (to leave Gibbs),'' said Pedregon, who owns some of the
quickest and fastest passes ever in the Funny Car division. ``It
just set the stage for my future. I've known for a long time that I
wanted to own the next car I drove.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedregon, who was rumored as a possible driver for the John
Force entry into the Top Fuel ranks, will do that. He has already
obtained a Pontiac Firebird and is now in the process of forming a
crew and securing sponsorship for his new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've set our sights on Bristol,'' said Pedregon, who despite
missing the past two national events is still in fourth place in
the point standings. ``We're burning the midnight oil, doing
whatever it takes to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedregon's quick formation of his new team has been no surprise
to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was preparing for it all along,'' said Pedregon's older
brother, Frank, himself a driver in the Funny Car wars. ``It was a
surprise to some (that he wanted to leave to form his own team),
but not really for him. There's always been this talk that Gibbs
might just go on and stick with NASCAR. So Cruz was at the
position, `Hey, I'd better start looking into that.' And now is as
good a time as any.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll run Bristol, run a few races this year and get ready for
a hard charge at 2000.'
</P>
<P>
   A change in drivers did little to alter the lack of
starting-line performance of the Gibbs' Funny Car.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Top Fueler Tommy Johnson Jr.'s debut at this past
weekend's Pontiac Excitement Nationals saw him lose on a hole shot
in the first round. Johnson ran a 5.083-second pass compared to
Frank Burkart's winning 5.087.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the first round my main concern was to keep the car
straight,'' Johnson said. ``I was having trouble getting used to
the steering in qualifying and as a result I wasn't keeping the car
in the groove. When I got to the starting line (Sunday) I gave more
thought about keeping the car in the narrow grove than leaving on
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also didn't expect Burkart to make the kind of run he did.
Give him credit, he made his best run of the weekend when it
counted.''
</P>
<P>
   Covina's Andy Manna Jr. doubled up on opposition this past
weekend, winning at both the Federal Mogul All-Star race on
Saturday and the Pontiac Excitement Nationals on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Manna, who competes in the NHRA Competition eliminator sportsman
class, defeated Mike Saye in the Federal Mogul All-Star final with
a 8.536-second pass. He then ripped off a 8.503 to defeat Robert
Bailey in the Competition Eliminator final on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Higa, a resident of Millani, Hawaii, and Adam Saruwatari
were the big winners last weekend at the IDRC West Coast Nationals
at Pomona Raceway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
