<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-LOTTERY18-COX     06-17 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LOTTERY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor appoints new Florida lottery chief
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSE, Fla. _ Florida's new lottery secretary doesn't
intend to gamble with multistate games anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position is you need to look back in your state to maximize
revenues,'' said David Griffin, a Republican appointed Thursday by
Gov. Jeb Bush to the $105,000-per-year job.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, 36, is a businessman with a law degree who rose to
assistant executive director of the Ohio Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The captain of Penn State's 1984 basketball team, Griffin, who
is married with two children, said he does not play the lottery
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said his priorities are to run an efficient, ethical
department while studying how to increase sales that have sagged
from a $2.3 billion peak in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He leans away from multistate games such as Powerball, which
Bush recently rejected, and video lottery machines, which the
Legislature considered, but rejected this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had his eye on Griffin even before he named Sue
Cobb interim lottery secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to David in the transition and found him to be an
excellent candidate at that time,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, Griffin also served as interim director in a lottery
also suffering sales declines and similar to Florida's 12-year-old
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin excelled at negotiating contracts _ one saved the state
$1 million _ and was ``very self-confident,'' said Ohio Lottery
Director Mitchell J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown chalked up sales declines to competition from casinos and
other gambling, among other economic reasons _ not a failure of
management.
</P>
<P>
   Among the outside challenges to the lottery in Florida is gaming
operations run by Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   A change in federal rules last April allows the Secretary of the
Interior to intervene when states refuse to allow Indian tribes to
operate gambling casinos, although Florida is suing to block the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
