<SLUG> BC-SUBURBAN-WILDLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBAN GROWTH DRIVES WILDLIFE INTO POPULATED AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After wandering at least 100 miles, a 175-pound black bear found
its way into the heart of the business district of West Haven,
Conn., about 2 a.m. on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Some police officers, all rookies at capturing a downtown bear,
gave chase, imitating barking dogs as they ran. Their first yelps
were feeble, recalled West Haven's animal control officer, Judy
Rettig. ``They were barking like Chihuahuas,'' she said. ``I said,
`Rottweilers, men, Rottweilers!'''
</P>
<P>
   The bear dashed through the parking lot of a video store, past
some startled students outside their dormitory at the University of
New Haven, and up a tree. In short order, the bear was
tranquilized, tagged and transferred to the woods of northwestern
Connecticut, almost a year after conservationists in New York state
tagged it deep in the Catskill Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rettig is plenty busy these days. Once she was simply West
Haven's dog warden. But the job description grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just do dogs anymore,'' she said. ``Now we're bear
control, raccoon control, possum control. You name it. No day is
the same anymore. You never know what you're going to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the New York region, wildlife biologists and
ecologists echo her sentiments. The world of wildlife is far
different from what it was a generation ago, as more housing eats
into once distant wilderness. All sorts of species no longer stay
secluded in deep woods. They are popping up in odd spots: moose on
the developing outer fringes of suburbia; coyotes, fox, deer and
the ubiquitous Canada geese in older suburban towns; bears and
turkeys in cities.
</P>
<P>
   Development has disturbed the instincts of animals and their
natural fear of people, wildlife experts say. The steady push of
people into once-rural areas has eroded woodland habitats and
reduced the open space for yearlings and weaned animals as they
follow their instincts and leave their birthplaces to search for
their own turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what's in front of them,'' said James
Applegate, a wildlife ecologist at Cook College, part of Rutgers
University in New Jersey. ``Now, in any direction it heads, it will
run into trouble sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kilpatrick, a biologist with the Connecticut Department
of Environmental Protection, said that animals ``just wander
randomly.'' A meandering animal ``has no perception of what's down
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   William Weber, a wildlife ecologist with the Wildlife
Conservation Society, based at the Bronx Zoo, said that the
animals' final destinations are a matter of chance. ``Some of them
head in the right direction and they wind up in other forest,'' he
said. ``Some wind up in suburbia. If we just keep clearing
everything and animals keep getting squeezed, they're going to
disappear, or they'll settle in our own backyards.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Smallwood, an ecologist at the University of Richmond,
notes that a ``behavioral evolution'' has enabled animals to live
more comfortably than their predecessors near houses and humans.
``I strongly suspect some of what we're seeing with this wildlife
invasion is changes of behavior by cultural evolution,'' he said.
``They're learning how to get along in the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   If these vagabond animals feel safe to eat and breed in a new
domain near people, they will stay, experts say. ``They'll learn to
eat what you plant in your backyard,'' said Susan Predl, a wildlife
biologist with the New Jersey Department of Environmental
Protection.
</P>
<P>
   For years, deer have roamed Barbara and Nick Van De Giesen's
front yard in the Bergen County borough of Old Tappan, N.J. Over
the Memorial Day weekend, a doe jumped the fence surrounding their
backyard and gave birth. At first, the doe nursed the fawn in the
seclusion of white pines and underbrush at the rear of the yard.
Now the feedings occur in the unsheltered front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Once, moose were content to stay in northern New York and
northern New England. But in the last two years, their wandering
has taken them to Kingston, N.Y.; Branchville, in northwestern New
Jersey, and northern Connecticut. Last June, a 500-pound female
moose meandered all the way to Old Saybrook on the Connecticut
coast before a car hit and killed it on Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   Peregrine falcons, once nearly extinct, now nest on bridges and
office buildings in New York City and thrive on the flocks of
pigeons. A pair of red-tailed hawks has a nest on a luxury
apartment building at Fifth Avenue and 74th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Wild turkeys are thriving in the region because of
rehabilitation programs started in the 1980s. In late winter, eight
wild turkeys rummaged around the suburban homes in West Orange,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Like the red-tailed hawks, turkeys have reached New York City.
They were spotted this year at Orchard Beach in the Bronx, on ball
fields in nearby City Island and at the Bronx Zoo near the flamingo
pen.
</P>
<P>
   Even coyotes, normally shy and furtive, are just about
everywhere in the region, wildlife ecologists and biologists said.
On April Fool's Day, one found its way to Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very, very adaptable, much more adaptable than we
thought 30 years ago,'' said Robert Eriksen, supervisor in charge
of wildlife control for New Jersey's environmental department.
Normally, coyotes eat rabbits, squirrels and other small wild
animals. But Eriksen and other experts cautioned that pet cats left
out at night are becoming a favorite prey.
</P>
<P>
   Weber said that coyotes are starting to ``behave like wolves''
and form hunting packs on the edges of the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, deer have made it to urban areas like
Elizabeth, N.J., and East Rutherford, near Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And black bears are not only reaching West Haven; some have also
made it to downtown New Brunswick and Trenton. Last Friday, a bear
was spotted in Morristown, N.J., near the town's busiest stores.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, calls about nuisance bears have increased from 15 to
330 a year in a seven-county region of southern New York just north
of New York City, including Westchester, Rockland and Orange, said
Dick Henry, a big-game biologist with the state's Department of
Environmental Conservation. He estimates that there are 4,000 bears
in the state. Glenn Cole, a wildlife biologist who is Henry's
colleague, recalls a black bear that broke through the screen door
of a house near Kingston and helped itself to a fresh apple pie and
some cookies on a kitchen counter, before fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's bear population is estimated at 30 to 60, double
the estimate in 1994. Paul Rego, a state wildlife biologist, said
that in the first five months of this year, the state received 70
calls of bear sightings, up from 25 in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since New Jersey banned bear hunting in 1971, the state's bear
population has doubled to about 600, and some seem to be getting
more aggressive toward other animals, said Dave Chanda, a state
wildlife biologist. Earlier this year, he said, a bear killed a
llama in a pen in Rockaway Township.
</P>
<P>
   People in southern New York are increasingly gripped with
``bearanoia,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, the people fear they'll eat the kids and
eat the house,'' he said. ``Bears live around people a lot better
than people live around bears.'' Henry said black bears are not
known to bite or cuff at people unless people try to touch them.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, environmental officials in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut have prepared leaflets with tips on reducing encounters
with bears. Bears are attracted to the grain in bird feeders, bee
hives, table scraps left on compost piles, uncovered garbage cans
and greasy barbecue grills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
