<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINSTON WEST KEEPS GROWING
</HEADLINE>
 WEST-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE -- In NASCAR, the trickle-down theory stretches to
more than just the Busch Grand National and Craftsman Truck series.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest benefactors has been the organization's
Winston West series. The series, which is in its 45th year, has
more prize money, more rookie drivers, more returning drivers and
more publicity than ever before. The series makes its first
appearance at Irwindale on Saturday night in the Irwindale 250,
presented by Jan's Towing.
</P>
<P>
   Winston West spokesman Kevin Green says there's two simple
reasons for the upsurge in the division: money and new tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growth has been unprecedented,'' he said. ``The series has
had its ups and downs through the years, but Winston sees potential
for growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, R.J. Reynolds posted $50,000 to the series'
points fund. Last year, it boosted the fund to $300,000, the same
amount it will award this season. The overall funds are expected to
surpass $500,000 for the 14-race series this year, which will
include two Irwindale events and a season-finale points race in
Motegi, Japan. Saturday's purse is $107,526.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really like any other business,'' said series points
leader Mike Chase, who commutes from Concord, N.C. to the west to
race. ``It's supply and demand. If you have the right supply and
good luck, you can make some good money racing this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Chase, who won the series title in 1994, nor Bill
Sedgwick, who won the series title in 1991 and 1992, raced in the
series last year. Both cited the formation of the Craftsman Truck
series and money stagnations for the diluting of talent in the
series in 1994. Chase, Sedgwick, Butch Gilliland, Ron Hornaday,
Mike Skinner, Jack Sprague and Rick Carelli, now all top drivers in
the Truck and Winston Cup series, left in droves.
</P>
<P>
   But then, western superspeedways in populated areas began
popping up: California Speedway in Fontana, Las Vegas Motor
Speedway and Pikes Peak in Fountain, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracks were being built, the money came up and now there's
really good racing,'' said Chino Hills' Gilliland, who won the last
NWWS race, at Mesa Marin Speedway in Bakersfield. ``This is just
showing the growth of racing on the West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer are drivers fleeing the series for any ride in any
division. Chase says he turned down a ride in the Truck series this
year to race in the NWWS. Mike Wallace, who has run in the Winston
Cup series, has raced in three of the events, winning two. The
brother of Winston Cup veterans Rusty and Kenny Wallace, and former
NWWS champion Ron Hornaday -- last year's Truck champion -- will
race in the Truck series tonight in Portland and compete at
Irwindale Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Other Winston Cup regulars to have taken part in this year's
races include Jerry Nadeau, Bobby Hamilton Jr., Ricky Craven and
Ken Schrader.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are a record 18 rookies running the series
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a newer group of kids and some really good older
drivers, like Chase, who have dropped back to Winston West,'' said
El Monte's Kenny Smith, who runs a limited NWWS schedule. ``We get
these bigger drivers here and it can be tough to run against their
(money) every race. Even in my situation (as a multi-million dollar
lottery winner), I cannot afford to run with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase said it has made it more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be probably six to eight guys who could win at
any given time,'' he said. ``Now, there's 12 to 15 guys who can win
any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winston West cars are similar to Winston Cup cars except for
compression ratio and tires. Approved models in both series must be
the Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Pontiac Grands Prix and Ford Thunderbird
and Taurus. The car must weigh at least 3,400 pounds and have a
110-inch wheelbase.
</P>
<P>
   The differences in engine compression is 12.5:1 for Winston Cup
and 9.5:1 for Winston West. Winston West has specific tire
specifications for each track. At Irwindale, all cars must run
Goodyear W-2 on the left side and W-4 on the right side, or Hoosier
1011 on the left and 1014 on the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think drivers in our series aspire with the idea to go from
the West to the three major series, Winston Cup, Truck, and (Busch)
Grand National,'' Green said. ``Running the West is the opportunity
for them to gain experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick says the series is a perfect training ground for
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Winston Cup or in Craftsman Trucks, if you don't qualify
each week, you can't get the experience,'' the Acton resident said.
``You go home without getting experience. In Winston West, you have
a better chance. You can work on things every week and save your
tires.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
