<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICKELSON SHARES LEAD BUT MAY NOT STICK AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., N.C.)   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ His wife is expecting a child June 30, and
until Tuesday morning, Phil Mickelson was not sure he would play in
this year's U.S. Open. Winning a major championship is very
important to Mickelson. But he said the birth of his first child,
and the health of his wife, Amy, rank much higher.
</P>
<P>
   So with his caddie carrying a beeper, and with a private plane
waiting to take him back to Scottsdale, Ariz., at a moment's
notice, Mickelson teed off this morning, and, for a few hours,
turned his attention from fatherhood to fairways. If his wife goes
into labor before the tournament ends, he vows he will leave, no
matter what, to be by her side. But if the beeper stays quiet, and
if Mickelson stays on the same path, his first major championship
and his first child may both arrive this month.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying the all-round talent that makes him a threat to win
here on a course that suits his skills, Mickelson finished at
three-under-par 67 and shared the first-round lead with three other
players. Joining Mickelson at 67 were David Duval, the world's No.
1-ranked player _ who performed well despite having slightly burned
his right hand last Friday _ and two players who have never
contended at a U.S. Open, Billy Mayfair and Paul Goydos.
</P>
<P>
   Five players were tied at 68, one stroke off the lead, led by
Tiger Woods, who birdied his last two holes; John Daly, who has
struggled this year but who has won two majors in his career; Payne
Stewart, the 1991 Open champion; David Berganio Jr. and Kaname
Yokoo of Japan. A host of other familiar names hovered near the
lead _ Jim Furyk, Justin Leonard, Vijay Singh and Hal Sutton are
among the 13 players at 69 _ setting up a weekend filled with
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day when Pinehurst Resort and Country Club's fabled No.
2 course proved it would be a difficult test, no matter what the
conditions. Heavy rain Wednesday night became steady rain this
morning, and it lasted until midday, softening Pinehurst's
turtleback greens. If ever a low score could be had on this
difficult course, this was the day to shoot it.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinehurst's excellent drainage system, coupled with
difficult pin placements, kept the teeth in the course, and many
players felt its wrath. By afternoon, the sun was out, the course
was drying, and it became apparent that it would be difficult for
anyone to shoot lower than 67.
</P>
<P>
   So Mickelson finished his round excited to share first place and
glad that his beeper had stayed quiet. As for the future, Mickelson
hoped that his wife's doctor was as accurate with the due date as
Mickelson was with his putter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting it to be at least June 30, possibly a little
more, according to the doctor,'' Mickelson said. ``She's seeing the
doctor every day, but with labor, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would leave the tournament if he was tied for the
lead Sunday morning and the beeper went off, Mickelson said that he
would.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate to be able to have a child,'' said
Mickelson, who turned 29 on Wednesday. ``We thought we were going
to have problems, and it came very easily. That's something I don't
want to miss. I have a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to be there,
whereas the U.S. Open takes place every year. I didn't know if I
would feel that way or not. But if she punches in that code, I'm
out. I'm getting a car as soon as I can and getting to the
airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, from the first hole until the last Thursday, Mickelson
managed to focus on golf. Possessing one of the world's best short
games, Mickelson used that skill to deftly navigate his way around
Pinehurst's treacherous greens, saving strokes with his putting and
chipping in situations where many others faltered.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing to stay with his wife until the last possible moment,
Mickelson didn't arrive at Pinehurst until Tuesday night, and he
played only one practice round, on Wednesday. But he looked as if
he had been hanging around all week. He got off to a sizzling
start, making birdies on three of the first five holes. On No. 2,
he made an 18-foot putt for birdie. On the par-5 fourth, he hit a
radar-like pitching wedge approach to 8 feet that led to a birdie
putt. And then Mickelson birdied one of Pinehurst's toughest holes,
No. 5, chipping in from 25 feet off the edge of the green.
</P>
<P>
   After making bogeys at Nos. 6 and 8, Mickelson regrouped with
birdies at Nos. 13 and 14. Mickelson's putter did the trick at the
13th, where he made a splendid downhill 30-footer. Then at 14,
Mickelson hit a nice 9-iron approach shot from 135 yards to within
8 feet of the cup, setting up his birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   While Mickelson obviously had reason to be distracted, he looked
upon his late arrival this week as a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practice rounds at major tournaments are a chore,'' he
said. ``It's a six-hour round, you're supposed to sign autographs
all day, and you're trying to prepare for one of the biggest
tournaments of the year. I feel like I like I'm much fresher.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval looked fresh as well, playing in the same group with
Mickelson. After burning his right thumb and forefinger on a pot
while making tea last week, Duval arrived at Pinehurst not knowing
how much the burns would hinder him. But they did not bother him at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove the ball well, hit my irons where I was trying to, and
I made a few putts,'' said Duval, who has won 11 times since
October 1997 but who is still looking to win his first major. ``I'd
be very content to do that for three more days.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Mickelson, but first he must get the opportunity to
play for three more days. A licensed pilot, Mickelson said he might
fly the plane back to Arizona himself if his wife called, although
he had a co-pilot available.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the tournament remained wide open. The greens were
soft Thursday, yet approach shots that were not placed perfectly
still rolled off the greens, down the slopes and into trouble. So
while Mickelson was smiling after his round, he and his peers knew
that the fun had just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best test of golf that I've played in a major
championship,'' Mickelson said. ``It tests every area of your game.
I think were in for a long weekend if the greens dry out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
