<HEADLINE>
BOEING WRAPS UP PARIS AIR SHOW WITH FINAL FLURRY OF ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Boeing Co. wrapped up a successful Paris Air Show
Thursday with firm orders for 25 more airplanes worth about $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The final flurry of orders raised Boeing's tally during the
world's biggest and oldest air show to 62 firm orders for airplanes
worth about $3 billion at list prices.
</P>
<P>
   The total does not include 50 next generation 737s ordered by
International Lease Finance Corp. Boeing said it did not include
that order in its official tally because the contract will not be
signed until next month, even though it was Boeing's highlight
order announcement of the air show.
</P>
<P>
   If those orders by International Lease are included, Boeing
announced firm orders for 112 airplanes worth more than $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   International Lease also took options for 50 more next
generation 737s.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Boeing orders announced at the show were for the
twin-engine next generation 737.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing came into the air show having made public only 52 firm
orders worth about $3.9 billion at list prices during the first
five months of 1999. So Boeing more than doubled its 1999 order
book in less than a week at the air show.
</P>
<P>
   That is not surprising. Traditionally, Boeing and rival Airbus
Industrie save orders so they can announce them at the air show.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus entered the air show saying it had 153 firm orders this
year. But it is difficult to calculate the Airbus tally at the
show.
</P>
<P>
   The European airplane maker issued a statement Thursday saying
that about 53 of its announced air show orders were actually
commitments rather than firm orders.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg news reported that if those commitments are included,
the European planemaker had 146 orders and commitments valued at
$6.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But that figure includes a 30-plane order by International Lease
for the new A318. Even though that firm order was announced during
the air show, Airbus had included those planes in the 153 firm
orders it claimed to have going into the air show.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Airbus said Northwest Airlines Corp. will buy 30
single-aisle Airbus Industrie planes worth $1.2 billion, as it
converts options for the jets into firm orders. Northwest will buy
18 A319 planes, which seat 124, and 12 A320s, seating 150, with
deliveries to begin in January 2002 and wrap up in 2004. The
options were first taken in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The orders announced by Boeing Thursday included six next
generation 737-600s ordered by Southwest Airlines. The planes are
scheduled to be delivered in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
