<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-PRODUCTIVITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD RAISES PRODUCTIVITY AT ITS PLANTS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The big difference in labor productivity between
American and Japanese automakers in the 1980s, then a matter of
considerable dismay in the United States, has been sharply reduced
by Ford, but General Motors and DaimlerChrysler still lag,
according to a comprehensive study released on Thursday..
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, Japanese car makers enjoyed a labor cost
advantage of roughly $1,000 a vehicle, adjusted for inflation,
according to Harbour &AMP; Associates, a manufacturing-consultant in
Troy, Mich., which published its annual productivity report on
Thursday. The labor cost difference has persisted for GM and
DaimlerChrysler, which have only improved as quickly as the
Japanese makers.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford has cut the gap in half, and has nearly eliminated it,
if Ford's huge costs for retired workers are excluded. Ford
factories are now almost as efficient and in some case more so than
Japanese-owned factories in North America, which in turn are almost
as efficient as Japanese company factories at home.
</P>
<P>
   Because the majority of Japanese-brand cars sold in North
America are now assembled here, Detroit automakers now compete most
directly with North American factories, unlike in the 1980s, when
they competed mainly with cars from plants in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the number of hours of labor needed to produce each
vehicle, the most efficient assembly plant in North America last
year was the Toyota Corolla factory in Cambridge, Ontario, which
required 17.66 hours for a vehicle. The next two in order of
productivity were the Ford Taurus factories in Atlanta and Chicago,
at 17.72 and 18.09 hours of labor a vehicle, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The most efficient light-truck factory in North America last
year was the Ford Explorer sport utility vehicle factory in
Louisville, Ky., at 19.29 hours. It was the first time that an
American-owned factory has led either of Harbour's lists of the
most efficient car and light-truck factories.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's overall productivity in North America is now almost the
same as that of Nissan, Honda and Toyota, according to the report.
By contrast, GM and DaimlerChrysler still require nearly 50 percent
more labor for a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Harbour, the president of Harbour &AMP; Associates, said that
GM and DaimlerChrysler were still spending billions of dollars
annually for unscheduled overtime, mainly because of
factory-equipment breakdowns and the need to repair cars that do
not come off the assembly line in salable condition. By contrast,
he said, Ford has done a much better job maintaining factories and
managing production to avoid unscheduled overtime.
</P>
<P>
   GM issued a statement on Thursday noting that it had two
factories on Harbour's list of the 10 most efficient car assembly
plants, and two more on the list of the most efficient light- truck
factories. The GM factories were near the bottom of each list. Ford
had four of the most efficient car factories and six of the most
efficient light-truck factories.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler had no factories on either list. David Barnas, a
DaimlerChrysler spokesman, said that the automaker believes it has
an edge in vehicle design. Harbour said that DaimlerChrysler's
profits a vehicle, at $1,470 last year, were the highest in the
world, partly because of attractive designs and also because of the
company's heavy reliance on sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks
and minivans, which are all very profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's wage and benefit costs now exceed those in Japanese-owned
factories in North America by only $154 a vehicle, according to
Thursday's report. The cost of pensions and retiree benefits put
Ford at an additional disadvantage of $348 a vehicle because Ford
has as many retirees as active workers.The Japanese factories in
North America have virtually no retirees.
</P>
<P>
   GM and DaimlerChrysler's wage and benefit costs lag behind the
Japanese by roughly $500 a vehicle. Their retiree costs are also
slightly higher than Ford's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
