<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.C.-LIGHTHOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTHOUSE IS SAVED FROM THE BATTERING SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Ohio, N.Y., Md.)  (mk) 
 By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUXTON, N.C. _ In a steady downpour with a powerful surf
crashing nearby, the 128-year-old Cape Hatteras Lighthouse began
its journey Thursday toward a new resting place.
</P>
<P>
   Using a sophisticated hydraulic system, movers pushed the
4,800-ton structure about 10 feet. Within two months, the
lighthouse will move 2,900 feet into the scrub pines, far from the
encroaching ocean that was threatening its foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a great sense of satisfaction,'' said Robert Reynolds,
the superintendent of the Cape Hatteras National Seashore, who
stood on the lighthouse balcony, nearly 200 feet up, through the
first five inches of the move.
</P>
<P>
   For Reynolds and others on North Carolina's Outer Banks who
worked to relocate the lighthouse, moving day has been a long time
coming. The National Parks Service first proposed repositioning the
lighthouse in 1988, but it was only last year that Congress
appropriated nearly $12 million to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The parks service, which cares for the lighthouse building while
the Coast Guard maintains its light, believed the only way to save
the building from the ocean that had crept to within 150 feet was
to move it. When it was built in 1870, it was 1,600 feet away from
the surf. Although it will be moving 2,900 linear feet, because of
the curving shoreline, the lighthouse will once more be 1,600 feet
from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was met here with some derision by folks who considered
moving the nation's tallest lighthouse akin to spraying graffiti on
the White House. They had suggested building a sea wall instead to
stop the erosion, something not allowed under North Carolina
coastal regulations. But they maintained the move would destroy a
piece of history. Plus, it could crack, crumble or tip over, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   None of that happened on Thursday, and the simmering
disagreement was not apparent. But some who came to see the
lighthouse in place one last time said it was bittersweet to see it
stripped from its granite base and resting on a mat of huge steel
beams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a different animal now,'' said Ron Berlinguet, a
real estate appraiser from Richmond, Va., who has vacationed on the
Outer Banks almost every year since 1969. ``Now it's being moved,
it doesn't seem that solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Cape Hatteras Lighthouse was built on a spit on the Outer Banks,
a thin sea island in the northern section of North Carolina, to
replace one nearby that had been damaged in the Civil War. The
light helped boaters navigate the perilous Diamond Shoals, which
were responsible for the hundreds of shipwrecks that gave this area
the nickname, Graveyard of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise in modern navigation equipment, the light had
become much less essential, but the allure of the black-and
white-striped lighthouse remained unchanged. Vacationers _ about
250,000 _ make pilgrimages here every year; motorists look for the
light in the distance as they trek across Pamlico Sound.
</P>
<P>
   More than a thousand people streamed into the park Thursday to
glimpse the lighthouse. One hundred hydraulic jacks and two sensors
will make sure the structure stays level as it moves. Top speed
will likely be 100 feet each day. The move is so slow, it is all
but imperceptible, ``like watching kudzu grow,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 500 or so people watching when the lighthouse moved
the first few feet did not respond until a parks service volunteer
announced the news. Then they clapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It moved easier than we thought it would,'' said Jim Matyako,
one of the owners of Expert House Movers of Maryland, which along
with International Chimney Corp. of Buffalo, N.Y., is conducting
the move.
</P>
<P>
   Matyako said he was not particularly worried about the challenge
of actually moving the structure. More daunting, he said, was
lifting the lighthouse five feet to make it even with the ground.
The job is one of the heaviest his company has undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're usually through with a move in two weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   International Chimney relocated all three lighthouses that were
moved in recent years, but the tallest of those _ Southeast
Lighthouse on Block Island, R.I. _ is only a third as tall as the
Cape Hatteras structure.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Expert House Movers moved the two keepers
houses, an oil storage building and some cisterns to the new
location for the Cape Hatteras light. The buildings are arranged
exactly as they were on the original site. The Park Service expects
the lighthouse and surrounding buildings to be open by Memorial Day
2000.
</P>
<P>
   One person who is looking forward to that time is 8-year-old
Ryan George of Bergholz, Ohio, who came out Thursday to see what
was happening with the lighthouse. He is a lighthouse climber, and
he climbed the Hatteras light last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to count the steps but couldn't make it,'' he said,
clutching a World Wrestling Federation magazine and looking up at
the lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing they can move it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berlinguet, the real estate appraiser, agrees, but adds, ``Once
they move it, the beach will probably start building back and the
man upstairs will be laughing at all of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
