<HEADER>
A0160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-JOURNEYMAN-     06-17 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-JOURNEYMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE SPURS' JACKSON, LONG RANGE OF EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Jaren Jackson of the San Antonio Spurs is
not surprised that opponents often challenge him to sling
3-pointers from the outside. After all, he has had his doubters
before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, throughout most of his professional basketball career,
Jackson has been perhaps the only person with faith in his skills.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a nine-year veteran, has played for eight franchises in
the National Basketball Association, four of which cut him and two
of which sent him looking for work after he toiled through
consecutive 10-day contracts.
</P>
<P>
   If that were the extent of Jackson's basketball-related travels
and tribulations, it would be the story of one of the emerging
stars of this championship series, with the Knicks also being a
noteworthy story.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, who supplemented Tim Duncan's dominance down low by
scoring 17 points in the Spurs' 89-77 victory in Game 1 on
Wednesday, has overcome much more than being undervalued by the
Nets, Golden State, the Los Angeles Clippers, Portland,
Philadelphia, Houston and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-6-inch swingman has experienced life in the
Continental Basketball Association, touring the heartland to play
before tiny crowds with the Wichita Falls Texans, the La Crosse
Catbirds, the Pittsburgh Piranhas and the Fort Wayne Fury. Jackson,
31, even spent a season with the Dayton Wings of the little-known
World Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   So disregarded was Jackson when he graduated from Georgetown in
1989 that in addition to not being selected in the NBA draft, he
was a mere fourth-round pick in the CBA. Through it all, however,
he never questioned whether he could become a major contributor in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some low spots,'' said Jackson, who scored all of
his points on Wednesday on outside jumpers, including five
3-pointers. ``When you're getting cut and stuff like that, that's
not too high of a time. But I didn't lose confidence in my game. I
never let the fact that a team cut me affect my belief in what I
could do on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who played for two championship teams in the CBA, did
not have to endure such basketball hardship to put food on the
table. He earned a degree in finance from Georgetown, and his wife,
Terri, is a lawyer currently teaching a course on women in sports
at Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Jackson had his dream. ``I've always known that if
this didn't work out that I could move on and be successful in the
real world,'' said Jackson, who plans to return to school
eventually to earn his master's degree. ``But deep down inside I've
always felt that I can play in this league just as well as any of
these guys. This was a dream of mine, and I knew that it was going
to happen at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   That point came in September 1997 when the Spurs signed Jackson
to a one-year deal. But Gregg Popovich, the team's coach and
general manager, admittedly had no idea that he was getting a
deadly 3-point shooter who would eventually be called the
Eliminator for helping San Antonio sweep the Portland Trail Blazers
and the Los Angeles Lakers from this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very honestly, I did not sign him because I thought he was
going to drill 3-pointers,'' Popovich said. ``I signed him because
we wanted to have somebody come off the bench and have a defensive
presence, have some toughness and be able to guard more athletic
people at the two position. But once we got him into camp and he
started shooting some 3s here and there, we decided to make that a
priority of his, and he loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's transformation from a player known solely for his grit
and hustle into a long-range marksmen has caught nearly everyone
but himself by surprise. After making only 6 of 34 3-pointers in
his first six NBA seasons combined, he shot 37 percent in making
112 3-pointers in the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this season, Jackson started over Mario Elie
but after the Spurs' sluggish start, Popovich reversed the two
players' roles.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the playoffs that Jackson emerged as a driving
force in San Antonio's quest for a title. Against the Lakers, he
made eight 3-pointers, including a franchise-tying six in Game 3,
and scored 42 points in the Spurs' final two victories over Los
Angeles. Then, he hit nine triples in scoring 30 points in Games 3
and 4 against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do whatever the team needs,'' Jackson said, ``whether it's
playing tough defense or shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Spurs go on to win the title, Jackson, who refused to
sign a two-year deal with the Spurs this season, should receive
more than a championship ring. As an integral part of their attack,
he should attract major interest and dollars as a free agent this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the Spurs will want him back, Popovich grinned and
said, ``Depends on how many more 3s he hits this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is a good chance the Spurs will come calling this
summer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
