u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELLOGG-CUTS-NYT &LR;      06-17 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLOGG-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLOGG TO SCALE BACK HOMETOWN OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kellogg Co., seeking to break out of a prolonged slump, said
Thursday that it might close a portion of a plant in its hometown
of Battle Creek, Mich., and dismiss as many as 700 of the 1,100
workers there.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts could come by the first quarter of next year and would
produce savings of $35 million to $45 million a year, according to
the company, which makes Frosted Flakes and Rice Krispies. Analysts
said the company would probably cut most of the 700 positions.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cuts, the analysts said, are a signal from Carlos
M. Gutierrez, who became Kellogg's president and chief executive in
April, that he intends to make the tough decisions necessary to
awaken the sleeping giant of a company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they would actually close capacity in their
hometown, which is pretty small, is a statement that Gutierrez
really means business and is really going to cut costs to be a
low-cost provider in the cereal business,'' William Leach, an
analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc., said.
</P>
<P>
   The planned cuts would include hourly and salaried workers. The
company said it intended to meet with union officials representing
the plant workers before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``An integral part of our strategy is continuing to reduce costs
and improve efficiency to enable greater reinvestment for
profitable growth,'' Gutierrez said. ``Streamlining our operations
and avoiding future costs would help keep our North American cereal
business cost-competitive going into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg has been struggling with how to expand its business
after watching sales tumble and profits shrink as consumers have
switched to cheaper generic cereal brands and more convenient
breakfast foods like bagels. Largely for those reasons, Kellogg's
profits have dropped in each of the last four quarters, including a
15 percent decline over the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said, however, that it would take more than cutting
costs to reinvigorate the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately you can't cut your way to growth,'' Andrew Lazar,
an analyst with Lehman Brothers, said. ``Cutting costs must be
combined with innovative new product launches and high-quality
marketing spending to try and get the consumer to eat more
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez has said he intends to focus on developing more
noncereal products as part of his growth plan. The company is
expanding its distribution of such products as Rice Krispie Treats
in convenience stores and other outlets and is investing heavily in
product development to expand its brand of snack foods like
Nutri-Grain cereal bars.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg is also marketing its core cereal products for the
health benefits the company contends they provide rather than for
the sugar rush.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves, combined with Thursday's reminder that the company
is focusing on efficiency, might ordinarily be enough to move the
needle on its slumping stock. But Kellogg investors know from past
disappointments not to get too excited about such announcements.
The company's shares were flat Thursday, falling 18.75 cents, to
$33.8125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kellogg is a company that has been long on excuses and short
on results,'' Donaldson, Lufkin's Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cuts would be the second round in six months. Last
December, the company, which employs about 14,500 workers
worldwide, eliminated 525 executive and administrative positions at
its headquarters. A new round of job cuts ``certainly would have a
significant impact'' on the workers and town of 54,000 people, said
Robert B. Young, president and chief executive of the Battle Creek
Area Chamber of Commerce. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
